<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-NUOJAI-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OJAI ADVANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK WELCH  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OJAI, Calif. _ Those who know the long and storied history of
the Ojai Valley Tennis Tournament likely are aware that William
Thacher founded in 1896 what is now the country's largest amateur
annual tennis event.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps what gets lost is just how, exactly, did Thacher
jump-start the tradition, which will serve up its 100th tournament
beginning today and running through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Before one can look at the humble and unassuming beginnings of
what is better known in tennis circles as ''The Ojai'', the present
needs to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   A total of about 1,600 players (100 of which hail from the San
Gabriel Valley), 600 volunteers, and countless coaches and fans
will descend upon this quiant, friendly town _ and others within a
25-mile radius _ to watch the likes of USC's Andrew Park and Cal's
John Paul Fruttero (both San Marino High products) compete in the
Pac-10 singles and doubles tournament. That is the featured event
held annually here at Libbey Park.
</P>
<P>
   Others will venture into Ventura, or, perhaps, Port Hueneme, to
watch independent and community college players compete in
early-round matches today and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Some also will head to private homes _ complete with tennis
courts, obviously _ to watch boys and girls junior events and the
CIF-Southern Section boys singles and doubles early rounds.
</P>
<P>
   The list of champions and participants is a who's who of the
greats of the game. You name it, with the exception of John McEnroe
and Andre Agassi, and they have played here.
</P>
<P>
   Alhambra High's Claude A. Wayne was a two-time Boys CIF champion
here _ in 1902 and 1903. Pasadena High's Ellsworth Vines Jr., won
the same event in 1928. So did fellow Bulldog Stan Smith in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kramer was a Boys' CIF champ representing Montebello High
in 1937. Talk about history! Who won the event in the three
previous years prior to Kramer? The answer: A fellow named Robert
Riggs of Franklin High. . . . Yes, that Bobby Riggs!
</P>
<P>
   The history of the ''The Ojai'' is mind-boggling. One look at
the past winners brings to life a truly vivid stroll down memory
lane to tennis fans of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   So where did it all start?
</P>
<P>
   The answer appears to lay with Thacher's older brother, Edward,
who settled in Ojai as a citrus grower in the late 1880's. Another
Thacher, brother, Sherman, later founded the renowed Thacher
School, a prep school whose list of alumni includes one Howard
Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Ojai Valley News' Patricia L. Fry in 1983,
Sherman told his brother William prior to an 1890 visit, ''William,
if you have brought white tennis trousers, tennis shoes, and a
racquet and white hat in your trunk, please, please keep them
there. We here do not play tennis at all. We work and play with
horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, William Thacher fell in love with Ojai, became a
headmaster at Thacher School, and organized the Ojai Athletic Club
to promote sports, including tennis.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1895, the Ojai Valley Tennis Club was formed and
the following year, a tennis tournament was held pitting champions
from Ventura. That was the inauguaral version of ''The Ojai.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1897, players from Santa Barbara, Los Angeles and Pasadena
were invited to play here as well. A year later, players from all
over the state descended upon the town. In 1899, 500 players
competing in Men's singles and Boys' high school singles and
doubles played and the tournament was off and running.
</P>
<P>
   The only shutdowns in the annual event came during the four
years of World War II and earlier in 1924, when the Ojai Valey was
closed due to Hoof and Mouth disease.
</P>
<P>
   What has kept ''The Ojai'' going strong as ever is a subtle
combination of elite tennis and a community that opens its
collective arms to the outside world for four days.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are the two things that absolutely stick out in my
mind,'' said Pasadena Poly High School tennis coach Howie Farer.
''The quality of tennis is fabulous and the people who help run the
tournament are just incredibily friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   And Farer, perhaps more than any other San Gabriel Valley tennis
enthusiast, speaks from experience. He will be making what he
believes is ''about my 50th trip to Ojai'' as both a former player
at Whittier College and the past 35 years as Poly's coach.
</P>
<P>
   ''While so many things have changed, ''The Ojai has remained so
consistently the same.''
</P>
<P>
   The one thing that seems to stick out to those included in the
Ojai alumni is their stay in town during the event. . . . Or,
actually, where, they stayed. Tennis results often get lost in
discussion's of one's Ojai experience.
</P>
<P>
   Binney Moss, a 70-year-old Ojai resident who played doubles in
the event here in 1945, is one of a number of locals who open up
their homes and backyards to players during the four-day event. She
also has housed players as well since 1977, and this year, former
champion and pro player Pam Teeguarden will be an occupant of the
Moss' family guest house.
</P>
<P>
   Moss twice watched a young Michael Chang play a early-round
match in her backyard in the mid 1980's. ''I remember him more than
others, perhaps, because he became famous,'' Moss said. ''He always
stayed very focused and he was very gentlemanly on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the action here centers around Libbey Park, located at
the center of town. The Pac-10 competition - men and women -
annually draw the biggest crowds. As a player in an event other
than the Pac-10's, the goal is to, ''make it to Libbey,'' which
means you're likely a semifinalist or a finalist competing in front
of packed-park crowds on Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Ojai'' also is tradition-rich, much in the same fashion as
Wimbledon. Fresh orange juice is served _ free _ during the morning
hours and afternoon tea is served at Libbey Park as well during the
afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   ''This tournament is a very big deal to this town, we all take a
great deal of pride in it and what we do as individuals,'' said
Gerry Roe, a tournament volunteer who annually handles those within
the media.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems to me that everyone in town has a story, a tennis
story. The players, the same thing. And you know what's funny? The
stories aren't usually about matches, but rather, where people
stayed, what they did in town, who they saw.
</P>
<P>
   ''And every story is different, new, and, yes, I find them
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Farer and his Poly girls strolled to an Ojai
private residence to watch a Prep League friend and rival play
during the 1990 season.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of the girls were friends with Lindsay when she played
for Chadwick,'' Farer said. ''And yeah, she won her match.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay Davenport has won a few more matches since her Ojai
triumph 10 years ago as a high school student at Rancho Palos
Verdes' Chadwick School. Take one peek at the women's singles
rankings, you'll find Davenport at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Ojai has a little tradition going for it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
