<HEADLINE>
BYLINE 
HOME RUNS NOT SPECIAL ANYMORE
</HEADLINE>
 ... CORRECTS NEWSPAPER WITH(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; The home run used to be a thing of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   A deep fly or cannon shot lifted 375 feet or further away from
home plate once was awe-inspiring, a lightning moment in time that
often defined a game.
</P>
<P>
   When a slugger like Willie Star gell, Hank Aaron or Reg gie
Jackson came to the plate at a crucial time, the hum of
anticipation by fans over the prospect of a game-winning home run
was palpable. These rare intersections were part of baseball's
passionate appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But not anymore. The home run has become baseball's cockroach.
</P>
<P>
   It is everywhere, and it is multiplying. Once the purview of a
few hitters, the home run now infests the game. A game born of
nuance now plays like pinball.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, a record 5,528 home runs were hit in Major League
Baseball, a 10 percent jump over 1998 (5,064 home runs), which held
the previous major league record. In 1999, 44 different players hit
30 or more home runs. In the entire decade of the '70s, 30-plus
homers were reached a mere 100 times.
</P>
<P>
   To put those numbers in an easy-to-understand form, imagine Fox
Sports' Keith Olbermann saying, ``It's deep and I don't think it's
playable'' 5,528 consecutive times.
</P>
<P>
   Chicks dig the long ball, of course, and fans aren't exactly
registering dissatisfaction at the box office. It has its place in
the game whether you're old school or new school. Earl Weaver, the
former sage of Baltimore, prayed at the temple of the three-run
jack.
</P>
<P>
   But Weaver never stopped managing games while waiting for his
deity to show. He sacrificed. He used the hit-and-run. He juggled
his lineup and used all 25 players on his bench. He did all this
because home runs were scarce.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball now is on autopilot. The only managing left in baseball
is guessing which middle reliever is least likely to be taken yard,
and the number of pitchers who truly are masters of their craft a
Pedro Martinez or Greg Maddux would fit in an egg box.
</P>
<P>
   The 1-0 game the Dodgers and Mets played Monday was an anomaly,
and it had less to do with good pitching than it did being a makeup
game played on a Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing for Mark McGwire to hit 70 in 1998 and have a
record four straight 50-plus seasons, but something else to scan
the totals of players with much smaller biceps. Members of the
20-homer club of 1999 include Rich Aurilia, David Bell, Brian
Daubach, Damian Easley, Rusty Greer, Butch Huskey, Ruben Rivera,
Lee Stevens and Miguel Tejada.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have already hit an NL-record 44 home runs in
April, with McGwire idle much of the month with a bad back. Among
the league home run leaders, you will find Shane Andrews, Geoff
Jenkins, Tony Batista, Jermaine Dye and Mike Sweeney. And there
have already been 14 walk-off, game-winning home runs this season.
</P>
<P>
   The home run was born in the '20s, when baseball cashiered the
dead ball and Babe Ruth moved from the Red Sox mound to right field
in Yankee Stadium. But even then, the home run was limited to the
few.
</P>
<P>
   In the American League between 1920 and 1939, there were 34
occasions when a player hit 35 homers or more in a season, but 25
of those seasons were accomplished by three men, Ruth, Lou Gehrig
and Jimmie Foxx.
</P>
<P>
   In the last four seasons (1996-99), there have been 77 30-plus
home run seasons in the National League, or more than the combined
total of any full decade in N.L. history. The previous decade high
was 66, in 1950-59.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball officials like commis sioner Bud Selig believe the
offen sive explosion has been good for baseball. Attendance in
1998, dur ing the McGwire-Sammy Sosa show, was a record 70,372,221.
But baseball was already enjoying an uptick in '90s. It drew a
record 70,256,459 fans in 1993, the year before the strike.
</P>
<P>
   More than one power trend is at work.
</P>
<P>
   __ Parks are smaller. Balls are flying out of two of the three
new parks for 2000, Houston's Enron and San Francisco's Pac Bell.
Last year, only 118 home runs were hit in the Houston Astrodome;
Enron figures to pass that total by the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore, Cleveland, Texas, To ronto, Atlanta and Colorado all
introduced new, homer-cozy parks in the '90s, and renovations in
Anaheim, Oakland and San Diego also increased scoring. More proof:
Boston's Fenway Park, long consid ered a haven for right-handed
power hitters, yielded an A.L.-low 152 home runs last season.
</P>
<P>
   __ The strike zone has shrunk. The high strike has been dead for
a long time and umpires have been told to stop expanding the plate
to compensate.
</P>
<P>
   Bats are lighter and players are stronger. Some bats are so
light they seem to be made out of balsa wood. Heavy lifting is of
no use to pitchers but a boon to hitters, as are muscle-making
supplements. Baseball's new formula: Mass + Bat Speed  &QC;  Dinger.
</P>
<P>
   __ Pitching is thin. Two new expansion teams created 24 new jobs
when pitching was already undernourished. Scouting puts all of its
emphasis on the radar gun, too, forgetting that a 90 mph fastball
is of no use if it's flat and straight.
</P>
<P>
   __ The ball is juiced. It has been for some time now, but
hitters and pitchers already have detected dif ferences in the 2000
baseball. The seams are lower and ESPN com mentator Harold Reynolds
says the new blue baseball logo on the ball allows hitters to pick
up rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone wanting to chart the rise of the home run only has to go
back to 1968. That season, Denny McLain won 31 games, Bob Gibson
posted a 1.12 earned run average, the major-league average was
.237, and Carl Yastrzemski won the A.L. batting crown at .301. The
next season, the height of the pitching mound was lowered from 15
inches to 10 inches. Four years later, the A.L. adopted the DH.
</P>
<P>
   More than one old-timer has suggested baseball should go retro
and raise the mound a few inches and can the DH. But who can hear
them above the din? Because what the '90s and '00s offer that can't
be changed is the sports media cul ture.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 5,528 home runs hit last year, I'd guess 5,000 of them
were replayed on videotape by ESPN, Fox Sports or your local TV
station. Just as today's 14-year-old basketball player tries to
drive the lane like Allen Iverson and Kobe Bryant, today's young
baseball player wants to go deep.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's enough for some fans. But it would be nice if there
was room for the well-pitched game, for a team nursing a run via
bunts and stolen bases, for all of the good things that can happen
when the ball doesn't leave the park.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 0005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
