u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-STRIKE-1STL     04-26 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-STRIKE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE HAVANA HEEDS CALL FOR ONE DAY WORK-STOPPAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs top of story for updating, rewriting) (With CUBAN-BOY-RDP) 
 By JUAN FORERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Little Havana's shops, restaurants, cafes and markets
were shuttered on Tuesday as thousands of Cuban-Americans
infuriated by the federal removal of Elian Gonzalez heeded a call
by exile leaders for a one-day work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 percent of Miami-Dade County workers, 2,580 people, and
10 percent of nonessential City of Miami workers, another 260
people, used their personal days to stay home. About 3,900 of
20,000 public school teachers stayed home, as did 115,000 students,
nearly a third of enrollment. Schools remained open. Essential
services continued to be provided, government officials said,
noting that buses and Metro Rail operated and the Port of Miami and
area airports were open. The stoppage affected Little Havana most;
in much of the city it was business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   But it was clear from the deserted streets in Little Havana _
and from the eased traffic flow on normally congested highways _
that untold numbers of people in the 800,000-strong Cuban exile
community had not gone to work. Many businesses in the
neighborhood, from Versailles restaurant to Sedano's Supermarkets
to L.P. Evans used car lot, were closed.
</P>
<P>
   Ten members of the Florida Marlins baseball team, including six
players, sat out the evening home game with the San Francisco
Giants. About a half-dozen other major league players and coaches
skipped evening games as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami-Dade County Commission called off Tuesday's meeting
because 6 of 13 commissioners said they would not attend.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents took to the streets, waving Cuban flags on
corners or driving in honking caravans that grew late into the
evening in Hialeah and Westchester, two neighborhoods west of
Miami. At the Freedom Tower, a former Customs house in downtown
Miami where many Cubans entered the United States, about 130
protesters chanted ``Libertad!'' as basketball fans arrived for a
Miami Heat basketball game at the American Airlines Arena. And in
Miami Beach, hundreds of Cuban-Americans silently walked to the
Holocaust Museum in a quiet show of protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a large segment of this community that is indignant
right now,'' said Miami-Dade County Mayor Alex Penelas, who went to
work. ``They're offended by what happened in Miami on Saturday.
Their reaction has been a very peaceful reaction. Some people may
not like what's happened today, but it's peaceful, it's calm.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the tranquility of Little Havana on Tuesday stood in
stark contrast to the protests of Saturday, when hundreds of
Cuban-Americans, most of them young men, burned tires and taunted
police after the federal government forcibly removed 6-year-old
Elian from the home where he had been staying.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of Saturday's unrest, Cuban exile leaders from
various organizations urged businesses to close and workers to stay
home. Talk of the stoppage dominated radio airwaves, and some exile
groups even sent vans, outfitted with megaphones, through the Cuban
enclave on Monday to remind people about the strike. The idea, said
many, was to leave Miami ``a dead city'' and send a message of
outrage to the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Little Havana, however, the effects were not as
visible. Although business closings were reported throughout the
region, stores in downtown Miami bustled with shoppers, and the
restaurants and clubs of Miami Beach were crowded with tourists.
Some non-Cubans expressed annoyance with the strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing is stupid,'' said Aaron Evans, 27, a parking
attendant in downtown Miami. ``The city isn't shut down at all.
Everybody's at work. It's just like every other day.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Watts, 30, a manager at a telecommunications company
downtown, saw the bright side. ``Traffic is better, finding parking
spots is easier,'' he said. ``The only thing that I noticed was
closed today was a McDonald's. I was upset because I did want a
biscuit for breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``This probably wasn't the most effective way of
sending a message to the city and the government, because life has
just carried on.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Cubans, however, viewed the day as a solemn one and saw a
work stoppage as the community's duty. ``This work stoppage today
might not be that successful, but it sends a message; it is
symbolism,'' said Maria Gonzalez, 32, a beauty salon worker who
spent part of her day waving a Cuban flag on a Little Havana
corner. ``We needed to do this because we lost a member of our
community unfairly. It's about mourning. It's more a day of
mourning than a day of protest.''
</P>
<P>
   Max Castro, a sociologist at the University of Miami who studies
the Cuban-American community, said he thought ``a very significant
percentage'' of Cuban-Americans took part. He said the work
stoppage was a positive way for the community to show its anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as there's not a corrosive aspect to it, as long as
people who choose not to observe it are not intimidated,'' said
Castro, a senior researcher at the university's North-South Center,
``then it seems like a good way to channel the anger and rage that
many Cubans have had since Elian was taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Osmel Lugo, 29, a construction worker who left Cuba last year,
was among those who said he was glad to take part. Lugo's employer,
an exile-owned construction company, closed for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people needed, they wanted, to be part of the stoppage,''
Lugo said. ``The people were pleased to have the chance. They were
worried that companies would not let them off, but that hasn't been
the case. People were allowed to take off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
