<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMESTORE-ANTITRUST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDS SEEK INFORMATION FROM HOMESTORE.COM
</HEADLINE>
bc-LADN-HOMESTOR.F (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thousand Oaks, Calif. _ The U.S. Justice Department's Antitrust
Division is investigating the online realty industry for possible
anti-competitive practices and has requested information from
Homestore.com Inc., officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same government entity that is prosecuting Microsoft
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Thousand Oaks-based home portal has complied with the
request for information about its business practices and the
dynamics of the industry, Chief Financial Officer John Giesecke
said.
</P>
<P>
   The government sought basic information, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe we've done anything that would violate any
law or regulation,'' Giesecke said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has not been told about the specific focus of the
investigation, nor does it know whether other companies have been
asked for similar information, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokeswoman Jennifer Rose confirmed that the
government is investigating the industry and declined further
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Giesecke said that Homestore.com's partner, the National
Association of Realtors, was also asked for information.
</P>
<P>
   Homestore.com has built a group of 11 related Internet sites -
organized as categories under the Homestore.com portal - that offer
information and services related to real estate.
</P>
<P>
   The company's business strategy has been to cover the full range
of home and real estate-related offerings: new and existing home
sales, apartment rentals, home improvement, home financing and
information about moving.
</P>
<P>
   It has formed partnerships with the National Association of
Realtors; General Motors Acceptance Corp.; HomePortfolio.com, a
home design Web site; Sundial.com, a wireless products seller; and
Champion Enterprises, the nation's largest home builder.
</P>
<P>
   Giesecke said Homestore.com has relationships with most of the
nation's 800 multiple listing services, and provides access to 95
percent of the listed homes in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   An undisclosed percentage of those homes are available through
exclusive agreements with the listing services, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Homestore.com has some agreements that make it the only
national Internet service with access to home listings, its
business practices are not harmful to the consumer, Giesecke said.
</P>
<P>
   Homestore.com's competitors include some of the largest names in
the Internet and real estate, among them Microsoft, Yahoo! and
Cendant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be hard-pressed for anybody to declare we have a
monopoly,'' Giesecke said. ``Having exclusive contracts (is) not
against the law. We're not restricting access, we're not tracking
for data, we're not harming the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Other leaders in the Internet economy - including Yahoo!, eBay
and advertising clearinghouse Doubleclick - also have been asked by
the Justice Department to provide information.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're certainly getting very interested in what's happening
on the Internet, and it's just very difficult to tell how long it
will take for these things to run their course,'' Giesecke said.
``Our strategy is to cooperate fully and completely and be as
helpful as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
