<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7310 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     04-26 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTPHAL HAS FINGERS ON ALL THE WRONG BUTTONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ To be honest, there has been an air of smugness in
Paul Westphal's voice these past few months, every time he talks
about how the Sonics have exceeded expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Quick to point out that some prognosticators did not pick the
Sonics to make the playoffs, Westphal has had the ammunition, or so
it seemed, to shoot down the naysayers.
</P>
<P>
   (begin italic)
</P>
<P>
   We made the playoffs. We did better than people said we would.
End of discussion.
</P>
<P>
   (end italic)
</P>
<P>
   Granted, defensiveness or paranoia are nothing new to NBA
coaches. But what if that sort of attitude does not end with
Westphal's interactions with the media?
</P>
<P>
   These days, down 0-2 in the playoffs against a Jazz team that is
picking apart Westphal's completely inept team, the Sonics are in a
torpor.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the Sonics goes deeper than Vin Baker failing
to live up to his All-Star days. It has been extremely convenient
to paint the power forward's disastrous free fall as the main
reason why the Sonics have no identity, no energy, no cohesion, no
hope.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the Sonics may even go back to owner Barry
Ackerley's unwillingness to pay for Phil Jackson to come in and
take charge.
</P>
<P>
   It might even be a little bit about general manager Wally
Walker's decision last summer to not forfeit winning in exchange
for tearing up this team and starting over, younger.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of signing Baker to a seven-year, $87 million contract
last August, instead of trading away a first-round draft pick for
warhorse Horace Grant, instead of signing Vernon Maxwell to a
three-year deal, the Sonics could have started over.
</P>
<P>
   That would have been a tough decision, a bold one, but looking
around, some NBA teams realize they have to start from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Or, another scenario: The Sonics' problems might be about how
Walker chose Westphal over Paul Silas, who was hired by Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Silas is not only winning in the playoffs, he got a
not-so-terribly talented team to work hard, win and, most
important, overcome a terrible midseason tragedy in the death of
guard Bobby Phills.
</P>
<P>
   Silas, whose Hornets ended the regular-season on a seven-game
win streak, was named the NBA's top coach for April. His players
are listening, working.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no going back at this point. Silas has done his job
coaxing good games out of Derrick Coleman, a near-miracle
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, here in Seattle, Baker is signed through the 2006
season. Someone has to resurrect him.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton is the biggest asset the Sonics have. But at age 31,
he is too old to wait for a major rebuilding in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   If you were Ackerley, whose ownership of the Sonics is as much
about the bottom-line value of the franchise as it is about
winning, would you consider trading your biggest commodity?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why, whenever this first-round series against the Jazz
is over, Payton will once again ask for a meeting with the Sonics'
owner and make his point that something must be done.
</P>
<P>
   And that something will go like this: (begin italic) Either
Westphal goes or trade me. Sacramento. L.A. Portland. Somewhere
with a prayer. (end italic).
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his previous post-season blow-ups, this time Payton will
have good reason to make such a demand. And this time, he might
have more than his own interests in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Payton's body language on the bench in the fourth quarter of
Game 2 Monday told the whole, sorry story. He was stewing. He was
defeated _ a rare sight.
</P>
<P>
   But Payton is not the first one _ nor is he the only one _ to
wonder what Westphal is doing. From Brent Barry to Ruben Patterson
to Greg Foster to Horace Grant to Vernon Maxwell, questions are
rampant. However, it will be Payton's query that starts to shake
this thing out.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing for Westphal to have failed to establish
rotation and substitution patterns for his players.
</P>
<P>
   And it is one thing to have created a free-for-all system that
makes every Sonics player believe he is a starter.
</P>
<P>
   It was one thing to try and let the Sonics ``just roll the ball
out there and play hard,'' as a hands-off Westphal did in the first
half of the season. Later, though, when that no longer worked,
Westphal seemed exposed for not having technical defensive schemes
to use against better opponents.
</P>
<P>
   All those things are big. But the final straw has to be when,
out of the blue, he takes the ball out of Payton's hands at the
start of the playoffs and turns him into a pick-setting,
screen-running shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   By halftime of Monday's 101-87 disaster in Salt Lake, Payton was
so incensed, he demanded to know from Westphal why Patterson hadn't
played a minute and why he (Payton) had been relegated to setting
picks and running off screens.
</P>
<P>
   This is Gary Payton, after all. Not Jeff Hornacek.
</P>
<P>
   Payton is not alone, however, in his disgust over Westphal's
decisions and seeming inability to communicate effectively with his
players.
</P>
<P>
   Top to bottom, Westphal has lost the respect of his players, and
we haven't even addressed the suspicion Sonics players have about
why Maxwell isn't on the playoff roster.
</P>
<P>
   It appears, however, that once a player fails to meet Westphal's
expectation or crosses him or, worse, openly challenges him,
Westphal exerts ``my way or the highway'' sort of control.
</P>
<P>
   Again, it is nothing new for coaches to battle with players, to
have run-ins and disagreements. But the good ones find a way to not
lose the confidence or kill the fire in their players.
</P>
<P>
   It's called knowing how to push the right buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Judging how the Sonics have careened to the end of this season,
the only buttons Westphal seems to have pushed are the wrong ones.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
