<HEADLINE>
NAME CHANGE REFLECTS MODERN OFFICE PROFESSIONALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``a'' national news file.) 
By JASON TAKENOUCHI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's a name change that goes far beyond just a
name.
</P>
<P>
   Today marks the first celebration of Administrative
Professionals Day, an annual event that until this year bore the
moniker Professional Secretaries Day.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say the name change by the International Association
of Administrative Professionals - the event's nonprofit sponsor -
reflects the shifting nature of work performed by secretaries and
other office professionals.
</P>
<P>
   And for many of the people whose contributions are being
acknowledged, the new name is a belated recognition of changing
times in general.
</P>
<P>
   Even traditional secretaries agree that today's commemoration,
changed name and all, is still an important reminder of their role
in keeping business moving.
</P>
<P>
   The recognition is needed for a simple reason, said Carol
Fernandez, a secretary in the admitting department of Providence
Holy Cross Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offices would cease to function without us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Yoko Senga, an administrative assistant at NetZero Inc.,
said the very word ``secretary'' evokes images and stereotypes that
run counter to what she and thousands of other workers do in the
modern work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hear the word `secretary' I think of the '50s and women
with crisp, ironed dresses answering phones and typing on a
typewriter,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Senga said her current title better captures the range of her
work and responsibilities, including completing independent
projects and acting as chief liaison to NetZero's chief marketing
officer.
</P>
<P>
   And, perhaps more importantly, she said the term
``administrative assistant'' doesn't carry the stigma of being a
job that only a woman would have.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's androgynous. It doesn't mean `woman' to me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The job has also shifted for traditional secretaries, according
to Rick Stroud, a spokesman for the IAAP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secretaries have realized for 25 years now that the days of
just being a typist are over,'' Stroud said. ``What this profession
has really evolved to be is an information manager for the
information age.''
</P>
<P>
   That evolution mirrored technological changes, including the
advent of personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   The transition from typewriters to computers eliminated the need
for some skills, emphasized more active work and helped secretaries
branch off into other areas, said Samuel Culbert, a professor of
management at UCLA's Anderson School and author of ``Kill the
Bosses,'' a book due to be released next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the computer, the whole nature of the job changed,''
Culbert said. ``It took a different kind of human being to work a
computer. The person had to start thinking a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Doreen Wilson, an administrative assistant to the vice president
of sales for Los Angeles-based Princess Cruises, has seen that
change firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   After a major reorganization at her company, Wilson said, her
responsibilities expanded greatly. She said she often has to learn
complex computer programs just to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because everything is changing so quickly, sometimes you don't
have time for the classes, so you have to be self-taught,'' Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much information that's coming in,'' she said.
``It's important for us to filter out that information and pass it
on to our bosses.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's boss, John Molinaro, said his assistant's role is now
key to the running of the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's my right arm - and my left arm,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
