<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAME FRONT OFFICE FOR TRIPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Los Angeles Dodgers aren't happy with a pair of
trips east to start the season, nor are they pleased about playing
16 of their first 21 games on the road.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's what the organization asked for when Major League
Baseball was setting up the 2000 schedule. The Dodgers wanted the
extra time in case the $50 million renovation project ran behind
schedule, so upper management requested it.
</P>
<P>
   But Dodgers president and CEO Bob Graziano said it was a
one-time deal, and the club has already told baseball officials
they'd prefer to open at home next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We requested to be on the road, and it's the only time we
requested to do that,'' Graziano said. ``You put in your
preferences for next season. (Baseball) will ask what our
preferences are, and we put in we would prefer to open at home.''
</P>
<P>
   The topic of the Dodgers' schedule became hot when the club had
to travel to New York to make up an April 9 snowout. Instead of h
off Monday in Atlanta, the Dodgers traveled from Cincinnati to New
York for an afternoon game, then hopped on a plane to Atlanta to
open the three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fairness to the Mets and fairness to Major League Baseball
_ and we did it with the Houston Astros _ you try to pick the
soonest possible date (to play a makeup),'' Graziano said. ``We
don't go to New York anymore, so we had to find the next available
date.''
</P>
<P>
   The hot spot of the early-season travel was Monday's trip to
play the Mets. Those things happen, but the Dodgers began the
season with a 12-game road trip to Montreal, New York and San
Francisco, preceded by two exhibition games in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't get much better in the coming weeks. The Dodgers
return home after the three-game series with the Braves for a
nine-game homestand but then embark on a four-city, 12-game road
trip to Arizona, St. Louis, Chicago and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   When it's all done, the Dodgers will have played 28 of their
first 42 games on the road.
</P>
<P>
   __ Off his Mark: Second baseman Mark Grudzielanek had a four-hit
game in Cincinnati, but he's far from feeling good at the plate. He
went 0 for 4 against the Braves and his average dipped to .207.
</P>
<P>
   It's a slump that has existed since the first weekend of the
season. He began with six hits in 16 at-bats, only to go 11 for 66
(.167) since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think my selection of pitches is good right now,''
said Grudzielanek, who called it the worst slump of his career.
``I'm putting myself in bad situations. It seems like I'm always
behind in the count and trying to keep battling. I have to stay
positive and try not to hit any walls.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Right-hander Chan Ho Park tested the blister
on the middle finger of his right hand with a bullpen session and
said he would make his start Thursday. . . . Pitcher Jeff Williams
was sent down before the game, leaving the Dodgers without a
left-handed reliever. . . . Angel Pena, considered the catcher of
the future, was placed on the disabled list at Triple-A Albuquerque
with soreness in his lower back. . . . Atlanta's Reggie Sanders
went 0 for 3 to extend his hitless streak to 27 at-bats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
