u a BC-NY-CABBY-SLAIN-1STLD-     04-26 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CABBY-SLAIN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 8TH KILLING OF A NEW YORK CABBY, MORE PROTECTION DEVICES
URGED
</HEADLINE>
 
(Subs 3rd graf for updating and rewriting) By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When a livery cab driven by Jose R. Olivares veered
out of control and slammed into a building in the Bronx late
Monday, it contained all the elements of a string of crimes that
has confounded the police.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares was dying, bleeding from a gunshot wound to the right
side of his head. With him in the cab, a silver Lincoln Town Car
that had no bulletproof partition and no security camera, were four
teenagers who the police said had tried to rob him after he picked
them up on the street. He had let one of the passengers get in the
front seat beside him. A loaded .380 semiautomatic pistol that the
authorities said was used to kill him was found tucked behind
Olivares' back.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares, 37, was the eighth livery cabby to be slain this year,
the latest in series of crimes that have mobilized the Police
Department and drawn condemnation from community leaders and city
officials. The four teen-agers were charged in the killing on
Tuesday night. But in the details surrounding Oliveares' death is
an illustration of just how hard these crimes are for the police to
stop.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Police Department has deployed hundreds of
officers each night on cabby-protection assignments, the officers
remain frustrated enough that Police Commissioner Howard Safir
faced a bank of television cameras on Tuesday and appealed to the
drivers to take steps to protect themselves. ``If you don't have a
partition, please do not pick up hails because you put yourself in
great danger,'' Safir said. ``And certainly do not let anybody in
the front seat of your automobile.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, the authorities said Tuesday, Olivares' death shows
that no single response can protect the cabbies from those who
stalk them.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the police have increased the number of decoy
cabs and have begun using the Street Crime Units to make random
stops of livery cabs, in the hopes of deterring the killers. But
the authorities said Tuesday that two elements were still needed to
complement their efforts: more safety equipment in the cabs, and
changes in cabby behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Olivares, the authorities said, underscored the
importance of both.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike yellow medallion cabs, livery cabs are prohibited by city
regulations from picking up passengers on the street, and police
data show that more than 80 percent of the robberies this year and
six of the eight killings occurred after drivers broke the rules.
And yet, in addition to picking up passengers assigned by
dispatchers, as they are allowed, drivers like Olivares have
continued to stop for fares at the curb, even at night, and even as
the homicide tally has been rising.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, although the city's Taxi and Limousine Commission
passed a regulation last week requiring livery drivers to outfit
their cars with partitions or security cameras by the middle of
May, local glass shops are backlogged by as much as four weeks to
meet the sudden demand. Olivares had a bulletproof partition on
order, but even if it had been installed, it would not have
protected him from a passenger he had allowed to ride shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department's message, however, must contend with the
realities of transportation in poor neighborhoods and the economics
of the livery-cab industry, which all but assure that the drivers
will continue to defy the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drivers are serving under-served minority neighborhoods,''
said Fernando A. Mateo, president of the New York State Federation
of Taxi Drivers. ``They are minorities serving their own people
because yellow cabs won't go into these neighborhoods, and because
they need the money to put food on their families' tables. When
they see someone who wants a ride, they are going to pull over and
pick them up. It's going to continue happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Given these circumstances, and given the fact that the police
have already stepped up their efforts, Mateo and city officials are
holding out hope that the partitions, once installed in the roughly
46,000 livery cabs operating in the city, will slow the rate of
killings.
</P>
<P>
   Crime data suggest they might. In 1994, the Taxi and Limousine
Commission passed a regulation requiring the fleets of yellow
medallion cabs to install approved partitions in their vehicles.
Since then, the yellow-cab homicides have virtually stopped. There
were nine in 1993, none in 1994, and then one each year through
January 1997. Since then there have been none. Yellow cab robberies
have also plummeted, from 723 in 1994 to 181 last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 0113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
