<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7325 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     04-26 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN AWES; BATS DON'T
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There were a few fleeting moments when Kevin Brown's
control was lacking, but there was no way to tell he missed the
past 16 days because of a broken right pinkie.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers' right-hander was superb in his return,
pitching seven innings. But for the second straight day, the
Dodgers hitters couldn't solve their opponent, this time Atlanta
lefty Tom Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine pitched a three-hit complete game as the Braves beat the
Dodgers 1-0 in the first of a three-game series Tuesday at Turner
Field. Glavine's 19th career shutout was his first since blanking
Arizona Sept.19, 1998, and it pushed Atlanta's winning streak to
eight.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, the Dodgers and Brown were pleased that he didn't
have any overwhelming problem with his pinkie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, the next time will be a little sharper, a little
bit better,'' said Brown, who kept the pinkie off the bat when he
hit. ``You know (the finger) is there. Normally, you don't think
about your fingers. It's just there. I could tell. I know it's
there. I kind of sticks out and from your mind. But again, I was
able to do well with it, so maybe in five days it'll be that much
better. It made a lot of progress in the last five days.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome mirrored what the Dodgers did the day before in New
York, where they lost 1-0 to the Mets and had just three hits. It's
the first time the Dodgers lost back-to-back games 1-0 since June
29-30, 1937, against the Boston Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the second inning, I made a conscious effort to pitch
inside a little more and keep them honest in there, in hopes it
would open up the outside part of the plate for me a little bit,''
Glavine said. ``I think it did. I felt like in the middle part of
the game and the end of the game, my pitches away, they weren't
quite attacking them as much as they were earlier in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive ineptitude the past two games contrasts what the
Dodgers did at the start of the road trip. They battered Cincinnati
pitching for 36 runs in a three-game sweep. Now, the Dodgers have
been shut out in back-to-back games for the first time since San
Francisco did it to them July 13-14, 1996. The Dodgers are 3-5 in
one-run games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brownie was outstanding and I tried really to hook him after
five; he hadn't pitched in two weeks, but he said, `You don't have
to worry about me hitting. I'm fine. I'm fine,' '' Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said.``I thought (Glavine) threw a lot of quality
pitches, and it hasn't been an easy travel start. But he's a heck
of a pitcher. It's not the first time he's done that, but that's a
heck of a job on Brownie's part.''
</P>
<P>
   The only time the Dodgers got a runner to second base was when
Shawn Green led off the seventh with a double. Gary Sheffield
struck out, Eric Karros singled to through the hole into left
field, Green holding at third. Adrian Beltre ended the inning by
grounding into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre had the other hit and was the only other baserunner when
he walked with two outs in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept hitting his spots,'' Sheffield said. ``He wasn't
making any mistakes over the plate, and when you hit the spots all
day it's tough to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' run came in the fifth when Quilvio Veras, who's 11
for 20 lifetime against Brown, singled to center with two outs to
score Walk Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   And while Brown had minor struggles during the night, including
a walk to Glavine, it was an outing that left many Dodgers in awe.
After all, Brown returned from two weeks of inactivity to throw to
bullpen sessions, then held one of the National League's top
lineups to one run on five hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was really more than impressive,'' Sheffield said. ``For
a guy that goes down and really doesn't throw at all, and then to
throw a couple bullpens and then go in a game and shut down a
lineup like this in unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   With Brown out, the Dodgers (11-8) were 8-4. The talk when he
went down was the starting pitchers needed to pick up the slack,
and they did. Including a seven-run, 1-inning performance from Orel
Hershiser, the starters went 6-2 with a 3.88 ERA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
