 MAD COWS, ENGLISHMEN AND US  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's a bloody shame. Mark Davids simply wanted
to donate some blood at his friendly neighborhood bloodletting
shop, Blood Centers of the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   But they sniffed and gave him the old ``fee-fi-fo-fum'' business
about the blood of an Englishman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently,'' Davids says, ``an unsuspecting American
neurosurgeon was fixing a British brain (good luck) and contracted
mad cow disease.''
</P>
<P>
   So as of April 15, by FDA rule, if your blood is British,
Americans are skittish.
</P>
<P>
   Davids doth protest. But what can he do? Chuck crates of
American tea into San Francisco Bay? The whole thing seems udderly
ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   SOMEBODY'S UNCLEAR on the concept. Maybe it's me. Reader Tony
Sannella also seems confused.
</P>
<P>
   On Mother's Day, the Marin Audubon Society will hold a
``Barbecue for the Birds,'' a fund-raiser feast.
</P>
<P>
   They will be barbecuing: chickens.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds delicious, I'll be there, so throw another
yellow-breasted sapsucker on the barbie!
</P>
<P>
   BURMA SHAVE lives.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Breuer was driving through Oregon, it's election time, and
among the many campaign signs along the highway he saw these four
consecutive signs:
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians, like diapers/from season to season/need to be
changed /for the very same reason.''
</P>
<P>
   EVERYONE'S GOT quiz-show fever.
</P>
<P>
   I was sitting on a bar stool next to Bill Gates, who was slumped
over the bar, and I heard him mutter to himself, ``Who wants to be
a millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   The impeccable Cuffs Corbett, a big fan of Regis' quiz show,
notes that not one single contestant, as their phone-a-friend
lifeline, has called either George W. Bush or Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   On Easter morning, my wife said to our 4-year-old son, ``There's
a claymation movie about Jesus on TV tonight. Do you want to watch
it?''
</P>
<P>
   Long pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is `Win Ben Stein's Money' on?''
</P>
<P>
   CELL PHONES: Everyone loves 'em, everyone hates 'em. How can
that be?
</P>
<P>
   VIPs in restaurants irritate diners by making pretentious,
booming, important calls, but who are they trying to impress? Every
13-year-old has a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Cell use in restaurants is considered slightly uncool, like
cleaning your ears with a breadstick.
</P>
<P>
   At Moose's restaurant, they have cute little signs on the tables
beseeching diners to refrain from cell use. Yet just the other day
there was a very famous local movie star, chatting away on her cell
phone. Maybe phoning a friend to tell 'em about the cute little
no-cell signs on the tables.
</P>
<P>
   If you do go on the wagon, cell-phone wise, you can donate your
phone to Call to Protect, which converts the phones into 911
signals and donates 'em to victims of domestic abuse
 &UR; (www.donateaphone.com). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   You could even use one in a restaurant to call 911 if you were
choking on a waxy breadstick.
</P>
<P>
   AT THE BAR in the New Pisa restaurant in North Beach, a customer
was admiring the posters of famous Italian boxers, footballers and
baseballers, and wondered aloud why there were no photos of Italian
military victors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have them upstairs,'' said barman Seamus Coyle, ``but
they're in Latin.''
</P>
<P>
   I TAKE NO credit for the recent removal of the Rush Limbaugh
billboard near the San Francisco side of the Bay Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   I merely made a suggestion and radio KNBR followed it, not only
replacing the billboard, but dumping the daily Limbaugh show.
</P>
<P>
   Rush reportedly is campaigning to be hired by ABC for Monday
Night Football.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Dittohead would be a welcome addition to that
announcing booth, as long as they don't give him a microphone.
</P>
<P>
   LOTTA DOTZ was sipping at the cog- &QL; 
nac bar on the Rich Guy level of the Giants' new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, it's $22 per shot, or gulp, or sniff, or dollop, or
whatever a serving of cognac is called.
</P>
<P>
   Six bucks for a brewski, $22 for a cognac. That could cause
feelings of financial inadequacy, which could drive a man to drink.
</P>
<P>
   Dotz mused aloud that with this class of clientele, the ballpark
ought to have a caviar bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caviar bar?'' a gentleman snorted, knocking back his $22
cognac. ``At a baseball park!?''
</P>
</TEXT>
