<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7327 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-VERMONT-GAYMARRIAGE-S     04-26 1420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERMONT-GAYMARRIAGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CIVIL UNIONS FOR GAYS, LESBIANS OKD BY HOUSE IN VERMONT  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTPELIER, Vt. _ With both sides acutely aware that their vote
might forever change American society, the Vermont Legislature gave
final approval Tuesday to homosexual civil unions, conferring on
gays and lesbians every right of marriage short of the name itself.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Howard Dean promised to sign the legislation as early as
Thursday, making Vermont on July 1 the first state in the union to
extend the privileges, benefits and responsibilities of marriage to
gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   The 79-to-68 vote in the packed state House chamber came after
nearly three hours of often raw debate that mirrored the bitter
chasm gay civil unions have opened in this rural state of quaint
hamlets and fierce independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was by far the most difficult bill I have ever seen in
the Legislature,'' Dean said afterward, as opponents wearing white
ribbons vowed retaliation and supporters wearing pink buttons
hugged in celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was very little politics in these votes,'' said
Dean, a Democrat. ``I think people had to reach deep in their
hearts to do what they felt was right.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote _ both last week in the state Senate and Tuesday in its
lower house _ was divided largely along party lines in the
Democrat-dominated Legislature. But many of those who crossed party
lines insisted that either Vermont was taking a courageous step
toward universal civil rights or abandoning the will of its own
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad, dark day for the state of Vermont, and God help
us all,'' declared Democrat George Allard of the town of St.
Albans.
</P>
<P>
   The action followed a unanimous ruling by the Vermont Supreme
Court in December that the state's exclusion of homosexuals from
the state-conferred benefits of marriage _ including everything
from inheritance and probate rights to hospital visitation _
violated the state constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The court instructed the Legislature either to allow homosexuals
to marry or to grant them all the benefits of marriage under
another name. Two attempts were made in the state Senate to amend
the constitution to thwart the ruling, but both were soundly
defeated in committee.
</P>
<P>
   While polls have shown significant public opposition in Vermont
to gay civil unions, the state does not have a referendum system
like California that would allow voters to decide the question
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents predicted a voter backlash in November. ``I think it
stinks,'' said Steven Davis, a citizen who came to watch. ``The
voices of the people of Vermont haven't been listened to. I think
next November there are going to be some legislators who aren't
going to be there anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the one significant change the state Senate made to the
original house bill was to move up the implementation date from
September to July, so as to put as more distance between the
expected flurry of publicity when the law takes effect and the
elections in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have said they'll not vote for me because of
this,'' Republican Marion Milne said after the vote, noting that an
opponent has already announced a challenge for her seat.
</P>
<P>
   Milne said the vote caused her great anguish. ``A lot of my
constituents and people I know and respect urged me to vote no,''
she said, but she voted yes ``because I listened with an open mind
and felt from everything I heard that this was the right thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear to what extent Vermont's action will affect
other states. The new law could be challenged as an inadequate
parallel system of ``separate but equal'' marriage rights that
continues to deny homosexuals the full stature of marriage, much
like segregated public education in the South for black Americans
that was found unconstitutional by the Supreme Court in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country has gone down the path of so-called separate but
equal before, and I think most of us agree that was a bad idea,''
said Evan Wolfson, director of the Marriage Project for the Lambda
Legal Defense and Education Fund. ``Likewise here, the right answer
is to treat gay people and nongay people equally, and that includes
the freedom to marry, rather than trying to set up two lines at the
clerk's office.''
</P>
<P>
   The two lesbian couples and one gay male couple who brought the
original lawsuit _ all of whom witnessed Tuesday's vote _ said they
did not yet know if they would take their case any further, but
preferred simply to celebrate the day as a great victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am amazed at this process, and I'm so proud of this state,''
said Peter Harrigan, one of the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't be happier with the results,'' added Bill Lippert,
the only openly gay Vermont legislator. The words civil union,
Lippert said, while short of marriage, ``carry a significance and
symbolism that is very appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermont's action ``has already reverberated nationally,''
Lippert said. ``Civil union creates a model that some other
jurisdictions can now look at to grant the dignity of a legal
relationship to gay and lesbian families.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights lawyers said the most immediate question was whether
or how other states will acknowledge Vermont's civil unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's completely unprecedented,'' said Jennifer Levi, a staff
attorney with the Gay and Lesbian Advocates and Defenders, or GLAD,
which served as co-counsel in the Vermont case. ``There are a lot
of open questions that nobody knows the answers to at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay lawyers agreed, however, that because Vermont's civil union
is not marriage, it will provide no basis to challenge the federal
Defense of Marriage Act, signed by President Clinton in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That law restricts all federal benefits and rights conferred by
marriage _ including immigration status and Social Security
benefits _ to unions between a man and a woman. The same holds for
the 30 similar state laws, including California's recently enacted
Proposition 22, or Knight Initiative, that voters approved in
March.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go into court and say your marriage is being
discriminated against until you have one, and as of today, in all
50 states, gay people are denied the freedom to marry,'' Wolfson
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Wolfson made clear that any effort by other states to deny
Vermont civil unions is likely to invite a challenge. ``The
question of how Vermont families who undertake the legal commitment
of civil union will be treated as they travel or as they deal with
the federal government remains to be seen,'' Wolfson said.
``Certainly they will have a need for protection, much as other
couples, and they should not be forced to play, `Now you're
recognized, now you're not,' depending on which border they've
crossed.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Marriage Is the Goal
</P>
<P>
   For many, marriage remains the ultimate goal. ``Any individual
with self-respect and self-esteem is not going to stop until they
have achieved full and equal status in society, and that includes
equal marriage rights,'' said David Smith, spokesman for the Human
Rights Campaign, a national gay lobby.
</P>
<P>
   But civil union already goes way too far for many Vermonters. A
small group gathered on the statehouse steps Tuesday morning,
praying that members who committed to vote yes would change their
minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remove from him his desire to be compassionate by believing
that which is in fact not true,'' the group prayed. ``Prevent this
unrighteousness from coming into Vermont.''
</P>
<P>
   Several legislators who spoke in opposition to civil unions
Tuesday compared homosexuality to alcoholism and called it a
``perversion'' that is ``against the law of nature.'' The notion of
gay marriage corrupts the meaning of language, others said, to
where ``depravity is virtue'' and ``moral values are ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   The most heated opposition came from Assemblywoman Nancy
Sheltra, who charged that granting civil unions would condone
conduct that spreads AIDS and other diseases. Several legislators
walked out of the chamber when Sheltra began reading from a tract
vowing that homosexuals would foist sodomy on the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Little, a Republican who helped shepherd the civil union
bill to passage, told the assembly that it is ``clear the state is
divided, and it will take time to become less divided.''
Recriminations on both sides, he said, point to ``the power of this
issue and how deep it goes into our own personal experiences and
psyches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
