<HEADER>
A7328 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-LANDSWAP-AZR &LR;      04-26 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANDSWAP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVIL IN DETAILS OF PLAN TO SWAP STATE, U.S. LAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JEFF BARKER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   interior secretary bruce babbitt and Arizona Gov. Jane Hull are
privately considering a series of massive land swaps that could
mean hundreds of thousands of acres changing hands between Arizona
and the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations, which at times have been marked by intrigue,
reached a critical point this week. To protect open space from
urban sprawl, Babbitt said, he proposed redrawing state and federal
boundaries to preserve 79,000 acres of wild country around Lake
Pleasant and an additional 24,000 acres in the Silverbell Mountains
region near Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about a really rare opportunity to effect some large
and really important land exchanges which will protect the scenic
part of Arizona,'' Babbitt said in an interview. ``This is really
wild country north and west from Lake Pleasant. It's not land that
should ever be developed.''
</P>
<P>
   In return for assuming possession of the state trust land, the
federal government would allow Arizona to select land of roughly
the same value from among 900,000 U.S.-owned acres spread around
the state, from Safford to Wickenburg to Bullhead City.
</P>
<P>
   State land taken by the federal government would be protected
from development, while federal acreage absorbed into the state
land trust would be eligible, eventually, for sale to developers or
other private parties.
</P>
<P>
   But the deals are far from struck. Hull told The Republic on
Tuesday that the state is still analyzing the proposal and that
there is concern that it does not provide fair value for Arizona's
lands and likely will need to be modified. The state estimates the
value of the federal land offered in the swap at less than
one-tenth the value of the state land Babbitt wants to acquire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be very hesitant in going forth when you look at the
difference with these appraisals,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the negotiations have been marked by intrigue.
At one point, a Babbitt aide inadvertently left behind her private
notes after a meeting in Phoenix about the land talks. The two
pages were picked up by a state employee, copied and given by a
governor's aide to the news media because the notes seemed to
illustrate a point the Governor's Office was trying to make about
fair value. The incident raised the question of whether some
members of Hull's own staff wanted to scuttle the deal, a scenario
Hull denied Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sheltering land from development in the Phoenix and Tucson areas
could be a significant part of Babbitt's legacy as secretary of
Interior. The former Arizona governor expects to step down in
January 2001 after two terms as President Clinton's chief land
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt made his proposal in a private meeting with the governor
on Monday in Phoenix. Hull told The Republic of her reservations
about the proposal Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The State Land Department believes the United States is offering
lands worth a total of only $66 million, compared with $700 million
for the state properties that would be swapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, obviously, have to protect the best interests of the state,
and (Babbitt) has been in my shoes, and I believe he would agree
that we both have to come out winners, and certainly the people of
Arizona have to come out winners,'' Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt could be running out of time to put the finishing
touches on his legacy. The land swaps would need congressional
approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``These opportunities, when the stars are aligned by virtue of
public awareness and interest, and when the right balance of
bipartisan leadership exists in both Arizona and Washington, come
once in a lifetime,'' Babbitt told Hull in his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   But the state has several times appeared to balk over the
proposed swaps. State negotiators, worried about getting
shortchanged, have variously asked Babbitt for more, including
water rights, an unspecified amount of cash, relief from their debt
from the Central Arizona Water Conservation District, and even the
land under the federal courthouse in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Under the courthouse scenario, the state would have leased the
building back to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt, for various reasons, has not agreed to any of those
proposals by the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure that we will be able to agree on approximate equal
values for these land transfers, and we should not let the
difficulty in achieving that general balance deter us from the task
at hand,'' Babbitt told Hull in his written proposal, delivered
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt and his staff did make a significant concession,
dropping from his proposal a chunk of state lands known as
Empire-Cienega in Pima County. The state simply did not want to
trade those lands because of expectations of future appreciation,
and Babbitt dropped them from consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt said the proposed swaps are a ``win-win'' because it
would not only conserve scenic land, it would allow the state to
unload about 78,000 acres of limited value because it is encircled
by federal land.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called state inholdings are located within the Grand
Canyon-Parashant National Monument, Lake Mead National Recreation
Area, national parks and other federal domains or Indian
reservations. Under Babbitt's proposal, those lands would be
exchanged for U.S. property ``more suitable for development or
other revenue generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Another section of Babbitt's proposal would provide Arizona with
15,234 acres of federal land that the state was owed for various
reasons, some of it land that could not be delivered as promised
when Arizona joined the Union. The state would be able to
cherry-pick from the 900,000 acres of U.S. Bureau of Land
Management property made available for the other exchanges. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 0116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
