<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABIES-DROPOFFS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STATE BILLS WOULD ALLOW BABY ABANDONMENT AT HOSPITALS  &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Legislation allowing mothers to anonymously abandon
newborn babies at hospital emergency rooms without fear of criminal
prosecution easily cleared its first hurdles at the California
Capitol Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With bipartisan support in the Legislature _ and bringing
together adversaries such as Planned Parenthood and the National
Right to Life Committee _ the proposals to decriminalize baby
abandonment appear to be headed for the governor's desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is for the life of these babies that we need to offer their
mothers another option _ one that will offer them hope,'' said Debi
Faris, founder of Garden of Angels, the primary sponsor of one of
two similar bills that began moving through the Legislature
Tuesday. ``We need to encourage this particular mother to take
their baby to a safe place.''
</P>
<P>
   The bills, one in the Senate and one in the Assembly, were
modeled after a law signed last year by Texas Gov. George W. Bush
that allows mothers to abandon their newborns at an emergency room
without fear of criminal prosecution. The author of one of the
bills, Republican Sen. Jim Brulte of Rancho Cucamonga, is one of
Bush's key supporters in California for the GOP presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The California versions are different from the Texas law,
however, because they allow mothers to change their minds and come
back for their babies within 14 days.
</P>
<P>
   Brulte's bill passed the Senate Judiciary Committee 8 to 0 and
goes to the Senate Public Safety Committee. The other bill, by
Assemblyman Ken Maddox, R-Garden Grove, passed the Assembly
Judiciary Committee 13 to 0 and goes to the Appropriations
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The bills will be merged before going to Democratic Gov. Gray
Davis, who has not yet taken a position on the legislation, a
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Garden of Angels
</P>
<P>
   Faris, a mother of three from Yucaipa (San Bernardino County),
started the Garden of Angels in 1996 after hearing on the radio
about a baby boy found on the side the road. She took charge of
burying the boy and two others who were also at the coroner's
office awaiting cremation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In just over three years, we now have 41 children, with two
more girls at the coroner's office waiting to come to the garden,''
said Faris, who breaks down often while talking about the children.
The garden is a small cemetery in Calimesa (Riverside County).
</P>
<P>
   Doyle Tobert of the Los Angeles County coroner's office said
babies have been buried alive in shallow graves, thrown on the side
of the highway or even thrown alive to two pit bulls, which tore
the child apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we back these women into a corner,'' he said. ``If
they were raising the child, and then abandoned it, that would be
different. But if they were too afraid to share their pregnancy
with anyone, than what else can they do?''
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposals, mothers _ or someone else who has legal
rights to the child _ could turn in the baby to a hospital
emergency room within 72 hours of the birth and would be immune
from criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The child would be given any necessary medical treatment and
then would be turned over to the child welfare agency. The mother
or other legal guardian could return to the agency within 14 days
with positive identification and reclaim the baby.
</P>
<P>
   One of the details still to be worked out is how to create an
anonymous system and still ensure the identity of the mother if she
returns to claim the child. While identification numbers have been
proposed, some legislators are worried that someone other than the
mother might use a number to try to claim an infant.
</P>
<P>
   Other sticking points include the rights of the father and the
possibility of someone other than the mother _ for example, her
parents _ bringing in the baby.
</P>
<P>
   Faris said the law now leaves no other choice for mothers who
have hidden their pregnancies from everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should a woman be penalized for putting their child in a
safe place when they can put it in a trash can and nothing
happens,'' she said. ``In addition to saving the child, we will
save the mother from a lifetime of guilt and anguish.''
</P>
<P>
   No records are kept on how many babies are abandoned, but some
estimates are as high as 57 a day nationwide. In a program in
Alabama similar to the one proposed in California, five babies have
been taken to hospitals to be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Brulte emphasized that abandoned babies represent a tiny
fraction of births nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who don't want to be parents use the legal route
and put the baby up for adoption,'' he said. ``But for the small
percentage who abandon their child, this provides the child the
right to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no money will be included in the bill for outreach,
Faris said, she has many people who want to support the efforts. If
the bill passes, a Los Angeles trash removal company that found a
newborn has agreed to place bumper stickers on all its bins,
telling mothers that they have another choice, Faris said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
