<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS: CAMPUS COMPETITIONS HELP VC FIRMS FIND TALENT  &HT;     BY PETER SINTON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ College athletes are not the only students under
the gaze of professional scouts these days. Companies, which have
long visited campuses for annual recruiting drives, are now finding
ways to reach more directly into the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capital firms are sponsoring dozens of business plan
competitions at graduate engineering and business schools, but it's
not entirely out of the goodness of their hearts or because they
have so much free time. The VCs want to be first in line to spot
hot ideas and new talent.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the more prestigious contests don't even have to
win to attract venture capital investments. Take Akamai
Technologies, for example. Two years ago, the team developing
technology to speed Internet content delivery was a mere finalist
in the MIT $50K Entrepreneurship Competition, the granddaddy of
business plan competitions. Akamai went on to win venture capital,
go public and have a market value of nearly $7 billion, even after
losing nearly 80 percent of its value in the recent Internet stock
sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   A new Los Angeles company called Information Technology
University (ITU) plans to get to student entrepreneurs even earlier
than annual awards competitions. It has hired student
representatives at graduate business and engineering schools
including the University of California at Berkeley, Columbia,
Harvard and MIT. Their job is to help student entrepreneurs turn
business ideas into viable businesses with $100,000 to $400,000 of
seed capital and critical support services such as public relations
and marketing, cash management, accounting and administration.
</P>
<P>
   The venture capital arm of Pacific Capital Group, a Beverly
Hills, Calif., merchant bank, has invested $6.6 million in ITU, and
managing partner Adam Winnick says the company is about to sign up
a campus partner at Stanford. ITU should have representatives on 15
campuses by year's end. Scouts like former Hewlett-Packard engineer
and current UC Berkeley graduate student Kai Xu receive a monthly
retainer plus equity stakes in portfolio companies as well as ITU.
</P>
<P>
   ITU CEO Jonah Schnel figures that ``intellectual capital at the
leading graduate schools will continually translate into the next
great commercially adaptable and scalable technologies.'' And his
company should be quicker than long and bureaucratic business plan
contests in finding fortune in ivory towers.
</P>
<P>
   VC STILL FLOWING: Many high-tech stocks have plummeted and
plenty of IPO investors are POd. A new Index of Investor Optimism
monthly survey by PaineWebber and the Gallup Organization shows
that following Bleak Friday, April 14, investor optimism fell a
whopping 12 percentage points, to 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But a torrent of so-called smart money is still flowing into
venture capital funds and chasing trendy startups.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield Fund on Thursday became the latest VC firm to announce
a billion-dollar fund to focus on communications and the Internet.
The Menlo Park firm, which has invested in more than 386 companies
and helped take 109 of them public since 1969, is specifically
targeting ``mobile Internet'' applications that capitalize on the
boom in wireless connections worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The $1 billion Mayfield XI fund, with investments from Stanford,
Harvard, MIT and other endowment funds and institutional investors,
is more than double the size of the previous $450 million fund
raised in June. Despite the current unsettled market, the fund has
already invested in a a dozen companies.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield General Partner Kevin Fong acknowledges that stock
valuations are going down, but he says much of the selling ``has
been indiscriminate.'' He figures, ``even if e-tailers have hard
times, Internet infrastructure companies are changing the way
people do business and are a force to be reckoned with.''
</P>
<P>
   Another local VC firm, Woodside Fund, closed its fourth and
largest early stage technology fund at $135 million on Friday. It
is focusing on business-to-business services and Internet
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Officers of San Francisco investment bank Robertson Stephens
have a new venture capital fund, too. Called Bayview 2000,
Robertson Stephens just joined with Amerindo Investment Advisors,
Dell Computer, Harrah's Entertainment and others to invest a total
of $50 million in Zoho Corp. The Sunnyvale company's Zoho
Hospitality Marketplace is an Internet marketplace designed to let
hotels and restaurants procure goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   Send small-business tips, comments and questions to
 &LR; entrepreneurs &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com,  &LR; or to Peter Sinton, Grow a
Business column, 901 Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
</TEXT>
