<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7335 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKW-WNBA-LADN-(SLANG)     04-26 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS CHOOSE NEBRASKA GUARD
</HEADLINE>
 ... CORRECTS SPELLING OF KUBIK (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After a last-ditch effort to trade for Cleveland's
No. 1 pick fell through, the Los Angeles Sparks waited patiently
for the next-best option in the WNBA draft on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   They started small and got bigger.
</P>
<P>
   With the No. 15 pick, the Sparks selected Nebraska guard Nicole
Kubik, who they hope will fill the gap left behind by Gordana
Grubin, who was lost in the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks then went for size, picking 6-foot-4 center Paige
Sauer from the University of Connecticut and 6-4 center Marte
Alexander, a 1998 graduate of Arizona who played in Italy the past
two seasons. They wrapped up the day by selecting former USC guard
Nicky McCrimmon, who played briefly for the former Long Beach
StingRays of the defunct American Basketball League.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks coach Michael Cooper was satisfied with the selections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a happy day for the Sparks organization,'' Cooper
said. ``As you know, we lost two great players . . . in Gordana
Grubin and Nina Bjedov last year in the expansion draft, but I felt
we kept the core of our team. But I think today we (rejuvenated)
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks general manager Penny Toler, who retired as a Sparks
player last year, said the team's needs were addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The huge difference from the past and this year is we had a
high draft pick (before),'' Toler said. ``This year we're picking
15th. We're so excited about getting Kubik and Paige Sauer. We
didn't want to duplicate what we have. We have slashers. It's the
role players that are going to make a difference in the big game.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's initial plan was to start drafting big to get some
reserve help for centers Lisa Leslie and DeLisha Milton, and then
work his way down. But when Cleveland held onto its pick and
selected Ann Wauters, a 20-year-old 6-4 center from Belgium, as the
first choice in the WNBA's fourth draft, Cooper had to change his
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We offered Cleveland a trade and they turned us down,'' Cooper
said. He declined to name the two players he offered to trade.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper feels Kubik is the answer to the team's vacancy at the
point-guard position, which was created after Indiana selected
Grubin as the top pick in the expansion draft. At 5-9, Kubik can
make the switch between the point and shooting guard. She averaged
14.6 points and 6.3 rebounds for the Cornhuskers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really mind where I went, I just wanted to get
drafted,'' said Kubik, who was born and raised in Cambridge, Neb.
``It's going to be a little bit of an adjustment for me coming from
a small town in Nebraska.''
</P>
<P>
   As expected, UCLA 6-2 center Maylana Martin was chosen in the
first round at the 10th spot by Minnesota, and 6-4 USC center
Adrian Williams was the 21st pick by Phoenix, which is coached by
former Trojan Cheryl Miller.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
