<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7336 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ROTTEN-MOVIES-SFCHRON     04-26 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROTTEN-MOVIES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ROTTEN TOMATOES SITE HELPS MOVIEGOERS DECIDE WHAT TO SEE  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There are some people, of course, who are
perfectly comfortable picking a movie to watch by whether it gets a
thumbs-up or a thumbs-down, or by the body language of a little man
in a little chair.
</P>
<P>
   But others may want a broader sampling of critical opinion
before deciding to shell out $8 on the latest from Hollywood. And
that's where Rotten Tomatoes comes in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically make it easy for people to decide what movies
they want to see,'' said Paul Lee, who heads up marketing for this
small Internet startup in Emeryville, Calif. ``When you have a
snapshot of 50 or 60 reviews, it's a pretty good resource.''
</P>
<P>
   What Rotten Tomatoes ( &LR; www.rottentomatoes.com &LR; ) does is gather
reviews from dozens of different print and online critics and
divide their opinions into two camps: ``fresh'' and ``rotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with brief excerpts from each review and links to the full
text, the site also uses its ``Tomatometer'' to come up with a
consensus ranking of how the critical winds are blowing.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Julia Roberts hit ``Erin Brockovich'' scored a
``fresh reading'' of 85 percent _ meaning that most of the reviews
surveyed found it a winner _ while the Brian De Palma dud ``Mission
to Mars'' produced a fresh reading of just 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A pretty cool idea. But whether this idea can translate into a
profitable business _ as the young University of California at
Berkeley college chums behind the venture are hoping _ may be
another matter altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Rotten Tomatoes began as a hobby for Senh Duong, 26, who had
recently launched a Web-design firm called Design Reactor with two
UC Berkeley pals _ Patrick Lee, 26, and Stephen Wang, 24.
</P>
<P>
   Between moneymaking gigs producing ``official'' Web sites for
movies and TV shows, Duong would indulge his passion for film by
prowling around the Web in search of new reviews.
</P>
<P>
   It was while hunting for word of Jackie Chan's latest movie that
he realized how much easier it would be if reviews from multiple
sources could be compiled in a single location.
</P>
<P>
   After working during off-hours sometimes until 4 a.m., Duong
took the wraps off Rotten Tomatoes in August 1998. Within days, the
site was spotlighted by both Yahoo and Netscape as a must-see
destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immediately,'' Duong recalled, ``traffic went up to a thousand
hits a day.''
</P>
<P>
   This only encouraged him to put more energy into his pet
project, which did not go over big with his colleagues at Design
Reactor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had plenty of discussions,'' said Wang. ``I mean, we all
had hobby sites, but Senh was spending a lot of time with his.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Duong left the firm to pursue film classes at a
community college in Sacramento. But he still kept Rotten Tomatoes
going, and the site continued to draw a growing number of visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The latest ``Star Wars'' movie boosted traffic considerably last
summer, as Web surfers flocked to Rotten Tomatoes to see what
critics were saying. The same thing happened with ``The Blair Witch
Project.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By this time,'' Duong said, ``it went from 10,000 users every
day to 30,000.''
</P>
<P>
   This success wasn't lost on his buddies back at Design Reactor.
Because Rotten Tomatoes was being hosted on their computer servers,
they couldn't help but notice that traffic was surging at their
friend's little upstart of a movie site.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, the other Design Reactor founders, Wang and Lee,
were by this time growing a little bored with their
bread-and-butter business designing Web sites for the likes of
``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' and Hong Kong action star Jet Li.
They were looking for new challenges.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for the partners to realize how much fun it
could be for them to pool their talents and really make Duong's
Rotten Tomatoes take off.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Duong liked the idea. ``We did Design Reactor
together,'' he said. ``I knew how well we could execute.''
</P>
<P>
   As a first step, the partners contacted a small San Jose design
firm called Smart Medium and cut a deal in January for the latter
to take on Design Reactor's name and existing client base. To
maintain continuity with their former customers, the Rotten
Tomatoes crew purchased a 40-percent stake in Smart Medium.
</P>
<P>
   With their design customers taken care of, the guys put all
their creative energy into the movie site. They launched their new
business on April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Momentum was clearly on their side. Under Duong, Rotten Tomatoes
was attracting 1 million visitors a month by December. In January,
that total doubled to 2.1 million and jumped to 3.7 million in
February. By last month, the site was drawing 7 million monthly
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This month,'' said Patrick Lee, ``we expect to break 10
million.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the tough part: How does Rotten Tomatoes turn all that
traffic into nice, tidy profit?
</P>
<P>
   ``For a site like this, an entertainment content site, it's not
clear what the business model is,'' said David Card, an analyst
with Jupiter Communications in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The guys at Rotten Tomatoes don't seem sure, either. But Patrick
Lee, the company's chief executive, hopes revenues can be found in
any of three ways:
</P>
<P>
   -- Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   -- Commissions from related e-commerce deals.
</P>
<P>
   -- Licensing of the Tomatometer and other Rotten Tomatoes
features.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter's Card was quick to point out that few online operations
can support themselves solely from ads or licensing.
</P>
<P>
   And he wasn't sure if Rotten Tomatoes would be able to cut deals
with sellers of videos and other movie-related goods whereby the
site would get a piece of the action for helping users make
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Online ticket sales would be a natural extension, Card noted,
but that market is already dominated by major players like
Ticketmaster and Moviefone. ``I don't think they can crack that,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Andrew Hoppin, chief executive of New York's
Sports Futures, an online gaming venture, said he invested $100,000
in Rotten Tomatoes just this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of faith in Patrick and his team,'' he said.
``They did some design work for us, and they really seem to get
what will be appealing to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoppin isn't too bothered by questions of how Rotten Tomatoes
will turn a buck. Perhaps the fact that his own company is nowhere
near being profitable has something to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume there will be subsequent rounds of capital that will
be required'' for Rotten Tomatoes, he said. ``I haven't dug into
their financial model in great depth.''
</P>
<P>
   However they do it, the Rotten Tomatoes crew will have to come
up with something soon. Patrick Lee estimated that it costs the
20-employee company about $100,000 a month to operate.
</P>
<P>
   With $1 million in initial funding from investors, he said
Rotten Tomatoes essentially now has six months to live before
running out of cash.
</P>
<P>
   Not that an air of urgency hangs over the firm. The mood in the
office is decidedly laid-back, and a clubhouse atmosphere prevails.
``Star Wars'' and ``Godzilla'' toys adorn cubicles, and when the
gang needs to blow off steam, they get together for networked
computer games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone has any fear,'' Patrick Lee said. ``When
we started Design Reactor, nobody was really worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, considering that just about everyone in the office is
still under 30, it's not as though this is the end of the line for
anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worst-case scenario,'' Patrick Lee said with a cocky smile,
``we just start another company.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 0122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7337 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PACBELL-DSL-SFCHRON &LR;      04-26 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-DSL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FAST DSL IS SLOW TO INSTALL  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ SBC Communications, which owns Pacific Bell,
reported yesterday that it has been flooded with orders for
digital-subscriber lines, straining the company's ability to
install the lines quickly and field calls from customers.
</P>
<P>
   The telecommunications company said it had signed up 301,000 DSL
customers by the end of March, up from 169,000 by the end of last
year. About two-thirds are in California. DSL offers Internet
access over traditional phone lines at speeds dozens of times
faster than a traditional dial-up modem.
</P>
<P>
   But SBC said it has only installed 201,000 lines and has a
backlog of 100,000 orders. As of yesterday, SBC said, it could only
install 3,000 lines a day _ meaning it would take more than a month
just to clear the backlog if it received no new orders.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell, however, says it has hired hundreds more technicians,
started using outside contractors and plans to soon let customers
install DSL themselves in the San Francisco Bay Area to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell spokesman John Britton said the company has already
slashed the waiting time this month to 16 business days (or three
weeks) from 28 business days (or nearly six weeks).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pac Bell has been plagued by complaints about
frequent DSL outages, slow e-mail and long waits on hold for
customer service.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are the leader, you are bound to hit some speed
bumps,'' Britton said. SBC has more residential DSL customers than
any other company in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At least twice in recent months, Pac Bell acknowledged that
e-mail was delayed for hours or days when messages started backing
up in the company's mail computers. But Britton said the company
thinks it fixed the problem by adding more hardware and coming up
with better formulas to forecast future demand.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies, including Covad Communications, Northpoint
Communications and Rhythms NetConnections, also provide DSL service
(using Pac Bell lines) in the Bay Area. But Pac Bell has signed up
far more customers and drawn more complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Pavek, who lives on a houseboat in Sausalito, Calif.,
said it took Pac Bell six weeks to install his DSL line, and it's
been plagued by glitches ever since. First, it ran painfully slow.
Then, for the past week, it didn't work at all. Pavek said he
waited on hold for technical assistance for 35 minutes three times,
only to be routed to a voice-mail box. At least once, the mailbox
was full and not accepting new messages.
</P>
<P>
   Pavek said his problems have been especially infuriating because
Pac Bell has been running television commercials and special
promotions to attract new customers. In recent months, Pac Bell has
offered to waive the installation and equipment fees (about $200)
and shave the monthly price to $40 from $50.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got no business soliciting new business when they
can't handle the business that they've got,'' fumed Pavek, who
teaches people how to run alternative health practices. Pavek said
a technician finally returned one of his messages yesterday
afternoon, promising to dispatch someone to fix the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Heritage, who has had a Pac Bell DSL line in San
Francisco for nine months, said outages appear to be occurring more
frequently. ``Pac Bell seems to be overextending themselves, and I
... am tired of their shoddy service,'' he wrote in an e-mail to
The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 0122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
