<SLUG> BC-CABBY-SUSPECTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO FAMILIES, JOINED BY A DEATH AND QUESTIONS OF WHY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-CABBY-SLAIN) 
 By AMY WALDMAN and WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Rivera struggled on Tuesday afternoon to
understand how his son could have crossed over from hanging out
with the wrong people to becoming one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Hours earlier, at 10:15 p.m. Monday, yet another livery-cab
driver _ the eighth in the city this year _ had been killed, just
blocks from Rivera's Bronx home.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, Rivera's son, who was a passenger in the cab, was
in police custody.
</P>
<P>
   While each of the driver slayings, this one included, offered
its own poignant tale of a life violently snatched, this one also
may tell of a life indifferently given away.
</P>
<P>
   The police said John Rivera Jr., 19, the son of working-class
parents who pushed him toward rectitude, was one of four people
involved in the slaying of the driver, 37-year-old Jose R.
Olivares.
</P>
<P>
   His father said he hoped it could not be true. ``He's not like
that; he's not that kind of person,'' Rivera said before his son
had been officially charged. ``I hope he didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Rivera worried on Tuesday, another Bronx family grieved
for Olivares, including his sister Gladys, 34, and his three sons:
Felix Jose, 9; Jose Renaldo, 12; and Jose, 18.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Olivares, one of the dead man's nine siblings, said in an
interview at her Bronx home that her brother had lived with her for
the last three months because he had separated from his common-law
wife, Maritza.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares, a driver for Excellent Car Service, always told people
that he was taking extra precautions, his sister said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't pick up hails, I don't load more than two people in a
car, and if I do there has to be a child involved,'' she remembered
him saying.
</P>
<P>
   But Olivares apparently broke his rule against picking up people
who hailed his cab on the street. Just blocks from his home about
10 p.m. Monday, he stopped his car at East 170th Street and the
Grand Concourse to let in a young woman and three young men.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, the police said, as Olivares was headed west
on East 150th Street, one of the passengers shot him in the back of
the head with a .380-caliber pistol. The silver 1996 Lincoln Town
Car jumped the sidewalk and slammed into an apartment building,
injuring all of the passengers, the police said. The car hit the
side of 255 Morris Avenue with such force that it crashed through
part of a brick and cinder-block wall and knocked in a large heavy
red metal door.
</P>
<P>
   The gun was found behind Olivares' back.
</P>
<P>
   All the passengers were trapped in the car, allowing the police
to detain them for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   And on Tuesday night, the younger Rivera, his girlfriend, Jasmin
Valentin, 16, and two of his neighbors at 3050 Park Avenue _
Norberto Hernandez, 16, and Ramon Anaya, 18 _ were charged with
second-degree murder, attempted robbery and weapons possession,
said Steven Reed, a spokesman for the Bronx district attorney's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Anaya and Hernandez were critically injured in the crash, and
were in stable but guarded condition at Lincoln Hospital on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares drove a cab only in the winter, and was set to switch
to his summer job driving a beer truck in a few weeks, his sister
said, adding that their mother had called from the Dominican
Republic on Monday to say that she had had an odd feeling and was
worried about him.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando A. Mateo, the president of the New York State
Federation of Taxi Drivers, said on Tuesday that Olivares had
emigrated from the Dominican Republic a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that the family is asking themselves today
is why him, a man that worked 15 hours a day, a man that worked to
support his children, support his family, support his mother back
home?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know how they're going to tell their mother that
her son is going back in a box, in a wooden box, as if he was
freight,'' said Mateo, who held a news conference at the accident
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo praised the recent efforts by the Giuliani administration
and the Police Department to respond to the recent spate of livery
killings, by financing partitions and security cameras for some of
the city's 41,000 livery drivers, and by setting up a police task
force to prevent robberies and killings. But he called on the
police to do more, particularly to increase patrols.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares' car, which he had rented for about three years from
the owner, Ramon Brito, 45, had no bulletproof partition to protect
the driver. Brito said on Tuesday that he was scheduled to have one
installed on May 30, the earliest date he could get.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Rivera said that he and his wife, Nydia, had seen
their son on Monday night around 9, in the building's lobby. He
told them he was going to play basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera was laid off from his job overseeing the loading dock at
Salomon Smith Barney in February. So Tuesday, while his wife went
to her job as an administrative assistant in Manhattan, using work
to distract her from worry, he sat at home, watching the news and
awaiting word from the police. He had not yet been able to speak to
his son.
</P>
<P>
   It was not, he said, that his son had never been in trouble: he
had been arrested twice for smoking marijuana in the back of the
building. But as the father saw it, his son was a good kid
influenced by bad peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows right from wrong,'' Rivera said.
</P>
<P>
   After learning at 10:30 on Tuesday night that his son had been
charged with murder, Rivera seemed to be in shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to talk to them,'' he said haltingly, referring to the
authorities. ``I don't know what to say right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Rivera was unemployed, and he had dropped out of the
High School for Graphic Arts in Manhattan. But he had artistic
talent, as evidenced by a scrap of graffiti his father showed, and
he planned to start classes toward his general equivalency diploma
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Rivera had reached the age where a firm voice and a daily
lecture could no longer corral him, his father said, but that did
not stop the elder Rivera from trying.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, Rivera said, he would lecture his son about hanging
out with the wrong people. Each day, including Monday, he said, his
son answered, ``They're just my friends; they're not going to do
anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
