<SLUG> BC-PALMDALE-AIRPORT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMDALE AIRPORT PROJECT SLOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Intent on building regional aviation capacity and
easing the burden on Los Angeles International Airport, city and
county leaders accused airport officials Tuesday of foot-dragging
on Palmdale Regional Airport marketing and expansion efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not thinking big enough,'' Los Angeles Councilwoman
Ruth Galanter, whose district encompasses LAX, told airport
department officials who presented an expansion progress report to
the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demand in Southern California is enormous and growing,''
Galanter said.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of cities and community groups have criticized Los
Angeles' plans to vastly expand LAX, complaining about the
predicted increases in traffic, noise and other effects. Critics
have called for a regional approach to accommodate the growth in
passengers and cargo.
</P>
<P>
   County Supervisor Michael D. Antonovich issued a statement
accusing the city's airport department of delivering ``little more
than lip-service to the work that would be involved in truly making
Palmdale a thriving airport.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Palmdale Airport is a competitive existing facility that is
vital to the economic prosperity of the city of Los Angeles and the
entire county,'' Antonovich wrote in a letter to the council.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Ritchie, deputy executive director of Los Angeles World
Airports, told the council that the department has made strides -
including landing a foreign aerospace contract - and is close to an
agreement with a major airline that he declined to name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not as far as we want to be, but we're going to get
further with the energy behind this program,'' Ritchie said.
</P>
<P>
   He outlined for the council a February report on the status of
air transportation in the five-county area surrounding Los Angeles.
The report said that region could lose its status as the principal
U.S. gateway for Asia and Pacific Rim commerce if smaller airports
don't modernize and expand to shoulder some of the growing demand.
</P>
<P>
   The airport department has worked with Palmdale officials to
lure SR Technics - a subsidiary of Swiss Air that officials say
will inject some $44 million into the Antelope Valley economy,
Ritchie said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the department is pouring $255,000 into a marketing
campaign focused outside the Antelope Valley and plans to increase
the Palmdale terminal's capacity from 800,000 passengers a year to
8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Palmdale Mayor Jim Ledford said the city is eager to create a
functional airport, and that residents support it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be a contributor to a regional solution for airport
development in Los Angeles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the city airports department agreed to develop the
Palmdale air facilities as part of a regional plan to absorb
growing air traffic to the area. The agreement included plans to
aggressively market the airport, and plans for Los Angeles to
provide right of way and easements to enable Palmdale to improve
access to the airport and build a new cargo ramp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think we ought to be a whole lot farther along,''
Galanter said. And, she said, the Palmdale program needs to have a
wider scope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marketing or promoting the airport just in the Antelope Valley
is not going to bring the demand and attention to make this airport
really work,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Hal Bernson agreed, saying Palmdale also should
consider ways to improve transportation routes to the airport,
possibly levying landing fees to build better highway connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make provisions for the future and I think Palmdale
is the ideal site,'' Bernson said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
