<HEADER>
A7345 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BOFA-CEO-SFCHRON &LR;      04-26 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-CEO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 McCOLL PAY FAILS TO RILE BofA SHAREHOLDERS  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bank of America Chief Executive Officer Hugh
McColl didn't have to break a sweat to swat away criticism of his
$76 million pay package at the bank's annual meeting in Charlotte,
N.C., Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders of the nation's second-largest banking company
overwhelmingly voted for all 18 director candidates, including four
members of the board's compensation committee, which approved
McColl's 1999 paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   A union-sponsored proposal to reform the bank's procedures for
setting senior executive pay was soundly defeated.
</P>
<P>
   McColl ran the parlay with military precision, fielding only a
handful of questions from shareholders, according to people who
attended. The entire affair took only an hour and 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That defied predictions that McColl would face a grilling from
shareholders over pay and corporate governance issues.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation that the meeting could turn unruly had been prompted
by criticism from the California Public Employees Retirement
System, one of the bank's biggest shareholders. CalPERS disclosed
recently that, to protest McColl's pay package, it would not cast
its 9.6 million votes for members of the compensation committee.
</P>
<P>
   CalPERS, the nation's largest public pension fund, often
influences other big investors on shareholder issues.
</P>
<P>
   BofA did not release vote totals for individual directors. But
it said that each candidate received at least 87.6 percent of the
1.36 billion proxy votes cast.
</P>
<P>
   A measure proposed by the pension fund of the AFL-CIO, the giant
labor confederation, to have executive pay packages vetted by
independent compensation consultants lost by a similar margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like there was a protest vote of about 10 percent,''
said AFL-CIO representative Brandon Rees. ``We're very satisfied
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to questions from Rees, McColl said his pay package
hadn't hurt employee morale, a point he said was proved by the
success the bank is having in building its business in California.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina bank, formerly known as NationsBank, entered
California in 1998 when it bought San Francisco's BofA and took its
name.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon Trujillo, chair of the board's compensation committee,
told shareholders that directors had set McColl's pay based on what
CEOs of similar companies got, measured over a period of years.
</P>
<P>
   McColl's critics say he didn't deserve his paycheck, which
included $72 million in stock and options, because the bank's stock
performance and financial results had lagged peers in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
