   &QL; 
 &UR; ROTTEN _ &LR;  There are some people, of course, who are perfectly
comfortable picking a movie to watch by whether it gets a thumbs-up
or a thumbs-down, or by the body language of a little man in a
little chair. But others may want a broader sampling of critical
opinion before deciding to shell out $8 on the latest from
Hollywood. And that's where Rotten Tomatoes comes in.  &UR; BY &LR; 
 &UR; DAVID LAZARUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; GROW (COLUMN) _  &LR; College athletes are not the only students under
the gaze of professional scouts these days. Companies, which have
long visited campuses for annual recruiting drives, are now finding
ways to reach more directly into the classroom.
 &UR; COLUMN BY PETER SINTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PACBELL _ &LR;  SBC Communications, which owns Pacific Bell, reported
yesterday that it has been flooded with orders for
digital-subscriber lines, straining the company's ability to
install the lines quickly and field calls from customers. The
telecommunications company said it had signed up 301,000 DSL
customers by the end of March, up from 169,000 by the end of last
year. &UR; BY TODD WALLACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; NETWORTH (COLUMN) _  &LR; When people think of index funds, they think
of words like cheap, predictable and straightforward. Internet
index funds are anything but. In the past nine months, at least six
mutual funds replicating four different Internet indexes have begun
clamoring for investors' money.  &UR; COLUMN BY &LR; 
 &UR; KATHLEEN PENDER &LR;
