<HEADLINE>
PROPOSALS AND PROPOSITIONS
</HEADLINE>
  
 
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Peter Sussman &LR;  passes along a shareholder proxy received from
SchwabFunds. Among the many things to consider:
</P>
<P>
   ``Proposal to Eliminate Fundamental Policy Making All Policies
Fundamental.''
</P>
<P>
   The explanation: ``Each fund adopted a fundamental policy at its
inception requiring that all of its policies be fundamental. It is
proposed that, for each fund above, the fundamental policy making
all fund policies fundamental be eliminated.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_A survey taken by iSwag.com has found that 37 percent of people
who have coffee mugs with their companies' logos on them have been
promoted within the past six months; the promotion rate for those
who use non-company mugs is 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_A survey taken for an erotic mail-order Web site found that the
average length of Americans' sexual encounters is 15 to 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_``I am working with the pet food industry,'' begins a letter to
the editor of the British magazine New Scientist forwarded by &UR; Paul
Rauber &LR; , ``to introduce legislation to enable people, at the ends
of their lives, to donate their bodies to pet food manufacturers.
The human flesh thereby recycled would release thousands of tons of
grain, at present used in pet foods, for feeding less fortunate
children, elsewhere in the world. It is right that the British,
with their love of animals, should set the rest of the world an
example.'' The author offers to send people a sample clause to be
included in wills and a ``pet-meat'' donor card to carry in wallets
or handbags.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Former Washington, D.C., Mayor  &UR; Marion Barry &LR; , who served time in
prison for drugs between mayoral terms, says he's considering
running for the D.C. City Council, ``out of a moral obligation'' to
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Procter &AMP; Gamble has established a sex task force to make sure
that magazines in which the company places ads are not sexually
explicit. ``What we're doing is part of an ongoing dialogue with
all different types of media,'' a spokeswoman told Ad Age, ``in
order to encourage a positive environment in which to advertise our
brands.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Ben Schatz  &LR; was a little wistful to read the line on the film
festival opening-night marquee at the Castro Theatre in San
Francisco: ``Virgin Suicides Sponsored by Bank of the West.''
``Bummer,'' he writes. ``My bank doesn't even sponsor eating
disorders.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Paul Ficklin-Alred &LR; , an online reader, has searched the Atlanta
phone book and come up with some intriguing plots from the page
headings: Ace-Action (a good Schwarzenegger character, says
Ficklin-Alred); Credit-Crisis (straightforward); Loving-Lucy
(``fans who take `I Love Lucy' viewing pretty seriously''); and
Dairy-Dance (picture ``cows dressed in finery waltzing around the
meadow''). Meanwhile,  &UR; Rob Irwin &LR;  found himself intrigued by a page
from his Webster's Ninth New Collegiate Dictionary that offered
``gonadectomized goof-off.''
</P>
<P>
   And  &UR; Bill Williams &LR;  found a Redwood City telephone directory
page that started with the Treasury Department (``those wonderful
folks who bring us the IRS,'' he says) and ends with Ulcer Peptic.
``Who says our government is unresponsive to our needs?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WAVING SUGGESTIONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Considering all the controversy over the state of South
Carolina's flying of the Confederate flag, Vibe magazine quotes
 &UR; Chris Rock &LR; 's suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _A flag in which the stars on the Confederate cross are replaced
with the pictures of African American sitcom stars.
</P>
<P>
   _A flag in which the cross goes sideways and is affixed to a
similarly styled section labeled ``Malcolm,'' so that it reads
``Malcolm X.''
</P>
<P>
   _A flag bearing a picture of a Saltine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Maybe people in America think being a Sir is a big deal, but &LR; 
 &UR; I think we should all be Misters together. I think the Sir thing &LR; 
 &UR; slightly perpetuates one of our diseases in England: snobbery. &LR; 
 &UR; And it also helps keep us quaint, of which I am not a great &LR; 
 &UR; fan.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Albert Finney &LR;  in &LR;   &LR; the Times of London; among the sirs to
whom he may have been referring are  &UR; Anthony &LR;   &UR; Hopkins &LR; , &LR;   &UR; Derek &LR; 
 &UR; Jacobi &LR;  and &UR; Ian McKellen &LR; .
