<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIOSCIA DISCOUNTS EXPERIENCE FACTOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Mike Scioscia had just one full season of
managerial experience _ last year at Triple-A Albuquerque _ before
landing in the big leagues as the Angels skipper.
</P>
<P>
   Not a problem, he insists.
</P>
<P>
   ``For one thing,'' he said, ``I did manage in the instructional
league and in the fall league. So it's more than just Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, you've got to do it, and you never know when
that opportunity is going to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say you're an astronaut,'' Scioscia continued. ``You can train
all you want. But you're never going to know how good an astronaut
you are until you're out there in outer space.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Caution: Scioscia gave shortstop Gary DiSarcina Tuesday night
off _ just one game after he returned from the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to work him in slowly,'' Scioscia said. ``He's such a
huge piece of this whole thing, we're going to need him the whole
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia's plan is for DiSarcina to play again tonight, then see
about Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia is treating reliever Troy Percival, who had shoulder
surgery in October, the same way. No matter how tempting, Scioscia
insists he won't use Percival in a ``maybe'' situation, such as a
tie game on the road, or for more than one inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might get you a win or two in April,'' Scioscia said of
Percival, ``but it might get you 12 losses in August. It's not
worth the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The Elian debate: No one among the Angels asked Scioscia for
the day off to protest the way the government handled the Elian
Gonzalez matter, as a number of players with various clubs did. But
if anyone had, Scioscia said:
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be sympathetic to a player's personal wishes. He'd
have to go through (general manager) Bill Stoneman. He's the one
who would have to sign off on it. But, yes, there are things that
transcend baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia then laughed and asked, ``Now that you mention it, Tim
Salmon's not Cuban, is he?''
</P>
<P>
   __ Around the horn: Doug Mansolino, Detroit's third-base coach
who was thrown out of Monday night's game in the third inning,
attended Long Beach State and is a close friend of former Dodgers
coach Mark Cresse, who is expected to return to the major leagues
soon as an instructor with the Angels. . . . The Tigers activated
second baseman Damion Easley from the 15-day disabled list and put
him in the starting lineup. He was sidelined with a bone fracture
in his right hand. To make room on the roster, outfielder Karim
Garcia, a former Dodger, was outrighted to Triple-A Toledo. . . .
The Tigers are expecting word today regarding suspensions and fines
stemming from last Saturday's on-field brawls with the Chicago
White Sox. . . . Angels right-hander Tim Belcher, in his third
rehab assignment, allowed one run and five hits in five innings
Tuesday night for Triple-A Edmonton at Calgary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
