<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7362 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-`BIBI'-REBOUNDS-INDEP     04-26 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`BIBI'-REBOUNDS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETANYAHU'S POPULARITY GROWING IN ISRAELI POLLS    
</HEADLINE>
   (This 900-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)     
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)     
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)     
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)     
 By PHIL REEVES  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ It was James Carville, the gritty Cajun genius
behind Bill Clinton's campaign war room, who came up with the
slogan which turned Ehud Barak from old soldier into new prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stuck. Stuck. Stuck,'' it said, indicting Benjamin Netanyahu's
performance on almost every front. Towards the end of the election
trial, it was running on television almost hourly.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a year later, the same staccato mantra could now be used
against the man for whom it helped secure a rare landslide victory.
The wave of giddy optimism that flooded Israel with Ehud Barak's
election last May has melted away.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-general is also stuck, stuck, stuck. And _ against all
odds _ Netanyahu is beginning once again to make a serious showing
in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred by persistent corruption allegations against
Netanyahu and his wife, 37 percent of Israelis surveyed by Gallup
this month said that they want the right-wing ``Bibi'' back in
office.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more importantly, only three percent more _ 40 percent _
declared support for the premier.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months earlier, when Barak first took over, the same poll
gave him 59 percent, a margin of 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The honeymoon is over. The neat V-shaped smile that permanently
adorns the prime minister's face is no longer assumed to be one of
confidence but of misplaced smugness.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis seem to be losing faith that Barak, who entered office
with more support than any Israeli prime minister since the 1960s,
can solve their chronic concerns _ war, peace, internal social
strains, the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanford-educated prime minister, with his 180 IQ and aloof
style, is increasingly being seen as too arrogant, and too inclined
to view himself as an expert in everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ehud Barak has become an increasing source of disappointment
for the Israeli people,'' wrote Yoel Marcus, a columnist in the
respected Ha'aretz newspaper, this week.
</P>
<P>
   His task is not made easy by the fact that the government is
built on an insecure parliamentary coalition. It has also been
distracted by scandal _ over campaign financing and now sex (police
say that Yitzhak Mordechai, a cabinet minister and Barak confidant,
should be charged after complaints from three women).
</P>
<P>
   But the central problem is that he has so far failed to produce
tangible results to feed to Israel's restless electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, ever the methodical military man, carries a laminated
card in his wallet on which his campaign promises are written. It
is beginning to look as if the only one of these that he will
fulfill is to withdraw Israel's troops from its mini-Vietnam of
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   As the prospects of a peace deal with Syria have again collapsed
_ building has begun anew on the occupied Golan Heights _ this will
almost certainly be unilateral.
</P>
<P>
   Although Israel will loudly claim credit for finally fulfilling
U.N. Resolution 425, which calls for its withdrawal, it will surely
feel like a defeat _ even though there will be relief that the
boys, at last, have come home and there is no further need for them
to be dispatched to the killing fields.
</P>
<P>
   The cries of victory from Hezbollah guerrillas, who have been
fighting the Israeli occupation for years, will be hard to drown
out. And they will find plenty of echoes around the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
   Two months before the pullout deadline, nerves are setting in
about the possibility that it will flare into a wider conflict;
Hezbollah have sharply stepped up their hostilities in the last two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Three Israeli soldiers were injured by a bomb on Thursday, and
Katyusha rockets _ albeit so far harmlessly _ have landed across
the northern border.
</P>
<P>
   There are mutterings from the Israel military that Barak _ who
has, by Israeli standards, shown restraint in the last couple of
days, not least because it is Passover and Israel's north is
crowded with tourists _ must strike back soon.
</P>
<P>
   Other fronts look no more encouraging. For all President Bill
Clinton's expressions of optimism after a White House fish supper
with Yasser Arafat last Thursday, a final peace settlement between
Israel and the Palestinians remains remote.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said on Monday that
she intended to travel to the region to assess progress and
predicted ``very intensive work'' in the next six to eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Under their timetable, both sides are supposed to have a peace
treaty framework ready by next month.
</P>
<P>
   The fundamentals _ such as the status of Jerusalem, the fate of
Palestinian refugees, the still-expanding Jewish settlements on
Palestinian land, and the amount of occupied land to be returned to
the Palestinians _ continue to represent a huge gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Disregarding its record of expanding Jewish settlements on
occupied Arab land, its flat refusal to budge on Jerusalem, and
Palestinian public opinion, Israel last week demanded more
flexibility from Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The reply had a weary ring. ``We have nothing new to add,'' said
Hassan Asfour, a Palestinian cabinet minister. ``There is no more
room for flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, Barak is a victim of his own image. Unlike
Netanyahu, he has done much to convince the West that he is
sincerely intent on peace. It tends to forget that he is also a
single-minded general, who specializes in hard ball.
</P>
<P>
   He wants peace, but on Israel's terms _ and that's one reason
why he is stuck. &QL; 
