<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALLEY-SECESSION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANS FOR VALLEY CITY UNVEILED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Showing how they think a San Fernando Valley city
will succeed where Los Angeles has failed, leaders of the secession
movement on Tuesday released the first portrait of a new Valley
city and the framework for creating it.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-page document offers very specific recommendations on
some points, from the composition of a Valley city council (one
member per 100,000 constituents) to the election of a Valley mayor
(by Valley-wide vote).
</P>
<P>
   It also lists nine specific points - the group's ``vision of a
new city'' - that many people would say are exactly what Los
Angeles lacks. Among them: ``Improved basic services ... safe and
clean neighborhoods ... (and) government that is accessible,
accountable and responsive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to see a city where there is local control, where
the residents of the Valley control the government,'' said Richard
Close, chairman of Valley Voters Organized Toward Empowerment, or
Valley VOTE.
</P>
<P>
   The vision statement, as it is known, was created at the request
of the agency that must study the possible breakup of the city of
Los Angeles. It will be used as the basis for a study by
consultants of the Local Agency Formation Commission on the nuts
and bolts of how secession would work and what its effect would be
on Los Angeles and the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The document - a preliminary version subject to future changes
as the study progresses - is due to be submitted to LAFCO on
Friday. It was released Tuesday and posted on Valley VOTE's Web
site - www.valleyvote.org - for public review and feedback.
</P>
<P>
   Calling secession a ``win-win'' for Valley residents as well as
other parts of Los Angeles, the statement envisions a Valley city
with a proportional share of the city of Los Angeles' departments.
Close said the group's intent is to leave decisions on any major
changes in services up to the new city council and mayor.
</P>
<P>
   But Valley VOTE believes that by having the departments
headquartered in the Valley, with their employees more accessible
to local citizens, the Valley's residents will have a greater say
in decisions that affect their community.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most noticeable changes would be to the city council.
Seven of the Los Angeles City Council's 15 full-time council
members have districts that include at least a portion of the
Valley, including three whose districts are entirely within the
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   But Valley VOTE's vision statement calls for a Valley city's
council members to be part time, and says they should ``be
compensated fairly but nominally in such a way as to attract people
sincerely interested in serving their community and neighbors, and
not to attract career politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Valley VOTE is working with Assembly Speaker Bob Hertzberg,
D-Van Nuys, to draft legislation that would allow the new city to
have one council member per 100,000 people, or roughly a 13-member
council. That would be more representative, the group said, than
Los Angeles' current council, which represents 3.7 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Cindy Miscikowski, however, said she believes that
full-time council members are necessary because of the many
responsibilities constituents expect of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the sense that at least those communities that I serve
have expected and believe that a full-time city council person
helping to make sure those services are delivered in those
communities is important,'' said Miscikowski, whose mostly Westside
district includes Encino and Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   She added that the issue of not attracting career politicians
was already taken care of by the state's voters when they approved
term limits.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan's office declined comment late Tuesday,
saying he had not yet seen the vision statement.
</P>
<P>
   Close said one of the other changes would be to have the new
city try to attract more business to the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the parts of the vision statement is the concept of
making the Valley business-friendly, encouraging people to operate
businesses in the Valley, rather than going to Burbank or the San
Gabriel Valley,'' Close said. ``The current business license tax in
Los Angeles is a detriment to the Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   The vision statement also seeks to divide the city's services
based on population and geography, depending on which is most
appropriate. It says the Valley has 1.34 million people, or 36
percent of the city's total population, and takes up 222 square
miles, or 47.7 percent of the city's land.
</P>
<P>
   The statement also says that physical assets now belonging to
Los Angeles but located in the Valley, such as buildings, land,
parks, libraries, equipment and vehicles, should remain in the
Valley and become the property of the new city. If the value of
those assets is different than what is calculated as the Valley's
proportional share - based on the 36 percent-of-population
statistic - then an adjustment or credit will be made to make up
the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles' financial obligations - including debts, pension
benefits and current employee contracts - would also be retained on
a proportional basis by a new Valley city, the document says.
</P>
<P>
   The vision statement argues that the Valley is entitled to its
share of ``independent and proprietary'' departments, ones that
happen to hold considerable assets and revenue sources outside the
Valley, such as the Department of Airports, the Harbor Department,
and the Department of Water and Power. They do not necessarily have
to be split up if an alternative can be reached, the statement
says.
</P>
<P>
   Valley VOTE board members discussed the plan Tuesday night in
closed session. They expect to submit it to LAFCO by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 0144EDT &QL; 
