<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS PROVIDE CURE FOR TIGERS' TROUBLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Hard to say which needed the boost the most,
Nomomania or the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Where there used to be as many as four dozen media members
chasing down everything Hideo Nomo said, threw, ate or drank, now
there is one. And that fellow splits his time with one or two other
Japanese players in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers?
</P>
<P>
   They haven't been deserving of that much attention.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday night at Edison Field, where Nomo bedeviled the
Anaheim Angels with his now-familiar twisting, deceptive style, and
the Tigers ended their agonizing losing streak at eight games with
a 4-2 victory before 17,086 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Asked beforehand what he hoped to get out of Nomo, Detroit
manager Phil Garner went for it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``A shutout,'' he snapped.
</P>
<P>
   A bit of a stretch. Nomo's last shutout was his no-hitter, the
one he pitched for the Dodgers at Denver's Coors Field on Sept. 17,
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm looking for,'' Garner added, smiling, ``is a savior.
I might even bat him fourth.''
</P>
<P>
   Garner didn't bat Nomo fourth and he didn't get the shutout he
wanted, either. What he did get was the Tigers' best-pitched game
since . . . well, since Nomo blanked Seattle for six innings two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo didn't get the win. That went to reliever Jim Poole (1-0),
who replaced Nomo in the seventh, then benefited when the Tigers
broke a 2-2 tie in the top of the eighth on a two-out, run-scoring
single by Bobby Higginson.
</P>
<P>
   But Nomo did what nobody else on the Tigers' staff has been able
to do lately: He kept them in the game.
</P>
<P>
   During the Tigers' eight-game losing streak, they'd allowed the
staggering sum of at least seven runs in each loss. Not on this
night. The Angels managed just eight hits off Nomo and three
relievers.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' Ken Bottenfield (1-3) pitched well enough,
scattering eight hits over 7 innings, the longest he's gone this
year. But one was a homer by Damion Easley, who was activated from
the disabled list just before the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers jumped on Bottenfield immediately, their first three
batters _ Luis Polonia, Brad Ausmus and Juan Encarnacion _
stringing together a double and two singles for a run. It was just
the third time all season the Tigers managed three successive hits,
but the second time in as many nights.
</P>
<P>
   The 1-0 lead lasted until the third. Nomo had whistled through
the first five batters, then walked two in the second but escaped
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Darin Erstad, who had three of the Angels' hits to
jump his major-league-leading average to .465, lined a one-out
single over Easley's glove at second, the Angels' first hit. And
Adam Kennedy (Cal State Northridge) followed with a drive into the
seats beyond the right-field scoreboard, his second homer, for a
2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels went on to load the bases on singles by Mo Vaughn and
Tim Salmon and a two-out walk to Troy Glaus. Nomo's immediate
future was clearly shaky, but the Angels couldn't apply the
knockout punch. Nomo escaped by striking out Scott Spiezio, who had
slugged two home runs the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield, meantime, got out of the first-inning jam OK, and
he held the Tigers hitless the next three innings, at one point
retiring nine consecutive batters. Then, with one out in the fifth,
Easley homered into the bullpen in left. It was his first homer of
the season _ and only his third hit _ and it tied the score 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers broke the tie in the top of the eighth. A throwing
error by shortstop Benji Gil, one of his two errors, a one-out walk
to Encarnacion and a two-out single to center by Higginson _ who
had been 0 for 10 in his career against Bottenfield _ nudged the
Tigers in front, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   It also finished Bottenfield, who clearly rebounded well from
his previous start: nine earned runs in 3 innings in a 12-11 loss
at Toronto last Thursday. Bottenfield worked 7 innings, the longest
of his five starts so far, and was charged with three runs, only
two of which were earned.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers added an unearned run in the top of the ninth, and
the Angels supplied some drama in the bottom of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs, Erstad beat out an infield single to short, then
Kennedy walked. But closer Todd Jones ended it by getting Vaughn on
a fly to deep center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
