<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ROBLEDO-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZAMBRANO HAS PROBLEMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No matter how tough it was to coach in Los Angeles, former
Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano remained a cool character, his Armani
suits always perfectly tailored, his hair as slick as another
former L.A. sports personality, Pat Riley.
</P>
<P>
   Life in New York, however, has caused a few of Zambrano's hairs
to rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I accepted this job, I knew it wouldn't be easy,'' said
Zambrano. ``Let's face it, we have a ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Zambrano was run out of town because Galaxy management
felt he had a problem communicating with players, not because of
his coaching. Zambrano left the Galaxy with the best winning
percentage (39-18, .684) in Major League Soccer, but without an MLS
championship in two playoff appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Now Zambrano has the toughest task of all, rebuilding the New
York/New Jersey MetroStars, a laughingstock in New York since its
inaugural season and a team with a famous malcontent, Germany's
Lothar Matthaeus.
</P>
<P>
   If communication was a problem here, it's nothing compared to
what's happening in the Big Apple, where Zambrano finally got some
relief in a 3-2 overtime victory against MLS champion Washington
D.C. United over the weekend to improve the MetroStars record to
2-4.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, the MetroStars dropped to 1-4 after losing to
Kansas City, causing an uproar in the lockerroom afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA has a team like us. It's called the Clippers,'' said
MetroStars goalkeeper Mike Ammann. ``Now I know what it's like to
play for them. You can't teach someone something if they don't have
a brain.
</P>
<P>
   Ammann was just getting started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it matters who we play, it makes no
difference,'' he said. ``We don't come to play. We could play the
worst team in the league. We'd lose to ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am always angry when we lose,'' added Matthaeus. ``This is
not teamwork. And I say communication is very important when you
have a team. We have no communication.''
</P>
<P>
   Such comments by Ammann, Matthaeus and others have caused
Zambrano to take notice. He says maybe years of losing has affected
some of his players, admitting some of them need to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not realize the power of those statements well,'' said
Zambrano. ``I thought that these guys could put the past behind
them, but for some of them it's too hard to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why sometimes change is good, not because they are bad
players, but because they have been through so much, they can't
walk out at Giants Stadium loose and fluid. They think about the
pressure of playing in New York and that works against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say for the first time I see this with my own eyes and
that some of these players need a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning the MetroStars around may take a while. Defender Thomas
Dooley and midfielder Tab Ramos are still out with injuries, plus
New York has a losing reputation (52-82 overall), which is tough to
change overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt in my mind that we have to change the
character and we have to bring an attitude that is much more a
winning attitude,'' said Zambrano. ``I think our guys are
shell-shocked in some ways from all the things that have happened
in the past and I don't think they can come out of it just by me
talking or just by training well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mind you, I tell you that and I also tell you that I don't
think these guys are such bad players. It's just that they are not
able to perform here. They cannot withstand the pressures that come
with playing in New York. That can happen. We need to have players
with the kind of character that can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano admits his patience has been tested by Matthaeus. He
said everyone knew the world's all-time national team appearance
leader would be the first to lash out if the team started losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand his (Matthaeus) frustration because I'm
frustrated as well,'' said Zambrano. ``He was forewarned when he
went (here) that this was going to be a difficult situation. So
it's not like right now he can say, `Well, I didn't know.' This was
pretty much spelled out to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Matthaeus ever be benched for his behavior? He threw his
captain's band at a linesman during the Kansas City match.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, he will play for this team; I won't bench him,'' said
Zambrano. ``I don't think that this is an issue where I'm going to
try to teach Lothar Matthaeus a lesson by benching him. He's a
quality player and I believe could be a very important factor for
our rebuilding, but that is obviously whether he wants to perform
that role or not. That's what it comes down to.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
