<HEADER>
A7380 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-US-SAVED-SE-ASIA-OPED     04-26 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-SAVED-SE-ASIA-OPED-IHT-RESEND-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMINOES: AMERICA WAS RIGHT TO WAGE WAR IN VIETNAM    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...RESENDING from April 21)   (This 1,025-word ``separate-buy'' commentary is from the
International Herald Tribune.)     
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)     
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)     
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``k'' commentary news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)     
 By DENIS WARNER  
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE _ Twenty-five years after the fall of South Vietnam to
the Communists, and the ignominious American flight from Saigon,
the fear that other non-Communist countries in Southeast Asia would
topple like a row of dominoes seems farfetched.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Communist-ruled Vietnam and Laos have joined the
Association of South-East Asian Nations, the group of non-Communist
countries that they previously castigated and threatened to
subvert.
</P>
<P>
   But what would have happened if U.S. President Lyndon Johnson,
faced with the awful choice of opting in or out of Vietnam so early
in his presidency, had elected not to fight?
</P>
<P>
   Soon after dawn on Aug. 17, 1964, a crowd began gathering in
Merdeka Square outside the gleaming white presidential palace in
the Indonesian capital of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   By midmorning, when President Sukarno, the self-styled Great
Leader of the Revolution, mounted the podium to deliver his annual
independence day address, the crowd had grown to a million.
</P>
<P>
   Sukarno once said that to intoxicate the masses was what he
lived for. Never before had he succeeded so well, and never would
he again. His address, interrupted by frequent applause, took three
hours to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   The fiery leader called 1964 ``A Year of Living Dangerously,'' a
title that was both apt at the time and prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few hours earlier, Indonesia had landed 50 guerrillas on
the west coast of the Malayan peninsula, striking for the first
time against the heartland of Malaysia, which then included
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Sukarno was launching an armed ``confrontation'' against what he
claimed was a British-sponsored neocolonial federation. Three weeks
later the air force followed with an airdrop of paratroops into
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Overshadowed in the media by events in Vietnam, the southern
tier of Southeast Asia came close to war.
</P>
<P>
   After the Soviet Union and China had become bitter rivals,
Sukarno and the Indonesian Communist Party, with its 3 million
members and 10 million sympathizers, turned to China and received a
warm response.
</P>
<P>
   A month after Sukarno proclaimed the year of living dangerously,
the People's Daily in Beijing, speaking for the Chinese Communist
Party, linked the Malaysian and Vietnam crises as joint struggles
against U.S. imperialism.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival in Jakarta of Marshal Chen Yi, the Chinese foreign
minister, in October 1964, marked the start of violent
anti-American demonstrations in Indonesia. These were followed by
the establishment of what became known as a Beijing-Jakarta axis.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia walked out of the United Nations and formed an
alliance with China to make Jakarta the world center of
anti-imperialism.
</P>
<P>
   Jakarta warned that if Britain, which had substantial military
forces in Malaysia, attacked Indonesia during its confrontation
with Malaysia, Chinese forces would intervene directly while
Beijing stirred up revolutionary elements in other parts of
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese Prime Minister Zhou Enlai arrived in Jakarta in April
1965 to advise Sukarno to create a ``people's army'' outside the
control of the regular army, which remained anti-Communist although
it was being infiltrated by leftists.
</P>
<P>
   Cases of weapons, shipped in from China as building equipment,
were distributed to Communist youth and women's units in Indonesia.
Communists took control of Antara, the official Indonesian news
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Large numbers of troops moved into eastern Sumatra, posing a
threat to the west coast of the Malayan peninsula. In Kalimantan,
the Indonesian part of the island of Borneo, some 15 battalions
took up positions close to the Malaysian states of Sabah and
Sarawak.
</P>
<P>
   All of this occurred when the situation in South Vietnam was
deteriorating rapidly. The Vietcong had become strong enough to
mount terror attacks in the heart of Saigon. They were also
threatening to cut South Vietnam in two. Regular North Vietnamese
forces were for the first time moving into the South.
</P>
<P>
   Without heavy American intervention, the war in Vietnam was
lost. Washington had two options: It could bow in massively or bow
out. President Johnson decided to intensify U.S. involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Jakarta, only the generals stood in the path of vigorous
pursuit of the revolution that Sukarno demanded. In a speech on the
night of Sept. 30, 1965, he called for those military leaders to be
crushed. That night six generals were killed in an attempted coup
in which the Communists were deeply involved.
</P>
<P>
   General Suharto, who led the successful countercoup, was
fortuitously left off the death list prepared by the coup planners.
He quickly took control.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia went into reverse gear. The Beijing-Jakarta axis
collapsed, and ``confrontation'' with Malaysia ended. Tens of
thousands of Communists were massacred and the party was banned.
</P>
<P>
   Friendly relations were re-established with the United States,
and Indonesia joined Malaysia and Singapore in ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Marshall Green, the U.S. ambassador to Indonesia at
this tumultuous time, wrote that a ``successful Sino-Indonesian
alliance would have created a great Communist pincer in Southeast
Asia, with the largest and fifth largest countries in the world
enclosing not only Vietnam but also the vulnerable countries of
mainland Southeast Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   If the United States had withdrawn from Vietnam before the
attempted Indonesian coup, the effect would have been to strengthen
Sukarno's pro-Communist stance and his determination, with Chinese
backing, to crush Malaysia. It would have undermined the will and
means of the Indonesian generals to resist the Communist takeover.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of the late Indonesian foreign minister Adam Malik,
who became vice president under General Suharto, if the attempted
coup against the Indonesian generals had not taken place, Sukarno
would soon have presided over a Communist Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   In the rest of Southeast Asia the situation was precarious. Laos
was all but in Communist hands. In Cambodia, Prince Norodom
Sihanouk had decided that Hanoi would win in Vietnam and had thrown
in his lot with China. Thailand faced a Beijing-sponsored war of
national liberation. And across the Strait of Malacca from
Indonesia, Singapore and Malaysia had separated bitterly.
</P>
<P>
   It seems likely then that Singapore, Malaysia and Thailand,
caught in the pincers that Green referred to, would not have
survived the pressure. The dominoes would have fallen. &QL;   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Denis Warner covered Vietnam and Indonesia for the
New York-based ``Reporter'' magazine in the 1960s.) &LR;  &QL; 
