<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOT.COM-MOM-IHT-RESEND-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFESSIONS OF A DOT.COM PARENT    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...RESENDING from April 24)   (This personal 925-word ``separate-buy'' article is from the
International Herald Tribune.)     
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)     
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)     
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle
news files.)     
 By AVIVAH WITTENBERG-COX  
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ I was overlooking The City. The executive dining room
was on the top floor of one of the world's foremost investment
banks.
</P>
<P>
   As the co-head of a small Internet start-up, I had a certain
sense of accomplishment. A feeling that the playing field had been
leveled. That the small could triumph and reach the heights. And
that the view was pretty nice from up here.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, I was having lunch with a moderately interesting
banker. And I'd gotten up at 5 a.m. to catch the Eurostar from
Paris _ in second-class, of course, no exchanges. And my daughter
had a bit of a cold the night before, and I was wondering if she
had made it to school.
</P>
<P>
   I was here for the clincher in a series of deals I had been
working on. All of which I had signed. I was pretty pleased with
myself. Pleased with my reflection in the eyes of these staid
businessmen who so obviously appreciated the energy and youthful
dynamism coming through their door with my new-economy label and my
trendy, Internet shoes. (Of course, it's not hard to look
fashionable in a British bank.)
</P>
<P>
   But after a year of frenetic travel, 150 e-mails per day, not a
single penny in the bank and a still-distant prospect of any form
of relief, I had to ask myself: Why am I doing this?
</P>
<P>
   Is it really going to work? All this stock is valuable only on
paper. Even that depends on the day. Am I not a little old to spend
precious mid-career years on something that may not pan out?
</P>
<P>
   My daughter turned 3 when I signed on to be co-director of an
Internet start-up. She will shortly be 4. I have not seen much of
her fourth year. How do I calculate what I have earned? How do I
measure what I have lost?
</P>
<P>
   I have begun to admit and accept my split personality. I am too
much of a mom.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I am ambitious and like to wield influence. Yes, my kids
drive me crazy if I spend more than a day with them both. Yes, I
would like to change the world.
</P>
<P>
   No, I cannot stand missing the moments when my 3-year-old
snuggles into the body she came from. Or laughing uproariously at
my son's apprenticeship with irony.
</P>
<P>
   I will not drop out completely, of course. But I will have to
accept my new self-imposed limits.
</P>
<P>
   Not Director of an Internet Start-Up, plus Chair of that
Professional Women's Network, plus that one-day-a-week commitment
to career counseling at my old business school. Plus mom of two and
wife of one (who definitely gets the short end of the stick). Plus,
plus, plus.
</P>
<P>
   The time has come to grow up and learn to say that
incomprehensibly rare word: ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   No, I do not, like many friends, want a huge house that takes as
much time as a job in renovations, decoration and lawn supervision.
</P>
<P>
   No, I do not want to earn sudden millions. (Did anyone in
business school ever calculate the opportunity cost of cash?)
</P>
<P>
   No, I do not want to talk about my company at every single
dinner party we go to.
</P>
<P>
   No, I do not want never to have dinner parties anymore because I
do not have the time or the energy.
</P>
<P>
   No, I do not want weekends to become a hermit existence
(interspersed with bouts of e-mail) in an effort to prepare for the
next week's high-paced onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   I want time. Time to get down on the floor and make puzzles with
my 3-year-old without thinking simultaneously of the 43 things I
should have added to my Palm Pilot's ``To Do'' List.
</P>
<P>
   Time to listen to my son's quasi-endless chatter and see in its
evolution his growing sense of himself and of the world.
</P>
<P>
   I want time to talk to my friends on the phone, to organize long
and leisurely dinners animated by conversation nourished by the
plays and films and friends we have recently seen.
</P>
<P>
   I bumped into a neighbor of mine at the market recently (the
first time I have been there this year). She asked about my
venture, as one of my most admiring fans. I told her I was slowing
down. She was consternated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to see more of my kids,'' I said. And her face broke
into a delighted smile. ``You are so smart _ and so wise,'' she
said. ``I have a photo of my son when he was 3. At that time, I was
running around like crazy, not paying attention. Then the time flew
by so fast. He's grown and gone now. Whenever I look at that photo,
I cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking to school in the morning with a small hand clasped
contentedly in mine, I have to admit it is not the boardroom. It is
much more valuable.
</P>
<P>
   You need time to fully grasp what you are missing. So I will
walk the talk, making decisions that resonate with my soul. And
tell my ego that life is long _ childhood short.
</P>
<P>
   I have spent years writing and reading about shareholder value.
The new-economy guys have stock options downloading into their
dreams. But last week, I picked up my 7-year-old son after school
for the first time in a year. Delight chased incredulity off his
face. And that's when I knew that my stock had finally gone up. &QL;   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Avivah Wittenberg-Cox is a partner of Internet
Exchange, a Web site for MBAs and business school alumni at
www.mba-exchange.com.) &LR;  &QL;   &LR;  &QL; 
