   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Maureen Dowd surveys family values
after Elian.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Paul Krugman on what's next in the
Microsoft battle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHARLESTON-RESTAURANTS (Charleston, S.C.) _ The city of
Charleston survived the first Reconstruction era, but just barely.
It will be interesting to see how it handles the second one. Around
every corner, the hammers are banging and dust is flying, as
stately old homes are freshened up for sale to Northern
carpetbaggers. With approximately one horse-drawn, tourist-laden
carriage for every bona fide resident, it has reduced traffic
accidents to almost zero by making it impossible for any car to
reach a speed of more than 8 miles per hour. The tourist rush that
has transformed Charleston in the last 10 years has brought an
unanticipated benefit: good restaurants. A decade ago, fine dining
took place in people's homes. Restaurants worthy of the name could
be counted on the fingers of one hand, with several fingers to
spare. Now it takes both hands, and some toes as well. In fact, it
would hard to think of another American city of the same size _
Charleston has a population under 100,000 _ with a more dynamic,
promising restaurant scene. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHARLESTON-GRITS (Charleston, S.C.) _ In a dimly lit corridor
just beyond the bustling kitchen of Anson Restaurant, the executive
chef, Mike Lata, is feeding corn into a one-horsepower mill the
size of an exercise bicycle. He reaches inside a bulging sack and
lifts a fistful of yellow kernels, sun-puckered and as hard as
glass beads, and drops them into a conical hopper to fall between
the mill's two pink granite stones. What emerges is a coarse meal
that will very soon be transformed into a creamy plate of yellow
grits like Northerners never see. Lata may be the only the chef in
the nation who is a miller, too. But the care he takes with his
grits _ controlling the variety of corn, the coarseness of the
grind and certainly the freshness _ is evidence of how important
North America's great native starch has once again become in the
South and beyond. By Matt Lee and Ted Lee.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN-BREAKFAST (Charleston, S.C.) _ One of the things that
brightens the lives of itinerant scribblers like me is breakfast.
As its happens, I've spent a lot of time, over the years, in the
American South, a region that specializes in big, bountiful
breakfasts, at least partly because an energy-giving meal is better
consumed in the morning than at midday in its steamy climate. At a
little place called Hominy Grill in the not-yet-quite-fashionable
Cannonborough neighborhood here, they serve what may well be the
best breakfast in the Carolinas, which means one of the best in
America. This is a place whose breads are homemade, where instant
grits and quick grits and machine-ground grits find no welcome.
Fried eggs are gentled to perfection. At Hominy Grill, in other
words, breakfast is no gastronomic stepchild. It is cooked as
carefully as if it were a banquet. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NOBOOK-COOKBOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Amanda Hesser reviews ``How
to Cook Without a Book'' by Pam Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Salmon with flavored oil.
By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   ORACH (Undated) _ The new spinach, or is it an herb? A Greek
green with potential. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ The column: Squid stuffed with shrimp
with blood orange emulsion. By Wylie Dufresne, his inaugural
column.
</P>
<P>
   FIBER-EATING-WELL (Undated) _ The column: Fiber revisited.
Reviewed by Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ The column: Daring West Coast winemakers
and other discoveries. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
