<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENNYS-BLACKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENNY'S HOPES FOR REDEMPTION AMONG BLACKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SALATHEIA BRYANT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Before Denny's built a restaurant in his neighborhood,
Vic Bonner Jr. had a personal reason not to eat there. He boycotted
the national restaurant chain because it had been accused of
treating black customers differently than whites.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Denny's Classic Diner opens Sunday, Bonner has
pledged to give the eatery another chance because he sees diversity
at this particular business.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see that long line out there (looking for jobs) was
encouraging,'' said Bonner, an African-American. ``It makes us feel
better that it's black-owned. It's showing a true commitment by
Denny's to rectify past wrongs.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite well-publicized, class-action lawsuits that accused the
chain of providing slow or no service to blacks, many residents in
this inner-city neighborhood south of downtown Houston are
welcoming this new Denny's _ and the company's new attitude that
has changed the ethnic makeup of its stores' owners
</P>
<P>
   The Houston store's owner is black, and residents and members of
the Third Ward Redevelopment Council hope the $1.5 million project
trimmed in neon green and red lights will stimulate other
commercial investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one way of putting up a big sign saying, `We're here
and we're viable,''' said John Guess, chairman of the council. ``We
have not seen a franchise come into our community in quite some
time. It says to the community it's not forgotten. We're glad to
see it.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
and Houston City Councilman Jew Don Boney also applauded the
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denny's is demonstrating they want to be a part of our
community,'' Boney said. ``It will point the way for other business
people to see the potential that exists in this neighborhood and
along that OST (Old Spanish Trail)/Almeda corridor we've been
trying to develop for four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Financing for the deal was spearheaded by Unity National Bank,
the only black-owned financial institution in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an investment in a community that hasn't experienced
anything new in many, many years,'' said Larry Hawkins, Unity's
president and chief executive officer. ``We're seeing this boom in
downtown. This will spill into the Third Ward community, given its
strategic location.''
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant is owned by 40-year-old Alan D. Bergeron, who
grew up in the neighborhood and already owns two Shipley Donut
shops.
</P>
<P>
   When he visited the corporate offices for training last summer,
he was impressed with what he saw: diversity and change. He said
that during the training, the company was open about discussing the
lawsuits and its customer policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went much, much further than the federal government
required,'' said Bergeron. ``They made a point to drive that home
to me. They almost went overboard with presenting it.''
</P>
<P>
   While his Denny's was being built, some residents asked him if
he knew about Denny's past. And when he trained in a local Denny's
store, he saw a few incidents in which black customers still were
leery of being treated unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just deal with it. What else can you do?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most publicized cases, black Secret Service agents
sued Denny's after they were refused service in an Annapolis, Md.,
restaurant while white officers were served quickly. U.S. District
Judge Kenneth Hoyt of Houston and his wife complained that they had
to wait a long of time for service at a Denny's in California.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartanburg, S.C.-based chain settled one class-action
lawsuit in 1994 for $54 million and hired a civil rights monitor to
oversee the company's compliance with a consent decree it signed.
Since then, Denny's parent company, Advantica Restaurant Group, has
led an aggressive public campaign to make itself over.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the year the lawsuit was filed, Denny's had only one
black-owned franchise. Blacks now own 123 Denny's franchises.
</P>
<P>
   The chain had no contracts with minority suppliers in 1992. Now,
corporate officials say, the company does 17 percent of its
business with minority contractors, totaling about $125 million.
Also, the company reports that it had a million more black
customers in 1998 than it had in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Denny's has 28 franchise stores in the Houston area and all but
one is minority-owned and operated, including 18 that are owned by
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Hood-Phillips, Denny's chief diversity officer in
Spartanburg, believes that the company has worked hard to overcome
past problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe there are people out there who don't know the new
Denny's,'' said Hood-Phillips. ``We hope people will realize we're
not the same company we were seven years ago. We're going in the
right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   At his Houston store, Bergeron so far hasn't had too much
problem with the company's past. He's turning away customers who
think the store is already open.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Bergeron readies his staff for opening day.
Workers have complied with all the training that has resulted from
the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Near the door, written in English and Spanish, is the company's
commitment to offer great service regardless of race, creed or
national origin. It gives customers a toll-free number to call if
they have a complaint that isn't resolved at the store location.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a perception out there that some folks may walk in
here with a chip on their shoulder. And that's not just here,
that's any Denny's,'' Bergeron told his mostly black crew. ``The
company is very aware of that. They have done everything short of
changing the name Denny's to change that. They've changed
everything from the way the building looks to the way they do
business.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
