</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 0748EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 09:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7482 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA-0427-     04-26 1876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA-0427-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA 0427: A Mattie Roundtree, 100, opens doors to
the past
 &HT;    Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. Photo and a sig/locator map are
available.
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ Mattie Taylor Roundtree has a way of
opening doors for people, opening doors and pointing to what's on
the other side, and pushing people on through and out into the
world. That's what Mattie Roundtree has done in her 100 years. Open
doors. She knows something about doors slamming shut, too.
</P>
<P>
   Her front door is good, solid old cypress, planed smooth and
hung straight in 1924 by her carpenter husband, Lloyd. The big
hurricanes of 1926 and 1928 didn't budge the door, or the frame
house Lloyd built on land he bought for $60, paying 25 cents a
week. But the land was low, wet, and Lloyd found a better location
nearby, high on an ancient dune up on 32nd Street in Riviera Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The men, they rolled that house up from the wet land. They
rolled it right up on tree trunks,'' says Mattie. ``Lloyd, he took
care of me. Me, I took care of Lloyd, and my family. But first was
the Lord. He came first. Lloyd understood.''
</P>
<P>
   For 40 years, Mattie Roundtree's door had no lock, was always
open. Open in the 1920s to kids from the white sand streets. Open
to the whole neighborhood in the '40s when her phone was the only
phone on the street. Open to her grandchildren in the 1950s, her
great-grandchildren in the '80s and great-great grandchildren in
the '90s. Always open for neighbors during hurricanes _ Lloyd built
a solid house. Always open, a portal to both past and future.
</P>
<P>
   Mattie Roundtree is 100, not as big a milestone as it once was.
It's not the length of her journey that makes her special. It's the
uncanny ability she has to unlock something in everyone she meets.
</P>
<P>
   She was born on a pecan farm in Boston, Ga. _ Thomas County,
just over the Florida border. Rural south Georgia in 1900 didn't
look a whit different than south Georgia in 1860 _ dirt farms, dirt
roads, dirt poor. Her family, the Taylors, had come down from South
Carolina after the Civil War. Freed slaves, they owned their farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never were sharecroppers,'' Mattie says.
</P>
<P>
   A good-looking young man lived nearby. Lloyd Roundtree, grandson
of a white planter and one of his slaves. The planter freed his
slaves, gave them his last name and gave them all farms, 160 acres
of good land. The Taylors and Roundtrees were not poor, but being
black they could get poor _ or dead _ in a single night. A wrong
word here, a wrong look there, and a black man could lose it all.
And doors to a better life were barred, shut and locked tight.
</P>
<P>
   The world Mattie was born into and left when she was 20 was
frozen in time by the Civil War. Gilded Age America did not make
its way to the pecan farms of south Georgia. The 20th century
hadn't started in Boston as of 1920, not for anybody, black or
white, especially black, like Mattie Roundtree.
</P>
<P>
   So Mattie and Lloyd set out for South Florida in 1920. Jobs in
the new restaurants for Mattie, carpentry work for Lloyd. A better
life, maybe, especially for the baby. Eddie.
</P>
<P>
   Now when Mattie speaks, you don't hear the 20th century, you
hear the 19th. To hear Mattie Roundtree, you have to let her open
doors to the past, and then you have to pass through. It's an
incredible passage.
</P>
<P>
   A childhood memory: ``I seen that tail star in 1910. That tail
star said something bad going to happen. And something did. That
big boat full of rich white people sunk two years later, and all
them rich white people got themselves drowned.''
</P>
<P>
   On a woman's place: ``My Lloyd didn't want me to work. But the
Lord didn't say to women, `Don't you go out and work.' So I worked.
At the Model Laundry, down on Dixie in West Palm Beach. I made some
kinda money _ 10 cents an hour. Some kinda money ... ``
</P>
<P>
   Don't let the old rural dialect fool you. This is a woman who
went her way guided by her Lord and razor-sharp intuition. And she
went a long way.
</P>
<P>
   Mattie's the oldest member of the Hurst Chapel African Methodist
Episcopal Church of Riviera Beach _ 72 years with the church. When
Mattie Roundtree commits to something, it's for life. She still
takes her daily walk, still fishes, if someone takes her to a good
stretch of water. And her politics? She's a life-long Republican,
to the consternation of her 82-year-old daughter-in-law, Louise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all good Democrats,'' says Louise, who lives with and
looks after Mattie. ``But that's Mattie's privilege and right.''
</P>
<P>
   So you lean over close to Mattie, because she can't hear too
well, and ask: a Republican?
</P>
<P>
   She says: ``Why, yes, of course, because Mr. Lincoln was a good
man, a good president. He freed the slaves. My people.''
</P>
<P>
   She does not simply mean her people, as in race, but her people,
as in family.
</P>
<P>
   You don't meet many Lincoln Republicans anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Mattie Roundtree, armed with an eighth-grade education,
harvested more wisdom from the slack weeds and peanut plants of
south Georgia than some folks reap from Ivy-covered academies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Lincoln didn't want to free the slaves,'' she whispers.
``It wasn't in his politics. You got to understand that. He was
ordained to free them, by the Lord. But he was still a good man.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattie's granddaughter, Doris Heastie, listens and nods and
says, ``Yes, Grandma.'' Doris herself can collect Social Security
now. She lives in a grand new house _ broad front porch, big
windows that catch the sea breeze _ next to Mattie's old house.
She's one of Eddie's three daughters, married to the Rev. Raymond
Hastings, presiding elder of the African Methodist Episcopal
Church, Fort Pierce District. The church, the Bible, the Lord are
the threads that tie the Roundtree family to their past, to their
future, to each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie, Mattie's son, my father, was the first to go to
college. Florida A&AMP;M,'' Doris says. ``He studied French and was the
first black notary certified by the state of Florida. That was
Mattie's doing. She only had that little bit of schooling, but she
loved to read. She knew what education meant. Doors open. Eddie was
an interpreter in France during World War II. Now imagine that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My Lloyd didn't like books,'' says Mattie. ``He thought a man
should work so as to stay free. You know, be his own man, his own
boss. He thought girls should go to school.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mattie, Eddie and his wife Louise won the battle of the
books. Eddie's three daughters _ Doris, Deborah and L'nette _ went
to college, Doris to Bethune-Cookman in Daytona, where she met
Raymond. And the children of the three daughters went to college.
And their kids' kids. All the Roundtrees love books. All those
Roundtrees out there in a world Mattie couldn't have conjured in a
fitful dream, all of them have gone somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth generation is yet too young to go anyplace. Six
generations. Think about it. Mattie Roundtree is a
great-great-great-grandmother. And great-great aunt to 537. The
cousins are teachers, landscape architects, shipyard
administrators, high-tech communications specialists. Distant
cousin Richard is better known as Shaft. The Georgia Taylors and
Roundtrees made their way into a new and, for them, dangerous
world. Mattie Roundtree launched her family into the rarefied air
of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her house was full of books,'' Doris says. ``Stacked
everywhere. I'd walk across the yard to Grandma's for ice cream,
you know, all the treats I couldn't get at home. And she'd hand me
a book. But you know, her real strength didn't come just from
books. It came from somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mattie went house to house at election time, went right down
to the polls. Telling people to vote. `You go and vote,' she'd say.
`It's your right.' Black people couldn't vote, of course. Poll
taxes and such. But Mattie was out there. In 1925, 1930. She was
out there 30 or 40 years before the big demonstrations. Lloyd said
it was dangerous. It was.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattie sits in a big chair. She's tiny, her face shines like
rich buffed mahogany. Big eyes shine bright behind big glasses. She
grips her cane, beautiful long fingers curled around the top. She
listens, nods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was right,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Doris says, ``Yes, Grandma, it was right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mattie could sew,'' says Doris. ``A seamstress she was. When I
was a teenager in the '40s, we weren't allowed to try on clothes at
Burdines, down on Clematis. So Grandmother would look in the
window, just look at the dresses. Then she'd come home and cut
patterns from memory, from newspapers, and make the dresses. The
same dresses as in the window. I wore all the latest fashions, and
Mattie made them all. People thought I was rich.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Girl, you was rich,'' Mattie says.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then there was the telephone,'' says Doris. ``In the
1940s, Mattie's was the only phone on the street. Well, Mr. Harry
T. Moore was the executive secretary for the Florida NAACP. He
worked for Thurgood Marshall. Well, Mr. Moore got fired from his
teaching job up in Mims around 1949 _ fired for his work with
Thurgood _ and he took his family down here to keep a low profile,
protect his family. He rented that house right across the street.
Mrs. Moore took a job teaching at Washington Junior High. Mr. Moore
did his NAACP work. When Thurgood Marshall wanted to talk to Mr.
Moore, he'd call our phone, and Mattie would send me across the
street to get Mr. Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the neighbors said, `Mattie, there's going to be
terrible trouble for us if you let that man use the phone.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mattie listens to the story. She nods. ``It was right,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' says Doris, ``they killed Mr. Moore anyway. He went up
to Mims for Christmas, 1951 I think. They killed him. Blew him up
in his house with a bomb on Christmas. His wife died, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattie's getting tired. She listens with eyes half shut.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to use the phone,'' she says, and you know she means
more than the words convey. She means Harry T. Moore had to do what
he had to do, and that she had to do what she had to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``My people have soared in the last 50 years,'' Doris says. ``I
mean my family, yes, but I mean black people. Oh, we got bad ones,
like the young ones who stole Mattie's money right out of her
Bible, stole her meat right from the freezer. We got the bad ones,
and so do your people. But we have soared . Because of people like
Mattie. People who didn't lie down and die. People who opened
doors, for themselves, for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   It's late, Mattie's tired. Her house awaits. The old fireplace
Lloyd built for her, with the photo on the mantle of Lloyd's father
_ white shirt, suspenders, a Georgia planter. Over there is the
pine cupboard with the ceramic plates she and Lloyd used for almost
60 years. A second front door has been added to the porch _ no
windows, covered in heavy wire mesh, big lock.
</P>
<P>
   The old front door door wears a lock now, too, but still shuts
tight and true, like Lloyd wanted.
</P>
<P>
   If you knock, Mattie will throw it open.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
