<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7485 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-BOOKS-CONNSIDEBAR-KAN     04-26 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CONNSIDEBAR-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGTIME FRIEND AND DEDICATION SUBJECT ADMIRES CONNELL'S OPUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN MARK EBERHART  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   ``For Naoma and Webster Schott.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Half a century of friendship lies behind the dedication that
graces Evan S. Connell's new work, Deus lo Volt! Chronicle of the
Crusades.
</P>
<P>
   The Schotts, a Kansas City couple, don't really know why KC
native Connell dedicated this particular work to them, but they are
pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea and I didn't ask. I was honored,'' says Webster
Schott. ``I've known Evan Connell for 50 years.''
</P>
<P>
   And not simply as friend but as colleague. Schott has had a
literary career himself, having edited a book of William Carlos
Williams' poetry (Imaginations), and having written book reviews
for publications ranging from Life magazine to The New York Times
to The Kansas City Star.
</P>
<P>
   Those reviews included a 1948 or '49 piece of an anthology that
included a Connell short story; Schott met Connell as a result of
that review.
</P>
<P>
   So how does a peer and friend view Connell's novel about the
Crusades? Schott is generally complimentary, but also honest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an astonishing work. It's an endless succession
of events, episodes, all of them with apparent historical accuracy.
... The amount of information that Evan has brought to this book is
breathtaking. I think it's totally convincing.''
</P>
<P>
   And?
</P>
<P>
   He notes that the book is full of ``violence, brutality and
inhumanity conducted on behalf of a spiritual ideal. All of it
suggests that ... in effect, no matter what man says about
religious guidance, he's really an animal on two feet.'' And yet
what Connell has done is historically grounded.
</P>
<P>
   Schott thinks Connell is truly what most writers only say they
are: independent and unique. He notes that Connell, married to his
craft, has never had a family. And ``he can get his possessions
into the back seat of a small auto,'' though he obviously has
enjoyed financial success.
</P>
<P>
   ``To visit his apartment, it's spare; it's like that of a
monk,'' Schott says. ``Evan has led the life almost of a hermit.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Deus lo Volt! fails to become a best seller like Son of
the Morning Star or the Bridge novels, the author will care little,
Schott thinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evan is in nobody's pocket, including the reading public's,''
Schott says. ``Evan writes what he wants to write and what he feels
he needs to write.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Connell's own views, he seems more concerned about his
next book than about how this one sells.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to do now and this bothers me,'' Connell
says from his home in Santa Fe, N.M. ``This happens every time I
finish a book; I feel empty and have no idea what to do next and I
get very uneasy about that, so I hope something turns up.''
</P>
<P>
   Deus lo Volt! originated when Connell found a paperback copy a
few years ago of accounts of the Crusades written by Geoffroy de
Villehardouin and Jean de Joinville. He appropriated Joinville as
the narrator for his novel and imagined a ``prequel'' to the actual
memoir Joinville had written.
</P>
<P>
   So inspiration will certainly come again for the 74-year-old
author. What's he doing in the meantime?
</P>
<P>
   ``Reading and loitering.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 0958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
