<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 10:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7486 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-BOOKS-CONNELL-KANSAS-     04-26 1564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CONNELL-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVAN CONNELL TACKLES AMBITIOUS CRUSADES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN MARK EBERHART  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deus lo Volt! Chronicle of the Crusades, by Evan S. Connell (462
pages; Counterpoint; $28)
</P>
<P>
   His agent doesn't like the book much. His sister is dismayed by
it. His publisher is putting out a guide to help readers get
through it.
</P>
<P>
   But Kansas City native Evan S. Connell couldn't be happier with
Deus lo Volt! Chronicle of the Crusades, the most ambitious but
most challenging book of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Deus lo Volt! (God wills it!) isn't your average modern novel.
It is millennial _ if the millennium in question is 1000. It's
action-packed, but the action is savage and the savageries are
committed by Christians. It is politically incorrect, disturbing,
saddening _ and brutally, brilliantly, historically accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Connell has been fortunate. Commercial and critical success have
united for him in works such as Son of the Morning Star, as well as
Mrs. Bridge and Mr. Bridge, which were set in Kansas City and later
combined to make a Merchant-Ivory movie that was filmed here.
</P>
<P>
   But will Deus lo Volt! fare as well?
</P>
<P>
   Evan S. Connell neither knows nor cares.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthless roads
</P>
<P>
   Prosperity and power can lead to mischief. In 1095 Europe
boasted a growing population, a strong economy _ and a Catholic
Church strengthened by a reform movement that had given royal
personages less power over the clergy.
</P>
<P>
   So when things look good domestically, it's natural to look
abroad. Late that year Pope Urban II declared that Seljuk Turks
were harassing Christian pilgrims to Jerusalem and said the ``holy
city'' must be captured by the West.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of people responded to his call, and what
followed was two centuries of bloodshed and death. Pilgrims marched
to their demise; soldiers and knights and kings went to battle;
even a disastrous children's crusade led innocents to their graves.
</P>
<P>
   And Connell decided his book would cover it all. Two centuries
in 462 pages? No problem _ for him, at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``My agent ... complains that there were so many characters and
they were treated so cursorily that you didn't have time to develop
any feeling for any one particular person,'' Connell says in a
telephone interview from his home in Santa Fe, N.M. ``But I
intended it to be a panorama. As you walk along an unrolled
tapestry, figures appear and are replaced by others.''
</P>
<P>
   Connell acknowledges the structure will be off-putting to some
modern readers. In fact, Deus lo Volt! was rejected by a couple
publishing houses.
</P>
<P>
   But in medieval literature, this ``tapestry'' approach was the
norm. Even the epic poems such as Sir Gawain and the Green Knight,
which do feature strong personages, display little of what
contemporary readers have come to expect. There are no character
studies. The ``plots'' are somewhat dynamic but they lack the
dramatic surges and upheavals of a novel.
</P>
<P>
   So Connell's presentation is authentic. Again, he is asked if
this might not prove problematic for the reading public.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way I wanted to do it,'' he says softly.
</P>
<P>
   He also spared nothing in his portrayals of atrocities committed
in the name of God. This book is not for sissies:
</P>
<P>
   ``Christian fishermen throwing nets just before sunset happened
to see a man swimming. They pursued him on their boats and saw he
was a Turk who, alarmed by their shouts, tried to escape. But they
rowed strongly, caught him in their net and saw he was carrying a
bottle of Greek fire (an incendiary) suspended from his neck. So
they landed their captive as though he were a fish and led him with
his evil mixture through the army, scourging him, reviling him,
after which they mangled his body and chopped him apart.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for being fishers of men.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister is ... extremely religious, and she has difficulty
accepting the fact that Christians would do these things,'' Connell
says. ``And I think that's not at all unusual; I think a lot of
people will be offended by these facts.''
</P>
<P>
   So how does he respond?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way to respond to that,'' he says and again the
voice is soft, noncombative. ``It is what happened and I didn't
invent anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Connell, in fact, allowed himself almost no deviation from the
historical record. Everything in the book is factual except for a
few philosophical musings that he put into the mouth of his
narrator, Jean de Joinville _ who was a real person, too.
</P>
<P>
   Connell doesn't blame his sister or anyone else from bridling at
the brutalities he includes. The author says he is ``not
religious'' _ and yet even he had trouble with the subject matter
at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started working on this book I was coming across these
horrifying things and at first ... I was questioning, doubting this
`Christian' behavior and after awhile I realized that was not how
he (the narrator) felt about it; it was how I felt about it. And so
I went back to the beginning and very carefully excised every
statement or anything I had written that would indicate my doubt
about the Christian pilgrimages.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own attitude is pretty common in the 20th century; most
people would be appalled by the Christians slicing off strips of
dead Saracens' feet because they were starving, and mounting
decapitated heads on poles; these are the sorts of things we frown
on these days. But that is a 20th-century sensitivity.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Joinville, the narrator, speaks with ease of his faith in
God but also his disdain for the Turkish ``infidels'' and
``vermin'' that he says practice a ``counterfeit'' faith. In his
mind there is no conflict between warfare and worship:
</P>
<P>
   ``At first our Church was poor and defenseless,'' Joinville says
early in the book. ``(N)ow she is rich and able to defend herself.
When Christ bade Peter to put up his sword, He spoke for that
occasion only, since the time for use had not arrived. Thus, to
make war against Saracens, who are enemies of the Messiah, must not
be incompatible with Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   Those aren't easy sentiments to swallow in a world that has come
to believe in religious tolerance (even if such a belief isn't
always practiced). But Connell thinks his unflinching depiction of
those times is relevant today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess more than one historian has commented that the
Christian//Muslim warfare from the Middle Ages continues to poison
our relations between East and West even today, you know _ the
Arabs and the Jews and all of this. ... (It) can be traced back to
this horrifying sack of Jerusalem in 1099 and the consequent fury
of the Muslims. I don't think anything can be done about it after
all these centuries, but maybe ultimately we can reach some kind of
accord _ and maybe the book can at least explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   A monumental read
</P>
<P>
   That Deus lo Volt! is a great book is beyond question. It's a
tough go in the first 150 pages, where it covers the years
1095-1170, or a year every two pages _ a dizzying pace for a novel,
even a historical one.
</P>
<P>
   But it gets easier as the reader acclimates. And the emergence
later in the text of England's King Richard the Lion-Hearted and
his adversary, the great Muslim sultan Saladin, add to the
narrative's depth and dramatic fire.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's demanding. There is no introduction. No character
list. No chronology. No glossary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a little ... not a quarrel, but a discussion with the
publisher about this,'' Connell says. ``They wanted an
introduction, bibliography and a glossary and these kinds of
things, but I wanted all the way to give the impression of an old
manuscript rather than one more professorial history. So they are
doing a reader's guide, a separate little booklet ... it has all
that kind of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Connell's historical novel of George Armstrong
Custer, Son of the Morning Star, wasn't exactly an easy read,
either, and yet it became a best seller. Custer, though, is part of
America's own history and legend.
</P>
<P>
   And in Kansas City, of course, Connell is most identified with
Mrs. Bridge and Mr. Bridge, books that concern the daily lives of a
well-to-do KC family up till World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Those books are fairly easy to read. And yet perhaps Deus lo
Volt! isn't quite such a departure after all: The Bridge novels
each are constructed as a series of vignettes _ a tapestry not of
knights, pilgrims and kings but of husbands, wives and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't really thought about that,'' says Connell, who was
born in Kansas City in 1924. ``But I suppose so. I had tried to
write 15 chapters and a dramatic climax for `Mrs. Bridge' but ...''
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't work out for him, and he stumbled onto the more
fluid vignette form, which he likes because of the freedom it
offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do, yes. It can become self-indulgent, so you have to be
careful, wondering if you're not playing tennis without a net. But
with some subjects it works.''
</P>
<P>
   And all in all, it works for Deus lo Volt! It's a stunning book
about a savage time, with a message that crosses a millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the same kind of religious fanaticism today, the same
kind of mindless obsession with a cause, the kind of stupidity that
got us into Vietnam,'' Connell says. ``It's very similar, I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   So things really don't change that much after a thousand years?
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
