   LIFE IN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   LIFE IN AMERICA 0427: Mattie Roundtree, 100, opens doors to the
past
</P>
<P>
   Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. Photo and a sig/locator map are
available.
</P>
<P>
   RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ Mattie Taylor Roundtree has a way of
opening doors for people, opening doors and pointing to what's on
the other side, and pushing people on through and out into the
world. That's what Mattie Roundtree has done in her 100 years. Open
doors. She knows something about doors slamming shut, too. Her
front door is good, solid old cypress, planed smooth and hung
straight in 1924 by her carpenter husband, Lloyd. The big
hurricanes of 1926 and 1928 didn't budge the door, or the frame
house Lloyd built on land he bought for $60, paying 25 cents a
week. But the land was low, wet, and Lloyd found a better location
nearby, high on an ancient dune up on 32nd Street in Riviera Beach.
``The men, they rolled that house up from the wet land. They rolled
it right up on tree trunks,'' says Mattie. ``Lloyd, he took care of
me. Me, I took care of Lloyd, and my family. But first was the
Lord. He came first. Lloyd understood.'' (Reid, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-GRAHAM _ WASHINGTON _ Finally, it seemed that Democrat Bob
Graham _ Florida's senior senator _ was breaking through to the
national political stage. Remembered as the most popular governor
in recent Florida history, he was being mentioned as on the short
list of vice presidential running mates for Al Gore _ hopefully
able to deliver a key electoral state. Then came Elian Gonzalez,
and a high-profile and emotional split with a president he has been
very close to for decades. Developing.
</P>
<P>
   (Lipman, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-POLITICS WASHINGTON _ With Republican congressional
leaders scheduling hearings into the pre-dawn raid to seize Elian
Gonzalez from the home of his Miami relatives, political obsrevers
say the GOP once again flirts with painting itself as the party of
extremists. But does it really have a choice? The Cuban exile lobby
has been one of the most loyal Republican voting blocs for decades
_ despite the fact that Clinton nearly split the vote in 1996. Yet,
there are even signs with GOP ranks that they don't want to go down
this road. Developing.
</P>
<P>
   (Shepard, Cox News Service) Moving by 7 p.m. EST in both
International/Washington categories.
