sheds its unregulated business unit through an initial public
offering and spinoff during the next year. But the utility holding
company will also get the chance to shore up its traditional
electricity businesses, perhaps through expansions into
telecommunications or acquisitions of neighboring electric or gas
utilities. The company is likely to intensify preparations for the
day when deregulation reaches the Southeast and it faces
competition from other electric suppliers. (Quinn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
