<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7499 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS27-COX-     04-26 1870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS27-COX-FILE2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   FILE 2 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the origin of the golf term ``fore''?
</P>
<P>
   A: The traditional vocal warning to golfers playing ahead that a
ball is headed their way comes from an old English word meaning
``in front.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a toll-free number for checking the Florida
Lottery's winning numbers?
</P>
<P>
   A: You'll have to pay for such telephone information. The
winning numbers hotline, as it's called, is 1-900-737-7777. Callers
are charged 77 cents a minute (47 cents of which goes to Florida's
Educational Enhancement Trust Fund, the remainder to the provider
of the service). Results are available online at
www.flalottery.com. For all other Florida lottery information, call
850-487-7784.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Considering all the recent turbulence in the stock market,
can you refresh my memory about a formula that I thought was in
place to stop trading if stock prices fell by a certain percentage?
</P>
<P>
   A: In April 1998, the Securities and Exchange Commission
approved three ``circuit-breakers'' for trading on the New York
Stock Exchange. As explained by Myron Greene, publisher of the
Mutual Fund Timing Guide, they are: (1) A decline of 10 percent
from the previous day's close will halt trading for one hour if it
occurs before 1 p.m., or for 30 minutes if it occurs between 1 and
2 p.m. A 10 percent decline after 2 p.m. will not halt trading. (2)
A decline of 20 percent will halt trading for two hours if it
occurs before 1 p.m. or one hour if it occurs between 1 and 2 p.m.
A 20 percent decline after 2 p.m. halts trading for the day. (3) A
decline of 30 percent at any time will halt trading for the day.
</P>
<P>
   The number of points represented by declines of 10, 20 and 30
percent is recomputed at the end of each quarter and rounded to the
nearest 50 points. The values curently are 1,050, 2,100 and 3,150
points.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these circuit-breaker rules, the NYSE and Chicago
Mercantile Exchange also impose restrictions on index arbitrage,
called ``collars,'' when the Dow rises or falls by more than 200
points. CNBC alerts viewers when these restrictions are in effect
by displaying ``curbs in'' above the current value of the Dow Jones
Industrial Average.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has Vice President Al Gore had anything to say about the
execution in his home state of Tennessee of the convicted child
killer, Robert Glen Coe?
</P>
<P>
   A: Apparently not. Melissa Ratcliff of Gore's press office said
she had researched it ``and not found that he has said anything on
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Henry O. Flipper, the first black West Point graduate, was
pardoned posthumously by President Clinton a year or two ago. The
Thomasville, Ga., native had graduated from the Military Academy in
1877. Where is he buried?
</P>
<P>
   A: Flipper, who was court-martialed in 1881 and dishonorably
discharged in 1882 after being accused of embezzlement, was buried
in Thomasville after he died in 1940 at age 84. The commander of
the all-black ``Buffalo Soldiers'' unit of the 10th Cavalry, he had
been acquitted in the court-martial, but found guilty of conduct
unbecoming an officer. In 1976, an Army board upgraded his
discharge to honorable, but the conviction stood. He was given a
posthumous pardon by Clinton in February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Although reports at the time of the pardon said the action would
clear Flipper's record and make him eligible for reburial at
Arlington, a cemetery spokeswoman said that has not taken place.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our mail is delivered regularly between 6 p.m. and 8 p.m. A
call to the local customer service number did no good and, in fact,
delivery has become worse. Is there still a postmaster general to
whom we can complain? What is the contact information?
</P>
<P>
   A: The postmaster general is William J. Henderson. Address: U.S.
Postal Service, Office of the Postmaster General and Chief
Executive Officer, 475 L'Enfant Plaza West SW, Washington, DC
20260-1200. Since you had no luck with the local customer service
number, you might try the Postal Service's consumer advocate in
Washington: 202-268-2284.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently saw the 1944 movie ``The Fighting Sullivans.'' I
know that two ships were named after the five Sullivan brothers. Do
you know any details about the first vessel?
</P>
<P>
   A: DD 537 _ USS The Sullivans _ was in service from 1943 to
1965. It's now a National Historic Landmark, berthed at the
lakefront Buffalo &AMP; Erie County Naval &AMP; Military Park in Buffalo,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   DD 537 is of the Fletcher class, the largest class of U.S.
destroyers in World War II. It took part in intense combat,
rescuing downed aviators, and earning nine battle stars. After a
Korean War deployment, the 376-foot-long, 2,100-ton vessel was laid
up, acquired by the City of Buffalo, and moved to the city's
lakefront naval and military park, where it's displayed along with
the USS Little Rock (cruiser), USS Croaker (submarine) and a number
of aircraft and military vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The legacy of the Sullivan brothers was one of the oft-told
stories of World War II. The brothers, who stipulated as a
condition of their enlistment that they be permitted to serve on
the same ship, died in the Battle of the Solomon Islands when their
cruiser, the USS Juneau, was sunk. Their loss has been called one
of the biggest blows to any one family in U.S. wartime history.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy again honored the brothers when it christened DDG 68 _
USS The Sullivans _ in 1995. It's an Arleigh Burke-class guided
missile destroyer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Two other Cubans escaping with Elian Gonzalez also survived.
What has become of them? Were they allowed to stay in the United
States, or were they deported?
</P>
<P>
   A: Arianne Horta, 22, and Nivaldo Fernandez, 32, were the other
survivors. At last report they were working for a car dealership in
Miami and hoped to remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Age wasn't the only factor in the difference in their situation
and that of 6-year-old Elian. Immigration policy permits Cuban
refugees who make it to land _ as Horta and Fernandez did _ to
stay. Elian was rescued at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was really upset with myself when I forgot the Discovery
Channel's ``Walking with Dinosaurs'' recently. Is a tape of the
show available?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're in luck. The ambitious three-hour undertaking, which
marries live-action filming with computer animation and
state-of-the-art animatronics to re-create the ancient world of
dinosaurs, is available for purchase. Call 1-888-404-5969 and order
item number 165340. The cost is $24.95, plus shipping and handling
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the difference between the new National Parks Pass and
the Golden Eagle Passport that I used to hear so much about? Both
cost $50.
</P>
<P>
   A: The new pass ``is more or less a substitute for the Golden
Eagle,'' said Paul Winegar of the National Park Service. It allows
entry for a year from date of purchase into National Park Service
sites that charge admission.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Eagle _ whose price has been raised to $65,
incidentally _ allows entry for a year from date of purchase into
other federal recreation areas as well, such as those managed by
the Forest Service, the Fish and Wildlife Service, and the Army
Corps of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Winegar explained that you can buy the new National Parks Pass
for $50 and pay an additional $15 for a sticker that gives access
to all the sites allowed by the Golden Eagle.
</P>
<P>
   For information on the new pass, call 1-888-467-2757 or check
online at www.nationalparks.org/pass/html.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently reported on the cost of gasoline in Canada. For
comparison, can you give us some sample prices of the cost of
gasoline in Europe, where prices historically have been higher than
here?
</P>
<P>
   A: In Europe, where taxes account for about three-quarters of
the cost of gasoline in most countries, prices have approached the
equivalent of $4 U.S. a gallon for years. Gasoline prices in many
European countries have jumped at least 20 percent just in the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   Sample national averages (changing local currencies to
equivalent U.S. dollars and quantities in which sold to equivalent
gallons) as of March 20, as reported by the Energy Information
Administration: France, $4.06; Italy, $3.93; and Germany, $3.77.
The U.S. average on the same date was $1.71. Britain's prices are
higher _ $4.66 a gallon _ because the value of the British pound
has climbed sharply against most other currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The U.S. House of Representatives recently appointed a
Catholic chaplain. Some reports called him the first and only
Catholic chaplain of the House, but at least one newspaper said
there was a Catholic chaplain before. Which is correct?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Rev. Daniel Coughlin, who was appointed March 23, is the
first Catholic priest to become the House chaplain. The Senate has
had one Roman Catholic chaplain _ Charles C. Pise, appointed Dec.
11, 1832 _ which may be the point of confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Since William Lynn, a Presbyterian from Philadelphia, was
appointed the first House chaplain in 1789, House chaplains have
come from nine denominations: Methodist (21), Presbyterian (17),
Baptist (8), Episcopalian (4), Christian (2), Congregationalist
(2), Unitarian (2), Lutheran (1), and Universalist (1).
</P>
<P>
   The first Senate chaplain was Samuel Provoost, an Episcopalian
from New York, also appointed in 1789. In all, Senate chaplains
have represented eight Denominations: Episcopalian (19), Methodist
(17), Presbyterian (14), Baptist (6), Unitarian (2),
Congregationalist (1), Lutheran (1), and Roman Catholic (1). The
current Senate chaplain is Lloyd Ogilvie, a Presbyterian who has
served since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A reported on House chaplains, which raised a question in
my mind. Doesn't the concept of having chaplains for Congress
impinge upon the separation of church and state? Also, why not
widen the base, for example having a Christian this time, a rabbi
the next, Muslim, Buddhist and so forth?
</P>
<P>
   A: Over the years, critics have charged that the practice of
official chaplains violates the concept of separation of church and
state. But in 1983, the Supreme Court upheld the practice as deeply
ingrained in the nation's history and tradition. The court stated
that the ultimate authority for the position lies in the
Constitution, which says the House and Senate each may choose their
officers, with no restrictions on what kind of officers may be
chosen. Using that authority, both chambers have chosen to continue
to elect an officer as chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   While all the official chaplains have been Christians, guest
chaplains _ who are invited about twice a month _ have come from
other faiths, including Judaism, Islam, Native American religions
and others. Regardless of denomination, it's expected that clergy
selected to serve as chaplain will do so not as a denominational
advocate, but as an individual pastor sensitive to diverse
religious backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
