<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAUCE-SIDE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mrs. Wrights' Sauce a condiment for all occasions
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Jamese Wright calls her mother`s sauce ``a
condiment.'' A peppery condiment.
</P>
<P>
   And it is unique. It's not a barbecue sauce _ though it goes on
ribs and wings. One backer described it as ``somewhere between
ketchup and Worcestershire sauce.'' But the texture is closer to
A-1. And the original is more spicy than sweet, made with an
abundance of peppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember as a child we used to sit in the kitchen and take
bread and dip it,'' the younger Wright says. Her mother always
cooked with it. Sometimes dinner would be spaghetti ``with those
huge hot franks, fried onions with tomato sauce and tomato paste,
and then we'd throw our sauce in it. Mom would mix the sauce into
hamburger and we'd put it on top. We would smoke with it and the
neighborhood would start smelling the sauce and come over.''
</P>
<P>
   Now customers who have bought Mrs. Wrights' Sauce have shared
their ideas for using it, adding it to Bloody Marys, spicing up
soups, stews and sauces as well as chili and gumbo. Some fans turn
to it as a marinade for beef and steaks, brisket and chicken.
</P>
<P>
   The sauce is available in the original spicy version and a mild
one created by the daughter to meet customer demand. She has also
came up with a spicy spread, a concentrate made with the
long-cooked peppers in the original sauce, to be used sparingly in
everything from a pot of chili to a cream cheese dip.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for the people who are not weak of heart,'' she says.
``At home we call it the `boomerang spread.'''
</P>
<P>
   This month the pepper spread won a third place New Product Award
in Chile Pepper magazine's Fiery Food Challenge. The sauce also won
third in the meat sauce competition.
</P>
<P>
   Both the original spicy and mild sauce are made in Englewood and
retail for $4.95 for a 12-ounce jar. It is marketed under the
clever slogan ``How can you go wrong with Mrs. Wrights?''.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
