<HEADER>
A7501 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-SAUCE27-COX     04-26 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAUCE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Making a pitch for the home team
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When Dayton Dragons fans buy their first hot dogs
and burgers at Fifth Third Field today, they'll find something new
alongside the ketchup and mustard bottles _ Mrs. Wrights' Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hometown sauce with an 115-year history. It comes with a
story of a dedicated daughter who went to bat for her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wright is Daytonian Bobby Wright, who took over as keeper
of the family sauce recipe 30 years ago. It had been passed down
from her great-grandmother, who created the sauce more than 100
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the special sauce would be just a treasured family recipe
were it not for Bobby Wright's daughter Jamese, 41, who was named
for her father James.
</P>
<P>
   Like her brothers, Jamese Wright had moved away from Dayton,
following careers first in the Air Force and later with an Austin,
Texas, firm that made computer parts. Then in the mid-1990s, her
father died. Her mother, an active woman whose jobs over the years
included being a model, an IRS agent and a Realtor, went into deep
depression. She stayed home, eventually retreating to her bedroom,
coming out only to feed the little dog her husband had given her
just days before he died.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Jamese Wright became a victim of company
downsizing. She was planning to use her severance pay for a
sabbatical, starting with a cruise to Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``But something stopped me,'' she said. ``I came home.''
</P>
<P>
   When she saw her mother's condition, everything changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was losing her. I thought that if she knew I needed her help
that would bring her out of her depression. That's what gave me the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I canceled everything and I told her, `I've been telling you
for years you're sitting on a gold mine with this sauce,' and I
made her teach me how to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Mrs. Wright showed no interest in the project. But at
the end of two weeks her daughter knew how to make the sauce. She
became the fourth-generation keeper of the recipe. And she became a
daughter with a mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took all my money and put it in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   First, she went back to Austin. A friend who had a restaurant
let her use the kitchen to start making and bottling the sauce.
Because of government regulations and the realities of setting up a
new business, it took months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sold my first little 5-ounce bottle on Sept. 8, 1998, to a
customer who came into the restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   And she sent a case to her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's when she realized I was serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wright certainly acknowledged her daughter's ``gumption.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `If she can do all this, I can get out of my
bedroom.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she saved her mother's life,'' Mrs. Wright says.
``That's what got me out _ the sauce.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wright starting going to stores, marketing the family
sauce. Her first sales were to The Little Store and Christy's
Restaurant in the Dayton area.
</P>
<P>
   She heard about the minor league baseball team coming to a new
downtown stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard they were really going to build it, I thought, `A
home team needs to use a home product.'''
</P>
<P>
   She met with Dave Levey, general manager for Sports Service
(which operates the ballpark concessions). Levy said, ``We keep
telling people we have to get someone local in here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `I heard you calling and here I am.'''
</P>
<P>
   So her family sauce will be among the more familiar condiments
at the ballpark. And the two women may be on the way to their goal
of making Mrs. Wrights' Sauce a household word.
</P>
<P>
   But now that Jamese Wright has moved back to Dayton she has
added another dream. While she works at the Dayton Mall, she says,
``I'd like to have a little place where I can make the sauce and
sell it with some chicken and ribs.''
</P>
<P>
   And her 67-year-old mother, now a part of the dreaming, adds,
``We'd like to be downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
