<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Thursday, April
27, 2000, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   LIFE IN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   LIFE IN AMERICA 0427: Mattie Roundtree, 100, opens doors to the
past
</P>
<P>
   Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. Photo and a sig/locator map are
available.
</P>
<P>
   RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ Mattie Taylor Roundtree has a way of
opening doors for people, opening doors and pointing to what's on
the other side, and pushing people on through and out into the
world. That's what Mattie Roundtree has done in her 100 years. Open
doors. She knows something about doors slamming shut, too. Her
front door is good, solid old cypress, planed smooth and hung
straight in 1924 by her carpenter husband, Lloyd. The big
hurricanes of 1926 and 1928 didn't budge the door, or the frame
house Lloyd built on land he bought for $60, paying 25 cents a
week. But the land was low, wet, and Lloyd found a better location
nearby, high on an ancient dune up on 32nd Street in Riviera Beach.
``The men, they rolled that house up from the wet land. They rolled
it right up on tree trunks,'' says Mattie. ``Lloyd, he took care of
me. Me, I took care of Lloyd, and my family. But first was the
Lord. He came first. Lloyd understood.'' (Reid, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   POOCH-INSURANCE _Maybe Old Yeller didn't have to die. Just when
it seemed insurance couldn't get any more complicated here in
America, along comes pet insurance. If not an entirely new concept
(one company's been selling the stuff since 1983 in _ where else? _
California) insuring pets is an idea that's taken off like Air Bud
in the last year. In some ways, it's a kinder, gentler process than
insuring humans _ policy holders get to choose their own
veterinarians, rather than spend hours sitting in some doggie HMO.
In other ways, it's just as bad _ just as many humans can't buy
coverage for partners or non-immediate family members, Internet
insurance giant insWeb won't let you
</P>
<P>
