<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Our wascally agents laid egg in raid
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I've thought up a way the federal government
could appear a little less heavy-handed the next time it conducts a
raid involving an impressionable young child.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion would be to dress up all of those menacing federal
agents in kid-friendly mascot suits _ you know, like Sylvester the
Cat, Tweety Bird and Bugs Bunny. ``Eh, what's up, Doc? Spread
'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, thanks to our unimaginative federal government,
America has come across to the rest of the globe as a bunch of
mean-spirited, weapons-toting goons. Just imagine how less ugly our
country would have looked if that agent in the infamous Associated
Press photo had been dressed for the occasion in a festive purple
Barney outfit, instead of those scary, olive-drab fatigues. If the
agent taking 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez from his Miami relatives had
been wearing a Barney outfit and singing, ``I love you, you love
me,'' the kid might have been smiling for the birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Heck. He might have even pulled Barney's tail. Why scare the kid
when you can give him a chance to jerk your tail?
</P>
<P>
   Much of the outrage being directed at America is based on
perception. Would the raid to reunite the child with his father
have been viewed as quite so dastardly if our federal agents had
been decked out in a colorful assortment of Disney costumes? The
kid probably wouldn't have been quite so frightened if he had been
taken away by, say, Huey, Dewey and Louie. Or Yosemite Sam. Or even
the Famous San Diego Chicken. The Chicken could have plucked him
out of there.
</P>
<P>
   And if you had some short agents, you could always do the Seven
Dwarfs thing. They enter the home singing, ``Whistle while you
work. Castro is a jerk. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Would America look so nasty to the rest of the world if that AP
photo had shown a federal agent in an Elmer Fudd outfit carrying
one of those cartoon guns with a horn on the end? Nah.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of side advantages to my plan. For one, Janet
Reno's gotta look less like Miss Transylvania dressed in a Barney
suit than she does in those dowdy clothes she runs around in. Is
she taking fashion tips from the Addams family?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, when you start using Disney characters, that means
you've got an instant corporate sponsor. Think of the advertising
campaign. ``Where you goin', Elian?'' ``I'm going to Disney
World.'' Let Disney or Warner Bros. pick up the tab on the raid in
exchange for advertising. Save the taxpayers some bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Better still, if the boy had been apprehended by agents wearing
theme-park outfits, he might be afraid to go to Disney World for
the rest of his life. Parents, as you know, that ain't all bad.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't anybody at the federal level have any snap? This is a
kid we're dealing with. The raid took place the day before Easter.
Put two and two together, you knuckleheads. Use your noggins for
something other than a bulletproof helmet. Why weren't the agents
dressed like the Easter Bunny and his chicken assistants?
</P>
<P>
   This raid would have taken on a softer tone if the agents had
been carrying gigantic colored polyurethane eggs. But since the
agents weren't carrying these eggs, they laid one.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso's humor column appears in the Austin
American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
