<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7505 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS27-COX-     04-26 1857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS27-COX-FILE1 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   FILE 1 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the outcome of Muhammad Ali's refusal to serve in
the armed forces in the 1960s? Were any criminal charges made
against him?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. In 1967, Ali, under his previous name, Cassius Clay, was
convicted of violation of Selective Service laws by a federal court
in Houston, which imposed a $10,000 fine and five-year prison
sentence. He remained out of jail pending appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department had advised Ali's draft board in
Louisville, Ky., to reject the fighter's claim of conscientious
objector status on three grounds: that his anti-war beliefs weren't
sincere, that they weren't based on religious training, and that he
didn't object to all wars. The board then rejected Ali's claim
without giving grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department later conceded that Ali's beliefs were
sincere and religious _ grounded in the Black Muslim faith _ but it
insisted that he didn't object to all wars, and the conviction
should stand.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court held that whether Ali opposed all wars was
immaterial, since the draft board had been wrongly advised and gave
no indication of what grounds it chose to disallow his claim. In a
unanimous ruling in June 1971, the Supreme Court reversed the
conviction and prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can we contact Janet Reno by mail or e-mail to express
our opinion about her action in the Elian Gonzalez case?
</P>
<P>
   A: The mailing address: Office of the Attorney General,
Department of Justice, 10th Street and Constitution Avenue N.W.,
Washington, DC 20530. Comments can be made by calling 202-616-0019;
faxes can be sent to 202-514-5331. The Justice Department says
there is no e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My husband and I heard about a ``nine-alarm'' fire. We've
never known of anything more than a three- or four-alarm fire. What
do the various numbers of alarms mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: The numbers simply refer to the resources needed to fight the
fire, as determined by the chief in charge. The higher the number,
the more units and manpower necessary to bring the fire under
control. A recent fire at a yacht club and pier in Boston was
nine-alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Iannone, senior editor of Firehouse.Com in College Park,
Md., said there's no national standard on what is meant by the
various numbers. For example, one alarm in a rural area might mean
a response from one fire station, and a second alarm means a second
station. Something even more serious would call for a general alarm
and an ``all call'' would mean all available manpower in a wide
area.
</P>
<P>
   But in Iannone's location, outside Washington, D.C., a first
alarm consists of four engine companies, two ladder trucks and a
rescue squad (involving seven stations), while a second alarm would
bring resources from another six or seven stations.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors, such as the types of structures, resources, and
manpower available at any given location, also figure into the
meaning of the number of alarms, he added. There's no maximum
number, but in many cities a ``general alarm'' means all available
manpower and units.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did the $ symbol for dollar originate?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Bureau of Engraving and Printing and World Book
Encyclopedia explain that there's no definitive answer, but the
most widely accepted explanation is that it evolved from the
Mexican or Spanish P's for pesos, or piastres, or pieces of eight.
</P>
<P>
   Another theory is that it derives from US, with the S atop the
U.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm curious about the logo of Circle K, the popular
convenience store chain. Do you know where it originated?
</P>
<P>
   A: The K in Circle K comes from the name of Kay Misenheimer,
operator of three Kay's Food Stores in El Paso, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The stores were purchased in 1951 by Fred Hervey of El Paso who,
as a boy, already was showing a good nose for business with the
tried-and-true concept of ``location, location, location.'' He was
savvy enough to relocate his soda stand from one of the city's
busiest corners, where it wasn't always convenient for motorists to
stop, to outside his father's open-air theater, which proved to be
a natural.
</P>
<P>
   The Circle K logo was adopted in 1957, and was chosen because _
as a nod to El Paso's Western location _ it resembled a cattle
brand. The logo has been updated now with a bolder look to the K,
said Julie Igo of the parent Tosco Corp. But the basic logo has
been kept to emphasize the Western heritage of the convenience
stores, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does the Federal Reserve do?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Federal Reserve System is an independent agency of the
U.S. government. It helps oversee the nation's banking system
through 12 Federal Reserve banks and 25 branches.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, its most important job is to assist the U.S.
government in managing the economy by encouraging economic growth
and controlling inflation, pursuing these goals by influencing
interest rates and thus the availability of money and loans.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed gets no money from Congress. It raises all its operating
expenses from investment income and fees for its services. It
reports to Congress about its proposed policies, but is legally
free to make its own policy decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has a seven-member Board of Governors, with each member
appointed by the president to a 14-year term, subject to Senate
confirmation. A president normally appoints only two Fed governors
during a four-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Much has been made recently of the lackluster academic
performances of both George W. Bush and Al Gore when they attended
Ivy League institutions. I thought that to be awarded a Rhodes
scholarship, as Gore was, a person had to have stellar academic
credentials. What gives?
</P>
<P>
   A: Rhodes scholarships are awarded in part to people deemed to
be potential leaders, with the aim of providing them an opportunity
to study at Oxford University in England. By definition, the word
``scholar'' implies, as you say, ``stellar academic credentials.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's a problem here. Gore was never a Rhodes scholar. He
received a degree in government with honors from Harvard University
in 1969, and after a stint in the Army attended Vanderbilt
University Divinity School and Vanderbilt Law School without
obtaining a degree from either one.
</P>
<P>
   You may be thinking of Bill Bradley, who was a Rhodes scholar at
Oxford from 1965 to 1967. President Clinton, of course, also was a
Rhodes scholar.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I remember reading that Clinton didn't finish his studies at
Oxford. Am I correct?
</P>
<P>
   A: Clinton didn't earn a degree at Oxford, if that's what you
mean. He attended Oxford for two years as a Rhodes scholar after
graduating from Georgetown University in 1968. He gave up a third
year of study at Oxford in favor of attending Yale University Law
School, from which he earned his law degree in 1973. In 1994,
Oxford awarded him an honorary doctorate in civil law.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who were the members of the three-judge federal appeals court
that extended a temporary ban on removing Elian Gonzalez from the
United States. Was their ruling unanimous?
</P>
<P>
   A: The order was issued by Judges J.L. Edmonson, Joel Dubina and
Charles Wilson. It was unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the academic and professional credentials of Dr.
Irwin Redlener, who was appointed by Attorney General Janet Reno to
advise the government about transferring Elian Gonzalez to his
father? Has he been involved in government duties before?
</P>
<P>
   A: Redlener is president and co-founder of the Children's Health
Fund, a philanthropic initiative created to develop and support
health care programs for medically underserved children. He's also
a professor of pediatrics at the Albert Einstein College of
Medicine and lecturer in pediatrics at Harvard Medical School. And
at Montefiore Medical Center in New York, he's president of the
Children's Hospital, director of the Child Health Network, and
director of community pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
   He received his medical degree at the University of Miami (Fla.)
School of Medicine and pediatric training at Babies Hospital of the
Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center in New York, the University of
Colorado Medical Center, and the University of Miami-Jackson
Memorial Hospital in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Redlener has had many government-related roles, including
serving as co-chairman of the Healthy Start Advisory Group for
America's Promise: The Alliance for Youth, and chairman of the
National Advisory Council on the National Health Service Corps. He
also has been a physician special consultant to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   He has been published, spoken and testified widely on health
care for homeless and indigent children, child abuse and neglect,
and national health policy. In 1993, he was vice chairman of the
health professional review group for the White House Task Force on
national health care reform.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Over the years, I've heard that Liz Claiborne, the fashion
designer, supports satanic worship. Can you shed any light on it? I
have boycotted buying her clothing.
</P>
<P>
   A: There's ``absolutely no truth'' to these rumors, said a
spokeswoman for Liz Claiborne Inc. She added that the rumor tends
to be circulated for a time, then dies out when people discover
it's not true, and then begins circulating again when someone else
hears and spreads it.
</P>
<P>
   The rumor sometimes includes the assertion _ also false _ that
Liz Claiborne talked about her ``devil donations'' on ``Oprah
Winfrey.''
</P>
<P>
   When the rumor first began making the rounds, the company
decided to respond to consumer inquiries on an individual basis
instead of launching a major counterattack in the media. That
seemed to work. The rumor hasn't affected the company's sales, the
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm considering building a shelter in my basement in case of
tornadoes. Do any government agencies provide plans?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. The Federal Emergency Management Agency has just what
you need to build a residential ``safe room,'' or have a contractor
do it for you. And as FEMA spokeswoman Mary Hudak pointed out, your
question is particularly timely, with storm season approaching and
the report of a recent survey of people in 15 tornado-prone states
showing that most residents have taken no action to safeguard their
homes and families.
</P>
<P>
   But there's help, and it's as near as your computer or your
telephone. Shelter information can be found online at
www.fema.gov/mit/saferoom, or you can call toll-free 1-888-565-3896
and ask for FEMA publication 320 (Taking Shelter From the Storm,
Building a Safe Room Inside Your House) and/or 320A. Publication
320 discusses different shelters, Hudak said, while 320A gives
details about specific construction techniques, specifications and
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Other useful tornado safety information can be found online at
www.fema.gov/library/tornadof.htm
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
