<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTSNBOLTS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't let cracks in driveway turn into potholes
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When it comes to driveways, there are two camps:
those who care about cracks and those who don't.
</P>
<P>
   I place myself in the latter group. An occasional tuft of grass
rising through the pavement doesn't bother me at all.
</P>
<P>
   But whether or not you react to minor cracks, you have to do at
least a little routine maintenance to keep the little cracks in the
driveway from turning into potholes.
</P>
<P>
   Asphalt driveways should be sealed every few years, and larger
cracks and holes in both asphalt and concrete driveways should be
repaired before they spread too far.
</P>
<P>
   To repair and reseal an asphalt driveway, wait for a period when
temperatures are at least 50 degrees and no rain is expected for
several days. Also, no seed pods, leaves or other plant material
should be falling.
</P>
<P>
   If the driveway has no large cracks or potholes, the resealing
job is easy but messy.
</P>
<P>
   Repairing large cracks and potholes, however, is fairly labor
intensive.
</P>
<P>
   FIX LARGE CRACKS BEFORE YOU SEAL
</P>
<P>
   Asphalt-driveway sealing products can cover a crack up to about
1/8-inch during the sealing process, but a larger crack or hole
must be fixed before sealing.
</P>
<P>
   Cracks up to about 1/2-inch can be sealed by pouring in a liquid
crack sealer, which costs $6 or $7 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Start by using your hand garden tools to remove any plant matter
and dirt in the crack. A wire brush works well to clean down to
bare asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   Asphalt crack fillers can be messy, and children and pets can
track the material into the house if they step on it before it is
dry.
</P>
<P>
   Sand sprinkled over fresh crack filler helps reduce the
potential for tracking. If you've got a deep crack, sand can also
be used to fill the bottom of the crack before using the crack
filler at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Larger cracks and potholes must be filled with ``cold patch,'' a
form of asphalt that comes in a bag, can or bucket. A 60-pound bag
costs about $6, and that's enough to fill a hole about 2 feet long
by 1 foot wide.
</P>
<P>
   To use cold patch, clean loose debris from the crack or hole.
Chip away asphalt at an angle so the bottom of the hole is larger
than the edge at surface level. (This is the hard labor part.) The
old asphalt rim at the surface of the hole will help hold the patch
in place.
</P>
<P>
   Pour cold patch into the hole until the patch is a bit higher
than the surrounding driveway. Tamp it down firmly. One way to
smush it in is to place a plywood board over the patch and then
drive across it.
</P>
<P>
   Use a liquid crack filler to seal the edges of the patch.
</P>
<P>
   Driveways also need to be clear of grease and oil before they
are sealed. If household detergents don't remove oil stains, check
hardware stores for chemicals designed for driveway cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Asphalt is made up of an oil-based adhesive that holds together
sand and bits of small rock. Motor oil spilled on the driveway
tends to break down the adhesive, so deep oil stains may have to be
treated with an oil-spot primer before you reseal the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   RESEAL ASPHALT EVERY 3 YEARS
</P>
<P>
   Asphalt driveways should be resealed about once every three
years to maintain their solid-black appearance and protect them
from cracking and oil damage. Sealing more often than that leads to
a buildup of sealing agent that cracks and becomes unsightly.
</P>
<P>
   Asphalt sealer comes in 5-gallon drums that sell from $7 to $20.
I found a wide range of prices for identical products, so a little
comparison shopping may be worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also need a brush and squeegee for spreading the sealer.
Coverage varies, but about 100 square feet per gallon is typical.
</P>
<P>
   You must wear gloves, a breathing mask and eye protection. Also
wear clothes and shoes you're willing to throw away or use as work
clothes. Asphalt sealer can be sticky, stinking, sloppy stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a tip: Buy your sealer a day in advance and turn the drum
upside down overnight. That brings sediments to the top of the
container, making stirring easier.
</P>
<P>
   Clear grass and plants from a couple inches on both sides of the
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Follow directions on the drum and spread the sealer carefully.
Work from the garage toward the street.
</P>
<P>
   When finished, place barriers at the driveway entrance, and keep
children and pets away until the seal cures. You should expect to
lose the use of your driveway for at least a day. Seals may look
dry in a couple hours, but read the can for an estimate of how long
the product should sit before you can drive on it.
</P>
<P>
   Beware of traveling scam artists who show up at your door
offering to seal your driveway at discount prices. If you want to
hire someone, check the Yellow Pages under ``asphalt'' and deal
only with companies you have checked out through the Better
Business Bureau or through references.
</P>
<P>
   REPAIR PRODUCTS AVAILABLE FOR CONCRETE
</P>
<P>
   You may have to visit several home-improvement stores, but you
should be able to find concrete-driveway crack-repair products
similar to those used for asphalt and in a similar price range.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it's nearly impossible to make a concrete repair
that perfectly matches the color of the rest of the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Again, if you're filling a large crack or hole, chisel the edges
of the hole at an angle to keep the patch from popping out.
</P>
<P>
   Concrete driveways can be sealed every other year to prevent
water and ice damage, but not everyone thinks sealing concrete is
worth the trouble. A sealed concrete drive sheds water, and some
experts believe that slows the processes that cause concrete to
crumble over time.
</P>
<P>
   Sealers designed specifically for concrete sell for about $6 to
$8 per gallon, and a gallon typically covers 200 to 300 square
feet. Application is quick and easy, and can be done using ordinary
rollers or sprayers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
