<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Wednesday, April 26, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS:  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Thursday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SUSAN-McDOUGAL (San Francisco) _ Whitewater figure Susan
McDougal, whom San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown deemed a ``steel
magnolia'' after she spent 18 months in jail for refusing to
testify against President Clinton, spoke out about rats, roaches
and drinking toilet water in the nation's prisons for women.
McDougal has become a prisoner-rights advocate. By ILENE LELCHUK.
</P>
<P>
   BEARD-DEBATE (Austin, Texas) _ In a case that may be seen as
bureaucratic hair-splitting, the Texas attorney general's office
has ruled that state law prohibits licensed cosmetologists from
trimming beards. Beards, the lawyers say, are the realm of barbers.
By RUSSELL GOLD.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DANDELIONS (Undated) _ Dandelions are reviled as Public Enemy
No. 1 by golf course superintendents and fastidious lawn owners
everywhere. The weed that won't go away. Yet dandelions are also
edible and amazingly good for you. This bitter green perennial,
high in fiber and rich in potassium and vitamin A, is one of the
world's healthiest plants. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-ELIAN (Undated) _ Now that Little Elian has been through the
entire cycle of the American media washer, and now that his story
is in the early stages of development as a TV movie for CBS (``a
writer of Cuban descent has been attached to the project''), we now
return you to regular programming while we search for another news
story to hammer into the ground. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-HOUSING (San Francisco) _ Bay Area home prices continued to
gallop upward at double-digit percentages in March, according to
new statistics. A booming regional economy continues to drive both
home sales and construction, according to the reports. By RICHARD
PAOLI.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-REVIEW-NAZIS (New York) _ Nobody knows what was said
that night in the fall of 1941 when Werner Heisenberg, Germany's
leading nuclear physicist, traveled to Nazi-occupied Denmark to
meet with his old mentor Niels Bohr. Nobody knows by the end of
``Copenhagen,'' Michael Frayn's scintillating new play at
Broadway's Royale Theatre, but the uncertainty commands a
remarkable dramatic intensity By ROBERT HURWITT.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ It was spy vs. spy, gossip-monger
vs. gossip-monger, one man's ``reliable sources'' vs. another's. It
was a match made in hearsay heaven. And Herb Caen bested J. Edgar
Hoover. Hoover's G-men called Caen a ``nit-wit columnist,'' a
``gossip monger,'' a ``keyhole journalist,'' and an
``ultra-liberal.'' But Caen drove Hoover crazy. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
