<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7540 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE-C     04-26 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE-COX27 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WRESTLING GRAPEVINE
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As World Championship Wrestling continues its rise, Extreme
Championship Wrestling is starting to slip away from contending
with the Big 2. The slide might continue after a less than
successful ``Cyberslam 2000'' event last week. First to the mat was
Justin Credible, who took the ECW title belt from Tommy Dreamer
moments after Dreamer beat WWF wrestler and ECW champion Tazz for
the belt. The title change means Credible will meet his tag team
partner Lance Storm, and Dreamer in a 3-way match for the title at
the ``Hardcore Heaven'' pay-per-view in May. But why would ECW want
to split up the Impact Players (Credible and Storm)? Two reasons:
one, because their gimmick is getting stale; and two, Storm may be
ready to jump to WCW. If he does leave, ECW would like to get a new
partner in crime for Credible or turn him to a face _ something he
has never been in ECW.
</P>
<P>
   The other main problem to come out from the convention was ECW
owner Paul Heyman's tirade on his most recognized wrestler, Raven.
Raven, who left ECW for WCW only to return to a hero's welcome last
fall, has struggled to get healthy. He had shoulder surgery before
returning to ECW. Heyman said he was less than pleased with Raven's
work ethic. While this may be an angle, those in attendance said
his words were disappointing. Heyman is caught between a rock and a
hard place because he has just lost his champion (Mike Awesome) and
is running low on star power.
</P>
<P>
   Another big signing for WCW.
</P>
<P>
   Former WWF Intercontinental champion, ``Marvelous'' Marc Mero,
agreed to terms with WCW last week. Mero was in the WCW as Johnny
B. Badd in the early 1990s before becoming a champion in the WWF.
While Mero's signing is important, the bonus is Mero's wife, Rena.
Maybe you knew her as Sable. While the WWF stripped her of that
name when she left in 1999, she could pop up on WCW at the end of
this year if WCW's attorneys can make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the law, New York state Sen. Thomas Libous recommend
a bill that would force wrestlers competing in New York to undergo
mandatory drug testing. The bill is meeting with obvious disdain
from the WWF. ``We are performers, we are showmen, he'd be drug
testing everyone on Broadway. He'd be drug testing the circus,''
WWF Entertainment Chairman Vince McMahon told the Associated Press.
``If in fact he's trying to single us out, that is
unconstitutional.'' Currently to wrestle in New York, wrestlers
must give references, divulge any criminal history and submit to a
pre-match physical. Libous' proposal would penalize wrestlers who
tested positive for drugs, by prohibiting them from wrestling in
the state for 24 hours. A second positive test would strip them of
their license for a year and fine their sponsors $25,000. A third
negative result would mean a permanent ban from New York
competition and $100,000 fine for the sponsors. Last year, Oregon
passed similar legislation. The result: a boycott of the state by
the WWF. McMahon and the WWF won't be able to do the same in New
York where Madison Square Garden has hosted some of the biggest
events in WWF history. The WWF also makes 2-to-3 stops a year in
New York cities.
</P>
<P>
   Rey Mysterio Jr. plans to return to WCW television soon.
Although he won't be in the ring until June.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday will be WWF's ``Backlash'' pay-per-view and it seems
to be suffering from ``Wrestlemania'' hangover. The main event will
see Triple H meet The Rock for his WWF title. To add some meat to
this repeat of Wrestlemania, the WWF is dragging out injured 'Stone
Cold' Steve Austin and maybe even retired Shawn Michaels. While
Austin is trying to return to active competition from his neck
surgery, he is at least a few months away from getting in the ring.
And banking on him to draw in the fans will only lead to
disappointment. Coming off the disappointing ``Wrestlemania,'' the
WWF could be opening the door for the WCW to get back in the
ratings' race.
</P>
<P>
   My only prediction for ``Backlash'' is the main event. The past
two weeks has been setting up Austin to double-cross The Rock,
which means that will not happen. WWF has been toying with the idea
of turning either Rock or Austin heel, but it doesn't make sense
with Austin still not ready to return to the ring. So expect to see
Rock to lose, Austin to be involved in a move that was going to
help the Rock, but ended up putting Rock in a losing situation,
with one of the McMahons completing the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Here's something to look for in the WWF after ``Backlash.''
Expect the Dudley Boyz to feud with the Acolytes. Another change of
events could be Rikishi turning heel and starting a major feud with
The Big Show. Also, coming off two straight ``Raw'' main events,
Chris Jericho is starting to get the push many expected from him
when he came over from the WCW last year. He is an early favorite
to win the ``King of the Ring'' pay-per-view in June. Finally, the
WWF will make a run at WCW high-flyer Juventud Guerrero as soon as
his WCW deal expires.
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for porn superstar Jenna Jameson in the WWF anytime
soon. One of the hottest rumors on the internet is that the
actress, who has worked as a correspondent for E! Entertainment
television, was talking about a job with the WWF. While the WWF has
a wrestler who claims to be a former male porn star on its roster,
to have a real, live porn actress in the ranks seemed to be pushing
the bounds of taste.
</P>
<P>
   The second hottest rumor last week was that out-of-work, NBA bad
boy Dennis Rodman was talking to WCW about returning. If 'The Worm'
is going to turn up my best guess is it will be at ``Bash At the
Beach,'' where he debuted in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
