<HEADER>
A7548 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r e BC-FAIRCHILD-NORMAN-REED     04-26 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIRCHILD-NORMAN-REEDUS-INTERVIEW-HOLLYWOOD-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORMIN' NORMAN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE B&AMP;W SLIDE is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of this
article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MARCY MEDINA  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Norman Reedus knew he stood a good chance of losing his
anonymity when he became a movie actor and began dating one-time
supermodel Helena Christensen. But the meaning of celebrity didn't
fully sink in, he says, until one day a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   He logged onto the Internet, did a search of his own name and
ended up in a chat room in which the main topic of conversation was
his and Christensen's relationship and what a horrible name they'd
given their newborn son: Mingus.
</P>
<P>
   Reedus, whose skin has yet to thicken, says he fired off a
defensive e-mail and got an embarrassed apology in return.
</P>
<P>
   Now, sitting in the Chateau Marmont with Christensen, who's
holding Mingus, he quickly explains that they named the baby for
jazz bandleader Charlie Mingus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babies are amazing,'' says Reedus, 31. ``So honest and
instinctual.''
</P>
<P>
   The infant has already been to Asia and Europe with his
globetrotting parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think my life was hectic,'' Christensen says before
excusing herself to join friends for lunch at a nearby table, ``but
I didn't know what hectic was until I had a baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one can deny that Reedus' young career has been on a
tear of late. After his appearance in 1997's ``Mimic,'' with Mira
Sorvino, he made a string of dark, mostly little-seen movies. But
he got noticed in ``Six Ways to Sunday'' as a serial killer with
Oedipal issues.
</P>
<P>
   His rough-edged appeal is about to be seen in Warner Bros.'
``Gossip,'' a college drama with Kate Hudson. Reedus says going
mainstream was not a conscious decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I choose roles based on how interesting they are to me,'' he
says. ``It's not about the length of the trailer.'' But he admits
big-budget movies aren't so bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I was used to only having two takes per scene, but I
could get used to having 15 takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe now, he says, he'll begin to get as much recognition for
his acting as for the Prada ads he appeared in two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken, like, six pictures in my life, and I still get the
model-turned-actor thing,'' he says. ``I feel like I'm going to be
called an `up and comer' forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Reedus has recently wrapped ``Beats,'' not to be confused with
his other upcoming movie, a comedy called ``The Beat Nicks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Beats'' chronicles the murder of Joan Burroughs (Courtney
Love) by her husband, William. Reedus plays Lucien Carr, who had an
affair with Joan.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a guy whose loud, drunken outburst at a party caught
the attention of a theater director, who promptly cast him in a
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play was just a drag,'' Reedus says, ``standing around
doing the same thing every night.'' But an agent saw it one evening
and signed him up.
</P>
<P>
   Reedus left his L.A. home at 12 to train for the pro-tennis
tour. He quit in his teens and moved to London, then Japan, with
his mother, eventually making his way back to L.A., where he eked
out a living painting abstracts and repairing motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   Previously linked with model Bridget Hall, Reedus met
Christensen at the hip L.A. bar R-23. He hadn't particularly
thought about having children.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when Helena and I met,'' he says, ``we started trying to
have one immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   The first night they spent together, he remembers with a smile,
was right here at the Chateau Marmont. Perhaps it was their
combustible chemistry, perhaps it was a candle or a cigarette, but
Reedus says a pillow caught fire, and they had to extinguish it in
the bathtub.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they ever found that pillow,'' he says. ``I
hope not.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Marcy Medina is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
