<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7550 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r l BC-FAIRCHILD-FITBALL-FIT     04-26 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIRCHILD-FITBALL-FITNESS/BEAUTY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE BALL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANN MARIE GARDNER  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Fitness trainer and Fitball enthusiast Ari Weller admits he's a
bit of a weirdo. He was once kicked out of his health-club job
because he wanted space to do cartwheels.
</P>
<P>
   Now, from his 23rd Street studio in New York City, Weller has
become the pied piper for a new, minimalist exercise movement that
could make the traditional gym a relic of the mechanical age.
</P>
<P>
   His followers? Sean (Puffy) Combs, model Chandra North and
scores of Manhattan professionals.
</P>
<P>
   His idea? That one rubber ball replaces weights, benches, and
step machines to provide a demanding workout and produce a lean,
cut body.
</P>
<P>
   With his shaved head, deep brown eyes and uniform of baggy army
trousers, Weller could be mistaken for a monk _ or maybe a
snowboarder. What he calls his ``new bohemian'' movement classes
are so organic, they don't even require sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream was to open up a gym without any equipment,'' Weller
says. ``If you had a tree, you could use a tree. In my case, I take
balls and resistance bands. It's a natural workout, without
machines or TVs to tap you out of the experience. Keeping your mind
involved is sort of the point.''
</P>
<P>
   So what exactly is required to work out with Weller?
</P>
<P>
   ``A leap of faith and a good deal of humility,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His movement class starts out innocently enough, with shoulder
rolls, head rolls and face, mouth and eyeball stretches. Then on to
frog leaps, crab crawls and snail slides up and down the length of
the room, ending with monkey cartwheels.
</P>
<P>
   When Weller demonstrates the monkey, his body is transformed:
His arms appear longer and he all but shrieks.
</P>
<P>
   ``His alter ego is Curious George,'' jokes one student.
</P>
<P>
   Weller uses the ball primarily for his one-to-one training.
Fitballs have been endorsed by orthopedic surgeons since the '60s,
so they're nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the possibilities are infinite,'' Weller says. ``Sitting
on the ball, for one, is not easy. And it allows you to make a
total connection with your body.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Coburn, a bond trader who has trained with Weller for
years, says, ``I'm more fit now than I've ever been. I used to be a
big weight lifter, but now I really know how to use my body.''
</P>
<P>
   Weller's technique is dynamic and constantly changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think how at kids' gyms they're running all over the place,''
he says. ``They're tumbling, rolling, jumping. I'm doing that for
adults.''
</P>
<P>
   He integrates movements from yoga, martial arts and dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compare the way a bodybuilder and a martial artist moves,'' he
says, ``ones walks like a robot, one flows like water.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been too much emphasis on exercising to look good,''
he continues. ``These exercises address a bigger priority _
longevity, dealing with life's circumstances, getting old, slipping
on ice, getting out of the way of a taxi. The irony is that when
you stop doing sport just for vanity, you end up looking better
than you've ever looked.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeking a higher level of exercise seems to be the craze du jour
_ even diehard gyms like Equinox are dragging yoga masters in with
the barbells. But Weller takes a practical view.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't go from Ninth Avenue to Nirvana in an hour,'' he
says. ``I'm not promising instant physical perfection or spiritual
enlightenment. If somebody finds those things in my class ...
hallelujah! Glad I could help.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information, log on to www.bohemiaex.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ann Marie Gardner is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
