<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: AN INTIMATE VIEW OF THE CARIBBEAN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ADELE MALOTT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    I recently asked a group of mature travelers what their favorite
trips were. One couple, speaking in unison, replied, ``Amazing
Grace.'' They had celebrated their 30th anniversary on the Amazing
Grace and were enchanted by what they called ``the unspoiled
voyage.''
 &HT;    The Amazing Grace is a rather graceless little boat that each
month cruises 2,000 miles from the Bahamas to Trinidad and then
back again to supply the five ships of the Windjammer Barefoot
Cruise fleet with provisions.
 &HT;    James Bishop is a voyager who chose the no-frills intimacy of
the Amazing Grace cruise.
 &HT;    ``There's no denying the hedonistic attractions of a Caribbean
cruise aboard one of those mobile pleasure platforms that carry a
thousand-plus people,'' he said. ``But, what is denied is the
opportunity to spend your leisurely hours poking around places
you've never heard of _ but if given the chance would never forget.
 &HT;    ``There is a tradeoff,'' Bishop added. Amazing Grace is for
people who are interested in a more down-home atmosphere, food
that's pretty much mom's standard fare and, as he put it, ``a
guarantee that you'll get smokestack soot on the seat of your
pants.''
 &HT;    A nearly half-century-old motor vessel that used to be a
lighthouse tender off the Scottish coast, Amazing Grace carries no
more than 94 passengers. The dress code is relaxed _ shorts and
shower shoes 24 hours a day. And, Bishop said, ``You might visit as
many as nine different ports on a one-way trip, maybe twice as many
going both ways. They may include such normally ignored places as
Iles des Saintes, Planta Cay and Jost Van Dyke. And you may spend
as much as a full day _ sometimes an overnight stay _ at any one of
them.''
 &HT;    The real beauty of Amazing Grace, Bishop said, is that on the
normal, southbound run, only three out of 13 days are spent
cruising the sea. In the other direction, it's just two out of 13.
Most time is spent on shore.
 &HT;    And, he added, ``For those who keep track, it's a different
country almost every other day.'' On an average round-trip, it's
possible to visit nine independent, micro-nations, plus overseas
territories still owned by England, France and Holland, as well as
all those inviting beaches.
 &HT;    The island-hopping is what really distinguishes a trip aboard
the Amazing Grace from a traditional cruise. ``On a regular cruise,
the ship is more important than the trip,'' Bishop said. ``On
Amazing Grace, it's just the opposite.''
 &HT;    For the most part, Amazing Grace's cabins have bunk beds, some
without ladders to the upper beds. Most rooms have no desks, and
few offer chairs. In some cases, the bathroom is down the
companionway and must be shared by other passengers.
 &HT;    Apart from the long, padded sunbathing lounges, there is nothing
particularly comfortable about the seating, and park benches are
used when movies are shown. The dining room has great U-shaped
booths.
 &HT;    But none of this seems to bother anybody, as demonstrated by the
fact that on one southbound voyage last fall, nine out of 10
passengers were repeaters. Some were on their sixth or seventh
sailing. One group of eight passengers from different parts of the
United States had been on Amazing Grace years ago and were enjoying
their fifth reunion trip.
 &HT;    Mildred Boudreaux of Berwick, La., was on her ninth round-trip
and had already signed up for another.
 &HT;    ``I just like being on the water,'' Boudreaux said, laughing.
``And since Amazing Grace is so small, I'm very close to it.
Besides, the ship is really so unpretentiously casual.''
 &HT;    In fact, it's so casual that status bars don't exist. The crew _
from dishwashers to the first mate _ quench their thirst at the
same bar as Amazing Grace's passengers. That can lead to some
entertaining, insightful stories, because most of the crew is
Caribbean.
 &HT;    Pay attention to the ship's cruise director and you'll get great
tips on saving money on land excursions. For example, it's best to
wait to buy duty-free stuff until the ship docks at the French
islands. There, a pack of cigarettes costs just a buck.
 &HT;    Except for predictably pricey memorabilia from the ship's shop,
Amazing Grace's rates are not out of line. Standard drinks are $2.
At most places onshore, beer is $2.
 &HT;    At the beat-up village of Soufriere on St. Lucia _ a soggy,
sagging town straight out of ``Somerset Maugham'' _ several Amazing
Grace passengers stopped by Harmony's bar to be served the local
beer by a barefoot 14-year-old and to watch near-naked fisherman
across the street gutting the morning's catch.
 &HT;    But having a drink is the least of the attractions. Rick and
Debbie Camp of Palmerton, Pa., went swimming with the stingrays on
Grand Turk.
 &HT;    ``Sure, they've got those long, twitchy, lethal-looking tails,
but they're really very gentle,'' Debbie Camp reported.
 &HT;    John Sweet and his son Andy, respectively from Chapel Hill,
N.C., and Denver, took a catamaran side trip to Mustique to mingle
with the rich and shameless. David Bowie and Mick Jaeger both have
homes there, and it was Princess Margaret who originally gave the
island its expensive cachet years ago ($14 hamburgers).
 &HT;    Less exalted women can be seen by the roadside on Bequia,
sitting beneath a thatch canopy, hand-chipping stone into pebbles
for construction.
 &HT;    At the tidy village of Terre-de-Haute, a cafe owner sits on the
sidewalk cutting coconut meat from its shell as a man putt-putts by
on his moped with a 50-pound tuna slung across the handlebars.
 &HT;    A rewarding travel experience is composed of such entertaining
trifles. And Jack Shea of Pompano Beach, Fla., wished he had been
able to accumulate more of them. But he ended his cruise at
Trinidad. ``Dumb move,'' he scowled. ``I should have signed up for
the round-trip.''
 &HT;    And he wasn't the only one who felt that way.
 &HT;    Low- or value-season rates on Amazing Grace start at $1,375 for
one-way trip between Grand Bahama and Trinidad. Low season is
usually between May and December. Port fees cost an additional $150
for each direction.
 &HT;    Port stops often include Antigua, Bequia, Conception, Cooper
Island, Dominican Republic, Grand Bahama, Grand Turk, Great
Ionagua, Grenada, Iles des Saintes, Jost Van Dyke, Nevis, Norman
Island, Plana Cay, St. Barthelemy, St. Kitts, St. Lucia, St.
Maarten, Tortola, Trinidad and Virgin Gorda.
 &HT;    For more information, call Windjammer Barefoot Cruises at (800)
327-2601; write P.O. Box 190120, Miami Beach, Fla., 33119-0120; or
visit www.windjammer.com on the Web. 
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    Adele Malott is the publisher of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
