<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7600 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BEARD-DEBATE-HNS &LR;      04-26 0286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEARD-DEBATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BEARDS REMAIN THE BAILIWICK OF TEXAS BARBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUSSELL GOLD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas attorney general's office has ruled
that state law prohibits licensed cosmetologists from trimming
beards.
</P>
<P>
   Beards, the lawyers say, are the realm of barbers.
</P>
<P>
   In a case that might be thought of as bureaucratic
hair-splitting, the law was fuzzy on where hair ends and the beard
begins, so the lawyers stepped in to clarify.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it likely that most observers would consider the
sideburns worn by the late Elvis Presley at the time of his early
success in 1956 as part of his hair,'' the attorney general's
office stated last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, whether the muttonchops which adorned his
face at the time of his death were hair which a cosmetologist might
trim, or a partial beard which could be serviced only by a
barber,'' is a difficult question.
</P>
<P>
   Henry O'Neal Holifield, director of the Texas Cosmetology
Commission, offered this advise for confused cosmetologists: ``If
you go below the bottom of the ear, you are probably going to have
a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential fines for unlawful beard trimming can range up to
$200.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Board of Barber Examiners is expected to decide by
this summer where the hair stops and the beard begins.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few years, state lawmakers have wanted to merge the
barber board and cosmetology commission into one agency.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Williams Sr., chairman of the state barber board, said
if that happens, it would wipe out his profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``The barbering that I know will never be the same,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7609 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-TV-ELIAN-HNS &LR;      04-26 0337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ELIAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEXT UP FOR ELIAN: `HOLLYWOOD SQUARES' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM GOODMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that Little Elian has been through the entire cycle of the
American media washer, and now that his story is in the early
stages of development as a television movie for CBS (``a writer of
Cuban descent has been attached to the project''), we now return
you to regular programming while we search for another news story
to hammer into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant Gumbel was right. If that kid were from Haiti, he'd have
been home in 48 hours and the whole Disneyland-media-circus,
hide-in-the-closet affair would never have happened.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe the Haitian kids have it better. Little Elian
is never going to be the same. He's going to be the Cuban Gary
Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   Or worse: In five years, he'll be on ``Hollywood Squares.''
</P>
<P>
   The people at ABC News have been in a major snit ever since
someone had the bright idea of allowing the actor Leonardo DiCaprio
interview President Clinton about global warming. The entire
interview, the text of which was released by the White House, was
pared down to a few snippets, probably to appease all those newsies
who cried about the end of journalism as we know it. But here's
what they should be most embarrassed about: Leo proved to be a far
better interviewer, with smarter questions, than Diane Sawyer or
many of the other celebrity anchors at the network.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, by cutting the interview _ which was informative and dense
with insight on both of their parts (about a serious environmental
issue) _ ABC proved that it values entertainment reporting over
anything hard-core.
</P>
<P>
   Either that or they were saving room for the real celebrity
coup: Little Elian interviews Al Gore about school lunches.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7611 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-COMING-HOME-$ADV30-CO     04-26 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMING-HOME-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FROM RUSSIA TO AMERICA: LEARNING TO COPE IN A STRANGE NEW WORLD
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (l) lifestyle categories for
release Sunday, April 30.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vodka consumption is down. The weather has
improved. Life is more stable, though there is a gnawing concern
about the health of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not summarizing the state of affairs in Russia. I'm talking
about my life in America since moving back to the United States
from Moscow five months ago. My family and I have come home after
seven years abroad in Russia and the Middle East, and we're coping
with culture shock in our own country.
</P>
<P>
   We're Rip Van Winkle: America is full of prosperity and
high-tech gadgets that we had only a vague notion of in Russia. We
watched in amazement at my sister's home near Baltimore when she
declined to pick up her ringing telephone, aware through her caller
ID that it was a bothersome telemarketer.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Pilot has replaced the Filofax as the repository of
choice for the yuppie crowd. The tech world seems to dominate all.
Among friends and co-workers, there seems to be two topics of
conversation _ the dot-com stock you shoulda bought two years ago
or the one you shoulda sold two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy to keep up, like arriving late at a party where
everyone else is in full revelry and you're trying to figure out
what they're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   We left Russia amid a brutal war in Chechnya and a sad reality
in the streets of Moscow as the mercurial economy took its toll on
working-class Russians. It is a country with profound problems just
feeding its population, not one of luxurious concerns such as the
value of stock options or affording gas for the SUV.
</P>
<P>
   As a journalist, it was a fascinating assignment, yet always
comforting to know that America was the oasis at the end of the
road.
</P>
<P>
   As Americans in Russia, we were sympathetic to the pain endured
by everyday Russians trying to survive, but also slightly smug at
seeing how far the mighty superpower has fallen. Lenin and Marx
were wrong, in practice if not in theory, and the evidence is plain
to see in the dirty streets and dilapidated apartment blocks
throughout Russia.
</P>
<P>
   We were smug, that is, until we returned to the States to news
of school shootings and a New Economy that has created a surprising
gap between the haves and the have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   If Russians have an abundance of poverty, we seem to have our
share of moral scarcities amid the boom.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as the old saying went during the Cold War, there are
more Russians trying to leave their country for life in America
than the other way around. It remains true today. Just take a look
at the line snaking around the U.S. Embassy in Moscow every morning
as Russians seek visas to visit and move here.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-week spending blitz last winter to reassemble our lives
in Washington, we bought a house and a car, and were reminded of
just how fortunate we are to live in a country that has a banking
system that actually works.
</P>
<P>
   Our Russian friend Andrei used to pepper us with questions about
credit; he marveled at the fact that a middle-class wage earner in
America could actually afford a home with payments spread out over
30 years, or a car over five years. No such thing exists in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in America, the world's premier service economy, we've
tolerated in recent weeks a profound lack of service as we set up
house, bought furniture and underwent delicate negotiations to
actually get the cable guy to come hook up the TV.
</P>
<P>
   But at least it's simply random incompetence, not commonplace
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Not once since we arrived last December have we had to pay a
bribe, a common occurrence in Russia if you expect to get anything
done in a timely fashion. In order to move our furnishings out of
Russia last fall, we had to give up a few pieces of furniture to
the Russian government before the rest of our shipment made it onto
the boat.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Sarah, had picked up the items for a pittance at a
Moscow flea market _ rustic farmhouse chairs, a table and some
knickknacks. Ostensibly, they were seized as a ``donation'' to be
displayed at a state museum near Moscow. In reality, it was a bribe
that gave us the right to move the rest of our belongings out of
the country with no further bureaucratic hassles.
</P>
<P>
   We suspect that those items are indeed on display near Moscow _
at the country home of some mid-level bureaucrat.
</P>
<P>
   It took weeks, sometimes months, to accomplish things in Russia
unless you paid bribes or had connections, or both. America, with
its voice-mail menus and drive-thru windows, seems surrealistically
efficient by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks after enrolling our daughter in a pre-school in
Chevy Chase, Md., we were confronted with a bizarre reality of
upscale suburban Washington. Her school hosted a seminar for
parents titled: ``How to apply for kindergarten and prepare your
child for the interview process.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviewing to gain admittance to kindergarten? Our Russian
friends would be baffled, just as we were by unwritten rules in
Russia that say the father has little to say about the way children
are raised.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, I can take my 4-year-old to the park without fear
of the disapproving stares I received in Russia from the
``babushkas'' _ the grandmas who apparently felt a father could not
responsibly care for his child. Just where was the mother, they
would ask me in Russian, with their arraigning stares, and why on
this chilly afternoon isn't your child wearing two sweaters?
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line of these anecdotes will come as no surprise for
anyone who has followed Russia and its history: Despite the fall of
the Soviet Union and America's well-meaning attempts to foster
democracy in Russia, they generally don't understand us and we
don't understand them. It is an unhealthy paradigm for two
countries that possess most of the world's nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Snugly back in America, we don't miss the gritty
unpredictability of Russia or seeing the sad effects of their
poverty from our apartment window in southern Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   But neither are we entirely comfortable with the almost
antiseptic nature of life in America these days and the
indifference with which many of our family and friends regard
politics and current affairs. There seems to be a lot of discourse
on talk radio and Internet chat forums, but not much serious
thought about America's place in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Russians have a popular saying, spawned during centuries under
the harsh rule of czars, and decades more under the authoritarian
regimes of the communists. The phrase is ``sto dyelat?'' _ What is
to be done? _ and it is widely applied to almost every aspect of
life. It reflects a fatalism and powerlessness that comes almost
naturally, earned through years of repression.
</P>
<P>
   As Americans, we, too, have a ready explanation for our
impassivity. For most of us, life is good and our problems are
relatively minor compared to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Complain all you want about Elian or the census or gas prices or
the tech-stock correction or taxes.
</P>
<P>
   What is to be done?
</P>
<P>
   Above all, be content. That seems to be the consensus in America
these days.
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
