<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7613 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     04-26 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MS. RENO, IT WAS JUST ABOUT TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Great job, Janet Reno. Or, to put it another way: Better late
than never.
</P>
<P>
   After procrastinating for months, after giving the belligerent
Miami relatives more leeway than they ever deserved, after
shrinking from her obvious duty more than once _ after all that,
the attorney general finally rescued Elian Gonzalez from his
kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
   I say ``kidnappers'' because, in effect, that's what they were,
these people who took possession of a 6-year-old against his
father's wishes and defied a lawful order to turn the boy over so
that he could be reunited with his lone surviving parent. Whatever
shortcomings Juan Miguel Gonzalez might have as a father, he surely
can provide a saner, safer environment for his son than those
lunatic uncles and cousins who forced last weekend's action by
Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Miami relatives forced Reno's hand with their
bullheaded insistence on dictating the terms of Elian's
long-awaited reunion with his father. These people had no business
trying to dictate anything. They had no legal claim to custody of
the boy. They had no legal standing to negotiate Elian's status
with Reno or anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Reno was more than patient. She was, if anything, derelict in
her responsibility by waiting so long to remove Elian from that
Miami home and return him to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Elian Gonzalez was found floating in the ocean on Thanksgiving
Day after his mother drowned in an ill-fated attempt to reach the
United States. He should have been sent home immediately to his
father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, these crackpot relatives latched onto Elian as if
they'd found a stray pet and proceeded to turn him into a poster
child for political activists who quickly identified him as an
invaluable propaganda tool in their perpetual war of words with
Cuban President Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the Miami relatives had put this kid on display like
an adorable exhibit in some human petting zoo. They sent him out
each day to perform for the TV cameras and news photographers and
even went so far as to feature him in a shameless propaganda video.
</P>
<P>
   Famed attorney F. Lee Bailey said the tape reminded him of one
that Patty Hearst's kidnappers made ``with a gun to her head.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Miami relatives were even slightly concerned about the
welfare of this child, they had a strange way of showing it.
</P>
<P>
   Life in Castro's Cuba might not be the fate we would wish for a
little boy who captured America's collective heart. But it's
difficult to imagine how being with his father, even in Cuba, could
damage Elian as much as the crass exploitation that was inflicted
on him in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   And how about that Marisleysis Gonzalez, the young woman who
supposedly had been acting as Elian's ``surrogate mother''? Either
she's a complete phony who has been grievously overacting in her
ranting, raving TV appearances, or she is dangerously unstable and
has no business anywhere near a 6-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Elian was well-served by being separated from her.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we have this gaggle of self-serving politicians
excoriating Reno for doing her job in a conscientious and effective
manner. Rep. Tom DeLay, to name just one, may be the most
embarrassing excuse for a public servant ever produced by the great
state of Texas. What in the world were Republicans in Congress
thinking about when they handed this nitwit an important leadership
position? And if they don't have the gumption to dump him as
majority whip, can't they at least put a muzzle on him?
</P>
<P>
   Here's the deal, folks. Reno had to remove Elian Gonzalez from
that house in Miami and return him to his father. The home was
occupied by unstable, unpredictable people who had threatened to
resist any attempt to remove the boy. There was a volatile,
agitated mob gathered in the streets around the home.
</P>
<P>
   What was she supposed to do? That commando-style raid was the
only way to get the kid out of there while minimizing the
possibility that someone might get hurt.
</P>
<P>
   No, it wasn't pretty to watch. But it worked.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
