<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANDELIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DANDELIONS: A WEED THAT IS WELCOME IN THE KITCHEN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dandelions are in dire need of a savvy spinmeister.
</P>
<P>
   Until the right person steps forward, however, dandelions will
continue to be regarded as nature's most schizophrenic offering.
</P>
<P>
   They are reviled as Public Enemy No. 1 by golf course
superintendents and fastidious lawn owners everywhere. The weed
that won't go away.
</P>
<P>
   Yet dandelions are also edible and amazingly good for you. This
bitter green perennial, high in fiber and rich in potassium and
vitamin A, is one of the world's most healthful plants.
</P>
<P>
   Dandelions rank ahead of both broccoli and spinach in overall
nutritional value. They are one of the top six herbs in the Chinese
medicine chest.
</P>
<P>
   As anyone with a lawn or access to a pasture will attest, they
are ubiquitous. And free.
</P>
<P>
   There is a simple rule of thumb regarding the lovely, much
maligned dandelion. The leaves are for greens, the blossoms for
wine, the roots for coffee.
</P>
<P>
   For our purposes, we'll concentrate on the nutritionally rich
greens, which tend to act as a tonic and gentle diuretic and can
replace spinach in almost every recipe in your cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   The ideal time to pick dandelions is before they flower and
blossom.
</P>
<P>
   Here are tips for harvesting dandelions:
</P>
<P>
   Cut the greens with the top of the root still attached so that
the leaves stay together. This makes them easier to clean. A
stirrup hoe works well.
</P>
<P>
   Collect the greens away from the road and in areas that have not
been sprayed with herbicide or pesticide.
</P>
<P>
   If buds or flowers have already appeared, wait until flowering
is complete. Cut the old greens and flowers off at the root and let
new greens grow. Harvest the new greens while young and tender and
they will be only slightly more bitter than in early spring.
</P>
<P>
   The greens can be eaten raw, and they make a fine salad. Simply
break the tender young leaves after washing them thoroughly to rid
them of sand and grit.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking dandelion greens is labor-intensive for folks who like
to buy bagged salad, but it's not complicated. Here are a few tips:
</P>
<P>
   Wash the greens thoroughly in slightly warm water, removing old,
discolored or badly broken leaves. Cut off the roots and any tough
stems, and wash again, lifting the greens out of the water to allow
any sand to settle in the pan. Sprinkle the greens with salt.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the greens with just the water that was clinging to the
leaves after washing in a tightly covered heavy pot or steamer
until they are limp and barely tender, between 5 and 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Drain them and chop them fine.
</P>
<P>
   Dress them with olive oil, garlic, salt and vinegar, or try
using them in any of the following recipes:
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   DANDELION OMELET
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 2)
</P>
<P>
   3 strips bacon
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   4 mushrooms, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup or so of fresh dandelion greens, chopped fine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (total) grated mozzarella, provolone, muenster or
similar white cheese and/or grated colby longhorn or mild cheddar
cheese
</P>
<P>
   Fry the bacon crisp in an omelet pan. Remove from pan and
crumble into a small bowl, reserving the fat. Saute the mushrooms
in the remaining bacon fat (which can be reduced by half if you
wish). After the mushrooms have sauteed for a minute or so, add the
dandelions and saute until wilted. Remove the mushrooms and greens
to the same bowl containing the bacon and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Scramble the eggs lightly, adding the cheese and dandelion
filling and cooking until the eggs reach the desired firmness.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   DANDELION WITH SPAGHETTI
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 2)
</P>
<P>
   1 pound (or more) fresh dandelion greens
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound uncooked spaghetti
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 can stewed tomatoes (16 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup light vegetable or olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Grated Romano or parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Hot pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   Boil fresh greens in a large pot of salted water until almost
tender. Add spaghetti to pot and cook until spaghetti is done.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, saute garlic in oil until lightly colored.
Do not let the garlic burn. Add tomatoes. Simmer 10 to 15 minutes
and put tomato sauce on top of drained spaghetti and dandelions.
Top with hot pepper flakes and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   DANDELION LASAGNA
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 10 to 12)
</P>
<P>
   2 quarts water
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds dandelion leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon basil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup wheat germ
</P>
<P>
   3 cups tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   9 whole-wheat lasagna noodles
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ricotta cheese
</P>
<P>
   Dash cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound mozzarella cheese sliced thinly
</P>
<P>
   Bring water to a boil, add dandelions and cook until tender.
Remove dandelions with a slotted spoon and reserve the cooking
water. Place dandelions in a blender with garlic, 1 tablespoon
parsley, basil and oregano. Blend thoroughly, but be careful not to
liquefy the greens. Add wheat germ, 2 cups tomato sauce and tomato
paste. Blend just enough to mix thoroughly and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Bring reserved cooking water back to a boil. Add lasagna noodles
and olive oil. Cook until just tender, but still firm (5 to 8
minutes), drain and reserve. Mix ricotta cheese, cayenne and the
remaining 2 tablespoons parsley; reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly butter the bottom of a 9-by-13-inch baking pan. Position
3 lasagna noodles side by side as a first layer. Cover with 1/3 of
the dandelion sauce, then 1/2 of the ricotta cheese. Shake some
parmesan cheese over the ricotta and cover with a layer of
mozzarella slices. Repeat.
</P>
<P>
   Layer the final three lasagna noodles and the last third of the
dandelion sauce. Cover with the remaining parmesan and mozzarella
cheese and 1 cup tomato sauce. Bake at 375 for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   DANDELION PIZZA
</P>
<P>
   Prepared pizza dough
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 cups finely chopped dandelions
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Shredded mozzarella cheese
</P>
<P>
   Prepare pizza dough using whatever recipe you prefer, and let
rise. When ready to bake, place in 350-degree oven on a cookie
sheet and bake until golden, but not brown, 10-12 minutes. Remove
from oven and brush on olive oil with a pastry brush. Let cool
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Steam dandelions and drain well. Brown garlic in olive oil and
add greens to it. Mix in parmesan cheese and lemon juice. Spread
greens on top of the baked crust and top with shredded mozzarella
cheese. Return to oven for about 10 minutes, or until cheese melts.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Recipes courtesy of ``The Dandelion Celebration,'' by Peter Gail
(Goosefoot Acres Press)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
