<SLUG> BC-SWEEPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG SWEEP
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: `Today' refers to Thurs., Apr. 27) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``People need stories more than bread itself,'' a mystical
tale-teller intones near the beginning of the ABC special-effects
extravaganza ``Arabian Nights.'' ``They tell us how to live, and
why.''
</P>
<P>
   On TV during sweeps month, however, stories generally have less
grandiose ambitions. They seek merely to get a rise out of viewers,
or at least a rise in the numbers of viewers. Sure, sweeps may be a
mindlessly antiquated system that serves neither the networks nor
the advertisers _ to say nothing of the shaft-job it pulls on
viewers, clustering all event programming around a handful of days
on the calendar _ but it's the only system we have, so they're
sticking to it, by God.
</P>
<P>
   Who would've guessed at the beginning of the 1999-2000 season
that one of the highlights of each and every sweeps month over the
past year would've been a spate of cheaply produced little game
shows that easily steamrollered vastly more expensive and ambitious
miniseries? It's been an unpredictable TV season _ comedy took a
dive, and was resurrected, inadvertently, in the form of dubious
``reality'' programming and game shows.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's merciful that it's coming to a close and that, by
and large, this May the networks are trotting out the usual barrage
of ``events'' and stunt casting and series cliffhangers. Here's how
the networks intend to entertain us for the next month:
</P>
<P>
   Today &QL; 
``Friends'' (NBC) _ Bruce Willis appears in a three-episode
storyline as Ross's girlfriend's father with a thing for Rachel
(Jennifer Aniston). The season ends May 18 with an hourlong episode
featuring Tom Selleck's return just as Chandler (Perry) is
preparing to propose to Monica (Courtney Cox). The battle for a
big-bucks payday for the cast in exchange for another season will
ensue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago Hope'' (CBS) _ Just desserts as the head of the HMO
(James Garner) running the hospital suffers a heart attack and
becomes a victim of his own bureaucracy. Quite possibly the show's
final episode. &QL; 
Friday, April 28 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Cosby'' (CBS) _ Cos bids farewell with considerably less
fanfare than that which attended his last TV series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit'' (NBC) _ Multiple Tony
winner and acclaimed mezzo-soprano Audra McDonald guest-stars as a
police psychologist; how can this show possibly work some musical
numbers into her role? She returns for the season finale May 19. &QL; 
Sunday, April 30 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The '70s'' (NBC) _ In the manner of predecessor ``The '60s,''
this miniseries follows four friends who somehow manage to be a
part of virtually ital!every significant event of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arabian Nights'' (ABC) _ Robert Halmi, Sr., fresh from the,
er, whatever ``The Tenth Kingdom`` was, returns with more
miniseries-sized special effects and fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take Me Home: The John Denver Story'' (CBS) _ Chad Lowe, Mr.
Hilary Swank, strives to help his family go for the acting-trophy
hat trick by essaying the sensitive singer-songwriter. Well, at
least it's a good lead-out for viewers of ``Touched by an Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Files'' (Fox) _ David Duchovny wrote and directed this
comic episode in which a case investigated by Mulder and Scully is
bastardized into a shlocky movie starring Garry Shandling and Tea
Leoni. Its cliffhanger episodes _ the question this time: Will
there be an eighth season? _ air May 14 and 21. &QL; 
Monday, May 1 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (ABC) _ As if this show needs
!ital!higher ratings, it offers a weeklong series of celebrity
editions, featuring David Duchovny, Queen Latifah, Ray Romano and _
yes, pipe down already _ Rosie O'Donnell. On May 18, the end of
Western Civilization is officially announced with a gratuitous
special going ``Behind the Scenes at 'Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventh Heaven'' (The WB) _ Another controversial topic is
handled in a subdued manner when the Rev. Camden (Stephen Collins)
counsels a sexually molested teenager. &QL; 
Tuesday, May 2 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Angel'' (The WB) _ Buffy (Sarah Michelle Gellar) guest-stars
for some more romantic travails; Angel (David Boreanaz) returns the
favor in ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer's'' May 9 episode. &QL; 
Wednesday, May 3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The 35th Annual Academy of Country Music Awards'' (CBS) _ Yet
more trophies get distributed to celebrities, who in turn thank
their agents and managers and publicists. Dolly Parton hosts; Faith
Hill and the Dixie Chicks will be on hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dawson's Creek'' (The WB) _ The romantic triangle between
Dawson (James Van Der Beek), Joey (Katie Holmes) and Pacey (Joshua
Jackson) gets so messy that it won't be until the May 24 season
finale that everything is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Party of Five'' (Fox) _ The Salingers bid viewers adieu;
America shrugs. &QL; 
Thursday, May 4 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Worlds Funniest Game Show Moments'' (Fox) _ There simply don't
exist words cynical enough to describe this one. &QL; 
Friday, May 5 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Sabrina, The Teenage Witch'' (ABC) _ Sabrina enjoys her last
days of potentially strong ratings before moving next season to The
WB. Also tonight: The series finale of ``Boy Meets World,`` which
I'm pretty sure no one has ever watched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Providence'' (NBC) _ Game-show mania strikes this romantic
series, as Robbie (Seth Peterson) wins loot on a show hosted by Ed
Begley, Jr. The season doesn't end so whimsically, however, as Syd
(Melina Kanakaredes) goes into a coma by the May 19 finale. &QL; 
Sunday, May 7 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Geppetto'' (ABC) _ Drew Carey not only dances, but sings, and
it's a far cry from ``Cleveland Rocks'` _ find out if this is a
good thing in this musical version of ``Pinocchio'' co-starring
Julia Louis Dreyfuss and Wayne Brady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason and the Argonauts'' (NBC) _ See ``Arabian Nights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cupid &AMP; Cate'' (CBS) _ Romantic comedy starring Mary-Louise
Parker, Peter Gallagher and Bebe Neuwirth. &QL; 
Monday, May 8 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The 4th Annual Celebrity Weddings: In Style'' (ABC) _ Those
darn celebrities just keep getting married, and In Style magazine
is there to coo and slobber all over them. Celine Dion and Jenny
McCarthy represent the level of intellectual vigor at work here. &QL; 
Wednesday, May 10 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Drew Carey Show'' (ABC) _ A lavish musical number
commemorates the consummation of Drew and Kate's relationship. The
following week, Drew, in an admittedly shameless bid for an Emmy,
closes the season with a parody of virtually every ``very special''
sitcom episode ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's to You, Charlie Brown: 50 Great Years!'' (CBS) _ Whoopi
Goldberg hosts a tribute to the world's most successful loser and
everyone else in Charles Schulz's beloved comic strip. And, since a
variety show's not a variety show unless Faith Hill pops in, she's
on hand to sing a song apropos of nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sharing the Secret'' (CBS) _ Mare Winningham stars in this
drama about bulimia. Suggested alternate titles: ``Cough It Up,''
``Finger Foods,`` ``Purge-atory.'' &QL; 
Thursday, May 11 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``ER'' (NBC) _ Julianna Marguiles is not listed in the credits
for the May 18 season finale, involving a school shooting, so she
may get jettisoned in this episode when her character revives a
``do not resuscitate'' patient and thereby irks Dr. Weaver (Laura
Innes) in an episode filled with ER mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paranormal: Do You Believe?'' (Fox) _ From the network that,
in January, declared it was putting a stop to tacky ``reality''
programming, and then, in February, after the debacle that was
``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?,'' swore that it was
seriously ceasing and desisting all tacky ``reality'' programming,
comes more tacky ``reality'' programming. &QL; 
Friday, May 12 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Gloria Estefan, Caribbean Soul: The Atlantis Concert'' (CBS) _
Musical special featuring Mark Anthony and 'N Sync.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 49th Miss Universe Pageant'' (CBS) _ An epistomological
study in global socio-economic dynamics in which attractive young
women in revealing clothing discuss their plans for improving the
planet. &QL; 
Sunday, May 14 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus'' (CBS) _ Stop me if you've heard this one: Blondish,
Anglicized guy, clean-cut except for the long hair, beard and
sandals, wanders otherwise swarthy environs doing good and
encouraging others to do likewise and discovers no good deed goes
unpunished, only to inspire an endless stream of blandly reverent
biopics and mini-series.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, May 15
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies Man'' (CBS) _ Stunt-casting alert: ``Golden Girls'' Rue
McClanahan and Estelle Getty join Betty White as they vie for the
affections of George Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roswell'' (The WB) _ Everything is revealed in the season
finale: Sheriff Valenti (William Sadler) discovers the extent of
the young aliens' powers, and Max (Jason Behr), Isabel (Katherine
Heigl) and Michael (Brendan Fehr) receive a communique concerning
their future, one that may not include Liz (Shiri Appleby) or, for
that matter, being on TV next season. &QL; 
!folo!Tuesday, May 16 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Dharma &AMP; Greg'' (ABC) _ This sitcom's season ends with the
happy couple thinking about a baby again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brady Bunch`` and ``Diff'rent Strokes'' (Fox) _ Because
our attention span won't accommodate a two-hour movie, Fox strides
boldly forward with two one-hour ``original Mini-Movies'' _ read
that, hacked out just slightly slower than the speed of light _ set
behind the scenes at and in the nation's jails after two
once-popular sitcoms. &QL; 
Wednesday, May 17 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The West Wing'' (NBC) - Sure, this series about White House
machinations may be full of itself sometimes, but how many other
shows would hinge its season finale on the issue of campaign
reform? Marlee Matlin reprises her role as a savvy political
operative in the May 3 and 10 episodes; in the latter, Sam (Rob
Lowe) is finally busted for consorting with the prostitute he met
in the season premiere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Judds Reunion: Power to Change'' (CBS) _ The former
country duo, Naomi and Wynonna, hooks up with its Hollywood
contingent, Ashley, and celebrate their celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beverly Hills 90210'' (Fox) _ The prime-time soap leaves the
air after a decade _ about damn time _ with everyone !ital!still
confused about their feelings for one another. The week prior, the
stars share memories of the series in a special, ``The Final
Goodbye.`` &QL; 
Thursday, May 18 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Frasier'' (NBC) _ This may be the one you've been waiting for.
Niles (David Hyde Pierce) interrupts his romantic weekend with
another woman to horn in on Daphne's (Jane Leeves) soon-to-be
disastrous wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murder, She Wrote: A Story to Die For'' (CBS) _ A TV film
reprises the old series: Someone's murdered, and Jessica Fletcher
(Angela Lansbury) figures out who did it. Richard Crenna co-stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Popular'' (The WB) _ Every season-finale cliche in the book _
weddings, pregnancies, funerals, etc. _ gets roasted in the teen
show's finale, with stunt-casting guest stars Peggy Lipton, Delta
Burke and Erik Estrada. &QL; 
Friday, May 19 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dukes of Hazzard: Hazzard in Hollywood'' (CBS) _ The long-
clamored-for reunion takes place. John Schneider, Tom Wopat and
Catherine Bach star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nash Bridges'' (CBS) _ Wrestler ``Stone Cold`` Steve Austin
guests as a rogue cop in the season finale, which coincidentally is
also the series 100th episode. Yasmine Bleeth's character
celebrates by breaking up with Nash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 27th Annual Daytime Emmy Awards'' (ABC) _ More
celebrities, more trophies, more agents and publicists thanked.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, May 20
</P>
<P>
   ``Early Edition'' (CBS) _ The season (and, likely, the series)
concludes with Gary (Kyle Chandler) discovering why he has been
receiving better newspaper service than the rest of us all these
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walker, Texas Ranger'' (CBS) _ A two-hour season-ender finds
Walker (Chuck Norris) and Alex (Sheree J. Wilson) the target of
assassins just before their wedding. Guest-stars: Joan Jett and Tom
Bosley (commence head-scratching now). &QL; 
Sunday, May 21 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing Up Brady'' (NBC) _ In the, um, tradition of ``The
David Cassidy Story'' comes this teleflick about ``The Brady
Bunch'' from the perspective of Barry Williams, who played Greg _
and dated both his mom and his sister on the series! Stud!
</P>
<P>
   ``The Linda McCartney Story'' (CBS) _ Telebiopic about a woman
known essentially for marrying well. At this rate, next May sweeps
they'll be doing movies about you and me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Futurama'' (Fox) _ Al Gore makes a cameo appearance, and no,
he won't be assuming the role of Bender the robot. Physicist
Stephen Hawking also lends his, um, ``voice,'' as well to the
season finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``King of the Hill'' (Fox) _ Country singers Randy Travis, Clint
Black, Wynonna Judd and others turn out for the season finale, but
the previous week's episode sounds funnier _ Hank's wife, Peggy,
learns that images of her feet are circulating on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Simpsons'' (Fox) _ The venerable cartoon's season finale
parodies VH-1's ``Behind the Music'' in a behind-the-scenes look at
the money, madness and egos behind the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm in the Middle'' (Fox) _ Bea Arthur guest-stars as the
family hits a water park in the comedy sensation's season finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Practice'' (ABC) _ Another season finale, another lesson
that there might be better ways to make a living other than getting
murderers off the hook. &QL; 
Monday, May 22 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Titus'' (Fox) _ The hit comedy, a rarity this year, winds up
its first season with a story out of star Christopher Titus' real
life involving his father and a case of auto-erotica.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal'' (Fox) _ They've already killed off Billy, so
what can they do for an encore? Ally (Calista Flockhart) slips into
something more comfortable _ a new relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' (CBS) _ All the facts behind
Robert's (Brad Garrett) divorce are revealed. &QL; 
Tuesday, May 23 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Will &AMP; Grace'' (NBC) _ Grace (Debra Messing) fools around with
Will's (Eric McCormack) boss (guest Gregory Hines); other
relationships change drastically in the sitcom's hourlong season
finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' (The WB) _ Buffy (Sarah Michelle
Gellar), et al, face down their worst fears in an episode written
and directed by creator Joss Whedon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging Amy'' (CBS) _ Amy finds romance at last _ or does she?
_ in the hit drama's first-season cliffhanger. Gregory Harrison
co-stars as the potential paramour.
</P>
<P>
   ``NYPD Blue'' (ABC) _ The cop drama's seventh season concludes
with a two-hour special as co-star Andrea Thompson departs for a
career as a TV news anchor.
</P>
