<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 HARVARD HOLDS A MOCK TRIAL FOR JESUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD HIGGINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ A Harvard Divinity School professor, playing
the role of prosecutor in the trial of Jesus, had just rested his
case, arguing that Jesus was not the harmless, otherworldly poser
of questions some made him out to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remind you of the testimony of one Mathias, who tells us
that Jesus said, `I have not come to bring peace, but a sword,' ''
said New Testament scholar Allen Callahan, taking some license to
refer to the then-unwritten Gospel of Matthew.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Dershowitz, Jesus' self-appointed pro bono lawyer, shot to
his feet, gesturing at ``Pontius Pilate,'' the Roman prefect of
Judea, played Tuesday by Harvey Cox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your honor, I want to call this Mathias as a hostile
witness,'' shouted Dershowitz, a law professor and trial attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we accept this heresay evidence about my client?
Nobody has even seen Jesus with a sword. And whatever sword he may
have been talking about, if indeed he was talking about one, was
surely a metaphorical sword of God.''
</P>
<P>
   So it went Tuesday at ``The Trial of Jesus of Nazareth,'' held
during a regular if unusual meeting of ``Contemporary
Interpretations of Jesus,'' the course Cox and Callahan are
teaching at Harvard Divinity School.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, Callahan, and Dershowitz were the only actors, and of them
only Cox played a historical role. The roles of prosecutor and
defense attorney were invented to personify the forces for and
against Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan said that he and Cox did it to jar familiar perceptions
of Jesus and to ``sharpen the issues'' of justice and truth in the
judgment against Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, a theologian and chairman of the divinity school's
department of religion and society, said he got the idea of
reenacting the trial after talking with Dershowitz about the nature
of Roman justice during the life of Jesus. He said he also decided
to take up Dershowitz on a dare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was saying to Harvey, `Just think of all the trouble the
world would have been spared if Jesus had had a good Jewish
lawyer,' '' Dershowitz recounted Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz said that the role fulfilled a lifelong dream.
``Jesus is the one client I've always wished I could have
represented,'' said the law professor whose clients have included
O.J. Simpson, Claus von Bulow, and Leona Helmsley.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, as Pilate, began by decrying the fact that the matter of
this ``rabble-rousing rabbi from Galilee'' was threatening the
peace during Passover and, worse, delaying Pilate from enjoying a
Roman bath.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan said that Jesus' claims of kingship were a threat to
the rule of Tiberius, the Roman emperor. ``Some have said his
kingdom is not of this world,'' he said, but his seditious acts
were occuring ``in this world.''
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz complained about Jesus being questioned the night of
his capture without the presence of a lawyer. He then said that,
among Jews, kingship was a longstanding metaphor and that
everything Jesus advocated had been said earlier by Hebrew prophets
and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, he is an itinerant preacher,'' said Dershowitz.
``If you crucify him, you will make him into a martyr who will
crumble your government.''
</P>
<P>
   Callahan rejected that warning. ``A cross doesn't make a
martyr,'' he said. ``A cross is a billboard that announces that
what he was doing was an affront to the emperor, and that anyone
who would do the same will suffer the same destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   The limitations of the class brought the trial to a premature
close. Students voted only with their comments, which were evenly
divided between those who saw the justice of getting rid of the
rebellious rabbi and those who saw no need to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz came up with a novel substitute punishment. ``I think
it would be appropriate to tie him in litigation and appeals for
years,'' he said. ``That way he would spend his life with lawyers,
whom he hated.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox, as Pilate, demurred: ``I think even the Romans would agree
that that would be cruel and unusual punishment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
