<HEADLINE>
PROUD TRADITION CONTINUES IN BRAZIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brazil's cultural and material wealth are enviable, its history
rich and varied. But, as the country celebrates the 500th
anniversary of the arrival of Europeans, probably no single
Brazilian event has received as much international attention as the
July 16, 1950, World Cup final at the Maracana in Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, Uruguay upset the Brazilians, 2-1, sending
virtually the entire population into mourning. The result confirmed
Brazil's colonial inferiority for some and provided motivation for
others to overcome those effects. Once Brazil recovered from the
defeat, it began transforming soccer, injecting a unique feeling of
joy into the game. The Brazilians have been able to blend tactical
imagination with individual creativity to produce an almost hybrid
variety of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   The last 50 years of Brazilian history have been marked by
military dictatorships, voracious consumption of natural resources,
and deteriorating social structures that left huge gaps between
rich and poor, literate and illiterate. But the Maracana still
stands _ it has been declared a historic monument _ and Brazil's
soccer still sets standards.
</P>
<P>
   When Brazil plays host to Ecuador in Sao Paulo Thursday, it will
be defending an unbeaten record in World Cup qualifying home
matches. Brazil has lost only once in World Cup qualifying, when
Bolivia converted twice in the final minutes of a USA '94 game in
La Paz.
</P>
<P>
   Though Brazil has lost one of its great young hopes, Ronaldo, to
more knee surgery, the Selecao should be well-armored. There is
even a chance Romario could return after scoring three goals for
Vasco da Gama in a 5-1 win over Flamengo in the Taca Guanabara
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brazilian Selecao does not exist without Romario,'' Vasco
vice president Eurico Miranda said. ``The Selecao is Romario and 10
other players.''
</P>
<P>
   Romario, 34, is in many ways more of a phenomenon than Ronaldo.
Romario paved the way to Europe for Ronaldo but did not make the
jump to Italy, likely because clubs were concerned about his lack
of physical size and the size of his ego.
</P>
<P>
   Romario has scored 45 goals in 63 internationals. He likely
should have been included on the France '98 team, and it is
incredible that coach Mario Zagallo not only left out Romario but
did not utilize Edmundo. Now, Romario and Edmundo are teammates
with Vasco, and Romario has emerged as the team leader as well as
the Taca Guanabara's top scorer with 15 goals.
</P>
<P>
   Flamengo had discarded Romario last year, and this was an
emotional reunion between Rio's top two teams at the Maracana _ six
players were ejected and seven were issued cautions.
</P>
<P>
   After Vasco fell behind to Flamengo, 1-0, ``Romario asked for
calm from the players and called for them to take responsibility,''
Vasco coach Abel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Romario is the best striker in Brazilian futbol and should be
in the Selecao,'' former Vasco striker Roberto Dinamite said. ``He
is a player cut out for the games that are disputed in a climate of
war, games like the qualifying matches.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   African qualifying for the World Cup moves to group stages with
a draw for the remaining 25 teams in Zurich Friday. Most of the
favorites advanced, though Algeria and South Africa had
difficulties. The Algerians edged Cape Verde, 2-0, sparked by Ahmed
Bourahli in his debut game. Bourahli scored in the ninth minute and
set up Rafik Saifi for the second goal four minutes later. The
crowd at Stade Olympique in Annaba was 80,000 _ greater than the
population of Cape Verde's largest city, Cidade de Praia. South
Africa struggled on a choppy rugby field in Bloemfontein, taking a
1-0 victory over Lesotho. Sean Bartlett, formerly of Colorado and
New York/New Jersey of MLS, converted his 19th international goal.
Assadi Mummer Al-Qadhafi, son of the Libyan chief of state, is
making progress as president of the Libyan Arab Jamahiriya Football
Federation. Assadi, who doubles as a striker for the national team,
has taken Libya into the next round despite a 3-1 loss at Mali. The
Libyans won the first leg, 3-0, in Tripoli. In Monrovia, Liberia,
president Charles Taylor proved he knows how to recruit a crowd to
Samuel K. Doe Stadium. ``Any government minister who is not at that
field will be in trouble,'' threatened Taylor, who is still a
fugitive from justice after his mid-1980s escape from Plymouth
County jail, during a reception before the Liberia-Chad game. The
Liberians advanced after a 0-0 tie, having won, 1-0, in N'Djamena.
But three spectators died as the stadium was filled above the
35,000 capacity. Two were crushed in the crowd and one fell from a
fence attempting to escape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
