<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVIC JOURNALISM: TAKING STOCK AFTER A DECADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ About 100 journalists are attending the James K. Batten
Awards and Symposium, sponsored by the Pew Center for Civic
Journalism. The event features seminars, speeches, an array of
media heavyweights, and a $25,000 prize to be shared by the
Savannah (Ga.) Morning News, The Philadelphia Inquirer, and New
Hampshire Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   The festivities are a celebration of the most significant
journalism reform effort in decades. According to Jan Schaffer,
executive director of the Pew center, the decade-old ``civic
journalism'' movement _ which engages news outlets in direct
conversations with their readers, viewers, and listeners to tackle
community issues _ has spawned hundreds of newsroom projects in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in many quarters, civic journalism is dismissed as
boosterism masquerading as news. While advocates see it as a way of
improving local journalism by reconnecting media outlets with their
audience, detractors see the emphasis on problem-solving as a
distortion of journalistic objectivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never very well defined, I think that was by design,''
says Edward Seaton, former president of the American Society of
Newspaper Editors (ASNE), who has a decidedly mixed view of civic
journalism.
</P>
<P>
   That gets to the heart of the movement's dilemma. To win
converts, it has defined itself so flexibly that both sides view it
through the prism of their own biases. And the detractors seem to
have the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't have a problem with the tools and techniques of
civic journalism,'' says Schaffer. ``They have a problem with the
label.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since this was an argument that tried to persuade people, I
think it's also fair to say a majority of the elite press . . .
remained unpersuaded,'' says Jay Rosen, chairman of the New York
University journalism department and a driving force behind civic
journalism. ``We lost control of part of the rhetoric here.''
</P>
<P>
   In what comes close to being an official definition, the Pew
center says civic journalism treats people ``as civic assets, as
players or participants in the story, rather than as victims or
passive spectators of legislative or bureaucratic processes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Savannah Morning News, a co-recipient of the Batten Award
for Excellence in Civic Journalism, used focus groups and community
forums for its series examining the impact of the region's growing
elderly population. The Inquirer's ``Citizen Voices '99'' project
included more than 60 public forums that helped focus coverage on
Philadelphia's mayoral race. New Hampshire Public Radio's ``Tax
Challenge'' Web site allowed citizens to calculate how various tax
proposals would affect their bills.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was founded in 1993, the Pew Center for Civic
Journalism _ funded by the Pew Charitable Trusts _ has created a
bustling cottage industry, subsidizing more than 92 civic
journalism initiatives in more than 170 print and broadcast
newsrooms. This year, it is bankrolling 15 new projects at outlets
ranging from Wisconsin Public Television to the Yakima (Wa.)
Herald-Republic _ to the tune of about $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The center runs numerous workshops in conjunction with groups
like the Investigative Reporters and Editors and the Radio and
Television News Directors Foundation (RTNDF). More than 2,500
journalists have attended its workshops and more than 6,500 receive
its newsletter, Civic Catalyst. The 116 applicants for the 2000
Batten Awards represent a 25 percent jump over the usual total.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen, for one, is surprised by this emergence. ``I certainly
didn't anticipate a movement . . . a lot of headlines in the trade
press, and a lot of controversy,'' he says. Adds Schaffer: ``I
think it's been validated. . . . We're an R &AMP; D center for content.
I'm proud to have that label. I think it's one of the legacies of
civic journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet civic journalism has run afoul of some high-profile critics.
Washington Post executive editor Leonard Downie Jr. has expressed
doubts and former New York Times executive editor Max Frankel has
written disapprovingly that ``the ardent civic journalists . . .
want to tell it and fix it all at once.'' In The New Yorker,
Michael Kelly, now editor of The Atlantic Monthly, lambasted civic
journalism during the 1996 campaign season, dismissing it as ``a
do-gooding philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   All this has forced advocates to practice careful diplomacy,
trying to win friends without turning off skeptics. The 1998 Batten
Award went to The (Baltimore) Sun, even though its editor John
Carroll (now editor of the Los Angeles Times) said the paper's
``Reading By 9'' project was not civic journalism. Later, a
chagrined Carroll said, ``I kind of regret'' that remark.
</P>
<P>
   ASNE spokesman Craig Branson says his group is ``scrupulously
neutral'' on civic journalism. ``Probably half our members hate the
idea,'' he adds. ``And about 30 percent of our members might say
`hey, we can probably do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently three editors who were leading practitioners _ Steven
Smith of The (Colorado Springs) Gazette, Martha Steffens of the
Binghamton Press &AMP; Sun-Bulletin and Cole Campbell of the St. Louis
Post-Dispatch _ departed those papers. Will their legacies live on?
While lauding civic journalism for helping ``deinstitionalize''
coverage, Smith's successor Terri Fleming, pointedly voices support
for ``a renewed emphasis on those core responsibilities, which I
think we drifted away from.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Swanson, executive director of the RTNDF, says civic
journalism is now less reliant on formal projects and more broadly
defined as ``expanding sources and Rolodexes . . . I would tell you
it's a good thing. The name's had some baggage attached to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston University journalism professor and ex-ABC newsman Bob
Zelnick, who moderates a Batten Symposium seminar Thursday,
expresses a typical view about civic journalism. If it is just
another term for old-fashioned shoe-leather reporting, ``I'm all
for it,'' he says. ``To the extent that civic journalism is looked
upon as a substitute for traditional things journalists cover, I
think it can be looked upon as a source of mischief.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, creative ambiguity about what civic journalism is has
allowed the movement to germinate. But that may also be the
double-edged sword that keeps the reform experiment from winning
the war for hearts and minds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
