<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR FINDS MORE STRIVING TO LIVE `SACRED' LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA AND MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an age when so many Americans are absorbed, perhaps even
obsessed, by the ebbs and flows on Wall Street it would seem an
unlikely moment to be talking about the rebirth of spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that's exactly what Roger Housden discovered when he
traveled across America meeting a diverse range of people, from
Hollywood producers to letter carriers to financial consultants who
are working and struggling to listen to their souls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen individuals all over the country essentially
coming to their own formulation and understanding of what the
sacred means to them personally,'' said Housden, who chronicles his
journey in a recently released book titled ``Sacred America: The
Emerging Spirit of the People.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Spiritual materialism prospers here to a degree that would
stagger any European mind,'' writes Housden, who is British.
``Transformation, or spiritual rebirth itself, through any number
of unique methods, has become a major product line, which points to
how unhappy people must be with who they are already.''
</P>
<P>
   What he finds are people striving to live ``sacred'' lives. But
that doesn't necessarily mean belonging to a religious congregation
or delving into Eastern spiritualism.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Housden found a ``growing call for authenticity. That
is the willingness to stand by and live by what one knows to be
true. I don't mean dogma or beliefs. I mean what you know in your
gut to be so from one moment to the next and having the courage to
live by one's own light.''
</P>
<P>
   Translated into concrete terms, Housden found people driven by
what he describes as a ``spiritual sensibility'' to engage in good
works _ doing something about homelessness, helping former convicts
reintegrate into society and improving public education, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   Housden is part of a recent wave of authors writing about a
spiritual renaissance in America _ a theme that has become hugely
popular in the publishing industry. Part of the reason Housden
cites in his book.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is still one of the most religious countries in the
world, with over 90 percent believing in a god of some kind, and
this religiosity has always colored the nation's own view of
itself,'' Housden writes. ``This is why Americans, even if they do
not articulate it in so many words, and in spite of everything that
points to the whole experiment going horribly wrong, feel in their
bones that there is something sacred about the United States of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   And confirming what has become a dominant view among observers
of American culture, Housden finds the reason Americans are turning
to the ``sacred'' is a response to modern times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prevailing goals set by the culture are entirely
materialistic,'' Housden said in a telephone interview from San
Francisco. ``More and more money and more and more toys. If in
doubt, go shopping. That consumerism is attempting to fill the gap
that you and I and pretty much most people feel _ who am I and what
does it all mean. The people I talked to are interested in
answering those questions in a much deeper way.''
</P>
<P>
   The search for answers is not necessarily leading many people
toward traditional religious institutions that might seem the
likeliest setting for wrestling with questions of meaning and
purpose, Housden said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Housden writes that the ``Sacred America'' he found
is an ``increasing communion of souls who are living their lives,
not by some external dictate of creed or culture, but by the
prompting of the knowing, intelligent heart _ the original meaning
of conscience. This, rather than yet more experts and priests, is
the fertile ground for a leaderless spiritual emergence.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why don't Christians all celebrate Easter at the same time?
</P>
<P>
   The scheduling of Easter is a complicated task that has split
the Eastern and Western branches of Christianity for millennia.
</P>
<P>
   The Western church, which includes Roman Catholics and
Protestants, generally schedules Easter on the first Sunday after
the first full moon after the vernal equinox. But there are
adjustments to that formula in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   The Eastern church uses a similar methodology, but does not
allow Easter to fall until after the Jewish holiday of Passover,
because in the New Testament, the crucifixion and resurrection of
Jesus follow the start of Passover. As a result, the Orthodox
Easter can fall as late as four weeks after the non-Orthodox
Easter.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox and non-Orthodox churches have agreed that scheduling
Easter at the same time is desirable, but they have been unable to
figure out how to do so. Next year, however, their separate
scheduling methods will coincidentally bring them to the same date,
and all Christians will celebrate Easter April 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
