<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TROUBADOUR OF TROUBLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The calypso beat became more insistent in my
noggin with every passing reference, every bumper sticker, every
earnest note about Earth Day, Earth Fortnight, and Earth Month. Tom
Lehrer summed it up Earth Decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you visit American city,
</P>
<P>
   You will find it very pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Just two things of which you must beware:
</P>
<P>
   Don't drink the water and don't breathe the air.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lehrer recorded that ditty at the hungry i (lowercase CQ) here
in July 1965. The North Beach nightclub was probably dark, dank,
and filled with smoke from, among other substances, today's
forbidden fruit, tobacco. Today San Francisco is a capital of what
the geographer Joel Garreau calls ``Ecotopia,'' a peaceable kingdom
awash in self-parody. Some of its denizens might not laugh at
Lehrer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pollution, pollution,
</P>
<P>
   They got smog and sewage and mud.
</P>
<P>
   Turn on your tap and get hot and cold running crud.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When I interviewed Lehrer in 1970, before the first Earth Day,
he noted that this song was his most popular, many furlongs ahead
of such touchy topics as ``Werner Von Braun'' and ``The Vatican
Rag.'' In the late 1960s, ``Pollution'' had become, so to speak,
mainstream. Among those singing it on television were Arthur
Godfrey, Carol Burnett, Nanette Fabray, the Smothers Brothers, and
Bing Crosby.
</P>
<P>
   Before Bing crooned it on ABC, the network asked the author to
change ``mud'' and ``crud'' to ``dust'' and ``rust.'' Lehrer
agreed, he said, ``in the interests of more fearless and forthright
satire.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pollution, pollution,
</P>
<P>
   You can use the latest toothpaste,
</P>
<P>
   And then rinse your mouth with industrial waste.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unlike more persistent troubadours, Lehrer has been publicly
silent, preferring his day job of teaching math, playing the piano
strictly for fun. Good news comes from Atlantic/Rhino Records,
which is issuing a boxed set, ``The Remains of Tom Lehrer,'' in
time to present to college graduates who soon will be, as Lehrer
wrote in 1953, ``sliding down the razor blade of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The CDs could form a crash course on the Cold War the grads were
lucky to miss. ``So Long, Mom,'' ``Who's Next?'' and ``The MLF
Lullaby'' might give some flavor. Among the 74 sendups are some
seldom heard before, like how Lehrer enjoyed spending ``Hannukah in
Santa Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just go out for a breath of air,
</P>
<P>
   And you'll be ready for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The city streets are really quite a thrill,
</P>
<P>
   If the hoods don't get you, the monoxide will.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lehrer once manned a lectern in Cambridge, breathing the same
sharp New England vapors as his peers in American satire, S.J.
Perelman and Fred Allen. He has since decamped to Santa Cruz, an
Ecotopian outpost on Monterey Bay, where the state university is
itself a study in self-parody. Designed in reaction to the 1960s,
the campus has no large Berkeleyesque quadrangle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pollution, pollution,
</P>
<P>
   Wear a gas mask and a veil.
</P>
<P>
   Then you can breathe, long as you can inhale.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 35 years since Lehrer wrote about its defilement, the
Earth has made a comeback. Boston Harbor is now a silken reservoir
of Perrier, recycling is a ritual for millions, and Earth Day has
surpassed for the truly hip the fussier rites of Easter and
Passover.
</P>
<P>
   The Earthlings Uber Alles cult surely needs the needle Lehrer
applied to ``The Folk Song Army.'' A grim bumper sticker, ``The
Earth Does Not Belong to Us. We Belong to the Earth,'' could
inspire ``Mudpie Lullaby.'' Lehrer could do it effortlessly. He's
already proved that he is brilliantly bicoastal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The breakfast garbage they throw out in Troy
</P>
<P>
   They drink at lunch in Perth Amboy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   is a New York taunt transformed into a California cavil:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The breakfast garbage that you throw into the Bay
</P>
<P>
   They drink at lunch in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
