<HEADLINE>
HOW DUMB ARE THESE REPUBLICANS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quick parlor game to determine the bona fides of the Republican
Party's feigned outrage over the snatching of the little Cuban boy
from his captors, er, his great uncle:
</P>
<P>
   Take a sampling of the statements from our leading Republican
solons, and where the name ``Elian'' appears, substitute ``Monica''
and scan closely any quote that contains the phrase ``the rule of
law.''
</P>
<P>
   First up: good old Henry Hyde, the Santa Claus of the
impeachment farce, rumbling about how he's ordered his staff to do
a ``preliminary investigation'' before some big-time congressional
hearings. Henry, we missed you. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   There's Senate majority leader Trent Lott, the oleaginous
Mississippian, forsaking his normal business of looting the defense
budget for his Pascalouga shipyard down home. Lott, who went
through three starched shirts a day running from microphone to
microphone during impeachment, hauled Janet Reno in for grilling
Tuesday. He wants hearings too.
</P>
<P>
   The usual claque of Sun Belt Claghorns evoked images of Waco and
jackbooted government thugs along the lines of the National Rifle
Association's anti-gun-control propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   Even New York Mayor Rudy Giuliani, who knows a thing or two
about storm troopers, denounced ``storm troopers'' in Miami. Now
there's one for the books.
</P>
<P>
   And how about New Hampshire Senator Bob Smith? This is a guy who
gives nincompoops a bad name. This oafish orator, who defected from
the GOP last year only to come crawling back when Lott bribed him
with a committee chairmanship, ran to the Washington airport to
embrace Elian's dysfunctional extended family when he heard there
were TV cameras at the gate and no politician to hog them. ``Abuse
of power,'' sputtered Smith, who is rarely at a loss for a sound
bite, no matter how hypocritical.
</P>
<P>
   The same old gang that led the charge on impeachment,
Whitewater, Filegate, Travelgate, and investigating and harassing
everyone around Clinton, including the secretary and the steward
who brings in his morning coffee, those same Grand Inquisitors are
back in business over this 6-year-old kid whom the Cuban lobby in
Miami refused to turn back to his own father.
</P>
<P>
   How dumb are these Republicans? Dumb enough to try it all over
again. Though I suspect their ardor will cool when they digest the
implications of the poll numbers. Outside of the hothouse
atmosphere of Dade County, most Americans think the boy belongs
back with his dad.
</P>
<P>
   From the lofty editorial perches of New York flutter down
condemnations cloaked in conflicting logic. Yeah, sure, the boy
belonged back with his dad, grumped The New York Times on Sunday,
but the method used, though no one was seriously hurt, ``is likely
to haunt the country for years to come.'' Oh?
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Times opinion hardened: the government acted ``rashly
and unwisely'' and should have taken longer in dealing with the
relatives, whose appearances on TV only reinforce the doubts Janet
Reno had about their willingness to ever turn the kid over to
rightful authorities. The Little Havana ``family'' makes ``The
Sopranos'' look almost normal.
</P>
<P>
   The Times thus joined hands with the rabid anti-Clintonists of
The Wall Street Journal, whose fulminations described this
skillfully exercised humanitarian act in gangsterish terms. And not
to be missed is Peggy Noonan's latest anti-Clinton jihad yammering
about the dolphins who surrounded Elian ``like a contingent of
angels.'' This is ax-grinding presented as a film script treatment.
Say, Irv, can we get Flipper for the dolphin part? Is it time to
get real yet?
</P>
<P>
   Remember all the marching around and harrumphing by the Sun Belt
Brigade over IRS horror stories, with tearful taxpayers complaining
that those meanies in green eyeshades were wrecking the lives of
decent citizens? They had hearings that went all over C-Span and
the networks. And the envelope, please?
</P>
<P>
   ``Congressional investigators were unable to substantiate the
allegations of IRS misconduct,'' the AP reported in deadpan fashion
Monday. It quoted the Government Accounting Office _ firmly in
control of the Republican majority these days _ whose report was
completed last May but withheld from the public, apparently because
the Republican ransackers could find no horror stories that
withstood scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our investigation established that the allegations themselves
had been based on an incomplete awareness of the total
circumstances,'' concluded the GAO. Game, set, match.
</P>
<P>
   Toss this report on the mountain of Republican probes that went
nowhere: Whitewater, impeachment, Travelgate, Filegate, the legal
shakedowns of the secretary of labor, the former secretary of HUD,
etc., etc. Millions have been sluiced down the trough of partisan
tomfoolery to no end but to discredit the Clinton administration
and try to overturn not one but two national elections. If that's
not a ``vast right-wing conspiracy,'' folks, it'll do till the real
thing comes along.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
