<HEADLINE>
NEW ENGLAND ARCHER ON TARGET FOR THE OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Butch Johnson has a gold medal in his trophy case, but a gold
medal isn't a return ticket to Olympus. Certainly not in the sport
of distant bull's-eyes and twitchy fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Archery is one of those games where you have your ups and
downs,'' Johnson said. ``If you're shooting good at the right time
. . .''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was on a down during the US Olympic Trials last summer.
So when he missed making the three-man team by 22 points (out of
more than 5,000), Johnson shrugged, packed up his bow and arrows,
and went back to Woodstock, Conn. ``It's OK,'' he told himself.
``Life goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in December, the phone rang from Colorado Springs. It was
George Greenway, the National Archery Association's executive
director, telling the 44-year-old Johnson that he had a ticket to
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Parker, the former schoolteacher who had edged Johnson at
the trials, had been kicked off the team for shooting two extra
arrows in the opening round. ``What was my reaction? Kind of glad I
made it,'' Johnson said. ``But nothing spectacular.''
</P>
<P>
   Archery's hit-or-miss nature tends to flatten out emotions that
way. If you let your psyche be ruled by the flight of an arrow,
you'll end up pulling drawstrings in a rubber room.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you run the same elimination round 10 days in a row,''
Johnson said, ``you'll have 10 different winners. That's the way
the game is.''
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson went to the 1992 Olympics in Barcelona, the US
males finished sixth. Four years ago in Atlanta, they won both the
individual and team golds. This time, they could be sixth again. So
Johnson is going easy on the euphoria pills.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have dreamed that Parker could have gotten the boot?
Nobody saw him shoot the extra arrows _ everybody was watching
Olympic hopeful Geena Davis (yes, the actress) at the other end of
the range.
</P>
<P>
   Parker claimed he didn't know he'd done it until he found the
arrows behind the target after the round, when the scores had
already been tabulated. If he hadn't told a fellow
archer/ex-girlfriend, who told someone else . . .
</P>
<P>
   And who would have guessed that Justin Huish, the hang-loose
ponytailed dude who'd gone double gold in Atlanta, would get
arrested in February for possessing marijuana with intent to
distribute, and quit the team?
</P>
<P>
   No alternate had ever made the Olympic archery squad. Suddenly,
two have. The new roster (original member Vic Wunderle, Johnson,
and Rod White) is ``Olympic team version 3.0,'' joked team coach
Lloyd Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is sanguine about all this. Random chance and
hairbreadth margins are archery's essence. Ask William Tell. To
make the US team, competitors shot 576 arrows in two sets of trials
in New Jersey and California, aiming at a target the size of a
softball from 70 meters away.
</P>
<P>
   The top archers will hit the bull's-eye more than 90 percent of
the time. Missing the target is virtually unheard of. ``I might
miss once a year,'' said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   It's nothing like shooting free throws, and athletic ability
only goes so far. (Johnson didn't play a sport in high school.)
Medals can be decided by a heartbeat _ literally.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people develop fear,'' Johnson said. ``Some of them
just can't handle it, and they basically fall apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who was born in Worcester, Mass. and moved to nearby
Webster when he was 14, came to the sport by chance. ``When I was
15, an archery shop opened up in our neighborhood, and I went with
my brother-in-law to give it a try,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, Johnson entered the state championships and
beat every adult there. The next year, he went to the nationals and
began a long, meandering path to the Olympics, which had just
restored archery after half-a-century's absence.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Johnson ever had five-ringed dreams. He'd glance at the
TV when the Games were on, he said, ``but I didn't go out of my
way.'' Johnson wasn't even competing in the Olympic event. He was
doing compound (where the bow has pulleys and cables), not recurve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I got disqualified for some of the picky rules they used
to have,'' Johnson said. So he crossed over to the Olympic side and
ended up making the team for Barcelona, roaming the athletes'
village with the runners and gymnasts and swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think, `Hey, there's Carl Lewis,' '' Johnson said. ``But
you'd walk by and wouldn't say anything. You didn't want to bother
them. They didn't know who we were.''
</P>
<P>
   Olympus was everything Johnson thought it would be _ and less.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it was a little disappointing,'' he confessed.
``There's all that hoopla, but it was like going to another
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   It was nothing like that in 1996, when the Americans came out of
nowhere (``We would have been happy with a bronze,'' he said.) to
pull off a sweep on home ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said it was one of the best events to watch,'' Johnson
said. ``The stands were full and everybody was going crazy.
Probably the best moment of my life was watching the flag go up and
hearing the anthem. I turned around and said to Rod (White), `This
makes all the hard work worth it.' I'd do 10 times the work to get
back here.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had no illusions about the gold medal changing his
world. Kerri Strug he wasn't. Woodstock, which is in Connecticut's
``quiet corner'' up near the Massachusetts and Rhode Island
borders, threw a get-together for him when he got back. So did
Webster. Then Johnson went back to his job as sales manager for
Hall's Arrow in Manchester, Conn., and began preparing for the next
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Archers work the amateur side of Olympus, along with the
judokas, the modern pentathletes, the table tennis players. Until
they make the national team, they pay for everything _ equipment,
coaching, travel _ out of pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to make some money at this, but it's not the
game I'm in,'' said Johnson, who also coached fellow Connecticut
resident Karen Scavotto to a place on the Olympic team. ``Oh, well
. . .''
</P>
<P>
   He is famous in the way small-town people are famous. ``Letters
addressed to Butch Johnson, Woodstock CT, show up at my house,'' he
said. ``And sometimes people will say, `Oh, you're the guy who does
the archery.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson didn't figure to be doing it Down Under this summer,
even though he'd won three national titles since Atlanta. He went
to last year's trials in a slump amid a hectic personal time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised I didn't make it, but there was a lot going on
in my life and I was going through a divorce, which didn't make
things any easier,'' Johnson said. ``So it didn't surprise me
completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson went back to Woodstock and resumed practicing on the
homemade range in back of his house. In October, he began hearing
grapevine talk about Parker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew something was going on, but they kept it very quiet,''
Johnson said. ``I was just waiting to see what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   When the word came down, Johnson popped no champagne corks. It's
not as if he hasn't climbed Olympus before. And Parker is still
going through the appeals process. ``My understanding is, he
doesn't have much of a prayer,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a hit-or-miss sport, which is why Johnson left the
year loose. ``I hadn't made plans,'' he said. ``I was going to keep
competing anyway. Whatever happens, happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is between jobs; he's worked at a marina, in an auto
body shop, and as a carpenter. The phone could ring any time
between now and mid-September, saying that an arbitrator has
decided otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, Johnson will pack up bow and arrows and head for
Australia, where he's never been. So it goes in Robin Hood's
pastime. ``If you don't make a team,'' Butch Johnson said,
``there's always another team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
