<HEADLINE>
ANNUITY YIELD IS FIXED, BUT CD'S A RATE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. A small pension, Social Security, dividends, interest from
savings, and a 401(k) that has been converted to a lifetime annuity
give me enough to live on in my senior co-op and to travel. Is it
better to leave my IRA in the bank and make the required
withdrawals or convert it to an annuity as I did with my 401(k)?
</P>
<P>
   M.H., Laguna Woods, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A. Well, let's assume you can earn 6 percent on your CD, the
national average for bank CDs entering this week. (The highest rate
for five-year CDs of less than $100,000 was 7.41 percent.) If you
are earning that 6 percent and if you simply withdrew $395 a month,
the pool would last you a little longer than 19 years, 10 months.
Should you die before those 19.9 years are up, the balance in the
account would go to your estate, or to whomever you chose to give
it through your will.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you go for the annuity, you are guaranteed
that $395 a month _ no matter how long you live. If you die before
age 90, the insurance company pockets the residual cash that you
have not withdrawn; nothing accrues to your estate.
</P>
<P>
   There is also another way to look at this proposition. You could
currently move the money to a 7.41 percent CD; if such rates held,
the pool would support withdrawals of $395 a month for a little
more than 26 1/2 years, until you are approaching age 96. Of
course, if you did buy that 7.41 percent CD you would be assured
that rate for only five years; after that you would have to renew
at a rate that could be higher, lower, or the same. So if you
decide to keep the money in CDs, you face the risk that future
rates might make a $395 monthly withdrawal deplete your capital at
a faster rate.
</P>
<P>
   A final consideration is that if you keep the money in the IRA,
you will have it available should you run into some kind of
emergency. You would not enjoy that flexibility with an annuity;
after all, the insurance company's bet is basically that you will
not live long enough to make you a winner in this deal.
</P>
<P>
   I searched the Web for an idea of life expectancy for a person
in your situation, but there were too many variables to get a firm
figure. The best estimate I could come up with was in the range of
eight to 12 years. If you kept the CD and withdrew $395 a month for
eight years, there would be a $47,772 balance when you died; if you
lived 12 more years, the balance would be $42,204. Both of those
calculations were based on the projected 7.41 percent return; if
you used the national average 6 percent interest, the figures would
be $40,259 and $29,780 respectively.
</P>
<P>
   It's up to you to decide. If you think you can celebrate your
95th or 100th birthday with a toast to the insurance company, go
ahead with the annuity. Myself, I'd keep the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Our children are now graduated from college, and we
anticipate retiring at age 62, after increasing our current savings
level. How should we allocate our money in the next 10 years so
that we will be able to add $15,000 a year to our pension income?
Where should we place our ongoing savings to best achieve this?
</P>
<P>
   P.P., Scituate, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, on paper the course you are taking works out almost
perfectly. If you achieved 8 percent average annual returns from
your portfolio for the next 10 years and contributed $600 a month,
you would have a pool of $229,597. If that were then moved to a
fixed-income portfolio yielding 6.5 percent, that would bring you
$14,728 a year, which, as the be-bop boys used to say, is close
enough for jazz.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not close enough for me, because this would mean you
would have no savings set aside to offset the inflation of the
later years or your retirement, and when you retire at age 62,
there are likely to be a lot of those later years. To give you an
idea of the effects of inflation, you would need $77,582 in 10
years to buy what $55,000 buys now. And even if you have already
factored in inflation when you came up with that $55,000 retirement
budget, you still would have the inflation after age 62 to deal
with.
</P>
<P>
   So I suggest that old unpleasant alternative _ save more, or
retire later.
</P>
<P>
   You may question why I used an 8 percent projection of portfolio
growth _ certainly the picture would have been brighter with an
assumption of 10 percent projected growth. And there is no question
that your fund choices are solid, and the money market position
represents only 16.66 percent of the portfolio. I do this partly
because about a decade before retirement I suggest that people
begin moving toward a more conservative portfolio, and partly
because I foresee some fairly lean market years in the early part
of that 10-year savings program.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion at this point would be to begin moving toward a
more conservative portfolio by using funds such as Vanguard
Balanced Index, Janus Balanced, Fidelity Puritan, or AIM Balanced _
all solid entries and within the fund families you are already
using. Since all of these funds divide their portfolios between
stocks and fixed-income holdings, you will be slowly building a
fixed-income element in your portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Then, about five years before your anticipated retirement date,
you should begin stepping up the pace, so that by the time you
retire you will have enough there to supply the needed income
stream, as well as a healthy reserve to be left in stocks to deal
with future inflation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We are retired and plan to sell our home in Massachusetts
this year and moving to Florida. We are thinking of renting for one
year before buying a house or condo there. What would you recommend
for a conservative low-risk investment with a reasonable yield?
This would be used primarily for paying the rent and any incidental
housing costs.
</P>
<P>
   J.G., Reading, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Boy, are you planning to do the right thing! I can't remember
how many times over the years I have received letters from people
who decided to sell their northern homes and move to Florida or
Arizona, or any of the other southern climes. And then, after
they'd sold their old houses, bought new ones, and made the move,
they found they hated it.
</P>
<P>
   So back they were coming from somebody else's idea of paradise _
and their finances were invariably in a mess. So, yes _ your idea
of renting for a year before taking the plunge is an excellent one.
And if you're uncertain after a year, it might make sense to look
at another part of Florida and rent there for a year, stretching
the process out further.
</P>
<P>
   As for the best conservative low-risk investment for parking
$300,000 for a year (or maybe two) _ that's a no-brainer. You can
get one-year jumbo CDs paying as high as 7.02 percent entering this
week. Provided you divide your CD holdings so that you're within
the FDIC insurance limits at each of the institutions you choose,
that's a conservative, NO-risk investment. How are you likely to
beat that?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
