<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7644 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BIOTECH-VENTURE-ART-B     04-26 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-VENTURE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 STILL BETTING ON BIOTECH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the last three years, it seems that venture capitalists have
been willing to invest in anything _ anything, that is, but
biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   Why struggle for eight to 10 years to develop a drug that must
go through extensive governmental regulatory approvals when a
dot-com venture can be launched with less money and provide a
twentyfold return 18 months later in an initial public offering?
</P>
<P>
   ``Biotech in the early 1990s was like a Hollywood that believed
in small films from independent producers where you had a cute
story and maybe a clever script and a director,'' said
Jean-Francois Formela, general partner at Atlas Ventures, the
Boston venture capital firm that has invested nearly 15 percent of
its funds in biotech.
</P>
<P>
   But after being burned with lots of little investments, venture
capitalists today ``are like big studios with lots of money
searching for script, stars, and hefty paybacks relatively
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a decade ago when science was the script and story that
wowed Wall Street, today's heftier biotech deals put greater
pressures on scientific management teams to execute a realistic
business strategy for revenue growth.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the big many venture houses have shied away from
biotechnology. Last year, 26 New England biotech companies received
$121.8 million in funding, or just 2.9 percent of the $4.1 billion
invested by venture capitalists in the region, according to a Price
WaterhouseCoopers. In 1997, biotech drew $202.6 million, or nearly
15 percent of the $1.4 billion invested in New England venture
deals.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is money to be had. ``We've seen a renewed interest
in biotech financing that we have not seen in quite a while,'' said
Sheila Matthews, chief financial officer of Epic Therapeutics Inc.
of Norwood, which received $12.5 million in new financing 13 months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Venture houses with sophisticated partners who can spot the
science that will succeed in the market are having no trouble
luring investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you pick the companies and execute well the financial
returns can be phenomenal,'' aid Nicholas G. Galakatos, a general
partner in MPM Capital LP who helped build Millennium
Pharmaceuticals, the Cambridge biotechnology firm that currently
has a market value of $5.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Tapping European money sources, MPM Capital's president, Dr.
Ansbert Gadicke, quickly raised $230 million for his
Cambridge-based firm, which has invested in 25 companies in less
than three years. Some have been in late-stage investments, where
companies need additional funds just before launching an initial
public offering. Others have been in companies that provide
software database tools to biologists and other researchers for
drug development.
</P>
<P>
   Gadicke, sees big opportunities ahead in biotech, particularly
weekly scientific breakthroughs in genomics, the study of genes
that cause diseases and other areas. These new findings, he said,
will spawn new companies and expand the biotech industry.
</P>
<P>
   One MPM investment, Caliper Technologies of Novato, Calif., a
developer of medical testing using a computer-like chip, hit the
Wall Street jackpot earlier this year when MPM's $5 million
investment became worth nearly $160 million.
</P>
<P>
   And earlier this month MPM rose to the top of a relatively small
group of big biotech financiers, announcing plans to invest a
record $600 million _ 90 percent of it in biotechnology and medical
device and 10 percent e-health startups. The huge investment is
nearly double the $310 million raised by Schroeder Ventures
International Life Sciences fund last September.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (MPM) are a very impressive and creative group,'' said
John Littlechild general partner at Healthcare Ventures, one of the
oldest biotechnology venture firms which is about to close on a
$175 million biotech fund after having invested $156 million over
the past 3 1/2 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will be more biotech money raised in the
near-term as investors see the opportunities in genomics,
bioinformatics, and other scientific areas but it will always be a
small part next to high tech investing,'' said Gadicke, who
previously worked at Boston Consulting Group developing business
strategies and product marketing development with pharmaceutical
companies firms as well as his own company.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, MPM led an $11 million investment to put
Worcester-based t.breeders Inc. , which has developed technology to
expand and replicate stem cells, the life-saving blood cells that
are the building blocks of the immune system, together with
ViaCord, Inc. a private cord blood stem cell service company. The
seven-year old Boston-based company collects and stores the blood
from the umbilical cord of newborn babies for future use within the
family.
</P>
<P>
   Gadicke and MPM are putting more money into companies _ an
average of $15 million per company in the new $600 million fund
spread out over three to five years, versus an average of $8
million in the current fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's venture capitalist in biotech is making bets on
companies that can generate revenue and profits in a short period
of time _ three to six years maybe _ compared to the old model of
developing a drug from start to finish that took eight years,''
said David Barry, senior editor of Venture Capital &AMP; Health Care, a
monthly newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond starting new companies, venture capitalists like MPM see
profits coming from financing existing biotech firms. Later-stage
companies _ those with positive data from early human clinical
trial enable investors to enter the last and next-to-last private
round before a company is either acquired or goes public. Knowing
whether the proposed drug will work and forecast its chances of
gaining US Food and Drug Adminstration approval sharply reduces the
financial risks, Gadicke said.
</P>
<P>
   Venture firms also are looking to invest in publicly-traded
biotech comapnies who need additional cash to complete a clinical
trial or launch a product but whose share price is often too low
for a secondary stock offering. Called Private Investments in
Public Enterprises, or PIPES, these investmentes enable venture
firms to get an equity stake in a promising company at a discount
price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biotechnology in the next 20 years will provide us with new
drugs to treat the underlying causes of diabetes, and certain
cancers and cardiovascular diseases,'' said Gadicke. ``I think a
lot of it will come from companies here in Boston, as well as
California and in Europe. And we want to be the major financial
player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
