<HEADLINE>
DURACELL SEEKS A RECHARGE STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How much juice does Duracell have?
</P>
<P>
   Deep inside Gillette Co.'s quarterly earnings news last week was
this disappointing nugget: Sales at Duracell's global battery
business were down 2 percent and, worse, operating profits had sunk
by a startling 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There are explanations for the setback, most notably the impact
of a weak euro currency on European business and excess battery
supply purchased months earlier by consumers worried about
potential Y2K malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bump on a long and profitable road,'' said Duracell
senior vice president Bruce Cleverly.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no getting around the fact that sales growth at
Duracell has slowed noticeably for more than two years. Revenue
growth that averaged about 10 percent annually between 1995 and
1997 came in at 4 percent in 1998 and 6 percent last year. Now this
year has begun with a quarterly sales decline.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, earnings growth has been better. Duracell operating
profits have grown by an average of about 10 percent annually over
the last five years, but only 2 percent to a total of $606 million
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette, which paid $7.8 billion for Duracell in late 1996,
boasted at the time how its global marketing operations could help
sell more batteries everywhere on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   It also pushed an intriguing idea: The market segmentation
strategy that worked so well with shaving products, generating new,
better, and more expensive labels like Sensor Excel and Mach 3,
would be applied to Duracell batteries around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Duracell plotted how it could move more of the global market up
from zinc batteries to superior and pricier alkaline products. By
1998, it rolled out a new Ultra label of high-end alkaline
batteries pitched to American customers who were using more
``high-drain'' expensive electronics than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened on the way to global domination. The
international strategy has succeeded to a degree, but economic
problems and other woes in different regions have impeded global
growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers (globally) are not trading up to the alkaline
batteries as much as I expected,'' said Gillette stock analyst Tony
Vento of Edward Jones. ``I think a lot of that is the result of
these economic difficulties around the world in the last few
years.''
</P>
<P>
   In America, other questions remain unanswered. Will a more
finely tuned segmenting strategy work for batteries over time? Can
Duracell pull off Gillette's strategy without the overwhelming 70
percent market domination its parent firm holds in the razor world?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very high-impulse, low brand-loyalty category,''
said John Daggett, a spokesman for Rayovac Corp., the number three
battery competitor. ``So far, the consumer hasn't fully embraced
(segmentation). There is some sticker shock with consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Duracell say the sales numbers speak for themselves. The company
generated $400 million in Ultra sales in 1999, its first full year
on the market. Duracell has just rolled out the latest generation
of Ultra and boosted promotional spending to back it up. ``Clearly,
we've demonstrated there's a need for a higher-powered alkaline
product,'' said Cleverly at Duracell.
</P>
<P>
   No one doubts Duracell is selling higher-margin Ultra batteries,
which cost about 20 percent more than regular alkalines. But
Duracell has been cannibalizing some of its own regular alkaline
sales to generate the business.
</P>
<P>
   Ultra doubled its share of the alkaline battery market in March,
to 12.4 percent, compared to the same month last year, but Duracell
lost even more in regular-alkaline sales. Overall, Duracell's total
alkaline market share slipped from 50.2 percent to 48.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, second-place Energizer has recently rolled out a
high-end battery of its own. Gillette never had to deal with a
significant second-place competitor to the Mach 3 razor.
</P>
<P>
   Duracell controlled 46.3 percent of the US battery market,
measured in dollars, over a 52-week period ended April 1, according
to A.C. Nielsen. Energizer, a newly independent company spun out of
parent Ralston Purina Group this month, owned a 31.7 percent market
share. Rayovac held 13.1 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue: Are high-performance alkaline batteries really
worth it? Research published in December by Consumer Reports found
Duracell Ultra did perform better in the most demanding situations,
but was too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``In effect, the Ultra's big price swamps its superior
performance,'' Consumer Reports said. ``The moral on battery
shopping is simple: Buy by price.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleverly points out that sales comparisons to 1999, with its Y2K
battery sales, will be difficult this year, but still other factors
work in Duracell's favor in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long-term prospects are brighter than ever,'' he said. ``I
think this is a high single-digit to low double-digit growth
business for us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
