u f BC-INVESTMENT-CLUBS-BOS &LR;      04-26 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVESTMENT-CLUBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN BONDING AROUND STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are not your stereotypical strong-willed investors: New to
the market all, they include a dental assistant, a hairdresser, an
accounts-payable clerk, and a nurse. But when the Dow performed its
stomach-turning acrobatics recently, the members of the South
Shore's Kitchen Kabinet Investment Club kept their equilibrium
quite well, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   If your stock-picking technique is a mixture of research and
women's intuition, they say, you surely can stick out the volatile
days.
</P>
<P>
   As analysts try to gauge the mass reaction to an up-again,
down-again market, they might as well examine women like these. If
the current economic boom was built in part on individual
investors, members of clubs such as Kitchen Kabinet represent a
significant subset. The mostly middle-income women meet around
dining room tables over brownies and Goldfish crackers, discussing
market shifts. Buoyed by group security, they are drawn to stocks
with a tangible appeal.
</P>
<P>
   And committed to investing with other women. Of the 36,500 clubs
affiliated with the National Association of Investors Corp. _ each
with an average portfolio of about $40,000 and an average monthly
contribution of $58 per member _ more than half are women-only.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they'll perform better than men is a matter of debate.
Research suggests that women and men do, indeed, approach the
market with different perspectives. One University of
California-Davis study suggests that in the long run, women will
win. Men, overconfident about their knowledge, trade too often to
maximize returns, it says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women, I think, simply make better investors,'' says Jonathan
Pond, an author and commentator. ``They're more likely to hold onto
investments. . . . You don't do well churning your portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   And at a time when investor stamina could mean the difference
between continued boom and recession, the market needs all of the
long-term investors it can get. It needs women like the members of
Kitchen Kabinet who, at their most recent meeting, held fast to
their 13 shares of Microsoft despite a scathing federal court
ruling that sent the value tumbling.
</P>
<P>
   Too early to tell, they said, comparing notes in one member's
Braintree, Mass. home. Not enough stock to worry. Besides, drawn as
they are these days to the business news channels, they try not to
fixate on the daily reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got you glooming and dooming,'' said Lynne Cowan, 47.
</P>
<P>
   It helps, they say, to have the support of a group of women like
them. Many say they wouldn't have plunged into the market at all if
men had been involved. Some cite math anxiety, some a belief that
men would stifle discussion. Some suggest they can better handle a
turbulent market if they bond with their fellow seafarers.
</P>
<P>
   Men? ``I think they'd cramp our style,'' Cowan said. ``If we
want to talk about the kids today, we do. If we want to talk about
how someone is premenopausal or perimenopausal, we do.''
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to investing, the nine women in Kitchen
Kabinet say they're most comfortable with what they consider a
feminine decision-making process. Picking a stock might be partly
about examining the numbers, they say. But it's also a matter of
examining your gut.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen Kabinet members decided, early on, that they wanted to
invest in growth companies without taking on too great a risk. They
wanted to gauge how well their stocks were faring, based on
patterns they could see and touch.
</P>
<P>
   So while they researched return rates and assessed stock values,
they often selected stocks for less analytical reasons. Their very
first purchase was Wal-Mart, because every time they drove by a
store, the parking lot was full.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `You know, Wal-Mart's never empty,' '' said Meredith
Keane, 54, a business telemarketer who is the club's president.
``Whenever I go by there, there's somebody coming and going. It's
like the cemetery.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion that daily observations can translate into profits,
is, to some women, a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Manton, a women's studies professor at the University
of Massachusetts-Boston, considers it one reason that, before the
precipitous dip of two weeks ago, her Womyn Investors' Club had
generated a $10,000 return after less than three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are really great investors,'' said Manton, 57, who
founded the club, of female UMass faculty, students and staff. ``We
tend to be fairly shrewd about looking at the things around us.''
</P>
<P>
   Male investors, too, often follow the ``buy what you know''
strategy, Brown University sociologist Brooke Harrington said, but
what they think they know can be vastly different. Women relate to
the economy as consumers, she said, and tend to focus on companies
such as Wal-Mart and Home Depot (another Kitchen Kabinet holding)
whose progress they can see and touch. Men view the economy as
producers and workers. So the relatively rare all-male investment
clubs, which make up 8 percent of the NAIC's member clubs, tend to
focus on stocks that relate to their fields of work.
</P>
<P>
   All-male clubs also tend to take more risks than women's clubs,
Harrington said. Kitchen Kabinet's portfolio is filled with proven
blue chips, and club members swear off any stocks that involve too
much watching or worrying.
</P>
<P>
   But Harrington suspects that a conservative approach has more to
do with the sorts of women who join all-female clubs than with
their gender alone.
</P>
<P>
   Women who enter the market in groups tend to be older; the
median age of NAIC members is 50. Most are new to investing,
uncomfortable with the financial decisions that, in the past, they
might have left to husbands or pension plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in a household where Daddy worked and Mom stayed
home. Men knew more about the money,'' said Susan Griffin, 51, a
marketing worker who belongs to the Womyn Investors' Club.
</P>
<P>
   Many club members also eye retirement with genuine concern,
aware of social trends that leave elderly women worse off than
elderly men. That fear can be a strong motivation, Manton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep down inside,'' it said, ``every woman fears she'll be a
bag lady when she gets old.''
</P>
<P>
   But if retirement can be fearsome, so can investing, Manton said
_ particularly for women who have never approached it before. Clare
Crawford, 61, an administrative assistant at UMass, said being
around other women helps.
</P>
<P>
   She was nervous at meetings, and, from relationships with an
aggressive father, husband, and boyfriend, shy in her dealings with
men.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy wanted to say something, I'd probably just wait,''
Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analyst Susan Kaplan said she has seen that dynamic
play out in clubs with both men and women. ``The men really run the
group, really tend to bulldoze women into doing things more
quickly, and, to use a male term, `pull the trigger,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With women, Crawford said, she is more comfortable interrupting
and disagreeing. She has become more accustomed to analyzing stocks
and doing math. ``I've grown through it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether her returns will grow as quickly is another matter.
Harrington, who studied investment clubs for her dissertation,
found that female-male clubs tend to perform the best, because
they're able to blend a mix of investing styles.
</P>
<P>
   And Terrance Odean, a business school professor at the
University of California-Davis, says investment clubs of all types
tend to underperform.
</P>
<P>
   But there are definite advantages to facing the Dow and Nasdaq
in groups, club members and financial advisers say.
</P>
<P>
   When the Womyn Investors' Club took a $5,000 paper loss in the
April 14 stock market dive, Crawford admitted to jitters. Had she
been a lone investor, she said, she might have started selling. But
because she shared her woes with 14 other women, she figured they'd
stay in.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, profits notwithstanding, Kitchen Kabinet members say
they're satisfied with the club dynamics as they are.
</P>
<P>
   So every time they've posted ads for new members, they've found
an easy way to winnow down the replies. First, they eliminate the
men.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7655 &Cx1f; tdt-z
