<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HO-HUM HOUSTON; A SERIOUS VIBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's an old expression ``GP time,'' which means ``gay
people's time,'' which means at least 30 minutes later than a
designated time. (C'mon brothers and sisters _ when's the last time
you attended a gay event that actually started on time?) Yet while
gay folks perhaps can't tell time, they have always been blessed
with a dramatic sense of timing. To wit, there's Whitney Houston's
megawatt smile beaming from the cover of the May issue of Out. This
would be significant if only because Miss Whitney has been dissed
no end lately, what with all sorts of nasty rumors following her
high-profile no-show at last month's Academy Awards ceremony. But
this is supposed to be major since this is a gay magazine, and from
the first note Houston ever sang, she has been dogged by rumors
that she is gay, and that her marriage to Mr. Whitney Houston _
formerly known as singer Bobby Brown _ is a sham. So, of course,
Barry Walters pops the inevitable ``are you now or have you ever
been'' question. Even less surprising is Houston's answer _ ``I am
not a lesbian, darling.''
</P>
<P>
   This interview took place in February, so there's nothing about
the recent escapades that have turned her into tabloid catnip _ and
that's too bad since tittering about her latest antics is far more
interesting than dusty decade-old dish about her sexuality. I mean,
does anyone still care whether Houston is gay? And besides, aren't
we now preoccupied with Kevin Spacey's business anyway?
</P>
<P>
   More provocative is Nicholas Weinstock's thoughtful essay about
being a straight man whose closest friends are gay. Having one gay
friend, he contends, is cheered in certain circles as ``a sign of
hipness, looseness.'' But since Weinstock's number of gay buddies
and galpals are nudging double digits, he's the ``subject of
anxious observation'' from the friends and family. Even gay
acquaintances find his associations suspect. Weinstock unveils his
journey from a boy raised to ``heckle and fear the dark cult of
same-sexdom'' to someone who, save for the purpose of this article,
doesn't spend much time pondering his friends' sexual orientations.
All that matters, he writes, is his hope that ``Someday we will
live and love and lunch in a place free from priggish rules.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did law enforcement fail to protect a young boy? Did government
officials ignore and neglect what was best for a defenseless child?
I'm not referring to the made-for-TV saga of Elian Gonzalez, but to
Leroy Brown Jr. In January 1999, the 8-year-old and his mother,
Karen Clarke, were gunned down in their Bridgeport, Conn., home.
Their deaths may have been just another statistic if not for the
fact that Brown was the star witness in a case that connected a
local drug dealer to the murder of Clarke's boyfriend. In Vibe,
writer Rob Kenner contends Brown didn't hesitate to tell his story,
but maintains law enforcement types dropped the ball in protecting
the boy and his mother from retaliation. Although initially there
were officers stationed outside the family's home, for reasons
still unclear the surveillance abruptly ended _ even though the
alleged killer, who was later charged in the murders, was out on
bail. In the aftermath of the deaths, the Clarke family hired
Johnnie Cochran and filed a multimillion-dollar lawsuit against the
state. ``Witnesses should not be treated like this,'' Cochran says.
``Somebody comes forward and they get murdered. That sends a
horrible, horrible message.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same issue, rapper Fat Joe eulogizes his pal, Big
Punisher, the Bronx-born rhymesmith who died earlier this year at
28 of a heart attack. He recalls his friend, whom he brought into
the rap game, but considered his idol a ``beautiful, genuine man.''
Says Joe, ``We can't jump on stage; we can't joke all night; We
can't argue. I even wish we had the arguments back. A part of my
heart is gone forever.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OK, so not even Oasis still believes it's the best and biggest
band in the world. Its latest CD, ``Standing on the Shoulder of
Giants,'' stiffed on the charts, and it's unlikely the group will
ever come out with anything as stunning as 1995's ``(What's the
Story) Morning Glory?'' But you still can't beat 'em when it comes
to an interview, such as Danny Eccleston's amusing sit-down with
lead guitarist-songwriter Noel Gallagher in Q. This is the new
clean-and-sober Gallagher, but he's lost none of his cheeky and
profane candor as he riffs on everything from fellow Brit singer
Jamiroquai, to his inability to drive to the Royal Family, whom he
would flog before booting them out of their various mansions and
palaces. But in true Cain-and-Abel fashion, he saves his sharpest
barbs for his younger brother Liam, Oasis's lead singer. Asked
about his brother's wobbly march toward sobriety, Gallagher
remarks, ``Well, he only drinks twice a week now, which is
Monday-to-Thursday, and Friday-to-Sunday.'' Asked whether he
himself is done with the ``powders'' (that would be cocaine) for
good, Gallagher sounds like a dedicated 12-stepper, although he
quit cold turkey. ``My motto is `Just Say No For The Foreseeable
Future.' I've been lucky; I had the best years of my life doing it
and I'm having a great time not doing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
