<HEADLINE>
PILOTING THE TABLOIDS INTO THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Pecker wants to be known as the man who brought the
supermarket tabloids into the 21st century. The question is _ is
that where we'd like them to be?
</P>
<P>
   Pecker is the former Hachette Filipacchi (Elle, George) magazine
executive who is now the czar of the supermarket checkout stand.
The company he runs, American Media Inc., has a monopoly on the
country's tabloids. Early last year, he and his investors bought
the National Enquirer and the Star. Last fall they snapped up the
Globe (no relation) and its weak step-sister, the National
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   A brief digression: I enjoy the tabloids. For many years, I
entertained the theory that the fact-based tabs _ the Enquirer, the
Globe, and the Star, as opposed to the Calf-Born-With-JFK's-Head
tabs, like the Weekly World News _ were the purest form of
journalism. They are demand-side, as opposed to supply side,
publications. We here at the good Globe occasionally supply you
with stories of largely medicinal value, about, say, the
re-structuring of the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   But not the tabs. They print only stories you (well, I) want to
read: Liz, Larry and the pink pills; Oprah, Stedman and those pesky
pounds; Bryant Gumbel and 70 blondes to be named later. When I read
an Enquirer profile of retired engineer Robert Adler, entitled
``Genius Who Invented the Remote Control Can't Stand TV'' _ what
can I say other than, Why We No Have?
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, the tabs are now under professional
management. In an interview, Pecker listed the changes that have
taken place on his watch: a $15 million television ad camapign; a
re-design; a return to circulation stability. Pecker has merged the
previously warring Globe and Enquirer under one roof, no small
accomplishment, given that less than a year ago the papers were
suing each other for ``tortious interference'' in the Frank
Gifford-Suzen Johnson hotel tryst. This is not a story you read
about in our Globe . . .
</P>
<P>
   Pecker claims to have broomed out some of the tab's more
egregious psychic hawkers (but not, apparently, ``Star Magazine's
Athena Starwoman, World's Most Accurate Psychic Astrologer'') to
create a less septic environment for advertisers. And, indeed, he
has lured national accounts like Warner Lambert, Schering Plough,
and Framingham's Bose Corporation to his pages.
</P>
<P>
   More disturbingly, Pecker has been pressing his editors for
increased accuracy, to ward off lawsuits. But if the tabs aren't
being sued, it's a sure sign they're not doing their job. Still, on
Pecker's brief watch, Celine Dion has already sued the Enquirer for
reporting that she was pregnant, and 10-year-old plaintiff Cody
Gifford, son of the above-mentioned Frank and the below-mentioned
Kathie Lee, is suing the Examiner over the Feb. 8 article, ``Kathie
Lee's Turning Poor Cody Into a Monster.''
</P>
<P>
   Pecker also talks about steering his publications into the
untested waters of . . . legitimacy. ``We don't publish grainy
photos,'' he insisted to me, a claim belied by some Globe
surveillance photos of actor Don Johnson in a San Francisco porn
store. ``We respect privacy laws,'' he mentioned at another point.
What about Kevin Spacey's privacy? Two of Pecker's tabs have been
working overtime _ grainy photos and all _ to ``prove'' that the
Oscar-winning actor is homosexual. ``I think it would be a
disservice not to run these photos for Star readers,'' Pecker says.
``(Spacey) scores very high in the Star's research on
celebrities.''
</P>
<P>
   Research panels and focus groups are just two of the latter-day
media tools that American Media is using to introduce the tabs to
the 21st century. (Pecker also has two new projects about to
launch: a Spanish-language tabloid, Mira, and a new consumer
magazine, Auto World Weekly.) I've seen a fair amount of Britney
Spears's backside lately, along with breathless coverage of the
middle-school boy band 'N Sync, evidence of Pecker's outreach to a
younger generation of tabloid readers.
</P>
<P>
   The next frontier? The web, of course. This summer, Pecker plans
to launch an ``all gossip channel'' for tab fans. ``It's the last
audience ready to convert to the new media,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a way around the problem of weekly publication
hamstringing some of the tabs' greatest opportunities. ``Kathie Lee
Gifford resigned her job on a Tuesday, because she knows the
(Enquirer) closes on Monday night,'' he avers. ``If our Web site
had been up and running, we could have gotten plenty of hits.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Beam's e-mail is beam(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
