<HEADER>
A7685 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HN     04-26 0207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Wednesday, April 26, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Editors &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file the following for Thursday. If
you have questions, please call Chuck Lewis or Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-GAY (Washington) _ Wading into one of the country's most
volatile cultural battlefields, Supreme Court justices struggle
over the question of whether the Boy Scouts can bar homosexuals
from serving as troop leaders. The case involves James Dale, a
Scout leader in New Jersey who was kicked out of the organization
after saying publicly that he is gay. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CAPITAL (Washington) _ For the first time as the
all-but-official Republican presidential nominee, Texas Gov. George
W. Bush visits the nation's capital. He stumped for votes at a
Republican women's forum, talked foreign policy with Russian
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, and appeared at a meeting on Social
Security with Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb. He also is scheduled to
collect a record $18 million at a Republican National Committee
black-tie gala. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
</TEXT>
