<HEADER>
A7686 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-COSTUME-FEUD-BOS &LR;      04-26 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSTUME-FEUD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLECTOR FACES SUITS OVER HOLLYWOOD MEMORIABILIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH RANALLI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How do you solve a problem like Maria's missing brown jumper?
</P>
<P>
   And the famous guitar that Julie Andrews toted across the
Austrian hills with the von Trapp brood?
</P>
<P>
   What about the Maltese Falcon, also allegedly among the missing,
along with the hot pink satin gown Marilyn Monroe wore while
telling the world that diamonds are a girl's best friend?
</P>
<P>
   And what of Betty Grable's famous white bathing suit, the one
that launched a thousand pinups?
</P>
<P>
   How do you solve these problems? In court, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   In a spat of Hollywood-esque proportions, Warner Bros. studios
and entertainer Debbie Reynolds have filed separate lawsuits in a
Massachusetts court, charging that a collector has taken as many as
250 famous movie costumes and props worth a total of $3 million
from their private collections.
</P>
<P>
   The movie studio and Reynolds, herself a longtime collector and
memorabilia preservationist, say they were stunned and horrified to
see their prized possessions among 1,178 items that collector John
Lebold was offering for auction on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Minimum bid for the lot: $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am shocked and astounded by the claims made against me in
this case,'' Lebold said in an affidavit filed in the two Middlesex
(Mass.) Superior Court cases. ``I have spent hundreds and hundreds
of hours maintaining, repairing, and preserving these costumes.
They are mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Lebold's proposed auction on the Internet site Auctionfun.com
was billed as one of the largest and most significant private
collections of Hollywood memorabilia ever offered.
</P>
<P>
   Among the advertised items were the ``The Sound of Music''
jumper and guitar, stone tablets carried by Charlton Heston in
``The Ten Commandments,'' jeans and a T-shirt worn by James Dean in
``Giant,'' and the blue gingham dress worn by Judy Garland in ``The
Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By the description, it sounds very impressive,'' said Giles
Moon, an expert on entertainment memorabilia with Sotheby's in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros. filed the first lawsuit last month alleging that
the James Dean clothing, the Maltese Falcon statue, and 148 other
items in the auction were missing from its inventory. The other
items include a white wool top and a paisley skirt worn by Ingrid
Bergman in ``Casablanca,'' a beige sweater worn by Natalie Wood in
``Rebel Without a Cause,'' and a three-piece green velvet costume
worn by Errol Flynn in ``The Adventures of Don Juan.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds followed with her own lawsuit two weeks ago, saying
that the Julie Andrews jumper and guitar, the Grable bathing suit,
the Marilyn Monroe dress, and other items were missing from her
extensive collection.
</P>
<P>
   The American Textile History Museum, which recently showcased
dozens of costumes from Lebold's collection in Lowell, Mass., has
become a neutral party in the dispute, caring for the items in
question until the court cases are resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Lebold insists he has receipts for all but a few of the items.
The confusion, he alleges, has been caused by the fact that
multiple copies of the costume or prop were often made, so that
when one became ripped or soiled, it could be quickly substituted,
saving expensive studio time.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, there were numerous duplicate guitars used by
Andrews in ``The Sound of Music'' because one scene called for her
to fall into a lake while singing, Lebold said.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists such as Moon say sloppy or nonexistent studio record
keeping makes it even more difficult to determine the provenance of
Hollywood costumes. One lawyer predicted that the case will be ``no
slam dunk'' for either side.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds says in court affidavits that she hired Lebold in the
early 1970s as a curator for her proposed Hollywood Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The two reportedly had a falling out after Lebold was arrested
and charged with larceny in 1980 after allegedly taking more than
600 items from Burbank Studios. The trial ended in a hung jury. The
charges were dismissed after most of the items were returned.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Lebold, of Brewster, Mass., nor Reynolds has been
particularly successful in their attempts to display their
collections.
</P>
<P>
   Lebold's Hollywood Museum on Hollywood Boulevard lasted just two
years, from 1983 to 1985, before closing its doors.
</P>
<P>
   The 67-year-old Reynolds, meanwhile, was forced to sell her
Debbie Reynolds Hotel &AMP; Casino in Las Vegas to the World Wrestling
Federation in 1998 as part of a bankruptcy sale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
