<SLUG> BC-ITALY-POLITICS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ITALIAN CABINET FEATURES MANY FAMILIAR FACES  
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ In an eerie tableau of deja vu Italian politics, a new
Cabinet appointed by the designated prime minister, Giuliano Amato,
was sworn in Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, most of the same people were sworn into office
in the same gold Baroque room in the presidential palace by Italian
President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi. Then, they served Prime Minister
Massimo D'Alema. D'Alema, who in December resigned amid coalition
squabbling but then cobbled together a new government, known in
Italy as D'Alema II, resigned for good this month after his
center-left coalition was defeated in regional elections.
</P>
<P>
   If the Amato government is approved by parliament this week, it
will be Italy's 58th government since World War II, and the latest
example of the Italian art of ``trasformismo'': the process by
which governments, built on fragile and often discordant
coalitions, easily collapse but are quickly rejiggered, often with
the same ministers and policies as before.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Ciampi asked Amato, 61, the treasury minister, to
try to form a government that could be accepted by parliament. The
center-left is badly divided and has a slim majority in both
houses, though it is wafer thin in the lower house.
</P>
<P>
   Silvio Berlusconi, a center-right politician and media tycoon
who was prime minister for less than a year in 1994, belittled the
new Amato government as ``a formation which speaks for itself, put
in place with the sole purpose of keeping the left in power.''
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by the center-right's success in regional elections,
Berlusconi and his allies have been pressing for early national
elections. But Ciampi, reluctant to put Italy through its fourth
parliamentary elections since 1992 a year ahead of schedule,
instead asked Amato to form a government.
</P>
<P>
   Key posts in Amato's new Cabinet remain in the same hands.
Lamberto Dini was sworn in again as foreign minister, and Defense
Minister Sergio Mattarella also retained his job. Vincenzo Visco,
the former finance minister, shifted over to the treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Amato had hoped to whittle down the number of ministers from 25
to 21, but the need to placate the many feuding factions within his
coalition undermined that goal. His Cabinet has 24 members, fusing
the ministries of industry and foreign trade into one.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And in a last-minute illustration of the underlying brittleness
of the coalition, the former environment minister, Edo Ronchi, a
member of the Green party, balked after he was reassigned to the
ministry of European Affairs and the environment was given to
Willer Bordon, a member of the small Democrats Party. Eager to keep
a precarious political balance, Amato said he would replace Ronchi
with a politician from the Green Party.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few new faces. Ottaviano Del Turco, a former union
leader and head of the anti-mafia committee in parliament, was made
finance minister. The health ministry was assigned to Umberto
Veronesi, Italy's best-known cancer specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Amato, a socialist, earned the nickname ``doctor subtle'' for
his deft tenure as prime minister in 1992, a tumultuous time when
corruption scandals engulfed and eventually caused the collapse of
the Christian Democrats and their Socialist allies.
</P>
<P>
   He spent the Easter holidays patching his new Cabinet together.
``It wasn't easy,'' Amato told reporters. ``But at the end, we did
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
