<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7698 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     04-26 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS HAVE MANY CHOICES FOR PRESIDENT  
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the ``mainstream'' media would have us believe that the
presidential campaign is down to a two-man race, the field, in
reality, is crowded with candidates, some of whom may actually be
deserving of your vote.
</P>
<P>
   (Notice I said your vote, not mine.)
</P>
<P>
   You can vote for candidates from such ``third'' parties as the
American Party, Communist Party, Green Party, Reform Party or
Libertarian Party, but the true originals are the Independents.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a brief run-down of some of the more intriguing
Independent candidates out there, assembled with the help of
Politics1.com.:
</P>
<P>
   A.J. ``Victor'' Albritton (Mississippi): The nominee of the
``American Republican Party,'' an unknown organization of which he
appears to be the only member. Pledges a ``new model Star Spangled
Banner'' and relocation of the federal capital.
</P>
<P>
   Paris C.L. Alvarez (Florida): Favors mandatory ``castration of
all international drug traffickers who are convicted in a court of
law'' and government distribution of ``marijuana to all retired
military personnel over the age of 35 if they so desire to smoke
(because) it will quilt all the world harmoniously.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez does not reveal whether he is retired military
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   David Broida (Maryland): Twenty policy statements include:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I am as honest as a natural-born citizen of the United
States can be.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I have never served jail time and I am not a crook, yet.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I would not end racism, but I might try to ban the Indy
500.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I have lived in the Washington, D.C., area most of my life
but I have no idea what is going on at the federal level.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Caruba (New Jersey): Head of the so-called ``Boring
Institute'' says even he cannot be as boring as Al Gore, Bill
Bradley and Steve Forbes. Caruba says he is prepared to ``campaign
vigorously so long as it doesn't involve leaving home too much''
and says his main reason for seeking the office of president is
``the perks.''
</P>
<P>
   Clifford R. Catton (New York): Reason for running: ``U.S. postal
employees have been stealing my mail since 1981.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Gottier (California): Sixty-four-year-old
self-described religious Agnostic who sums up his qualifications
with the single sentence: ``I have lived long.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but probably not long enough to get elected.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Grimes (Delaware): Grimes (no relation, I sincerely hope),
bills himself as the ``Leader and Director of the United Fascist
Union'' which advocates a New World Order based on a ``military
dictatorship form of government over the Earth.'' Grimes predicts
that ``the United States will be reduced from its present size to a
small, triangular-shaped land mass through the loss of many of its
coastal states.''
</P>
<P>
   Can we hope that one of those states is Delaware?
</P>
<P>
   Clay O. Hill (Florida): Hill collected 32 votes as a write-in
candidate for Congress in 1998 and is now running for president as
the Populist-Democratic-Viking candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Just what we need in the White House: Another guy wearing horns.
</P>
<P>
   Martin J. McNally (Illinois): Possibly the most exciting
independent candidate currently serving a federal prison sentence,
McNally claims to represent the unknown ``National Christian''
party and lists his mailing address as ``U.S. Penitentiary, Marion,
Illinois.'' Perhaps McNally is running so he can pardon himself
after he is elected. It will be an uphill battle, however. Although
McNally can run for office, he can't vote, not even for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Andisheh ``Andy'' Nouraee (Georgia): The only known candidate to
recommend porno books on his Web site, Andy's site also gave
shopping tips for would-be Y2K looters. (``Steel garbage cans
aren't just useful for breaking storefront windows; you can also
use them to carry away looted goods.'') Campaign slogans include:
``Putting the `racy' back in democracy'' and ``Putting the `vice'
back in service.''
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be fun to see Andy and Pat Robertson in a family
values debate?
</P>
<P>
   David E. Wyatt (Florida): The darling of artists and poets
everywhere who insist on wearing sunglasses whenever they are
photographed. Don't look for any references to Lincoln, Reagan or
FDR in this former bill collector's speeches; Wyatt says ``nothing
in the world has had a greater influence on my mind'' than the rock
band Pink Floyd's movie and album, `The Wall.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by his Web site, it's a pretty safe bet that he's in
favor of government distribution of marijuana, whether you're
retired military personnel over the age of 35 or not.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
