   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-ZIMBABWE _ GWERU, Zimbabwe _ Farming is anything but the
``simple life'' here in Zimbabwe. (Roughton, Cox News Service) WITH
PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DEBATE _ MEXICO CITY _ The reaction to the very heated
presidential debate Tuesday night. It was only the second in
Mexico's history, and with roughly two months before the July 2
election, was a preview of how tough the increasingly tight contest
will likely be. Developing. (Ferriss, Cox News Service) Expected to
move by 4 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-ATL _ ATLANTA _Local Vietnamese look back at the end of
the Vietnam War 25 years ago and their lives since then.(Melvin,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DATELINE-CHINA _ TAIPEI _ It was hard to say who had annoyed
Annette Lu more: her critics in mainland China or the ``male
chauvinists'' of Taiwan. Come to think of it, she wasn't too happy
with former U.S. President Jimmy Carter, either. The new vice
president of Taiwan talks about the future of her country. Pegged
to conference at the Southern Center for International Studies in
Atlanta this week on that very subject. (Graham, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SRC - t's a different time for the Southern Regional Council,
the long-time think tank for the Civil Rights Movement. Back in the
1960s, the SRC and other civil rights groups were helped by
violent, white Southern males _ like infamous Birmingham police
chief Bull Connor, who turned dogs on black protesters _ who helped
illustrate the plight of minorities. As the SRC celebrates its 80th
anniversary Thursday in Atlanta, president Charles Johnson reflects
on where the group is going and where it's been. (Maunel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   STNMT-REBELFLAG _ Lest ye forget, the rebel flag controversy is
not going away. Stone Mountain Mayor Chuck Burris, first black
mayor of the city long associated with the Confederacy, ordered
down a flagpole that the Sons of Confederate Veterans put up to fly
the Rebel flag for Confederate Memorial Day on Wednesday. Now that
group says it will sue. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LIFE IN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   LIFE IN AMERICA 0427: Mattie Roundtree, 100, opens doors to the
past
</P>
<P>
   Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. Photo and a sig/locator map are
available.
</P>
<P>
   RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ Mattie Taylor Roundtree has a way of
opening doors for people, opening doors and pointing to what's on
the other side, and pushing people on through and out into the
world. That's what Mattie Roundtree has done in her 100 years. Open
doors. She knows something about doors slamming shut, too. Her
front door is good, solid old cypress, planed smooth and hung
straight in 1924 by her carpenter husband, Lloyd. The big
hurricanes of 1926 and 1928 didn't budge the door, or the frame
house Lloyd built on land he bought for $60, paying 25 cents a
week. But the land was low, wet, and Lloyd found a better location
nearby, high on an ancient dune up on 32nd Street in Riviera Beach.
``The men, they rolled that house up from the wet land. They rolled
it right up on tree trunks,'' says Mattie. ``Lloyd, he took care of
me. Me, I took care of Lloyd, and my family. But first was the
Lord. He came first. Lloyd understood.'' (Reid, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-GRAHAM _ WASHINGTON _ Finally, it seemed that Democrat Bob
Graham _ Florida's senior senator _ was breaking through to the
national political stage. Remembered as the most popular governor
in recent Florida history, he was being mentioned as on the short
list of vice presidential running mates for Al Gore _ hopefully
able to deliver a key electoral state. Then came Elian Gonzalez,
and a high-profile and emotional split with a president he has been
very close to for decades. Developing.
</P>
<P>
   (Lipman, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-POLITICS WASHINGTON _ With Republican congressional
leaders scheduling hearings into the pre-dawn raid to seize Elian
Gonzalez from the home of his Miami relatives, political obsrevers
say the GOP once again flirts with painting itself as the party of
extremists. But does it really have a choice? The Cuban exile lobby
has been one of the most loyal Republican voting blocs for decades
_ despite the fact that Clinton nearly split the vote in 1996. Yet,
there are even signs with GOP ranks that they don't want to go down
this road. Developing.
</P>
<P>
   (Shepard, Cox News Service) Moving by 7 p.m. EST in both
International/Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   COSMOS _ WASHINGTON _ Measurements of minute temperature
variations from when the universe was only a few hundred thousand
years old have convinced scientist that it is ``flat,'' not
``curved,'' as some cosmologists had speculated. Still echoing in
the cosmic background is the ``noise'' of the Big Bang, when space
expanded at speeds faster than the speed of light, and when
analyzed on a supercomputer, these echoes suggest that a flat
universe will continue to expand forever. (Nesmith, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-CHIEFS WASHINGTON _ New ways of improving teacher quality
are outlined and urged Wednesday by 8 state education chiefs in the
Education Leaders Council, a rival to the long-dominant Council of
Chief State School Officers. From states that educate 30 percent of
the nation's public school kids, the 8 breakaway school chiefs
include those in the Cox states of Colorado, Georgia, Florida and
Texas. (Mollison, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DRUGS _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Tuesday is
pressing Congress to extend prescription drug coverage to all who
get Medicare. The White House is releasing a private study whowing
that prices for prescription drugs commonly used by older Americans
rose faster than inflation last year. Congress is pressing ahead
with its own plan, which excludes wealthier Medicare recipients.
(Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
