A7713 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-BEERNUT-TEX     04-26 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEERNUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODPECKER ENGLISH CIDER GOES WELL WITH BRATWURST, RIBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Woodpecker English Cider certainly isn't beer, and the Beer Nut
hasn't had much experience with cider, but it might be an
interesting alternative for beer drinkers to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Cider is apple juice that has been fermented, which sounds like
wine to me. The trouble here in the office, however, is that our
hoity-toity wine writer won't drink anything that didn't start out
as grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Also, since cider comes in a beer bottle and looks like beer,
the powers that be here in the office made me try Woodpecker.
</P>
<P>
   The label says the ingredients are fermented apple juice or
apple juice concentrate. Frankly I don't like this ``or'' business.
I believe they and we should know exactly what it is, but I
digress.
</P>
<P>
   Woodpecker also contains sugar, coloring, light carbonation and
sulfites, which I for one, can't seem get enough of.
</P>
<P>
   The taste is tart and clean with just the tiniest bit of fizz.
It is reminiscent of the apple wine that one can acquire at the
apple bars near the train station in Frankfurt, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   It was there, while in the employ of our government, that I was
compelled to rub elbows with the locals and eat platters of smoked
pork chops and sauerkraut washed down with apple wine made on site.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodpecker's color is pale, even lighter than that that of
most supermarket apple juice, but it doesn't have the intense apple
taste or sweetness one finds in apple juice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that it's not real apple-ly,'' said The Rev _ a
full-time neighbor, part-time friend and self-frocked minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing I like here is this does not give you beer
mouth,'' he said. ``You could come in from a night of drinking and
just tell your wife you'd been eating apple pie all night.'' (It's
an observation that means little right now, since both of us are
between ex-wives, but each of us made mental notes to file this
idea away.)
</P>
<P>
   Woodpecker is made in Springfield, Vt., using an English recipe
licensed by H.P. Bulmer of Hereford, England. Bulmer is the world's
largest cider maker. Stateside, the company also markets Woodchuck
Draft Cider and Strongbow, which is slightly more tart than
Woodpecker.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev gives Woodpecker a 3 on the international 0-5 scale. He
said he puts it slightly ahead of Schlitz and Schaeffer, but just
this side of Miller Genuine Draft.
</P>
<P>
   I give it a 3.5. I'm thinking it might be right on target this
summer to wash down grilled bratwurst and sweet barbecued ribs. A
six-pack sells for $6.99.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
