<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7716 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-26 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A `NIT-WIT' TAKES ON THE G-MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: APBNews.com is CQ)  
 &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It was spy vs. spy, gossip-monger vs.
gossip-monger, one man's ``reliable sources'' vs. another's. It was
a match made in hearsay heaven.
</P>
<P>
   And Herb Caen, the legendary San Francisco newspaper columnist,
bested J. Edgar Hoover.
</P>
<P>
   Hoover's G-men called Caen a ``nit-wit columnist,'' a ``gossip
monger,'' a ``keyhole journalist,'' and an ``ultra-liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   But Caen drove Hoover crazy.
</P>
<P>
   You can almost hear Hoover's panties twisting into a knot when
he teletyped the FBI office in San Francisco: ``Obviously this
matter must be handled with the utmost discretion and no contact is
to be made with Caen until (blacked out). Expedite, Hoover.''
</P>
<P>
   What set him off? Caen ran an item in the Oct. 8, 1956, edition
of the San Francisco Examiner about John Dillinger's watch. He said
the FBI museum had a fake substituted by one of the agents who shot
the bank robber.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents were assigned as Caen fact-checkers, going so far as
to trace serial numbers of Hamilton watches, even though there was
no watch at all in their museum.
</P>
<P>
   After much ado, an FBI agent finally told Caen his item was
wrong. In the agent's report, you can almost hear the great
columnist shrug.
</P>
<P>
   But the item that really must have gotten under Hoover's skin
was one that ran the previous August. Caen wrote that Hoover was at
the Del Mar races, ``on a diet, sober-faced, reading a Racing
Form.''
</P>
<P>
   Caen quotes an anonymous Texan as saying, ``Edgar is no fun
anymore. So serious. Why, he used to come over to our house every
night and sing `Pistol Packin' Mama.'''
</P>
<P>
   An agent put on the trail of that item told Hoover that Caen
``thrives on secondhand information written to suit his own
personal distorted sense of humor. He thinks he is a master of wit
and very funny. In fact, he is a no-good, loudmouthed individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Yep, that's the Caen we knew. And J. Edgar Hoover was a great
humanitarian.
</P>
<P>
   Caen's FBI files, recently posted by APBNews.com, were compiled
from May 1941 to May 1967. They start with an inquiry into a Caen
item about a woman who supposedly ran through a San Francisco store
shouting ``Heil Hitler.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoover wanted to know more about the woman. San Francisco-based
agent N.J.L. Pieper replied that he was unable to substantiate
anything in the story. ``Herb Caen is a nit-wit columnist,'' Pieper
wrote. ``Most of his stuff has no basis in fact, and is purely
rumor. This is a typical example.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 20, 1946, Caen reported that Gov. Earl Warren was a
shoo-in as next president, and that Warren would appoint a certain
``Mr. P'' to replace Hoover as FBI director.
</P>
<P>
   Caen got Hoover's attention with that one. An agent was assigned
to investigate, and told Hoover that ``Mr. P'' was retired San
Francisco agent Pieper, ``who, as you know, is highly regarded by
Gov. Warren.''
</P>
<P>
   The agent wrote that Caen was unreliable and possibly a
communist, but went on to recommend that ``the Bureau consider
inviting Gov. Warren to address a graduating class of the National
Academy.''
</P>
<P>
   Caen may be a nit-wit, but why take chances? Hoover should buddy
up to Earl Warren anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The last item in Caen's FBI files, dated May 15, 1967, again
concerns an item on Hoover's possible firing. This time Caen
floated the rumor that then-Chief Tom Cahill of the San Francisco
police would be the new FBI director, with Caen adding, ``but
that's too good to be true.''
</P>
<P>
   Caen and Hoover both used anonymous sources for information, and
both used that information to maintain their power. Both often were
misinformed. But Caen used his sources coyly, while Hoover seemed a
paranoid prisoner of his sources.
</P>
<P>
   Hoover would send San Francisco agents scurrying upon receipt of
Caen columns sent by informants with names like ``Jane Doe'' who
sniffed pro-communist sympathies between the dots.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI tracked such subversive activities as Caen serving as
master of ceremonies for Russian War Relief and being friends with
labor leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Caen's file also contains this gem: ``A confidential informant
of known reliability reported in July, 1943, that he received a
report from a reliable source that Herb Caen was a member of the
Communist Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Caen's own informants were dubious, but never as
dubious as that. And the FBI didn't have moles like Caen's.
</P>
<P>
   In March of 1963, Caen ran an item about a high official of the
FBI coming to San Francisco and throwing the local office into a
tizzy by inspecting their shoeshines. ``It's a reign of terror,''
Caen quoted an unnamed agent as saying.
</P>
<P>
   An FBI memo to Hoover called Caen a ``gossip monger,'' but
confirms that Caen's gossip was accurate.
</P>
<P>
   In his next column, Caen wrote of FBI agents being suspended
(``by their thumbs'') and tattling on each other. ``Frevvin's
sakes,'' Caen wrote. ``They turn each OTHER in.''
</P>
<P>
   Columnists apparently turn each other in, too. According to the
files, in June 1949 an anonymous anti-Caen letter was forwarded to
the FBI by Walter Winchell.
</P>
<P>
   It's a brutal world, and was particularly so during J. Edgar
Hoover's reign. But Caen was just the nit-wit columnist to take on
Hoover, and he didn't even stoop to material about cross-dressing _
with the possible exception of that pistol packin' mama item.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
