<P>
   TAUBMAN-AUCTION (New York) _ A. Alfred Taubman, the shopping
mall tycoon, made a second career out of rescuing companies in
distress _ including the Sotheby's auction house 17 years ago. But
this tale of a white knight does not have a happy ending, as
Taubman leaves Sotheby's board under a cloud. Federal prosecutors
investigating possible price-fixing at Sotheby's and its chief
rival, Christie's, are being told that it was Taubman, now 75, and
the former chairman of Christie's who devised a scheme to fix
commissions in the early 1990s. Taubman has denied any wrongdoing.
Yet what is clear is that Taubman came under financial pressures
during that time as real estate slumped, store sales slowed and the
art market went into a recession. By Leslie Eaton.
</P>
