<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7730 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-THEATER-REVIEW-NAZIS-     04-26 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-REVIEW-NAZIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PLAY GENERATES NUCLEAR FRISSON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT HURWITT  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nobody knows what was said that night in the fall of
1941 when Werner Heisenberg, Germany's leading nuclear physicist,
traveled to Nazi-occupied Denmark to meet with his old mentor Niels
Bohr. Nobody knows by the end of ``Copenhagen,'' Michael Frayn's
scintillating new play at Broadway's Royale Theatre, but the
uncertainty commands a remarkable dramatic intensity.
</P>
<P>
   What makes it all the more remarkable, as many commentators have
noted ever since ``Copenhagen'' became a surprise popular hit in
London two years ago, is that much of the dialogue is about
physics. For two hours and 20 minutes, two men and a woman rattle
off the names of significant figures in 20th century physics and
engage in heady discussions of fission, quantum mechanics, wave
function and the uncertainty and complementarity principles.
</P>
<P>
   But the stakes are incomparably high. As Margrethe Bohr, the
third person present, observes in what is actually almost an
understatement: ``From those two heads the future will emerge.
Which cities will be destroyed, and which will survive. Who will
die, who will live. Which world will go down to obliteration and
which will triumph.''
</P>
<P>
   Frayn's triumph lies not only in making complex principles and
conundrums of physics unusually clear, but also in putting them in
their social and political context: World War II and the race
between Germany and America to develop the atomic bomb. Nor does he
stop at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Copenhagen'' immerses us in the exhilaration of the '20s, when
Bohr and his associates redefined our fundamental notions of the
physical world. He confronts us with the horror of the moment when
they realized that their theories might have a military application
(``My love, no one is going to develop a weapon based on nuclear
fission,'' Bohr reassures his wife just before the truth sinks in).
And he raises disturbing questions about the moral implications of
both failure and success.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Blakemore, who brought those ideas to life in the play's
Royal National Theatre premiere, has recreated that triumph with
some of the same design team and a new American cast. Philip Bosco,
Blair Brown and Michael Cumpsty inhabit the roles and embody the
ideas with compellingly natural immediacy.
</P>
<P>
   The story is both simple and provocatively complex. On one
level, it's an examination of just what took place _ or might've
taken place _ when Heisenberg visited Bohr in 1941. But it's an
examination conducted by the ghosts of the principals, ghosts that
slip quickly from one time frame to another, recreating the crucial
visit, the happier times in the '20s, the bitter recriminations
after the war.
</P>
<P>
   Heisenberg, for those with only a smattering of physics, was the
1932 Nobel Prize winner most famous, among many notable
contributions, for developing the uncertainty principle: Broadly
applied, the idea that knowledge of one truth about a particle
(location, say) negates knowledge of any other (velocity) _
``because we can't observe it without introducing some new element
into the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1941, Heisenberg had become head of the German atomic program
and, apparently, had realized at least some of the potential for
building an atomic bomb. Niels Bohr, generally considered second
only to Einstein in his impact on modern physics, was still in
occupied Denmark. Months later he would escape, along with most of
Denmark's Jews, due to a remarkable collaboration of Danes and some
Germans. He made his way to America and the Manhattan Project.
</P>
<P>
   Margrethe Bohr is the lay person of the trio, though as wife of
one Nobelist (who typed every draft of his papers) and mother of
another, she's more than capable of holding her own. As played by
Brown, she's the ever-alert conscience and sometime judge-and-jury
of the trio, but very much a partisan as well. She's fiercely
protective of her husband and more than a little suspicious of
Heisenberg's motives throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Bosco creates a beautifully rounded portrait of the
elder-statesman scientist. Cautiously fearful about the impending
visit, his eyes light up with intellectual excitement when he
contemplates a new idea. Cumpsty, whose Heisenberg is the engine
that drives the piece, is tense, combative and fiercely engaged. He
wrestles with a concept with riveting intellectual energy. His
personal accounts of a shattered Germany after each World War are
vivid and affecting.
</P>
<P>
   Frayn, who proved himself a master of the complexities of farce
with the popular ``Noises Off,'' is equally adept at juggling time
frames, states of reality and difficult concepts this time out. He
creates a dazzling fugue of uncertainty, playing on the
unreliability of personal memory and juxtaposing the historical,
social, metaphysical and political ramifications of the ideas.
</P>
<P>
   There's the revelation that modern physics has reversed the
effect of a millennium of science by placing humans once again at
the center of the universe _ since all we can know of it is a
matter of perception, and the act of perception affects what it
perceives. There's the troubling moral paradox that Heisenberg,
working for Hitler, never killed anyone, while the good Bohr
contributed directly to the annihilation of Nagasaki.
</P>
<P>
   The unresolved mystery to which the characters keep returning,
is the ever more provocative question of what caused Heisenberg to
go to Denmark. Did he mean to warn Bohr about the Nazi atomic
program? To seek assurances that neither side would develop a
nuclear bomb? Or information about how far the Allied program had
progressed?
</P>
<P>
   Hanging over the end is the key issue of why Heisenberg,
atypically, never asked himself the question that might've led his
team to the bomb _ the simple formula for the necessary critical
mass. The moment of alternative reality _ when Bosco quietly
suggests it and Cumpsty seizes the idea with intellectual fervor _
is staged with harrowing simplicity by Blakemore. It lingers in the
mind with the awful indelibility of a mushroom cloud.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Michael Frayn's ``Copenhagen`` plays at the Royale Theatre, 242
W. 45th St., New York, N.Y., 800-432-7250, 212-239-6200 or
www.copenhagenbroadway.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
