<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, April 27:
</P>
<P>
   JUNKYARD ( Baxter, Ga.) _ ``This probably won't be too thrilling
to you, a wrecking yard like this,'' Franklin Ray said, stepping
out of his jumbled homemade house and leading the way through piles
of tires and aluminum cans, decades of rusting cars and tractors,
entwined in wisteria and wild grapevines, sunk to their hubcaps in
years of pine needles and magnolia leaves. ``Daddy, what are you
going to do with this boat?'' Janisse Ray, a poet and nature
writer, asked, narrowing her dark eyes at a cabin cruiser blocking
her path. ``Who knows?'' he said, walking past a tricycle perched
on a 1958 Chevrolet Biscayne. Ms. Ray, 37, was born in this
junkyard. In her first book, ``Ecology of a Cracker Childhood,''
part memoir, part clarion call to save the longleaf pine, published
in December by Milkweed Editions, she casts a loving but
unflinching eye on growing up poor and fundamentalist in southeast
Georgia, with mental illness snaking through her clan like a dark
tributary of the Altamaha River. Her daddy ran the junkyard (he
still does), and his quicksilver mind could just as easily
resurrect a dead machine as answer the voice of God. By Ann Raver.
</P>
<P>
   DECORATOR-SHOWCASE (New York) _ You would become a white wine
drinker pretty quickly if you lived in the Kips Bay Boys and Girls
Club Decorator Showhouse, as I did for three days last weekend. Or
straight vodka. You'd think twice about chocolate ice cream. The
28th annual showhouse, open through May 21, is packed to its
sixth-story rafters with white lampskin and goatskin rugs, pale
linen walls, cream-colored microfiber, ivory silk and white-peach
velvet. Red burgundy and bordeaux drinkers: check your weapons at
the door. Lotus-eaters, step right in. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki.
</P>
<P>
   MOMA-SCULPTURE (New York) _ ``They were expecting some kind of
experimental house like the one I built in Kobe,'' said the
architect Shigeru Ban last Monday, referring to the cardboard `log'
houses he designed, along with a paper church, for victims of the
earthquake in 1995. But Ban proposed something unexpected: a
soaring lattice arch made of cardboard tubes, which covers about a
third of the Sculpture Garden of the Museum of Modern Art. Weighing
six tons and spanning 87 feet, it has a lightness of being, a
kinetic energy. And even though it is solidly bolted in place, it
looks like a giant box kite about to snap its string and take off
into the sky. By Ann Raver.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst
