<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKINAWA-BODIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. NAVY TO INVESTIGATE DEATHS OF 3 WORLD WAR II MARINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
(EDS: This article does not carry a byline) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The U.S. Navy is investigating the deaths of three
American marines whose remains were concealed in a cave on Okinawa
from the end of World War II until 1998, according to a Marine
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on a tip in 1998, the police in the town of Naha
discovered the remains of the marines, who had been missing since
July, 1945, shortly before the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   After the Navy identified the bones as those of Pvts. James D.
Robinson, John M. Smith and Isaac Stokes of the 37th Marine
Company, they were returned to family members in the United States
this month.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese news media reported Wednesday that Naha residents
and Japanese soldiers had killed the U.S. servicemen in retaliation
for the rape of Okinawan women. The news reports quoted local
residents who said that the bodies had been dumped in the cave and
that villagers had made a pact never to speak of the incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1527EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
