<SLUG> BC-U.N.-IRAQ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQ DENIES ENTRY TO RUSSIAN U.N. INVESTIGATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A former Russian ambassador to the United
Nations and the United States has been rebuffed by the Iraqis as he
tried to reopen an investigation into Kuwaiti prisoners still
missing after the 1990 Iraqi invasion and occupation of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   The former ambassador, Yuli Vorontsov, who Secretary-General
Kofi Annan appointed in February as a special coordinator for
unanswered questions about missing Iraqis and citizens of other
nations, as well as Kuwaiti property, reported to the Security
Council Wednesday morning that he was still seeking a meeting with
the Iraqis. The envoy met recently with officials of Kuwait, the
Organization of the Islamic Conference and the Arab League.
</P>
<P>
   About 600 people are still missing after falling into Iraqi
custody. Ambassador James Cunningham, the deputy U.S.
representative, told the council that Iraq, which is considered
close to the Russians, had an obligation to release prisoners or
return the remains of those who had died. ``Moreover, it is the
decent, humanitarian thing to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Saddam Hussein has also refused entry to the
Dutch ambassador at the United Nations, Peter van Walsum, who is
the chairman of the council's Iraqi sanctions committee. He has
tried for several months to visit Iraq to gauge the level of
civilian suffering because of sanctions imposed in 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
