<SLUG> BC-E-MAIL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COME HEAVEN OR ... ONE FINAL E-MAIL
</HEADLINE>
 TO THE DEAD-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dead men tell no tales _ unless, of course, they have e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   At FinalThoughts.com, the dearly departed can send messages from
the Great Beyond to anyone with an electronic address. Web site
members can pen letters _ to friends, relatives, enemies, whomever
_ that are mailed upon their death.
</P>
<P>
   Never told Uncle Harry how much those fishing trips meant? Ship
him a posthumous thanks. Still not speaking to the ex-best friend
who can't keep a secret? Patch things up postmortem.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for FinalThoughts.com (www.finalthoughts.com) came to
30-year-old Todd Michael Krim during a particularly turbulent
flight from Los Angeles to London. As the plane tossed, Krim got to
thinking about ``what I would have left unsaid and undone'' in the
event of his demise.
</P>
<P>
   FinalThoughts.com launched in September and expanded in
February. Krim says about 10,000 people have signed up for the free
services the site provides: estate planning, funeral planning,
end-of-life-care, spirituality and genealogy. Members come from 50
countries and average a surprisingly spry 39 years of age.
</P>
<P>
   Although estate planning is the site's most popular feature, the
buzz has focused on e-mails from the hereafter. (In reality,
members choose one or more ``guardian angels,'' who send the
members' messages postmortem.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have told me that they've written apology letters
to friends and family members who they no longer talk to,'' Krim
says. ``It's pretty powerful. Think of how many people have lost
touch with people, or for whatever reasons there are just
irreconcilable differences. It's a way of bringing closure, I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   FinalThoughts.com remains relatively untested: No member,
thankfully, has expired. But peace of mind counts for everything in
a business like Krim's. Clients will one day be departed, but at
least they won't be deleted.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1534EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
