<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET A DOWNLOAD OF THIS: E-BOOKS COULD BE THE NEXT WAVE IN
PUBLISHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The movies couldn't do it. Radio couldn't do it. Even television
couldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   With each great leap forward in communications, pundits have
prophesied the death of the lowly, old-fashioned paper book. Now
it's the Internet's turn, as growing numbers of technophiles claim
that Internet ``e-publishing'' will deliver the death blow to
paperbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, touting its e-book reading software, predicts that
e-book sales will overtake paper by 2009. Bill Gates and other
high-tech aficionados say digital books will be significantly
cheaper than printed titles, because there won't be costs related
to printing, binding and shipping. And, they say, as newly designed
reading devices (some of which will be hitting stores by Christmas)
replace eyestrain with ease, consumers will flock to them.
</P>
<P>
   E-enthusiasts point to the success of Stephen King's ``Riding
the Bullet,'' a 67-page novella published in mid-March as an
``electronic-only'' book. When the story became available,
Amazon.com averaged one consumer download per second for it. Within
three days of its release, more than 500,000 King fans either paid
$2.50 for the story or took advantage of downloads offered free by
some Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   That phenomenal commercial performance led to a ``Time''
magazine cover story and a lot of I-told-you-so's from e-book
proselytizers. Now, they say, all the revolution needs for ultimate
success is some clever design work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the (current) e-book devices are not ready for prime
time, but that is changing,'' says Jeff Bezos, chief executive
officer of Amazon.com. ``It's not a matter of whether (they'll
penetrate the market), it's a question of when.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite the news media hype and ambitious publishing plans,
there are holes in this scenario. For one, King _ one of a few true
name-brand authors _ is a phenomenon unto himself. No matter what
format he uses, people will buy his work. (Lost in all the
excitement of ``Riding the Bullet's'' success is the very real
possibility that if the novella had been offered in print as well
as online, the unprecedented tide of electronic sales would have
been reduced to a trickle.)
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Applebaum, senior vice president of Random House, says
``Riding the Bullet'' is probably an aberration, at least in
today's book market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe right now one of the most popular full-length
e-books is Peter Abraham's `Crying Wolf,' and that has maybe
downloaded 1,000 copies,'' Applebaum says. ``We are not
unenthusiastic about e-books, but we're not in the front lines of
those saying they will replace bound books in a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, what's good for publishers _ and consumers _ isn't
necessarily good for writers. Author royalties are based on the
retail price. On a $20 book, a 15 percent royalty _ the typical
percentage _ earns the writer $3. If the e-book version has a
drastically reduced price, as its proponents claim it will, authors
lose out. (Royalties on a $2 sale, for example, are 30 cents).
</P>
<P>
   And because so few authors sell books by the crate as King does,
``They're not going to go along with that,'' predicts Phyllis
Grann, president of Penguin Putnam.
</P>
<P>
   Which means that, unless authors and publishers work out a new
pay structure (or e-books remain as expensive as print),
technophiles will mostly be reading test patterns or a lot of
college fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, say bibliophiles who are unwilling to part with their
book jackets and bindings, there is another way.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry watchers say that not only will e-books at best be
a niche product, but recent advances in printing technology in this
digital age will usher in a new golden era of old-school
publishing. The emerging process is called ``print on demand,''
which Random House's Applebaum says ``is getting less attention
(than e-books) but is very interesting.'' The process, in short, is
making it faster, cheaper and easier to print books than ever
before.
</P>
<P>
   Print on demand makes use of high-speed laser printers and
cutting-edge publishing software that eliminates many of the most
expensive, time-consuming steps in the printing process.
Previously, it was far too expensive for a printing company to
produce just 10, 50 or 100 copies of a book, but the new process
can produce limited runs inexpensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big offset press that everybody uses for traditional
printing can't print profitably under about 2,000 copies,'' says
Paul Hilts, technology editor for Publishers Weekly. ``Print on
demand is a wonderful boon because you can profitably print tiny
orders of one book _ 10 books, less than a cartonload.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Hilts, retail chains such as Barnes &AMP; Noble and
Borders Books and Music are experimenting with placing
print-on-demand stations in their stores: If the book you want
isn't on the shelf, the store would be able to print and bind it
for you in about five minutes. But print on demand won't just make
it easier to pick up a new paperback copy of an out-of-stock
bestseller. Hilts thinks it will lead to an explosion of
small-press publishing companies.
</P>
<P>
   Don DeHart, president of DeHart's Printing Services in Santa
Clara, Calif., which offers print on demand, says he has seen the
explosion begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get requests for it daily,'' he says. ``I've had half a
dozen requests today from people who are interested in having us
print anywhere from 25 copies of a book to several hundred.''
</P>
<P>
   DarkTales Publishing, founded last year by three horror fans,
has jumped on the print-on-demand bandwagon, printing eight novels
and short-story anthologies.
</P>
<P>
   Although DarkTales' most popular book has sold only about 1,000
copies, the low cost of on-demand printing has kept the company in
the black.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is going to spark a renaissance in literature,''
says Keith Herber of Mt. Prospect, Ill., one of DarkTales'
founders. ``You no longer have to kowtow to the publishers and
write something they want to sell. If you've got a book you want to
publish, you can do it yourself for $250.''
</P>
<P>
   None of which, to be sure, is likely to hold off the rise of
e-books, especially for kids already more comfortable with laptops
and Palm Pilots than printed books. But it does suggest that
Gutenberg's adherents won't go without a fight.  &QL; 
Where the e-books are
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most popular places to download e-books on personal
computers include:
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com
</P>
<P>
   Barnesandnoble.com
</P>
<P>
   Netlibrary.com
</P>
<P>
   ebookcentral.com
</P>
<P>
   ebookshoppe.com
</P>
<P>
   electronicbookseller.com
</P>
<P>
   bb.com
</P>
<P>
   rocket-ebook.com
</P>
<P>
   softbook.com
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
