<SLUG> BC-E-HIJACKING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBERHIJACKERS STEAL CELEBRITY NAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's in a name? Until a few months ago, the last thing you
would have found on www.brianwilson.com was Brian Wilson. At the
time, the site consisted of a save-the-Earth campaign manned by an
environmentalist who was using the name of the famous Beach
Boy-turned-recluse to lure Web surfers.
</P>
<P>
   But Wilson is not the only victim of cybersquatting or what
others popularly call cyber-hijacking.
</P>
<P>
   Try punching in brucespringsteen.com. A Broooooce fan site? A
list of tour dates? Set lists from every show?
</P>
<P>
   Nope. Brucespringsteen.com is a celebrity site. The site's
current ``celebrity of the week'' isn't even The Boss. It's Brad.
As in Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   And one site named for Paul McCartney leads to pornographic
material.
</P>
<P>
   No celebrities, apparently, are immune from this latest trend.
From musicians to movie stars to politicians, people with famous
names are getting hijacked.
</P>
<P>
   Matter of fact, unless you protect your name by registering it
with a dot-com directory such as networksolutions.com, it's open
season on (insert your name here).
</P>
<P>
   This is how it works: Cybersquatters pay as little as $70 to
purchase an unclaimed Internet domain name through one of the many
dot-com companies that offer the service. Once they have dibs on
the name, they create a site using that name as the address _
brianwilson.com, for instance. You do a search for Brian Wilson.
Brianwilson.com shows up. You click on it.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing this is not what you wanted, you are now faced with
two choices: stay or go. Cybersquatters, of course, are hoping
you'll stay and pay attention to whatever it is they're touting.
</P>
<P>
   Confusion and frustration are the obvious problems associated
with cybersquatting. The bigger problem: Some cybersquatters have
demanded money from famous people whose names have been
cyber-jacked to relinquish the claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's legalized thievery,'' says Jeff Liles, creative director
for Nvision, a division of Vectrix, a Dallas-based Internet company
that, among other things, creates Web sites. ``To take someone
else's name and sell it back to them, that's almost extortion.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of cybersquatting cases recently involved high-profile
artists, politicians and organizations, from the Worldwide
Wrestling Federation to pop singer Don Henley to Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens every day,'' says Matthew Yarbrough, Special
Internet Council for law firm Vinson &AMP; Elkins in Dallas. ``Some
people know that using a famous person's name alone is gonna
generate traffic, and traffic is one of the most valuable
commodities on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, though, lawmakers are catching up. The first step toward
regulating cybersquatting was taken in November, when the
Anti-Cybersquatting Consumer Protection Act was passed, making it
illegal to register a trademark name for the purpose of peddling it
to its rightful owner. Consequently, Yarbrough says, the number of
cases in which cybersquatters demand money to relinquish domain
names will probably drop (the Brian Wilson case, the perfect
example, was settled out of court; the site now belongs to him).
</P>
<P>
   ``The standard the court uses on cybersquatters is, `Are you
using this site in bad faith and intend to profit from it?' If they
do, then the court cannot only abort that site but it can also take
other action,'' Yarbrough says.
</P>
<P>
   But not all cybersquatters want your money. Some would rather
have your time. They lure you in the same way _ using a famous
person's name as their site address _ but push personal agendas,
not products or services.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has clinched the Republican presidential nomination,
recently encountered such a situation. A 30-year-old New York
database programmer, Zack Exley, started an anti-Bush site,
gwbush.com, causing the Texas governor to say, ``There ought to be
limits to freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign never sued, but it lodged a complaint with the
Federal Election Commission; the FEC recently dismissed it, saying
it had more serious complaints to tackle.
</P>
<P>
   But even seemingly harmless fan sites that use celebrity names
as addresses have come under fire. Courtney Love and the estate of
Kurt Cobain went to court in February to gain control of hole.com,
courtneylove.com and Kurt-Cobain.com, a trio of Nirvana-related
sites that are not sanctioned by Love, the controversial lead
singer of the rock group Hole and widow of Nirvana leader Kurt
Cobain.
</P>
<P>
   According to her PR flack, Love is upset because these sites
feature personal information that she doesn't want floating in
cyberspace. Kurt-Cobain.com, for instance, contains Cobain's
suicide note.
</P>
<P>
   Since Love took the issue to court, though, hole.com and
courtneylove.com have disappeared, at least this week.
</P>
<P>
   Love may have gotten lucky. Web sites that aren't created for
profit, only to provide information, may be a little harder to
exterminate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those sites are probably going to be OK as long as they don't
try to ride on the coattails of the celebrity and say that they
represent them or are affiliated with them,'' says Geoff Mantooth,
a lawyer for Decker, Jones, McMackin, McClane, Hall and Bates in
Fort Worth. ``If they're just presenting information, they have
First Amendment rights to do so. There's a fine line between
putting up a Web site for commentary and trying to make money off
it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBR/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
