<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   How to Get Noticed By a Search Engine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a small Web site that I would like to get listed on a
search engine. How do I do that?
</P>
<P>
   A. Most of the major search engines have a link that will let
you submit your site's URL for inclusion in their database. (It may
take a while to get added to the list, so be patient.) If you don't
want to go from site to site and register your address, there are
services like the one at www.submit-it.com that will do it for you,
for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   Search engines are usually composed of three parts. The
``spider'' or the ``crawler'' will first visit your site, follow
the links to the other pages within the site and check back
regularly to see if anything has changed. The information the
spider collects is passed to the index, a catalog of all the Web
pages that the spider has found. Until the page has been indexed,
it will not appear in the results given to users of that particular
search engine.
</P>
<P>
   The third part of the search engine is the actual software,
which combs the index and looks for results that match a query. The
software will try to rank the results according to relevance, which
can be based on several factors.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a keyword in the title of your page, or in the
headline, the page would probably rank higher on the relevance
scale. If a keyword is used repeatedly in your Web site, the site
would probably get a higher relevancy rating as well. These are
basic guidelines, though, because search engines have gotten much
more sophisticated in how they determine relevancy.
</P>
<P>
   For Web masters and site builders, The Search Engine Watch page
(www.searchenginewatch.com) is a good source of information. There
is a fee for some of the information, but there is still a lot of
data available for free.
</P>
<P>
   Deciphering an Error Message
</P>
<P>
   Q. When I boot up my computer, I get a message box that says,
``Incorrect version of MAPI32.dll.'' What is the program with the
problem, and how do I fix it?
</P>
<P>
   A. That particular error message is related to the Microsoft
e-mail program, Outlook. If you are getting that message, which is
not uncommon, or a message that the file is missing or damaged, you
may want to try the following for your version of Outlook. If you
have it open, close the program before trying to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   For Outlook 2000 users, go to the Start menu, then to Find and
choose Files or Folders. Type ``Mapi32.dll'' in the Named box. In
the Look In list, select My Computer and click Find Now.
</P>
<P>
   In the Search Results list, right-click on Mapi32.dll and click
Rename from the pop-up list. Rename the file Mapi32.old and press
Enter.
</P>
<P>
   You might see several copies of the Mapi32.dll file in the
results list, and you should rename each one. Close the Find Files
box when you are done.
</P>
<P>
   When you restart Outlook 2000, the program will look for the
files it needs to start up. If it cannot find them, it will try to
replace them. If you get a message saying they are missing, click
Yes in the dialog box and the Windows Installer should replace the
missing files and fix the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Follow the same steps for renaming the Mapi32.dll file if you
use Outlook 98.
</P>
<P>
   Next, reinstall the parts of Outlook 98 that the system needs.
To do this, go to the Start menu to Settings and then to Control
Panel. Click twice in Add/Remove Programs and select Microsoft
Outlook 98, then click -Add/Remove. Click on Rerun Outlook 98
Setup, then click Next. Work through the dialog boxes and pick the
type of installation you need and the E-Mail Service Options you
want.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have verified the folder you are installing the missing
files to, click Next and the Setup program should replace the
missing files. Then restart your computer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
