<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7800 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-OBIEWINNER-INTERVIEW-     04-26 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIEWINNER-INTERVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM OFF-BROADWAY TO WAY OFF BROADWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PERRY STEWART c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ A life in the theater is one of extremes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in New York, Melia Bensussen directed a supernatural
chiller about evil spirits that menace children on a 19th-century
English estate. Now, back home in Dallas, the director is about to
mount a nostalgic American comedy set in early-20th-century
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The New York project, at Primary Stages theater, was an
adaptation of Henry James' ``The Turn of the Screw.'' Her direction
won her an Obie, the premier award for off-Broadway productions and
a signature honor, especially for an artist who devotes only a
small part of her career to working in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Her current project is Eugene O'Neill's ``Ah, Wilderness!'' at
Southern Methodist University in Dallas, where Bensussen is on the
theater faculty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep the Obie in my office here at SMU,'' she says with a
smile, taking a break from rehearsal. ``It's not a statue. It's a
piece of paper. They give it to you framed, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Statue or not, does the prestige of having an Obie dramatically
change a director's life _ at least in terms of monetary reward?
</P>
<P>
   Bensussen answers quickly with a soft, ``No.'' She waits a
dramatic beat, then laughs heartily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rocco Sisto, the actor in `Turn of the Screw,' has won a
couple Obies,'' she says. ``He called me when he heard I won and
said, `Welcome to more recognizable poverty.'
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wonderful about the Obie for me,'' she adds, ``is that
I feel welcomed into a community that I have always admired.''
</P>
<P>
   That community includes the top producers in the theater capital
of the world; and they want her to spend more time there, which
she's trying to accommodate. Now a favorite at Primary Stages,
Bensussen will return to the theater to direct the much-anticipated
world premiere of ``Krisit,'' by Y York.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll go into rehearsal in December,'' she says. ``The play
is about a Greta Garbo kind of star who emerges in her 70s after
having disappeared as a superstar in the 1930s. It deals with what
it means to age as a star in America.''
</P>
<P>
   But first is ``Ah, Wilderness!'' at SMU.
</P>
<P>
   Bensussen has never before directed an O'Neill play, and she's
starting with an atypical one. ``Ah, Wilderness!'' _ a celebration
of an idealized vision of middle-class America _ is the only comedy
written by America's greatest dramatist. It depicts a loving,
charmingly eccentric family _ the kind that O'Neill wished he had
grown up in. The play, which originally opened on Broadway in 1933,
stands in poignant contrast to ``Long Day's Journey Into Night,''
his corrosive drama that is more autobiographical.
</P>
<P>
   ``''Ah, Wilderness!'' reminds me of Thornton Wilder's `The
Matchmaker,' which I love,'' Bensussen says. ``The optimism, the
American spirit, the energy. It's so hopeful, so positive. And it's
a style piece. It's not so easy to do as it appears.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being her first O'Neill project, ``Ah,
Wilderness!'' is also Bensussen's first collaboration with another
director. She is co-directing with Kevin Paul Hofeditz, chairman of
the theater division at SMU's top-ranked Meadows School of the
Arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been great fun,'' she says. ``The arts division, and
Kevin in particular, has done me a great favor by sharing the work
with me at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Married to Dallas biologist Chuck Epstein and the mother of two
small children _ including a 4-month-old _ Bensussen says she
``felt, in the first year of my daughter's life, that I wanted to
emphasize her as much as possible. That was the logistical reason
(to collaborate.) What's happened that has been a revelation is
that I find myself understanding how I work and why I work when I
have to explain it to a colleague.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, but has she had any arguments with her co-director?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have major disagreements, but not arguments,'' she admits.
``And the disagreements are jolly. ... I think the reason it has
worked is that our cast is of such high caliber. Where Kevin and I
perhaps contradict each other, the (cast) is able to find the best
in each of our adjustments and go with that choice. Stylistically,
in terms of the overall vision of the play, we see very much eye to
eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the play's period setting, Hofeditz and Bensussen went
with colorblind casting for ``Ah, Wilderness!,'' which she felt was
an important choice to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a completely interracial cast,'' she says. ``The play
is all about this idealized family. It's not about genetic
matchups.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, cultural blending comes easily for Bensussen.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father's Mexican and my mother's American,'' she says. ``I
grew up in Mexico City, but New York is the homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   Which raises the question, now that she's gaining attention for
her work, will her homeland _ a la Sam Mendes _ soon be Hollywood?
Bensussen shakes her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love going to the movies,'' she says, ``but I feel like my
work in the theater is only at a beginning point. I've been doing
theater for 20 years now, and I hope to be doing it for another 40
years. I think the great master artists of the theater only hit
their stride in their 50s and their 60s. I'm almost 40.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
