<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-GAP-TOOTH27-COX     04-26 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAP-TOOTH27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Star's dental deficit truly gap-tivating
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's hard to escape Lauren Hutton.
</P>
<P>
   As the handsome face and husky voice of our very own Gardens
mall, she appears in its TV and radio ads. She still shows up on
the occasional magazine cover, and now she's the author of
``SlimFast Body, Mind, Life Makeover'' (Regan Books, $24), which
came out this month.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever you encounter Hutton's mug, you can't help but notice
the gap between her front teeth. David Letterman has a gap; so do
Madonna, Maya Angelou, Sandra Bernhard, Ernest Borgnine, Laurence
Fishburne and Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   But Hutton's is surely the most famous and most ironic, given
her status as one of the late 20th century's great beauties.
</P>
<P>
   Her modeling career has spanned from the mid-'60s, when Vogue
editor Diana Vreeland declared that she had ``quite a presence,''
until today. Just last fall, she showed up again on a Vogue cover
with fellow mannequins Iman, Kate Moss and Gisele Bundchen. Her
number of Vogue fronts: 26.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, her spaced-out smile, beaming from beneath
those stratospheric cheekbones and clear blue eyes, inspired debate
over standards of beauty in the modeling industry.
</P>
<P>
   The medical term for a gap between the front teeth is
``diastema,'' and the condition is not unusual among people who
have never visited the orthodontist.
</P>
<P>
   It's common enough to have its own Web site. At
www.gap-toothed.com (the slogan: ``everybody needs a little
space''), Hutton has been crowned Queen Lauren. ``This, this is a
woman who knows how to make it work,'' the site says. ``Lauren
Hutton makes it obvious: Truth is beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   According to filmmaker Les Blank, who celebrated diastema in his
1987 film ``Gap-Toothed Women,'' several African tribes regard a
gap between a woman's teeth as a sign of fertility. Other cultures
view it as a sign of good fortune or frequent travel.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the lusty Wife of Bath in Chaucer's
``Canterbury Tales,'' who never lacked suitors: ``She knew much of
wandering by the way/Gap-toothed was she, truthfully to say ...''
</P>
<P>
   In modern-day America, the gap is largely regarded as a flaw
that needs fixing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people feel more comfortable with their appearance having
the gap closed,'' says Richard Masella, associate professor of
orthodontics at the College of Dental Medicine-Nova Southeastern
University in Fort Lauderdale. ``A few regard it as a defining
personal trait and don't want it closed. I think Miss Hutton falls
in the latter category.''
</P>
<P>
   Masella says he has heard of some Asian cultures where a space
between the front teeth is considered positive. And, ``in Western
culture, sometimes there's a family history of having this gap, and
subsequent generations view it as a mark of their family and don't
wish to disturb it.''
</P>
<P>
   (He adds, kids and teenagers often enjoy having diastema: It
allows them to spit with authority.)
</P>
<P>
   So what causes diastema?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the upper front teeth are extremely narrow. Sometimes
they have straight sides when they should be curved. And sometimes
the pressure from a person's bite pushes the teeth apart.
</P>
<P>
   To correct the space, patients can get braces to move the teeth
together or be fitted for crowns that would increase the width of
each tooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mostly an aesthetic concern,'' Masella says. ``I really
don't see a risk to dental health given a space between the front
teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
