<HEADER>
A7804 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-BUILDING-TETRIS-N     04-26 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BUILDING-TETRIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOCK BY BLOCK, TITANIC TETRIS GAME FELL INTO PLACE AT BROWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: R.I.)   (Circuits)  
 By CATHERINE GREENMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It started as a hallucination. In describing the reasons for
re-creating the classic videogame Tetris on the side of the
Sciences Library at Brown University, Keith Dreibelbis, a computer
science major, wrote, ``For anyone who has ever played way too much
Tetris, and looked at squarish buildings, it is easy to start
hallucinating Tetris blocks in them.''
</P>
<P>
   This month, after months of planning and working with other
students, Dreibelbis, a senior, was able to see his vision become a
reality. Powered by 14 custom-built circuit boards, a data network
that traveled several hundred feet and 10,000 Christmas lights, a
10-story version of Tetris was played on the facade of the
decidedly squarish library on the Providence, R.I., campus.
</P>
<P>
   The Tetris installation had been conceived as a prank by
Technology House, a residence for Brown students interested in
science and technology, including Dreibelbis. The idea had been
kicking around for a couple of years before Nik Lochmatow, a Tech
House member and art student, got permission to go ahead with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that if we did it as a prank, it would only be
able to work for a short time and would get us all expelled,''
Lochmatow, a junior, said. ``So we got permission to do it
legally.''
</P>
<P>
   Tetris was developed 15 years ago by Alexey Pajitnov, a Russian
mathematician, and involves manipulating four shapes (each made up
of four blocks) as they fall down the screen to form horizontal
rows, which disappear when they are complete. The object of the
game is to keep clearing out rows as the falling blocks speed up.
</P>
<P>
   Tech House began the installation in January on the south side
of the 14-story library. Floors 4 through 13 were used for the
game, and each floor has five windows across the facade. The
students built 100 4-by-4-foot wooden frames, wrapped each one with
strings of Christmas lights and installed two of them in each
window.
</P>
<P>
   Each frame had a small relay that was connected by a cable to a
circuit board, in a dumbwaiter shaft on each floor. The circuit
boards controlled the lights on each frame based on the signals
they received from a computer on the third floor, with each lighted
frame forming one block of a four-block shape. Lower floors were
lighted in turn, giving the illusion of the shape's falling down
the library's facade.
</P>
<P>
   The circuit boards were connected to the computer by 24 cables
running up and down the dumbwaiter shaft. The computer on the third
floor was connected to a computer in another building, MacMillan
Hall, a building directly across from the Sciences Library, where
the game was played.
</P>
<P>
   Soren Spies, projects manager for Tech House, estimated that
about $750 was spent on materials, including wood for the frames,
Christmas lights, relays, hooks, circuit boards and 3,000 feet of
cable.
</P>
<P>
   During the two weeks that the game was played, people gathered
every night at midnight, which is when the library closed. The game
was not played during library hours because the relays on each
floor made clicking noises that distracted the students.
</P>
<P>
   Players sat on the steps of MacMillan Hall with a laptop
computer that was connected to the computer inside, and they used
the arrow keys to maneuver the Tetris pieces as they fell from the
13th floor. Each player's turn typically lasted four minutes, about
the time it took to move through the game's two skill levels.
</P>
<P>
   Powering the system posed one of the biggest challenges, said
Neel Joshi, a senior who was involved in the installation. ``The
circuitry was the most technically difficult,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people came each night during the last week of
installation, Spies said. A klezmer band also showed up for a few
nights to play music from the original version of Tetris.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think Tech House is the biggest bunch of non-fun people
in the world,'' Spies said. ``But they also thought this was the
coolest thing. They've been very excited.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was partly dismantled on Saturday. It will probably be
reactivated during commencement week in May, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
