   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-GAY (Washington) _ Wading into one of the country's most
volatile cultural battlefields, Supreme Court justices struggle
over the question of whether the Boy Scouts can bar homosexuals
from serving as troop leaders. The case involves James Dale, a
Scout leader in New Jersey who was kicked out of the organization
after saying publicly that he is gay. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CAPITAL (Washington) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush visits the
nation's capital for the first time as the all-but-official
Republican presidential nominee. He stumped for votes at a
Republican women's forum, talked foreign policy with Russian
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, and appeared at a meeting on Social
Security with Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-GALA (Washington) _ In a keynote speech to a Republican
gala, which is expected to raise at least $15 million for the
party, Gov. George W. Bush will call for more bipartisan
cooperation. The money is likely to set a record for a single
fund-raiser, but that is expected to fall in just a couple of weeks
when the Democrats have an even richer event. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-RIOT (Undated) _ In the fifth incident of serious
violence in the Texas prison system this year, a race riot breaks
out at a minimum-security unit, leaving one inmate dead and several
hospitalized. Prison officials say it began when two inmates
started fighting, and the fight spread with prisoners using garden
tools to beat one another. By EVAN MOORE.
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-SHUTTLE (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ Citing bad weather, NASA
again postpones the launch of the shuttle Atlantis, whose
seven-member crew is to make repairs to the international space
station. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ANALYSIS (Mexico City) _ After a throat-cutting Tuesday
night debate that was notable for its vigor, Mexico's longtime
ruling party is in the unusual position of defending its wobbly
record against a strutting opposition candidate seen increasingly
as presidential material. The televised event with six presidential
candidates had little substance but plenty of punch _ mostly
stinging blows aimed at the Institutional Revolutionary Party. By
SUSANA HAYWARD.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Des Moines, Iowa) _ Many Americans become irate
when the courts decree that efforts to inject religion into
non-religious aspects of our lives are unconstitutional, as
recently happened in Ohio. But in doing so, the courts simply
perform a basic duty that prevents any single religious sect from
dominating life in the United States. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (For
release Sunday, April 30.)
</P>
