<P>
   &UR; SABRA-CHATILA RATS. VACUUM-PACKED WRATH: WHY OUT-OF-TOUCH
PALESTINIANS ARE LOSING MIDEAST'S WAR OF WORDS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VACUUM-PACKED-WRATH-FISK-INDEPENDENT-750&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A few days before setting off for the U.S. to speak
at a conference in Boston of the Palestinians' ``Right of Return''
to their homes in pre-Israel Palestine, I walked again through the
ruins of the Sabra and Chatila Palestinian refugee camp in Beirut,
where up to 2,000 civilians were massacred by Israel's Lebanese
Christian allies in 1982. I've been there perhaps a hundred times
since the slaughter, yet the place never ceases to horrify me. If I
lived there, I always think, I'd go mad. Is it any wonder that the
Arabs are losing the Middle East's war of words? That American
liberals fail to understand the real dangers of their hopelessly
biased policy in the region? Or that America and the Sabra Chatila
refugee camp are a million miles apart?...By Robert Fisk, The
Independent &QL;
</P>
