<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-BOOKS-(1500-2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET A DOWNLOAD OF THIS: E-BOOKS COULD BE THE NEXT WAVE IN
PUBLISHING
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Resending to break into two takes) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The movies couldn't do it. Radio couldn't do it. Even television
couldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   With each great leap forward in communications, pundits have
prophesied the death of the lowly, old-fashioned paper book. Now
it's the Internet's turn, as growing numbers of technophiles claim
that Internet ``e-publishing'' will deliver the death blow to
paperbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, touting its e-book reading software, predicts that
e-book sales will overtake paper by 2009. Bill Gates and other
high-tech aficionados say digital books will be significantly
cheaper than printed titles, because there won't be costs related
to printing, binding and shipping. And, they say, as newly designed
reading devices (some of which will be hitting stores by Christmas)
replace eyestrain with ease, consumers will flock to them.
</P>
<P>
   E-enthusiasts point to the success of Stephen King's ``Riding
the Bullet,'' a 67-page novella published in mid-March as an
``electronic-only'' book. When the story became available,
Amazon.com averaged one consumer download per second for it. Within
three days of its release, more than 500,000 King fans either paid
$2.50 for the story or took advantage of downloads offered free by
some Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   That phenomenal commercial performance led to a ``Time''
magazine cover story and a lot of I-told-you-so's from e-book
proselytizers. Now, they say, all the revolution needs for ultimate
success is some clever design work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the (current) e-book devices are not ready for prime
time, but that is changing,'' says Jeff Bezos, chief executive
officer of Amazon.com. ``It's not a matter of whether (they'll
penetrate the market), it's a question of when.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite the news media hype and ambitious publishing plans,
there are holes in this scenario. For one, King _ one of a few true
name-brand authors _ is a phenomenon unto himself. No matter what
format he uses, people will buy his work. (Lost in all the
excitement of ``Riding the Bullet's'' success is the very real
possibility that if the novella had been offered in print as well
as online, the unprecedented tide of electronic sales would have
been reduced to a trickle.)
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Applebaum, senior vice president of Random House, says
``Riding the Bullet'' is probably an aberration, at least in
today's book market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe right now one of the most popular full-length
e-books is Peter Abraham's `Crying Wolf,' and that has maybe
downloaded 1,000 copies,'' Applebaum says. ``We are not
unenthusiastic about e-books, but we're not in the front lines of
those saying they will replace bound books in a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, what's good for publishers _ and consumers _ isn't
necessarily good for writers. Author royalties are based on the
retail price. On a $20 book, a 15 percent royalty _ the typical
percentage _ earns the writer $3. If the e-book version has a
drastically reduced price, as its proponents claim it will, authors
lose out. (Royalties on a $2 sale, for example, are 30 cents).
</P>
<P>
   And because so few authors sell books by the crate as King does,
``They're not going to go along with that,'' predicts Phyllis
Grann, president of Penguin Putnam. (MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
