<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7821 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV3     04-26 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV30-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PUTTING DISTANCE BETWEEN CHURCH, STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, April 30)  
 &HT;     Commentary   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Here in America's heartland, where farmers
are engaged in their spring ritual of plowing fields and planting
corn, an argument is under way over the proposed display of the Ten
Commandments in the state Senate chamber.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Neal Schuerer wants to post the Ten Commandments in
the chamber because he believes that ``government is not an
invention of man, it is an extension of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus the separation of church and state, which is guaranteed in
the First Amendment to the Constitution, has become a volatile
issue in Iowa, where religion and education are of paramount
importance. Iowans who oppose Schuerer's stand are as vehement in
their position, as the proposal's supporters are in their advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the importance of the debate over Schuerer's plan,
the Des Moines Register, Iowa's premier newspaper, printed on
Easter Sunday six thoughtful, well-reasoned letters from readers
who are against the posting of the Ten Commandments in the Senate
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Kelly Sargent, of Ankeny, wrote that Schuerer's
proposal ``convinced me that it has become essential for the
citizens of Iowa to institute a mandatory American history
examination, which anyone elected to the Legislature must pass
before being allowed to take office. He (Schuerer) has apparently
forgotten that this country was founded by men and women who risked
all to escape the religious tyranny of the majority in their
homelands.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Herwig of West Des Moines, wrote: ``Every Christian child
I know has to memorize the Ten Commandments in Sunday school, and
this is an appropriate venue for posted reminders. However,
government is of, by and for all the people, and not all are
Christian. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   As always in our republic, debate over the issue of church and
state has generated anger. It has been that way since the first
settlers came to America to escape religious despotism in Europe.
But once here, some of the settlers decreed that refusal of
individuals to attend church on Sunday was an offense punishable by
incarceration.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over church and state is not confined to any one
state. Ohioans are involved in a dispute over the display of their
state motto, ``With God, all things are possible.'' A federal
appellate court has ruled the motto unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   When the founding fathers added the Bill of Rights to the
Constitution, they recognized the need for religious freedom in the
young republic. The first of those ten amendments declared that
Congress ``shall make no law respecting an establishment of
religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to his death on July 4, 1826, the 50th anniversary of the
Declaration of Independence, Thomas Jefferson designed his own
tombstone and wrote its inscription: ``Here was buried Thomas
Jefferson, Author of the Declaration of Independence, of the
Statute of Virginia for Religious Freedom, and the father of the
University of Virginia.''
</P>
<P>
   To Jefferson, those achievements apparently were more important
than his eight-year tenure as president, his purchase of the
Louisiana Territory, or his commissioning of the monumental Lewis
and Clark expedition across the unchartered land from the Missouri
River to the Pacific Coast.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months ago, the religious issue arose in the battle
for the Republican presidential nomination. It was during the South
Carolina primary campaign that Texas Gov. George W. Bush accepted
an invitation to speak at Bob Jones University, a religious
institution with a reputation for being anti-Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bush formed a firm political alliance with the
Rev. Pat Robertson, a pillar of the religious conservatives who are
intolerant of individuals who do not adhere to their policies,
including opposition to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's action was denounced by Arizona Sen. John McCain, who at
the time was still in the race for the Republican presidential
nomination. In a letter to Cardinal John O'Connor of New York, Bush
apologized for appearing at the university and denied that he was
anti-Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Bush was adhering to one of Richard Nixon's basic
principles of conduct for Republican presidential hopefuls: run as
a doctrinaire conservative while seeking the party's nomination,
but move to the political center once you have won it.
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what Bush has done. After currying favor with
religious conservatives, he triumphed over McCain and sealed his
hold on the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Bush began courting gays, African-Americans and other
constituencies that traditionally have been aligned with the
Democrats. He has not cut himself loose from the religious right,
but he has decided that if he is to win the presidency, he must
broaden his appeal to win the voters who helped elect Bill Clinton
in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans become irate when the courts decree that efforts
to inject religion into non-religious aspects of our lives are
unconstitutional. But in doing so, the courts simply perform a
basic duty that prevents any single religious sect from dominating
life in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
