A7825 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     04-26 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BIRMINGHAM, A HEALING PLACE STANDS IN TESTAMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ ``You're not going to ask me about Frank
Cherry?'' the Rev. Christopher Hamlin asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank Cherry?'' I repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I understand he might be indicted tomorrow on a rape
charge,'' Hamlin says. ``But that's just a way to get him back
here. The next step is an indictment for the bombing of our
church.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin smiles, happy that justice might finally come to members
of the Sixteenth Street Baptist Church. In 1977, Ku Klux Klansman
Robert Chambliss was convicted of murder in the bombing, which took
the lives of four little girls 14 years earlier. He died in prison.
Another suspect, Herman Cash, died in 1994. The targets of the
reopened case, Tommy Blanton of Birmingham and Cherry of Mabank,
Texas, have denied any involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The news makes my heart soar, even though my reason for being in
Birmingham had nothing to do with the church and that old crime. I
had walked across Kelly Ingram Park, where hundreds of student
demonstrators were blasted with water hoses and chased by police
dogs in years past. I'd visited the Birmingham Civil Rights
Institute across the street, purchased souvenir T-shirts and clocks
for my daughters. I stared at the church.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just three hours before I had to catch a plane to Fort
Worth, I stood outside wondering whether I should go inside.
</P>
<P>
   I felt I had to breathe the air, see where an earlier generation
of children had stood their ground in the fight for equality in the
'60s, where Martin Luther King Jr. spoke, where demonstrators
gathered to sing after the civil rights leader was jailed, and
where tragically, hate and dynamite took four innocent lives.
</P>
<P>
   Would it be like entering a room where a loved one died? Do the
hateful images linger like ghosts? Or do you just try not to think
about it, focusing on the present and progress?
</P>
<P>
   When I finally climbed the stairs leading to the churchs
administrative office, Hamlin was on the phone. I waited.
</P>
<P>
   He was only 3 years old and living in Macon, Ga., when Sixteenth
Street Baptist was bombed in 1963. It wasn't until five years
later, when King was assassinated, that Hamlin even heard of the
church, let alone its importance in the struggle for civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Now 41, Hamlin shares this history with more than 80,000
visitors annually to the church.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived in 1990, Hamlin says, church membership had
fallen to about 125, compared with 1,200 at the peak of its
popularity. Even though the church was the heart of the community,
there was much internal bickering over the years. Pastors came and
went, membership dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hamlin works to restore the luster. He wants the church to
be a beacon for reconciliation. ``We're getting there,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the church, which is open for tours Tuesday through
Saturday, has about 600 active members and is beginning to host
community forums on a variety of issues, particularly race.
</P>
<P>
   The first such forum was in 1993, when Washington Booker, Ricky
Powell and other people involved in the demonstrations as youths
were invited to talk about their experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are few outward hints of the racial strife that
gripped Birmingham that summer, Hamlin believes there is a great
need for healing here, to bring people together to discuss issues
and seek solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting to me that after shootings like those that
occurred in Columbine and Oklahoma, counselors are made available
for people,'' he says. ``People here have never been invited to
talk about the movement and how it impacted their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin said he hopes to create a church center for
reconciliation where people can come and discuss race issues and
community conflict. ``That's what happened in '63,'' he says.
``People rallied to work out some really crucial issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, while in the church sanctuary, I imagined what those
meetings might have been like and marveled at my surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteenth Street Baptist is a beautiful edifice designed and
built by African-Americans. Its stained glass windows are
spectacular. So is the pipe organ installed in 1912.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sturdy old building,'' Hamlin says. Wallace Rayfield
designed it right. Thomas Windham built it right, he says.
</P>
<P>
   But, he says, it will take an additional $2 million to make
needed repairs to the church exterior.
</P>
<P>
   As we walk back outside, TV reporters stand in Kelly Ingram
Park, cameras trained on the old church. A young woman runs over to
ask Hamlin about Frank Cherry and the bombings. He says it's too
early to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin says that he understands the need for justice, but that
his church members don't want to go through it all again. Most,
like the visitors to the church, want healing.
</P>
<P>
   On the plane back to Fort Worth, it occurred to me that I had
come for healing as well.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1627EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
