<SLUG> BC-CYBER-CAMP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOTING UP FOR SUMMER CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WINDA BENEDETTI  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer camp. Those two words inspire images of youngsters
tromping down forest trails, paddling canoes across sparkling lakes
and singing ``Kumbaya'' while roasting marshmallows over a fire.
</P>
<P>
   Get with the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Today's cutting-edge summer camps are held on college campuses,
not in forest meadows. Time-honored activities such as whittling,
archery and macaroni art are out.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, video game programming, 3-D animation and digital
movie production are in. And you can forget campfires. Kids huddle
around computer screens instead.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech camps are cropping up around the country with the
tenacity and frequency of summer dandelions. Here kids learn about
Internet navigation, Web page design, robotics, computer animation
and multimedia programs. But do kids actually like this stuff? Do
they really want to sit in front of computers, learning while other
kids are outside playing?
</P>
<P>
   Michelle and Monica McQuaid of Seattle wanted to attend computer
camp about as much as most teens want to be seen at the mall with
their parents. That's to say, they were none too thrilled last
summer when their mom signed them up for the Cybercamps program at
the University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be some geeky computer thing,'' 15-year-old
Michelle says, describing her dismay at the idea of spending a week
staring at a glowing screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my friends that I was going to computer camp and they
all made fun of me,'' says 13-year-old Monica. ``It seemed kind of
nerdy and stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, at first glance, computer camps sound ... well ... they
sound booooring. But camp organizers, parents and even the kids
insist that isn't the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sooo much fun,'' Monica enthuses, explaining that she's
thrilled to be returning to the Cybercamps program this summer. Her
sister echoes her sentiments. ``I loved it. I thought it was a
great experience,'' says Michelle, who now counts Cybercamps among
her favorite summer camps. And she's been to a few _
horseback-riding camp, soccer camp, etc.
</P>
<P>
   So what gives?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a generation growing up with a mouse in their hands,''
says Peter Findley, CEO and founder of the Kirkland-based
Cybercamps. ``Every kid wants a Web page. And kids want to learn
programming because they want to program video games for
Nintendo.''
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, the lessons offered to these kids aren't
humdrum. Tech camps teach kids about computers by teaching them
about things they already love _ movies, cartoons, robots and video
games.
</P>
<P>
   One of InternalDrive Tech Camp's most popular courses is digital
video and movie production. ``They're writing the scripts, they're
shooting the footage. They come into the lab and edit it and add in
the sound and graphics,'' says president Pete Ingram-Cauchi. ``By
the end of a week, they've actually finished a movie. It's great
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Monica and Michelle speak enthusiastically about learning to
write programs that made a calculator work and a rocket move across
their computer screens. They had so much fun at the camp, they're
planning to take a course this summer on how to be computer-camp
counselors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fundamental philosophy is that human brains learn better
if they're having fun,'' Findley says.
</P>
<P>
   Findley was attending the University of Washington in 1997 when
he wrote the business plan for Cybercamps. That summer he held his
first camp at the UW with 122 kids. This year he expects more than
8,000 kids to attend Cybercamps at 27 different colleges around the
country _ UCLA, Georgetown University and the University of
Maryland among them.
</P>
<P>
   Findley isn't the only one who's seen enrollment blossom.
Ingram-Cauchi (also a UW graduate) started the California-based ID
Tech Camps last summer on four campuses. This year he's expanded to
21 campuses around the country and expects enrollment to increase
from 500 students to 2,000. The Atlanta-based American Computer
Experience now offers computer camps at 80 locations around the
United States and United Kingdom. They started with 100 students in
1993 and expect 20,000 to attend this summer.
</P>
<P>
   These three computer camps offer courses suitable for kids ages
7 through 18 and classes suitable for a broad range of skill levels
_ from kids who've never laid hands on computers to kids who could
build them out of tinfoil and toothpaste. They also offer the
option of attending camp during the day only or overnight, with
enrollment ranging from a few days up to several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   For those parents who worry tech camps would have their kids
spending too much quality time with a beige box, Cybercamps, ID
Tech Camps, and ACE all set aside time for outdoor activities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to computer-specific camps, regular summer camps
also have begun incorporating a technological element. The
Northwest School is a private middle and high school that also
offers a summer program with 54 classes for kids to choose from.
This year, in addition to courses in baking, photography and
ceramics, the school will offer classes in Web page design, desktop
publishing and multimedia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computers are such an important part of daily life and they're
only going to become more important,'' says Susan Mueller, summer
program director for The Northwest School.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly why parents are flocking to computer camps _
despite the steep enrollment fees (often more than $500 for a
week). Parents are concerned about their children's ability to
survive and compete in an increasingly technical world.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you choose a camp for your child, you're choosing life
activities that will help them in the long run,'' says Kathy
McQuaid, mother of Michelle and Monica. ``If they focus on computer
science, I feel they'll have a really good job. And Cybercamp makes
it so fun, they don't even know they're learning.''
</P>
<P>
   TO LEARN MORE
</P>
<P>
   There are a variety of summer computer camps where kids learn
everything from Web page making to game programming. Campers can
stay for a few days or for weeks, during the day only or overnight.
Many camps offer scholarships as well as discounts for families
that sign up more than one child. For more information:
</P>
<P>
   CYBERCAMPS
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 904-CAMP
</P>
<P>
   Web page: www.cybercamps.com
</P>
<P>
   Sample Costs: $279 for 3-day daytime-only camp; $1299 for 10-day
overnight
</P>
<P>
   Comments: offers a half-computer/half-sports hybrid
</P>
<P>
   INTERNALDRIVE TECH CAMPS
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 709-TECH
</P>
<P>
   Web page: www.idtechcamps.com
</P>
<P>
   Sample Costs: $548 for five-day daytime-only camp; $1670 for two
weeks overnight
</P>
<P>
   Comments: Offers girls-only courses
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN COMPUTER EXPERIENCE INC.
</P>
<P>
   Phone: 404-439-4400; 800-386-4223
</P>
<P>
   Web page: www.computercamp.com or www.aceplanet.com
</P>
<P>
   Sample costs: $185 for a weekend camp, $560 for weeklong
daytime-only camp; $860 for a weeklong overnight camp
</P>
<P>
   Comments: offers a girls-only camp (apply at
www.allgirlplanet.com starting Tuesday)
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)For a comprehensive list of summer camps around the
country visit www.summercamps.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
