<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV14-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., MAY 14, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have to install some shelves and hang a number of pictures,
plus a mirror, on the walls of my new condominium apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The walls are made of painted drywall and I have only a few
basic hand tools.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of hollow wall anchors or similar mounting fixtures
should I use that will be quick and simple for an inexperienced
amateur to use and install, particularly since I own no power
tools?
</P>
<P>
   A: Auger type anchors that look like large, fat screws, and are
made of plastic or some type of zinc alloy, are probably the
quickest and easiest to install.
</P>
<P>
   They require no drilling of pilot holes and they work well in
all wall panels of almost any thickness. In addition, they are also
easy to remove when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   You drive them into the wall with an ordinary Phillips type
screwdriver until they are tight (they make their own hole and
expand inside the wall after being tightened).
</P>
<P>
   A matching size screw is then inserted into the center and
serves to actually attach the shelf bracket or hook to the anchor.
</P>
<P>
   For heavier loads there are also combination toggle type auger
anchors that are installed the same way _ again without need for
drilling a pilot hole.
</P>
<P>
   Once in place a machine screw is inserted into the center and
tightened. This flips open a built-in toggle at the inside end so
it forms a right angle to the anchor body, thus causing it to lock
securely against the back side of the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My hardwood floor has several dark urine type stains left by
the previous tenant's dog. Is there any way I can get these stains
out of the wood?
</P>
<P>
   A: The only sure way to lighten such stains is to use a wood
bleach, but this only will work on raw or unfinished wood. This
means that the floor will undoubtedly have to be completely sanded
down, then the bleach can be applied before the floor is
refinished.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have a rectangular hole in one wall where an electric
switch was removed. How can we patch and refill this hole before we
repaint that wall?
</P>
<P>
   A: One simple way to cover up or patch a hole of this kind is to
cut a scrap piece of drywall the same size as the opening, but
slightly oversize so it will be a tight fit when pushed into place.
</P>
<P>
   After the patch is in position, apply a thin layer of joint
cement around the edges then cover this with joint tape and apply
another thin layer of joint cement over the tape.
</P>
<P>
   Allow this to harden, then smooth over where necessary with a
thin application of spackling compound, evening it out with a wide
spackling knife.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A number of double-hung wood windows in my old house have
broken sash cords and some of the sash units fit so loosely that in
the winter they allow cold drafts to enter.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot spend the money needed for installing new windows, but
was told there are replacement units that I can install myself.
</P>
<P>
   Have you heard of such items that a do-it-yourselfer can
install?
</P>
<P>
   A: If the sash units are still in good enough condition to reuse
them, you can buy replacement window jambs (also called window
channels) that are made of plastic or metal _ or both.
</P>
<P>
   They can be ordered from many lumber yards and home improvement
centers and can be installed by an experienced do-it-yourselfer.
(They usually come with complete instructions and illustrations.)
</P>
<P>
   These are made to fit inside your present window frames in place
of the existing window channels and make use of the original window
sashes.
</P>
<P>
   The replacement jambs contain built-in weather-stripping to seal
out drafts, and they eliminate the need for sash cords or separate
balances.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``AUGER TYPE WALL ANCHOR'' goes with
this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Auger type wall anchors can be driven into the drywall
with a Phillips type screwdriver without need for drilling any
holes first.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
