<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SPIRITED DEBATE SHOWS VULNERABILITY OF MEXICO'S RULING PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ After a debate that was notable for its vigor,
Mexico's longtime ruling political party is in the unusual position
of defending its wobbly record against a strutting opposition
candidate seen increasingly as presidential material.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's televised event with six presidential candidates
had little substance but plenty of punch, mostly stinging blows
aimed at the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, that has
been in power since 1929.
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Fox, a tall northern rancher with a cool demeanor and
deep voice, was seen as the victor in the debate. Likening his
candidacy to democracy movements that altered the world, Fox stayed
clear of personal attacks that have marked much of his heated
contest with the PRI's staid candidate, Francisco Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a former governor of Guanajuato state and executive of the
Coca-Cola Co., is the candidate of the conservative National Action
Party (PAN), the nation's strongest opposition movement.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said he wanted to build the country's first democratic
transition government, and compared the efforts at winning the
presidency on July 2 to those of South Africa's Nelson Mandela and
Poland's Lech Walesa.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one imagined that Mandela, a farmer, or Walesa, a worker,
could break the chains of oppression and authoritarianism,'' Fox
said during the debate. ``No one imagined that students or
housewives, with their own, hands, would knock down the Berlin
Wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that Fox, 57, is only a few percentage points behind
Labastida in the most contentious presidential race in Mexican
history. Analysts believe that for the first time, an opposition
party has the chance to beat the PRI in a clean election.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, 57, an experienced economist and career public
servant who has held a wide range of jobs in the government,
conceded his party has made mistakes, but said he was committed to
changing an often corrupt and undemocratic system.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wanted to incorporate the values of Luis Donaldo
Colosio, the young, popular PRI candidate who was slain in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many politicians have failed people. That's why we have to
change politics,'' Labastida said. ``I am promoting change in my
party, changes in favor of democracy, and changes to fight for
honesty.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Labastida's candor, overnight opinion polls indicated
most television viewers thought Fox had won the debate.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexico City daily Reforma said 44 percent of people
questioned by telephone thought Fox had won. Only 14 percent of
respondents thought Labastida was the winner.
</P>
<P>
   In another poll, conducted by the daily El Universal, 54 percent
said Fox had won, compared with 28 percent for Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was more a series of speeches, with each candidate
allotted 14 minutes spread over 90 minutes. No questions were
asked, no major issues or proposals were addressed, and it remains
to be seen whether it will change the minds of voters.
</P>
<P>
   Although six candidates are competing, the race has shaped into
a showdown between Labastida and Fox. A debate with just the three
main candidates will be held at the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   Three-time presidential candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, of the
left-center Democratic Revolutionary Party, could not advance his
third-place position, trailing at 12 percent in polls after the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Fox and Labastida men cut from the same official cloth,
Cardenas aimed at Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know he is the candidate who represents the corruption of
the regime, who represents complicity with drug trafficking,''
Cardenas said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The only other contender who made an impact was Gilberto Rincon
of the Social Democratic Party, which has not figured prominently
in Mexican politics.
</P>
<P>
   He called for better treatment of minorities, and urged viewers
to see his party as an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to be a party that could have impact,'' said
political analyst Erick Fernandez. ``He addressed minorities,
women, the handicapped, the indigenous population. After all,
Mexico is a country of minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Fox's standing in the polls, he still will have a hard
time defeating Labastida, who has the formidable strength of the
PRI machine that controls and influences much of the country.
</P>
<P>
   A former agriculture secretary and governor of Sinaloa state,
Labastida appealed to the poor, rural vote that is easily
influenced and which usually sides with the PRI in elections. Much
of the countryside views PAN as the party of the rich business
class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vicente Fox, you remind me of the old PRI. Talk of change is
easy; producing it is not,'' Labastida said. ``When Fox was
governor of Guanajuato he dedicated himself to travel. ... What is
not clear is what the state gained.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who has much sway with the middle class, which has become
increasingly fed up with crime and corruption, responded that his
travels brought employment and business to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Aware that the backing of other parties could be just what he
needs to close the small gap between him and Labastida, Fox asked
for the support of two other candidates _ Manuel Camacho Solis, a
former mayor of Mexico City and a one-time PRI member, and veteran
politician Porfirio Munoz Ledo. Both took part in the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manuel and Porfirio, I need you in the final round,'' said
Fox, who already has an alliance with the environmental Green
Party. ``Because what I am proposing is a transition government ...
a change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
