<P>
   VIETNAM-MCCAIN (Hanoi, Vietnam) _ As he strode Wednesday through
the shadowy hallways and incongruously sunny courtyards _ gesturing
here, pointing to a detail there _ Sen. John McCain might have been
a father showing a son his alma mater. Except the landmarks on this
tour were dank cells like the one where McCain spent two years in
solitary confinement, and leg irons, which he once wore as a
punishment for insulting the guards. McCain took his wife and
13-year-old son Wednesday to see the jail where he spent the
darkest days of his life as a prisoner during the Vietnam War. It
was an emotional capstone of the senator's visit to mark the 25th
anniversary of the end of the war, and McCain was
characteristically blunt about his raw feelings a quarter of a
century later. By Mark Landler.
</P>
