<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7846 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-SWEEPS-SPI &LR;      04-26 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SWEEPS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADOFF SWEEPS SHOWS TAKE YOU BACK, TAKE YOU HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let the stunts begin. The four-week May ratings sweep _ the most
anticipated of the three ``sweeps'' periods because it incorporates
the season finales of most regular series _ starts Thursday, with
the first salvo of blockbuster programming scheduled this weekend
on ABC, CBS and NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Two are four-hour miniseries, which is the networks' way of
killing two nights with one millstone. The other _ the best bet of
the three choices _ is a standard two-hour movie about a deceased
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   None will be remembered as memorable moments of the new
millennium, unless some crafty film historian combines them into
``Take Me Home to the Arabian Nights of the '70s.'' Until then,
they remain completely separate and titled as follows:
</P>
<P>
   Arabian Nights
</P>
<P>
   Sunday and Monday on ABC
</P>
<P>
   Parental guideline rating: TV-14
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Possibly the glossiest miniseries yet from the Robert Halmi
Sr./Jr. fantasy factory, ``Arabian Nights'' holds up reasonably
well the first night. But as a two-night, four-hour homage to the
therapeutic value of storytelling, it commits the storyteller's
cardinal sin of not knowing when to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Like all Halmi projects, ``Arabian Nights'' has a boatload of
special effects, ranging from sophisticated to sophomoric. More
important are the performances _ mostly good _ from a good cast.
</P>
<P>
   Mili Avital is especially pleasing as the ingenious sultana,
Scheherazade, who avoids execution at the hands of her mad husband
by telling him a story each night and _ in perfect May-sweeps
cliffhanger style _ withholding the final act till the following
night. In this manner, Scheherazade runs through five tales, among
them ``Aladdin and the Lamp'' and ``Ali Baba and the Forty
Thieves.''
</P>
<P>
   John Leguizamo injects humor, maybe a tad too much, playing two
different genies in the Aladdin segment. Alan Bates adds wry wisdom
as Scheherazade's storytelling mentor: ``If your audience isn't
interested,'' he advises, ``you're dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the Halmis and ABC might have taken Storyteller's advice
and compressed ``Arabian Nights'' into three hours on one night, as
the network does when it airs big theatrical movies. That way, they
could avoid the inevitable nodding off of viewers on the second
Arabian night.
</P>
<P>
   Take Me Home: The John Denver Story
</P>
<P>
   Sunday on CBS
</P>
<P>
   Parental guideline rating: TV-PG
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B (B+ for Denver fans)
</P>
<P>
   ``The John Denver Story'' has all the markings of another Sunday
night biopic destined for the biohazard pile. But with performances
that raise the pedestrian material to unexpected heights, Chad Lowe
(``Now and Again'') and Kristin Davis (``Sex and the City'') render
the usual obscurity-to-fame-to-obscurity ride of a pop star
watchable if not riveting.
</P>
<P>
   From his dead-on lip-syncing (using Denver's original music) to
an amiable interpretation of the singer's gee-whiz public persona,
Lowe, better known these days as Mr. Hilary Swank, helps make
``Take Me Home'' less rigid than most biographies of the recently
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, however, is the real star. She imbues Annie _ Denver's
first wife and his one true love _ with a glowing strength of
character that generously spreads luster to everyone within her
sphere.
</P>
<P>
   The camera likes Davis a lot, and director of photography Mike
Fash wisely gives the lens sufficient time to register the nuances
in her expressive face. In one scene, when Denver is driving off in
his Porsche for yet another extended period away from his wife and
kids, Davis' eyes wring love, bitterness, frustration, wistfulness
and determination from the moment without benefit of a single word.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Denver's 1994 autobiography, ``Take Me Home: The John
Denver Story'' is an affectionate treatment that still manages to
examine the singer's difficult struggle for acceptance from his
taciturn father. It doesn't ignore the rough spots in his first
marriage, the time he chain-sawed the furniture in a fit of anger,
or his driving while drunk.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS film doesn't recreate Denver's death, which occurred in
1997 when the small airplane he was piloting crashed into the
Pacific Ocean. Instead, viewers are left with a high-sucrose moment
backed by one of the 15 Denver songs featured in the movie. Though
corny in the extreme, it's a fitting ending to a story about the
boyish songwriter who, as a man, discovered he was much like his
father but found a measure of redemption in tuneful messages of
hope, inspiration and love.
</P>
<P>
   The '70s
</P>
<P>
   Sunday/Monday on NBC
</P>
<P>
   Parental guideline rating: TV-14
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Not a single John Denver song is included in the soundtrack of
``The '70s,'' even though 13 Denver songs, in aggregate, spent more
than two years on Billboard's Top 40 list in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Probably doesn't matter. No amount of poems, prayers and
promises could help this rambling follow-up to ``The '60s,'' one of
NBC's success stories from the February ratings sweep last year.
Like its predecessor, ``The '70s'' follows four individuals through
an entire decade, spotlighting their ``journeys of self-discovery''
against a backdrop of the big events of the period, including
Watergate, Richard Nixon's resignation, the end of the Vietnam War,
the women's movement, the rise of disco and the ascension of Ronald
Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with their days at Kent State University, the four
amigos follow divergent paths after National Guardsmen kill four of
their fellow students on May 4, 1970. One goes to law school and
then to Nixon's re-election campaign committee. One sheds her
conservative ways and embraces the fight to gain equal rights for
women. Another tries modeling before heading west and dabbling in
every self-improvement fad available. The fourth, a guardsman who
fired upon his fellow students, runs away to Los Angeles and
eventually finds the leader within himself in the black power
movement.
</P>
<P>
   The acting in ``The '70s'' turns out to be a lot like the music
of the era: mostly forgettable. If anyone stands out, it's Vinessa
Shaw as the budding feminist. The writing is equally vapid, with
this revelatory line, uttered near the end of the second night,
serving to capture the purported essence of the film: ``I guess
none of us are the same people we used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, ``The '70s'' tries to cover too much ground as it
bounces from one story to the next, and thus fails to make its
character development convincing, or even plausible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1648EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
