<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7851 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-JUNKYARD-CHILDHOOD-11     04-26 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUNKYARD-CHILDHOOD-1170-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GEORGIA DAUGHTER'S LULLABY OF THE PINES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNE RAVER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAXTER, Ga. _ ``This probably won't be too thrilling to you, a
wrecking yard like this,'' Franklin Ray said, stepping out of his
jumbled homemade house and leading the way through piles of tires
and aluminum cans, decades of rusting cars and tractors, entwined
in wisteria and wild grapevines, sunk to their hubcaps in years of
pine needles and magnolia leaves. Like Mayan ruins slumbering in
the Yucatan, the detritus of a civilization is piled here in his
back yard, awaiting some archaeologist _ or daughter _ to reveal
its meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy, what are you going to do with this boat?'' Janisse Ray,
a poet and nature writer, asked, narrowing dark eyes at a cabin
cruiser in her path.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows?'' he said, walking past a tricycle perched on a
1958 Chevrolet Biscayne, past the old yellow school bus where his
children played church, baptizing one another in imaginary water,
past the pond where they floated on discarded gas tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, 37, was born in this junkyard. In her first book, ``Ecology
of a Cracker Childhood,'' part memoir, part clarion call to save
the longleaf pine, published in December by Milkweed Editions, she
casts a loving but unflinching eye on growing up poor and
fundamentalist in southeast Georgia, with mental illness snaking
through her clan like a dark tributary of the Altamaha River. Her
daddy ran the junkyard (he still does), and his quicksilver mind
could just as easily resurrect a dead machine as answer the voice
of God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear you, Lord,'' he shouted one morning, crashing through a
bedroom window, arms beseeching the sky, stumbling into the
wilderness of junk that stretches for 10 acres off Route 1, on the
edge of this town, population 3,800. His wife, Lee Ada, had to
commit him to the state hospital for months. When Ray read about
those bad years in ``The Ecology of a Cracker Childhood,'' he said,
``it jarred me around a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I made up my mind not to make up my mind until I had went
through it and digested as much of it as I could,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Tall and courtly, with a head of white hair framing bemused blue
eyes, Ray looks more like a professor of junk or a folk artist than
a man who whipped his four children with a belt when they failed
his moral code, like standing, paralyzed with horror, as a neighbor
boy stomped a turtle to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ain't no sense in killing things for pleasure,'' he tells
them in the book, and metes out five licks to each, ``relentless
and unending.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, this same man tapes a heron's broken leg and wing, letting
it perch for months in the living room, while he hopes, in vain, it
will heal.
</P>
<P>
   The Rays were descendants of the whiskey-loving, lawless Celts
who fled the border wars of Scotland and England for the Georgia
wilderness. They built their houses out of 100-foot pines and let
their hogs, known as pine woods rooters, forage unfenced in the
forest's thick wire grass.
</P>
<P>
   Grandpa Charlie Joe Ray, orphaned as a boy, raised himself in
the woods and swamps. He could ``tickle'' fish _ catch them
barehanded _ and tree raccoons better than a hound. Granny Ray sold
bathtub gin and ran a cafe until her husband wrecked it in a fight
with a boxer. He beat his children in rage, and his wife committed
him, too, when his violence scared her.
</P>
<P>
   But it was C.J., as Charlie Joe Ray was known, who taught
Janisse to love the woods, showing up at the door with iris bulbs
dug from the swamp. He taught her irony, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus wept, Moses slept, and Peter went afishin','' he would
say, when it was his turn to recite a Bible verse at dinner.
</P>
<P>
   In alternate chapters, Ray tells of a land that existed long
before the likes of the ``wild McRaes'' settled southern Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, in the 1700s, a magnificent forest of longleaf pine,
100 feet tall, with great spreading limbs, marched across 85
million acres of coastal plain, from Virginia to Florida. Cushioned
by wire grass, which evolved along with the resin-soaked pines to
survive fire, this elegant ecosystem harbored nearly 200 species of
plants and animals, like gopher tortoises, cockaded woodpeckers,
indigo snakes and salamanders.
</P>
<P>
   That was before 1818, Ray writes, when the Creek Indians were
bloodily defeated and ceded their land to Georgia, and her kin
fanned out over the wilderness, cutting down trees for pastures and
cropland, timber, turpentine and paper.
</P>
<P>
   The memory of what they entered is scrawled on my bones, so that
I carry the landscape inside like an ache,'' Ray writes. ``The
story of who I am cannot be severed from the story of the
flatlands.''
</P>
<P>
   Early one April morning, Ray barreled down a state road toward
the Fort Stewart Military Reservation near Hinesville, to show a
visitor a healthy longleaf forest, only a fragment of which still
exists. Dressed in a white T-shirt and farmer's overalls, she
leaned forward at the wheel of her truck, thin, intense, every
fiber of her body turned up to high.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only have 3,000 acres of virgin forest left in Georgia,''
she said, driving by row upon row of slash pine, a fast-growing
tree that is now farmed on plantations like corn. ``Because of the
spotted owl and pressure from environmentalists in the Northwest,
tree cutting has swung around to the Southeast, so we're in the
middle of a cutting cycle worse than at the turn of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   A pine plantation is not a forest, she kept repeating like a
mantra. The land is plowed up and herbicided, destroying natural
vegetation and driving out most of its creatures. Machines then
plant a single species, usually a fast-growing tree like slash pine
or loblolly, in row after row. So little light falls through the
canopy that not much else can grow.
</P>
<P>
   A longleaf pine forest, however, is widely spaced, with hundreds
of species thriving on its wire grass floor. It evolved to thrive
on fire, started by lightning or humans, scattering its seeds in
the rich mineral ash, and getting a leg up on other pines and
hardwoods that grow faster but can't take the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Years of fire suppression gave these other species the upper
hand. Though the military periodically sets fire to parts of the
280,000-acre forest at Fort Stewart and does selective cutting of
longleaf trees, such efforts are rare in a state that sees its
trees as a cash crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longleaf pine is critically endangered,'' Ray said.
``We've cut down 99 percent of its natural stands.'' She's afraid
people won't know a forest from a pine plantation. Children will
have to go to a planetarium to see a starry sky. They won't know
the sound of silence.
</P>
<P>
   She knew all these things in the wilderness of the junkyard. Her
father never finished high school, but he read encyclopedias and
pondered the theory of relativity. There were rare moments of
paddling a leaky barge down the Altamaha with Daddy, going to sleep
under a full moon. And no one was prouder when she got a
scholarship to North Georgia College, a military school on the edge
of the Chattahoochee National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   She couldn't wait to leave.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no doubt in my mind when I was growing up that I
would leave Baxley,'' she said. ``I knew how bound I was,
restricted. They did it out of love, really, but it was absolute
oppression.''
</P>
<P>
   Her father forbade Janisse and her sister, Kay, to cut their
hair or wear pants, to visit other children or have them over.
</P>
<P>
   (``We set this TV out of the house when Kay was born in '58,''
Ray told me, nodding at a set in back of a '54 Chevy. ``Been here
ever since.'')
</P>
<P>
   His daughter said that when she got to college, ``I felt
socially retarded.'' She added: ``I'd never spent the night at
anybody's house. Never had a date or been to a dance or a football
game.''
</P>
<P>
   She gravitated to the writers and the hell-raisers, drinking
beer and sky diving, reading and writing poetry. She talked James
Dickey into coming to her little mountain school for a reading.
Then she went to Florida State University, in Tallahassee, to get a
degree in English, and fell in love with the hippie culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met this man at the food co-op who had a piece of land in
the country,'' outside Tallahassee, she said. She bought a piece
from him and built her own house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very simple design I came up with myself,'' said Ray,
who after all had spent her youth as the junk man's assistant. ``I
used old telephone poles and got sliding glass doors at Goodwill.
It was a six-sided house of windows, with a tin roof on the edge of
a ravine.''
</P>
<P>
   She could walk out the back door and down to a stream bordered
with mountain laurel and trillium. She'd watch foxes pass by her
windows.
</P>
<P>
   She fell in love with a woodworker, had a baby named Silas and
got married, in that order. But the marriage didn't last.
</P>
<P>
   She and Silas lived in the little glass house, doing farm jobs,
growing garlic, eating from her own big garden. They washed their
clothes in the creek. She still weeps at their hand-to-mouth
existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loneliness of it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she published poetry and studied with Wendell Berry, the
novelist and poet who came home to Kentucky to farm and to write.
In time, with a fellowship to the University of Montana, she earned
a master's degree in nature writing and environmental science and
wrote ``Ecology of a Cracker Childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to tell the story of the land,'' Ray said. ``And
because I had an interesting childhood, I thought it could be the
vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   But most people weren't interested in trees. When the book was
sent to New York publishers, a number of them said they would take
it if she cut out all the natural history.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wouldn't do it,'' Ray said. To her, the two stories were
inseparable. ``With a child, we have the chance to help their
spirit flourish, just as we do with the landscape,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Milkweed, a small press in Minnesota devoted to
environmental writing, offered her a $20,000 contract. The book has
sold 10,000 copies, and is in its second printing.
</P>
<P>
   She came home ``as a matter of honor,'' she said, to be on the
frontlines of environmental activism. ``It's an illness of rural
areas that we teach our children if they want to be anything, they
have to leave and never come back,'' she said. ``And if you come
back, you've failed.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the next breath: ``On the other hand, I don't think I
could raise Silas here.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, as she works with the Nature Conservancy to save the
Moody Swamp, 3,100 acres along the Altamaha, where a virgin
longleaf forest still remains, and while she fights the chipping
mills that are chewing up the upland woods, another voice in her is
rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wendell Berry returned to his Kentucky, but truthfully, I
think I'm failing at it,'' she said. ``You find that childhood is a
mythological place.''
</P>
<P>
   Silas, now 11, is going to a public school, where she has to
tell his teachers not to whip him, because corporal punishment is
the norm. They live in a little cabin of heart pine, surrounded by
azaleas and fragrant wisteria, where her maternal grandmother,
Beulah Mae Miller, let Janisse and her siblings do forbidden
things, like read the funnies and watch ``Wheel of Fortune'' until
they saw the lights of Franklin's car.
</P>
<P>
   A Mason jar of azaleas sits in her bedroom, and over the rickety
table she uses for a writing desk, she has tacked a penciled list
of ``Verbs from `Cold Mountain,''' and a note from a fellow nature
writer, Rick Bass, scrawled on the back of an envelope: ``The only
good writing I've ever done came from someone else pushing my hand
across the paper while I sat in the chair.''
</P>
<P>
   Her soul mates live everywhere else but here. And she concedes
that her next book, on rural communities, isn't going too well.
</P>
<P>
   She talks of moving to Vermont, so that Silas can be closer to
his father. Of writing poetry again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to write about longing,'' she said, as she drove by
mile after mile of slash pine and trailer homes.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a book is so powerful, it holds its writer hostage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
