<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7855 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-IN-SYNC-2TAKES-NY     04-26 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-IN-SYNC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAYING IN SYNC: ALL THE DATA, UP TO DATE, ALL THE TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE HUTSKO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It happens all the time: You arrive home from a long day at work
and realize you left something at the office. On your computer. In
a folder. Something you wish you had now, be it a memo you need to
revise, or maybe a recipe for Jamaican jerk chicken you saved as a
Web favorite while browsing during your lunch break. So much for
that exotic dinner you were going to fix.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, everyday life is often intricately tied to our
computers, whether they are at work or at home, or for most people,
both. E-mail, word processing and spreadsheet documents and
personal information like schedules and contacts have to be kept in
sync between home and office. And many people would like to move
digital pictures and MP3 music files back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   One way to do all that is to tote a notebook computer back and
forth. The same goes for owners of Palm and Windows CE-based
handheld computers _ apart from acting as organizers and miniature
Web and e-mail devices, handheld computers also synchronize data
between home and work. But there are even more alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   First, you need to decide what information to keep in sync.
Often it is just a couple of documents, like expense reports. For
that, a good old-fashioned floppy disk will do _ assuming that your
company doesn't have a rule against taking home things from your
computer and that your computer has a floppy drive. Apple's iMac
and iBook computers, for instance, do not.
</P>
<P>
   Another alternative is to use e-mail. You can send home a file
as an attachment, but make sure that the home and office computers
can handle the same files. Both computers must, for instance, be
loaded with Microsoft Word if that was the program used to produce
the document. If the computers have different versions of Word,
there are extra steps, and sometimes it isn't worth all the fuss.
If the document is simple text, you can just cut and paste it into
the body of the e-mail; any special formatting like bold or italic
or tables would be lost.
</P>
<P>
   For larger files, like PowerPoint presentations and MP3 music
files, floppy disks and e-mail are less practical. Floppies are
generally too short on space, and e-mail is often too slow on the
receiving end. A 56K modem at home can make even text attachments
very slow to download. For these jobs a Zip drive or other
high-capacity device is in order.
</P>
<P>
   Iomega's latest Zip drive, which sells for $179.95, is as small
and thin as a Harlequin romance novel and packs 250 megabytes of
storage space per disk. Disks cost $20 each, or $100 for a pack of
six. The drive connects to a USB port on either a Mac or a Windows
machine and works very fast, because USB is many times faster than
the serial or printer port connection the older drives use to
connect to older computers.
</P>
<P>
   The Microtech Zip drive (about $170) is thinner and lighter than
Iomega's drive, but works only with 100-MB disks. Imation's
SuperDisk USB drive (about $150) can use both floppy disks and
disks that hold up to 120 MB. It's especially useful for Mac owners
without a floppy disk drive and works with Windows PC's, too.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller still but big on storage are compact flash cards, which
are matchbook-size memory chips that behave just like disks but
have no moving parts. Though compact flash cards cost more than Zip
disks, the card readers themselves, which are no larger than a pack
of cigarettes and are easy to carry, cost less than $50. Sandisk's
flash cards start at about $35 for 8 MB and go up to about $325 for
128 MB. Compact flash cards are especially suited to people who own
a digital camera that stores snapshots on compact flash cards; all
you need is the card reader to use the same storage cards with your
desktop computer, or an adapter to pop the flash card into the PC
card slot of your notebook computer.
</P>
<P>
   One benefit of the Zip drive is its collection of easy-to-use
programs for backing up, restoring and keeping files in sync
between computers. The handiest is QuickSync, which will
continually back up your documents folder to the Zip drive any time
there is a change. Or you can use the very helpful file-sync
programs that come with all new and recent Macintosh and Windows
PCs, which, incidentally, also work with floppies.
</P>
<P>
   The Mac program is aptly called File Synchronization. It can be
found in the Control Panels folder. If it is not there, it may need
to be installed from the Software Installer CD that comes with the
Mac. File Synchronization benefits from a well-written,
step-by-step guide that explains how to choose and sync files.
Newer Macs equipped with FireWire and Ethernet ports (like the
latest G4, iMac and Powerbook models) can be connected to perform
the sync directly.
</P>
<P>
   Windows users get a clever sync program called Briefcase. If it
isn't already on the Windows desktop, it can easily be added: Click
the right mouse button on the Windows desktop, select New, then
Briefcase. (If Briefcase isn't a New option, run the Add/Remove
Programs utility in Control Panels and choose Windows Setup to add
Briefcase.)
</P>
<P>
   Briefcase works like a real briefcase, by letting you fill it
with items you want to carry between home and work. Once filled,
the Briefcase gets dragged to a floppy or Zip disk (or compact
flash card). Pop the disk into the other computer and drag to the
Briefcase onto the Windows desktop. Open it to work with the files,
and at the end of the day drag it back onto the Zip or floppy disk
to take back home, where it is then dragged back onto the desktop.
Right click on it and choose Update All and Windows does the rest,
figuring out which files have been added, removed or edited, then
updates accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Mac and Windows synchronization helper programs pay
attention to conflicts. Say, for instance, the same file gets
changed on both computers, either on purpose or by accident. The
helper programs will announce the conflict and offer to replace one
file with the other, in either direction, or will let you cancel
the exchange so you can double-check and ensure that you'll wind up
with the version you want.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7858 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-IN-SYNC-2NDTAKE-N     04-26 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-IN-SYNC-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: you want.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is critical to make sure the date and the time are set
correctly on both computers. A day or even a few hours off on one
or the other may make a file being synchronized appear newer than
the one it is replacing, or vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   There are also off-the-shelf synchronization programs.
LapLink.com's LapLink 2000 includes a combination serial and
parallel cable for connecting two computers and synchronizing
files. (An optional USB cable provides a much faster connection.)
The program creates dual window panes to show what is on both
computers; drag and drop files in either direction to move them
from one machine to the other. Custom options too numerous to cite
here make it possible to create sets of synchronization jobs,
depending on what you want to bring up to date and when. The
program can also dial up another computer to operate it remotely,
letting you transfer and work with files and programs as though you
were working in front of it. (Symantec's pcAnywhere is one of the
best-selling dial-up remote-control programs.)
</P>
<P>
   Puma Technology's Intellisync for Notebooks offers the same kind
of back and forth synchronization wizardry, but with more emphasis
on PIMs (personal information managers). It is especially practical
for people who must keep contact, schedule, e-mail and task data
absolutely up to date. The company gets its expertise from having
developed a version of the product for Palm and Windows CE handheld
computers.
</P>
<P>
   It is the handhelds that offer perhaps the best-kept secret of
desktop synchronization, acting as both electronic organizers that
do e-mail and Web browsing and, most important, as a data shuttle
for more than two computers. The Palm-based devices, which include
the new Palm IIIc color device and the competing Handspring Visor,
use a technology called HotSync. When the handheld computer is
placed in an accompanying cradle that is connected to the desktop
computer, pressing the cradle's HotSync button brings everything on
the little computer up to date with the desktop. Another HotSync
with the home computer at the end of the day brings updates that
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Handhelds running Microsoft's Windows CE or new Pocket PC for
palm-size devices use a program called ActiveSync. Like HotSync, it
synchronizes PIM data between the big and little computers and can
act as a bridge between home and work. It also readily synchronizes
Word and Excel files.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the Web alternative. A number of sites offer
``virtual disk drives'' for stashing files for private or shared
consumption. Impressive among the free-service sites is i-drive.com
(www.idrive.com), which, besides storage space, offers an inventive
``clippings'' utility for snipping items like coupons and articles
for later viewing. The service's Sync program makes sure that what
is on your i-drive matches what is on your computer's hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Apple offers a free service called iTools on its Web site, in a
members-only space where Mac owners can store up to 20 megabytes of
personal or shared data, as well as land a free
``yourname(at)mac.com'' e-mail address. The virtual drive appears
on the desktop, just like another hard disk. Next month i-drive.com
will offer the same kind of desktop icon for Windows users, with a
Mac version due in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   With so many options for synchronizing, the only remaining
challenge is actually locating the files you want to sync. Some
programs, like the elegant Palm Desktop software that Apple
thoughtfully includes with every new Macintosh, store PIM data in a
folder named after its user.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Outlook for Windows squirrels away the PIM file _
``outlook.pst'' _ like so: ``C:/Windows Local Settings/Application
Data/Outlook/outlook.pst.''
</P>
<P>
   With names and places like that, it's no wonder so many people
lead divided, out-of-sync digital lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
