<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNGER-TEXAS-4000(3TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD CHARITIES ACROSS TEXAS SERVING MORE CLIENTS DESPITE STRONG
ECONOMY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For years, Helen gave to charity. She cared for
disadvantaged children. She raised money for the arts. She walked
beside fellow breast cancer survivors in the Race for the Cure.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, she tries to keep a can of food in her car in case she
encounters someone in need.
</P>
<P>
   But when the 66-year-old grandmother and Southern Methodist
University graduate got in her car a few weeks ago and drove to
North Dallas Shared Ministries, she was not embarking on another
mission to help others.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in her life, she was asking for charity
herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried all the way,'' she said. ``I didn't even want to go in
the door. I said, `Be yourself. See what they recommend.' ''
</P>
<P>
   By the time she left, Helen had received some relief from her
utility bills, a few cans of a nutritional supplement and some
groceries. She hadn't asked for food _ only help with the light
bill _ but she was grateful to get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Well, you need this and this,' and I didn't refuse
it,'' she recalled. ``I'm not Julia Child in the kitchen, but
things have been ...''
</P>
<P>
   She paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I have gone to bed hungry,'' she said softly. ``I have
said, `Well, there is just nothing here this evening.' I really
shouldn't have gone hungry, but I have had shortages of food.''
</P>
<P>
   Too embarrassed to give her last name or allow her picture to be
published, Helen shared the account of her painful spiral downward
_ and reluctant plea for help _ during an often emotional interview
at a TGI Friday's restaurant in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   According to charity workers in Fort Worth-Dallas and beyond,
Helen has joined a growing number of Texans who are seeking food,
despite unparalleled nationwide prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   They are down and out in the best of times, locked in a largely
forgotten struggle while others marvel at widespread prosperity,
record-low unemployment rates and burgeoning government surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we're seeing every day. (Helen) is not the
exception,'' said Judy Rorrie, executive director of the
all-volunteer North Dallas Shared Ministries. ``She's the exception
only in that she had a little bit better circumstances to begin
with.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE YOUNG AND THE OLD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Food pantries call them ``clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Many are older people like Helen, who often have little left to
spend on food after buying medicine. Others are young, minimum-wage
workers with no health insurance _ and maybe a sick husband or
wife.
</P>
<P>
   Some are just getting into the work force, but not in a
well-paid job, after leaving the welfare rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their circumstances, their increasing reliance on
private food pantries was cited in a report to Congress last year
as evidence that the strong U.S. economy has done little to help
the hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Although food stamp rolls have been slashed by a third since
1995, ``the need for food assistance has not diminished,'' the
General Accounting Office found. ``Rather, needy individuals are
relying on sources of assistance other than food stamps.''
</P>
<P>
   Charities are willing to help, but many agencies say the demand
is rising faster than they can respond. And they accuse
policy-makers of treating their emergency network like a permanent
safety net.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones that grab you hard are the children and the
elderly,'' said Melanie Gibson, executive director of Arlington
Charities. ``Elderly people, we have found, won't ask for help
until they are hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the children who come in often ask excitedly for
specific items, such as soup, cereal and milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a kid is asking, do you have this and this, and their
eyes are lighting up, you know that child has been hungry and he's
probably been eating just bread or what he got at school for a
while,'' Gibson said. ``That's very hard to deal with.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEMAND FOR FOOD SOARS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The increase in aid requests at Arlington Charities has been
staggering.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the agency received 20,742 requests for help. Last
year, that figure had more than doubled to 42,064, agency figures
show. Although the nonprofit organization offers clothing and other
help, about two-thirds of those seeking assistance requested food,
Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   The increased demand propelled Arlington Charities into grim new
territory in 1999: For the first time, the agency distributed more
than $1 million in food.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1995, we began to see a steady rise in requests, and it has
grown and grown and grown, until we can hardly keep up with it
anymore,'' Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   It is a common refrain in Texas and across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   A report late last year on hunger in 26 cities by the U.S.
Conference of Mayors showed that the demand for emergency food
assistance had risen 18 percent over 1998. The report also found
that 21 percent of the requests for food were going unmet.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, the more than 120 million pounds of food distributed
to the 19 large food banks represents a 26 percent increase over
1996, according to the Texas Association of Second Harvest Food
Banks.
</P>
<P>
   And that figure does not include fresh produce, said Janet
Cocciarelli, director of the association, which helps acquire and
manage resources for the food banks.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Texas, food banks in Corpus Christi and Victoria
doubled their distributions in 1999 from the previous year, and the
Food Bank of the Rio Grande Valley handled a 50 percent increase in
distributions, officials at those organizations said.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, distributions at the Tarrant Area Food Bank rose
15 percent between fiscal years 1997 and 1999 and are up 60 percent
at the North Texas Food Bank since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The North Texas group distributed 15.7 million pounds of food
last year and set two distribution records in the past few months,
handing out 1.5 million pounds of food in July and 1.6 million
pounds in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food bank system was set up to be a supplemental food
system,'' Cocciarelli said. ``We were not set up to meet the needs
of the chronically hungry. We can't keep up with that daily
demand.''
</P>
<P>
   `I'VE NEVER DONE ANYTHING LIKE THIS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. Department of Agriculture, 5 percent of
Texas households experienced hunger between 1996 and 1998. Hunger
is defined as the uneasy or painful sensation associated with
inadequate food intake.
</P>
<P>
   More common than outright hunger is food insecurity, or
experiencing inadequate food supplies ar times. Nearly 13 percent
of Texas households fit that category during the same period.
MORE: &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS: the same period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mayors Conference report ranked Texas second and third,
respectively, in the two categories. It also touched off a
controversy when Gov. George W. Bush, the likely Republican
presidential nominee, questioned the accuracy of the report and
suggested that its release was timed to embarrass him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think the governor would know if there are pockets of
hunger in Texas,'' Bush said in a December ``Star-Telegram''
interview. ``I'd like to know who's going hungry in the state of
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer to that question was obvious and painful to Jessie
Williams, a 52-year-old security guard from Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's lots of nights I go to bed and I can't go to sleep
because I'm hungry,'' a teary-eyed Williams said after picking up
some groceries one recent afternoon at the Northside Inter-Church
Agency in Forth Worth.
</P>
<P>
   She blames the dramatic decline in her fortunes _ and food
supply _ on an injury she sustained at work. She hesitated to ask
for food, but Williams said she had little choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't come down here if I hadn't been hungry,'' she said,
her voice barely audible. ``I've never done anything like this in
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe the contents of her pantry at home, Williams
responded: ``Slim to none.'' She said she mostly eats cereal with
the powdered milk she gets from the Northside charity.
</P>
<P>
   Williams can only fantasize about what she'd like to eat.
Cracking a smile as she formed a large circle with her hands, she
said, ``I'd do anything for a nice, round piece of steak.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `A LITTLE SOUP AND SOME BEANS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sister Jean Thomas Dwyer _ she's affectionately known as
``Sister J.T.'' _ chuckles knowingly when asked whether she's ever
seen any hungry people. She said she sees them all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if there weren't pantries like this one, we'd have a lot
more,'' she said. ``Food stamps cannot feed the family for a month
in most cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Dwyer's office at the Catholic Charities Family
Assistance Center in Oak Cliff _ just southwest of downtown Dallas
_ sits behind thick, black burglar bars.
</P>
<P>
   She calls the place her ``hell hole.''
</P>
<P>
   A gaping hole in the plaster wall is covered with a board. The
office has no hot water or, for that matter, potable water. She
carries in the drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   It is a stressful job. Sister Dwyer took a sabbatical a few
years ago after developing shingles. She is also a cancer survivor.
</P>
<P>
   She is busy dealing with the many crises that visit poor
families. One of her current projects is the Martinez family.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus and Consuelo Martinez have five children, one born this
month with a serious heart ailment.
</P>
<P>
   Their income is limited because Jesus, who walks with the aid of
crutches, has a serious ailment. He's been told that it's
arthritis, although he's not sure. Whatever it is, it makes his
joints swell, particularly in the winter, and prevents him from
working full time.
</P>
<P>
   They have no telephone and are expecting to lose their borrowed
stove and refrigerator. They've applied for food stamps _ and
managed to get them for two months _ but they say their case has
been mishandled by the local food stamp office.
</P>
<P>
   At her ramshackle Dallas home, Consuelo, nine months pregnant at
the time of the interview, said the shelves are sometimes bare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we don't have anything,'' she said, stretching her
legs and grimacing with discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what she does when she has no food, Consuelo said with
calm resignation: ``Well, the children cry because they're hungry.
Jesus will ask his brothers to bring something. Anything, you
know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The children don't eat like they should. They don't eat like
they want to. They ask for a piece of meat,'' she said. ``We barely
have enough for a little soup and some beans. When we had the food
stamps, the kids ate well. But now they don't.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOOD STAMP HASSLES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although the Martinez family requested and eventually obtained
government assistance, they and others like them have discovered
that it is not always easy.
</P>
<P>
   They asked for ``emergency'' food assistance in December, one
week before Christmas, but they say food stamp caseworkers told
them there was no such thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they don't do emergency food stamps no more,'' said
Patricia Martinez, Jesus' bilingual sister-in-law, who went to the
state welfare office to translate for the couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expedited'' food stamps exist, and state guidelines call for
granting them within a day for those who qualify, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   With the cold weather aggravating Jesus' condition and throwing
him out of work, Consuelo said, the family income had dropped to a
level that made them eligible for expedited food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   But they said they had a hard time getting that across to the
Department of Human Services, or DHS.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Jesus nor Consuelo speaks English, and they said no
bilingual caseworkers were at the office to help them, despite
federal guidelines requiring translations when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Patricia Martinez telephoned on her
brother-in-law's behalf and was told that a Spanish-speaking
caseworker would help them. But when the couple arrived 15 minutes
later, they said, they were told that no Spanish speakers were
available.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, nearly a month after they applied, Consuelo said, she
received a $213 food stamp allocation. It helped tremendously _
while it lasted.
</P>
<P>
   After two months, the money was gone, something Consuelo said
she discovered only after a store clerk ran her benefit-dispensing
Lone Star Card through the register. She bought her son, Guillermo,
a treat with the 35 cents that remained. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DHS vs. INDIGENT TEXANS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DHS officials have been unable to confirm or deny the Martinez
family's account of their dealings with the agency. But Mario
Caballero, a lawyer with the Gulf Coast Legal Foundation, said he
has heard strikingly similar tales.
</P>
<P>
   He recently settled one lawsuit against DHS, and just filed
another, on behalf of indigent clients with food stamp problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got clients who come in and say, `I don't want food
stamps, it's too much of a hassle,' '' Caballero said. The chief
problem, Caballero said, is that DHS is so concerned about
ferreting out fraud that it overlooks the needs of legitimate
clients.
</P>
<P>
   DHS officials deny that assessment, saying the agency cares
about stopping fraud and helping the needy. MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS: helping the needy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of Caballero's lawsuits featured complaints about illegal
delays in the processing of requests, and it accused officials of
granting too many short approval periods _ between one and three
months _ after which recipients must reapply.
</P>
<P>
   Before the case went to trial, DHS agreed in January to a
federal court order forcing the agency to provide better and more
timely services. DHS did not admit any wrongdoing in the
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, the Fort Worth-Dallas area was out
of compliance about 20 percent of the time last summer _ worse than
the Houston area, which produced the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether some Texans might have gone hungry because of
caseworkers' documented slow response, DHS spokesman Chris Traylor
said, ``It's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   A new lawsuit, filed March 31, accuses the department of
violating federal guidelines requiring translations for food stamp
applicants who need them.
</P>
<P>
   Traylor said he could not comment on pending litigation, but he
acknowledged, ``There are problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``State agencies have a very difficult time recruiting and
retaining bilingual staff,'' he said. ``We have undergone efforts
to do so, but in today's economy, bilingual staff are at a premium,
and it's difficult to recruit and retain staff.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $10 A MONTH IN AID &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the poor say the hassle associated with food stamp
applications is one of the many reasons food stamp rolls have
dropped since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Between October 1995 and October 1999, the number of food stamp
recipients in Texas declined 45.7 percent, more than in any other
state during that period, according to USDA figures. That compares
with a national decline of 32.6 percent during those years.
</P>
<P>
   Many poor Texans who do not receive food stamps, including
former welfare recipients who may have lost other benefits, remain
eligible for the program.
</P>
<P>
   In a few counties, including Collin and Denton, more than 90
percent of those eligible in 1999 did not receive food stamps,
according to an analysis of government data by the Center for
Public Policy Priorities, which lobbies for poor Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and DHS officials say they are trying to sign up all Texans
who are eligible for the federal food stamp program.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Bush said critics do not mention that he
signed a bill in 1999 appropriating money to fund an outreach
program so ``people can get on food stamps who are deserving to be
on food stamps.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The best place to address the hunger issue is to make sure
people who are eligible for food stamps realize there's a program
available for them, so we're doing that,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Friedman, the DHS' executive deputy commissioner, said the
agency distributed 265,000 fliers advertising the program at more
than 16,000 sites across Texas between December and April.
</P>
<P>
   He said people have moved off the rolls for many reasons, not
the least of which is an aggressive effort to get jobs for
recipients. New rules bar or restrict able-bodied adults and many
legal immigrants from receiving food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor: Some recipients are entitled to so little that
they feel that it's not worth the effort, officials said. The
elderly and disabled who receive food stamps, for example, get an
average of $10 a month in benefits, according to DHS.
</P>
<P>
   Although Friedman's goal is to sign up everybody who is eligible
for food stamps, he said that still wouldn't be enough. Those who
get help often need more assistance before the month is out, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are hearing is that food stamps will last two and a
half, maybe three weeks. There is a gap,'' he said. ``It was
intended as a supplement. It was never meant to be the sole
nutritional program.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EATING `JUST ONCE A DAY' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The limits of governmental and private help are not lost on Mary
Sandoval. A night cashier at Wal-Mart, Sandoval receives help from
the Women, Infant and Children (WIC) program and relies on
assistance from local charities.
</P>
<P>
   It is not enough. Faced with food shortages, she said, she has
given sugar water to her 5-month-old baby when she didn't have milk
and skips meals herself to make the food last longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I eat just once a day, because we don't have enough
in the house for us to be eating all the time,'' said Sandoval, who
lives in a mobile home with her boyfriend in Pelican Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I eat just before I go to work so I won't get hungry at
work,'' she said. ``I don't want to sit there and watch other
people eat, and I can't afford to buy anything.''
</P>
<P>
   She is candid about her own failings. A former drug abuser, she
said she voluntarily relinquished custody of one of her children
because her addiction was getting the best of her.
</P>
<P>
   Sober for eight years, she is trying to make a go of it again.
Her boyfriend is unemployed, recovering from a serious work injury.
So she has to rely on her salary of $6.50 an hour to keep baby Rae
in diapers _ and fed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sleep whenever I can,'' Sandoval said, choking back tears as
she comforted her fussy daughter. ``It's frustrating. It's real
frustrating. But every time I look at her and see her smile, it
just seems like everything is going to be OK.'' (Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
