<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7863 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BLUE-MAN-GROUP-2TAKES     04-26 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUE-MAN-GROUP-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE MAN JOINS THE VEGAS COLLECTION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   By VICKI GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Thank God the Twinkie strike was so brief. Never
mind all those people with the shakes from involuntary withdrawal;
Blue Man's show was in trouble. One of the group's best acts is the
one with the Twinkies, the electric saw and Andrew Wyeth's
``Christina's World.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation was approaching crisis levels. At least Cap'n
Crunch, which Blue Man uses as a percussion instrument, wasn't
having any trouble with the Teamsters union.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Man Group is the three-man performance troupe, the bald,
blue-headed guys who, though unspeaking (and occasionally
unspeakable), have been wreaking havoc on contemporary art in the
intervals between playing their own music on plumbing pipes at the
Astor Place Theater in Manhattan since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Before that they did their thing in living rooms and in Central
Park, once conducting a ``Funeral for the '80s'' for the late,
great postmodern and deconstructionist theories of art.
``Surprisingly,'' they write on their Web site (www.blueman.com),
``the funeral worked. The next day, artists all over the world
agreed to stop making art based on these misguided concepts.''
</P>
<P>
   The original Blue Men, Matt Goldman, Phil Stanton and Chris
Wink, were street performers who established their own Club Nowhere
on a sidewalk outside the Copacabana in the late 1980s. By now,
Blue Man has effected a corporate merger with himself. Thirty other
Blue Men have joined the troupe, plus two in training. On Third
Street in the East Village, Blue Man has an enormous rehearsal and
performance theater, plus a recording studio (its first CD,
``Audio,'' came out last year).
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Man: Tubes,'' the New York show, is still going strong.
In 1995 it opened in Boston; it's going strong there, too. In 1997
it was Chicago, where, yes, it's still going strong. Last month,
Messrs. Goldman, Stanton and Wink opened in ``Blue Man Group: Live
at Luxor'' in Las Vegas, with a five-year contract. Long-term
thinkers, they hope to go on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas may seem like an unlikely site for hip and irreverent
performers up from the sidewalks of New York. But there's Blue Man,
drumming up trade at the Luxor, the pyramid in the American desert
that is the second-largest hotel in the country. The Luxor's lobby
space amounts to 29 million cubic feet, enough to shelter nine
Boeing 747s stacked on top of one another, if you had a mind to
stack up 747s, and heaven only knows how many mummies.
</P>
<P>
   Here, huge Egyptian goddesses with distinctly 21st-century
features guard the entrance to the sacred precinct of the casino.
Beyond (italics)that(end italics) is the Blue Man store, the
theater and a ladies' room, where sprightly recorded voices sing,
``bathroom, bathroom, bathroom'' and once again, ``bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Man's first show sent up the art scene, with paintings made
by splashing paint randomly off drums, a fish analyzed in the
thorny terms of art criticism: in-jokes for the downtown New York
crowd. If the art scene has outgrown the references, the audience
finds Blue Man so funny it doesn't matter. But will it play in
Peoria? Or Las Vegas?
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes. Blue Man has cut down the art references for the
Luxor show and replaced them with music and spectacle, but they
still make a couple of paintings every evening, which sell out in
their store.
</P>
<P>
   The Las Vegas production was the third time I had seen the show
(which has a kind of cult following that comes back five and six
times, as if ranking Blue Man somewhere between the ``Rocky Horror
Picture Show'' and ``Star Wars'') and every time, the audience,
including me, laughed itself silly at the sneakily wise and
eminently clueless, determinedly deadpan glee of the art riffs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the polyvinyl-chloride-pipe instrument Blue Man
whomped up long ago, which rather resembles a xylophone attached to
a plumber's model of the intestinal system, the group has devised
enough clever new PVC-pipe instruments to put the pipe industry on
the charts.
</P>
<P>
   They say they are playing tribal rock, ``with kind of a
spaghetti western theme,'' as Chris Wink put it in a recent
interview, like ``the Magnificent Seven, the people who drift into
town.'' The show rocks, pulsates and percusses with the aid of a
16-piece band in fluorescent devil gear. They make compelling
jump-up-and-down music, and by the end a lot of the rock concert
habitues in the audience were doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   The group is still heavily invested in art, more on the Web than
in Vegas. Its site includes an updated history of modern art that
reveals important new information for art historians: It was Blue
Man who pushed Yves Klein out the window for his famous
flying-through-the-air photo; Blue Man who wielded most of the
paint cans in Jackson Pollock's studio; Blue Man whose spiral
painting inspired Robert Smithson's jetty.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas itself has recently embraced art in its very own Las
Vegas way: as entertainment. (Art is heading in that direction as
fast as it can in museums and galleries; Vegas just has
higher-octane fuel.) At Caesars Palace, people concentrate on the
slots under busts of the Roman emperors, and classical Venuses fill
all the niches in the shopping arcade except the ones with Elmer
Fudd and Wile E. Coyote.
</P>
<P>
   Cirque du Soleil's ``O,'' the under-and-over water fantasia at
the Bellagio, is a revue composed of acrobatic acts in the
costumes, settings and disguise of art theater, staged in a tank.
</P>
<P>
   The main attraction at the Bellagio, where the meeting rooms are
named Cezanne, Degas, Renoir and van Gogh, is Steve Wynn's $300
million art collection. The big sign in front of the Bellagio reads
``Now Appearing: Van Gogh, Monet, Cezanne and Picasso.'' They do
appear, in a manner of speaking, in two windowless rooms lined with
deep black fabric, each painting relentlessly lit by spotlights to
the point where textures seem flattened out and one or two might as
well have been airbrushed. Please welcome Vincent van Gogh, star of
stage and screen!
</P>
<P>
   In the kingdom of stars, spectacle reigns. (All right, it reigns
everywhere, but in Vegas it's the emperor.) Blue Man came out here
when he felt ready for the big time. Up to now, he has been playing
in theaters that hold 300 to 600 people; at Luxor, there are 1,250
seats at $55 or $65 a ticket, less than some other Vegas shows.
</P>
<P>
   The trick, as Matt Goldman said, ``was to make a show big enough
for an arena that would still seem small and intimate,'' as it did
in the vest-pocket theaters they have been playing in. (Though Las
Vegas' notion of intimacy is an escort service.) So a giant screen
sometimes duplicates the action at Luxor, or Blue Man and the band
loom large only as projected shadows behind cloth.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   I confess I missed the close encounter of the first kind, but
the special effects in this $7 million production were as fetching
as special effects onstage have any right to be in the era of ``The
Matrix'' and ``Toy Story'': clumsy, bent-kneed statues suddenly
swayed and bobbed up and down in the staccato glare of precisely
timed strobe lights; neon stick figures did a disjointed shuffle
against a black backdrop, then imperceptibly stepped out of the
backdrop to accompany the band as fluidly as any majorette.
</P>
<P>
   The real ingenuity of this production lies in Blue Man's ability
to connect to a large audience and keep it participating in the
show. Electronic message boards with streaming messages warm things
up before the performance begins: ``OK, now everybody make that
noise they used to make on the Arsenio Hall show.'' Everybody does.
``OK,'' the sign says, ``that's enough.''
</P>
<P>
   All three Blue Men periodically sprint up the theater aisles or
climb through the rows of spectators on chair arms and backs. Twice
they bring someone up onstage to join the antics; once they carry a
lighted tube over to a man on an aisle, open his mouth wide, shine
a light at his throat and project an entire endoscopy onto a
screen.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the performance the night I was there, when miles
of paper, oceans of sound and storms of flashing light rained down,
lots of people were on their feet dancing, waving, shouting. Rock
came to the Las Vegas tribe.
</P>
<P>
   If Blue Man seemed an unlikely choice for Las Vegas, it must be
pointed out that everything in Las Vegas is unlikely, and the city
has changed so much in recent years that it's unlikelier than ever.
Though even today there are some things that are as close to
eternal as a town built on roulette wheels could hope for: the
airport still has slot machines; the casinos still play a
repetitive, purling tinkle, kind of like Philip Glass on a
hurdy-gurdy but punctuated now and then by the chunk-chunk-chunk of
coins bouncing out of the slots.
</P>
<P>
   The cocktail waitresses in the casino still wear perilously
little and an ad for the ``Midnight Fantasy'' show pictures a pair
of bare legs in high-altitude heels and promises ``a place where
there is truth in the statement that less is more.'' But things
ain't what they used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Vegas has become the very emblem of the contemporary,
computer-induced preference for the virtual over the real, the
special effect over the natural, fantasy and the fantastic over the
everyday. It has welded the lust for escape to the lust for sex and
money. The Strip is a new entity: the city as simulacrum, a global
fun house cum theme park, with the Eiffel Tower rising directly
across from a lagoon in Italy and Egypt connected by a walkway to
Mandalay.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of instant travel that was initiated by the railroad
and furthered by photography, film, the automobile and the airplane
is here translated into an amusement park, the current version of
the 19th-century world's fairs that brought Polynesian and African
villagers to the West and instructed them to act like Polynesians
and Africans for the edification of the paying customers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Las Vegas obeys the basic rules of political correctness.
Only the monuments have been transported this time, and they have
been converted into giant toys, as if to say that everyone on the
premises is part of the game, and anyone can win.
</P>
<P>
   The city is a nutty mix of entertainments and intrusions, where
people scream on the roller coaster directly above a restaurant at
New York New York, and a taxi driver's radio proclaims Darwin
totally, scientifically wrong. It is the fastest-growing city in
the United States; almost 50,000 people move here every year. The
school system has a good reputation, the climate and prices are
right, the state has no income tax.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas itself, of course, has become a major tourist
attraction; the Chamber of Commerce says there are 32 million
visitors a year. Chris Wink says: ``Las Vegas is like touring. The
tour comes to you every three and a half days, when the entire
population of Vegas changes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, 99 percent of visitors to Las Vegas came to
gamble, but by the mid-1990s only 87 percent did. Maybe they came
for the waters, but if so they were misinformed.
</P>
<P>
   They came for conventions _ 2,600 conventions in 1994, 3,800 in
1999 _ and for entertainment. Spending on entertainment, shopping
and dining rose more than twice as fast as gambling revenues
between the mid-1980s and the mid-1990s. No wonder Spago, Chinois
and Le Cirque have opened branches. That's not chopped liver.
That's foie gras and lobster bisque for the new rich, the filthy
rich, the expense-account crowd and aging boomers with the mad, mad
urge to pay more than they have to.
</P>
<P>
   In the citadel of kitsch they can now get culture too, on
multiple levels, from a genuine Rubens to ersatz Michelangelos,
from the silicone breasts at the Folies-Bergere to Blue Man's
authentic plumbing pipes and marshmallow sculpture: the world's
greatest (and probably only) work of art crafted from marshmallows
lobbed from a distance into a Blue Man's mouth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
