<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DEBATE-0427-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEBATE GIVES MEXICAN OPPOSITION CANDIDATE BIG PUSH
 &HT;    (700&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With box information attached at end of story.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Vicente Fox, the cowboy-booted rancher who is
threatening to upset 71 years of one-party presidential rule in
Mexico, is relishing high poll marks and a burst of positive
publicity following a bitter presidential debate here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's performance appears to have at least consolidated his
position in a very close second to Francisco Labastida, candidate
of Mexico's ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI. The
race, which culminates in a July 2 election, is turning into the
most hotly contested presidential election in Mexico's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``After an exciting night and a caffeine-filled morning, it's
really hitting people today that Labastida might not win,'' said
Daniel Lund, who runs his own opinion survey company, MUND, here in
Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   But the Labastida camp is downplaying an array of instant
opinion polls after the six-contender debate that declared Fox the
winner, often by a large margin. All polls, including some that
placed Labastida in first place, were conducted by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   And opinion surveys have shown in the recent past that Mexico's
rural communities and the less educated _ who are less likely to
have telephones _ remain a voting stronghold for Labastida and the
PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much can you trust polling that's done ... only among
people with telephones?'' said Sandra Fuentes-Berain, Labastida's
coordinator for international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have come out of the debate feeling like we're fighting the
media, too _ certain media,'' she said, declining to identify which
newspapers or broadcasters she was referring to.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City's Reforma newspaper, which is often critical of the
government, conducted a telephone poll of 1,019 people in 190
cities and 105 smaller communities in all Mexican states after the
debate. It found that 44 percent of respondents thought Fox won the
debate. Twenty percent thought nobody won or didn't know, and only
14 percent thought Labastida won.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the percentage points were divided among the other
candidates, including just 7 percent for Cuauhtemoc Cardenas of the
center-left Democratic Revolution Party, who polls show trailing in
third behind Labastida and Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Another major Mexico City daily newspaper, El Universal, and
some radio surveys also declared Fox the debate winner. Excelsior,
which is considered generally pro-government, published a poll it
had commissioned that showed Labastida the winner over Fox with 40
to 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's campaign officials were ecstatic, however, with the
results in general.
</P>
<P>
   Press aide Gina Morris said the Fox campaign agrees that the
instant telephone polls conducted Tuesday night are not reliable
indicators of popularity when it comes to Mexico's countryside and
urban poor, who often don't have phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are conscious of that,'' Morris said. But for months, she
said, Fox _ a former governor of largely rural Guanajuato state _
has been trying to make inroads into parts of rural Mexico where
sympathy for him has not been strong.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate, Fox appealed to all Mexicans _ and even the
four rivals also competing against Labastida _ to join him in his
fight to win the presidency and build a ``pluralistic''
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Fox belongs to the conservative National Action Party, or PAN,
but one of his challenges is to convince the poor who don't like
the PAN and more liberal voters to make their votes count by
choosing him.
</P>
<P>
   At least one Mexican voter says she's buying the line Fox pushed
during the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for young people to fight for a better country,''
said Jimena Ramirez, 18, a psychology student at Mexico's National
Autonomous University. ``Maybe Fox isn't the best option, but right
now he's the closest thing we have to one.''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, who also looked pleased and claimed triumph after the
debate, told a Mexico City radio station that his campaign would be
conducting polls over the next week to come up with figures it
believes are more reliable than the instant surveys.
</P>
<P>
   Pollster Lund agreed with the notion that to measure widespread
public opinion, more in-depth surveys would be needed.
</P>
<P>
   Because the debate wasn't broadcast on television channels that
attract the biggest audiences, ``basically, rural Mexico didn't see
this debate,'' Lund said.
</P>
<P>
   However, as much as 30 percent of the vote-rich urban zone of
the Valley of Mexico may have either seen or heard the debate,
according to preliminary internal estimates by INDEMERC, a Mexican
affiliate of the U.S.-based Louis Harris polling company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox beat them all,'' said INDEMERC director Vicente Licona.
``The debate gave him a tremendous push.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------------------------
</P>
