<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL ELIAN, ALL THE TIME. STOP, POR FAVOR!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
UNDATED: 12, 13 and 19. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the network's big coup was Diane Sawyer's ``Good Morning
America'' interview with the boy, his 21-year-old cousin
Marisleysis and psychiatrist Gunther Perdigao. The interview ran
March 27 and 28 and was recapped March 29.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer, the experienced newswoman, elicits responses such as
``Hello. Hello'' and ``No'' from Elian, and tells us Elian scolded
her when she touched his teacher's paper flowers. This must be what
they mean by ``Must-see TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Through Marisleysis, who was interpreting, Elian talks about the
sinking of the boat _ occupied also by his mom and her boyfriend _
the dolphins that he said kept him afloat for two days, and the
prayer he said to his guardian angel.
</P>
<P>
   The most spirited (and often confusing) debate, however, has
been held the past two Sundays, on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder and House
Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Sugar Land, argued over whether there
was a search warrant and whether Saturday's predawn raid/seizure
was legal; DeLay promised congressional hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, there was a search warrant (DeLay says there
wasn't), because it was shown on CNN on Monday. DeLay sounded at
times as if he were inspired more by a political agenda than the
seizure of Elian.
</P>
<P>
   The previous week might have been more confrontational. Jose
Garcia-Pedrosa, one of the Miami family's many attorneys, said
there was ``ample evidence'' that Juan Miguel Gonzalez had a
``violent temperament'' and beat Elian and his mother. He stopped
just short of accusing Gonzalez of sexual molestation.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Serrano, D-New York, fired back by asking why the
family has gone from characterizing him as ``a great father who
should stay in this country to a father who beats his child and
sexual molestation.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for the conspiracy theory angle to be
introduced. It started when the photos of Elian with his father
were released by the U.S. government. The photos, Elian's Miami
relatives said, were doctored. This seemingly desperate theory,
floated most hysterically on Sunday by Marisleysis, contends that
the boy's hair is longer in the reunion photos than when he was
with the family in Little Havana less than 48 hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Rep. Lincoln Diaz-Balart, R-Florida, said the
government was drugging and brainwashing the boy, based on seeing a
Band-Aid on the child in the reunion photos.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, a quick perusal of Internet search engine Yahoo
finds at least seven Web sites devoted to the controversy, fairly
evenly divided between he-should-stay and he-should-go.
</P>
<P>
   Web site www.pathtofreedom.com features two essays _ ``A Kick in
the Rear'' and ``A Pie in the Face'' _ and a poem called ``Soul
Wrecked'' by Jules Dervaes. It also runs a ``days in captivity''
tally and the phone and fax numbers of Reno, President Clinton,
Vice President Al Gore and others for those wishing to express
their outrage that the boy is not already back in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   One opposing view is the bilingual libertyforelian.org site,
featuring photos and a pre-recorded e-mail message to Clinton and
the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Web site thesmokinggun.com contains official documents
pertaining to the case. The name ``Gonzalez'' has been mentioned in
10,913 Web pages found on Yahoo, mostly in reprints of newspaper
articles and/or photos.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, we can only say, in the unforgettable words of
boxer Roberto Duran, no mas.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
