<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-OVERLOAD-1800(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL ELIAN, ALL THE TIME. STOP, POR FAVOR!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of COURSE we want the world's most famous 6-year-old to be safe
and happy.
</P>
<P>
   Of COURSE we wish only the best for Elian Gonzalez and his cute
little puppy.
</P>
<P>
   Of COURSE. We may be reporters, but we're not heartless.
</P>
<P>
   But E-NOUGH already. We've had our fill of the saga of Elian
Gonzalez, and we suspect that many other Americans have, too.
</P>
<P>
   After a soap-opera-like five months, highlighted by the armed
federal raid last weekend _ ordered by Attorney General Janet Reno
_ that spirited the boy from the home of his Miami relatives and
reunited him with his father, the saga of the child/political
football has long since reached saturation point.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take a look at how the print, broadcast and electronic
news media have covered All Things Elian:
</P>
<P>
   Print coverage has been led, as you might expect, by ``The Miami
Herald,'' which has printed 92 stories and dozens of court records
just in one week (April 17 to 24).
</P>
<P>
   The big days were Saturday (22 stories) and Sunday (23 stories).
The paper's coverage was so extensive that it included coverage of
reporters covering the events _ lowlighted by an ugly incident
involving a ``New York Post'' reporter accused of stabbing a local
cameraman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Herald'' columnist/novelist Carl Hiassen has written the most
incisive columns on the issue. Hiassen's clear tone has cut to the
core of several aspects of the case.
</P>
<P>
   In the same seven-day period, ``The New York Times'' did 32
stories, put the story on the front page five times, and did seven
columns or editorials; the ``New York Post'' printed 31 stories,
devoted Page One space to the story three times, and ran nine
columns; and the ``Star-Telegram'' ran 18 stories and had the story
on Page One three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time'' has put Elian on its cover three times, the latest
being this week's `` `Papa!,' '' which contained three stories. The
Jan. 17 headline was ``Where Does He Belong?'' and the April 17
cover story looked at ``Elian and His Dad.'' The magazine has run
38 stories, columns and info boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newsweek'' has been a bit less Elian-mad: He's made the cover
twice _ this week's ``Seizing Elian'' and April 17's ``Elian's
Ordeal'' _ and has been mentioned in stories 24 times.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's not funny, the Elian saga has certainly inspired a
bevy of quips from the likes of David Letterman, Jay Leno and Conan
O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman's April 6 Top Ten list was ``Top Ten Things Elian
Gonzalez's Dad Said His First Day in the United States.'' That was
funny, but Monday night's ``Top Ten Janet Reno Pet Peeves'' was
better:
</P>
<P>
   10. Having to brush up on Spanish just to read hate mail.
</P>
<P>
   9. Armed troops plus civilian resistance equals paperwork,
paperwork, paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   8. In the Elian TV movie, she'll probably be played by John
Lithgow.
</P>
<P>
   7. When she gets angry, she turns green and muscles burst
through clothes just dry-cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   6. No one believes, ``It was a chocolate gun pointed at Elian's
head.''
</P>
<P>
   5. Whenever she calls ``Playboy'' and offers to pose, Hefner's
``in a meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   4. Saying, ``It's the tear gas'' when crying at ``Erin
Brockovich.''
</P>
<P>
   3. When Lenscrafters runs out of gigantic, outdated, poorly
fitted frames.
</P>
<P>
   2. Men who feel inadequate when she brings battering ram into
bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   1. Constant political pressure to reunite Hall and Oates.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Leno, meanwhile, mentions Elian just about every night _ and
definitely on nights when there's been a significant development.
He has also done two skits involving the story: In one, he created
a fictitious program called ``Tonightline'' and played Ted Koppel,
interviewing actors looking like Reno and Elian's father, Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, and the boy's great uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez.
Gilbert Gottfried played Elian. In another, a spoof of the new
movie ``U-571,'' he played Bill Paxton's character; looking through
the periscope, he saw Elian on a raft. He also referred to Reno's
warning to the Miami relatives as ``Livin' La Vida Waco.''
</P>
<P>
   But the funniest stuff may be Michael Moore's open
letter/apology to Elian, which he posted on his site
(michaelmoore.com) March 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please forgive me for writing to you in English,'' the letter
begins. ``Three semesters of Spanish, and I can't remember a
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He goes on to criticize the Miami relatives and America's
foreign policy toward Cuba. A few choice moments:
</P>
<P>
   ``You are with a `great-uncle' and a `second cousin.' It's not
that they aren't blood-related but, let's face it, in our country
they and the third cousins-once removed are usually not sitting at
the Thanksgiving table and are only rarely heard from, when they
need bail money or part of the inheritance.''
</P>
<P>
   And:
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst that could be said is that, in Cuba, you were in
jeopardy of receiving free health care whenever you needed it, an
excellent education in one of the few countries that has 100
percent literacy, and a better chance of your baby brother being
born and making it to his first birthday than if he had been born
in Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore ends his letter by hoping that Elian can come back to
America by the time he's 18 _ the Detroit Tigers, he notes, ``will
still be in desperate need of some good pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   TV coverage has been extensive, and nowhere more than at ABC's
``Nightline,'' which has done six segments on Elian since April 6,
the most recent being Monday night's Ted Koppel/Janet Reno
interview. Previous segments this month were run April 6, 7, 12, 13
and 19. MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
