<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7870 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TRISHA-BROWN-DANCE-2T     04-26 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRISHA-BROWN-DANCE-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILLING THE STAGE WITH HER INVENTIONS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 30) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.C.)   By VALERIE GLADSTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sometimes the choreographer Trisha Brown likes to
dance an answer to a question.
</P>
<P>
   Looking elegant in a long, simple black dress on a late March
weekend, she rises to her feet to show how close her dancers come
to one another in ``Five Part Weather Invention,'' the first
section of a new three-part collaboration with the jazz composer
Dave Douglas, the visual artist Terry Winters and the lighting
designer Jennifer Tipton.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly she raises her arms above her head and then draws them
down close to her face as she gives her demonstration in a small
space between the rustic wooden table in the kitchen of her SoHo
loft and the sparsely furnished living area.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get as close as weather,'' she says, her tall willowy
body curving like Saharan dunes. ``That's why the name.'' Even
though Douglas' score is not playing, its joyful spirit permeates
her movements.
</P>
<P>
   Across the room on the windowsill a couple of leafy plants soak
up the midday sun. The only other color comes from two yellow
captain's chairs and a clear glass vase full of bright orange
anemones, although a big, green porcelain ring gleams on Brown's
left hand.
</P>
<P>
   It's an appropriate setting for the 63-year-old choreographer,
whose finely structured dances unexpectedly overflow with life. Her
impromptu dance finished, she sits down to nibble on a croissant
and pour herself a cup of Georgian tea, a gift from her 35-year-old
son, Adam. He and her husband, the video artist Burt Barr, have
gone to the family's house in the Hamptons, leaving her to work.
</P>
<P>
   Both this piece and ``Rapture to Leon James,'' the second part,
will have their New York premieres when her 12-member troupe
celebrates its 30th anniversary with a two-week engagement at the
Joyce Theater, beginning on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the complete trilogy will be presented at the American
Dance Festival in North Carolina, which commissioned ``Rapture''
and the last untitled section. The first week at the Joyce, ``Five
Part Weather Invention'' will be accompanied by a recording, and
the following week Douglas and his Charms of the Night Sky ensemble
will play for ``Rapture.''
</P>
<P>
   The program also features three solos performed by Brown, a new
piece for the company and a film by Jonathan Demme. At the
company's gala on May 14, Mikhail Baryshnikov will dance her new
version of ``Homemade'' (1965).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hell bent right now,'' Brown says. ``The learning curve is
stretched so tight it's twanging. I'm discovering, questioning,
looking for solutions. I want to get out as much work as
possible.'' She smiles broadly and remarks, almost as an aside,
that she has changed. ``It's not surprising,'' she says. ``After
all, I've been a wife, a mother, a dancer, a choreographer, a
citizen in a radically changing world. I'm in my seventh decade.
Over time one gets rewritten by experience _ by loss, by death, by
accidents. All these things have made me think a lot about emotion,
about the shape of emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been Brown's gift over the years to incorporate a myriad
of influences without ever losing her striking identity.
Surprisingly, she did have a few old-fashioned dance moments
growing up in Aberdeen, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did she take classes in tap and ballet, but she and her
older brother, Gordon, also acted out Broadway routines, imitating
the famous hoofers Marge and Gower Champion in the privacy of their
home. ``He owed me,'' she says. ``I played football with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long after graduating from Mills College in Oakland, Calif.,
in 1958, she arrived in New York and wholeheartedly joined the
revolutionary Judson Dance Theater group. Setting out to do nothing
less than expand the dance vocabulary, she chose Merce Cunningham,
Robert Dunn and Louis Horst as her guides. ``I'd decided as a
child,'' she says, ``that I wanted to make a mark.''
</P>
<P>
   In the process of exploring the relationships between movement,
space and sound, she invented dances from simple skips, jumps and
runs and set some of them on roofs and floating rafts. In
``Equipment Pieces'' in the late '60s, she juxtaposed natural
movement with mechanical equipment; she based ``Accumulations'' in
the '70s on mathematical systems.
</P>
<P>
   In time, she produced larger theatrical works, combining forces
with the artists Robert Rauschenberg and Donald Judd and the
composers John Cage and Laurie Anderson. New York's downtown art
scene was flourishing and she thrived on it. While several years
passed before she gained substantial audience and financial
support, both grew in the '80s and in 1991 she became the first
female choreographer to win a MacArthur Fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   Totally committed to experimentation and to dancing only in
silence or to soundscapes, Brown startled her fans five years ago
by beginning to choreograph to classical music, opera and jazz.
``Choreographing to music is something expected in the dance
world,'' she says. ``I had to try it and see if I could keep music
from dominating my choreography _ one reason I never had used it.
Music is so authoritarian.'' She had gotten a taste for working
with a score when she choreographed and danced in Lina Wertmuller's
production of the opera ``Carmen'' in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Although her goal was to return to opera, she approached it
indirectly through the music of Bach and Webern. For the first
time, she studied a polyphonic score. The pleasing result was
``M.O.,'' set to Bach's ``Musical Offering'' (1995). ``I discovered
dance could throw light into music,'' she says, ``and cause you to
hear it differently, and I saw that dance becomes illuminated in
the process.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, she choreographed ``Twelve-Ton Rose,'' to Webern's
Opuses 5 and 28, described by Jennifer Dunning in The New York
Times as filled ``with mystery and beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   She finally got her chance at opera when the Theatre Royal de la
Monnaie in Brussels invited her to direct and choreograph
Monteverdi's ``Orfeo,'' considered the first important opera in
Western music. With this work, she came to terms with narrative and
character.
</P>
<P>
   ``To develop the characters emotionally,'' she says, ``I had to
delve into my own emotional experiences. At first, I wasn't sure I
could.'' A critical success at its premiere in May 1998 in
Brussels, ``Orfeo'' had its American premiere at the Brooklyn
Academy of Music in June. ``Canto/Pianto,'' a series of formal
dances drawn from the production, will have its New York premiere
at the Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   Next spring, she will direct the contemporary opera ``Luci Mie
Traditrici'' (``My Betraying Eyes'') by Salvatore Sciarrino at the
Monnaie. It comes to the Lincoln Center Festival next summer.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the influence classical music has recently had on
Brown, nothing matches the effect of African-American social dance.
More than anything, it has prompted her to be much more
transparently emotional. She speaks with awe of Leon James, a famed
dancer at Harlem's Savoy Ballroom in the '30s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was dancing in a line with five or six other men,'' she
says, describing a film she saw three years ago, ``clearly the
leader, clearly doing African-based movement, performing a cagey,
rhythmical pattern with his hands and feet, and surveying the line,
with the biggest smile. He was the picture of ecstasy. How he
looked is why I dance.'' ``Rapture to Leon James'' had its premiere
at the Kennedy Center in Washington in February.
</P>
<P>
   Although James inspired Brown's entire jazz trilogy, she did not
begin it with her tribute to him but with ``Five Part Weather
Invention,'' which was commissioned by the Jacob's Pillow Dance
Festival in Massachusetts and was first seen there last summer.
Douglas' music provided a perfect complement to her ideas for the
works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trisha has a deep understanding of the music,'' he says,
``perhaps deeper than I have. I'd write a section thinking I was
giving her something specific and she'd come up with something very
different. She opens up the music in ways I couldn't have
imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   Jazz encouraged Brown's natural style of movement. ``Isolated
gestures and undulating spine are my cup of tea,'' she says. ``We
boogie.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown often starts a piece by showing her dancers drawings of
what she wants. But with ``Five Part Weather Invention,'' she began
by asking Kathleen Fisher, a longtime company member, to put
together scraps of movement. Giving her dancers tasks to perform is
one of her basic working methods. ``Kathleen just took off, mixing
them up in such amazingly beautiful ways,'' she says, exclaiming,
``She's a Cuisinart, a veritable Cuisinart.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher had no idea she had succeeded. ``I do it differently
every time,'' she says, ``because every time I respond differently
to the musicians and to the set. Terry's drawings inspire me to
invent all kinds of gestures,'' she adds, speaking of the set
designs by Winters. Fisher sees the new freedom Brown gives her
dancers as a broadening of her expression. ``But Trisha will never
be literal,'' she says. ``When you're abstract, there's a lot more
room for metaphor and a much better chance of being universal.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Brown is after. ``I would hope my choreographies are
perfectly constructed and filled with life,'' she says, ``and
people would see in them models for their own lives.'' Suddenly
self-conscious after this declaration, she quickly switches the
conversation to how much longer she'll perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forever,'' she laughs, ``like Merce. He's the man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
