<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7874 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER27-COX     04-26 2205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: The wine and food better be pretty good
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush's first fund-raising effort for the Republican
Party will collect a record $18 million at a black-tie gala
Wednesday night in Washington boasting a guest list that reads like
a Who's Who of interests with business before the government. AT&AMP;T,
the NRA and tobacco giant Philip Morris are just a few of the
companies and groups that will wine and dine with Bush and GOP
lawmakers. In all, 38 companies or individuals raised or donated at
least a quarter-million dollars for the Republican National
Committee, and an additional 16 shelled out at least $100,000,
according to a donor list obtained by The Associated Press. One
co-chairman, who raised or contributed at least $250,000, is
Kenneth Lay, head of the Texas-based energy giant Enron Corp. The
previous record for a political party in a single night was $14
million last year when Bush's father, the former president,
headlined the same event.
</P>
<P>
   A LITTLE STATESMANSHIP FOR AN APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Before attending Wednesday night's GOP gala affair, George W.
Bush, whose foreign policy credentials have been questioned by
critics, met with Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, in
Washington to see President Clinton and other U.S. officials. Bush
and Ivanov talked of peace and progress though still disagreeing
over U.S. proposals to build a national missile defense system.
Bush and his wife, Laura, were also the keynote speakers on a
midday panel at a conference of Republican women leaders. In
addition, Bush met Wednesday with Sen. Bob Kerrey (D-Neb.) to
discuss Social Security policy, a session advisers hoped would
highlight the Texas governor's pledge to bring a bipartisan spirit
to Washington. Cox News Service's Jena Heath and Ken Herman report
that Bush's speech Wednesday night will have an end-the-gridlock
message centering on ``changing the tone in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   GUNNING FOR GLORY
</P>
<P>
   Wayne LaPierre, who runs the National Rifle Association, will
have a seat at the big spenders' table by virtue of his
organization's $250,000 pledge, The New York Times reports. In
fund-raising letters to its membership, the NRA has touted George
W. Bush's support of concealed-gun laws, asking members to
encourage him ``to continue his strong stance in favor of your
Second Amendment rights.'' The NRA also has switched from
hard-money donations to candidates to a ``soft money'' strategy,
the Times said, giving $540,000 to Republican Party election
committees this year. Bush campaign spokesman Ari Fleischer said
his boss couldn't be happier than to be an NRA-backed candidate.
</P>
<P>
   HE'S NOT A REAL DOCTOR, BUT HE GOES TO DRUGSTORES
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore campaigned for increased government health care help for
the elderly Wednesday, standing with a 65-year-old woman and her
monthly supply of drugs at a pharmacy in East Hartford, Conn.
Shirley Kindle of Ansonia accompanied Gore to Pelton's drugstore
earlier for what he called ``an illustration'' for invited news
cameras: pharmacist Hal Schoen lining up on the counter Kindle's 12
different prescriptions and ringing up the total to $506.34. Kindle
told Gore the amount was ``more than I get from Social Security.''
She said her husband made a little too much money to qualify for
government assistance, at which point Gore chimed in: ``She was
advised if they got divorced she'd be eligible for some low-income
assistance, but she said after 35 years she's really not ready to
give him up.''
</P>
<P>
   MILKING THE UPSTATE FARM VOTE
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton said Wednesday that farmers should be
given more breaks on estate taxes so businesses can be kept in the
family. Visiting a century-old dairy farm in Sheldon, N.Y., near
Buffalo, she said the exemption on family farms and family-owned
businesses should be raised to $1.75 million, up from the current
$600,000. (That figure is scheduled to rise to $1 million by 2006.)
As some of the farm's 289 cows mooed in the background, the Senate
candidate said she would work to lower utility and labor costs, and
other taxes that make farming difficult in New York.
</P>
<P>
   HEY, GUYS, THAT WASN'T INTENDED FOR YOU
</P>
<P>
   New York Senate candidate Rudy Giuliani said he wouldn't
apologize for characterizing the federal agents who seized Elian
Gonzalez as ``storm troopers,'' adding that it was ``an appropriate
criticism'' directed not at the agents but at President Clinton and
Attorney General Janet Reno. ``I'm not going to back down from
it,'' Giuliani said at Shea Stadium. ``I've been involved in law
enforcement for a very long time. I've never seen a situation in
which a 6-year-old was removed in that way.'' But Giuliani took
care to say that the term ``was not intended as a criticism of the
particular law enforcement officers carrying out the mission.''
Earlier, the Federal Law Enforcement Officers Association, a
nonpartisan group representing 17,500 federal agents and officers,
expressed ``strong disgust and dismay'' with the labeling of the
officers as storm troopers.
</P>
<P>
   RUDY RUNNING WELL UPSTATE
</P>
<P>
   A new poll conducted by Zogby International for Colgate
University shows that Rudy Giuliani ``appears on his way to
controlling the upstate vote in his bid for the U.S. Senate,'' the
Washington Times reported. The poll, with a margin of error of 3.2
percentage points, shows Giuliani leading Hillary Clinton by 14.
Fifty-two percent of those polled said they would vote for
Giuliani, although Clinton has a slight lead in the state's
cities.``Giuliani is right where he needs to be right now,'' Zogby
said. ``But Hillary is campaigning vigorously in those cities,
where 40 percent of the vote is.''
</P>
<P>
   THE OTHER SIDE OF THE GENDER GAP
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has seen George W. Bush cut into the Democrats'
traditional support among female voters, but Gore also finds
himself distantly trailing Bush among men _ a situation that has
gotten less attention but presents a fundamental hurdle in White
House bid. In the latest USA Today-CNN-Gallup Poll, Gore and Bush
split the female vote evenly, but Bush led among men by 17 points _
and among white men by 26 points: 59 percent to 33 percent. USA
Today reported that independent pollsters calculate that Gore, to
win in November, must cut that gap among white men in half. Even
though he would still trail among men, he could win if he built an
advantage among white women and generated strong turnout among
African-Americans, the Democratic Party's most loyal supporters.
</P>
<P>
   TRYING TO CHANGE THE CONGRESSIONAL ENVIRONMENT
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to make the environment a bigger political issue, the
Sierra Club began an $8 million TV and radio campaign aimed at five
Senate and 12 House races. The ads will be combined with other
activities, including voter guides and fliers at community events,
as the group attempts to elect a more pro-environment Congress. The
ads attack the environmental records of six Republican candidates
and praise those of 10 Democrats. Only one Republican, Rep.
Christopher Shays of Connecticut, is singled out for praise. Since
1996, Cox's Ken Foskett reports, the Sierra Club has become one of
the most aggressive and effective practitioners of unregulated
issue advertising in political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH ATTACK, TIMES TWO
</P>
<P>
   An early Al Gore counterpunch to the George W. Bush compassion
campaign will be to remind voters of the deficits rung up under the
last Republican administration, according to The New York Times.
Gore said that eliminating the national debt by 2013 is a top
priority and warned Americans against the debtor days of Ronald
Reagan and George H.W. Bush, W's father. ``This is a test of our
memory,'' Gore was quoted as saying. ``Have we forgotten the
dangers of irresponsibility? Have we forgotten the virtues of
responsibility?''
</P>
<P>
   BRING ON THE `CYBER DEBATES'
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of a new nonpartisan political Web site hope it will be
the host for daily ``cyber debates'' between the presidential
campaigns this fall. The Markle Foundation is joining with 16
Internet traffic centers to produce Web White &AMP; Blue 2000, which
will also have links to political news and information furnished by
the participants. They include Internet giants America Online,
Microsoft and Yahoo!, major TV networks and some of the nation's
largest newspapers. ``The Web White &AMP; Blue 2000 sites will be a
collective resource for voters, for journalists and for those
citizens who usually sit on the sidelines,'' said Zoe Baird,
president of the foundation. The daily debates are scheduled to
begin in October at www.webwhiteblue.org
</P>
<P>
   BLACK FAVORITE IN THE BLUEGRASS
</P>
<P>
   A Louisville lawyer dropped his primary campaign against a woman
vying to become Kentucky's first black member of Congress. Ched
Jennings said he couldn't keep up with state Rep. Eleanor Jordan in
raising money. Jordan pulled ahead after getting endorsements from
Gov. Paul Patton, the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee
and some key labor groups. Jordan, the only African-American woman
in the Kentucky General Assembly, now has only minor opposition for
the May 23 Democratic primary. The Louisville-area district is
almost one-fifth black. Jordan is trying to unseat two-term
Republican Rep. Anne Northup. Republicans hold five of the state's
six congressional seats.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY GET YOUR GUN
</P>
<P>
   Chicago police have recovered a gun stolen from a Secret Service
agent assigned to protect Hillary Rodham Clinton last October. The
gun ``allegedly landed in the hands of a heroin addict who has been
arrested 33 times,'' according to the Chicago Sun-Times. The agent,
Mary Drury, was sitting at the bar in Chicago's Fairmont hotel when
the weapon was taken from her purse. The Sun-Times said the Secret
Service would not say whether Drury was drinking at the time: Drury
was ``protecting the first lady at the Fairmont that day, but, for
security reasons, officials declined to say whether Clinton had a
room there.''
</P>
<P>
   DOUBTS ABOUT HILLARY'S DONORS
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani, in the wake of an Albany Times Union report
showing that Hillary Rodham Clinton has a higher rate of in-state
donations, has accused Clinton of concealing her ``soft money''
donors. Giuliani spokesman Bruce Teitelbaum said Clinton is hiding
unsavory givers by shifting money from her campaign accounts to
Democratic Party accounts that accept soft money. ``They hide it in
this committee and then they transfer it,'' Teitelbaum said. ``This
is classic Clintonian mathematics.'' The Times Union said its
analysis of contributions covered hard money, and did not examine
the soft-money donations to either Clinton or Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   SMALL CROWDS FOR BUCHANAN
</P>
<P>
   On a campaign swing through Baton Rouge, La., that drew a total
of about 100 listeners at two events, Pat Buchanan talked about
trade with China, illegal immigration and the Elian Gonzalez
matter. On the Elian matter: ``It's a sad day in America when a
little boy whose mother dies trying to bring him to freedom in the
United States is picked up at gunpoint to bring him back to Fidel
Castro.'' The Baton Rouge Advocate reported that when asked if his
third-party bid would ``hand the White House to Gore,'' Buchanan
said, ``Conservatism is more than Clinton-bashing. People come up
to me and say, `You don't want Gore (to win), do you?' But no one
comes up to me talking about how excited they are about the dawn of
the George W. era.''
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-PRIORITY DISTRICT IN INDIANA
</P>
<P>
   An Indiana congressional seat that was held by the Democrats for
20 years before going into the GOP column with Newt Gingrich's
Republican Revolution six years ago is up for grabs in a wide-open,
11-candidate primary. By November, both parties could spend $2
million on the House seat, now held by conservative third-term Rep.
David McIntosh, who's stepping down to run for governor. Six
Republicans and five Democrats are vying for their parties'
nomination May 2. The GOP front-runners are former radio host Mike
Pence, who has strong name recognition, and state Rep. Jeff Linder,
who leads in fund-raising _ more than $291,000 as of March 31.
Indiana Democratic Party spokesman Doug Davidoff said there's no
clear front-runner in his party.
</P>
<P>
   HARD NUMBERS ON SOFT MONEY
</P>
<P>
   The raising of lightly regulated campaign ``soft money''
campaign money picked up speed in the first quarter of 2000 for
Democrats and Republicans. From Jan. 1 to March 31, Democrats
raised $26.7 million in soft money donations and Republicans took
in $27 million. In all of 1999, the Democrats raised $49.4 million
in soft dollars and the Republicans raised $57.8 million. In the
first quarter of 2000, 104 donors gave more than $100,000,
according to Public Disclosure, a Washington firm that tracks
donations, and 21 gave more than $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from Cox staff and wire reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
