<HEADER>
A7876 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      04-26 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET THE EMPEROR'S NEW CLOTHES: ATTACK BOOKS GO WAY BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``He was excessively lustful. His constant sexual intercourse he
called bed-wrestling, as if it were a kind of exercise.'' Yet
another fresh cut about the president? No, this was from Suetonius'
biography of the Roman emperor Domitian, published circa A.D. 100.
It apparently sold pretty well then, and it's still in print. It
bashed the guy. Beating up on the subject works; it did then, and
it does now.
</P>
<P>
   Such books are more or less publishing's equivalent of negative
campaign ads; and while publishers say they don't like them (just
as candidates claim to dislike negative campaigning), they keep
buying them and publishing them. There's another similarity with
the ads. For these books to succeed, there has to be a large,
militant anti-constituency for which there is nothing so
extravagant that can be said about the politician they hate or
disdain that the writer's words wouldn't be gobbled up like salted
peanuts. (Yes, Jefferson and Lincoln were relentlessly attacked in
newspapers, but a quick check failed to uncover contemporary books
that went after them.)
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, there were an awful lot of Romans who didn't like
Domitian. And Plutarch's great biographies were richly anecdotal,
but his accounts were not always known for their accuracy. So the
attack book has a lusty tradition. Therefore it is hardly
surprising that two such books in that formula, one by an
intoxicant from the right and another by a reveler from the left,
are selling well. Indeed, Peggy Noonan's ``Case Against Hillary
Clinton'' (ReganBooks/HarperCollins), a polemic, will be No. 4 on
The New York Times' best-seller list on May 4. And ``Shrub: The
Short but Happy Political Life of George W. Bush'' (Random House)
by Molly Ivins and Lou Dubose will remain on The Times' extended
list.
</P>
<P>
   For those publishers who cannot resist political-celebrity
books, little is more lamented than the paying of a goodly advance
for a book because of the prominence of the subject (e.g., a
politician constantly in the news) and then having that book fail
in the marketplace. With few notable exceptions that's what happens
and nearly always has. In this genre, John McCain's ``Faith of My
Fathers'' (Random House), Bill Bradley's ``Values of the Game''
(Artisan) and others that became best sellers were aberrant.
</P>
<P>
   Within the genre, if it can actually be called that, there seems
to be a bottomless pit for anti-Clinton books, despite the success
of Jeffrey Toobin's opposite tack in ``A Vast Conspiracy'' (Random
House). Thus it follows that with the retirement of President
Clinton, the election of Hillary Rodham Clinton to the Senate would
appear to be pretty nearly essential to the economic well-being of
book publishing.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, at last count there were more than three dozen
books about Clinton in print, and more are on the way. Even a
psychoanalytic examination of the first lady, ``Hillary's Choice''
(Random House) by Gail Sheehy, had a brief buzz with her startling
conclusion that Clinton was addicted to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   John Sterling, president and publisher of Henry Holt, said,
``The secret is to identify the constituency and throw them some
red meat, and if you do that there's a good chance you'll sell a
lot of books.'' He added: ``It seems to be that if you really hate
the politician, you buy the books to get all riled up; it's a great
feeling to get all riled up. Just like the media finds stories for
people who want to get angry. It's a matter of identifying your
book buyers for the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Sterling said that for years the conventional wisdom had been
that political attack books worked only for readers who were
politically conservative _ this started with ``The Way Things Ought
to Be'' by Rush Limbaugh (Pocket Books, 1993) _ ``but now you have
Molly Ivins' book selling well to people who have very strong
feelings about the presumptive Republican nominee.'' Sterling
hasn't published what he calls ``the red meat'' political book but
did publish Al Gore's best-selling ``Earth in the Balance'' at
Houghton Mifflin in 1992, which is being reissued. ``A lot of books
succeed because they have a strong ideological point of view,'' he
said, ``but I don't know if we can put out an endless number in the
genre and succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   David Hirshey, executive editor at Harper/Collins, said he was
going to test whether ``red meat'' is indeed the necessary
ingredient for success in a political book. He is publishing
``Truth at Any Cost: Ken Starr and the Unmaking of Bill Clinton''
by Susan Schmidt and Michael Weisskopf, which arrived in bookstores
this week. It has a first printing of 60,000 copies, a healthy
number for such a book. ``It presents Starr, warts and all; the
reader will be like a fly on the wall in Starr's office, and learn
a lot about what went on in his mind,'' Hirshey said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, polemical books seem to have all the velocity these day,
like those attack ads. Nonetheless, Hirshey said: ``I hope we
didn't hurt its commercial potential by making it as balanced we
could. I think this will be an interesting litmus test, whether a
book about a highly charged political figure that is not a hate
book can succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows how many sesterces Suetonius' monumental ``Lives of
the Caesars'' earned? What is clear, however, is that his capacity
for compelling prose was considerably heightened by tales of
cruelty and avarice rather than by dignity and gentleness. Quite
modern really.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
