<HEADLINE>
BOOKS FOR LITTLE GARDENERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SANDY GUERRA-CLINE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This spring, you can go from watching your kids grow to watching
your kids grow things. And if you're lucky, they'll grow good
things to eat, like tiny tomatoes and crisp lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   Five children's books cover all aspects of the garden patch,
with fun projects to keep little green thumbs busy.
</P>
<P>
   1. ``The Kids Can Press Jumbo Book of Gardening'' by Karyn
Morris (Kids Can Press, $14.95). Gosh, it's pretty much all here _
from composting to ``building'' a sunflower fort _ with a
no-nonsense writing style and really fun illustrations. Neat
projects include a night-blooming garden and a birthday garden,
using the flower symbols for the months of your family's birthdays.
And a good project for dry areas: the Water-Saving Garden.
Recommended for ages 8 and older.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Better Homes and Gardens New Junior Garden Book'' by Felder
Rushing (Meredith Books, $15.95). Wacky illustrations will appeal
to kids, and wonderful projects using recyclables like 2-liter
plastic soda bottles will wow parents and educators. Cool projects
include: planting flowers in an old boot, making decorative
steppingstones with bits of broken tiles and such, and stringing up
wind chimes made from painted soda cans. Projects are on a skill
scale _ from one flower (easy) to three flowers (must drag Dad away
from the TV).
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Dig and Sow: How Do Plants Grow?'' by Janice Lobb
(Kingfisher, $10.95). If you've got a kid who loves to ask things
like ``Why is grass green?'' this is the book for you _ and him.
Part of the ``At Home With Science'' series, this book contains 12
garden-oriented experiments. They're easy and fun, and the
``special equipment'' never gets any more demanding than a
magnifying glass, food coloring and a clean jar. Recommended for
ages 5 and older.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Starting With Nature Plant Book'' by Pamela Hickman (Kids
Can Press, $5.95 in paperback). A fine introduction to plants in
the United States _ from wildflowers to endangered plants. Kids
will enjoy the pages on plant defenses and poisonous plants. Other
books in the series are devoted to bugs, trees and birds. Ages 7 to
11.
</P>
<P>
   5. ``Are You a Ladybug?'' and ``Are You a Snail?'' (Kingfisher,
$9.95 each). Intelligent and easy-to-read, these books are aimed at
preschoolers and beginning readers (with a little help) and stuffed
full of fun facts. Did you know animals and birds won't eat
ladybugs because they taste terrible? You do now!
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
