<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLUING: MORE TO IT THAN YOU THINK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 9 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many beginning woodworkers think that gluing is simple and
straightforward, requiring only squirting glue on mating surfaces,
then clamping the pieces together until the glue cures.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the task is a lot more complicated. First it is
important to use the right glue. While it might seem that all glues
are pretty much alike, they differ in a number of important
properties: cost, convenience, assembly and setting time, and
application.
</P>
<P>
   For woodworkers, the most familiar glue is yellow woodworker's
glue, also called carpenter's glue. It's an aliphatic resin, much
like the household white glue, but it is formulated to dry faster
than white glue. Both white and yellow glue can be sanded after
they dry (although yellow glue does not clog sandpaper as much as
white glue). They both clean up with soap and water, and they have
good holding power.
</P>
<P>
   Neophyte woodworkers may find that the longer drying time of
white glue allows them more time to assemble pieces. As they become
more experienced, they will want to move up to the faster-setting
woodworker's glue.
</P>
<P>
   Another glue that is ideal for woodworkers is liquid hide glue.
It is a favorite with professional furniture manufacturers because
it has a longer setting time than the aliphatic resins. This makes
it a good choice for assembling complicated projects like antique
furniture. Like aliphatic resins, it can be cleaned up with soap
and water.
</P>
<P>
   These glues are fine for indoor applications but they are not
waterproof, so they cannot be used on exterior jobs or projects
that will be exposed to moisture. Here, you will have to switch to
a waterproof glue, like epoxy resin. Epoxy consists of two separate
liquids that must be mixed in equal portions just prior to
application. It takes anywhere from five minutes to five hours to
cure (depending on the formula), and it dries to a rock-hard,
glossy finish. Since it is impervious to water, it is an ideal
bonding agent for putting together window boxes, planters and
outdoor furniture. On the downside, epoxy is difficult to sand and
more expensive than other glues. Epoxy can be cleaned up with
lacquer thinner.
</P>
<P>
   Even the strongest glue will produce a weak joint if it is not
applied correctly. Surface preparation is important. Both gluing
surfaces should be clean, dry and relatively even or else the glue
will not bond properly. This means that newly sawed surfaces must
be smoothed to remove the ridges left by the saw blade. The best
tool to use for this is a plane or a sharp wood chisel. Sandpaper
isn't very good for this because it clogs the wood pores, which
prevents the glue from penetrating.
</P>
<P>
   Before applying the glue, test fit all the pieces together and
inspect all joints for gaps, out-of-square edges and alignment
problems. These flaws should be corrected before spreading any
glue.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest mistake neophyte woodworkers make is in using too
much glue. When the project is clamped together, the excess glue
will ooze from the joints onto the workpiece. Not only will this
require extra cleanup; the glue will penetrate the wood and leave
stains. Unlike ordinary stains that darken and discolor wood
fibers, glue stains are not apparent until a finish or stain is
applied. Then they show up as unsightly light spots where the
finish or stain did not soak in. The only way to remove them by
sanding them out.
</P>
<P>
   The glue should be spread with an applicator in thin layers on
both surfaces. You can use an inexpensive bristle brush, but be
sure to wash the bristles afterward. Low-cost foam paint brushes
and serrated plastic picnic knifes make ideal disposable
applicators. Sometimes it is tempting to spread the glue with your
fingers, but this is not a good practice because you are likely to
put glue fingerprints all over the work surface. No matter how you
spread the glue, keep it at least one-quarter inch from the edges
of the piece.
</P>
<P>
   After applying the glue, wait a few minutes before joining the
pieces. This will minimize slippage when the pieces are pushed
together. Clamp the work and keep the joint under pressure for at
least 24 hours. Be sure to place scraps of wood under the clamp
pads to protect the workpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the surfaces on a piece of wood bond equally well. The
ends of a board, commonly called end grain, are more porous than
the other surfaces. The end grain readily absorbs the glue and
reduces its holding power. When gluing the end of a board to
another surface, it is necessary to reinforce the joint with
dowels, glue blocks or wood screws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
