<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7886 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX     04-26 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALT-COUNTRY'S ROBBIE FULKS VEERS FROM FUNNY TO SERIOUS TO
WORLD-WEARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robbie Fulks' latest CD is called ``The Very Best of Robbie
Fulks,'' and right there we know his cynical sense of humor has not
betrayed him.
</P>
<P>
   First, this is not a greatest-hits collection, because the
37-year-old alternative-country musician has never had any hits;
mainstream country radio stations won't come near him. And second,
even though some of these songs are 10 years old, few have been
released before.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, in a way, the title rings true: ``Very'' is classic
Fulks, which is to say he can be winsomely funny (there are paeans
to actress Jean Arthur and Bangles hottie Susanna Hoffs) and turn
around and do a song such as ``Parallel Bars'' (a duet with Kelly
Willis) that rings with an authentic love of classic honky-tonkers
such as George Jones.
</P>
<P>
   He'll trash self-satisfied retro-rock fans on ``Roots Rock
Weirdos,'' turn right around and write a stinging put-down to an ex
``(I Just Want To Meet the Man)'' and then do a bluegrass
instrumental such as ``Hamilton County Breakdown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like odds-and-ends records, such as Elvis Costello's
``Taking Liberties,'''' says Fulks, munching on a noontime pizza as
his 7-month-old son, Tennessee, (his third child) naps nearby. ``I
realized I wasn't ripping off my fans once I listened to it in
different orders. And I wanted to put out an album this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbie Fulks just doesn't like to be categorized; he'll be
stone-cold serious on one song and sarcastically funny on the next,
and he'll mix different genres.
</P>
<P>
   Which is where ``Weirdos'' _ one of the CD's standouts _ comes
from: When asked if he isn't putting down some of the very people
who go see his shows, he's quick to answer in the affirmative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, definitely!'' he says. ``But that's why it's fun to
do _ it's a much riskier thing to do than just put down Nashville.
My tastes are out of date and old-fashioned, so in a way I'm one of
them. I've always played for a rock audience _ I play country for
noncountry people. I'm never gonna play at a state fair opening for
Lorrie Morgan. I see them as my people, but when they get a little
fussy, I don't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he readily acknowledges that there is a
certain world-weary point of view at work in much of his writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes from being 37 years old and divorced and Southern,''
Fulks says. ``It's a useful tool. Having a jaundiced eye helps you
get through the storms of life. It deepens and broadens as I grow
older.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not just part of my personality. It's also because so
much country is sappy; it's important for me to say, `Let's get
real here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Fulks grew up in Pennyslvania, Virginia and North Carolina, and
in 1983 joined the Chicago-based Special Consensus Bluegrass Band:
That's him on guitar on their Grammy-nominated 1989 CD ``Hole in My
Heart.'' After forming the rock 'n' roll Trailer Trash Revue, he
went solo and released two very entertaining CDs, ``Country Love
Songs'' and ``South Mouth,'' on the Chicago alt-country Bloodshot
label.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 he left, signed with Geffen, and released ``Let's Kill
Saturday Night,'' which had more of a rock/pop feel than
``Country'' or ``South.'' ``Kill'' was a very good CD, but Fulks
was dropped from the label; he re-signed with Bloodshot and
released ``Best'' in January.
</P>
<P>
   But while ``Best'' is often the equal of any of his three
previous CDs, he says it's also a ``capstone'' to the first stage
of his solo career. His next CD, he says, will be ``totally
serious,'' without the cuter songs, such as ``Weirdos.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've done the Bakersfield shuffles and novelty songs
as well as I can,'' Fulks says. ``I'm not going to leave country
behind, but I don't think I need to do another CD of old-sounding
stuff with cussing on it. I don't even think I'll be a footnote in
the country reference books, but I'd like some of the songs to
outlast me _ that's what I'm shooting for.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
