<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7887 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BEACH-FILMS-$ADV30-NY     04-26 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEACH-FILMS-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SUBTEXT BARELY HIDDEN BY THE BEACH BLANKET  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 30) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Boldface ``to'' in 4th graf should be italicized.) 
 David Bahr's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about the
filmmaker Paul Morrissey.  
 By DAVID BAHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Santa could make a list and check it twice, but he would still
have trouble labeling Frankie and Annette naughty or nice. As
moviegoing cats old enough may recall, Frankie Avalon and Annette
Funicello (whose screen name was Dee Dee _ really) cavorted in
cagey camp classics like ``Muscle Beach Party'' (1964), ``Beach
Blanket Bingo'' and ``How to Stuff a Wild Bikini'' (both 1965).
</P>
<P>
   Wearing scanty swimsuits and perky smiles, Frankie and Dee Dee
shook their derrieres and shimmied their shoulders while singing of
love, heartache and going all the way. With a wink-wink and a
nudge-nudge, they wallowed in wordplay with a decidedly suggestive
tang.
</P>
<P>
   Take these lyrics to the theme song of ``Beach Blanket Bingo'':
``Every lad and every lassie/ when they're down by the shore/
looking smart and looking classy/yeah, they're learning the
score.''
</P>
<P>
   Or was that learning  &UR; to &LR;  score? Given all the half-naked
smooching going on during that opening number, it would be an easy
mistake to make. Surely one intended by the filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these movies, it's not always easy to separate what's
innocent from what's a calculated attempt to make everything as
sexual as possible,'' says Robert Lee King, the director of
``Psycho Beach Party,'' an affectionate satire of '60s surf flicks
that is due out in August. ``But I do know the stock and trade of
those movies was innuendo and a lot of heavy breathing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the beach movie genre is generally considered to have
begun with ``Gidget'' (1959) _ starring Sandra Dee as an affable,
late-blooming teen-ager reluctant to go on her first surf-and-sun
``manhunt'' _ it wasn't until the successful release of American
International Pictures' ``Beach Party'' (1963) that film studios
began to fully exploit the economic rewards of niche marketing. And
with two-thirds of all filmgoers being between the ages of 16 and
24 by the late 1950s, the intended target was clear.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanine Basinger, chairman of film studies at Wesleyan
University, says that teen-agers and young adults were a
significant part of Hollywood's intended audience as far back as
the silent film era. The difference is that with films like ``Beach
Party,'' teen-agers were now targeted without the folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Films like `A Date With Judy' and `Two Weeks With Love' were
basically aimed at the teens but also a wider audience,'' Basinger,
referring to movies released in 1948 and 1950, respectively.
``These were family movies. But the beach films specifically went
after kids going to the summer drive-in. They suddenly perceived
they could speak directly to the teen-age psyche.''
</P>
<P>
   As AIP discovered, teen-agers' psyches and their hormones are
often inseparable. And the beach films _ of which there are, gulp,
seven, including ``Bikini Beach'' (1964), ``Pajama Party''(1964)
and ``The Ghost in the Invisible Bikini'' (1966), skillfully
straddled the line between lasciviousness and chastity. Thoroughly
titillating and cornball, they catered both to teen-agers' fleshy
fantasies and to the moral concerns of allowance-providing parents.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the beach films have a schizophrenic feel,
occupying a cinematic place between the virginal heroics of Doris
Day and the permissive culture represented by ``Midnight Cowboy''
(1969) and ``Klute'' (1971). Feminism, homoeroticism and
socioeconomic class conflict are all broached by the beach movies,
only to be buried beneath insipid story lines and fairy tale
endings.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the genre's darker subtext, say the creative talents
behind ``Psycho Beach Party,'' that begged to be explored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to avoid the sort of nostalgia that accompanies most
contemporary movies about that period: that life was so simple back
then,'' says Charles Busch, the New York drag performer who adapted
the screenplay from his Off Broadway play and appears in the film
as the police captain Monica Stark. ``Our take is that maybe life
wasn't so simple and that there always was an active sexuality, of
every kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Basing his script on ``Gidget'' and psychological melodramas
like ``Spellbound'' (1945) and ``Marnie'' (1964), Busch employed
broad camp to soften its rendering of teen-age sexual inadequacy,
closeted homosexuality, mental illness and mass murder. ``There had
to be something childlike about this material or else it would have
been kind of ugly,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Set in Malibu in 1962, ``Psycho Beach Party'' follows the pert
and peppy Chicklet (Lauren Ambrose) in her struggle to become a
surfer; win the guy of her dreams, Starcat (Nicholas Brendon); and
overcome a multiple personality disorder that encompasses a
sadomasochistic dominatrix and a black urban homegirl.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there are subplots about two surfer dudes who can't
stop wrestling, a sexually frustrated mother with a shady past and
a wheelchair-bound vixen with an evil streak. Oh, and there's a
serial killer on the loose.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its silly bent, ``Psycho Beach Party'' definitely
tackles the era's cinematic sexual conflicts. One scene shows the
boyish Starcat detailing his erogenous zones to Chicklet, causing
her to flee in panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to make the audience as conscious of the beach
movies' sexual subtext, and if possible, a little bit
uncomfortable,'' King says. ``We wanted to recreate it and then
take it one step farther. And that fits in exactly with what those
films are about, which is exploring repressed sexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, for many, there's a certain comfort in all those
mixed messages and cheesy double entendres. As Basinger observes,
Frankie and Dee Dee did try to have it both ways and therein lies
their appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, Hollywood has always made a living off
ambiguity and ambivalence,'' she says. ``And these films are a
continuation of that successful formula. You can see these beach
movies lasciviously or innocently, heterosexually or homosexually.
The films make room for that. And that's their genius.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
