<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCKESSON27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McKesson HBOC shares hit 52-week low
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA McKesson HBOC shares hit a 52-week low Wednesday as
reduced sales at its Alpharetta-based health-care information
technology unit hurt earnings for the fifth consecutive quarter.
</P>
<P>
   McKesson's fourth-quarter profit from continuing operations,
before special items, fell 52 percent to $61.4 million, or 22 cents
a share, from $127.1 million, or 45 cents, the year-ago quarter.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco-based McKesson missed the average estimate of 29
cents by analysts polled by First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Shares dropped to a 52-week low of $16.68 before closing at $17,
down $1.93 in heavy New York Stock Exchange trading.
</P>
<P>
   McKesson's overall sales rose to $9.3 billion from $8.3 billion
for the same period in 1999. But sales at the software and services
unit, which employs about 2,000 here, fell 29 percent, with
software revenues alone tumbling 48 percent. The unit's operating
profit dropped to $15.3 million from $68.7 million in the quarter a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, McKesson, the leading U.S. drug wholesaler,
recorded a pre-tax charge of $229.9 million in the quarter related
to its recently announced suspension of some health-care software
products. The software revamp also led to 260 job cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blame the decline in our profitability solely on the
performance of our information technology business,'' said McKesson
spokesman Larry Kurtz. The operating profit from its supply
management business also dropped 16 percent, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Michael Krensavage of Brown Brothers Harriman said, ``It
was another disappointing quarter. The turnaround is not completed,
that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's troubling that problems at HBOC have affected the
distribution business as well,'' Krensavage added.
</P>
<P>
   Financial trouble has continued to swirl around the former
Atlanta-based HBO &AMP; Co. business since McKesson acquired it in
January 1999. Accounting improprieties found at the unit led
McKesson to restate fiscal 1999 earnings by $152.2 million. The
announcement of accounting problems a year ago sent the share price
plunging almost 50 percent in one trading day.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholder lawsuits and government investigations followed. An
executive shakeup included the firing of Chairman Charlie McCall,
who had spearheaded HBO &AMP; Co.'s rise to become the leading
health-care software and services firm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
