<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7891 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-CAPITAL-HNS &LR;      04-26 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAPITAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH DOES WASHINGTON FOR FIRST TIME AS CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush made the rounds in the
nation's capital for the first time as the likely Republican
presidential nominee, meeting Russia's foreign minister, appealing
for the women's vote, and replenishing the GOP's financial war
chest.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was the centerpiece of a black-tie gala that raised a
record $15 million for the Republican National Committee. The
previous record for a political party's take in a single evening
was $14 million, raised last year when the candidate's father,
former President George Bush, headlined the GOP gala.
</P>
<P>
   The money will help Republicans run television ads this fall
that take aim at Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive Democratic
nominee, without directly endorsing Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will win the White House; we will hold the House; we will
hold the Senate,'' Bush said in remarks prepared for delivery at
the gala. ``And come January, Vice President Al Gore will have one
last official duty: To swear in Senator Rudolph Giuliani of New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is fighting First Lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton in a titanic struggle to succeed Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y., who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   The gala gave Bush his first opportunity as the all-but-official
GOP presidential nominee to address the Republican Party
establishment and its business-oriented backers. The event featured
high-profile Republicans, including Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott of Mississippi and House Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois,
and business contributors from AT&AMP;T, the Philip Morris Cos., and
United Parcel Service.
</P>
<P>
   With National Rifle Association executive vice president Wayne
LaPierre serving as the gala's co-chair, Bush's appearance drew
Democratic fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much for George W. Bush's moderate makeover,'' said Gore
campaign press secretary Chris Lehane. ``Time and time again, when
he's had to choose between the gun lobby and our children, he has
stood with the gun lobby. He has supported guns in churches, and
opposed closing the gun show loophole.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bush said LaPierre's role in the gala did not
trouble him in the least. ``I know what I believe,'' he told
reporters. ``I support reasonable laws to keep the guns out of the
hands of people who shouldn't have them. I believe we ought to
enforce the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Bush met with Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov, who was in Washington for meetings with President Clinton
and other U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in his second term as governor of Texas, is potentially
vulnerable to critics' charges that he is a lightweight on foreign
policy. The meeting with Ivanov game him a chance to ``talk with
him about some of the views he's expressed on the campaign trail,''
according to Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among these was Bush's support for rolling back the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty, which prohibits both nations from
creating shields of defensive weapons to shoot down incoming
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Russia adamantly opposes any such changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a matter of principle, my job as president is to provide
stability in the world, to protect our homeland and our citizens,''
Bush told Ivanov, according to Hughes. ``I don't view your country
as the enemy, and you should not view our country as the enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the two had ``a very frank, a very forthright''
discussion, adding that Ivanov ``made his country's position
clear'' on revisions to the ABM treaty.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to build an image of bipartisanship amid the
constant back-and-forth with Gore, Bush met with Sen. Bob Kerrey,
D-Neb., and Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., to talk about preserving
Social Security. Earlier in the week, Bush took four Democratic
Texas legislators _ all Bush supporters _ to a campaign event in
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``recognizes that solving problems as president requires a
bipartisan effort,'' Hughes said. ``Today he began that process by
meeting with Republican and a Democrat to discuss an area that's
going to require a bipartisan consensus Social Security reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in an appearance calculated to bolster Bush's appeal to
women voters, Bush also attended the Republican Women Leaders Forum
with his wife, Laura.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the usual podium, Bush spoke from a livingroom-style
stage set that resembled a daytime television talk show. Flanked by
leading Republican lawmakers, Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas
and Rep. Jennifer Dunn of Washington, Bush talked about his efforts
to improve educational standards in Texas, and his determination to
be a president ``that our children can respect,'' as Dunn put it.
</P>
<P>
   With polls showing moral values as a top concern of voters, Bush
is engaged in a not-so-subtle effort to contrast his character and
23-year marriage to those of the impeachment-bruised president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country needs a leader who will bring honor and dignity to
the White House and, in turn, ask for the best from American,''
Bush told the Republican women's gathering.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Democrats dismissed Bush's strategy as an effort to make it
appear as though he's running against Clinton, not Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who knows Al and Tipper Gore knows what a strong moral
guy Gore is and how committed he is to his family,'' said Jennie
Backus, spokeswoman for the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Among women voters, Gore narrowly leads in most polls. But
Bush's appeal to women far surpasses that of the 1996 Republican
candidate, former Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll earlier this month by Emily's List, which raises money
for female Democratic candidates who favor abortion rights, Gore
led Bush in a sample of women voters 44 percent to 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But among white married mothers with children at home _ a
variation of the ``soccer moms'' who dominated the polling world in
1996 _ Bush is ahead of Gore 47 percent to 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The polls prove that although women voters have favored
Democrats in the past two presidential elections, ``we are not
one-size-fits all,'' said Republican co-chair Patricia Harrison.
``That doesn't work with bathing suits, and it certainly does not
work with women.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
