<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7898 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-MARKERS-NYT     04-26 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MARKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET GIVES HIGHWAY PHOTOS A WAY TO BE SEEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Circuits)  
 By MICHAEL POLLAK  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thanks to the Internet, a 42-year-old engineer from
Texas named Matt Frondorf has done the impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Frondorf's highway snapshots of his coast-to-coast auto trip
have been put on the Web, singly and in slide-movie form, and
instead of inspiring a race to the door, they have turned the
mundane into a work of art.
</P>
<P>
   About seven years ago, Frondorf, of San Antonio, who drives a
lot around West Texas in the oil business, got the idea of
memorializing the landscape from New York City to San Francisco by
rigging a camera to take photographs from his car exactly one mile
apart. His first attempt, using interstate highways, was
unsatisfactory; they bypassed too many small towns, and there were
too many pictures of rock faces and concrete walls instead of
vistas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't get a good view of what was really there,'' he
said. ``I wanted to see the Rockies rise out of the wheat fields of
Western Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
   So in 1993, with a camera attached to the front passenger window
of a Ford Explorer, and following older roads like federal Highways
30, 40 and 50, he took 3,304 pictures, starting with Nos. 1 and 2
(Lower Manhattan and the Statue of Liberty, which he took standing
in Jersey City, N.J.; they were his only shots on foot) and ending
with the Golden Gate Bridge from the Marin Highlands. Each night,
as the sun set, he marked the spot where he took his last photo and
went looking for a motel. In the morning, he would return to the
same spot.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs languished in several suitcases while he sought
in vain to interest a publisher. Then he wrote to Eastman Kodak
Co., which was looking for photo features for its Web site, and it
arranged for Second Story Interactive Studios, a Web production
company in Portland, Ore., to put it online a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The feature, ``American Mile Markers,'' can be accessed off
Kodak's home page (www.kodak.com, and click on ``previous
features''), where it is listed along with photographic adventures
like Shackleton's ``Endurance'' Antarctic voyage and the space
program.
</P>
<P>
   By themselves, the photographs are uninteresting, Frondorf
admits. Together, they are an epic, greater than the sum of its
parts. They are what Frondorf calls statistical photography:
showing everything and letting chance, not an editor, sort out the
highlights. Everything has equal weight, he noted: the homeless
person in New Jersey and the cowboy in Nevada, the trailer house in
the desert and the World Trade Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to create a continuum that would be a panoramic
cross-section of the country, that would be totally objective and
totally candid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures grow on you, as Frondorf wrote in an introduction,
``with city streets flowing into farms and prairies, parched
deserts flowing into forests and mountains, and thunderstorms
rolling into azure skies.'' Mile 30: Honest Al's used car lot on
Market Street in Paterson, N.J. Mile 234: a Civil War statue at
Gettysburg, one of the few photos where Frondorf cheated by a few
yards to get a better shot. Mile 1504: a grain elevator in Bavaria,
Kan. Mile 2811, east of Eureka, Nev.: cowboys in a roundup; they
are branding a calf, and one rider has his lasso in the air. Mile
3099: Stevens Peak, the Sierra Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures can be viewed singly, or at 25-mile and 100-mile
intervals. They can also be viewed in quick succession in movie
form.
</P>
<P>
   Frondorf's original idea was to present the photographs as a
panoramic strip, and he is still looking for a publisher. But while
some claims for the Internet may be out of proportion, he said the
medium seemed perfect for this project. The United States may be
unique for this kind of a travelogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really the only place in the world where you can drive
3,000 miles and it isn't a wild adventure,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1803EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
