<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7899 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      04-26 0287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, April 27, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snow fell in parts of southeastern New England on Wednesday as a
cold storm drifted north along the coast. The storm will reach the
Canadian Maritimes on Thursday. This storm track would normally
result in drier air reaching the Northeast, but a contorted flow of
the jet stream will force some of the storm's moisture westward,
causing clouds and spotty showers across the interior Northeast on
Thursday. Flurries are also possible in the mountains of New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered showers and isolated thunderstorms will occur across
North Texas as humid air from the Gulf of Mexico intercepts an
approaching cool front. A few light showers will also fall farther
north in the Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A band of showers will accompany a cold front advancing into the
Pacific Northwest. Isolated thunderstorms are possible late
Thursday over interior Washington and Oregon.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: FUNNEL CLOUDS
</P>
<P>
   Several funnel clouds were observed in northeastern Kansas on
Tuesday. Often the forerunner of tornadoes, funnel clouds are
typically outgrowths of severe thunderstorms. When the wind changes
speed and direction as altitude increases, updrafts _ the rapidly
rising currents of air that sustain thunderstorms _ can begin to
rotate. Air rushing into the spinning updraft cools and its water
vapor condenses to form a funnel cloud. If a funnel touches the
earth, dust and debris are swept upward and a tornado is born. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1805EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
