A7905 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-VIETNAM-ATL27-COX     04-26 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-ATL27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Many Vietnamese recall U.S. role with sadness
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Master Sgt. Chieu Q. Phung served seven years in the
U.S. Marine Corps, fighting to keep the communists from taking over
South Vietnam. When the Marines pulled out in 1972, Phung switched
to the South Vietnamese Army to keep fighting.
</P>
<P>
   And 25 years ago this Sunday, Phung tried to reach the roof of
the U.S. Embassy in Saigon to catch a helicopter ride out of the
country. The throngs of people already on the building made it
impossible, and South Vietnamese First Lt. Phung could only stand
and watch as the last U.S. helicopter lifted off and flew away.
</P>
<P>
   It was, he said, a terrible sight to see. The United States
abandonment of South Vietnam was complete.
</P>
<P>
   Every year on April 30, Vietnamese in the Atlanta area get
together to observe the day. People share stories of the war and
how they fled Vietnam. More importantly, they talk about the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a quarter of a century later, Phung, 64, lives a happy life
in Doraville. He has been a U.S. citizen since 1989. He is deputy
director of the local chapter of the International Rescue
Committee, an agency that works with refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But, like many Vietnamese in the Atlanta metro area, he still
looks back at the end of U.S. involvement in his native land with
sadness. They had felt so certain that the United States, with all
its weaponry and manpower, would never let the communists win the
war. But, Phung said, they were betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just felt very bad about the United States leaving one of
its allies in the lurch,'' he said. ``A lot of victims were left
behind and put in communist hands and in re-education camps.''
</P>
<P>
   Phung spent 4 1/2 years in a re-education camp in the central
part of the country, near Tuy Hoa. He worked 10 or 11 hours a day
in the fields on little food and then was forced to say that he had
not done enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to say something you don't want to say,'' he
recalled. ``That is mental torture.''
</P>
<P>
   After his release, he tried three times to leave on a boat, but
was intercepted. Then his former wife, who was living in Italy,
used diplomatic channels to get him out of Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owe my life to her,'' Phung said.
</P>
<P>
   When the wheels of the plane lifted off the runway at Tan Son
Nhut airport, Phung was swept with relief. He couldn't believe it.
He would survive.
</P>
<P>
   He misses the landscape of Vietnam and the sights of his youth.
But he has never been back. Nor will he go while the communists
still hold power.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta resident Victor Nguyen Vinh has never returned, either.
</P>
<P>
   Vinh, 67, the owner of Asian Business Community Services,
remembers April 30, 1975, vividly. It is the day he left Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was trying to get out that day,'' he said. ``It was
chaos. We didn't have time to weigh any decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinh had been a military judge in Saigon for 17 years. If he
stayed, he feared he would be sent to a re-education camp, as
happened to many of his friends. He and a son jumped on a ship and
left the country, leaving behind his his wife and two other
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very difficult time for me,'' he said. ``We had to do
whatever we could to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife and family joined him in Atlanta in 1980. Though it has
been 25 years, he wants one day to visit Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to visit the cemetery where my ancestors are
buried,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as relations have warmed between the U.S. and the communist
rulers of Vietnam _ and as U.S. Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) has paid
a friendly visit this week to the country where he was once held as
a prisoner of war _ many expatriate Vietnamese retain an
uncompromisingly anti-communist point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Lilburn resident Tom Nguyen, 37, who is president of the
Vietnamese Community Association of Georgia, was 12 when Saigon
fell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was complete panic and chaos,'' he said. ``There were
people running everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   He will never go back while the communists hold power. ``They
treat people like non-human beings,'' he said. ``We cannot freely
believe in God or Buddha. There is no freedom of speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor will Thanh Cao, 67, return. The Alpharetta resident was a
captain in the South Vietnamese Army and spent nine years in
prison. The U.S. betrayal, he said, made him feel as if he had
fought for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling that South Vietnam was betrayed is not limited to
people who were living there at the time. Monsignor Francis Pham
Van Phuong, 60, of Our Lady of Vietnam Catholic Church in
Riverdale, spent the last three years of the war in Connecticut,
where he was earning his master's degree in counseling at Fairfield
University.
</P>
<P>
   So, like many Americans, Pham, 60, spent the early 1970s
transfixed by television coverage of the Vietnam war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the TV every minute,'' he said. ``I followed it
closely. My family _ my father, my mother, my brothers, my sisters
_ were home in Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   He was angered by the images of people protesting U.S.
involvement in Vietnam, whom he feels were misled by news reports.
Those accounts made it seem as if the U.S. effort was not a worthy
cause, when Pham strongly believes that it was.
</P>
<P>
   And that day 25 years ago, when the last chopper lifted off the
rooftop as people still tried to clamber aboard, was terrible, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not stand it,'' he said. ``I cried all the time. It
was heartbreaking, even for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Pham has returned to Vietnam several times. ``I could not say
the mass in Vietnam, even today,'' he said. ``They say you are a
priest from outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Le Thi Hang, 57, who owns Cha Gio restaurant in Midtown, escaped
the turmoil of the U.S.'s final week in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked for the government, so I knew we would be evacuated
at any time,'' she said. ``We knew we were leaving, but we didn't
know when or how or where we were going.''
</P>
<P>
   Several days before Saigon fell, Hang and her husband and nine
children left Saigon on a military flight. They flew first to the
Philippines, then to Guam and on to Hawaii. Then they were sent to
a refugee camp in Fort Chaffee, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   They were some of the first people there. ``Then thousands
started arriving,'' she said. ``And thousands more.''
</P>
<P>
   Hang has done well here. All nine of her children have graduated
from college. One daughter is on the U.S. Olympic fencing team. One
son is a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Some expatriate Vietnamese believe those refugees _ while they
were forced to leave their homeland by air, by boat or any way they
could _ ultimately prevailed. They brought the world the truth
about communism, helped change the political climate in the United
States and other countries, and contributed to communism's global
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but to Hang, the war itself accomplished nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a waste,'' she said. ``It is an awful thing when you
die without a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
