<HEADLINE>
LAND, SPREADING OUT SO FAR AND WIDE TO SEE; JUDGE BACKS SEARCH
ENGINE'S USE OF COPYRIGHTED IMAGES; MICROSOFT OFFERS A DICTIONARY
THAT TALKS; GOING FROM CARMEN SANDIEGO TO AN ONLINE RECRUITING
SITE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Other than forest ranger or possibly professional surfer, no
occupation has more romance to the cubicle-bound daydreamer than
surveyor: the great outdoors, the hard hats and, most of all, the
cool gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   The Leica LRF 800 Rangemaster enables anyone to become an
amateur surveyor, although it does not have quite the same accuracy
as the professional models. With a laser beam and an optical
rangefinder system, the device instantly measures distances between
33 feet and a half-mile. Users sight their targets through a
monocular viewfinder with seven times magnification. The distance
to the object is projected in the viewfinder _ in either yards or
meters _ by light-emitting diodes that automatically adjust to the
ambient light.
</P>
<P>
   As the Rangemaster's readings are only accurate within 40 inches
either direction, the $449 hand-held device is not suitable for,
say, bridge building. But Roger Horn, president of Leica Camera
Inc., the German company's U.S. agency, said that level of
precision is more than enough for hunters, golfers or gardeners
laying out plots.
</P>
<P>
   There is one type of outdoor enthusiast, however, that may have
some trouble with the device. ``I've had a lot of boaters say this
would be great,'' said Horn. ``But it would be very difficult
keeping it steady to take a reading in a moving boat.''
</P>
<P>
   _IAN AUSTEN
</P>
<P>
   Judge Backs Search Engine's Use of Copyrighted Images
</P>
<P>
   When Leslie A. Kelly, a photographer in California, discovered
last year that several pieces of his work were being used on the
Web without his permission, he did what many artists would do: He
sued the Web site's company to stop posting pictures without
permission.
</P>
<P>
   His case, however, came with a twist. The company that used his
images was not just a Web site; it was an image-based search engine
using thumbnail versions of his photographs as part of its index.
Ditto.com, as the company is now called, includes millions of such
images. And its officials argue that making copies of these images
is, in legal terms, fair use of the copyrighted material because
they are not trying to sell the images; they are simply using them
to build their search engine.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in California has ruled in the company's favor.
Gary A. Taylor, a judge for the U.S. District Court in central
California, ruled last month that Ditto.com's use of Kelly's images
was ``less exploitative'' than traditional commercial uses would
be. Even though Ditto.com is using the images commercially, Taylor
wrote, the company's use of them as part of a search index was
different enough to be considered fair use.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Willis, president and chief executive of Ditto.com, said
the ruling established that ``impeding search would be a huge
disservice to all Internet users who rely on search to help them
find what they are looking for.'' He added that Ditto.com no longer
uses Kelly's images.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawsuit is hardly over. Kelly has appealed the ruling to
the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which is expected to hear
his case in the next year. One of his complaints is that Ditto.com
has changed its practices since he sued. When the company first
posted his images, he said, it was not only using his material for
its index but also was giving users an easy way to download the
images without any indication that the material was copyrighted.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said he is worried about Web sites' taking Ditto.com's
lead if the judge's ruling stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``They continue to harvest images without permission for their
commercial use,'' he said. ``The outcome of this case will define
use of images by surfers or businesses for quite some time.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Offers A Dictionary That Talks
</P>
<P>
   If you're baffled by the upside-down characters and odd accents
most dictionaries use to show pronunciation, you're not alone.
``It's a very widespread perception,'' said Richard Bready,
managing editor of the Microsoft Encarta Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's answer, which went online this month, is a
dictionary that talks. About 60,000 of the roughly 100,000 word
entries posted on the Encarta World English Dictionary site
(www.encarta.com) contain a small speaker icon. When clicked, it
produces a tiny audio clip of what Bready and his 300
lexicographers have determined to be a word's most common
pronunciation in the United States. The emotionless male voice that
supplies the pronunciations for the dictionary's sound clips
belongs to an actor ``chosen primarily for his clarity of speech,''
said Jeffrey Smith, the group product manager for Encarta.
</P>
<P>
   The online version of the dictionary is available at no charge
to users. However, it does not contain additional reference works
like a thesaurus and a style guide that are packaged in the $59.95
CD-ROM version.
</P>
<P>
   Alternative pronunciations for words used in other
English-speaking countries are currently on the Web site only in
text form. But Smith, who was born in Canada, said audio clips of
those versions may be offered in the future.
</P>
<P>
   _ IAN AUSTEN
</P>
<P>
   Going From Carmen Sandiego To an Online Recruiting Site
</P>
<P>
   What do you do if you are a software engineer looking for life
after Broderbund Software, the computer game company of Myst and
Carmen Sandiego fame?
</P>
<P>
   Why, start an online recruiting site, of course.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem counterintuitive, but that is precisely what a group
of Broderbund engineers, including Broderbund's co-founder, Douglas
Carlston, did after Broderbund was bought by the Learning Co. in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The well-financed Web site, called ICplanet (IC stands for
independent consultant), which went online Wednesday, uses a
sophisticated search technology to match recruiters and managers
with temporary contractors.
</P>
<P>
   The company's main focus is on information technology workers.
Some of the other job categories that ICplanet focuses on include
marketing, business development, training and finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ugly truth is that it can be very frustrating for
recruiters to find qualified technical consultants,'' said Jeffrey
Walker, ICplanet's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most interesting aspect of the site is its search
technology (patent pending), which works with the use of pull-down
menus instead of search terms typed in by the user. Carlston said
the search engine learns as it goes and gradually begins making
suggestions to the user for refining a search.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could come back to you and say if you expand the radius of
your search, you'll get 20 more people in the database,'' Walker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Carlston said ICplanet is not as far afield from Broderbund as
one might think, as its main strength is its software. ``A group of
eight technologists started the company,'' Carlston said. ``It
wasn't started by marketing people. That's what attracted me to the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   _ KATIE HAFNER
</P>
</TEXT>
