<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7913 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-GAY-HNS &LR;      04-26 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-GAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT HEARS ARGUMENTS IN GAY BOY SCOUT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wading into one of the country's most volatile
cultural battlefields, U.S. Supreme Court justices struggled
Wednesday over the question of whether the Boy Scouts of America
can bar avowed homosexuals from serving as troop leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is about the freedom of a voluntary association to
choose it's own leaders,'' said Scouts' attorney George A.
Davidson, arguing that the organization had the right to oust New
Jersey troop leader James Dale after learning he is homosexual.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson said the Boy Scouts' strong belief in a ``moral code of
conduct'' had become so ingrained in the nation's consciousness
that the phrase, ``He's a real Boy Scout,'' had entered the
American idiom.
</P>
<P>
   By publicly admitting his homosexuality, ``Mr. Dale had created
a reputation for himself'' that would harm his ability to be a role
model for Scouts, Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
   But Evan Wolfson, Dale's lawyer, said his client did nothing to
wrong under the Scouts' moral code, which does not specifically ban
homosexuals from the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``They removed him for being a homosexual, but their policy says
nothing about being a homosexual,'' said Wolfson, adding that Dale
never attempted to use his position as a Scout leader to advocate
homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said the Scouts kicked Dale out simply because he was
a homosexual, not because he was an advocate for gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is based on the identity of Dale and not on his
advocacy of gay rights,'' Wolfson argued.
</P>
<P>
   Dale and his parents listened to the arguments from the
courtroom audience.
</P>
<P>
   The case began in 1989, when Dale, then 19 years old, applied to
be an adult Scout leader of a troop in Matawan, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, he had been an exemplary Boy Scout and had attained the
Eagle Scout Badge _ Scouting's highest award _ when he was a member
of a troop in Middletown, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   His application for a leadership role was accepted and he served
16 months as an assistant scoutmaster for the Matawan troop.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Dale was attending college at Rutgers University.
There, Dale served as co-president of the university's Lesbian/Gay
Alliance and acknowledged his homosexuality in a speech in July
1990. His speech _ dealing with the needs of lesbian and gay
teenagers _ was reported in a local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Later that month, Dale received a letter from the Boy Scouts
severing his relations with the organization. When Dale wrote back
demanding an explanation, the Scouts replied that his acknowledged
homosexuality was ``contrary to the values of the organization''
and that the Scouts ``specifically forbid membership to
homosexuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale sued the Scouts for reinstatement under a New Jersey law
that forbids discrimination in ``public accommodation'' on the
basis of race, gender, religion or sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   He lost in a New Jersey state trial court which ruled in 1992
that the Boy Scouts of America was not a place of public
accommodation. The court concluded that it would be
unconstitutional to force the Scouts to accept Dale because it
would be ``contrary to the BSA's rights to association.''
</P>
<P>
   But in 1999, the New Jersey Supreme Court overturned that
decision and handed Dale a victory. The state Supreme Court
rejected the argument that the Boy Scouts was a private membership
organization and had First Amendment rights of ``intimate'' and
``expressive association.''
</P>
<P>
   The court referred to the Scouts as a ``quasi-public entity''
because of its partnerships with public institutions and
facilities. The Scouts appealed to the U.S. Supreme
Court.Throughout Wednesday's arguments before the high court, the
justices attempted to find a balance between the right of
homosexuals to have equal access to mainstream organizations, with
the right of Americans with similar ideas to form groups that
exclude people who don't share those ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Justice David Souter questioned Davidson on one of the Scouts'
major arguments: that Dale was a ``gay-rights activist'' who
wouldn't be able to ``communicate Scouting's moral values.''
</P>
<P>
   Souter asked how Dale's ``mere admittance'' of being gay made
him an advocate of homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Souter also pointed out that Dale repeatedly has said that he
would not advocate gay rights or homosexuality as a Scout leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Dale is not asking to carry a banner he's saying, 'I'm not
going to carry a banner,''' Souter said.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson responded that Dale ``put a banner around his neck'' by
leading a college campus gay-rights organization and by talking
with the media about homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, the man was in Time magazine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Souter followed up, asking, ``So if a troop leader just told
other Scout leaders he was gay instead of a newspaper, he wouldn't
be excluded?''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson said it would depend on the ``circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg told Davidson that ``it sounds like
the Boy Scouts have a `Don't ask, Don't tell' policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson responded, ``I don't know if I'd call it that, but
something similar, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson also fielded a number of critical questions.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia asked him why the Scouts should be
required to accept as a leader ``someone who embodies a
contradiction of their message, whether the person wears a sign or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson said there would be no contradiction if that ``person is
only saying, `I'm gay, here I am.'''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy quickly asked, ``Who is better
qualified to determine the expressive purpose of the Boy Scouts _
the Boy Scouts or the New Jersey courts?''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson answered, ``It depends.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's argument was the last for the current term, and the
justices will decide by July whether the Scouts had the right to
oust Dale.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The court has straddled similar issues in the past, with
decisions that could favor both the Boy Scouts and Dale.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the court let the private sponsor of Boston's St.
Patrick's Day Parade exclude a group of gays and lesbians. Parades
are a ``form of expression'' and private sponsors cannot be forced
to include a group promoting a message the sponsors oppose, the
court said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, in a trilogy of cases in the mid-1980s, the
court rejected claims by all-male organizations, including the
Jaycees and the Rotary Club, to a First Amendment right to continue
excluding women.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
