<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWN-RANGER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REEL-LIFE ADVENTURE IN THE SEARCH FOR SHANGRI-LAWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB DAVIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three acres of some grass, lots of weeds and a lawn mower
without an engine? OK, where are the Fox TV guys?
</P>
<P>
   This scenario seems like a pilot for one of those reality-based
programs _ ``When Good Gardeners Go Bad.'' But this is more than a
gimmick designed to keep some Bubba's backside glued to the couch.
</P>
<P>
   It is an inner struggle. A turf war of the soul, if you will. A
battle of saving the planet vs. being a real guy. Hugging a tree
vs. mowing it down with my gas-guzzling mower. Will I be Captain
Planet _ or Mr. Douglas, bopping along on that tractor in the
opening scene for ``Green Acres?''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for my conflict is simple enough: The air in parts of
North Texas is dirty. The air is full of pollutants that scientists
say cause health problems.
</P>
<P>
   It's so dirty that unless it gets cleaner, the Environmental
Protection Agency could inflict drastic measures. (Hint: Say
goodbye to those highway funds.)
</P>
<P>
   Don't think Fort Worth-Dallas is the only part of the state with
dirty air; Houston has replaced Los Angeles as the city with the
most smog in the country, so it's worse off than we are.
</P>
<P>
   While various local government entities are fighting over who's
to blame and what can be done, the idea occurs that my big, old
nasty garden tractor isn't helping matters. Estimates predict that
some gas-powered mowers pollute as much as 50 to 350 times more
than a car does in an hour. If only I, and a few thousand others in
North Texas, cut back on our gas-powered mower addiction, the air
quality might be improved.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the reel mower, also known as a ``push mower'' or a
``rotary mower.'' No engine. No pollution. No problem?
</P>
<P>
   Well, one problem: I like my tractor. It's not a really big
tractor, only one of those small souped-up riding lawn mowers that
Sears sells. It's dependable over my rough-hewn 3 acres. It mulches
leaves and knocks down any kind of foliage in its way. It's your
basic ``guy's toy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's nowhere near the size of my grandad's big Ford tractor, the
one he used to sit me on top of when I was just a pup. That
monstrosity pulled a Bush Hog and cut huge swaths through the
countryside. (Even today, he pays lip service to my ``garden
tractor,'' but I suspect all the while inside he's thinking I
should have to wear a dress while mowing with such a puny little
thing.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite its shortcomings, my little garden tractor is a big hit
with my 18-month-old daughter. She likes to sit in my lap for short
rides.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those precious memories, and it pollutes, too.'' That's
what the little green voice would whisper every time I cranked up
the mower.
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever seen a reel mower, it was probably in an old
movie. According to the industry leader American Lawn Mower, that's
changing, with sales more than doubling since the mid-1980s. The
costs range from $100 to $250. Home Depot had ours _ a Scotts brand
for $100 _ on a high shelf, with very little in the way of signage
directing you to it.
</P>
<P>
   If you go shopping, be prepared: These Earth-friendly devices
are still stuck on the back of the retail bus. You'll probably have
to check in some out-of-the-way places for a reel mower unless you
go online.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits are plentiful for making that extra effort. Reel
mowers are quieter than gas-powered versions. They eliminate the
need for lugging that gas can to the local filling station or
getting the regular engine tuneup. They are easier to push,
although that is balanced with the fact that instead of horsepower
it's using you-power.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the fitness benefit of burning more than 500
calories per hour using the reel mower. Pushing one will give your
arms and legs a workout. Reel mowers are lighter than the motorized
kind, but don't kid yourself; they still weigh about 30 pounds, and
pushing one around your yard is not a day at the beach.
(Gas-powered mowers weigh about 70 pounds.)
</P>
<P>
   I tried the experiment of sprinting about 50 yards at a clip
with the reel mower. My legs got real tired real fast. Besides,
that's not very safe. Slow and steady pushing makes the job a
little more strenuous than pushing a standard-size wheelbarrow
half-filled with rocks or a stroller filled with a curious
18-month-old.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest drawback is that a reel mower is meant for grass _
and well-behaved grass, at that. It doesn't do well whacking down
weeds or tall grass. The rotating blades get stuck in the tall
stuff, and you have to pull the mower back to get the thing
unjammed.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, a reel mower is best suited for small (half-acre or
less) lawns in the suburbs. (Do you think we can find a few of
those around here?)
</P>
<P>
   On my little plot of uneven ground populated by more clover,
weeds and dandelions, I would be better off with another
Earth-friendly device: a slingblade.
</P>
<P>
   But if you have a small plot of grass and a desire to go green
plus keep your neighborhood quiet, a reel mower might be for you.
</P>
<P>
   Can a real man be a reel man? I think so _ and that little green
voice agrees.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
