<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7916 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-PRIVACY-2T     04-26 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-PRIVACY-2TAKES-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERMEDIARIES STEP INTO PRIVACY VOID
</HEADLINE>
 (Circuits)  
 By CATHERINE GREENMAN  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shopping online or visiting a Web site that requires
registration usually means surrendering some privacy _ providing a
name, e-mail address and other personal information.
</P>
<P>
   Some Internet users bristle at the notion that Web sites gather
such data, no matter how safely tucked away the companies say the
information is. On the other hand, some people are not bothered at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Just how concerned Web users should be about privacy, and how
much of it they should have to give up when they go online, is a
heated topic among Web companies, consumer advocates, and users
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the growing discomfort about how personal
information might be used without a person's knowledge, several
companies, including Enonymous, PrivaSeek and Zero-Knowledge
Systems, have developed ways for people to exert tighter control
over who knows what about them. The companies, which call
themselves ``infomediaries,'' act as intermediaries, collecting
personal information from a user and providing it to other sites
with the user's approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research shows that consumers are concerned about privacy
but that very few people get involved and actively watch what's
being done with their information,'' said Tim Kane, director of
privacy for Enonymous, San Diego. ``It's something they care about,
but they don't walk 10 feet for it.''
</P>
<P>
   But some privacy advocates say these intermediaries are part of
the problem rather than a solution because they could profit from
the very information they are protecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The infomediaries are just more third parties who can change
their mind while holding your information, or who could be bought
by somebody else who has a different privacy policy,'' said Lauren
Weinstein, co-founder of People for Internet Responsibility, an
organization in Woodland Hills, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, among the first things that a user does at an
intermediary's Web site is provide personal information. Surfers
can go to Enonymous.com, for example, and download a software
program called Enonymous Adviser. When launched, the program asks
the user to provide information including name, date of birth,
shipping and billing addresses, e-mail address, phone number,
credit card number and preferred method of contact.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the user goes shopping online or visits a portal or
other site that requires registration, Enonymous checks to see what
rating it has given the site's privacy policy _ whether and under
what circumstances it will share information it receives with third
parties, for example. The company has a team of site raters who
have given from one to four stars to more than 30,000 Web sites,
Kane said.
</P>
<P>
   If the site has a low rating or has not been rated, the
Enonymous Adviser sends a pop up message alerting the user. If, on
the other hand, the site has an adequate privacy policy, the
software retrieves the necessary data from the user's hard drive
and fills in the blank fields when the user registers or makes a
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Users can set up several different information packets. One can
contain only a name and e-mail address, for example, while another
can contain credit card information and a shipping address. The
user can then instruct the program to enter more or less
information as desired.
</P>
<P>
   Although the automatic form filler component is similar to other
``digital wallets'' offered by companies including Gator.com and
CyberCash.com, the ability to pick and choose the information
released based on a site's privacy policy gives users more control,
Kane said.
</P>
<P>
   So what does Enonymous get in exchange for all this
conscientious watchdogging? Nothing, yet. Kane said the company
isn't yet profitable, but that it expects to enter into
partnerships with other Web sites so that it can offer e-commerce
links, for example, at its site.
</P>
<P>
   Enonymous is hoping to make money by persuading users of its
software to give up some of their privacy to it. The site currently
beckons users to visit the ``Enonymous Community'' and fill out a
marketing survey regarding their hobbies, their shopping
preferences, and how they like to be contacted. Kane said Enonymous
will sell only this volunteered information. ``If we get a million
people who like this, we'll be able to charge merchants for the
information we give them,'' he said. Delivering banner
advertisements and e-mail messages to people who answered the
survey is also part of the company's plan. About half of the
100,000 people who have downloaded the software have participated
in the survey.
</P>
<P>
   PrivaSeek, Broomfield, Colo., assumes that customers are willing
to reveal some information about themselves as long as they get
something in return. The company's PersonaValet program functions
as a digital wallet, storing a user's information at a data center
(not on the user's hard drive), and letting the user pick and
choose what data a site can have. Privaseek does not rate sites,
assuming that users will read a site's privacy policy. Once a user
sets up an account, PersonaValet maintains for the user a record of
sites visited, on what date and what personal information was
submitted.
</P>
<P>
   The company has formed partnerships with several online
merchants, including ShopNow.com and RMI.net. In return for
PrivaSeek's services, users will see advertisements and special
offers geared to their interests and shopping tastes when they
visit partner sites, based on the information they have given to
PrivaSeek. ``Web sites are making a lot of money off of selling
this information,'' said Steve Lucas, chief information officer at
PrivaSeek. ``We believe consumers should profit from this exchange
too,'' he added, by getting discounts and other offers that are not
available to people who don't provide personal information.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom program from Zero-Knowledge Systems gives a Web
surfer anonymity by protecting identifiable information within the
network of the company's servers.
</P>
<P>
   People who download the Freedom software can create several user
identities, or pseudonyms. In addition to encrypting data so that a
person or another computer cannot read it, Freedom routes the
information through the company's network of servers so that it
cannot be traced to a user's computer. The information is invisible
even to Zero-Knowledge, said Austin Hill, president of the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We struggled a lot with how to build privacy into a protocol
that's never had privacy built in before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Each pseudonym costs $10 per year and the software can be
downloaded at www.freedom.net. Hill said that Zero-Knowledge also
markets Freedom to companies that wish to protect their clients'
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is certainly a market of users who are willing to go out
and pay for privacy,'' Hill said. ``But businesses are starting to
realize that privacy matters to their users.'' For example, he
said, if health care companies wanting to put individual medical
information online would have to be concerned with protecting
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Digitalme.com from Novell, which offers automatic form filling
in exchange for a customer's agreement to accept e-mail
advertisements from its partners, and Anonymizer.com, a portal that
sends users to its partner sites _ all of which have approved
privacy policies and which deliver banner advertisements based on
surveys the consumer has filled out _ are more variations on the
intermediary theme.
</P>
<P>
   But critics of the intermediaries say that the companies fail to
provide enough protection and that they have the potential to
exploit what they are supposed to be protecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The infomediaries are a patchwork solution,'' said Chris
Kelly, an associate analyst at the Internet research firm Forrester
Research. ``They're taking the privacy issue far enough so that the
government doesn't come down hard, but even as far as they've come,
there are still privacy breaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein of People for Internet Responsibility said that
instead of using intermediaries, Web surfers should stop providing
sites with information if they don't necessarily have to.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should start saying no to these information requests,''
he said. ``Because in the end we're finding that very often the
information is being abused, sold, manipulated, or just plain
corrupted. It's just not worth it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Apart from the intermediaries, efforts to develop industry-wide,
enforceable privacy standards have been proceeding slowly. For the
past few years, the World Wide Web Consortium, the organization,
based in Washington, that sets standards for the Internet, has been
working on the Platform for Privacy Preferences initiative, known
as P3P. The initiative includes plans for a software program that
would let Web browsers automatically read a Web site's privacy
policy and compare it with the user's privacy preferences.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unclear how P3P will work with existing intermediary
programs, and whether browser companies and Web developers will
incorporate it into their products.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics of P3P say it does nothing to improve existing
privacy policies, or breaches of them. ``These companies have no
compelling reason not to pass on personal information to someone
who will pay for it, and P3P doesn't say that it shouldn't go on,
it only says you should know about it,'' said Andrew Shen, policy
analyst at Electronic Privacy Information Center in Washington.
``What we really need are higher privacy standards and
enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   After a recent privacy conference, Richard Purcell, director of
corporate privacy for the Microsoft Corp., said the company was
working toward developing a P3P compliant program for businesses
and people before the end of the year. ``It will automatically
compare a Web site operator's privacy practices to the consumer's
preferences, and inform the consumer of any nonconformance or
mismatch,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Cranor, chairwoman of the P3P specification working
group, said Web developers would see a working version of P3P this
summer. ``There are some who've been critical of the whole idea,
but it's not meant to solve all privacy problems,'' Cranor said.
``It's aimed specifically at providing consumers with notice about
a site's policy.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
