<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7920 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-MASTERCOOK-NYT &LR;      04-26 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MASTERCOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RECIPE BANK THAT CHEFS CAN CUSTOMIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a world not too far in the future, where voice-activated
computers are installed in kitchens everywhere. Suppose the family
cook is throwing a dinner party: ``Computer! The recipe for beef
Bourguignon with fettuccine. Scale ingredients up for 15 people.
And give me a wine suggestion.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is probably a working model of such a computerized
kitchen somewhere, the recipe software is already here. Food fans
may want to take Sierra Home's The Best of MasterCook for a spin.
</P>
<P>
   This latest version of the popular MasterCook series
incorporates 10,000 recipes, culled from Betty Crocker cookbooks
and Cooking Light magazine and from the MasterCook Deluxe archives,
onto a set of two CD-ROMs. The program is more than a computerized
recipe index; it also provides a complete nutritional analysis of
each recipe and menu planning. Users can edit and add their own
recipes and send them to friends via e-mail, and they can drag and
drop recipes found on the Web into the program's database.
</P>
<P>
   Short videos showing some of the finer points of food
preparation are included with the program. If you're planning a
meal for more than the number of servings listed in a recipe, you
only need to click on the Scale icon and type in the number of
servings you need, and the program will do the math for you.
Templates for printing favorite recipes are also available.
</P>
<P>
   As you select recipes, the program helpfully keeps track of the
ingredients with a shopping list of the necessary items and
quantities required. The program's MealPlan function will let you
also drag-and-drop recipes into a dining strategy for the whole
day. Combined with the shopping-list function, that trip to the
grocery store can be completed with surgical precision.
</P>
<P>
   MasterCook's interface is easy to figure out because the names
of the tool icons pop up on the screen if your mouse lingers over
them. For those who find security in paper manuals, the program
comes with a hefty one.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are intimidated by 200-plus-page manuals may be a
little nervous around MasterCook's book, but the authors seem to
have taken a tip from the creators of those instructions for
dummies/idiots/morons books and written the program guide in clear
English with plenty of screen shots to guide the reader. When you
start the program for the first time after installing it, a box
pops up on the screen and asks you if you'd like to take a quick
tutorial of the software.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for recipes containing specific items can be very
slow, as the basic search function seems to go through each of the
33 cookbooks in the database individually. You can choose to search
specific cookbooks in the collection if you have a better idea of
where to look. There probably won't be any double-fudge brownie
instructions in the Hot Off the Grill section, for example.
</P>
<P>
   The Advanced Search feature is quite powerful. You can search
for recipes based on foods to avoid or include, the ingredients you
have in your kitchen (provided you have added your pantry's
inventory into MasterCook's database), the type of cuisine or the
recipe category.
</P>
<P>
   As one might expect from the Betty Crocker content, the recipes
in The Best of MasterCook are fairly mainstream. But more
imaginative dishes, like eggplant matzo lasagna, are sprinkled
throughout, and there are some nice selections from international
cuisines, particularly Asian.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs with a sweet tooth will find plenty of cookies, cakes and
other desserts. Before-and-during libations are also included in a
cocktail guide and a wine-advisory section.
</P>
<P>
   On the technical side, you'll need a computer using Windows 95
or 98 to run The Best of MasterCook with, at a bare minimum, a
90-megahertz processor, 16 megabytes of RAM and 98 megabytes of
free hard drive space. When you install it, MasterCook gives you
three options for the amount of space it will grab from your hard
drive. Besides the minimum 98 megabytes, you can opt just to
install the cookbooks you are interested in, or you can install the
whole enchilada in exchange for 426 megabytes of your disk space.
</P>
<P>
   The Best of MasterCook is available on the Web at
www.sierrahome.com, in stores or by calling (800) 757-7707.
</P>
<P>
   Until computers invade kitchens, cooking programs are unlikely
to live up to their potential, but The Best of MasterCook could
make life easier for cooks and foodies. And with 10,000 recipes
easily on hand, ``what's for dinner?'' might have a lot more
answers.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE BEST OF MASTERCOOK  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sierra Home; $59.95; Windows 95 and 98.)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
