<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7921 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-DATELINE-CHINA27-COX     04-26 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DATELINE-CHINA27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Female politician ruffling many in Republic of China on Taiwan
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Most newly elected officials enjoy a political
honeymoon for a time.
</P>
<P>
   Not Annette Lu. Honeymoons aren't her style.
</P>
<P>
   Schooled in law at the University of Illinois and Harvard, Lu is
by anyone's definition a remarkable woman. A leading advocate for
women's rights at home and abroad, she also has been a determined
campaigner for expanding Taiwan's democracy. Her courageous
activism, while Taiwan was ruled under martial law, cost her 5 1/2
years in jail but also earned her recognition from Amnesty
International as a prisoner of conscience. Since then, she has
served in Taiwan's legislature and as a crusading anti-corruption
county governor.
</P>
<P>
   On March 18, at the age of 55, Lu was catapulted into a new role
as the first woman ever to be elected vice president of the
Republic of China on Taiwan or, for that matter, any state with a
Confucian cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Another politician might be basking in the symbolism of the
moment. But in the past month, Lu _ who will take office May 20 _
has not only feuded with members of her own party but become
embroiled in a high-stakes game of name-calling across the Taiwan
Strait that separates this island from China's mainland.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, it was hard to say who had annoyed her
more: the ``male chauvinists'' of Taiwan or her critics on the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that she had been treated like a ``forgotten concubine,''
Lu has complained loudly and repeatedly that she was shut out of
the process of choosing the new Cabinet. If anyone thought she
would settle for the role of ``political wife'' for the new
president _ her longtime Democratic Progressive Party ally, Chen
Shui-bian _ they were mistaken, she said.
</P>
<P>
   DPP Chairman Lin I-hsiung has responded publicly that ranking
party members _ and everyone assumed he meant Lu, in particular _
should study Taiwan's constitution and ``be circumspect in their
words and behavior to avoid damaging the party's image.'' When Lu's
name came up in an interview last week, the party leader chuckled
and said the vice president has no real power and is only a reserve
president if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Other party members have chimed in that the incoming vice
president should use internal communications, not interviews with
the media, if she has complaints. And even the future first lady,
Wu Shu-chen, has spoken out. Wu said Lu should stop pushing the
president-elect so hard, that she was the real ``forgotten
concubine,'' and that if people put too much pressure on her
husband he might ``go crazy and Lu would have to take his seat.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Lu has been making waves at home, she has unleashed a
tsunami across the strait. Tensions between Taiwan and the mainland
have been high because Chen and Lu will be the first politicians
from the independence-minded DPP to control the government.
</P>
<P>
   Though their party has long advocated independence from China,
both candidates pledged during the campaign not to push the issue.
Chen even said last week that some kind of loose alliance or
confederation with China might be a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Lu, however, triggered a barrage of criticism across the strait
this month when she told a Hong Kong station that Taiwan already
had ``independent sovereignty'' and repeated a remark she has often
made: the people of Taiwan and China are ``distant cousins and
close neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   China sees the people of Taiwan as anything but distant cousins.
And, in response to Lu's comments, Beijing's New China News Agency
editorialized that she is not only the ``scum of the (Chinese)
nation'' but a ``traitor'' and ``hideous.'' She was ``insane,''
too, the Liberation Army Daily added. And to the People's Daily,
she sounded like a ``lunatic leader'' who was propelling Taiwan
toward catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   Far from retreating, Lu _ who has earned the nickname the ``Iron
Lady'' _ has fired back as she sat in her office talking with one
journalist after another.
</P>
<P>
   Though her duties in the new administration remain
``ambiguous,'' she said she has no quarrel with the president-elect
but does have complaints about some other officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these male chauvinists really made me angry,'' she said.
``Just because I'm a woman everybody asks me to shut up. ... I am
the second national leader. How can you treat me that way just
because I'm a woman?''
</P>
<P>
   And though she said she worries that the mainland government
could do something ``irrational,'' she was equally dismissive of
her critics in Beijing. No one in China should be upset, she
contended, because her message has emphasized peace and good will.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are neighbors, so let's co-exist peacefully for mutual
development,'' she said, adding that the Chinese just ``don't know
how to react at all.''
</P>
<P>
   If her roiling of the waters in the Taiwan Strait should have
ripple effects across the Pacific in the United States, Lu didn't
seem to mind. The United States and Taiwan have strong economic
ties, and the U.S. is committed to providing the island with the
means to defend itself from any attack. Last week, the Clinton
administration stopped short of selling the Taiwanese the advanced
destroyers they wanted but did agree to sell long-range radar to
detect missile launches as well as provide training and technical
help. A bill, which passed the House in February and is now pending
in the Senate, would deepen the military ties.
</P>
<P>
   But more than weapons, Lu said, Taiwan needs the United States
to engage in preventive diplomacy. Not only should the U.S. tell
the Chinese they will pay a high price if they start a war, she
said, but President Clinton also should try to arrange Camp
David-style peace talks between China and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   While she was on the subject of American policy, Lu also raised
what she called a ``minor but significant issue:'' She and Chen
have been told through official U.S. sources not to plan to visit
the United States after they take office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that correct? Is that justified?'' she asked. ``Is China's
policy America's policy as well?''
</P>
<P>
   Such statements are not likely to calm Lu's critics in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Yawei Liu, a Chinese professor of history at Georgia Perimeter
College, cited her request for the United States to mediate between
the two sides as just one of several stances she has taken that
make Chinese leaders ``very nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   And Kellee Tsai, a China watcher at Emory University, said that
in Beijing ``there is grave concern that if Chen Shui-bian passed
away, she would become president and become more open in advocating
independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year when former President Jimmy Carter spoke in Taiwan, Lu
publicly demanded that he apologize for normalizing relations with
China in 1979. Carter turned paler the more she spoke, Lu recalled
with relish. But he refused to apologize, and Lu said she still
considers him ``very arrogant.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, when a group of mainland scholars visited
Taiwan, Lu demanded that they apologize for the statement from the
Chinese media that she is the ``scum of the nation.'' They refused,
too, and Lu called them ``arrogant'' as well.
</P>
<P>
   Lu doesn't always get what she wants. But in her three decades
as a leader of Taiwan's opposition, she has never hesitated to
disturb the peace. She insisted that as a member of the government
she will not be ``voiceless.'' And that is one pledge she seems
determined to keep.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
