u k BC-EDITORIAL-PALESTINE-B     04-26 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PALESTINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All the diplomatic detours have been traversed, all the bluffs
and delays played out, all the international maneuvering completed.
The time has finally come for Israel and the Palestinian Authority
to forge an agreement on the thorny issues of land, refugees, and
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have shown each other draft documents that state
their preferences and thus clarify the differences to be bridged
through negotiation. They have agreed to meet this Sunday in the
Israeli port of Eilat for intensive discussions in the presence of
American envoys who will take a more active mediating role than
they have until now, even being prepared to offer positive
suggestions to resolve disagreements between the principals.
</P>
<P>
   As the Israeli government of Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Yasser Arafat's Palestinian Authority grapple with the issues they
have postponed until the final stage of the Oslo peace process, it
should be clear to all that Israel is by far the stronger party.
The only cards Arafat has to play are gestures of renunciation and
reconciliation. In the name of the Palestinian people, he may
renounce property claims and declare an intention to live alongside
Israelis peacefully, as a good neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Barak may decide how much land the Palestinians
will recover, where that land is located, what the capital of the
Palestinian state shall be, what the limits will be on that state's
sovereignty, and to what degree more than 4 million Palestinian
refugees will enjoy either a right to return home or compensation
for their forced exile.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of the refugees, it is in Israel's long-term
interest to reach a solution to alleviate the profound grievances
of the Palestinian diaspora. Possibly nothing short of an absolute
right of return to homes and villages within pre-1967 Israel will
satisfy many dispossessed Palestinians. There are already signs
that members of the Palestinian diaspora are preparing to resist
anticipated backsliding by Arafat on the refugee issue. But the
more Israel can do now to help create a viable Palestinian state
and to make up for the injustices of the past, the more authentic
will be the peace they make.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
