<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOROTHY-HAMILL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOROTHY HAMILL STILL A NICE ICE LADY AT 43 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLIFFORD PUGH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The year before Dorothy Hamill won the gold medal in
women's figure skating at the 1976 Olympics, most of her classmates
didn't even know what she did in her off-hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just this quiet girl who came into class and left when
school was over,'' she recalled during a recent telephone interview
from a restaurant near her home in Baltimore. ``I didn't get to
stay for the fun things. I had to go right back to the skating
rink.''
</P>
<P>
   Just about everything has changed in the world of figure skating
since then.
</P>
<P>
   Now, competitions are on television nearly every weekend, and
young stars like Michelle Kwan and Tara Lipinski are household
names, making millions while performing triple jumps that Hamill
never imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, when Hamill steps into the spotlight to perform in the
John Hancock Champions on Ice Summer Tour 2000 show, which will
make a Houston stop May 2 at Compaq Center, she consistently
receives a warm reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always amazes me. I feel like the dinosaur out there, and
the people are just wonderful,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the ancient age of 43, Hamill is old enough to be the mother
of many of the skaters on the tour. Of those affiliated with
Champions on Ice, only Brian Boitano, at 36, approaches her in age
and ice-skating longevity.
</P>
<P>
   The famous Hamill wedge haircut is flecked with gray now,
although she laughingly says that she has ``lots of help from my
hairdresser so you wouldn't know it unless you caught me between
hair colorings.''
</P>
<P>
   If photographs are any indication, she maintains a youthful look
that matches her attitude. She joked that perhaps spending all that
time indoors on the ice kept her skin from being damaged in the
sun. But she also believes skating is great exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were competing against the youngsters, I wouldn't be able
to (continue to) do it (as a profession),'' she said.
``Fortunately, my sport is also entertainment. One is able to do it
longer than a gymnast, who has to be 14 years old and a little
rubber band.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep in shape, Hamill skates for several hours six days a
week and does weight-training at least three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me it's not a luxury anymore; it's a necessity. If I don't
work out that much, I cannot even stay at a fit level,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While Hamill has remained largely injury-free throughout her
career, she recently hurt a couple of muscles while performing. She
returned to Baltimore to recuperate.
</P>
<P>
   The injury occurred after she didn't warm up properly before a
performance because a reception for tour sponsors ran longer than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only had 10 minutes to put on make-up and warm up for the
opening number, and that's not nearly enough time,'' she said.
``Unfortunately, I had to learn my lesson. Those things are going
to have to take a back seat. I was disappointed. I was skating
well.''
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, Hamill plans to perform two ``straightforward
skating'' numbers to music by Patti Lupone.
</P>
<P>
   She said the younger skaters on the tour don't often ask her
advice. ``And I don't know if I have any advice I could give them
that would be helpful because it's so different now. They have so
much pressure on them at such a young age.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, competition revolves around the ability to do a large
number of difficult triple jumps. When Hamill competed, jumps were
not so important.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she spent five hours a day tracing figure-eights on the
ice for a part of the competition known as compulsory school
figures. These were abolished in 1990, so now skaters devote their
time to perfecting triple jumps.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, ``There's so much more to skating than jumping and
spinning,'' Hamill said. ``I still think the art of skating is very
much in its infancy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamill remains competitive with herself. She continues to do a
double lutz like she did when she won the Olympic medal and is
working on putting the double axel back in her repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   The double axel was the hardest jump in her Olympic performance,
and she is aiming to perfect it again to mark the 25th anniversary
of her Olympic victory next year.
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult part of Champions on Ice, Hamill said, is
being away from her daughter, Alexandra. The 11-year-old joins
Hamill on the tour on weekends and returns to Baltimore on Sunday
nights to attend school the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Hamill has been seeing a ``very nice young man'' for three
years. But having been through two painful divorces, she said she
has no plans to get married again.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't know how much longer she will skate professionally.
Her doctor tells her that she can continue for another 10 years if
she takes care of her body.
</P>
<P>
   But even if she chooses to end her professional career sooner
than that, ``I think I will always skate, no matter what,'' she
said, ``because I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
