<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7932 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-PURCHASE-N     04-26 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-PURCHASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAITING FOR HARRY POTTER IN LONG LINES ON THE NET
</HEADLINE>
  (Circuits)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   417.
</P>
<P>
   According to my calculations, that is the number of times a day,
on average, that my 9-year-old daughter, Ella, asks me when we will
be able to buy the fourth book in the Harry Potter series.
</P>
<P>
   416.
</P>
<P>
   That is how many times I respond in a reasonable tone,
explaining patiently that we will have to wait until July 8, the
worldwide publication date for all English language versions.
</P>
<P>
   1.
</P>
<P>
   That is how many times _ usually after supper but before the
dishes are washed, while her little sister is mashing red Play-Doh
into the dog's tail _ that I say: ``Leave me alone about the Harry
Potter book! I can't take it anymore! I can't take it, I tell
you!''
</P>
<P>
   You can imagine, then, that it came as a relief recently when
Ella said she wanted to ask a different question. Until she asked
it. ``Mom, can I have your credit card number?''
</P>
<P>
   The question arose because my daughter, like generations of
intrepid young hackers before her, had begun to address her
repetitive questions to an authority figure infinitely more patient
_ and logical _ than the average parent. She had turned to the
computer. In an exhaustive question-and-answer session at the Ask
Jeeves search site, Ella had typed, ``How can I buy the fourth
Harry Potter book?''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of countering that if she wanted an answer, she had
first better go make that bed and put away that stack of clean
laundry that had been sitting on her dresser for three days, the
wise computer offered Ella what seemed like a solution. It told her
that a number of online booksellers were already taking orders.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Amazon, which took advance orders last year before the
publication of the third Harry Potter book, a number of Internet
booksellers are following suit this time around. Ella compiled a
list of comparative prices that included not only Amazon (which is
discounting the book's $25.95 list price to $18.17), but also eToys
($20.76), Borders ($18.17), 1Bookstreet ($17.56) and Barnes &AMP; Noble
($18.16).
</P>
<P>
   The book, described on Amazon only as ``Harry Potter (NU)4,''
was the site's second-best-selling title one day last week. And at
Barnes &AMP; Noble, said Debra Williams, the company's director of
corporate communications, ``people have been asking us for the book
for months, and thousands have placed orders, both online and at
our stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a person who reserves a table at a trendy restaurant
several weeks before it's time to eat the meal, I figured that I
could get some peace of mind by placing an order online. And on
Amazon, where I make the bulk of my online book purchases, it would
not cost me anything because Amazon does not charge a buyer until
an order is shipped. And yes, I entered the credit card number
myself.
</P>
<P>
   But as Ella and I agonized over delivery options _ she thought
it would be reasonable to pay an additional $10.99 for overnight
delivery, while I favored the more frugal $3.99 standard shipping
option (three to seven business days) _ I began to feel the first
twinges of doubt.
</P>
<P>
   That is because I realized that placing an online order would
probably not get the book to us faster. In fact, we might get a
copy sooner if we just walked into a bookstore on the release date
and grabbed one from the ceiling-high stacks that the publisher
plans to distribute nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we were opting for convenience. Online booksellers must
wait _ like everyone else _ for the book's release date before
shipping. An Amazon spokeswoman told me that the company would ship
from its seven regional distribution sites ``after midnight on July
8.'' So the earliest an Amazon customer could get a copy would be
on July 9.
</P>
<P>
   Did we really need the book any sooner? Truthfully, no. Because
then we would just finish it that much faster and Ella would start
asking me when we could buy the fifth book in the series. It seemed
more valuable for Ella to have a talisman. She wrote our Amazon
order number in her official Harry Potter notebook. It's on the
page with questions she is compiling for the author, J.K. Rowling,
who I hope will be prepared to discuss such minutiae as the details
of Harry's prescription for eyeglasses if Ella ever tracks her
down.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it was enough to know that a copy of the book would be
ready and waiting for Ella on the release date. She had a
guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   But did she? I started thinking about a number of recent
disasters that occurred after shoppers flocked online to place
orders for long-anticipated, highly publicized products, like
Handspring's Visor personal digital assistant and Palm Computing's
collapsible keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Handspring had to halt online sales temporarily
because of unexpectedly high demand. And there is currently a wait
of at least two weeks for the Palm keyboards, which made their
debut in February. The company is scrambling to speed up production
to meet demand, but as of last week it had no firm date for when
the backlog would end.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Garrigus, a Palm spokeswoman, told me last week, ``We
knew it would be popular, but the demand has exceeded
expectations.'' The problem is, she said, that ``you have to have
enough bandwidth on your assembly line to make it, as well as
enough components to build it.''
</P>
<P>
   Could Scholastic Books, the U.S. publisher of the Harry Potter
books, face similar problems? I called to find out.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jacobs, the senior vice president of Scholastic's trade
division, tried to reassure me. ``Yes, it's been beyond our wildest
expectations,'' Jacobs said. ``But we're taking every possible
measure we can to anticipate how large the demand is going to be
and to meet it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he declined to say exactly how many copies Scholastic
planned to print, Jacobs said the figure was in the millions.
``It's big,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Online orders give the publisher an advantage in calculating the
size of the first printing. That's because the return rate, the
number of unsold books that retailers send back to the publisher,
is lower for online sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people have put their money down on these books, or their
credit cards, it's almost guaranteed that the copies are in fact
spoken for,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we'll get our copy right away?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do our best,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   I accepted that answer for now. I wonder if he would mind if I
called him back 416 more times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1835EDT &QL; 
