<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DRUGS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, GOP DRAW BATTLE LINES OVER MEDICARE COVERAGE OF DRUGS
 &HT;    690&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and his Republican foes drew
sharp battle lines Wednesday over competing election-year plans for
adding prescription drug benefits to Medicare, the federal health
insurance program for senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was ``encouraged'' that Republicans have
proposed such benefits, and he insisted that they and congressional
Democrats should be able to work out compromise legislation this
year.
</P>
<P>
   But the president blasted the GOP proposal as too limited,
calling it a ``phantom'' plan that could not be paid for under the
huge tax cut that congressional Republicans endorsed two weeks ago
in their $1.83 trillion budget resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would leave nothing left for a prescription drug benefit,''
Clinton said at a White House event to spotlight the issue. ``Any
prescription drug plan that is not adequately financed is not
available in fact, is not affordable to all, and therefore is not a
real plan at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan calls for $40 billion over five years to
help pay for prescription drugs for low-income Medicare recipients.
It calls for subsidies for other Medicare recipients who opt for
privately run prescription drug insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
   The approach is expected to be woven into a broader approach to
Medicare reform to be taken up by the Senate Finance Committee as
early as May.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, working closely with the White House, are finishing
up their own proposal for a plan to spend $195 billion over 10
years, providing a prescription drug benefit to any Medicare
recipient who wants the coverage.
</P>
<P>
   By covering millions of Medicare beneficiaries, the White House
claims, the plan would let recipients take advantage of the same
sort of volume discounts that drugstores give participants in large
private insurance plans.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have criticized that approach as too large and
unneeded. The GOP plan provides help to those who most need it, the
nation's poor, said House Republican Conference Chairman J.C.
Watts, R-Okla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans want to help seniors who rely on prescription
drugs but simply cannot afford them,'' Watts said in a prepared
statement. ``We want to protect Medicare, not recklessly bankrupt
the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Watts said the White House approach to volume purchases and the
discounts that come with them reflected a ``socialist mentality''
that ``does not work.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton countered that the Republican plan, by limiting the bulk
of its benefits to low-income recipients _ those with incomes below
$12,500 a year in the case of individuals _ it would exclude nearly
half of all the Medicare beneficiaries who currently lack
prescription drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials also argue that political support for
Medicare would be weakened if important benefits were withheld from
those who paid the most payroll taxes to support the program.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties accused the other of using the issue to shore up
the support of senior citizens ahead of November's presidential and
congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats insist on making life-saving drugs a campaign
issue,'' said Watts.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., said Republicans had
embraced the idea of prescription drug coverage _ first put forward
by Clinton more than a year ago _ only in recent weeks, after polls
showed that Democrats led Republicans nearly 2 to 1 in voters'
perceptions of which party showed greater interest in the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, we're close enough to the election next fall that
Republicans have decided that they can't continue simply to
stonewall on prescription drug coverage,'' Gephardt told reporters
at the White House. ``Unfortunately, their program is fundamentally
flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem of rising prescription drug prices was highlighted
by the release of a report showing that prices for the 50
prescription drugs most widely used by seniors have risen, on
average, twice as fast as the inflation rate over the past six
years.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, 11 drugs rose four times faster than inflation,
according to research compiled by Families USA, a non-profit
Washington-based organization that claims to represent health care
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The issue is also of high concern to AARP, the nation's largest
retiree group. Its data show that one-fourth of Medicare recipients
over the age of 65 spent an estimated $3,000 of their own money
last year on medical expenses not covered by their Medicare
insurance plans. A large portion of those out-of-pocket expenses
went to purchase prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk is cheap. Prescription drugs are not,'' said Gephardt.
``They're expensive, and they're getting more expensive every day.
Seniors need help now.''
</P>
<P>
   In a related move, Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., announced plans
to introduce legislation that would prohibit drug makers from
charging higher prices to Americans than they charge for comparable
medications sold abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton said his office has done research showing that
prescription drugs are often sold in Canada, Mexico and elsewhere
around the world for a fraction of the prices charged in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, he said, is that drug manufacturers seek to recoup
their production costs, as well as their research and development
costs, through their U.S. sales, while only hoping to recover
manufacturing costs through their sales overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the research and development work that leads to new
drugs, however,
</P>
<P>
   is funded through U.S. government grants or by the National
Institutes of Health in Bethesda, Md., said Gorton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current system leaves Americans feeling ripped off,''
Gorton said at a Capitol Hill news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies counter that they price their products in
accordance with local markets.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton's bill would amend a 65-year-old law that forbids price
discrimination from one state to another. His legislation would add
to that bill price discrimination between U.S. and overseas
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans should not pay higher prices for their prescription
drugs in order to allow foreign customers to pay lower prices for
precisely the same drug,'' said Gorton. ``My bill is aimed at
curing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans's e-mail address is bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
