<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-CHIEFS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REBEL STATE EDUCATORS ENDORSE GOP EDUCATION PLAN
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rebelling against their peers, eight state
superintendents and commissioners of education Wednesday endorsed a
Republican proposal to give states much more flexibility in
spending federal education dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``State education agencies on average are forced to use over 40
percent of their staff time to deal with paperwork required by
federal programs, which make up only 6 percent of their education
budget,'' Virginia Secretary of Education Wilbert Bryant said as
the Education Leaders Council became the first national group of
educators to endorse the GOP approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``States want much more flexibility with all their federal
funds, including Title I,'' which consists of funds currently
earmarked by the federal government for use only in schools with
many low-income students, Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP plan endorsed by the eight-state council is called the
Academic Achievement for All Act, or the Straight A's Act. It is in
a major education bill that the Senate will take up next week.
</P>
<P>
   Today, federal grants are earmarked for specific purposes such
as reducing class size, educating children of migrants, educating
the disabled, opposing drug abuse or boosting the budgets of
schools in which most of the children come from poor families.
</P>
<P>
   The Straight A's Act would give each state the option of
choosing to ignore most federal restrictions when it decides how to
spend its federal grants. States that choose that option would have
to set academic standards for their students, with the risk of
losing federal funds if their students don't reach those standards
within five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a state leader, and someone offered to hand me a
check and say the only condition is that you have to tell me in
five years whether it did any good, I'd love it too,'' said Michael
Cohen, assistant secretary for elementary and secondary education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Straight A's doesn't require any tough-minded intervention in
low-performing schools, which is the hallmark of real
accountability for results,'' Cohen charged.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., said the act's sponsors welcomed the
endorsement by the officials from Arizona, Colorado, Florida,
Georgia, Michigan, Pennsylvania, Texas and Virginia, who oversee
the education of more than 14 million students, or 30 percent of
those in American public schools.
</P>
<P>
   But he conceded that virtually all other national education
organizations _ including the older, 46-state Council of Chief
State School Officers, to which some of the rebels still belong _
oppose the Straight A's Act.
</P>
<P>
   Carnie Hayes, director of federal-state relations for the
46-state group, said, ``a lot of this is just general revenue
sharing or block granting, in which the federal money wouldn't be
targeted to the neediest places or connected to national
priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that unless the Straight A's portion is deleted, her
organization will oppose the entire bill.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: Education Leaders Council,
http://www.edreform.com/elc; Council of Chief State School Officers
_ http://www.ccsso.org
</P>
<P>
   Andy Mollison's e-mail address is andym(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
