<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHWEST-PASSAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TO UNDERTAKE `NORTHWEST PASSAGE' VOYAGE THROUGH CANADA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ America's newest military icebreaker, the
Coast Guard's USCGC Healy, is preparing to undertake a politically
sensitive voyage through Arctic waters claimed by Canada, officials
confirmed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the United States has secured permission from Ottawa,
the journey through the legendary Northwest Passage is likely to
trigger public controversy in Canada, which regards the labyrinth
of usually-frozen channels of its huge northern archipelago as an
internal waterway.
</P>
<P>
   The United States asserts the Northwest Passage is an
international waterway and that commercial and military vessels
should have the right to free navigation of the icy lanes linking
the North Atlantic to the rich markets of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, the United States enraged its northern neighbor by
sending the icebreaker Polar Sea through the passage in a direct
challenge to Canadian sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the United States apparently hopes to avoid a
confrontation with its close ally and largest trading partner.
Washington asked permission to send the powerful cutter through the
passage in July on its maiden voyage to its home port in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mutual agreement has been reached through an exchange of
diplomatic notes,'' said Buck Shinkman, spokesman for the US
Embassy in Ottawa. ``There has been no settlement of the overall
question (of the status of the Northwest Passage), but there is a
go-ahead for this particular voyage.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently completed at the Avondale Industries shipyard in New
Orleans, the 420-foot Healy, which displaces 16,000 tons, is the
first icebreaker built by the United States in a quarter-century,
said Philip McGillivary, science liaison for Coast Guard icebreaker
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ship is unarmed,'' he said. ``Although capable of search
and rescue, its primary mission is high-latitude scientific
research.''
</P>
<P>
   The vessel, which carries a crew of 75 and up to 35 scientists,
is undergoing sea trials off Greenland and next month will commence
ice tests off Canada's Baffin Island before heading west along the
treacherous sea route first charted by Norwegian explorer Roald
Amundsen in 1903-05.
</P>
<P>
   Control of the Northwest Passage looms as a potentially bitter
international controversy pitting Canada against not only the
United States, but the maritime nations of Western Europe and Asia.
In the past, Canada's insistence that it owns the passage was an
abstract matter, since the waterways running across the top of the
world are so clogged with ice as to make commercial navigation all
but impossible.
</P>
<P>
   But global warming is thinning the ice packs, and many
scientists and military analysts predict that within a decade or so
the sea lanes of the Canadian Arctic will be passable for much of
the year by ordinary vessels, including oil tankers, freighters,
vacation cruise ships and regular naval craft. That could bring
about one of the most important changes in international shipping
since completion of the Panama Canal in 1914.
</P>
<P>
   Plying the Northwest Passage between Europe and Asia shaves more
than 4,500 nautical miles off the journey by way of the Panama
Canal, saving shipping companies enoromous sums. Such an opening,
too, might finally make the transport of crude oil from the fields
of Alaska's North Slope to the cities of the American northeast,
including Boston, economically feasible.
</P>
<P>
   But Canada is alarmed that commercial use of the passage would
inevitably lead to shipwrecks and oil spills in one of the planet's
most fragile _ and unspoiled _ ecosystems.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the environmental worries are basic issues of national
security. Some Canadians fear the opening of northern waters to
world shipping could undermine the country's claim to vast Arctic
domains rich in resources but populated by only a few thousand
Eskimos and guarded by just 200 troops.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's sovereignty over the Arctic is so sensitive that the
resolutely peaceful nation has pledged to use military firepower to
enforce its claim to the Northwest Passage, if necessary.
``National security, the safety of native coastal communities, and
the protection of an extremely vulnerable ecosystem are at stake,''
Col. Pierre Leblanc, commander of Canada's northern military zone,
recently told The Globe. ``We will defend our interests.''
</P>
<P>
   But Canada's Foreign Ministry insisted Wednesday that the
government is not disturbed by the voyage of the Healy since the
United States sought permission. ``This mission is not a
provocation,'' Foreign Ministry spokesman Reynald Doiron told
reporters in Ottawa. ``The United States has sought and obtained
Canadian consent.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Canadian officials will be aboard the Healy as observers
as it threads its way from Baffin Bay to the Beaufort Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Dorion stressed that Canada is not backing away from its claim
to the waters, and said that the United States, by seeking
permission, was effectively showing respect for the Canadian claim
``even though they dispute that claim.''
</P>
<P>
   The Healy's voyage will only be the third complete transit
through the passage openly undertaken by an American military
vessel since the two countries signed a 1988 agreement on
scientific cooperation in the Arctic.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely believed by military analysts, however, that US
submarines regularly tresspass on Canadian northern waters, as do
the underwater vessels of Russia and France.
</P>
</TEXT>
