<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-NOTES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENCE RULES IN `FIGHT CLUB' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ If Seven, The Game or even Alien 3 made you a fan of
director David Fincher, you should be enthralled by Fight Club, his
most audacious _ and violent _ work yet.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface it looks reprehensible. But if you can distance
yourself from its grim mayhem, the film can be intriguing _ at
first.
</P>
<P>
   In it, men disturbed by society's corporate bent and
materialistic mind-set vent their frustrations by flailing at each
other in secret brawls, then licking twisted liberation from their
cracked lips in the form of their own spilled blood.
</P>
<P>
   Their leader is Tyler (Brad Pitt), a revolutionary soap salesman
(don't ask _ it fits) who intellectually seduces miserable
white-collar worker Jack (Edward Norton).
</P>
<P>
   Soon Jack is living with Tyler in a decaying house, where Tyler
trysts with the troubled Marla (Helena Bonham Carter).
</P>
<P>
   Others join, and Tyler becomes the virtual fascist dictator of
an army of street fighters turned anti-establishment terrorists.
For Jack _ and the viewer _ things get out of hand, and it only
gets worse, as the film degenerates into a bloody blur.
</P>
<P>
   But the leads are superb. Pitt is persuasively articulate with
his charismatic swagger, while Norton is a study in defiant,
fiercely focused anger.
</P>
<P>
   As for Fincher, he keeps the pedal to the metal with a darkly
exhilarating style, even when it is used at the service of
sickening scenes.
</P>
<P>
   The fights will be too brutal for some, but fast-forward
controls should make the film easier to digest on video. And that's
a good thing, for despite its bloody mess, Fight Club offers food
for thought.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, after an absorbing first half, those thoughts
are engulfed in a flood of blood and yet another gimmicky plot
twist. It's as if Fincher wants to one-up The Sixth Sense, The
Usual Suspects and The Crying Game in one delirious swoop.
</P>
<P>
   He also falters via reliance on mere violence in response to
society's false values. Violence is just as false, and no film that
wallows in it can pretend to be hostile toward it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Fight Club's carnage is emblematic of Hollywood's own
false values, which are no less driven by commerce than those of
the heartless car manufacturer for which Jack toils.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, violence sells. In the '30s it was feel-good
musicals. Today it's spectacular violence.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the ratings board. If movies were rated as
stringently for violence as they are for sex, violence would be
toned down and manageable. But they aren't, and the limits for
violence are continually pushed.
</P>
<P>
   Even such mainstream directors as Steven Spielberg have upped
the ante toward explicit gore while still making millions in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, violence has become a narrative cure-all for box-office
uncertainties. It's as much of a cliche and a cop-out as the
mass-market products Fight Club ridicules and reviles.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't have to be that way. In the far more turbulent
'60s, The Graduate's Dustin Hoffman didn't respond to youthful
disenchantment with ``plastic'' society by detonating bombs but by
pursuing reckless romance.
</P>
<P>
   And in the far more materialistic '80s, the yuppies of Lost in
America (Albert Brooks and Julie Hagerty) took an amusingly naive,
Easy Rider-style jaunt to free themselves from work-world tyranny.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers today seem to want no part of either approach. They
take the sadly safe commercial route of increasingly vivid
violence. Fincher hasn't made a nonviolent movie yet, and even his
themes are getting repetitious.
</P>
<P>
   In Fight Club, as in The Game, he shows a man stifled by
capitalism who comes alive only by facing mortal danger. Fincher's
answer to everything seems to be make-believe battles and gallons
of fake blood.
</P>
<P>
   The big baby. Fight Club may preach growth and liberation, but
it's utterly dependent on juvenile infatuations with thrill-ride
catharses to rub that message in your face.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
