<HEADER>
A7944 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WONDERLAND-NYT &LR;      04-26 1412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WONDERLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARKNESS FINDS NO ASYLUM FROM TV'S REALITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD WEINRAUB    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Are there some network series, no matter how well
received by critics, that are doomed by their gritty themes?
</P>
<P>
   To Peter Berg, who created ABC's ``Wonderland,'' about patients
and doctors in the psychiatric unit of a New York hospital, the
answer is an unmistakable yes. The series, which was heavily
promoted and earned strongly favorable reviews, was abruptly
canceled after its second episode on April 6 because of a
precipitous decline in its ratings.
</P>
<P>
   To Berg the cancellation was ``completely irrational.'' He said
that ABC executives aborted ``Wonderland'' without warning, even
before the show had a chance to find an audience as it faced the
enduring NBC powerhouse ``E.R.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, ABC executives said that as proud as they
were of the unsettling series, ``Wonderland'' was simply rejected
by audiences, who probably found it too dark and harrowing. Those
executives said that viewers were turned off by the show and that
neither protests from mental health professionals nor the
skittishness of some advertisers had any bearing on their decision.
ABC had ordered eight episodes, which leaves six unseen on
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to interpret the behavior of ABC
executives,'' said Berg. ``I'm not privy to what goes on behind
closed doors at their meetings. But I know that when I was told by
Stu Bloomberg, the co-chairman, that the show was not able to find
an audience and was in the process of being rejected by audiences,
I literally had to laugh. I thought he was kidding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're telling me that the show could not find an audience
after two episodes while it was being pitted against one of the
most popular series in the history of television,'' said Berg, a
film and television actor who spent nearly seven months researching
the show at the forensic psychiatric unit of Bellevue Hospital in
Manhattan. ``It's absurd. The behavior of ABC in regards to
`Wonderland' is completely irrational by any standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Even rival television programmers said that ABC may have acted a
bit quickly but that such action was justified. The days of letting
a series ``breathe,'' or take its time to find an audience, are
just about over, those executives said. And this was especially
true of a dark drama like ``Wonderland.'' Although hit shows like
``Seinfeld,'' and ``The Practice'' began slowly and were able to
snare audiences, they said, those series hardly came with the
baggage of ``Wonderland.''
</P>
<P>
   So will the failure of a show like this one make it harder for
others with dark themes to prevail on network television?
</P>
<P>
   ``By their very nature most risky shows will probably not
work,'' said Lloyd Braun, co-chairman with Bloomberg of the ABC
Entertainment Television group. ``But you will, at some point, have
a breakout hit by taking those types of risks.''
</P>
<P>
   The show itself, which was made in an abandoned wing of the
Creedmoor Psychiatric Center in Queens, took viewers into the lives
of patients with severe emotional and chemical disorders, some of
them violent. The show starred Ted Levine as the stern and
thoughtful head of a criminal psychiatry department. In the opening
episode a patient tries to harm himself with a syringe, and in the
scuffle that follows the needle pierces the stomach of a pregnant
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Caryn James, reviewing ``Wonderland'' in The New York Times,
called it gripping and dazzling. ``The uncompromising `Wonderland'
is worth every demand it makes,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Its premiere episode on March 30 was not a ratings disaster. It
was No. 2, with an average of 13.2 million viewers, behind a rerun
of ``E.R.,'' which had 14 million viewers. Nonetheless ABC
executives were alarmed by warning signs: in the show's first
half-hour, 14.8 million viewers tuned in. But by the episode's
second half-hour _ after the pregnant doctor was injured _ the
audience had dropped to 11.5 million, a 22 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
   In its second week ``Wonderland'' was floundering. It lost about
20 million viewers delivered by its lead-in, ``Who Wants to be a
Millionaire,'' the No. 1 show in the nation, and wound up with an
audience of 7.5 million viewers. (The show did perform somewhat
better than CBS' Mafia series, ``Falcone,'' which also is no longer
on the air.)
</P>
<P>
   To ABC executives the decision to kill ``Wonderland'' was
plainly an uneasy one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very up front with Peter,'' Braun said. ``Everyone
knew it was a challenging time slot. However, we had the benefit of
`Millionaire' as a lead-in. We were able to launch the show. We
could not have devoted more promotion resources to the show. A lot
of people tuned in the first week. But unfortunately the tune-out
was very significant. The following week was even more significant.
We saw nothing to gain by continuing in that time slot.''
</P>
<P>
   Braun said that there had been some backlash among advertisers
because the show was so bleak, but that this played no role in the
network's decision. Nor was the network swayed by complaints from
groups including the National Alliance for the Mentally Ill that
``Wonderland'' reinforced stereotypes about mental illness, he
said. (``Wonderland'' earned the cooperation of top doctors at
Bellevue's forensic psychiatric service.)
</P>
<P>
   Braun said that ABC took pride in the show, an offbeat one for
network television. The network spent heavily on producing and
promoting the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very proud of the work Peter did on the show, and we
have no second thoughts about our decision to air it,'' said Braun.
``Clearly `Wonderland' pushed the envelope in a way few shows have
done, and I hope we will continue to take these types of chances in
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg said he was now working on two series for HBO but declined
to discuss their subjects. That cable network is the home of some
of the most provocative series on television, including ``The
Sopranos,'' about a Mafia family in New Jersey, and ``Oz,'' a
prison drama. Executives there indicated that there was a slim
possibility that the setting for ``Wonderland'' could be used for
an HBO series.
</P>
<P>
   Network executives at ABC and elsewhere said it would be unfair
to regard the early death of ``Wonderland'' as a symbol of
television's indifference to serious shows. Successful series as
different as NBC's ``West Wing,'' ABC's ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' and Fox's
``Party of Five'' tackle serious issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't `Law and Order' a serious show?'' asked Leslie Moonves,
CBS' president and chief executive. ``Isn't `E.R.' a serious show?
Isn't `Judging Amy' serious? A show that's dark and bizarre may
have trouble. But there are plenty of serious shows on
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly Karey Burke, executive vice president of prime-time
series development at NBC, said: ``Of course you can tackle serious
shows. The only standard is it has to be a satisfying viewing
experience. We're broadcasters. This is network television. The
goal is to try to reach as many people as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke said that the ``gold standard'' was a show like ``E.R''
because ``it tackles very serious subject matter and is the No. 1
series on television and manages to do so in a way the people want
to come back every week.'' Shows like ``My So-Called Life'' have
struggled to tackle important issues, she said, but for one reason
or another never found audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Burke said the huge success of ``E.R.'' was based partly on a
sense that the doctors on the show, while personally flawed, were
heroic and saved lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally believe it comes down to a show about heroes,''
she said. ``It's also wish fulfillment. Everyone's nightmare is
getting sick or injured and winding up in an emergency room. Well,
if you wind up in an emergency room, you'd better believe that you
want Dr. Greene treating you.'' (Dr. Mark Greene is the noble
doctor played by Anthony Edwards on ``E.R.'')
</P>
<P>
   To ABC executives and rivals, one flaw in ``Wonderland'' was
that viewers could not identify with its troubled patients and
doctors. But Berg said that future episodes were to have been far
lighter and funnier than the first two. One was to include the
hospitalization of a comedian played by Jeremy Piven, and the
healthy birth of the child of the doctor who was stabbed with a
syringe in the first episode. ``The majority of `Wonderland,''' he
said, ``was in no way depressing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
