<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-VISIT-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRLS SAY ELIAN `LOOKED SAD' 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNIE DELINSKI   
 TimesDaily, Florence, Ala.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORENCE, Ala. _ Two young Alabama sisters who shared pizza with
Elian Gonzalez over the weekend said the young Cuban ``looked
sad.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls, 6-year-old Ashlie Fristoe and 9-year-old Brittanie
Fristoe, were staying with their grandparents at an Andrews Air
Force Base hotel when they had the encounter Saturday, the day that
federal agents grabbed the 6-year-old from his Miami relatives in a
pre-dawn raid.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my Nanny's friends called us that morning and said
where we were on the news, and we turned it on and we saw our car
on TV,'' Brittanie said during a Tuesday telephone interview while
the girls continued vacationing with their grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel at Andrews was swarming with federal agents, the girls
said. The girls and their grandparents asked the agents if the
girls could visit with Elian, said their mother, Diane Fristoe, who
stayed behind in the family's Muscle Shoals' home during her
daughters' trip. The agents asked Elian's father, who said yes.
</P>
<P>
   The girls said Elian seemed nice but didn't say much, and they
had to use an interpreter during the visit, which lasted a few
minutes. ``He looked sad,'' Brittanie said.
</P>
<P>
   Brittanie enjoyed the experience. ``I was excited,'' she said.
``We talked about our brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian's father gave them some pizza they were eating, and
Brittanie gave Elian a stuffed animal that had ``WWJD'' on it. She
had received the stuffed animal as an Easter gift. The initials
stand for ``What Would Jesus Do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he knew what it meant,'' Brittanie said.
</P>
<P>
   When they left, Elian gave Ashlie a kiss on the cheek and his
father hugged Brittanie. ``I didn't know people gave sugar to
people they don't know,'' Ashlie said.
</P>
<P>
   Brittanie and Ashlie's grandparents said Elian's room was in the
Generals' Quarters and had a cast-iron fence around it.
</P>
<P>
   When she first heard about the meeting, Diane Fristoe admits she
was skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't believe them when they called me,'' she said. But
once she realized they were serious, ``I actually told my mother
they need to stay in another hotel because somebody might bomb that
one, with everything going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Fristoe home-schools her daughters and they had discussed
Elian during lessons. Brittanie said ``I feel lucky'' to have met
Elian.
</P>
<P>
   The girls were vacationing in Washington with their
grandparents. Their grandmother, July Zills, is area manager for
the Army and Air Force Exchange Service in the Washington area and
arranged a private White House tour.
</P>
<P>
   During the White House visit, Ashlie and Brittanie petted
``first dog'' Buddy. And, Ashlie said they saw President Clinton,
``close up, playing golf'' while at the White House. They also took
part in the annual Easter Egg hunt on the White House lawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've learned so much from this weekend,'' Diane Fristoe
said. ``It's one thing to study about the White House but another
thing to visit Elian and pet Buddy.''
</P>
<P>
   The TimesDaily in Florence, Ala., is part of The New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
