<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NOTES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST MEETS IRISH IN ENGLISH FILM ABOUT PAKISTANIS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ A big hit English movie.
</P>
<P>
   A cast of Pakistani characters.
</P>
<P>
   A first-time Irish director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Born and bred in Dublin,'' Damien O'Donnell said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell fully understands why people are surprised that a
fellow who has spent almost his entire life in Ireland directed
East Is East, a comedy-drama about a Pakistani family trying to
cope with the cultures of the father's homeland and the family's
adopted country, England.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell didn't even see a foreigner until grade school.
``Ireland is famous for exporting people, but we're not very good
at returning the favor,'' O'Donnell said.
</P>
<P>
   East Is East features Indian film star Om Puri, (familiar from
such movies as My Son the Fanatic and The Ghost and the Darkness)
as George Khan, a hard-nosed father determined to make his children
follow traditional Pakistani culture, even though they have a
British mother and have been raised in swinging England.
</P>
<P>
   The film, set in the disco-era 1970s, roller coasters between
hilarity and dark drama as George becomes increasingly determined
to force his will. Each child, in turn, tries to find his or her
own way in the world. The tiny film became a mainstream English
hit, winning the Korda Award for best British film and several
other English and European awards.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the subject matter, O'Donnell was pretty surprised
when he was approached with the script, which was based on a small,
partly autobiographical play by Pakistani-English actor Ayub
Khan-Din (My Beautiful Laundrette).
</P>
<P>
   Several well-known directors had already been approached,
including Stephen Frears (High Fidelity, My Beautiful Laundrette).
Frears suggested that Khan-Din find a first-time director, and the
writer took his advice.
</P>
<P>
   But how did the writer-actor end up with an unknown Irishman?
</P>
<P>
   Since graduating from film school, O'Donnell and some
film-school partners had made mostly commercials and low-budget
``pop videos'' for Irish bands. That was fine for a time _ he was
getting paid to learn his craft. But ultimately those outlets
proved to be unsatisfying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a falling out with about every record company there
was,'' O'Donnell said. ``We were highly opinionated, and we had our
principles. We took quite a hammering over it for three or four
years. We gave up pop videos and commercials and went back to short
films.''
</P>
<P>
   He produced an award-winning short, and with the prize money, he
directed a short called 35 Aside, which won several European
festival prizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (screen) writer's girlfriend was watching TV one night
when 35 Aside came on. It's quite a visual film. She suggested,
`Why don't we talk to this guy?' ''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell may have been taken aback when he was approached about
East Is East, but any hesitation he had disappeared when he read
the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I liked was its humanity. It had great heart and soul,''
he said. ``I didn't know it had been a play, and I didn't know it
was autobiographical. But I knew reading it that whoever was
writing it was writing about events in his or her life _ things
that actually happened. Ayub had quite a traumatic childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   In the film, the author's character is the youngest son; the
character always wears a parka with the hood over his head, indoors
and out, whatever the weather. It's a kind of security blanket
against the uncomfortable world around him.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, O'Donnell felt that having never directed a
feature film also acted in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an attraction of first-time filmmakers,'' he said.
``People who have made two or three films that haven't been
successful are less attractive (to producers), even though they've
had that experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the irony of filmmaking. The least experienced person
on the crew is usually the director, if you talk about time on the
set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was exactly that man. I had shot three short films at that
stage. (On this film) I was working with (cinematographer) Brian
Tufano _ who had done Trainspotting and The Lords of Discipline and
Quadrophenia _ and a lot of other people with huge experience.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell set out to establish himself early as a director in
charge, ready to put his own stamp on the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the first day I walked on the set to assert my
authority,'' he said. ``I tripped over a cable and fell on my nose
in front of the cast and the crew. Whatever mystique I'd tried to
develop just evaporated in one go.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
