<HEADLINE>
THE WORLD AS WE DON'T KNOW IT YET
</HEADLINE>
  
 
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Alicia Bay Laurel &LR; , who in 1971 hand-drew and hand-wrote
``Living on the Earth,'' has created a 30th anniversary edition
(Villard Books; $16.95) of the hippie manual. The new book looks
like its forebear, with a line drawing of a dancing nude on the
cover, but promises new organic recipes and environmental
preservation tips among these old standbys: how to tune your
Autoharp, how to deliver a baby, how to make your own moccasins.
</P>
<P>
   Neither ``online'' nor ``computer'' nor ``Internet'' was
mentioned in the index; the publisher informed Personals that the
author could be queried about that by e-mail. ``Remaking a work
created by a teenaged girl requires some delicacy of decision,''
Laurel replied. ``It was tempting to overlay my 50-year-old self's
greater sophistication, but I tried to stay as close to the spirit
of the original as I could.'' She noted that Web site addresses are
included in the appendix.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Foods on the horizon, as reported in the Futurist: The
``conewich,'' a piece of bread that wraps around sandwich filling,
in a cone shape that ``allows snackers to hold it nearly in one
hand _ ideal for cell phone addicts on the go.'' Also, scrambled
eggs on a stick and an elevator-type device that helps with the
removal of pickles from jars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Tomorrow, the last Friday in April, is National Hairball Awareness
Day, a day set aside by Kansas organizers to ``recognize hairballs
in cats _ the inconvenience created for owners and the discomfort
suffered by our feline friends.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_The 45-foot-long Humvee limo, which costs $300,000 and up, is ``no
more of a menace than a big semi,'' Huntington Beach Humvee
salesman  &UR; Mike Sabbarese &LR;  told Mother Jones magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I've worked with many athletes and I have never seen a
sports &LR; 
 &UR; guy so comfortable in front of a camera. Michael Jordan came &LR; 
 &UR; across as a professional actor who has been doing movies all his &LR; 
 &UR; life. But he told me that he never intends to act again. He said &LR; 
 &UR; he was comfortable with what he had done with his life, with his &LR; 
 &UR; niche as the owner of the Washington Wizards, and he wants to &LR; 
 &UR; leave it at that.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Director  &UR; Jim &LR;   &UR; Stern &LR; , at a New York premiere party for
``It's the Rage,'' an anti-gun movie in which Jordan appears, along
with stars  &UR; Jeff Daniels &LR; ,  &UR; Andre Braugher &LR; ,  &UR; Gary &LR;   &UR; Sinise &LR; ,  &UR; Josh
