<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE YOUR FEMINISM TO WORK DAY
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Boldface ``Children'' in 10th graf should be italicized.) 
 By LISA BELKIN 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than 19 million girls are expected to play hooky
from school on Thursday for a lesson their parents consider even
more important.
</P>
<P>
   It's the eighth annual Take Our Daughters to Work Day, which was
created to give adolescent girls a peek at a limitless future.
</P>
<P>
   I used to be a girl. And as books that had not even been written
back then would have predicted, I lost much confidence in myself _
and all interest in math _ at the stroke of age 12. (Most of the
confidence has come back; not so for the math.) As a former girl,
and as a feminist and defender of girls, I am thrilled by Take Our
Daughters to Work Day. But as the mother of two young sons, I am
torn.
</P>
<P>
   I do not for a moment question that this is good for girls.
``It's a national intervention,'' said Marie Wilson, the president
of the Ms. Foundation for Women, which started the day for girls.
``It sends a positive message to girls and focuses on their
potential.'' That message is heard, she added, only ``if the boys
are not there _ otherwise, the boys take over and everyone reverts
to the behaviors we are trying to address in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's stop for a moment and talk about those boys. If we as a
country have learned anything in the last year, it is that they
also are in trouble. They are shooting, and being shot, using drugs
and being medicated for behavioral disorders, far more than their
sisters. As parents we are frightened for them.
</P>
<P>
   Even Mary Bray Pipher, author of ``Reviving Ophelia: Saving the
Selves of Adolescent Girls'' (Ballantine Books, 1995), warns that
it is time to pay more attention to the boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``An event like this comes out of a certain place and time,''
she says, treading carefully, trying not to directly attack Take
Our Daughters to Work Day. ``But the farther you get from that
place and time, the less likely it is to be fitting and
appropriate. No one would make the argument now that boys have an
easy time in middle school and high school.''
</P>
<P>
   What I'm wrestling with, I admit, is less the welfare of all
boys than the specific needs of two particular boys: a
kindergartener who recently insisted that girls can't be doctors
(even though two of his pediatricians are women) but who is
fascinated by the fact that one of my editors is a ``he'' and one
is a ``she''; and a third-grader who loves to compare the
techniques I use in my articles with the ones he uses when writing
his reports on the Arctic and the Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   Every night they ask me, ``How was your day?'' Would it be a
boon or a blow to feminism if, I show them?
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, the mother of three sons and two daughters, believes it
would be a little of both. Although she is all for raising feminist
sons, she warns that the trend toward companies' opting for ``Take
Our  &UR; Children &LR;  to Work'' days is diluting the point. The Ms.
Foundation, she explains, has created a separate program _
``Working It Out: Especially for Boys'' _ to be taught to those who
are left in the classroom while the girls head to the office. But
if my children's school is at all typical, the program is not
widely used, and the day is a wasted one for the boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't teach anything new that day,'' says my older son's
teacher. Adds his principal, in her strictest principal voice:
``Why on earth do they schedule this during the school year? You
know, it's not a legal absence.''
</P>
<P>
   No, but, done right, it can be an educational one.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly is at The New York Times, where each year hundreds
of daughters energize the building with their presence and produce
their own remarkable newspaper. It is called Girls' Times, and
three years ago, its lead editorial was an impassioned plea to end
a practice it called ``needlessly discriminatory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Times have changed,'' the girls wrote. ``Daughters already
know they can become lawyers, engineers or golf professionals. Sons
as well as daughters can benefit from seeing what their fathers and
mothers do at work.'' In the title of their editorial, they
advised: ``Take Your Sons to Work, Too.''
</P>
<P>
   With apologies to the principal, I plan to take that advice.
</P>
<P>
   My older son will spend the day helping me conduct interviews
for a magazine piece, then joining me back home in my office where
we'll each write an article about what we learned.
</P>
<P>
   Next year _ fair is fair _ it will be his brother's turn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
