<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS GEAR UP FOR MAY SWEEPS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAY HANDELMAN   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can travel back in time to the days of Jesus, Jason and the
Argonauts, Ali Baba and his 40 thieves, or to the more recent past
when Watergate and Vietnam and ``The Brady Bunch'' took over the
news and television sets.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for the May ratings sweeps, and in addition to those
``extra-special'' episodes of your favorite shows, along with
season and series finales, you'll find the major broadcast networks
offering a range of mini-series and one-night movies basking in a
historical glow.
</P>
<P>
   Networks vie for viewers during sweep periods, when ratings are
crucial in the pricing of commercials for an entire business
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brady Bunch'' is the subject of two behind-the-scenes
movies during the month, and ``Diff'rent Strokes'' also is
remembered in a one-hour film.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is offering a week of celebrity editions of ``Who Wants to
be a Millionaire,'' that will run May 1-5, with such stars as David
Duchovny and Rosie O'Donnell trying for a chance in the hot seat
and to win money for charity.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will bid farewell to its long-running ``Beverly Hills,
90210'' and ``Party of Five,'' both of which have more than worn
out their welcomes. ``Party of Five'' ends its six-year run on May
3, while the former high school students on ``90210'' say goodbye
in a two-hour finale on May 17, after a one-hour special look back
on May 10.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Fletcher is back in a two-hour movie, Drew Carey sings
in ``Gepetto,'' Chad Lowe pretends to sing as John Denver, and
Michael J. Fox bids his own farewell to his hit comedy ``Spin
City.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at some sweep's highlights.
</P>
<P>
   April 28
</P>
<P>
   ``Cosby,'' 8:30-9 p.m. CBS. Hilton (Bill Cosby) and Ruth
(Phylicia Rashad) say goodbye after four seasons by looking back on
how they've survived 30 years of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   April 30
</P>
<P>
   ``Arabian Nights'' 9-11 p.m. ABC. Schariar (Dougray Scott) plans
to kill his new wife, Scheherazade, who saves her life by capturing
his imagination with tales from the Arabian Nights. The large cast
in this Robert Halmi, special-effects laden mini-series includes
Alan Bates, Jason Scott Lee, Rufus Sewell and John Leguizamo. The
special concludes at 9-11 p.m. May 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '70s'' 9-11 p.m. NBC. Following on the success of last
spring's ``The '60s,'' NBC moves ahead one decade with this
two-part mini-series that looks at the politics and culture of the
era, focusing on four young people just getting started in the era.
NBC is releasing a soundtrack to accompany the series. The film
concludes at 9-11 p.m. May 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take Me Home: The John Denver Story,'' 9-11 p.m. CBS. Chad
Lowe, remembered for his role as a young AIDS patient in ``Life
Goes On,'' and as the teary-eyed husband of new Oscar winner Hilary
Swank, stars as the late folksinger in this biographical film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Files,'' 9 p.m. Fox. Tea Leoni (Mrs. David Duchovny) and
Garry Shandling appear in this episode portraying FBI agents Mulder
and Scully in a film version of their work.
</P>
<P>
   May 1
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire'' 8 p.m. ABC. The hit game show
kicks off a week of celebrity contestants playing for charity.
Featuring Ray Romano, David Duchovny, Kathie Lee Gifford, Drew
Carey and Rosie O'Donnell. Through Friday, with additional regular
installments during the month.
</P>
<P>
   May 3
</P>
<P>
   ``Party of Five,'' 8-10 p.m., Fox. After six years of crises,
the Sallinger family says its final farewell in ``All's Well That
Ends Well.'' After abusive relationships, soured romances, death
and near-fatal illnesses, the series may offer some happy tears in
the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Academy of Country Music Awards,'' 8-11 p.m. CBS. The 35th
annual edition of this popular awards show features host Dolly
Parton.
</P>
<P>
   May 7
</P>
<P>
   ``Gepetto,'' 7-9 p.m. ABC. Drew Carey and Brent Spiner star in
this ``Wonderful World of Disney'' musical version of
``Pinocchio.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason and the Argonauts,'' 9-11 p.m. NBC. Jason London, whose
twin brother played Griffin in ``Party of Five'' for several years,
has the right name to headline NBC's two-part film about Jason's
efforts to find the Golden Fleece in ancient Greece. Dennis Hopper
also stars. Concludes 9-11 p.m. May 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cupid &AMP; Cate,'' 9-11 p.m. CBS. Peter Gallagher, Mary Louise
Parker and Bebe Neuwirth star in this ``Hallmark Hall of Fame''
romantic comedy about a young woman whose life changes when her
sisters play cupid.
</P>
<P>
   May 9
</P>
<P>
   ``The Smartest Kid in America,'' 8-10 p.m., Fox. Here's
something different from Fox, a special that seeks out the
brightest students across the country. Dick Clark is the host.
</P>
<P>
   May 10
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's to You Charlie Brown: 50 Great Years;'' 8-9 p.m. CBS.
Whoopi Goldberg is host of this salute to the popular cartoon
character. Faith Hill performs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   May 12
</P>
<P>
   ``Gloria Estefan, Caribbean Soul: The Atlantis Concert,'' 8-9
p.m. CBS. The popular singer stars in her first network TV special,
with guests Marc Anthony and 'N Sync.
</P>
<P>
   ``49th Annual Miss Universe Pageant,'' 9-11 p.m. CBS. Women from
more than 80 countries compete for the coveted title.
</P>
<P>
   May 14
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus,'' 9-11 p.m., CBS. Jeremy Sisto has the title role in
this two-part series on the life of Christ. Gary Oldman plays
Pontius Pilate; Jacqueline Bisset, who last season played the
mother of Joan of Arc, plays Mary, and ``Will &AMP; Grace'' star Debra
Messing plays Mary Magdalene. Armin Mueller-Stahl, the father in
``Shine,'' plays Joseph. Concludes at 9-11 p.m. May 17.
</P>
<P>
   May 15
</P>
<P>
   ``25 Years of No. 1 Hits: Arista Records Anniversary
Celebration,'' 8-10 p.m. NBC. Recording stars Whitney Houston,
Carlos Santana, Sara McLachlan and others join a tribute to the
record label and founder Clive Davis.
</P>
<P>
   May 16
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brady Bunch,'' 8-9 p.m., Fox. A dramatized look at life
behind the camera at the 1970s sitcom. (See also ``Growing Up
Brady,'' May 21.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Diff'rent Strokes,'' 9-10 p.m. Fox. ``What 'choo talkin' about
Willis?'' Another one-hour dramatized look at the 1980s comedy
whose young stars Gary Coleman, Todd Bridges and the late Dana
Plato ended up leading troubled lives.
</P>
<P>
   May 17
</P>
<P>
   ``Beverly Hills, 90210,'' 8-10 p.m. Fox. Long graduated from
high school and college, the Beverly Hills gang says farewell after
10 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Judds Reunion: The Power to Change,'' 8-9 p.m. CBS. Naomi
and Wynona (joined by Ashley Judd) star in this special taped at
Rupp Stadium in their hometown, Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   May 18
</P>
<P>
   ``Murder She Wrote: A Story to Die For,'' 9-11 p.m. CBS. Angela
Lansbury is back as mystery writer and amateur sleuth Jessica
Fletcher, who investigates the murder of an author on a book about
the KGB.
</P>
<P>
   May 19
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dukes of Hazzard: Hazzard in Hollywood,'' 9-11 pm. CBS.
Who'd have thought we'd ever see those playful Duke boys again? Tom
Wopat, John Schneider and Catherine Bach star in this reunion film
that takes them to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   May 21
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing Up Brady,'' 9-11 p.m. NBC. A look at life behind the
scenes at the popular family sitcom ``The Brady Bunch,'' based on
Barry Williams' book. Williams, who played Greg Brady, appears in
the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Linda McCartney Story,'' 9-11 p.m. CBS. George Segal,
Elizabeth Mitchell and Gary Bakewell star in this biographical film
that traces her life from meeting Paul McCartney through her cancer
diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   May 23
</P>
<P>
   ``Opening the Tombs of the Golden Mummies Live,'' 8-10 p.m. Fox.
Geraldo Rivera came up empty handed when he opened Al Capone's
vault several years ago. Let's hope Hugh Downs will find something
more interesting in this special.
</P>
<P>
   May 24
</P>
<P>
   ``Spin City,'' 9 p.m. ABC. Michael J. Fox's final episode in
this funny series about life in the New York City mayor's office.
Judd Nelson takes over next season. Michael Gross, who played Fox's
father on ``Family Ties'' is a guest star.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., which is a member of The
