<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: AMERICAN OBSERVER DEPORTED
</P>
<P>
   Ted Lewis, the director for Mexico of the San Francisco human
rights group Global Exchange, was detained by immigration agents in
Guadalajara and deported. Lewis was organizing 40 foreign
professors to study election conditions before the July 2
presidential balloting. The autonomous Federal Electoral Institute
had approved his credentials as an election observer.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE: PINOCHET HEARING
</P>
<P>
   An appeals court opened a hearing into arguments about whether
it should strip Gen. Augusto Pinochet of his legislative immunity
as a senator before he can stand trial for human rights violations
that occurred during his rule between 1973 and 1990. The three-day
hearing is only the beginning of what promises to be a long legal
battle. If Pinochet loses his immunity, defense lawyers are
expected to appeal to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: OPPOSITION TO CANDIDATE
</P>
<P>
   The presidential candidate supported by major political party
leaders, Ahmet Necdet Sezer, faced quiet but growing opposition
before Thursday's first ballot. Some members of Parliament, which
must choose the next president, said they had been told Sezer was
either too liberal, too sympathetic to Islam, or too critical of
the military. The speaker of Parliament, Yildirim Akbulut, is his
most prominent opponent.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: SELF-DEFENSE DISPUTE
</P>
<P>
   The Conservative Party leader William Hague called for a radical
overhaul of the law of self-defense after a public outcry over the
murder conviction of a Norfolk man who shot an intruder at his
farm. Chief Constable Crispian Strachan of the rural Northumbria
Police said the law permitting use of ``reasonable force'' worked
well enough and that Hague's idea would generate American-style
levels of violent assault and killing in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: PREMIER WINS APPROVAL
</P>
<P>
   Parliament voted 202-148 to approve a second term for the
center-right Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar, whom voters
re-elected March 12 with an unexpected outright majority. In the
two-day investiture debate, Aznar, 47, promised more reforms to
maintain economic growth and a firm stance against armed Basque
separatists.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: 5 CONVICTED IN BASQUE DEATHS
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Enrique Rodriguez Galindo of the Civil Guard and four other
officials who also served under Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez were
sentenced to up to 71 years each in prison for their roles in the
1983 murders of two suspected members of the Basque separatist
group ETA. Two people were acquitted, including a former senior
interior ministry official. It was the second major trial looking
into a shadowy campaign blamed for the deaths of 27 suspected
Basque rebels in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: DROUGHT RELIEF
</P>
<P>
   The government has begun a large-scale relief effort for the
drought-stricken states of Rajasthan and Gujarat. It will send
wheat and rice, fodder for cattle and water to the hardest-hit
areas. Officials say the country has ample grain stores to prevent
a famine. No deaths have been attributed to the drought.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: ENVOY REBUFFED
</P>
<P>
   A former Russian ambassador to the United Nations and the United
States, Yuli M. Vorontsov, has been rebuffed by the Iraqis as he
tried to reopen an investigation into Kuwaiti prisoners still
missing after Iraq's invasion and occupation of Kuwait in 1990.
Vorontsov, whom Secretary-General Kofi Annan of the United Nations
appointed in February, reported to the Security Council that he is
still seeking a meeting with the Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: OPPOSITION WARNING
</P>
<P>
   The leader of Zimbabwe's opposition, Morgan Tsvangirai, said his
Movement for Democratic Change, which saw two more of its
supporters killed Tuesday in political violence, would not stand by
and watch as government loyalists continued to attack its members.
At least five backers of the new opposition party have died in the
last 10 days in attacks by people claiming to be supporters of
President Robert Mugabe's ruling party. The opposition has urged
its members to observe the law.
</P>
</TEXT>
