<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7969 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-U.S.-HOLOCAUST-ART-NY     04-26 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-HOLOCAUST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXILE'S HEIRS CLAIM A PICASSO AT THE MODERN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Texas, Minn.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 18 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The heirs of a Jewish art collector whose home was
looted by German occupation troops in October 1940 believe that one
of hundreds of paintings seized on that occasion now hangs in the
Museum of Modern Art in New York. The painting, Picasso's ``Still
Life: Job,'' of 1916, is among 15 works recently identified by the
museum as having incomplete provenance records from the World War
II era.
</P>
<P>
   Francis Warin, who represents the heirs of Alphonse Kann, one of
France's most important prewar collectors, said that he had
photographs showing the small Cubist work on the wall of Kann's
home in St.-Germain-en-Laye outside Paris in the late 1920s. He
said there was no evidence that the oil was sold on the market
before the Nazi raid on the house, in which Kann's entire
collection of more than 1,000 works was seized.
</P>
<P>
   Warin raised the possibility that the Picasso belonged to the
Kann estate in a letter last year to Glenn D. Lowry, the director
of the Museum of Modern Art. Lowry said in an interview Wednesday
that he had since been working closely with Warin to research and
clarify the case. Warin in turn praised Lowry's ``exemplary way of
handling this.'' Both parties agreed that a solution was not
imminent, since crucial evidence was missing.
</P>
<P>
   Warin, a retired television producer, has spent the last five
years trying to trace artworks taken by the Nazis from Kann, who
was his great uncle. Warin was first alerted to the problem by
``The Lost Museum,'' a book by an American journalist, Hector
Feliciano, that asserted that the French authorities had been less
than diligent in finding the true owners of looted works recovered
after the Allied victory. The book was published in English in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Kann, who fled to Britain in 1939 and never returned to France
before his death in 1948, had a particularly strong collection of
early 20th- century art. However, because Kann did not keep a
detailed inventory of his collection, Warin has had to rely on
German wartime records, French postwar documents, photographs and
other archives to put together a list of works he believes ended up
in the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Kann estate has begun a lawsuit against the Georges Pompidou
Center in Paris for the return of a 1914 Cubist painting by Braque
called ``Le Guitarriste,'' and it is claiming two paintings by Juan
Gris also owned by the Pompidou Center. It has already regained two
Picasso oils from French and Swiss collections and has initiated
claims to another Picasso, ``Tete de Femme,'' owned by a French
regional museum; Leger's ``Fumees sur les Toits,'' at the
Minneapolis Institute of Arts; and Matisse's ``Riviere aux Aloes,''
at the Menil Collection in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Last July Kann heirs filed a lawsuit in New York state Supreme
Court in Manhattan against the Wildenstein family, among the art
world's best-known dealers, asserting that the Wildensteins stole
eight rare manuscripts worth about $15 million that had been looted
by the Nazis. A lawyer for the Wildensteins termed the suit
``baseless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These claims show that there are probably many other claims to
come in the United States from looted European families,''
Feliciano said in an interview from New York.
</P>
<P>
   As with ``Still Life: Job,'' long research usually follows
claims for restitution. In this case, the Museum of Modern Art
notes on its Web site (www.moma.org/menu/provenance.html), which
also includes photographs and descriptions of 15 other paintings
with incomplete provenance, that the contested Picasso was donated
to the museum in 1979 by Nelson A. Rockefeller, who acquired it
from the Carstairs Gallery in New York in 1950. It also notes that
the painting belonged at one point to Rolf de Mare, a Swedish dance
director and art collector who lived in Paris from 1926 to 1942,
although it is not clear how he acquired it or when he sold it.
</P>
<P>
   Warin said the lack of provenance before de Mare was suspicious
because any prewar collector would have been proud to mention Kann
as a prior owner. The most likely explanation, he said, was that
the painting was bought from some dealer who had acquired it from
German spoils of war. Warin and Lowry believe that the answer may
lie in de Mare's archives, currently held by the Dans Museet in
Stockholm. ``We know he kept a ledger book,'' Lowry said, ``but we
have not been given access to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowry said that so far no claims had been made to any of the
other paintings posted on the museum's Web site (including works by
Leger, Klee, Grosz, Braque and Bonnard). ``I think it very, very
unlikely that others will turn out to be problematic,'' he added.
``We have admitted that one, the Picasso, has a question mark, but
we're far from knowing conclusively. There is inconclusive evidence
in both directions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I can say is that there will be no contention over
this,'' he went on. ``And Francis Warin and I agree on this. We
will push our research until we agree we have gone as far as
possible. Then we will sit down and find the right solution. I
don't know what it will be, but I do believe Francis Warin has a
legitimate right to think it may have belonged to Alphonse Kann.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1914EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
