<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT CRUCIFIXION SITE, A PROFOUND DISCOVERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the coming of Easter, my thoughts flash back to last month
when I had an ultimate experience of that holy period commemorating
Christ's death, burial and Resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   On a cool morning in March, I arose early to walk from my hotel
in Israel to the Church of the Holy Sepulcher, inside the Christian
quarter of the Old City of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Before I began reporting on Pope John Paul II's visit to Israel,
I wanted to visit the domed church, which has been identified for
centuries as the place where Jesus was buried and rose from the
dead.
</P>
<P>
   The usually crowded streets of the Old City were almost empty.
</P>
<P>
   As I wandered through the maze of narrow streets _ very similar
to those of Jesus' time _ I lost my way. Luckily, a robed priest
whisking past was going in the same direction. I asked him the way
to the landmark church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just follow me,'' he said. ``I have to be there in just a few
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   He was on his way to celebrate a Roman Catholic Mass in a part
of the Church of the Holy Sepulcher.
</P>
<P>
   I followed the priest, asking no questions because he seemed in
a hurry, for one thing, and also because my early-morning trek
wasn't a search for interviews. It was a personal journey.
</P>
<P>
   Queen Helena, mother of the Roman Emperor Constantine, ordered
the first church built there in the fourth century, after early
Christians informed her that it was the place where Christ died,
was entombed and arose. She also believed she had found a piece of
the true cross in a cave near that site.
</P>
<P>
   The Church of the Holy Sepulcher is built over a rock formation
that, since A.D. 336, has been identified as the place of the
skull, or Golgotha _ the site of the Crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   Although the church is inside the walled city, archaeologists
have concluded that the site was in a rocky area outside the walls
during the time of Jesus. Executions and burials were not held
inside the walled city at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Brisco, a professor at Southwestern Baptist Theological
Seminary in Fort Worth and author of the ``Holman Bible Atlas,''
states that archaeologists have concluded the area under the church
was used as a quarry, with numerous tombs cut into the rock during
Jesus' time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The circumstances fit the biblical description, but the
authenticity of the site cannot be established conclusively,''
Brisco writes.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Brisco says, there is even less evidence for the
authenticity of an alternative site for the Crucifixion and burial
_ a picturesque area north of the Old City known as the Garden Tomb
and Gordon's Calvary, so named because of its support by British
Gen. Charles Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   The church is shared by six Christian groups, and they sometimes
get into intense arguments over control of various portions.
</P>
<P>
   When I walked into the Church of the Holy Sepulcher, only one or
two people were kneeling at a stone slab, believed to be the place
Jesus' body was laid after he was crucified. After they left, I
also knelt at the holy slab.
</P>
<P>
   Then I climbed the winding stone steps that lead to Golgotha.
Pope John Paul II would laboriously climb those same stairs in an
unscheduled stop on the final day of his pilgrimage to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   As I gained the top of the stairs, music filled the old church.
A group from Germany sang hymns in the chapel where many believe
Christ was nailed to the cross. Next to that chapel is one of the
holiest places in Christendom _ a chapel marking the place where
the cross stood.
</P>
<P>
   I was alone in the chapel of the Crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   As I knelt before an ornate image of Christ, I saw something I
had never seen in past visits to the church: a glass wall revealing
a massive white rock formation underneath the altar: Golgotha.
</P>
<P>
   I was able to touch a piece of marble directly above a hole in
the rock some believe is the exact place soldiers planted a cross
in those ancient stones on a fateful day a little less than 2,000
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was a moment of Easter before Easter began.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
