<HEADLINE>
ROBBIE FULKS AT HIS `VERY BEST' 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL D. CLARK 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When dealing with alternative country rebel Robbie
Fulks, it doesn't hurt to read between the lines on song titles and
record packaging. Beneath his freckle-faced Opie Taylor innocence
is the humor of a biting satirist.
</P>
<P>
   Fulks is the honky-tonk strummer whose 1996 debut solo album,
Country Love Songs, featured such touching heart-wringers as We'll
Burn Together and She Took a Lot of Pills (and Died).
</P>
<P>
   The follow-up, South Mouth, was highlighted by a
talking-out-of-school country-punk track. The title alone _
unprintable in this family newspaper _ blasted Nashville as a home
of country money-makers, not music-makers.
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't be surprising, then, that the 37-year-old
Chicago-based singer-songwriter has put out an album called ``The
Very Best of Robbie Fulks'' _ featuring none of these songs.
</P>
<P>
   The cover art is a smiling portrait on canvas, but it would be
more accurate had the painter planted Fulks' tongue firmly in his
cheek.
</P>
<P>
   In Fulks' world, ``very best'' doesn't necessarily mean the
hits. It couldn't, because he's never really had one. The album is
not really a retrospective either, since nearly half of the 14
songs were just recorded for this release.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the very best of the stuff I had lying around that
hadn't been released,'' Fulks said. ``I can't really claim that I
gave much thought to how the songs worked together. It was just
kind of a personal odyssey.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulks won't even promise that he'll play many of the songs
during his performance April 28 at McGonigel's Mucky Duck in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But he will swear that the album was perhaps the most satisfying
record project of his career. If anything, ``Very Best'' represents
the buffer zone between the entertainer's stay with a major label
and his current search for more creative distribution.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Fulks moved from New York City, where he was attending
Columbia University, to Chicago to become a member of the Special
Consensus Bluegrass Band. He stayed with the group the rest of the
decade and played on its 1989 Grammy-nominated album, ``Hole in My
Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, he left the band and joined the cast of a
regional production of the play ``Woody Guthrie's American Song.''
</P>
<P>
   His final act of group participation was with the comically
low-brow Trailer Trash Revue, a loose rock band featuring go-go
dancers. Within another two years, Fulks decided to put his own
name above the marquee and go solo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got to the point where I was writing all these songs
and I wanted to take credit for them,'' Fulks said. ``I didn't want
it to be some Dire Straits situation with one guy writing all the
songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the release of his first two albums on the
Chicago-based indie label Bloodshot Records, Fulks finally got a
stab at national exposure when Geffen picked him up and released
his finest album, ``Let's Kill Saturday Night.'' A fine mix of
traditional country and pop tunes, the album features guest spots
by Vince Gill, Lucinda Williams and mandolin specialist Sam Bush.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that Fulks was heading down the eclectic yet
accessible country path of such artists as Rosie Flores and BR5-49.
Last spring, however, the large record industry beast that he'd
been wary of in that earlier song finally came around to bite him.
</P>
<P>
   With the merger that resulted in the creation of Uber-label
Universal-Polygram, Geffen was swallowed whole, then picked apart.
Along with bigger names like 10,000 Maniacs and Cowboy Junkies,
Fulks was shown the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's plenty of stupidity to complain or laugh about (in the
music business),'' Fulks said. ``The mega-mergers caused a loss of
interest in niche acts, but I just don't think that can stay true
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulks believes that sooner or later focus will cycle back to
more exotic artists, but only after small labels start making money
off the big-fish castoffs. Songwriters like Aimee Mann, who was
also axed by Geffen but came back with a Grammy for the
``Magnolia'' soundtrack earlier this year, are held up as the
poster children for the movement.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Fulks will continue to book his own gigs, tour about
100 days a year and personally prepare packages of his CDs, which
can be ordered online: www.robbiefulks.com.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in lieu of a record deal, Fulks has found the Internet
to be an invaluable tool in managing his own career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredibly fortunate time now that this great new
sales tool has come along that provides for direct contact with
consumers,'' Fulks said of response to his Web site. ``Right now,
67 million Americans have computers. That number will double in the
next couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulks is preparing a disc of all-new music to follow up ``Let's
Kill Saturday Night.'' He is in the process of shopping it to an
interested label, though contracts haven't been signed.
</P>
<P>
   The recording is tentatively titled ``Couples in Trouble.''
Fulks describes it as a theme record on the rise and fall of
relationships. Until then, ``The Very Best of Robbie Fulks'' will
have to keep fans satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   With the continuing extinction of vinyl, there really isn't any
such thing as a ``B-sides'' collection of recordings anymore, but
the odds-and-ends ``Best'' set features one song from when such
items still existed. The buoyantly bent notes of ``Jean Arthur''
provided the flip side of Fulks' first solo 7-inch single, ``Little
King.''
</P>
<P>
   Also not to be missed is ``That Bangle Girl,'' his red-faced
love-song crush on Susanna Hoffs and the '80s hit queens.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's actually less of a smart-aleck element to that song.
The Bangles were just great pop singers in tradition of Ronnie
Spector.'' Fulks said, ``and they were kind of seductive, hot
girls.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
