<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JILL-SOBULE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JILL SOBULE CAN AFFORD TO KISS NOVELTY SONG GOODBYE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's get this out of the way: Jill Sobule is the woman who sang
1995's controversial ``I Kissed a Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's the song that got her on MTV and a few gigs on the
Lilith Fair second stage, but also got her banned on some Southern
radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the song, she acknowledges, that's responsible for
her 15 minutes of fame.
</P>
<P>
   Duly noted.
</P>
<P>
   But it's time to move on, because Sobule certainly has, which is
clear when you listen to her fourth _ and probably best _ CD,
``Pink Pearl.'' Released this week, her debut on independent label
Beyond Music ends the Denver native's three-year hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   With a mix of acoustic folk, bossa nova and a touch of hip-hop
on the first single, ``One of These Days,'' ``Pink Pearl'' is more
wide-ranging musically than Sobule has ever been.
</P>
<P>
   But her ability to pen incisive (and sometimes wickedly funny)
portraits and observations is undimmed: ``Heroes'' addresses the
imperfection of such icons as Dorothy Parker and Pablo Picasso;
``Lucy at the Gym'' looks at a sad, compulsive, weight-obsessed
woman; and ``Mary Kay'' is her take on the strange case of Mary Kay
Letourneau, who was convicted of child rape after an affair with a
junior high school student.
</P>
<P>
   All the CD's positives, she says, stem from recording at a slow
pace _ thanks to being unemployed and broke since she was dropped
by Atlantic Records after her third CD, ``Happy Town.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew my time was up with Atlantic when I was on the Lilith
tour in 1998 and I was playing at 4 p.m. and the ticket said the
show was starting at 5,'' Sobule says with a laugh. ``They thought
I'd give them another I Kissed a Girl,' and I didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only one guy from Atlantic ever called me _ they were so cold.
I mean, I know I was dropped but they could have treated me more
like a human being and less like just a ... I don't know ... a
content provider.''
</P>
<P>
   So she dealt with her bitterness (''I'd be like, `Why is this
person on the radio and not me?' ''), took several months off and
then began playing guitar in Lloyd Cole's band, the Negatives.
</P>
<P>
   And every so often, she'd swing into Nashville and record a
couple of tracks at a small studio owned by Brad Jones and Robin
Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just like doing demos,'' she says. ``They let me record
for free, 'cause I was broke. There was no feeling of risk _ it
wasn't like I had to go in and do a record. It all sort of just
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Sobule says she had more time to contemplate, to
look at the world around her and into herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``One'' came from reading old junior high journals and realizing
that she was writing the same things she had written way back then;
``Heroes'' was the product of reading biographies of Picasso and
Parker, and so on. The CD's forlorn ender, ``Rock Me to Sleep'' _ a
simple declaration of loneliness and needing human contact _ was
done at home on a four-track tape recorder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm attracted to troubled, lonely women in my writing,'' she
says. ``Even if you write about another character, you put yourself
into the point of view. I spent about a year in high school with
this eating/exercising disorder, and it's a lonely existence and a
big waste of time. So `Lucy' isn't about me, but part of me is her.
And `Mary Kay' I saw as a great modern Greek tragedy _ it's about
the love you can't have, and we've all felt that.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the humorous ``Heroes.'' A roll call of famous,
talented people, it also looks at their real or imagined faults _
``Orson Welles peaked at 25, ballooned before our eyes and he sold
bad wine/Heard Babe Ruth was full of malice/Lewis Carroll I'm sure
did Alice'' _ and ends with Sobule deciding to ``get drunk and
depressed'' upon reflection.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just an exercise I did after reading biographies of
Dorothy Parker and Picasso,'' she says. ``She just wasn't a nice
person, and neither was he. I can see where the music business has
made me bitter and depressed, but I don't want to go there. It's
toxic to be bitter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not be Dorothy Parker! I will fight against it!'' she
says, laughing again.
</P>
<P>
   And these days, she doesn't have to fight that hard. Her new
label, she says, is a good fit for her: It's smaller, and there's
virtually no pressure to come up with a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an easy thing; I don't fit in anywhere easily,'' she
says. ``I was just a novelty act to Atlantic. Beyond (Music) can
figure out what to do with me more.''
</P>
<P>
   What she plans to do, she says, is hit the road hard; she
recently completed Warren Zevon's tour and plans to stay on the
road for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna do the grassroots thing, 'cause you can't rely on
them record companies,'' Sobule says, adopting a hick Southern
accent and giggling.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, she will be doing ``Kissed;'' after all this time,
she's learned to appreciate the song again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to re-embrace it because it did get me on MTV, which
I don't think will ever happen again,'' she says. ``And I've had so
many people write to me, thanking me and telling me, `I was 13 when
I heard that and it made me feel better about having a crush on my
girlfriend.' So in a way it was a great thing. I don't play it
every night, but I will if people ask for it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
