<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7976 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-26 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MAXIMUS PUNISHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's axiomatic. If you cross Rudolph Giuliani, he will come
after you.
</P>
<P>
   City Comptroller Alan Hevesi spent years avoiding any serious
confrontations with the mayor. Why mess with a hornets' nest?
Hevesi, a Democrat with a studiously low-keyed demeanor, apparently
made up his mind very early on that he would get along with
Giuliani, a Republican who is about as keyed up and combative as
any politician you'll ever see.
</P>
<P>
   If there were disagreements, they could be handled quietly,
gentlemanly, with a phone call or an explanatory memo. No need for
unpleasantness. That was Hevesi's way. And it seemed just fine with
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   This peaceful coexistence ended in January, when the comptroller
came across big-league irregularities in the mayor's
welfare-to-work contracts and refused to sign off on them. The
contracts should have been competitively bid but were not. And, in
Hevesi's view, a Virginia consulting company that was gobbling up
most of the money, Maximus Inc., was the beneficiary of blatant
favoritism and cronyism.
</P>
<P>
   One of the individuals who stood to benefit from the contracts
(worth at least $104 million and potentially a lot more) was
Richard J. Schwartz, a former adviser to Giuliani who just happened
to have designed the mayor's welfare-to-work program.
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller's objections were communicated to the mayor
quietly. The mayor, in his usual dismissive way, told the
comptroller he was wrong and insisted the contracts be approved.
Not only did Hevesi refuse to approve the contracts, he spelled out
his objections publicly, saying he believed the process for
awarding the contracts had been corrupted, and he referred the
matter to the Manhattan district attorney's office and the U.S.
attorney's office for further investigation.
</P>
<P>
   He might as well have put a sign on his chest that said ``Hit
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week the mayor hit him. Giuliani's rosy budget for the
upcoming fiscal year had lots of goodies to toss around, and nearly
all of the city's elected officials were spared budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But what do you think happened to the comptroller? Ah, yes. Alan
Hevesi's budget was slashed by nearly $5 million. It was the first
time his budget has been cut since Giuliani became mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Can you spell retribution?
</P>
<P>
   Back in December, before the Maximus dispute erupted, the mayor
had proposed a budget cut of $4.3 million for Hevesi's office. But
that was considered routine, no different from similar proposed
cuts in prior years. In those years the money was always restored
after some negotiating. Additional revenues and savings were found.
Accommodations were made. That's the way the budget process works.
</P>
<P>
   But not this year. Not for Alan Hevesi, who dared to cross the
mayor. When Giuliani's preliminary budget proposal was announced in
January, the proposed cut for Hevesi's office had increased to $4.8
million. This, perhaps, still could have seemed routine. The budget
process is complex, an annual, almost sacred ritual of give and
take that is difficult to analyze before it is completed.
</P>
<P>
   What happened this year is that the City Council, as usual,
restored some of the cuts imposed by the mayor. It sent the budget
back to Giuliani with restorations in the following areas:
libraries, arts and cultural institutions, the City Council's own
budget, and Hevesi's budget.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani OK'd all the restorations, except the one for Hevesi.
</P>
<P>
   When the mayor announced his final budget proposal last week,
the cut in the budget of the comptroller's office stood at $4.86
million. Hevesi had officially been punished.
</P>
<P>
   What was happening with Maximus during this extended budget
negotiating period? Well, the mayor took Hevesi to court in an
effort to force him to register the contracts, but that backfired.
A judge ruled two weeks ago that there was ``compelling evidence
that the contracting process has been corrupted,'' and that Maximus
had misled the city about Schwartz's role.
</P>
<P>
   The city is appealing. Meanwhile, officials at the mayor's
Office of Management and Budget denied Wednesday that Hevesi's
budget cut had anything to do with the dispute over Maximus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
