<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7979 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ELIAN-POLITICS-0427-C     04-26 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-POLITICS-0427-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP TREADING IN DANGEROUS, FAMILIAR WATERS WITH ELIAN HEARINGS
 &HT;    With ELIAN-GRAHAM-0427.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Republicans, in scheduling hearings
into the pre-dawn raid to seize Elian Gonzalez from the home of his
Miami relatives, are once again defying public opinion and the
advice of their own political experts.
</P>
<P>
   The warning from some of the GOP's top analysts is that the
hearings on the Elian Gonzalez case could backfire on the party the
way the impeachment of President Clinton led to the loss of five
Republican seats in Congress in the 1998 election and the
resignation of House Speaker Newt Gingrich, the architect of the
GOP takeover of Congress four years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, one lesson we learned from the impeachment process
is that we blew what should have been a very strong election year
by politicizing the process,'' said Ed Goeas, president of the
Tarrance Group, one of the most successful Republican polling and
strategy teams.
</P>
<P>
   The political calculations went on as the Elian Gonzalez drama
continued on several fronts Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In Atlanta, the father of the Cuban shipwreck survivor filed a
motion with a federal appeals court seeking the sole right to speak
for his 6-year-old son before the courts. ``This father beseeches
this court with all the emotion and fervor of a parent protecting
his son to let him raise his child in peace,'' the motion said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In Havana, Elian's 10-year-old cousin Yasmany Betancourt
Valentin and his former kindergarten teacher Agueda Cecilia Fleitas
Miranda left Jose Marti International Airport for a reunion with
the boy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In Washington, a child psychiatrist, Dr. Paulina F. Kernberg
of Cornell University, who Tuesday interviewed Elian for the
government recommended postponing any visit by the Miami relatives
until they reconcile with Elian's father. ``She believes that
before the Miami relatives see Elian they need to work out their
differences with Juan Miguel,'' said Justice Department spokeswoman
Carole Florman.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In Queenstown, Md., satellite trucks, television crews, state
troopers and a handful of protesters gathered near the secluded
estate where the Cuban child and his family were staying. Heavily
armed U.S. marshals patrolled the property's perimeter and Coast
Guard launches on the Wye River chased away boaters who strayed too
close to the 1,100-acre grounds.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In Miami, shops reopened and people returned to work, a day
after a general strike in Little Havana to protest last weekend's
pre-dawn seizure of Elian. But about 80 people left for Washington,
D.C., in a caravan of cars and buses. Messages written on the
windows read: ``Justice for Elian,'' ``Elian's S.W.A.T.'' and
``We'll never forget you Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Also in Washington, Assistant Secretary of State Peter Romero
said Cuban President Fidel Castro has ``manipulated'' the case for
his own political purposes. The administration vowed to continue
efforts to isolate Cuba. The comments were the most strident by an
administration official since Elian arrived in South Florida last
November after being rescued at sea during an ill-fated boat trip
that claimed the life of his mother and 10 others.
</P>
<P>
   And as the five-month-old international tug-of-war over the
little boy heads for congressional hearings next week, it is
rapidly evolving into an election-year issue for the GOP despite
the counsel of caution from within party ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an issue to be politicized,'' Goeas said. ``Let
people come to their own gut conclusions.''
</P>
<P>
   But does the Republican Party really have a choice?
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban exile community has been one of the most loyal GOP
voting blocs for decades, historically voting 80-90 percent
Republican. And the Cuban American vote is pivotal in Florida, a
key state in the Republican strategy to reclaim the White House
after Bill Clinton's two terms.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the Republicans in Congress appear to be marching
in near unison once again to express outrage over acts committed by
the Clinton administration. And they know what to expect in the way
of Democratic criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone knows the spin that the White House is going
to put on this ... You know, 'there go the Republicans again',''
said Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., even as he pressed for hearings. ``I
think we ought to move ahead and we ought to be prepared that we're
going to be attacked, saying that this is more political witch
hunt,'' added Mack, who is not seeking re-election.
</P>
<P>
   However, a USA Today/CNN/Gallup poll shows overwhelming approval
of the federal raid that led to the reunion of 6-year-old Elian
with his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez. Sixty percent approved of
the raid while 35 percent disapproved.
</P>
<P>
   And 68 percent of those polled in the days following the
military-style raid in Miami expressed opposition to congressional
hearings on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Independent pollster John Zogby had similar results in his poll.
Sixty-two percent opposed hearings while 30 percent supported them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this could be is the impeachment debacle all over
again,'' Zogby said. ``Regardless of the merits of the issue one
way or another, you get a strong sense here that voters are sick of
it, and that any effort to prolong this could really hurt
Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Majority Trent Lott of Mississippi, in announcing the
hearings, dismissed such polls. ``I don't believe the American
people approved of the kind of action they saw Saturday morning,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Republican-led Congress already has a reputation of
preferring to ``investigate rather than legislate,'' said Celinda
Lake, a Democratic pollster. ``The American people are wondering
what Congress has actually done.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the impeachment of Clinton, the GOP leadership of
Congress has also conducted highly publicized investigations of
Clinton real estate dealings, Clinton-Gore campaign fundraising,
the suicide of former Clinton White House aide Vince Foster and the
federal raid on the Branch Davidian compound in Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to assess the effect of possible GOP campaign ads
featuring television footage of the raid on Elian's Miami
relatives's home, Lake insisted it would help Democratic efforts to
win the six seats needed to regain control of the House. ``It would
put the House in play,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Shepard's email address is: scotts(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.ins.usdoj.gov
</P>
<P>
   libertyforelian.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
