<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, April 27. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S.-ARMS (Washington) _ The Russian foreign minister,
Igor Ivanov, laid down a challenge Wednesday, saying in a vivid
speech here that the Clinton administration should not follow
through on national missile defense and make the ``fatal mistake''
of changing the basic arms control treaty of the Cold War. Just
hours before Ivanov spoke Sen. Jesse Helms said that if President
Clinton succeeded in persuading the Russians to amend the
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty, the deal would be ``dead on
arrival'' in his committee. Helms derided the president for wanting
a ``final photo-op'' with Russians before leaving the White House.
By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story: refer photo
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-MCCAIN (Hanoi, Vietnam) _ As he strode through the
shadowy hallways and incongruously sunny courtyards, gesturing
here, pointing to a detail there, Sen. John McCain might have been
a father showing a son his alma mater. Except the landmarks on this
tour were dank cells like the one where McCain spent two years in
solitary confinement, and leg irons, which he once wore as a
punishment for insulting the guards. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   MATH-SCHOOLS (Undated) _ Three years ago, one of New York City's
most innovative school districts set out to tackle a nagging
problem: the math phobia that afflicts many students, and the
disparity between the test scores of white middle-class and Asian
students and their poorer black and Hispanic counterparts. The
district, stretching from the wealthy Upper East Side to immigrant
Chinatown, embraced a new ``constructivist'' curriculum without
textbooks, which preaches that it is more important for children to
construct their own solutions than to learn the standard
theoretical rules. Now the district is at the center of a rebellion
by parents, mathematicians and many mathematics teachers over how
to teach math that has shaken the education establishment from New
York City to Plano, Texas, and Lincoln, Mass. A special report by
Anemona Hartocollis.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-BOYSCOUTS (Washington) _ The question before the Supreme
Court on Wednesday was whether the Boy Scouts have a constitutional
right to exclude gay members, but the justices did not seem
particularly interested in either Boy Scout policy or the future of
gay rights. Rather, what clearly concerned the court were the
implications of ruling for one side or the other. If the Boy Scouts
cannot exclude homosexuals, can they still exclude girls, the
justices wanted to know. More generally, the justices asked, if an
organization deems a particular kind of exclusivity to be central
to its identity, must courts take that assertion at face value? By
Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-COUNTERSUIT (Washington) _ Seven of the nation's largest
gun manufacturers filed suit today to block New York State,
Connecticut and 14 cities from adopting purchasing policies that
favor gun companies who agree to stringent rules governing the ways
they make, sell and distribute weapons. By James Dao.
</P>
