<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7981 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ELIAN-GRAHAM-0427-COX     04-26 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-GRAHAM-0427-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FLORIDA'S GRAHAM IN TOUGH POSITION OVER ELIAN SITUATION, BUT
REMAINS UNBOWED
 &HT;    With ELIAN-GRAHAM-0427.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Bob Graham, a moderate Democrat who counts his
friendship with President Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno
in decades, finds himself in an unusual position in the fallout
over Elian Gonzalez _ aligned with conservative Republicans who are
harshly critical of the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Graham's high-profile, emotional split with Clinton
and Reno comes amid what may be his best, and last, chance to break
through on the national political stage. The 63-year-old Graham has
been frequently mentioned as a possible running-mate for Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, in a interview with Cox News Service, said he has not
weighed the potential political impact of his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not given one second's thought to the political
consequences of this,'' Graham said. ``My responsibility is to the
people of Florida and the national issues raised by this case, and
I have been trying to carry out my responsibilities to the best of
my ability.''
</P>
<P>
   A Gore campaign advisor said it's too early to assess the impact
of Graham's actions this week on his prospects for being selected
as a running-mate but speculated that ``they won't help or hurt
him.'' The advisor, who spoke on condition of anonymity, noted that
the highly personal selection of a vice presidential candidate
probably won't be finalized until August.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a long way to go,'' the advisor said.
</P>
<P>
   Two well-known Washington political analysts said they did not
believe Graham's split with the administration _ a position similar
to that taken by Gore _ would hurt the senator politically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though there are sharp differences in Florida among the
Cuban and the non-Cuban community, I don't think you are going to
see the non-Cuban community turn against Graham,'' said Norm J.
Ornstein, an analyst with the non-partisan American Enterprise
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is so much less shrill than (others) that it's not
going to offend people even if they disagree,'' Ornstein said,
adding that ``this gives him a little more national visibility. I
doubt it has caused a schism between Graham and Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Cook, publisher of the independent Cook Political
Report, said national politicians understand that ``any statewide
elected official in Florida has to take the positions (Graham) has
taken and do what he has done. I can't imagine any of the
Democratic leaders begrudging him what he has done. It's what you
have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., who has been one of the biggest
defenders of the administration's actions, said Graham ``has
impressed people like me who disagree with him ... being honest,
consistent and compassionate should not hurt somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Graham statements over the past four days have put him
sharply at odds with Clinton and Reno.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance on NBC's Meet the Press Sunday and at a Capitol
news conference Tuesday, Graham testily accused Clinton of going
back on a commitment not to conduct a night-time raid on the house
of Elian's Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who said there was ``an insensitivity and a crudeness''
to the pre-dawn raid the day before Easter, said he did not know
what was ``motivating the administration to act in such a perverse
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham's comments were disputed by White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart who portrayed Clinton's statement as more of a desire than
a promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Joe Lockhart was not in the room when the statement was
made,'' Graham responded when asked about Lockhart's comments at
the Tuesday news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida senator's rise to a potential No. 2 spot on the
Democratic ticket is due to a combination of geography and ideology
and personality.
</P>
<P>
   Geographically, Graham has to be considered by the Gore because
Florida's 25 electoral votes is one of the largest blocs in the
Electoral College, where 270 votes wins the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   A former two-term governor now in his third term as senator,
Graham has dominated Florida politics for nearly a quarter century
and is still immensely popular throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   Most political observers put Florida in the Republican column
this year for two years: Florida has a post-World War II tradition
of voting Republican for president _ eight out of 12 times in the
past half-century; and the presumptive GOP nominee, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush is the brother of Florida Gov. Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But adding Graham to the ticket could put the outcome in Florida
in doubt, forcing Bush to spend precious time and money there
instead of other states around the country, Ornstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Ideologically, Graham has built a solid moderate base, which he
demonstrated most recently as one of the primary organizers of a
group of moderate Democratic senators.
</P>
<P>
   Gore followed Graham's lead initially in splitting with the
Clinton administration over whether the fate of the 6-year-old
Cuban rafter should be decided by the Immigration and
Naturalization Service or by a state court specializing in custody
matters.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's position _ espoused by Clinton and Reno _
is that the issue is an immigration matter and only Elian's father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez, can speak on his behalf. The father has
repeatedly said he intends to return the boy to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Gore joined Graham and Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., in supporting a
bill that would grant Elian and his father permanent residency
status in the United States _ a move that would take the case out
of federal jurisdiction and allowed the boy's Miami relatives to
challenge custody in state court.
</P>
<P>
   But while Graham has been outspoken, almost bitter, about
Saturday's events, Gore has been more reticent _ although he said
he would not have ordered the raid.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who has previously indicated he would be eager to serve
as Gore's running-mate, dismissed suggestions that his recent
behavior might have knocked him out of consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a job that I love and find to be very challenging _
more challenging in the last five days than I would hope to be the
norm _ and I am not looking for any other occupation.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Graham said he would prefer to have positive relations
with Clinton and Reno, ``the three of us are all adults.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham and Reno have known each other for 40 years. Both Miami
natives cut their political teeth in Dade County, Fla., politics.
Reno was state attorney in Dade County when Graham was governor and
Graham was instrumental in persuading Clinton to consider her for
attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were probably times when Janet was state attorney and I
was governor that she disagreed with what I did. That's the nature
of a long-term relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Graham first met Clinton after they were elected governors of
their respective states in 1978. The two were among the early
moderate Democrats who formed the Democratic Leadership Council.
Graham was reportedly on Clinton's short list of possible
running-mates in 1992 before the nod finally went to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been a friend of Janet for 40 years and a friend of the
president for 22 years, and I intend to continue to be friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham: http://www.senate.gov/(tilde)graham/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
