<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7983 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SRC27-COX     04-26 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SRC27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Civil rights group alters agenda as it celebrates 80 years
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In its incarnation as the Commission on Interracial
Cooperation, the Southern Regional Council sought to end obstacles
blacks faced on tenant farms, in schools and in the media.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Atlanta-based SRC became the brain power for
front-line activists in the civil rights movement. Its scholars and
researchers documented the plight of blacks in the South. The
unraveling of the Deep South's desegregation in the 1960s helped
stir the region into the melting pot it is today.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Southern minorities face more complex, but less graphic,
encumbrances, says SRC President Charles S. Johnson. At the group's
80th anniversary celebration tonight at Swissotel in Atlanta,
Johnson will outline the changes and provide a signpost for SRC's
direction in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Former Atlanta Mayor Maynard Jackson will be among those honored
during tonight's ceremonies. The organization will present its
journalism award to Brad Warthen, editorial page editor of The
State newspaper in Columbia, S.C. Warthen has been an outspoken
supporter of those who want the controversial Confederate battle
flag removed from the Statehouse dome.
</P>
<P>
   In the confrontational days of the 1960s, the violent opposition
of white officials _ like infamous Birmingham, Ala., Police Chief
Bull Connor, who let loose dogs on civil rights demonstrators _
helped demonstrate the depth of racial separation, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when, in a lot of ways, the problems were
more stark,'' said Johnson, whose grandfather was the first
chairman of the SRC's executive committee in 1944. ``The problems
were problems about which it might have been easier to prick the
conscience of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more difficult for people to grasp the problems that come
from electoral districts that are malapportioned, or are
apportioned in a way to minimize black voter participation. ... You
can't draw a picture or show a photograph that dramatizes those
kinds of problems. They require a lot more explaining, and
sometimes the remedy is a lot more technical than direct action.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, Johnson's address will be a reintroduction of SRC _
once the pre-eminent voice for social change and one of the first
groups to form a biracial coalition in the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it has the high profile it once had,'' said John
Shelton Reed, director of the Howard Odum Institute for Research in
Social Science at the University of North Carolina. A sociologist
at UNC, Odum became SRC's first president in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was conspicuous because it was one of the voices of
dissent,'' Reed said. ``These days, it's one civil rights group
among many, and the agenda is not as clear as it once was. Once
upon a time, they were a single-issue group, and that issue was
race relations.''
</P>
<P>
   As the conspicuous clues of racial segregation have disappeared
_ no more whites-only bathrooms, no more whites-only schools _ the
rudder of the civil rights movement has wavered. There's cause to
step back and chart the possible paths, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've continued to try and be a think tank for the movement,
recognizing that the focus of the movement _ if you could find a
focus _ has certainly changed and become more diffused,'' said
Johnson, a lawyer at the Atlanta firm Holland and Knight.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, for instance, the SRC began its voting rights program.
For the next 15 years, the program helped shape fair redistricting
plans for more than 2,000 jurisdictions in the South. Today, SRC is
reaching out to growing minority populations, including Latinos and
Asians, trying to forge new coalitions.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six months, civil rights groups have re-energized
themselves in the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, the National Association for the Advancement
of Colored People has launched a tourism boycott in the state until
the Legislature removes the Confederate battle flag from the top of
the Statehouse dome. On Tuesday, the state House Judiciary
Committee approved a bill that would do just that.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, the NAACP organized an 11,000-person march in
protest of Gov. Jeb Bush's order that ends racial set-asides in
state hiring and admission to public universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two issues kind of illustrate where we are,'' Johnson
said. ``In a lot of ways, the flag is a symbolic issue. It's hard
to show how the presence of a particular flag over the Capitol in
Columbia affects anybody's life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't affect what somebody takes home in their paycheck
or how they live on a daily basis or their access to education. It
may, however, affect their perception of whose society this is,''
Johnson said. ``Are folks who are not descended from Confederate
veterans, are they just visitors or people who remain in sufferance
of somebody else who, quote, `controls' society, or is this a
society that belongs to everybody?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
