<HEADLINE>
SHAREHOLDERS PASS CONTROL MEASURES AT RAYTHEON ANNUAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Shareholders have delivered a rebuke to Raytheon
Co. management at the company's annual meeting here, passing
nonbinding resolutions to soften antitakeover provisions and elect
all directors annually.
</P>
<P>
   The measures, opposed by the Lexington defense contractor's
board, underscored the frustration of many Raytheon stock owners
after a year of diminished profits and sinking share prices.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's leaders say slowing overseas orders and difficulty
absorbing acquisitions have contributed to the company's problems.
But Wednesday, its chief executive, Daniel Burnham, said the
company is on track to recover. ``Raytheon has issues, we know what
they are, and we're dealing with them,'' he said. ``We believe that
Raytheon can be great again.''
</P>
<P>
   But resolution sponsors said Burnham and other top executives
must be held more accountable following thousands of layoffs and
other cost-cutting steps the company has taken in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is: We're holding you to a standard that you're
not meeting,'' said Bart Naylor, a Washington consultant for labor
and environmental groups who spoke in favor of the shareholder
resolutions. ``A board that's truly accountable wouldn't tolerate
failure for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Other backers included many of the large institutional investors
that together control 75 percent of Raytheon's shares. Public
pension funds, including the California Public Employees Retirement
System, also have voiced support for the measures.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have passed similar resolutions at dozens of other
companies in recent years, according to the nonprofit Investor
Responsibility Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's Burnham said the resolutions don't represent a major
setback. He said the board would consider implementing them. Some
of the company's antitakeover policies are required under the terms
of the mergers with other defense contractors that have doubled its
size in recent years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The shareholder proposals were submitted by John Chevedden, a
former employee of Hughes Electronics Corp. in California prior to
its acquisition by Raytheon in 1997. Last year, he made an
unsuccessful bid to have directors elected annually.
</P>
<P>
   But the drop in Raytheon's share price by about a third since
last summer _ and the large salaries the company paid to Burnham
and others in 1999 _ brought out plenty of critics at the meeting,
held in an ornate hall at the US Chamber of Commerce, near the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   One speaker was Reed Hinchliffe, a senior staff engineer at
Raytheon's command and control systems division. He criticized
Burnham for accepting a $900,000 bonus for his work last year even
as bonuses for about 75,000 less senior employees were eliminated
because the company didn't meet certain goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't share our pain, sir,'' said Hinchliffe, who told
Burnham he has worked at Raytheon for 20 years. Citing a positive
review from Pentagon officials last year, he said that ``I did my
job, and the people I work with did their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnham, who like 5,000 other senior managers had his bonus
reduced by about 40 percent in 1999, told Hinchliffe, ``I
understand your point of view and I respect your view.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he felt the decline in the company's fortunes personally
as well, as the value of shares he holds have decreased by about
$15 million. He doesn't intend to return his bonus, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing stock owners, Burnham said, ``Clearly 1999 was a
sobering year for us all.'' He repeated his previous statements
that Raytheon's outlook will improve through various
quality-improvement programs and increased defense spending. Steps
by the Pentagon to offer longer-term contracts also might help the
company earn higher returns, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham said the company doesn't know yet how much it will make
on its work on a proposed national missile defense program. A
recent report by the Congressional Budget Office put the cost of
such a program at around $60 billion, far higher than previous
estimates. Some think that could be good news for Raytheon, which
would produce a missile-destroying space rocket if the
controversial program is approved.
</P>
<P>
   Of the measures passed, one calls for Raytheon to eliminate the
so-called ``poison pill'' plan it maintains to make it more
difficult for a hostile bidder to take over the company. Among
ballots cast, the proposal was supported by 62 percent of class A
shares and 61 percent of class B shares. Raytheon managers said the
suggested change could make it difficult to fend off a hostile bid
that didn't treat all of its shares equally.
</P>
<P>
   The second resolution calls for the election of board members
each year, rather than on the present staggered schedule that
opponents say entrenches the company's management. It was supported
by 58 percent of class A shares and 56 percent of class B shares.
</P>
<P>
   Another resolution, to freeze executive pay following sweeping
layoffs, was defeated, receiving the support of 9 percent of class
A shares and 10 percent of class B shares. The measure was proposed
by the Boston-based Responsible Wealth campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The total number of shares voted wasn't available, a company
spokesman said. Raytheon's largest investors, including Templeton
Global Advisors Ltd. and Barrow Hanley Mewhinney &AMP; Straus Inc.,
didn't return calls seeking comment on the resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's widely traded Class B stock dipped 81.25 cents a
share to $22.4375 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
