<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOMA-SCULPTURE-NYT &LR;      04-26 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOMA-SCULPTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING CHOICES, AN EXHIBITION AT THE MUSEUM OF MODERN ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 has been being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``They were expecting some kind of experimental house
like the one I built in Kobe,'' said the architect Shigeru Ban,
referring to the cardboard ``log'' houses he designed, along with a
paper church, for victims of the 1995 earthquake in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But Ban proposed something unexpected: a soaring lattice arch
made of cardboard tubes, which covers about a third of the
sculpture garden of the Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   Weighing 6 tons and spanning 87 feet, it has a lightness of
being, a kinetic energy. And even though it is solidly bolted in
place, it looks like a giant box kite about to snap its string and
take off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make a strong contrast between the curve and the
verticals of the surrounding buildings,'' said Ban, 42, who was
commissioned to do the piece for ``Making Choices, 24 Exhibitions
of Modern Art From 1920 to 1960,'' a show that opened on Tuesday
and runs through Aug. 1. Ban, who is famous for making sturdy,
temporary structures for the world's refugees and victims of
disasters, loves assembling, disassembling and then reassembling
recyclable materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also wanted to make nice shadows,'' he added, as the arch
cast curves and diamond shadows on sunlit stone and water. He
wanted to cover the entire garden, but the budget was limited. So
the arch stops short of the three weeping beeches, which are still
open to the sky. But it covers the rustling white birches, changing
one's perception of their space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting an arch over the trees'' _ Ban searched for the words
in English _ ``makes the space underneath active and alive.''
</P>
<P>
   No steel or wood reinforces the cardboard tubes, which are
self-supporting and bracketed to the garden wall on one side and
the museum building on the other. Stainless steel cables keep the
bow to the arch. And there's a dynamic yin and yang between warm
brown paper and hard metal.
</P>
<P>
   The tubes, which are from 4 to 5 inches in diameter, were
manufactured in Germany and shipped to New York in 40-foot lengths.
The arch was then assembled in Queens over a scaffolding that
served as a mold, cut into curving sections for delivery and lifted
by crane over the trees and wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called it the turtle delivery,'' said Dean Maltz, the
project's associate architect, conjuring an image of giant
carapaces being guided down into the garden and set in place by
engineers.
</P>
<P>
   The lattice or diagonal grid of the arch fits elegantly into the
truss chords or curving perpendicular tubes that rise from the
garden wall. They are made of spun paper fiber that is both
flexible and water-resistant. And three coats of marine varnish
don't hurt either.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of engineering recalls the geodesic domes of
Buckminster Fuller, who built three temporary structures in the
museum's garden in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the first architect to build with paper,'' said Ban,
who studied with Fuller. ``He used corrugated cardboard for the
geodesic dome.''
</P>
<P>
   Ban went on to earn a degree in architecture at Cooper Union,
and is building paper houses, museums and greenhouses of cardboard
and Plexiglas all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people recognize that this is made of paper,''
Ban said, gazing at his arch. ``I want them to be surprised. I want
them to throw away the prejudice that stops creativity.'' In other
words, you, too, could live in a paper house.
</P>
<P>
   From the log houses Ban built for the people of Kobe _ with
cardboard tubes for walls and sand-filled beer crates for
foundations _ to his own circular paper house on Lake Yamanaka in
Japan, to the Japanese pavilion he is building with Frei Otto for
Expo 2000 in Hanover, Germany, Ban is demonstrating the diversity
of a material that is the stuff used to roll toilet paper and paper
towels. And it can be recycled, which saves trees.
</P>
<P>
   So when it came time to commission an architect for ``Making
Choices,'' which focuses on experiments with materials, ``Shigeru's
use of paper as a primary structural material, and his interest in
recycling made him an obvious choice,'' said Matilde McQuaide, the
curator of the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Ban is good at seeing disconnections _ and fixing them. When
refugees started returning to Rwanda in 1996, Ban designed tents
with cardboard tube frames, to stop the last trees from being
chopped down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United Nations provided plastic sheets and aluminum pipes
for frames,'' he said. ``But people sold the aluminum for money and
then cut trees to make a frame.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kobe, he noticed that people displaced by the earthquake were
not using the temporary housing provided outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to be near their work,'' he said. ``So they were
living in the park, and the city wanted to kick them out. So we
built pretty paper log houses to convince the neighbors to let them
stay there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ban's arch will be dismantled in August, when the garden closes
for renovations until 2004. ``It's a kind of farewell to the garden
as we know it,'' McQuaide said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1943EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
