<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7988 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-JOURNAL-ZIMBABWE-0427     04-26 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-ZIMBABWE-0427-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: FOR WHITE ZIMBABWEAN FARMER, LOVE OF COUNTRY IS NOT
ENOUGH
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    Moving in both International and commentary categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In late February, I sat with Iain Kay on the back porch
of his house on Chipesa farm in southern Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   It was hot, maybe 90 degrees. We drank a cold beer, and sat
gazing out at his lush African land. Chipesa is a rich 4,500-acre
spread of grazing land for beef cattle and farmland for tobacco,
corn and paprika about 45 miles from Harare, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Kay is 51 years old, a gentle lanky man with an Abe Lincoln
beard. As he scanned his land, his eyes held a mix of love and
loss.
</P>
<P>
   If he had an inkling of what was to come, he gave no clue.
</P>
<P>
   I was in Zimbabwe to write about the plight of children whose
parents had been killed by AIDS. His wife, Kerry Kay, is an AIDS
activist and the main reason for my visit to the farm.
</P>
<P>
   Locals see the Kays as important and generous people who have
seen to the care and education of farmworkers and their children.
</P>
<P>
   We had lunch in the large main room of his fine old farmhouse.
Over plates of food grown on the farm, Kay seemed tormented by the
state of his country. He told me he me he hates politics. He
considers it a dirty yet inescapable part of his life. He is a
leader in the opposition to President Robert Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
   Kay detests Mugabe, who made his name during the country's war
in the 1970s to end Rhodesia's white rule. Like many in Zimbabwe _
black and white _ Kay believes it is time for Mugabe to end his
20-year reign.
</P>
<P>
   Kay considers Mugabe a poor leader who has squandered the
country's vast resources with mismanagement and a pointless
military adventure in the Congo.
</P>
<P>
   His father purchased Chipesa as virgin land before Kay was born
there a half-century ago. Paradoxically, Kay's father was Mugabe's
deputy minister of agriculture in the early 1990s. His family is
from Scotland. I told him mine probably is from England. But Kay is
no more a Scot than I am an Englishman.
</P>
<P>
   He is a Zimbabwean and believes this is no less his country than
it is Robert Mugabe's.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Mugabe and his followers treat him as a foreign
invader. About 70,000 whites live in this country of about 11
million. They inherited much of the old colonial trappings, such as
the large farms and businesses. About 4,500 white farmers own about
a third of Zimbabwe's productive land.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe paints whites as enemies of the state who refuse to
abandon their old ways and conspire with Britain to maintain
control at the expense of blacks. Whites have become Mugabe's
scapegoats for the legion of troubles that besiege Zimbabwe, where
more than half the people are unemployed and a quarter are infected
with HIV, the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe is pushing laws to require white farmers to surrender
their farms to the government without compensation so the land can
be redistributed to blacks.
</P>
<P>
   The state-run newspapers in Harare carry chilling accounts of
the evil done by the whites. If you were to substitute the word
``whites'' with ``Jews,'' you would get a disturbing reminder of
another country where a foreign minority was demonized by the
national government.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Kay agrees with the general principal of land
redistribution; he just believes the government must recognize that
the farmers' rights are undiminished by their race.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, I received an e-mail from Kerry Kay (apparently
no longer on the farm):
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Bert, in haste. Pretty awful situation. We had to
evaporate as there is a tag on Iain's head. Fortunately our
community is keeping an eye on things at home. Can't believe the
violence and brutality being unleashed on the population at large _
we pray for an end to the madness soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Iain Kay ventured to a nearby school, which he
had built for the children of his 120 employees. He was trying to
get a clear cellphone signal.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, 25 men jumped him and began beating Kay with sticks,
fan belts and iron rods. They pummeled his back, legs and head,
tearing a gash in his face. They tied him up with barbed wire and
dragged him into the bush. Kay told friends that he had assumed
they would execute him.
</P>
<P>
   In the nick of time, Kay's 20-year-old son approached creating a
diversion. Kay escaped into a reservoir. His attackers fled.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, a young black policeman was killed when he went to
the farm to arrest Kay's attackers.
</P>
<P>
   The attackers are part of a Mugabe-supported invasion of nearly
1,000 white-owned farms by an estimated 3,000 men who describe
themselves as veterans of Zimbabwe's war for independence. They
moved onto Kay's farm in March, built shacks and became squatters.
</P>
<P>
   The farmers consider the invasion an attempt to provoke violence
to create sympathy for the embattled Mugabe. Moreover, such an
outbreak would provide Mugabe an excuse to declare a state of
emergency, thus delaying a national election that he very well
might lose.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe says the occupation of white-owned farms is a justified
act of protest. He blamed the whites for creating the anger that
moved the veterans to act in such a way. Despite a series of court
orders declaring the occupations as illegal, the president has
refused to send in the police to restore order.
</P>
<P>
   So, far, nine people have been killed _ seven of them black. All
were Mugabe opponents. Dozens more have been beaten.
</P>
<P>
   I must confess that as a guilty white Southerner I have had a
certain ambivalence to what is happening in Zimbabwe. My gut sides
with those who want to end the vestiges of colonialism, an evil
cousin of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   As honorable a man as Kay seems to be, he inherited his land
from an evil system. I've worried that I might be lionizing a man
who could just as well be seen as a modern version of the
benevolent slave owner, a character often cited in the argument
that the Old South wasn't really so bad.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, I look at this man and see the love he has for this place
and his people, and I worry even more that Zimbabwe would be
diminished without him.
</P>
<P>
   And I know that destroying a man like Iain Kay will never make
up for the wrongs of colonialism.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s email address is: bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
