<HEADLINE>
MERRICK WAS COLORFUL BROADWAY FIGURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN DEZELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Merrick, the colorful and frequently contentious theater
impresario who's been called the ``Barnum of Broadway'' and ``The
Abominable Showman,'' died early Tuesday in London. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably Broadway's most successful producer, Mr. Merrick in the
late 1950s and 1960s is said to have grossed $20 million annually,
earning $2 million a year in salary.
</P>
<P>
   Best known for his musical hits such as ``Gypsy'' (1959), ``42nd
Street'' (1980), and ``Hello, Dolly!'' (1964), Mr. Merrick also
brought a number of groundbreaking plays to the Great White Way.
Among them were the American premieres of John Osborne's ``Look
Back in Anger'' (1957), Tom Stoppard's ``Rosencrantz and
Guildenstern Are Dead'' (1967), and Peter Weiss's ``Marat Sade''
(1965). Mr. Merrick transferred the 1964 Dublin premiere of
``Philadelphia, Here I Come!,'' by a then unknown Brian Friel,
intact to Broadway, where it ran for 326 performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to keep his passport in his pocket at all times in
case he heard of a show opening in London. That way, he'd be there
first,'' producer Jon B. Platt, chairman of Broadway in Boston/SFX
Theatrical, said Wednesday. ``He was one of a kind _ a showman's
showman.''
</P>
<P>
   A believer in the the maxim that no publicity is bad publicity,
Mr. Merrick was almost as well known for media stunts as for
putting on plays. He once placed a monkey at the wheel of English
taxicab with a sign on the side of the vehicle proclaiming, ``I am
driving my master to see `The Matchmaker.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Even Mr. Merrick's feuds with actors helped sell tickets. The
producer battled regularly with Jackie Gleason, who starred in the
musical ``Take Me Along.'' He also fought with Anna Maria
Alberghetti, star of ``Carnival,'' who reportedly hung his
photograph in the bathroom of her dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   His relations with playmakers and the press were no easier.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of the opening preview performance of a troubled
production of ``42d Street,'' shortly before the curtain was to go
up, the audience was told the show had been canceled because of
technical problems. In fact, Mr. Merrick _ who had barred the press
from previews _ had spotted Cliff Jahr of The New York Times in the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a snake loose in the theater,'' he said the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merrick is the Bermuda Triangle in a Brooks Brothers suit,''
Stan Freberg told the Globe in 1989, after working with the
producer on a stage version of his comedy album ``Stan Freberg
Presents the United States of America.'' After telling Freberg he
was brilliant _ the next George S. Kaufman _ and promising him
fame, fortune, and a Pulitzer, Mr. Merrick suggested bringing in
another writer to punch up the writer's script, according to
Freberg. He later told him to take Abraham Lincoln out of a Civil
War sequence ``because he doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Merrick suffered a stroke in the early 1980s that affected
his speech and for the rest of his life he used a wheelchair. His
personal life was as volatile as his career. He was married six
times, most recently to Natalie Lloyd, who had been his live-in
companion since 1989. He leaves two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Merrick's death came three days after the passing of
Alexander Cohen, another flamboyant producer with an impressive
list of Broadway shows. Cohen died Saturday at age 79.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this story.)
</P>
