<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION LEADER THREATENS FORCE TO HALT ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ As President Robert Mugabe's party boycotted
church-led peace talks, Zimbabwe's opposition leader said Wednesday
his party may be forced to use force in order to defend its members
from attacks by government supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Movement for Democratic Change, a fledgling political
organization that threatens to break Mugabe's 20-year grip on
power, has until now urged its followers not to give the president
cause to impose emergency rule.
</P>
<P>
   But with violence rising against its members and the police
making only minimal efforts to stem the lawlessness, opposition
leader Morgan Tsvangirai hinted that his party would no longer turn
the other cheek. Five opposition members have been killed in the
past three days by pro-government mobs.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition ``will no longer sit back and watch our
supporters being killed,'' Tsvangirai told reporters in Zimbabwe's
capital. ``We cannot stand by and watch while our people are being
murdered. We shall devise a strategy to protect ourselves. We shall
take this violence to their doorstep.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite urgent regional and Western diplomatic efforts, Zimbabwe
is sliding deeper into a state of anarchy. In the past two months,
government supporters and veterans of the liberation war against
colonial Rhodesia have seized nearly 600 white-owned commercial
farms and invaded hundreds more. Two farmers have been killed and
scores of farm workers and their families have been badly beaten.
</P>
<P>
   The veterans claim they are taking back the land they fought for
two decades ago, but as popular support for the opposition grows,
the violence has turned increasingly political and moved off the
farms. The veterans, who launched the attacks in late February
after voters rejected Mugabe's proposed new constitution, have
vowed to go back to war if the ruling party loses upcoming
parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   Far from condemning the farm invasions, Mugabe has encouraged
them. He allocated $500,000 back in February to help fund the
veterans, urged his supporters to ignore two High Court orders to
halt the illegal invasions, and resisted pressure from Britain and
his neighboring counterparts to evict the squatters.
</P>
<P>
   As he dispatched three cabinet members to London for high-level
talks on land reform, due to start Thursday, Mugabe firmly
denounced Britain's attempt to link aid for land reform to a return
of law and order. His party also resisted internal pressure,
boycotting church-led peace talks Wednesday with the opposition in
Harare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mugabe has maintained power by simulating violence all the
time,'' said Washington Sansole, a former High Court judge. British
and regional leaders ``are asking him to give up the one thing
that's kept him in power. He can't let go.''
</P>
<P>
   The deteriorating political climate dealt another blow to
Zimbabwe's already beleaguered economy as all-important tobacco
sales opened slowly Wednesday. Economists said only about 30
percent of the country's normal annual yield of tobacco reached the
auction houses in time for the opening gavel.
</P>
<P>
   Large quantities of tobacco have been burned by angry mobs
invading the farms, and many farmers have been blocked entry to
their barns to grade their leaf. The Zimbabwe Tobacco Association
has urged farmers to delay delivery of their bales until next month
in the hope that the violence will ease. Zimbabwe's top foreign
exchange earner, tobacco accounts for about 25 percent of the
country's annual economic output.
</P>
<P>
   There were conflicting reports Wednesday about the situation on
the farms. The Commercial Farmers Union said the violence was
slowing somewhat, but individual farmers said as many as 12 new
farms have been seized since Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ending the attacks is critical. Speaking ahead of the meeting in
London, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said Wednesday that
Britain would increase aid for land reform in Zimbabwe by $57
million over the next two years only if Mugabe called off the
invasions and organized the elections. ``The illegal occupations
must be stopped before any land reform starts,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has also demanded that a priority had to be placed on
resettling poor rural families and that farmers be compensated for
land they gave up. Earlier this month, Zimbabwe amended its
constitution to seize land without payment to the owner.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, opposition leader Tsvangirai said two more men were
killed in Kariba, about 220 miles northwest of Harare, by
government supporters on Tuesday. One was dragged from his office
and beaten to death in the streets. Three men died on Monday _ one
from gunshot wounds and another from a blow to his head from an ax.
The third was beaten to death after Mugabe followers saw that he
was wearing an opposition T-shirt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
