u i BC-ARMS-HELMS-BOS &LR;      04-26 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMS-HELMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELMS TO CLINTON: NO ARMS BILL `ON MY WATCH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An emboldened Senator Jesse Helms declared
Wednesday that President Clinton would not be able to pass any
arms-control measure in the last months of his term, saying, ``Not
on my watch, Mr. President.''
</P>
<P>
   Arms control analysts said the North Carolina Republican's
outburst carries considerable weight because of the absence of
strong Clinton administration leadership on non-proliferation
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration has created their own Jesse Helms
monster,'' said Seyom Brown, a visiting fellow at the Brookings
Institution in Washington and a professor of international
relations at Brandeis University.
</P>
<P>
   Helms' statement on the Senate floor came at a time when the
United States is talking with Russia about renegotiating the
landmark 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty to allow for a US
national missile defense system. His remarks came just a day after
President Clinton met with Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov at
the White House to talk about the future of disarmament agreements.
</P>
<P>
   But Helms, the chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, said if the administration tried to amend the ABM
treaty, he would not hold hearings or let the measure out of his
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be clear to avoid any misunderstanding down the line,''
he said. ``Any modified ABM treaty negotiated by this
administration will be DOA _ dead on arrival.''
</P>
<P>
   He further said, ``This administration's time for grand treaties
is clearly at an end. We will not consider any new, last-minute
arms control measures that this administration negotiates in its
final closing months in office.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin dismissed Helms'
remarks, saying it wouldn't stop the administration from
negotiating with Russia to amend the ABM treaty if the United
States goes ahead with the missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Helms is not the entire Senate,'' Rubin said. ``Senator Helms
is an important senator (but) in the past, treaties have been
approved that he voted against and that he opposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said, however, that Helms' statements represented a
failure of the Clinton administration strategy of trying to bring
him over to their side.
</P>
<P>
   First, Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright tried to
cultivate Helms, praising him in public, even visiting him in North
Carolina. Then, UN Ambassador Richard Holbrooke tried to curry
favor with Helms by bringing him before the UN Security Council in
the hopes that both sides could learn from the other and defuse the
issue of US arrears to the United Nations. That plan worked, in the
short term, with the passage of partial US payment.
</P>
<P>
   Later, again under Holbrooke's encouragement, the UN Security
Council traveled to Washington with Helms as their host, a move
that ``enhances the notion that Helms is somehow as important as
the president in setting a foreign policy agenda,'' Brandeis' Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have Madeleine Albright and Richard Holbrooke genuflecting
in the direction of Helms for tactical political maneuvers. It
inflated the man's sense of his own power. What we have here is
Holbrookeian arrogance feeding Helmsian arrogance,'' said Brown,
who is working this year on a study of force and diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Arms control, stalled in recent years after moving swiftly at
the end of the Cold War, looms as one of the top issues for this
year and coming years.
</P>
<P>
   It has become extraordinarily tumultuous in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Russia has taken the high moral ground in three major
steps favoring non-proliferation _ passing a nuclear test ban
treaty, ratifying the Start II nuclear arms reduction pact with the
United States and then proposing deep cuts in Start III talks _ the
US testing of a missile defense system has greatly angered other
world leaders. Those leaders fear that such a system would give the
United States a significant strategic advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But there are major doubts about whether even a system that is
greatly scaled down from President Reagan's Star Wars dream could
ever work.
</P>
<P>
   In late June or early July, the Pentagon plans a third and final
test of a missile defense system before Clinton decides to either
back funding for the entire program or delay the decision for his
successor.
</P>
<P>
   John D. Steinbruner, professor of public policy at the
University of Maryland, said the administration has allowed its
non-proliferation policy to drift while waiting on a decision for
missile defense, estimated to cost $60 billion this week by the
nonpartisan Congressional Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   That report, authored by Geoffrey Forden, raises several
questions about the viability of the current schedule for the
program, suggesting that the 10-year timeframe may be too short and
some analysts believe it could benefit from more than 21 flight
tests _ each costing $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Steinbruner said, administration officials had
made only ``nominal efforts'' on behalf of the nuclear test ban
treaty, which was defeated earlier this year. And he criticized the
lack of administration push for the Start II pact, which means it
won't likely go through the Senate this year either _ whether Helms
spoke up or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton needs to marshal the majority view in this country
that supports the arms control treaties,'' Steinbruner said. ``But
the minority realizes there's basically no team on the field and
they can have a field day. Who do you blame? The crazies? Or the
the people who are supposed to defend good sense but aren't?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
