<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-VIVAROCKVEGAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FLINTSTONES' PREQUEL FALLS SHORT OF ROCK-SOLID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as a preschooler, I never quite got into ``The
Flintstones.'' The idea of audience laughter accompanying a
cartoon, which couldn't possibly have been real, always bugged me
(my first critical decision!). Still, one tries to approach
boomer-friendly TV spinoffs such as ``The Flintstones in Viva Rock
Vegas'' with an open mind, and although the new movie isn't
completely, as the song says, a ``gay old time,'' it's better than
anyone had a right to expect.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean that it's great, just that it's innocuous.
It's a surprisingly kid-friendly prequel to ``The Flintstones''
saga, showing how the modern Stone Age family got together. It
plays like an episode or two of the TV show, stretched out to fill
an hour and a half or so.
</P>
<P>
   Fred and Barney (Mark Addy and Stephen Baldwin) are young quarry
workers. Betty (Ally McBeal's Jane Krakowski) is a carhop at the
local bronto-burger stand. Wilma (''3rd Rock From the Sun's''
Kristen Johnston) is an unhappy heiress who sets the story into
motion when she runs away from her empty life and her materialistic
mother (Joan Collins). Betty mistakes Wilma for a, um, caveless
woman (hey, it's the movie's joke, OK?), takes her in as a roommate
and gets her a job at the burger stand. When Fred asks Betty for a
date, Barney begs to be set up and is paired with Wilma. After some
awkwardness, the couples discover where the true chemistry lies,
and head toward romantic bliss.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of movie left to go, however, and we're not even
in Rock Vegas yet. We get there when Wilma's jilted boyfriend, the
smug and snooty Chip Rockefeller (''Dharma &AMP; Greg's'' Thomas
Gibson, clearly enjoying hamming it up), invites the foursome to
his Vegas casino. It is, of course, part of a scheme to ruin the
couples' romantic dreams and steal Wilma back. Since we already
know how things will turn out, this isn't exactly suspenseful.
</P>
<P>
   Acting as a sort of Greek chorus is the Great Gazoo, a
supercilious little space alien who has been banished to Earth to
study mating rituals. Gazoo doesn't really have any business in the
movie except to give stage actor Alan Cumming a chance to hone his
shtick _ which he does much better in his other role, a send-up of
Mick Jagger. Fred kicks the Great Gazoo offscreen a lot; it's easy
to wish that the little twerp would just stay there.
</P>
<P>
   Watching familiar performers enact live-action cartoon
characters is sort of like walking into the biggest-budget
high-school play ever mounted. Perhaps that's why Addy, best-known
to American audiences as the most desperate of the dancers in ``The
Full Monty,'' comes off best; his round face gives Fred a
vulnerability that the blustery cartoon version seldom had. Baldwin
and Krakowski do a pretty good job of nailing their characters'
voices, and especially their goofy laughs. Johnston tries less hard
as Wilma, but at least she looks great in designer cavewear.
Collins' Liz Taylor-lite act and Harvey Korman's addle-brained
portrayal of Wilma's shell-shocked father are mildly amusing.
</P>
<P>
   Characterization and dialogue aren't a big deal here, but then
they weren't a big part of the TV series, either; the cartoon's
best bits were its imaginative use of prehistoric (and pre-human,
but never mind that) animals as household appliances and heavy
machinery. The movie re-creates this passably well, and earns some
points for sliding in some double-entendres that will amuse adults
without stinging young ears. These days, a kid movie that includes
only one gas-passing joke is practically a model of restraint, and
``Viva Rock Vegas'' has a clever moment every 10 minutes or so to
carry it along. The best thing about it, however, is that there's
no laugh track. Bet the producers were tempted to add one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas'' is rated PG for a couple
of mild swear words, some innuendo, many merchandising
possibilities and way too many rock puns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM: ``The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Director: Brian Levant &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Mark Addy, Kristen Johnston &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Length: 91 min. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: PG &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
