<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8002 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TIMECODE-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      04-26 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMECODE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE GIANT LEAP FOR TECHNOLOGY
</HEADLINE>
  (One small leap for film) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Timecode is the little bit of technology appended to
good-quality video or film that allows an editor to synchronize
sound and picture, so that a mouth moves when a voice speaks,
hooves hit the ground when their clip-clop is heard, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Timecode also makes possible the movie of the same name,
directed and based on a story more composed and conducted than
written and directed by Mike Figgis, perhaps best known for
``Leaving Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   More than most of Figgis' sometimes difficult work though, this
one should intrigue if not always delight viewers.
</P>
<P>
   It is billed as a film that shatters the linear narrative form
used in cinema for the past century, largely by taking advantage of
the possibilities of digital video cameras that could be used for
extremely lengthy taping and quite intimate shots. Thankfully,
though the technology makes for a remarkably different looking
film, there is a story, a pretty solid one, underpinning the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Be warned, though, that the technical tricks may cause some
viewers to reach for the aspirin in trying to make sense of what's
happening on screen.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the viewer doesn't see one full-screen, linear
view of the film's events. Rather, we see four views, all playing
simultaneously in split-screen mode.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of minutes, the viewer figures out that this is
the way things will be for the next hour and a half. Soon after
that, the viewer figures out that the events on the four screens
are related.
</P>
<P>
   The film is basically set in and around an office building on
West Hollywood's Sunset Strip, as the four cameras follow the
intertwining stories of two couples, one played by Saffron Burrows
and Stellan Skarsgard, the other by Salma Hayek and Jeanne
Tripplehorn.
</P>
<P>
   Skarsgard plays a dissipated though talented movie producer
having an affair with Hayek's gold-digging bisexual
actress-wannabe.
</P>
<P>
   Tripplehorn's character suspects as much and bugs Hayek's purse
to listen as Hayek meets Skarsgard at his work. Burrows' character
is deeply unsatisfied with her marriage and comes to visit
Skarsgard at his work as well, to tell him she is leaving him.
</P>
<P>
   The fine cast _ which includes Holly Hunter, Julian Sands and
Kyle MacLachlan, among others _ all improvised their lines,
sometimes quite funnily, following a story structure created by
Figgis.
</P>
<P>
   Their performances are all the more remarkable because they were
shot without breaks or second takes, in fifteen 93-minute,
four-camera shoots done over a nine-day period. When the shooting
was done, Figgis settled on one four-camera shoot, the fifteenth,
as the one to be used for the film.
</P>
<P>
   Figgis didn't edit the video at all, merely putting the four
cameras' results (he was one of four videographers) on screen
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   To draw the viewer's eye from one screen to another, and thus
tell the story, Figgis relied on sound, raising the audio level
from one screen, or two, or all four, or none.
</P>
<P>
   The sound mix thus defines the film. A different mix would have
created a different film, much as an underground club DJ can
radically reshape a familiar song by the way he mixes in samples,
drum beats and found sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures still have weight, of course, because this is film.
Indeed, part of ``Timecode's'' strength is the way you can watch an
actor's reactions on one screen to events unfolding on another.
</P>
<P>
   Figgis has constructed a darned clever technology gimmick.
What's remarkable is that despite the gimmick, the film works
pretty well as entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   It's not perfect. A series of fake quakes, for instance, detract
from the story (though they show off how well synchronized the
shooting was). And the confrontation between Tripplehorn's jealous
character and Skarsgard's philandering one and its immediate
aftermath doesn't feel as organic and real as much of the rest of
the film.
</P>
<P>
   That said, ``Timecode'' is a fascinating step forward in the
filmmaking process, and one we can only hope will stimulate the
imagination of other creative people, and the audiences who enjoy
their work. But just in case, bring that bottle of aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QL; 
The film: ``Timecode''; (R; sexuality, violence, bad language). &QL; 
The stars: Stellan Skarsgard, Saffron Burrows, Salma Hayek, Jeanne
Tripplehorn, Julian Sands, Holly Hunter, Kyle MacLachlan, Laurie
Metcalf, Golden Brooks. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Mike Figgis from a story he wrote.
Sound mixer Robert Janiger. Music composed by Figgis and Anthony
Marinelli. Produced by Figgis and Annie Stewart. &QL; 
Running time: 1 hour, 33 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
