<HEADER>
A8007 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-STRANGE-NYT &LR;      04-26 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-STRANGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV INVENTS WHAT JAPAN LACKS: IMPOLITENESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The show began with a clamor befitting a three-ring
circus as the host, one of Japan's most famous comedians, entered
the set shrouded in smoke and dressed as a stick of dynamite.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes after he announced the day's theme _ the nuisance
caused by Japan's motorcycle gangs _ a brief fistfight broke out
between the television show's panel of 100 foreigners and the dozen
or so bike-riding teen-age rebels, pale shadows of Brando's ``wild
one,'' but volatile nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   When order was finally restored, an Iranian panelist bluntly
challenged the Japanese toughs. ``You think you are so strong and
manly because you live in a weak society,'' he said. ``If you are
so brave, you should come to my country and try your tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   With its numbing mixture of idiocy and bully-boy cruelty served
up in a high-pitched din, this show, which was first broadcast in
1998, has become one of the country's most popular by opening a
window on a parallel universe scarcely imagined by most viewers, a
world peopled with foreigners who speak fluent Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   The format for the show, ``Strange Things About the Japanese,''
might best be described as the United Nations meets Jerry Springer.
And on Wednesdays, when the Tokyo Broadcasting System brings a
boisterous mass of 100 opinionated foreigners _ more than most
Japanese will ever meet _ into the nation's living rooms, what
ensues is a vigorous raking over the coals of this deeply insular
society and its sometimes peculiar ways.
</P>
<P>
   The themes have included topics like delinquency and promiscuity
among the young, racism and the long-troubled relations with Korea.
Indeed, Japan is often presented in an unflattering light, as the
show slyly uses foreigners to criticize aspects of society that
much of the news media treats with kid gloves.
</P>
<P>
   But for Japanese viewers, the biggest vicarious thrill may
simply be confrontational debate. In a protocol-constricted
society, where venturing one's opinion too forcefully or even out
of turn is frowned on, the show's arguments, in which foreigners
regularly take on the most enervating features of life here, is
like a bracing breath of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until recently, there haven't been any hard-core debate shows
on TV,'' said Justin Patterson, 25, an American who is a regular
panelist. ``You have plenty of silly shows with people goofing off.
But Japanese have never had shows with people going at it over
ideas or serious issues. I don't mean this to sound bad, but
Japanese often don't have the guts to just tell it like it is, with
a bang.''
</P>
<P>
   The program eagerly shatters other cultural molds, as well.
Rather than ending in the consensus that this society prizes so
highly, ``Strange Things'' ends each week with no particular
conclusion. And although Beat Takeshi, one of Japan's best-known
humorists and filmmakers, is the host, the moderator's role is
almost nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   For many participants, foreigners from every continent, one of
the most important features is the free-flow cosmopolitanism. Not
only does the program serve as a kind of a televised National
Geographic, introducing the residents of one of the most ethnically
homogeneous countries to people from every horizon, but it also
demonstrates to the chagrin of xenophobic rightists that people of
different cultures can successfully cooperate and mix.
</P>
<P>
   The loquacious panelists shatter another cherished myth along
the way _ that only Japanese people can master this country's
tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until this show, for most Japanese, foreigner simply meant
American,'' said Eli Bergmann, 23, a French panelist whose mother
is Japanese. ``Now, they are gradually coming to understand that
there are other countries out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Another participant, Moogwi Kim, 22, a Korean university
student, also emphasized the program's role in helping ease a
closed-off Japan into the globalized world.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more foreign people are coming to Japan, and for the
first time in their lives, Japanese people are realizing the
importance of dealing with them,'' he said. ``Both sides have
lacked a means to communicate with each other until now. The show
has become a sort of bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the earnest talk of multiculturalism and painless
geography lessons, though, inevitably the show favors entertainment
over erudition. For one thing, the producers sometimes find it
simpler to divide up the participants by race or color, lumping
Australians and Israelis with Europeans, and Bangladeshis with
Africans.
</P>
<P>
   For another, the emphasis in many debates seems to be on working
the foreigners into a hot lather and cutting back and forth between
commentators so quickly that there is little opportunity for
follow-up, or indeed serious thought. ``It can fairly resemble a
zoo,'' Bergmann conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Although it may open windows on other worlds for its viewers,
for some the zoolike aspect of the program, with its raucous,
inconclusive debates, might almost seem to advertise Japan's
conservative values. For all the giddy freedom of foreigners, the
disorder subtly recommends the tranquillity of a uniform society
governed firmly by rules understood by all.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, though, the show works as Japanese entertainment,
because it unthreateningly highlights this country's unusual
situation as an island of high prosperity inhabited by a
provincial, nearly homogenous and inwardly turned people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan is the only country in the world to have such a
program,'' said Rufin Zomahoun, 35, a graduate student from Benin
who is the biggest star of the show. ``As a closed society, this
country is a special case. They know that foreigners find them
strange, and they itch to hear what we think.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
