r e BC-AUDIO-BRAXTON27-COX     04-26 0322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-BRAXTON27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braxton returns with confidence and style
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Heat'' Toni Braxton is generating on her third album isn't
really because of the barely-there outfit she wears on the cover _
or the summery title track.
</P>
<P>
   It comes from the confidence that resonates throughout this
return.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly enjoying the luxury of being an artist who is
appreciated whether barefoot and blue-jeaned (her 1992 single ``How
Many Ways'') or all-gowned-up with an orchestra (the 1996 ballad
``Un-Break My Heart''), the throaty singer revels in her range of
musical styles here.
</P>
<P>
   Which shifts the focus to perhaps the only problem with the
album: lyrically, much of this is forgettable mood-setting, rather
than her usual, well-done storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   Braxton teams up with big ballad provider Diane Warren
(``Un-Break'') on ``Spanish Guitar'' and explodes on an almost
over-orchestrated ``Killing Me Softly'' for a now-Latino-savvy
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Breathless come-on ``Maybe,'' ``Speaking In Tongues'' and sweaty
instrumental ``The Art of Love'' erase any memory that she was a
shy preacher's girl.
</P>
<P>
   But the certain hit single is the slow, slinky offering ``Just
Be A Man About It.'' Created by Atlanta talents John'ta Austin,
Teddy Bishop and Bryan Michael-Cox, the plainspoken and
well-written ballad is as sassy as her first solo hit, 1992's
``Love Shoulda Brought You Home.''
</P>
<P>
   Hear it and you can almost see Oprah and her audience waving one
hand in affirmation and exchanging ``Mmm-hmm girls! Tell 'em!''
</P>
<P>
   R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``The Heat''
</P>
<P>
   Toni Braxton. LaFace Records. 12 tracks. Our critic's grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : More on Toni Braxton, LaFace Records:
www.tonibraxtononline.com
</P>
<P>
   /www. laface.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
