<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By Nick Tate and Eric Sundquist
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Is There Anybody Out There? The Wall Live''
</P>
<P>
   Pink Floyd. Columbia. 30 tracks
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Pink Floyd's colossus ``The Wall'' set the standard for '70s
progressive rock concept albums. Which is to say parts of it were a
crashing bore. Now, 20 years after redefining art-rock pretense,
Floyd has issued a live two-disc set culled from several 1980-81
``Wall'' shows. And this time, Roger Waters and Co. get it right.
``The Wall Live'' is wonderfully free of the art-school touches
that cluttered the original. Gone are the melodramatic segues and
crazed teachers shouting over David Gilmour's shimmering guitar
licks, which are looser and more engaging live. All that's left is
the menacing, raucous rock show singer-composer Roger Waters
intended _ as much a play on Floyd's love-hate relationship with
fans as a commentary on the angst of modern life. In places, ``The
Wall'' still goes over the top _ exhibit A: the campy ``Vera'' and
``Bring the Boys Back Home'' shtick. But for the most part, this
set captures Floyd stripped bare, showcasing the nexus of Gilmour's
clean, soulful breaks, Waters' madhouse-howl vocals and Richard
Wright's trippy keyboard washes.
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : More on Pink Floyd: www.thewalllive.com,
www.pinkfloyd.co.uk
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Silver &AMP; Gold''
</P>
<P>
   Neil Young. Reprise. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   The first album of newly released Neil Young tunes since
``Broken Arrow'' in '96, ``S&AMP;G'' is alternately pretty and dark,
melodic and random-sounding, obvious and inscrutably personal. Of
Young's dozens of records, ``S&AMP;G'' sounds most like '78's ``Comes a
Time.'' The title track, a short, bright tune about the uselessness
of material possessions (``I used to have a treasure chest/Got so
heavy that I had to rest'') even dates to the same era, only now
being released. Among the more lyrically idiosyncratic tracks,
``Red Sun'' merges familiar Youngian Western-rustic imagery (``When
the red sun sets/on the railroad town/And the bars begin to
laugh/with a happy sound'') with what seems to be a suggestion of
Jesus' return (``The well will be flowin'/and the words will come
fast/When the one who is comin'/Arrives here at last''). As a rule,
Young's best stuff is electric, and this mostly unplugged set isn't
an exception. His best recent song, the moving ``Slowpoke,'' was
transferred from ``S&AMP;G'' to last year's CSN&AMP;Y album. Yet new Neil
is always worth a listen, and there's enough going on that this
promises to grow on you with each hearing.
</P>
<P>
   _Eric Sundquist
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : More on Neil Young: www.neilyoung.com
</P>
<P>
   Nick Tate and Eric Sundquist writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
