<HEADER>
A8014 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-FASTCOOK-RECIPES     04-26 2942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-FASTCOOK-RECIPES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to saute and make a pan sauce
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Simple techniques in words and pictures and words
</P>
<P>
   The whole world of food has opened up to us in the past few
years. Now, if only we had the time to enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have access to so many ingredients, but we have a lot less
time to cook,'' said Pam Anderson, author of ``How to Cook Without
a Book'' (Broadway Books, $25).
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was in Atlanta this month to teach a class and preach
the gospel about the importance of mastering a few basic cooking
techniques in order to enjoy home-cooked meals on weeknights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cherry-picked the simple techniques that will work on
weeknights, when people most need help,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   We've cherry-picked even further to give you a feel for her book
and her message. Below, we focus on searing, sauteing and pan
sauces. We also offer Anderson's answer for how to quickly prepare
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Her book is a primer on simple techniques, with easy recipes
that can be memorized, along with rhymes to help you learn the
techniques.
</P>
<P>
   An ideal companion to Anderson's book is James Peterson's ``The
Essentials of Cooking'' (Artisan, $40). Peterson said he made the
book, with hundreds of color photos demonstrating techniques, for
``the MTV generation'' that works better with visuals. It's a
handsome book worthy of space on most kitchen shelves as a
reference. Below, you'll see his photos for sauteing pork chops to
go along with Anderson's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Good Gadgets
</P>
<P>
   Some kitchen gadgets and tools are useless; others are real
timesavers. During a class at Cook's Warehouse this month, Pam
Anderson revealed three she wouldn't live without.
</P>
<P>
   The salad spinner _ great not only for spinning the salad
greens, but she also uses it to drain the water from shredded
potatoes before making potato cakes. It works wonders. Anderson got
nearly a half gallon of water out of two spins on the potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Egg slicer _ Anderson keeps boiled eggs in her refrigerator at
all times. She plops one or two in the egg slicer and tosses with
salad greens for an instant, substantial salad.
</P>
<P>
   Tongs _ the cheaper the better, Anderson said. She uses them to
turn meat, lift lids, toss salads.
</P>
<P>
   Searing
</P>
<P>
   ``The only trick to searing is a pan that's good and hot,
</P>
<P>
   The only other thing you need is a fan that vents a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How to Cook Without a Book''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Choose the right size skillet, making sure the pieces of meat
will have neither too much nor too little space between them. Make
sure the skillet is heavy-bottomed. Cast iron works well unless
you're making a wine sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Set the skillet over low heat for 5 to 10 minutes while
preparing dinner and seasoning the meat or fish. Drizzle both sides
of each piece of meat or fish with oil. Season both sides with salt
and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Crank up the heat under the dry pan and turn on the exhaust
fan 3 or 4 minutes before searing. Cook the pieces of meat or fish
over high heat until an even, rich brown crust forms, 2 to 4
minutes, depending on type and thickness of the cut. Turn and cook
until the remaining side develops a crust, 2 to 4 minutes longer.
Set a timer so you don't lose track.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  This method works best for steaks, burgers, pork tenderloin,
fish steaks (tuna, swordfish, halibut, sea bass, salmon) and
scallops. Seared meats pair well with pan sauces (see recipes, next
page). Anderson also suggests flavored butters and relishes.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Seared Scallops
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 5 minutes Cooking time: 4
minutes
</P>
<P>
   One or two of these make a lovely first course, especially when
served with Orange Pan Sauce With Pernod (see recipe, next page).
Anderson suggests buying only untreated or dry scallops. By law,
treated scallops should be labeled ``water added scallop product.''
Such treated scallops don't sear well.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds dry (see explanation above) sea scallops
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Lemon wedges or a pan sauce
</P>
<P>
   Set a heavy-bottomed 12-inch skillet over low heat for 5 to 10
minutes while preparing the meal and seasoning the scallops. (To
speed up the heating process, the skillet can be set over medium
heat for 3 to 4 minutes.) About 3 to 4 minutes before searing the
scallops, turn on the exhaust fan and increase the heat to high.
</P>
<P>
   To season the scallops, set them on a plate and drizzle with
oil; turn to coat. Sprinkle both sides with salt and pepper. A
minute or so after the residual oils in the skillet send up wisps
of smoke, put the scallops in the pan. Cook over high heat until
they develop a thick, rich brown crust, about 2 minutes. Turn them
and continue to cook over high heat until the other sides develop a
thick, rich brown crust, about 2 minutes longer. Remove from the
pan and let stand a couple of minutes. Serve with lemon wedges or
make a pan sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 210 calories, 28 grams protein, 8 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 35), 4 grams carbohydrates, 56
milligrams cholesterol, 274 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Seared Pork Tenderloin
</P>
<P>
   Medallions
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 5 minutes Cooking time: 7-8
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Roasting whole tenderloins has always been the standby; but
cutting the tenderloins into medallions is a much quicker way to
prepare this tender meat. And it's quite tasty, too, especially
paired with the black pepper molasses pan sauce (see recipe, next
page).
</P>
<P>
   2 pork tenderloins (about 1 1/2 pounds total), patted dry and
cut crosswise into 1 1/2-inch medallions, each pressed with
fingertips to 3/4- to 1-inch thickness
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Pan sauce
</P>
<P>
   Set a heavy-bottomed 12-inch skillet over low heat for 5 to 10
minutes. About 3 to 4 minutes before searing the medallions, turn
the exhaust fan on and increase heat to high. Set medallions on a
plate, drizzle with oil and turn to coat. Sprinkle with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   A minute or so after the residual oils in the skillet send up
wisps of smoke, put medallions in the pan. Cook over high heat
until the meat develops a thick, rich brown crust, 3 1/2 to 4
minutes. Turn the medallions and continue to cook over high heat
until the remaining sides develop a thick, rich brown crust, 3-3
1/2 minutes longer. Check that it's cooked through (make a small
cut). Remove to a plate. Serve with pan sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 272 calories, 34 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 46), no carbohydrates, 107 milligrams
cholesterol, 74 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Sauteing
</P>
<P>
   ``Heat butter and oil, swirling them around.
</P>
<P>
   Add meat, seasoned and coated, and cook until beautifully
browned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How to Cook Without a Book''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Choose the right size skillet so that the pieces of meat have
neither too much nor too little space between them. Before
preparing the meat, set the skillet over medium-low heat,
immediately adding a mix of oil and butter, so that they heat up
with the skillet.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  While the skillet is heating, prepare the meat, sprinkling
both sides of each piece with salt and pepper, then dredging each
side in flour. A couple of minutes before sauteing, increase the
heat to medium-high. When the oil is hot but not smoking and the
flecks of milk solids in the butter turn golden brown and smell
nutty, add the meat.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cook the meat, turning only once, until golden brown on each
side. Make a pan sauce or serve with an uncooked sauce or relish.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  This method works well with chicken and turkey cutlets,
boneless pork chops, fish fillets (flounder, catfish, snapper,
tilapia, grouper and other thin, white-fleshed fish) and duck
breasts.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Sauteed Boneless,
</P>
<P>
   Skinless Chicken
</P>
<P>
   Cutlets
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 6-8 minutes
</P>
<P>
   There probably isn't a greater standby in most households than
boneless, skinless chicken breasts. This method is quick, and when
the chicken is served with pan sauces, an everyday meal becomes
something special.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon oil
</P>
<P>
   4 boneless chicken breast halves, trimmed of fat and pounded
with the dull side of a chef's knife until texture and width are
more or less even
</P>
<P>
   Salt and ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup all-purpose flour, measured into a pie plate or other
shallow pan
</P>
<P>
   Lemon wedges, or a pan sauce or uncooked relish
</P>
<P>
   Heat butter and oil in an 11- to 12-inch skillet over low heat.
While the pan is heating, sprinkle chicken breasts on both sides
with salt and pepper, then dredge in flour.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of minutes before sauteing, increase the heat to
medium-high. When the butter stops foaming and starts to smell
nutty, arrange the chicken breasts, skinned side up, in the
skillet. Cook, turning only once, until chicken breasts are rich
golden brown, about 3-4 minutes per side. Remove chicken from
skillet. Serve immediately with lemon wedges, an uncooked relish or
a pan sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Pork chop variation: Substitute 4 thick-cut boneless pork chops
for the chicken breasts and follow the above directions. Serve with
an uncooked relish or pan sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 325 calories, 34 grams protein, 18 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 50), 4 grams carbohydrates, 111
milligrams cholesterol, 139 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Pan Sauces
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Measure pan sauce ingredients in a measuring cup (liquids
always total 1/2 cup).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pour liquid (and other ingredients) into hot skillet once
meat, poultry or fish has been removed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Reduce liquid to 1/4 cup. (But don't measure, just eyeball it.
When it looks like the liquid has reduced by half, it's ready for
next step.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tilt the skillet and whisk in butter or cream or other fat,
and spoon over each portion and serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``How to Cook Without a Book''
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Orange Pan Sauce With Pernod
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 3 minutes Cooking time: 3-4
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Pernod is an anise-flavored aperitif. This sauce is great with
chicken and turkey cutlets, boneless pork chops and tenderloin,
fish fillets, steaks and scallops.
</P>
<P>
   Liquid:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup canned low-sodium chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   Flavorings:
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely grated orange zest
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Pernod
</P>
<P>
   Fat:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   Combine the broth, juice, zest and Pernod. Pour into the searing
or sauteing pan and boil until the liquid is reduced to about 1/4
cup, scraping up bits on the bottom of the pan. Tilt the skillet so
that the reduced liquid is at one side of the pan. Whisk in butter
until sauce is smooth. Spoon over meat or fish.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 36 calories, less than 1 gram protein, 3 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 76), 2 grams carbohydrates, 8
milligrams cholesterol, 32 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Mushroom-Goat Cheese Pan Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 5 minutes Cooking time: 5-6
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Shiitake mushrooms are best in this, but any kind will do.
Packages of pre-sliced button mushrooms will save even more time.
The goat cheese substitutes for butter or cream _ most delicious
with chicken, turkey, pork chops, tenderloins, steaks and burgers.
</P>
<P>
   Liquid:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup canned low-sodium chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup full-bodied red wine
</P>
<P>
   Flavorings:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound mushrooms, stems removed and discarded, caps sliced
thin
</P>
<P>
   Fat:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced fresh parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   Measure the broth and wine in a measuring cup. Put the mushrooms
in an empty skillet; saute until wilted, 2 to 3 minutes. Pour in
the broth and red wine and boil until the liquid is reduced to
about 1/4 cup, scraping up the bits on the bottom of the pan. Tilt
the skillet so that the reduced liquid is at one side of the pan
and whisk in the goat cheese until smooth. Add parsley and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 32 calories, 2 grams protein, 1 gram fat (percent
calories from fat, 39), 3 grams carbohydrates, 3 milligrams
cholesterol, 25 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   White Wine Vinegar Pan Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 2 minutes Cooking time: 3-4
minutes
</P>
<P>
   A classic that goes well with chicken, turkey, fish, steaks and
scallops.
</P>
<P>
   Liquid:
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons canned low-sodium chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Flavoring:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   Fat:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   Combine the broth, vinegar and mustard in a measuring cup. Pour
into the searing or sauteing pan and boil until the liquid is
reduced to about 1/4 cup, scraping up the bits on the bottom of the
pan. Tilt the skillet so that the reduced liquid is at one side of
the pan. Whisk in butter until sauce is smooth. Spoon over meat or
fish.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 36 calories, 1 gram protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 87), 1 gram carbohydrates, 8 milligrams
cholesterol, 137 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Tomato-Tarragon Pan Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 3 minutes Cooking time: 3-4
minutes
</P>
<P>
   A quick tomato sauce will liven up chicken, turkey, pork chops,
fish and steak.
</P>
<P>
   Liquid:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup canned low-sodium chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dry vermouth or white wine
</P>
<P>
   Flavorings:
</P>
<P>
   4 canned tomatoes, coarsely chopped, about 3/4 cup
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced fresh tarragon or scant 1/2 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   Fat:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   Combine the broth and vermouth with the tomatoes and tarragon.
Pour into the searing or sauteing pan and boil until the liquid is
reduced to about 1/4 cup, scraping up the bits on the bottom of the
pan. Tilt the skillet so that the reduced liquid is at one side of
the pan. Whisk in butter until sauce is smooth. Spoon over meat or
fish.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 39 calories, 1 gram protein, 3 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 71), 2 grams carbohydrates, 8 milligrams
cholesterol, 106 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Black Pepper Molasses Pan Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 3 minutes Cooking time: 3-4
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Power-packed with flavor and an excellent choice for pork and
steaks. This sauce is also good on duck breasts and burgers.
</P>
<P>
   Liquid:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup canned low-sodium chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup full-bodied red wine
</P>
<P>
   Flavorings:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons molasses
</P>
<P>
   Several grinds freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Fat:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   Combine the broth, wine, molasses and pepper in a measuring cup.
Pour into the searing or sauteing pan and boil until the liquid is
reduced to about 1/4 cup, scraping up the bits on the bottom of the
pan. Tilt the skillet so that the reduced liquid is at one side of
the pan. Whisk in butter until sauce is smooth. Spoon over meat or
fish.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 54 calories, less than 1 gram protein, 3 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 49), 6 grams carbohydrates, 8
milligrams cholesterol, 36 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Steam-sauteing
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Steam-Sauteed Vegetables
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 5-10 minutes Cooking time:
9-14 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is a master recipe that will offer a quick side dish. It's
ideal for asparagus, broccoli, Brussels sprouts, cabbage, carrots,
parsnips, cauliflower, celery, fennel, green beans and winter
squash. You'll need to snap, chop and peel the veggies accordingly,
thus the flexible prep time. And cooking times will also vary, but
the goal is to get vegetables to the ``just tender'' point.
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fat (extra-virgin olive oil, vegetable oil, butter
or bacon fat)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 pound prepared vegetable
</P>
<P>
   Optional aromatics:
</P>
<P>
   ( 1/2 small onion, sliced thin; or 2 medium garlic cloves,
minced; dried/fresh herbs; ground black pepper)
</P>
<P>
   Bring the water, fat, salt and vegetable, along with optional
aromatics, to a boil in a Dutch oven or large, deep skillet. Cover
and steam over medium-high heat until the vegetable is brightly
colored and just tender, 5 to 10 minutes, depending on vegetable
size.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the lid and continue to cook until the liquid evaporates,
1 to 2 minutes longer, adding more fresh herbs or other flavorings
as desired. Saute to intensify flavors, 1 to 2 minutes longer.
Adjust seasonings, including pepper to taste, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Steam-saute variations
</P>
<P>
   Here are examples to use while following the recipe above:
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable: 1 pound carrots, cut into 1/2-inch-thick coins
</P>
<P>
   Fat: 1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   Spice: 1/4 teaspoon grated nutmeg (add with carrots)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 75 calories, 1 gram protein, 3 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 38), 12 grams carbohydrates, 8 milligrams
cholesterol, 365 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable: 1 pound fennel, tops trimmed (fronds reserved), bulbs
halved, cored and sliced thin crosswise
</P>
<P>
   Fat: 1 tablespoon extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Flavoring: 1 tablespoon minced fennel fronds (add during saute
stage)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 62 calories, 1 gram protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 52), 8 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 349
milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   1. Olive oil and butter go in pan for saute.
</P>
<P>
   2. Pork chop is breaded.
</P>
<P>
   3. Pork chops being sauteed.
</P>
<P>
   4. After the pork chops are cooked, mushrooms are sauteed in
pork fat.
</P>
<P>
   5. Wine is added to the mushrooms to deglaze the pan.
</P>
<P>
   6. Goat cheese is whisked into the mushroom pan sauce.
</P>
<P>
   7. The pan sauce is added to the finished pork chops.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
