<HEADER>
A8015 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-FASTCOOK27-COX     04-26 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-FASTCOOK27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When time is a factor, remembering the basics of sauteing,
searing and deglazing will help you get it on the table
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's 6:30 and the workday was a bear. Relaxing would be nice,
but stomachs can be heard growling all through the house. The rest
of the family is looking at the cook with urgent ``What's for
dinner'' expressions.
</P>
<P>
   This is no time to go digging for a recipe and rounding up a
dozen ingredients. The family needs dinner in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it's time to rely on a few basic cooking techniques _
like sauteing, searing and deglazing to make a pan sauce. In a
half-hour, all will be eating well.
</P>
<P>
   ``After work, I'm tired, and sometimes a recipe is a stumbling
block. If you have to engage with a recipe, read it through, find
all the ingredients, you're likely to say `forget it' and order
out,'' said Pam Anderson, author of ``How to Cook Without a Book''
(Broadway Books, $25).
</P>
<P>
   If Anderson stumbles over recipes, then it's not hard to see how
the average home cook would. Anderson is the former executive
editor of Cook's Illustrated magazine, which specializes in testing
numerous recipes to find the perfect one for a dish. Her last
cookbook, in fact, was called ``The Perfect Recipe: Getting it
Right Every Time'' (Houghton Mifflin, $27).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd spend my days testing recipes and analyzing them, then at
5 o'clock I would go home and open the refrigerator and I didn't
know what to do,'' Anderson confesses. ``I felt like a failure.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, Anderson learned, was returning to basics and
focusing on the how-to more than the what. By mastering a few
simple techniques and rules and keeping the pantry stocked, dinner
can be on the table in a half-hour almost any night.
</P>
<P>
   James Peterson, author of ``The Essentials of Cooking''
(Artisan, $40) also urges cooks to focus on techniques rather than
exact recipes. His new book has thousands of step-by-step color
photos demonstrating the most basic techniques such as slicing a
carrot to trussing a chicken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we learn backwards,'' said Peterson, an
award-winning cookbook author. ``I was cooking I don't know how
long before I learned how to peel a turnip.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's book doesn't have photos, but it does offer short,
master recipes along with a few rhymes that can be memorized to
help home cooks learn to work without the safety net of recipes.
</P>
<P>
   She's also streamlined certain techniques to adapt them to
modern, time-crunched lifestyles. For pan sauces, she's cut the
amount of liquid and therefore the cooking time it takes to reduce
to a sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perfect way is fine for entertaining,'' said Anderson.
``But I've learned we need the `get it on the table' style of
cooking, too.''
</P>
<P>
   So, in one pan, a cook can first steam-saute some veggies; then
saute some chicken breasts or boneless pork chops or sear a steak
or scallops; and then from the pan juices create a quick, tasty
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you can concentrate on what's really important _ sitting
down with the people you love,'' said Anderson, ``and rediscovering
the magic you can have at the dinner table.''
</P>
<P>
   SAUTEING
</P>
<P>
   ``Heat butter and oil, swirling them around. Add meat, seasoned
and coated, and cook until beautifully browned.''
</P>
<P>
   SEARING
</P>
<P>
   ``The only trick to searing is a pan that's good and hot. The
only other thing you need is a fan that vents a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   A PREPARED PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   If a cook keeps the pantry stocked with these few essential
items, dinner is always a quick half-hour away:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A dozen eggs
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Boneless chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pasta
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Canned tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Potatoes
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Onions
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hearts of romaine lettuce
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
