A8016 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP27-COX     04-26 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rice salad the perfect mix of flavors
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Susan Terry of Roswell, Ga., asked for a
sweet-and-sour rice salad she vaguely recalled that had green
onions in it. Beyond that, she said, it might have included raisins
and a bit of cinnamon.
</P>
<P>
   While we didn't come up with a perfect match, this salad sent by
Florence Prince of Woodstock, Ga., sounded too good to pass up. Our
tester reports it is both easy and delicious, as terrific a
combination as sweet-and-sour.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Hot German Rice
</P>
<P>
   Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   With a nice balance of sweet, sour and salty flavors, this
unusual salad would be an excellent choice for a potluck.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup uncooked long-grain rice (3 cups cooked)
</P>
<P>
   8 slices bacon
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon celery seed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped green bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped pimento
</P>
<P>
   1 hard-cooked egg, diced
</P>
<P>
   Cook rice according to package directions. Meanwhile, in a
skillet over medium heat, cook bacon until crisp, about 5 minutes.
Reserve drippings; drain bacon and crumble. In a saucepan, combine
1/4 cup bacon drippings, cooked rice, sugar, vinegar, water, salt,
celery seed, onion, green pepper, pimento and egg. Cook and stir
until liquid is absorbed. Add bacon and toss. Serve hot or warm.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 243 calories, 6 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 20), 41 grams carbohydrates, 42 milligrams
cholesterol, 378 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Request
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Stevens wants to make Dutch Lettuce, which includes
mashed potatoes, boiled eggs, bacon and lettuce mixed and covered
with hot bacon drippings to wilt the lettuce. ``It sounds strange,
but it is delicious. It's a great stick-to-your-ribs meal,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
