<HEADER>
A8017 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION2     04-26 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHOPPING DESTINATION: Summerville, S.C.
 &HT;    Finding charm amid the Lowcountry pines
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUMMERVILLE, S.C. _ Wealthy plantation owners and their families
began coming here as early as 1745 to settle among the pines,
seeking respite from swamp fevers and insects plaguing the
peninsula of ``Charles Town,'' now Charleston, 20 miles away on the
coast.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1900s, the town had become a popular winter resort
for Northerners who came for the mild climate, the fresh air (with
its reputed therapeutic qualities) and good hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, people are drawn to the lovely ``Flowertown in the
Pines'' for its small-town friendliness, 700 buildings on the
National Register of Historic Places, cozy bed-and-breakfast inns
in historic homes and a fabulous resort on the outskirts of town
and, no doubt, the excellent shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Brick storefronts downtown house a wonderful array of specialty
shops with antiques, collectibles, original art, handmade crafts,
toys, home decor, gifts, apparel and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Among the shops facing shady Hutchinson Square are Piazza, a
home decor shop with an artist studio and garden shop inside; High
Cotton, which offers first-quality overruns and closeouts with
labels including Banana Republic, American Eagle Outfitters, Lands'
End, L.L. Bean and Talbots; and Dorchester Jeweler and Gifts, which
carries affordable jewelry and pins inspired by Charleston
architectural design.
</P>
<P>
   Folks still stop in at the corner drugstore _ Guerin's Pharmacy
_ for old-fashioned sundaes and milkshakes at the soda fountain.
</P>
<P>
   Just off the square is Bunny Business, an adorable pink cottage
filled with pretty things for little girls. The 200-year-old house
was renovated and expanded by owner Cathy Tuten.
</P>
<P>
   The 1913 Cauthen Hardware building is now People, Places and
Quilts _ 5,000 square feet of new and antique quilts, antiques,
folk art and thousands of bolts of fabric that create a
kaleidoscope of color.
</P>
<P>
   The original hardware furnishings, even the 1919 cash register,
are still in use.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us who work here love old things,'' says owner Diane
Wilson. ``It suits us to ring up purchases by hand and write up
tickets. No plastic here.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, a fat brown stuffed bear lounges lazily on a
bench outside Pear Tree, hinting of the wondrous toys and games
inside.
</P>
<P>
   And down Cedar Street, there's Cow Hydes Ltd., with its
black-and-white bovine-inspired awning and leather creations
inside.
</P>
<P>
   You get the idea: You stroll around town, chat with the friendly
shopkeepers, have a bite to eat, maybe stop in at one of downtown's
two day spas and then buy-buy. There's really not much else to do
in Summerville _ which is part of its charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lived here 16 years, and we love it,'' says Lydia
Williams, a former Atlantan who opened her consignment shop,
Scarlett's Closet, eight years ago. ``All my family is in Atlanta.
This is close enough to home, and we are 45 minutes to Wild Dunes,
where we have a beach house. We have the best of both worlds. This
is God's country.''
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Take I-20 east to I-26 in Columbia, S.C., then
southeast on I-26 to Exit 199 (U.S. 17A). Summerville is two miles
south of the interstate.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Most stores are open by 9 or 10 a.m. and stay open
until 5 or 6 p.m. Most are closed on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: On the street and in small lots.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 843-873-2931 or www.gsdcchamber.org; 843-851-7800
or www.summervilletourism.com (Summerville D.R.E.A.M.).
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to stay: The most upscale lodging is the elegant
Woodlands Resort and Inn, a Relais &AMP; Chateau property with a AAA
Five-Diamond rating for both the inn and the restaurant. The
restored and expanded 1906 mansion is located on 42 wooded acres
less than a mile from downtown. Rates $295-$350. 125 Parsons Road.
1-800-774-9999; www.woodlandsinn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Intown, the antiques-filled 1883 Linwood Bed &AMP; Breakfast, once a
plantation owner's home, has three suites and a swimming pool set
amid two acres of historic landscaped gardens. Rates $75-$150. 200
S. Palmetto St. 843-871-2620, www.bbonline.com/sc/linwood/
</P>
<P>
   Other options include the 1889 Victorian Flowertown Bed &AMP;
Breakfast ($85-$110; 710 S. Main St. 843-851-1058;
www.flowertownbandb
</P>
<P>
   .com) and the circa 1812 Price House Cottage Bed &AMP; Breakfast
($125; 843-871-1877, www.bbonline.com/sc
</P>
<P>
   /pricehouse/).
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  McNeill's: The Restaurant: Chef Herman McNeill puts his spin
on international dishes while incorporating Lowcountry favorites.
Lunch selections include shrimp and grits ($7.50), portobello
sandwich ($6.25) and artichoke hearts McNeill ($6.95). Lunch 11
a.m.-2:30 p.m. Tuesdays-Fridays; dinner 5:30-9 p.m.
Tuesdays-Saturdays. 105 S. Cedar St. 843-832-0912.
</P>
<P>
   At Continental Corner, the menu has decidedly Greek overtones.
We lunched on one of the day's specials _ chicken boureki, chicken
and Kassari cheese baked in a phyllo pasty ($7.95) _ and a menu
mainstay, Greek salad topped with tiny grilled shrimp ($7.95). 11
a.m.-8:30 p.m. Mondays-Thursdays (until 9 p.m. Fridays) and 11
a.m.-2 p.m. Sundays. 123 W. Richardson Ave. 843-871-1160.
</P>
<P>
   Also recommended: The Turtle Deli, 131 Central Ave.
(843-875-0380); Micah's Bakery and Cafe, 102A S. Cedar St.
(843-851-1185); Oscar's Place, 207 W. Fifth North St.
(843-871-3800); Harvest Grill, 101 S. Main St. (843-832-8131);
Charleston Crab House, 800 N. Main St. (843-873-5122); Eva's
Restaurant (home cooking), 129 S. Main St. (843-873-5081); Time
Well Spent (tearoom), 211 Stallsville Loop (843-875-2408);
Tradewinds, 114 Central Ave. (843-875-3357); and Simply Delicious,
219 S. Cedar St. (843-821-0101).
</P>
<P>
   Beyond shopping
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sculpture in the South: The annual fine sculpture exhibit and
sale is 10 a.m.-6 p.m. May 20-21 in Azalea Park. The works of a
dozen nationally known sculptors will be featured _ from hunt
scenes to miniatures, cowboys to Confederate generals. $5; ages 15
and under are free with adult. 843-821-7260.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tours: Sheila Myrick's Trails and Tales Tours offers jaunts
around Summerville, to the plantations along Ashley River Road and
to historic Charleston. 843-821-4022.
</P>
