<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Farewells, celebrities pack schedule for May sweeps
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hang a big red ``Exit'' sign over the May sweeps: It's all about
the goodbyes.
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Fox is leaving ``Spin City'' (May 24) to deal with
his Parkinson's disease. Julianna Margulies, whose character Carol
Hathaway tried to kill herself in the very first episode of ``ER,''
finally departs (May 18), alive, after five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   All those grown-up kids of ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' are outta
here in a two-hour finale May 17. Another Fox youth series, ``Party
of Five,'' has its last episode Wednesday. CBS' ``Cosby'' and ABC's
``Boy Meets World,'' neither of which made any impact, get
send-offs nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the networks will also try to distract you with
specials, which sometimes are big and sometimes just long. Mirrored
disco balls on ``The '70s'' will battle flying carpets on ``Arabian
Nights'' this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But if you had to predict one show that will crush them all, it
would be the all-celebrity editions of ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' next week.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quick rundown of some of what's ahead in May sweeps,
which start tonight:
</P>
<P>
   S E R I E S
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Friends'' (8 tonight on NBC) _ Bruce Willis starts a
three-week guest role as the disapproving dad of Ross' girlfriend;
that older man/younger ``Friends'' woman plot is dusted off when he
gets involved with Rachel.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''
</P>
<P>
   (8 p.m. Monday-Wednesday, 9 p.m. May 4 on ABC) _ The
much-heralded celebrity version, with Kathie Lee Gifford, Rosie
O'Donnell, David Duchovny, Drew Carey, Queen Latifah, Ray Romano
and others playing for charity. Alex Trebek had a conflicting
engagement.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``ER'' (10 tonight on NBC) _ Nurse Hathaway has been getting
ready to leave for months, just as that painfully sweet Croatian
Dr. Kovac has been working up the nerve to make his romantic move.
There's no indication that George Clooney will ride to Carol's
rescue, as has been widely rumored.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Popular'' (8 p.m. May 18 on the WB) _ The spoofy teen series
skewers the conventions of season-ending cliffhangers with two
weddings, a funeral and a natural disaster.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Frasier'' (9 p.m. May 18 on NBC) _ No credible leaks yet on
the one-hour finale, where Daphne is supposed to get married, but
may end up with Niles.
</P>
<P>
   M O V I E S
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Arabian Nights'' (9 p.m. Sunday and Monday on ABC) _
Scheherazade (Mili Avital) tells the stories of Aladdin, Ali Baba
and other legendary characters in a feast fit for a sultan.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The '70s'' (9 p.m. Sunday and Monday on NBC) _ Fictional
archetypes (Black Power guy, druggie girl) truck through 10 years
of travails. Great soundtrack: Marvin Gaye, Steely Dan, the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Gepetto'' (7 p.m. May 7 on ABC) _ Drew Carey and Julia
Louis-Dreyfus sing in a new musical of ``Pinocchio.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Jesus'' (9 p.m. May 14 and 17 on CBS)_ Jeremy Sisto has the
title role, with Debra Messing of ``Will &AMP; Grace'' as Mary
Magdalene and Gary Oldman as Pilate.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Linda McCartney Story'' (9 p.m. May 21 on CBS) _
Elizabeth Mitchell (``Gia'') stars as Paul's late wife.
</P>
<P>
   S P E C I A L S
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Academy of Country Music Awards'' (8 p.m. Wednesday on CBS)
_ Dolly Parton hosts, all the usual suspects sing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Judds Reunion: The Power to Change'' (8 p.m. May 17 on
CBS) _ Not just Wynonna and Naomi, but Ashley too.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Daytime Emmy Awards'' (9 p.m. May 19 on ABC) _ Susan Lucci
hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
