<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8020 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-SECRETARY27-COX     04-26 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-SECRETARY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Secretaries make their mark
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, every one of you callous, corporate-nose-to-the-grindstone
bosses who forgot that Wednesday was Secretaries' Day raise your
hand. Now, here's your chance to make it up to him/her. Send your
invaluable minion home with one of these rentals:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Nine To Five'': What's most intriguing about this broad 1980
farce blending office and sexual politics is the casting. Imagine
Jane Fonda, Lily Tomlin and Dolly Parton (in her feature debut) all
drowning in the same typing pool thanks to their contemptible boss
(a very funny Dabney Coleman). The first half is much better than
the second, but the stars' easy ensemble triple-playing gives it
its spark. Interesting side note: as part of the research, director
Colin Higgins asked secretaries how they'd dispose of their bosses
if given the chance. The most popular choices were guns, poison and
hanging.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Clockwatchers'': A kind of Gen X ``Nine to Five.'' In this
wicked little 1997 take on workplace hell, some temps bond over
happy hour wings and shared complaints about working in an office
rife with petty politics and nonstop Muzak. Much like the
Fonda/Tomlin/Parton picture, the plot is not as sharp as the
nuanced observations of your typical dysfunctional corporate
``family.'' And again, the casting is a trip: Parker Posey (then
reigning queen of the independent scene), Lisa Kudrow, trying to
parlay her ``Friends'' fame into a movie career and Toni Collette,
recently Oscar-nominated for ``The Sixth Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Take a Letter, Darling'': Rosalind Russell plays an
advertising executive who hires Fred MacMurray to be her secretary.
An enjoyably prescient and witty movie for its time (1942), it
shrewdly adds the inevitable romance. In her memoir, Russell
recalls that the role led to a slew of career-woman parts, so much
so, that she was asked to address a convention of real-life female
executives. She humorously pointed out that every picture usually
began with her barking orders at ten or twelve guys in a conference
room, but there was always one fellow with a hat pulled down over
his eyes who says ``verrry interesting'' before leaving the room.
The topper: by the end of the picture, she was always married to
him and gratefully retired to a house in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Swimming With Sharks'': In L.A., they don't always call them
secretaries. They're known by the more politically correct title,
``personal assistant.'' In this scathing 1994 low-budget blast at
Hollywood, Frank Whaley plays the ``personal assistant'' to Kevin
Spacey, a vice president in charge of production at a major movie
studio (Joel Silver, some have whispered, is the real-life model,
but for my money, Spacey's megalomaniacal boss-from-hell is the
rule out there, not the exception). The movie's frame _ an
exasperated Whaley has gone over the edge and taken Spacey hostage
in his own house _ is a little forced, but overall, the film
captures just how horrifying life among the latte-drinkers can be.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Working Girl'': Yep, it's the ultimate fantasy for everyone
who's ever fetched coffee for a self-centered boss or heard said
boss take credit for his or her idea. But boy, it works and works
and works. Made in 1988, Melanie Griffith gives her best
performance to date (she got an Oscar nomination) as the
teased-hair heroine who uses her smarts to reinvent herself as
executive material. Harrison Ford generously underplays as the
dream guy she wants. Best of all, however, is a ferociously funny
Sigourney Weaver (another Oscar nominee) who shows us that selfish
bosses come in all shapes, sizes and genders.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
