<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8023 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-SPOTLIGHT27-COX     04-26 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-SPOTLIGHT27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bare-knuckled look at bad boys a knockout
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of last year's most controversial studio releases, the Brad
Pitt-Edward Norton flick will have as many people loathing it as
liking it. Either reaction is justifiable.
</P>
<P>
   The film, about a pack of guys beating each other to bloody
pulps, is violent, nihilistic, intoxicated by its own bad-boy
humor. And, yeah, it falls apart in its last half-hour with a twist
ending that doesn't totally stack up. But it's still one of those
rare films that creates an electrifying alternate universe
onscreen. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO PICK:
</P>
<P>
   `Fight Club'
</P>
<P>
   Rated R / Our critic's grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Flawless'' (R) _ It might be a guilty pleasure _ if they'd
made it 30 years ago. You could slip it into the VCR and giggle at
its dated, consciousness-raising plot and its by-the-numbers tale
of a homophobic security guard (Robert De Niro) who learns to
respect the brassy/soulful drag queen (Philip Seymour Hoffman) next
door. Unfortunately, the flick from writer-director Joel Schumacher
is a new release full of weary cliches and flat comic bits. Grade:
D+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Dinner Game'' (PG-13) _ A feast of foolishness. A bunch
of snotty Paris yuppies holds a weekly dinner to see who can bring
the biggest idiot as his guest. Publisher Thierry Lhermitte thinks
he's got a sure thing when he meets Jacques Villeret who builds
scale-model monuments out of matchsticks. But fate intervenes when
Lhermitte throws out his back and is forced to spend the evening
with Villeret who, with all the best intentions, systematically
wrecks his life. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``On the Ropes'' (unrated) _ An admirable, Oscar-nominated
documentary about three young boxers fighting dead-end lives in New
York's Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood. Like ``Hoop Dreams,''
``Ropes'' records the hope and sometimes heartache athletic ability
offers; it's a powerful democratic equalizer. The movie also
reminds us that reality is often more dramatic than fiction. Grade:
B
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
