<HEADER>
A8027 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-HEATHER-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      04-26 1473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEATHER-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEATHERS
</HEADLINE>
  Many sides of Heather Graham 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mystery, thy name is Heather Graham.
</P>
<P>
   After some of the boldest, and some of the goofiest,
performances in recent cinema, the big-eyed blonde from Agoura
defies the one-note celebrity take without, apparently, even
trying. As soon as you try to fit her into a convenient conceptual
box, intriguing contradictions knock down perceived boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly, she's a good kisser,'' jokes Casey Affleck, who plays
a supporting role in ``Committed,'' the new romantic comedy that
marks Graham's emergence as a leading lady. ``Basically, she's a
lot of fun. She's kind of like a sister to everyone, always bouncy
on the set and easy to get along with.''
</P>
<P>
   But Luke Wilson, another ``Committed'' actor, was impressed by
different, more mature aspects of the actress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember being really affected by `Drugstore Cowboy,' and
even though she didn't say a lot in the movie, I was very
interested in her character,'' Wilson says, referring to Graham's
style-setting, troubled-child role as a pharmacy-robbing drug
addict. ``And I really dug 'Boogie Nights' ... But sometimes you
can work with somebody that you've liked from afar, then the other
shoe drops in one way or another and you think, 'Oh, that's too
bad.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But Heather is just a really hard worker, and you can feel it
on the set. Heather is not about her angle or your angle; she's
just about doing a good job. I got the feeling that she was really
going for it in a good way.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Graham a giggly California girl or a solid, adventurous
professional? For that matter, is she determined to remain the
artsy taboo-breaker of ``Drugstore,'' ``Boogie'' and ``Twin Peaks''
or is she morphing into the blithely naughty, mass-market comedian
seen in last year's ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' and
``Bowfinger,'' and in the upcoming Farrelly Brothers sex farce
``Say It Isn't So''?
</P>
<P>
   While we're on the subject, is Graham, at age 30, still
rebelling against her strict Catholic upbringing (her parents
famously forbade her to appear in the namesake black comedy
``Heathers'' after reading the expletive-rich script) or choosing
her roles, however outrageous they may be, by more mature criteria?
</P>
<P>
   It's probably not an either/or proposition in any of these
cases. Like Joline, the devoted-beyond-reason young wife she plays
in ``Committed,'' Heather Graham is a complicated individual.
</P>
<P>
   Saner, but complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I understood where this character was coming from,
I thought the script was funny and dramatic at the same time, and I
could see certain things about myself in her,'' says Graham,
looking incongruously funky/glamorous (silky black top, jeans of a
near-radiant blue) and on her way to Wal-Mart (carrying around a
fuzzy, lime green overcoat). ``I've never been in her exact
situation, but I just felt really passionate about the whole
project.''
</P>
<P>
   In the independently produced film, which was written and
directed by Lisa Krueger (``Manny &AMP; Lo''), Joline is a New York
nightclub owner who takes promises very, very seriously. When her
photographer husband Carl (Wilson) abruptly relocates to El Paso
to, y'know, work some things out, Joline tracks him down.
</P>
<P>
   But she doesn't act like your typical abandoned wife. Determined
to save her marriage, Joline watches Carl from afar, insinuates
herself into the lives of his associates (including his new
girlfriend) and, generally, gives the confused man his space.
</P>
<P>
   Until, that is, she can't take it any longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought she just embodied the idea of really believing in
something,'' Graham explains. ``So even if she is annoying, and at
a certain point should really get the idea of giving up, I think
the movie is really about figuring out who you are. She finds out
that, yes, she is a committed person and has to learn to accept her
disappointments and then move on. She can still be that same sort
of person and even go at it again more _ but, maybe, have more
wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrying a film for the first time was certainly a
wisdom-getting experience for Graham, even if she typically jokes
about the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to get nine hours of sleep a night,'' she says,
laughing. ``Since I was in practically every scene and we were
working six days a week, I got pretty tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters was the fact that Graham had just fallen in
love with Ed Burns, the writer-director (``The Brothers McMullen'')
and actor (``Saving Private Ryan'') when filming commenced. He
joined her in El Paso for most of ``Committed's'' shoot, which was
nice. Then again ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It was right at the beginning of our relationship, and I was
afraid to show him the script because I didn't know him that
well,'' she reveals. ``But it was very romantic, him being there
every day. Of course, the director was going, 'Great. We're doing
this movie about a girl whose husband leaves her and you guys are,
like, the couple hanging out together every second.'''
</P>
<P>
   No problem with commitment as far as Burns and Graham are
concerned. They've been together ever since, and she recently
played a role in his upcoming movie ``Sidewalks of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like, the night I met him, we talked a lot, and then I
went home and couldn't fall asleep,'' she admits. ``I was all
excited; we were committed! It's a good relationship; we're honest
and discuss a lot of things. And he's fun to work with; he would
listen to me when he was writing the script and incorporate some of
my ideas into it, which was really exciting. And he's always
encouraging me to write myself and develop projects, which is
really inspirational.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there are few subjects Graham is shy about discussing,
the couple's recent, widely reported interest in purchasing the
late John Kennedy Jr.'s New York loft is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I wouldn't really talk about it anyway, because
where we live is private,'' says Graham, who nonetheless indicated
that they won't be buying the place. ``It would be kind of creepy
for certain people out there to know where we're living _ and
besides, moving to this couple's apartment that died? That's not my
desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham is also reluctant to get very specific about her
five-year estrangement from her retired FBI agent father, her
mother and her sister Aimee, who is also an actress. Her feelings
about her family, though, have been extensively examined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hate to think that I was leading my life to rebel
against them,'' she allows. ``That's what years of therapy have,
hopefully, untaught me to do. I think I have sort of reached the
point of just really trying to make myself happy. Because I feel a
lot happier, I know that I am doing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just great to enjoy who you are and not really worry
about what other people are thinking, or how it affects them.
Sometimes, you really have to make sacrifices in order to be the
person that you are and to enjoy your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Wisconsin and raised in several parts of the country
before her family moved to Agoura Hills, Calif., when she was 9,
Graham describes herself as an introverted child whose unfocused
creative nature made her feel out of place in the conservative
suburb.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham discovered her own Yellow Brick Road _ both out of
her adolescent shell and in the direction of her budding muse _
when she played Dorothy in a school production of ``The Wizard of
Oz.'' She followed it to Hollywood, and while still in school she
appeared in a number of commercials, on the sitcom ``Growing
Pains'' and in several TV movies. Her first feature film was the
1988 teen comedy ``License to Drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Graham has exhibited an unmistakable taste for edgy
movies and characters caught up in dire lifestyles _ junkies,
rollerskating porn stars, promiscuous actresses. In ``From Hell,''
the film she'll be making this summer, she'll be an English
prostitute stalked by Jack the Ripper.
</P>
<P>
   But much like fellow San Fernando Valley film talents Kevin
Spacey and ``Boogie Nights'' director Paul Thomas Anderson, Graham
has a way of locating the attractive humanity _ and in her case,
often, the fun _ beneath the surface of alarming, even appalling
behavior. She attributes a big part of that signature ability to
her passionately complicated relationship with the place where she
grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of exciting, creative people are coming out of the Valley
now,'' she notes. ``And why couldn't they? Whatever else you want
to say about it, the Valley is great. It's like, there's as much
crazy, weird culture going on here as there is in New York. And I'm
not saying this just because I'm from there; it's got its own
amazing thing going on.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
