<HEADLINE>
LIFE IN A ONE-ROOM ORPHANAGE, THE STORY OF CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NADTERECHNOYE, Russia _ When Russian bombs rained down on Grozny
last fall, the city's only orphanage moved to this small town in
northern Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to have been a temporary stay. But seven months
later the orphanage is still here in a cramped former schoolhouse.
Nobody can say when it might move back.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the children, Tatyana Tkachenko, a sprightly
11-year-old, would dearly like to return. Life in Grozny was no
picnic, but at least the children had more than one room to share.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the orphanage is the story of what is happening in
Chechnya. Or more aptly, what is not happening. As the war has
dragged on, temporary dislocations seem to have become
semipermanent.
</P>
<P>
   It is as if Chechnya has stopped in time.
</P>
<P>
   It has no elected leaders because the situation is too unstable
to arrange local elections. Maj. Gen. Vladimir Kovrov, the Russian
military commandant who administers the Nadterechny region, said
Tuesday that the voting for a new leader of the republic and heads
of local districts would probably not take place for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has Chechnya made much headway in dealing with the crush of
refugees. The refugee camps in this district are still overflowing.
The refugees, who live four families to a tent, say their homes
either have been destroyed or are still in a battle zone.
</P>
<P>
   For many, life is a kind of Catch-22. If they leave the refugee
camps for a few days to check the conditions of their homes, they
may miss their food rations. Petimat Gelikahnova, a 48-year-old
refugee who was waiting for a shipment of food aid in nearby
Znamenskoye, is one of thousands who are trapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to Grozny and saw that everything was destroyed,'' she
said. ``So we came back.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the orphanage, whose 29 children had thought they
would have to make do with the spartan home here for just a few
months. Now they are settling in for a long stay.
</P>
<P>
   The orphanage _ officially called the Home for Orphans and
Children Left Without Parental Support, No. 1 _ was opened as the
1994-1996 war in Chechnya was ending. Not all of the children are
without parents. Some were left at the home by desperate mothers or
fathers who were too poor to care for them.
</P>
<P>
   Chechnya enjoyed a de facto independence then, but it was also a
zone of anarchy and poverty. The orphanage was one of just eight,
and the only one that did not close for lack of money. Even so, it
did not have much government support. It received 5,000 rubles from
the Chechen authorities over four years (less than $1,000 at the
old 1996 exchange rates).
</P>
<P>
   The current war has made a difficult situation immeasurably
worse. The orphanage was near a rail line in a Grozny district
pounded by bombing raids.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the staff decided it was time to flee. So the
orphanage was relocated in a small school building here, the one
Arbi Mamakayev, a famous Chechen poet, once attended.
</P>
<P>
   The local authorities pay the staff's salaries, and the
Volgograd militia, which polices this town, donates potatoes and
onions. But beyond that the orphanage has little.
</P>
<P>
   Meat, fruit and milk are in short supply. The furniture is spare
and the children need shoes and summer clothes. The building is
small. In the room where virtually all of the children sleep _ some
three to a bed _ a green curtain separates the girls from the boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had more space we could accept more children,'' said the
bookkeeper of the orphanage, who did not give her name.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the children have been shaken by the war.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Magomed, a 9-year-old who spent several months at the orphanage
while his mother was being treated for tuberculosis, had lived with
her in a basement for months to escape the fighting. During his
stay apart from her he was withdrawn and barely spoke.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   But by and large, the children appear to be well treated, well
adjusted and eager to go back to Grozny. Tanya was left at the
orphanage by her parents, who were out of work and too poor to look
after her. She has two dresses. While she is not one to complain,
she agreed it would be nice to have one more.
</P>
<P>
   Because her parents are still in Grozny, she wants to return.
But that will not be easy. The orphanage compound there was damaged
and awaits repair. The city still lacks electricity, and the
orphanage has no generator. The senior Russian representative in
Chechnya, Nikolai Koshman, has ruled the ravaged city not yet
suitable for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we left they were bombing day and night,'' Tanya said.
``And it's OK here. But I'd like to go back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
