<HEADER>
A8030 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SHAFT-FILM-2TAKES-$AD     04-26 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAFT-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BLACK GUMSHOE WHO BUILT A GENRE IS BACK ON THE JOB  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At this year's Academy Awards, Isaac Hayes performed the theme
from ``Shaft'' engulfed in a special effect gone horribly wrong: a
billowing wave of stage smoke that looked ready to waft him away.
</P>
<P>
   The 1971 movie, a massive hit that saved its troubled
distributor, MGM, from bankruptcy and gave a whole new meaning to
the phrase film noir, exists under a similar cumulonimbus.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Parks's groundbreaking detective film never got the
respect it deserves; I recently overheard a major filmmaker giving
the picture short shrift and claiming he could have done a much
better job with the material, given Hayes' score _ which some
consider the true star of the motion picture. In fact, the score
builds a frame around the likable cool of Parks's picture; it
doesn't usurp it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a new version of ``Shaft'' _ starring Samuel L.
Jackson, directed by John Singleton and written by Richard Price _
due for release this summer, the original film will be scrutinized
once again. Will it get any more respect this time around? (At
least last time, the picture's flashy clothes were accorded a
degree of admiration.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaft'' affirmed the growing success of the blaxploitation
genre, which had begun in 1970 with the release of ``Cotton Comes
to Harlem,'' a swift, comic retelling of Chester Himes' novel that
cagily tempered the author's Old Testament brutality. The
surprising box-office performance of ``Shaft,'' adapted by Ernest
Tidyman from his novel, sparked studio interest in black action
films and gave Parks _ a Renaissance man with fiction, music and,
of course, photography among his accomplishments _ a new career.
</P>
<P>
   His photography has a marvelous emphatic vitality, and that
vitality informs his filmmaking in ``Shaft,'' which was as much a
tribute to the detective movies of the 1930s and '40s as it was a
fountainhead for those of the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   A true pioneer, Parks had, in 1969, directed an adaptation of
his Bildungsroman, ``The Learning Tree'' _ the first
studio-financed film directed by an African-American. In ``Shaft,''
just two years after his directorial debut, he shows a feel for
creating indelible moments, like the opening sequence: the star,
Richard Roundtree, hits the streets and the urgent sizzle of the
high-hat from the theme alerts the movie world to a different kind
of party. (John Badham's introduction to ``Saturday Night Fever,''
where John Travolta's sexual bounce is a manifestation of New York
ego, seems directly influenced by the start of ``Shaft.'')
</P>
<P>
   Shaft's agile swing into a hotel window, snaking through so he
doesn't bang his head on the sill while clad in his black leather
street armor and brandishing a shotgun, is such a classic piece of
action that it's used as the film's poster.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Shaft'' doesn't hold up these days as an action film,
its detractors are probably too young to be aware of the elation
that charged movie houses of the '70s as cheering black audiences
saw a dark-skinned hero _ iconic and masculine in his
up-to-the-minute proto-fade haircut and collection of leathers _ in
total control of his destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Roundtree's on-screen relish, which was itself a kind of
dynamism, connected to an audience hunger. And he held the screen
like an aristocrat. New to the movies, he had appeared onstage; but
his greatest success had been as an Afro Sheen model: he could be
seen grinning in hair cream ads in the backs of magazines whose
covers proclaimed his arrival as a movie star.
</P>
<P>
   In one stroke, he was lionized and doomed; he scored so soundly
as Shaft that he was finished. Between the lack of roles for black
actors outside the genre, and the impact he made as Shaft,
Roundtree was boxed in. The constraints of the era are enough to
allow forgiveness for his accepting the role in the short-lived
``Shaft'' television series of the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Roundtree's sunny self-possession helped him temporarily
displace Sidney Poitier, whose rigidity made him unappealing to
young black audiences, as the reigning black actor. What they
couldn't see at the time was that the upright precision that made
Poitier seem so humorless was a boiling anger that he held in
check, the elegant and inexplicable righteousness that had made him
a star and that Denzel Washington seized upon years later.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Roundtree has a glint of devilishness, visible in
the scene where Shaft pretends to be a gay bartender. His evolution
as an actor went largely, and unaccountably, unnoticed. He simply
got better, displaying aplomb even in the minor ``George of the
Jungle.'' And those who had hoped to see him become the black Sean
Connery _ he has the same outsize wellspring of charm and virility,
but with a leavening sense of self-deprecation _ were disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   There was no room for his move upward and onward. Roundtree's
curse was that he appeared on the scene when there was room for
representations of only one type of black man: the avatar of
inner-city aplomb.
</P>
<P>
   The title character's name itself suggested the heavy,
elbow-to-the-rib swing of the theme song. If the makers of the new
``Shaft'' are smart, they will include the Hayes theme, if only to
give it the ground-shaking Dolby send-off the audio technology of
the time couldn't provide.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this piece of heavy jam kept audiences in their seats
waiting to see, or hear, whether anything nearly as good would
follow. And it did: plenty of muscular orchestral funk, a seeming
contradiction that Isaac Hayes had mastered long before he was
courted to score ``Shaft.'' With its strains of urban melancholy
and horns used for soft punctuation, Hayes's work was obviously
influenced by Ennio Morricone and Burt Bacharach. The percussion
and flutes were pushed to the front of the sound mix to add
poignant contrast to the bombast of the strings, and in Hayes's
case, of the throbbing, danceable bass lines and warm, moody
Hammond B3 organ interludes.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes's music was made for the movies, and his score for
``Shaft'' helped establish a whole new brand of soundtrack. After
its success, which included a best-song Oscar for Hayes, almost
every major R-and-B performer of the period was snagged to compose
music for blaxploitation movies. But only a handful of scores _
including Curtis Mayfield's ``Superfly'' and Marvin Gaye's
``Trouble Man'' _ emerged from the pack. (Willie Hutch's score for
``The Mack'' and Bobby Womack's theme song for ``Across 110th
Street'' are also notable. The off-white soul man Quentin Tarantino
used ``110th Street'' over the opening credits of ``Jackie
Brown.'')
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The success of blaxploitation movies, and their guilty-pleasure
importance to white audiences, is easy enough to explain. During
the Vietnam era, when Richard Nixon's 5 o'clock shadow blotted out
the sun, misery became an emblem of cool. For the most part, white
movie protagonists were hobbled by their shame. The heroes of
blaxploitation, however, were active, proudly potent heroes: John
Shaft and his brethren were able to effect change, to do good.
</P>
<P>
   They also had a capacity for pleasure, because they accomplished
what they set out to do _ which was, more often than not, to stick
it to the Man with grinding regularity. The fact that whites _
Honky, Mr. Charlie, depicted in these films as the whitey who often
snarled a racial slur at the heroes before dying a spectacular
death that elicited cheers _ were also responsible for producing
these movies was a paradox not lost on the crowds in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   The fairy-tale carnality and wish-fulfillment plots of these
films embodied an optimism that most '70s movies lacked, a
folkloric bravado that the heroes _ if that's the word _ of
Scorsese and Altman and Coppola were denied. Yet blaxploitation
movies came armed with a political imperative.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, when the revolution would not be televised,
militants and community activists were invariably among the good
guys in black action-movie story lines. After all, ``Shaft'' was
released in 1971, only a few years after the premiere of the
light-stepping espionage program ``I Spy,'' in which Bill Cosby was
the first black man to carry a gun on series television.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Shaft,'' the black gangster Bumpy Jonas hires the black
detective played by Roundtree to retrieve his kidnapped daughter
from the Mob. When Jonas tries to discredit the Black Panther-like
revolutionaries, Shaft rebukes the criminal. Shaft sides with the
militants, who assist him in the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   It's the one thing that the newer, affectionate but often clumsy
attempts to replicate the genre miss out on. Blaxploitation movies
were built upon a shared recognition of the need to shake up the
status quo _ the collateral rage of the civil rights movement was
brought to the big screen. These movies didn't limit themselves to
making style statements, or tracking ingenious petty crimes and big
ripoffs. At the climax of ``The Mack,'' one of the best-known and
most revered blaxploitation pictures, the protagonist is
enlightened about his misadventures in the pimp trade by his
militant brother.
</P>
<P>
   There's no point in inflating, or overly romanticizing,
``Shaft.'' Like others in its genre, it was a movie in which the
women weren't well realized, let alone well treated. In a
post-coital scene, after Shaft brusquely tries to dismiss his
one-night stand, the woman criticizes him for his callousness.
</P>
<P>
   This is a set-up for a joke, but the worldliness of the gesture
transcends the genre, as do a number of touches in ``Shaft.'' When
its dry-ice hero can't get a cab, it drew peals of knowing laughter
from black audiences _ and helped seal this movie with an
African-American director's perspective.
</P>
<P>
   There's more to watch, like Moses Gunn's crocodile tears as his
Bumpy Jonas talks about his missing little girl, and the assurance
with which Parks moves the picture around the city; it's a time
capsule of a Manhattan that used to be a much wilder theme park
than it is now. At its best, ``Shaft'' is robust and earthy _ the
root of a movement that was just starting to bloom.
</P>
<P>
   But this new, raw form of expression had critics, who feared
audiences wouldn't regard the movies as simple entertainments and
would be damaged by their violence. And what finally cut off its
development was a problem no one had anticipated. After the core
audience tired of seeing the same movie being remade over and over
_ even Roundtree couldn't muster much pride for ``Shaft in
Africa,'' the brotherman-in-the-motherland third go-round _ studios
assumed they'd exhausted the wallets of black audiences and
abruptly stopped making movies with blacks casts. As a result, a
new form was left to die.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
