<SLUG> BC-KRUGMAN-PRINCETON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIST KRUGMAN LEAVING MIT FOR PRINCETON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Paul Krugman, a respected international economist and
star in the Massachusetts Institute of Technology's economics
department, will be leaving Cambridge for Princeton University.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, Krugman plans to depart MIT for a joint appointment
to Princeton's economics department and the Woodrow Wilson School
of Public and International Affairs. The news, which first appeared
in MIT's student newspaper, The Tech, was confirmed Wednesday by
faculty at both universities.
</P>
<P>
   The move is being made as much for personal as professional
reasons, according to people familiar with the decision. The pull
of Princeton, N.J., was great for Krugman because his parents live
nearby and because his wife, Robin Wells, an economist, was offered
an employment contract to teach at Princeton, colleagues said.
Wells, unlike her husband, did not have a tenured post at MIT; it
could not be determined Wednesday whether her Princeton contract
included tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Landing a matched set of university postings _ particularly
difficult-to-obtain postings at elite institutions _ is a major
problem for the modern academic couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get an ideal arrangement for two people is not easy, and
this (Princeton appointment) seems to be it. I believe that to be''
the reason for Krugman's departure, said MIT economics professor
and Nobel laureate Paul Samuelson.
</P>
<P>
   Krugman, who has gained a popular audience this year through a
regular column in The New York Times, was on a sabbatical at
Princeton for part of the current academic year. Wednesday, he
could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   As a professional move for Krugman, Princeton's international
school has a sterling reputation. But its economics department is a
notch below MIT's, which is widely recognized to rank among the top
two or three in the country. However, Princeton is building its
department _ and the addition of Krugman will certainly add to its
luster.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is an economist extraordinaire,'' said Michael Rothschild,
dean of Princeton's Wilson School. ``He has made more original
contributions to basic economics than almost anyone in the
profession. At the same time, he writes sharply, freshly,
controversially, presciently about economic policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Krugman, 47, firmly established his star reputation within the
profession in 1991, when he received the John Bates Clark Medal
awarded to promising young economists. Although he first
specialized in international trade, his interests have become more
eclectic in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Krugman has written 16 books, including ``The Age of Diminished
Expectations'' and ``The Accidental Theorist and Other Dispatches
from the Dismal Science.'' A Democrat, he was a member of the
Council of Economic Advisers for two years during the Reagan
administration.
</P>
<P>
   While his departure is clearly a loss for MIT, the Cambridge
university has had difficulty hanging on its wunderkind and former
PhD student. MIT lost Krugman _ the first time _ when he briefly
departed for Stanford University in California, returning to his
alma mater in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sad to lose him to Stanford and glad to get him
back,'' Samuelson said. ``I don't think this (Princeton move) was
an easy decision for him.''
</P>
<P>
   While well known by economics insiders, Krugman's gained
celebrity status when he began writing a twice-weekly column for
The New York Times on Jan. 2, competing for the top spot on the
op-ed page with Times political columnist Maureen Dowd. (The Boston
Globe is owned by the New York Times Co.)
</P>
<P>
   While Krugman had earlier written for publications as varied as
Foreign Affairs, Fortune, and Salon, the Times column allowed
Krugman _ whom one newspaper dubbed the ``bad boy of economics'' _
to unleash his sharp pen on a range of economic and business
topics, from President Clinton's budget surplus to Bill Gates'
Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The column has made his name so familiar that he may be in
danger of becoming a ``pop internationalist,'' a label he once
affixed to economist and MIT colleague Lester Thurow, journalists
James Fallows and Robert Kuttner, and former Labor Secretary Robert
Reich.
</P>
<P>
   A Princeton spokeswoman said the university's trustees had not
yet acted on the appointments and would not comment further.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
