<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8038 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-DARKSIDE-SUMMER-FILMS     04-26 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DARKSIDE-SUMMER-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAPPED IN THE CITY: THE DARK SIDE OF SUMMER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   Kristin Hohenadel's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was
about European films being made in English.  
 By KRISTIN HOHENADEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In the Prague summer of 1994, during a heat wave
unrivaled in 200 years, nude sunbathers posed in their front yards
and old ladies in transparent nighties cruised the streets. I was
stuck in a city that had not yet embraced deodorant or
air-conditioning, and whose hardware stores had run out of fans.
</P>
<P>
   One Saturday afternoon in the midst of this evil swelter, I got
stuck in the elevator. Visible through the open cage, I hoped a
neighbor would soon wander out in his underwear to check the mail
or take the dog for a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Time passed. The hallway was lonely as a church.
</P>
<P>
   When the super's wife _ dressed in a bra and a skirt _ opened
her door to bid some guests a boozy farewell, I shook lightly on
the bars.
</P>
<P>
   Please help me, I said in well-rehearsed Czech. Help me, please.
She widened her eyes, snorted deeply and slammed the door behind
her.
</P>
<P>
   It was at this moment that I understood the meaning of being
stranded _ punished by circumstance, bereft of language, mired in
bad weather, too broke to get out of town. Suddenly I was starring
in the remake of the 1964 ``Lady in a Cage,'' in which Olivia de
Havilland, trapped inside a home elevator on a hot summer day,
rings the emergency button for help from the alley only to be
tormented and robbed by strangers.
</P>
<P>
   So often in the movies, summer is a time of flight and escape,
romance and bliss; too brief in real time but long in the memory,
like all the things we love. But films such as ``Lady in a Cage''
reveal the dark side of summer, that season in which fights break
out on the subway and lovers sleep far apart in the bed and the
heat tempts normally passive mortals to madness.
</P>
<P>
   An endless summer of another sort, in which insomniacs drag
their mattresses to their rooftops and live with the blinds open
and dream murderous dreams. If we know the ingredients of a happy
summer _ free time, beautiful weather, the great outdoors _ then we
know that the unhappy summer is its antithesis. And if all happy
summers seem to resemble one another, each unhappy summer is
unhappy in its own cruel way.
</P>
<P>
   It takes just a few quick establishing shots _ a dog picking
through trash in a Brooklyn gutter, people slumped on their stoops,
watering their sidewalks and cluttering the city pools _ to set the
stifling mood for ``Dog Day Afternoon.'' It's a brutal August day
in 1972 when Al Pacino, as a reluctant bank robber, finally decides
to change his destiny with a heist. You can't help feeling sorry
for him when the cops cut the air-conditioning; after all, he's
kept on his jacket and tie for a noble portion of the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   And pity his hostages, prisoners not only of a random crime but
of a relentless heat, who weakly fan themselves and faint
occasionally and mop their perspiring brows, with only a couple
cans of Tab to quench their thirst.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been crazy all summer,'' Pacino's lover, Leon, tells the
police, who have brought him from the psychiatric ward. ``He's been
trying to kill me since June.''
</P>
<P>
   Spike Lee has chronicled the volatile forces that can explode
the calm of a New York summer. The heat is a backdrop, catalyst and
star in his 1999 film ``Summer of Sam,'' based on the Son of Sam
slayings in 1977. The sense of menace is thick as a swamp as crime
rises with the temperature. The killer is taunted by a neighbor's
barking dog, the city is plagued with blackouts and looters, and
the hotter it gets, the more people are afraid to leave their
houses or sit in their parked cars or sleep with their windows
open.
</P>
<P>
   In the first moments of Lee's ``Do the Right Thing,'' shot in a
steamy palette of oranges and reds, Samuel L. Jackson, playing the
local D.J., announces the weather with an apocalyptic air. Rosie
Perez soaks her face in ice water, and the street kids bust up a
fire hydrant and chase the ice cream man. The newspaper headlines
cornily shout: ``BAKED APPLE''; ``HELTER SWELTER''; ``QUE CALOR!''
</P>
<P>
   People curse the heat the way you might stick pins in a voodoo
doll, to try to defuse the source of its vexing power. ``I'm gonna
kill somebody today,'' Danny Aiello says out loud, in a stark
prelude to the inevitable violence. But we have always seen it
coming; every excruciating airless moment has led us to it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not every miserable summer ends in bloodshed, even in
New York City. Sometimes the pent-up urban summer is a study in
restlessness, of that inescapable feeling of being where one should
not be, powerless to get out. The cast on Jimmy Stewart's broken
leg in Hitchcock's ``Rear Window'' leaves the poor grounded
photojournalist with nothing to do with his appetite for adventure
but look out the window and spy on the neighborhood theater. And,
of course, give him time to finally realize his true love for Grace
Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   The Paris summer in Eric Rohmer's ``The Green Ray'' is a
barometer of dashed expectations for the poor Delphine, who has
lost her boyfriend and has no vacation plans for the month in which
all good Parisians depart for the grandes vacances. This is not the
fiery landscape of a Spike Lee film: Parisians recline listlessly
on park benches and read in the sunshine and sunbathe by the Seine.
Still, Delphine flees the tranquil but stagnant city three times
before she finds what she is looking for.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For it seems that in the hopeless discomfort of summer in a
city, the only relief might be romance. The sweetest moments in
``Raging Bull,'' which portrays the years-long decline of Jake
LaMotta, are in its beginning, when he finds the cool blonde at the
city pool in the midst of a scorching summer. In ``West Side
Story,'' the forbidden, quick-burning love of Maria and Tony is the
respite from the turf wars of the Jets and the Sharks, acted out in
the stifling summer playground of the park, the river, Sweeney's
lot.
</P>
<P>
   The terrible ``Taking the Heat'' begins at Christmas but soon
leaps to the hottest day of the year: ``It's 100 degrees ... the
city's gonna be a zoo today, power outages, maybe riots ... jungle
hot and humid,'' cries the ubiquitous radio announcer. What follows
is gridlock, death and a predictable romance to send us off with a
happy end.
</P>
<P>
   But if love is the answer, the heat can also drive otherwise
happily married couples to distraction when one leaves the other
behind to roast in the kitchen. In ``A Walk on the Moon,'' Diane
Lane makes a summer bachelor of her devoted husband (Liev
Schreiber), who stays behind in the city eating cereal out of a
frying pan and repairing televisions. But she's the one who gives
in to the temptation for a summer fling.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Seven Year Itch,'' the wife goes away for the summer
and assumes she'll be having all the fun, while the poor husband
stays behind _ only to meet Marilyn Monroe on his first night
alone. It's her first New York summer, and she learns to survive it
by putting her ``undies in the ice box,'' finding a neighbor with
air-conditioning and standing over the subway vent while her white
dress is famously blown above her ears.
</P>
<P>
   The husband does his best to remember his vows, and to stay away
from cigarettes and booze, all of which lasts a few hours. In the
1965 ``Paris in the Month of August,'' Charles Aznavour starts out
a happily married summer bachelor and ends up having an affair with
a tourist when the wife and kids are away.
</P>
<P>
   My elevator incident ended happily. Still, I swore then and
there that I'd never spend another summer in the city. But the next
summer I was living in Paris, and my English boss made us mind the
office while she went to St.-Tropez. Those of us left behind shared
one fan and took turns dumping bottles of Evian over one another.
</P>
<P>
   When we were free to roam with the other foreigners around the
airless ghost town of August in Paris, we drank rose as if it were
water till all hours on the Place de la Contrescarpe, had
late-night picnics on the quais of the Seine, found the cinemas
with air-conditioning. Yes, there were worse fates than being
shipwrecked in Paris, and like any group of castaways, we found
comfort in one another's company. We even got used to the sweat; it
was the being left behind that hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The dull pang of knowing the rest of the world was in Provence
or Biarritz. Like the patissier across the way, the next summer I
packed my bags and closed the blinds. I left my Paris apartment for
the month of August and returned Sept. 1 with the first cool
breeze.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
