<SLUG> BC-FAT-FINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIET PRODUCT MAKER TO PAY $10 MILLION IN REFUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``You can eat what you want and never, ever, ever
have to diet again.''
</P>
<P>
   Really? No, not really, the Federal Trade Commission said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said the company making that boast and others aimed
at people who dream of being slimmer had agreed to cease and desist
and to pay $10 million to the people who bought its products, or to
the U.S. Treasury if refunds to buyers are not practical.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Enforma Natural Products of Encino, Calif., made
those assertions on the Internet and in televised commercials. On
Wednesday the company's chief executive, Andrew Grey, said Enforma
was admitting no wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stand by our excellent products and are settling this case
to avoid prolonged, costly legal battles,'' Grey said. He said the
federal agency's demand that Enforma refund money to customers was
in line with the company's policy of giving refunds to people who
are not satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisements in question featured an obviously fit man
with Popeye-like forearms: Steve Garvey, the former major-league
baseball player. Garvey told viewers that Enforma's Exercise in a
Bottle contained a natural enzyme that worked by ``forcing every
cell in your body to work harder whether you're exercising or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Enforma product, Fat Trapper, ``literally traps fat
before it gets into your system,'' Garvey assured viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The two products come in capsule form and together cost about
$35 a month. While admitting no wrong, Enforma agreed not to make
misleading claims in the future and to back up assertions with
evidence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
