A8051 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      04-26 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW&AMP;NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: RETRANSMITTING FOR THOSE WHO MAY MISSED THIS.
 &UR; STORY MOVING IN THE ``E'' AND ``L'' CATEGORIES.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule book reviews:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ``THE WORLD'S SHORTEST STORIES OF LOVE AND DEATH'' &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Steve Moss and John M. Daniel (Running, $7.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We flatter ourselves to think we know something about writing
tight, but we are pikers compared with these people. Granted, there
was self-interest involved. They were embroiled in a contest
sponsored by the San Luis Obispo newspaper ``New Times,'' which
invited readers to submit stories using plot, setting and characte
in fewer than 55 words. First prize included a certificate and a
T-shirt. If ``New Times'' hasn't upped the ante since then, it
doesn't deserve readers like these. Most of the stories are long
(relatively speaking) on dialogue, humor and creative implication,
and short on everything else. It sounds easy, but try it. Here is
``The Britches of Madison County,'' in which author Bill Crown
one-ups Robert James Waller in 37 words: ``Francesca came out on
the porch and welcomed them home, her husband, their son, and
daughter. But her skirt was hung up in the waist of her drawers.
The old man got hip and he shot her.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``ORCHID FEVER'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Eric Hansen (Pantheon, $23) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Please do not shy away from this book because its subject is
orchids and you don't know anything about them. Hansen didn't know
anything about them either, until he was hired to guide two orchid
fanatics into the wilds of Borneo in search of the holy grail of
orchids, the Latin name of which we refuse to repea here. Hansen
hired some Borneo natives to provide sherpalike assistance on this
journey, and these simple, jungle-savvy men provide lots of laughs
as they react to the orchid zealots' reasons for sloshing up a
muddy Borneo river with a stockpile of equipment that includes a
camouflaged cardboard toilet. This trip was the author's
introduction to the world of orchids and orchid lovers, which was
far more complex, seductive, competitive and pricey than he ever
imagined. Read all about it in this captivating and often funny
book. (Hansen appeared briefly in a recent ``60 Minutes'' story
about the orchid world. As is almost always the case when media
overlap, the book is better.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``SHRINK YOUR HANDICAP'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Phil Lee and Jeff Warne (Hyperion, $23.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can read this as a means to improve your golf game, or you
can read it for laughs. New &AMP; Notable has no golf game to speak of,
but in search of good suggestions for Father's Day, we read gamely
on, stifling our guffaws. Lee, a psychiatrist, and Warne, a golf
instructor, join forces to explain the mystery of why you play
better when no one is watching. The villain is the dreaded panic
attack syndrome. As Lee says, There are specific swing weaknesses
that are magnets for the chemicals of anxiety. Even the tiniest
amount of anxiety produces chemicals that will feast on certain
specific weaknesses in the swing. Their solutions include a
pre-shot routine that involves entering a light trance, developing
``Insight-Oriented Defenses'' to fight the nasty chemicals and
``uninstalling'' the ``Blame Game,'' or the urge to be angry over
bad shots. They take this very, very seriously, but we could not.
Disguised as psychobabble, even common sense sounds like hooey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``LEFT FOR DEAD'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Beck Weathers (Villard, $24.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The survival of Dallas pathologist Beck Weathers was just about
the only good news to come out of the storm on Mount Everest that
killed nine people in 1996. Left for dead by other climbers, he
suddenly, miraculously stood up and walked through the squall to
the nearest camp. Fellow climber Jon Krakauer (``Into Thin Air'')
comes off well in this version of the day's events. Anatoli
Boukreev, the guide who climbed without oxygen and so was unable to
help his clients descend before the storm hit, does not. Neither
does George W. Bush, who would not help Weathers' family get him
home from Nepal. Less interesting sections about Weathers' youth
and relationship with his wife and family are followed by sobering
descriptions of his recuperation (he lost both hands and his nose
to frostbite). Best of all, he tells of the daring Nepalese pilot
who flew alone, perilously higher than his helicopter was meant to
go, and brought Weathers off of Mount Everest alive.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8052 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-BOYSCOUTS-2TAK     04-26 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-BOYSCOUTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES CONSIDER WHETHER HOMOSEXUALS CAN JOIN THE BOY SCOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The question before the Supreme Court on Wednesday
was whether the Boy Scouts have a constitutional right to exclude
gay members, but the justices did not seem particularly interested
in either Boy Scout policy or the future of gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, what clearly concerned the court were the implications
of ruling for one side or the other. If the Boy Scouts cannot
exclude homosexuals, can they still exclude girls, the justices
wanted to know. Would a Jewish social group be forced to accept
non-Jewish members, or a gay organization to include heterosexuals?
</P>
<P>
   More generally, the justices asked, if an organization deems a
particular kind of exclusivity to be central to its identity, must
courts take that assertion at face value? If not, by what standard
are they to judge it? If so, might that not be the equivalent of
giving a free pass from the anti-discrimination commands of civil
rights law?
</P>
<P>
   The questions came thick and fast for the lawyers representing
the Boy Scouts of America and James Dale, who was an Eagle Scout
assistant scoutmaster when his troop in Monmouth County, N.J.,
expelled him 10 years ago, after learning from a newspaper article
that he is gay.
</P>
<P>
   The Boy Scouts ``specifically forbid membership to
homosexuals,'' he was told. Dale, who as the article reported was
co-president of a student gay rights organization at Rutgers
University, sued under New Jersey's anti-discrimination law, which
includes protection for sexual orientation. Last year the New
Jersey Supreme Court ruled that the Boy Scouts are a ``public
accommodation,'' to which the state law applies, and rejected the
argument that the First Amendment guarantee of freedom of
association shielded the Scouts' policy.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' questions on Wednesday reflected their effort to
decide where to slot this case into an array of First Amendment
precedents that offer ammunition to both sides. For example,
several justices asked in different ways whether Dale's termination
reflected the simple fact of his sexual orientation, as opposed to
scouting officials' conclusions that he was engaged in ``public
advocacy,'' as Justice Anthony M. Kennedy put it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the message that would go to youth in the
program,'' replied George A. Davidson, the Boy Scouts' lawyer.
``Being openly homosexual communicates the concept that this is
OK,'' he said, adding that ``coming out'' as a gay person, ``in the
culture in which these statements are made, is a statement fraught
with moral meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of whether being gay inherently conveys a message is
important, given one of the court's precedents, a 1995 decision
that the organizers of Boston's St. Patrick's Day parade had a
First Amendment right to exclude a group of gay marchers. The court
ruled in that case, which the Boy Scouts have cited prominently,
that the organizers did not have to turn their parade over to an
unwanted message, in that instance to an expression of gay pride.
</P>
<P>
   But Dale's lawyer, Evan Wolfson of the Lambda Legal Defense and
Education Fund, maintained that what was at issue in Dale's case
was ``identity-based discrimination, the equation of a human being
with an assumed message,'' without reference to anything Dale had
said or done. ``A human being is not speech, other than `I am who I
am,''' Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   His assertion that there is no message inherent in Dale's sexual
orientation was an effort to invoke, rather than the case of the
St. Patrick's Day parade, a trio of sex discrimination cases from
the 1980s. In those cases, the court rejected claims that all-male
organizations, including the Jaycees and the Rotary Club, had a
constitutional right to exclude women, with the court noting that
the women simply sought to join and were not trying to change the
essential nature of groups that were organized around
business-networking.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson from those cases, Wolfson said, is that scouting must
show that its own ``expressive purposes in bringing its members
together are significantly burdened'' by a requirement to admit gay
members. The Scouts have failed to meet that test, he said, because
the Boy Scouts are not organized around a principle of opposition
to gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is better qualified to determine the expressive purpose of
the Boy Scouts _ the Boy Scouts or the New Jersey courts?'' Kennedy
said to Wolfson.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson, representing the Scouts, conceded that the policy of
excluding gay members did not appear in the organization's official
manuals. But that makes no difference, he said, noting that ``the
Boy Scouts are so closely identified with traditional moral values
that the phrase `He's a real Boy Scout' has entered the language.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson said the policy was based on the Boy Scouts' ``moral
code,'' as expressed in the phrase ``morally straight'' in the
Scout Oath and the word ``clean'' in the Scout Law.
</P>
<P>
   Justice John Paul Stevens asked whether the Boy Scouts took the
position that a person who engages in homosexual activity ``cannot
fit that definition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's correct,'' Davidson replied.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said the Scouts were in an even stronger position
than the organizers of the St. Patrick's Day parade, who won their
case even though, he said, there was ``no readily apparent message
in the parade.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we have a moral code,'' Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice David H. Souter, who wrote the court's unanimous
opinion in that 1995 case, Hurley vs. Irish American Gay Group of
Boston, disputed Davidson's analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem in simply drawing a parallel to Hurley,'' Souter
said, ``is that we're not at the point where anyone is proposing to
use the Boy Scouts'' for expressing their own message. Dale wanted
to rejoin scouting and was ``not proposing to carry a banner,'' the
justice said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put a banner around his neck when he appeared in the
newspaper,'' Davidson replied. ``He can't take it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson, arguing for Dale, said the Boy Scouts, ``one of the
least private public accommodations in the country,'' had not
justified an exclusion from a ``neutral civil rights law of general
applicability.''
</P>
<P>
   Some justices suggested that perhaps none of the court's
precedents was really a good fit for this case. Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor told Wolfson that ``I can well understand'' why public
accommodations law should apply to organizations that have a
commercial purpose, like the Jaycees or the Rotary Club in the
earlier cases. ``But should the weight we give it in the context of
a First Amendment claim be the same for private organizations?''
she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist asked whether members of a
Catholic organization could limit the group to Catholics on the
basis that ``we just feel much more comfortable with Catholics, and
we do Catholic work.'' He asked Wolfson whether, in light of the
Constitution's protection for freedom of association, ``they need a
more expressive message than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson replied that freedom of association did not exist as a
``free-floating right'' but rather was entitled to recognition only
to the extent that it served the ability of an organization's
members to express their message. As simply a free-floating right,
he said, it could be invoked ``as a defense against civil rights
laws that would swallow civil rights laws.''
</P>
<P>
   While most members of the court appeared uncertain of how to
decide this case, Boy Scouts vs. Dale, No. 99-669, Justice Antonin
Scalia left little doubt of his view.
</P>
<P>
   ``To require the Boy Scouts to have as a scoutmaster someone who
embodies a contradiction of their message _ how can that be?''
Scalia asked Wolfson. He said the Constitution ``prevents a state
from diluting or imperiling the message an organization wants to
convey, whether by speech or by dropping a bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   A decision is expected by early summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
