<HEADER>
A8054 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      04-26 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW&AMP;NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: RETRANSMITTING FOR THOSE WHO MAY MISSED THIS.
 &UR; STORY MOVING IN THE ``E'' AND ``L'' CATEGORIES.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule book reviews:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ``THE WORLD'S SHORTEST STORIES OF LOVE AND DEATH'' &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Steve Moss and John M. Daniel (Running, $7.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We flatter ourselves to think we know something about writing
tight, but we are pikers compared with these people. Granted, there
was self-interest involved. They were embroiled in a contest
sponsored by the San Luis Obispo newspaper ``New Times,'' which
invited readers to submit stories using plot, setting and characte
in fewer than 55 words. First prize included a certificate and a
T-shirt. If ``New Times'' hasn't upped the ante since then, it
doesn't deserve readers like these. Most of the stories are long
(relatively speaking) on dialogue, humor and creative implication,
and short on everything else. It sounds easy, but try it. Here is
``The Britches of Madison County,'' in which author Bill Crown
one-ups Robert James Waller in 37 words: ``Francesca came out on
the porch and welcomed them home, her husband, their son, and
daughter. But her skirt was hung up in the waist of her drawers.
The old man got hip and he shot her.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``ORCHID FEVER'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Eric Hansen (Pantheon, $23) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Please do not shy away from this book because its subject is
orchids and you don't know anything about them. Hansen didn't know
anything about them either, until he was hired to guide two orchid
fanatics into the wilds of Borneo in search of the holy grail of
orchids, the Latin name of which we refuse to repea here. Hansen
hired some Borneo natives to provide sherpalike assistance on this
journey, and these simple, jungle-savvy men provide lots of laughs
as they react to the orchid zealots' reasons for sloshing up a
muddy Borneo river with a stockpile of equipment that includes a
camouflaged cardboard toilet. This trip was the author's
introduction to the world of orchids and orchid lovers, which was
far more complex, seductive, competitive and pricey than he ever
imagined. Read all about it in this captivating and often funny
book. (Hansen appeared briefly in a recent ``60 Minutes'' story
about the orchid world. As is almost always the case when media
overlap, the book is better.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``SHRINK YOUR HANDICAP'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Phil Lee and Jeff Warne (Hyperion, $23.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can read this as a means to improve your golf game, or you
can read it for laughs. New &AMP; Notable has no golf game to speak of,
but in search of good suggestions for Father's Day, we read gamely
on, stifling our guffaws. Lee, a psychiatrist, and Warne, a golf
instructor, join forces to explain the mystery of why you play
better when no one is watching. The villain is the dreaded panic
attack syndrome. As Lee says, There are specific swing weaknesses
that are magnets for the chemicals of anxiety. Even the tiniest
amount of anxiety produces chemicals that will feast on certain
specific weaknesses in the swing. Their solutions include a
pre-shot routine that involves entering a light trance, developing
``Insight-Oriented Defenses'' to fight the nasty chemicals and
``uninstalling'' the ``Blame Game,'' or the urge to be angry over
bad shots. They take this very, very seriously, but we could not.
Disguised as psychobabble, even common sense sounds like hooey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``LEFT FOR DEAD'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Beck Weathers (Villard, $24.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The survival of Dallas pathologist Beck Weathers was just about
the only good news to come out of the storm on Mount Everest that
killed nine people in 1996. Left for dead by other climbers, he
suddenly, miraculously stood up and walked through the squall to
the nearest camp. Fellow climber Jon Krakauer (``Into Thin Air'')
comes off well in this version of the day's events. Anatoli
Boukreev, the guide who climbed without oxygen and so was unable to
help his clients descend before the storm hit, does not. Neither
does George W. Bush, who would not help Weathers' family get him
home from Nepal. Less interesting sections about Weathers' youth
and relationship with his wife and family are followed by sobering
descriptions of his recuperation (he lost both hands and his nose
to frostbite). Best of all, he tells of the daring Nepalese pilot
who flew alone, perilously higher than his helicopter was meant to
go, and brought Weathers off of Mount Everest alive.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
