r e BC-FILM-LASTSEPTEMBER-TE     04-26 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LASTSEPTEMBER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEGINNING OF THE END FOR THE ANGLO-IRISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Deborah Warner's historical drama introduces us to the
end of the world of the Anglo-Irish, aristocrats who dominated
Ireland until the country's early 20th-century war for independence
from England. It takes place at the estate of Sir Richard Naylor
(Michael Gambon) and his wife, Lady Myra (Maggie Smith), who
continue to entertain guests and host lawn-tennis matches even as
violence escalates around them. They're not so much ignoring the
war as defying it, which is easy to do because there is little
evidence around them, aside from the British soldiers who stand
sentry near their country home.
</P>
<P>
   Among the people staying there are Sir Richard's 19-year-old
niece, Lois (Keeley Hawes), who is almost blissfully naive about
the war. She sees it as an opportunity to dance and flirt with the
soldiers, and understandably attracts the romantic attention of an
earnest British captain (David Tennant). Just as understandably,
she's drawn to the more dangerous and exciting rebel Peter Connolly
(Gary Lydon), who provides an opportunity for a sexual awakening _
and an opening to an almost inevitable family.
</P>
<P>
   Warner and screenwriter John Banville fashioned ``The Last
September'' from an Elizabeth Bowen novel, and the film retains the
literary qualities, unfolding and building upon itself much like a
book, but also taking its time. Despite the methodical approach,
the film is a bit top-heavy with characters, and demands attention
until Lois' story emerges as its focal point. Hawes, whose
apple-cheeked features make her ideal for the kind of ingenue we
don't see much anymore, makes us empathize with Lois, and Slawomir
Idziak's elegiac cinematography suits the film's melancholia. The
film's slowness is a minor drawback, but it offers rewards for
patient viewers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM: ``Last September'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RATING: 3 1/2 on a 1-5 scale &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
