<HEADER>
A8066 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-POLICEMAN-SHOT-BOS &LR;      04-26 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICEMAN-SHOT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COCHRAN PLANS SUIT ON BEHALF OF SLAIN POLICEMAN'S MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMAL E. WATSON AND TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ In a move that raises the stakes in the
racially &UR;  &LR; charged shooting death of police Sgt. Cornel Young,
Johnnie Cochran Jr., the O.J. Simpson lawyer, and his legal ``Dream
Team'' say they plan to file a wrongful death and civil rights
lawsuit seeking $20 million on behalf of the victim's mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking the first step on a journey, hopefully a journey
for justice,'' said Cochran during a news conference at Allen
A.M.E. Church here. ``Healing will only begin when you have true
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Cochran said his high-profile team is working with the US
Justice Department's Civil Rights Division, which is itself
launching an investigation into the Providence police department.
</P>
<P>
   The development brought cheers among the city's black leaders,
who said they are convinced that the Cochran group will raise the
stakes in the case, flushing out more details about the incident _
and, perhaps, forcing Providence into a more searching discussion
of race.
</P>
<P>
   But other city leaders, mindful of the media circus that
surrounded the Simpson case, said they fear that Cochran will play
a more divisive role, just as poeple are trying to put the case in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disappointed in Ms. Young, in her choice of lawyers,''
said Michael Marcoccio, head of Providence Fraternal Order of
Police. ``She has the right to sue, but Cochran and his grand stand
act will only further divide the city.''
</P>
<P>
   But The Rev. Marlowe V.N. Washington, a member of the Rhode
Island Ministerial Alliance, defended Young's decision to pursue
the sought-after lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not O.J. Simpson's legal team, but this is Leisa
Young's legal team,'' said Washington. ``They have come to assist a
grieving mother who lost her one and only son.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week a Rhode Island grand jury cleared Patrolmen Carlos A.
Saraiva and Michael Solitro III of criminal wrongdoing in the
shooting death of Young. The Providence officers apparently mistook
Young, a black man in civilian clothing, for an armed suspect at a
late-night restaurant on Jan. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Young was off duty when he drew his gun to help the two
officers, who were confronting an armed suspect during a fight
outside The Fidas diner. The two officers said they didn't
recognize Young and when he didn't drop his weapon, they shot him.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Young's father, Major Cornel Young Sr., is the highest
ranking officer in the department. It is unclear if Young Sr.,
divorced from hiw wife and who could not be reached for comment,
supported the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Vincent A. Cianci said he had begun to meet with The Rev.
Eugene Rivers of Boston and local city and religious leaders to
discuss what could be done to improve relations between the police
and minority community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were starting to heal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Leisa Young said she had begun to lose faith after
government officials were unable to tell her what happened on the
night of son's death. She said she needed a powerful person to help
in her quest for justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't heal unless you know what is wrong,'' she said. ``I
can't let this go until I found out what happened to my son.''
</P>
<P>
   Cochran and his associate, Peter J. Neufeld, joined Robert B.
Mann, a local laweyr, in filing a claim Wednesday with the city
council. The notice argued the ``actions of Providence police
caused the wrongful death of Cornel Young Jr., interfered in his
family relationship and deprived him and his family members of
their federal and state constitutional rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Cochran said the case, which has been the talk of Providence for
months, is not about money but about making ``the streets of
Providence safer for all citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Young contacted Cochran and Barry Scheck, who both defended O.J.
Simpson on murder charges, months ago, after she felt she couldn't
get answers from city and state officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just realized how unprepared I was to fight this battle
alone,'' said Young. ``I knew of their reputation and I thought
they didn't live here so they wouldn't have to worry about the
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week Cianci said he would be willing to meet with
Cochran and his legal team as well as Young to try to bring about a
resolution, but Cochran said it may be too late for discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran has taken on a number of racially charged cases,
including the case of Abner Louima, the Haitian immigrant assulted
by three white police officers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Law School Professor Charles Ogletree said that Cochran
was probably drawn to the Young case because of the potential to
affect how the city's police force operates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will turn that whole department on its head,'' said
Ogletree. ``You will see a different level of training... on how to
use firearms. It will be a wake-up call to Providence.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Charles Walton (D-Providence) contends the arrival of
Cochran team is just another chapter in a sad, ongoing saga.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had one small section of closure with the grand jury
decision,'' said Watson. ``That didn't close everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
