A8067 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COOPER-WORKPLACE-NYT     04-26 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOPER-WORKPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PIPE FITTER`S WRENCH OF HER OWN
</HEADLINE>
 By EVE TAHMINCIOGLU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It used to take Nannette Cooper about an hour every
morning to curl her hair, put on foundation, eye shadow and
lipstick and pick out just the right business suit and three-inch
heels for her job as a hotel manager in Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it takes her all of five minutes _ showering, throwing on
jeans and a T-shirt, tying her hair in a ponytail and lacing up her
steel-toed boots.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, 39, is now a construction worker who has her sights set
on becoming a premier pipe fitter and welder, maybe at a nuclear
plant.
</P>
<P>
   True, it is hard for the 5-foot-2, 125-pound blonde to hide her
female frame, even in baggy pants, from her co-workers, mostly men.
And she isn't crazy about their habits of spitting constantly and
answering nature's call under the open sky. (She uses the portable
toilet and has ``gotten so that I can go once a day and be OK with
it,'' she said.)
</P>
<P>
   But none of that really matters. ``I've been working toward this
for 20 years,'' said Cooper, who is in her third year of a
full-time apprenticeship. Her latest gig is at Ashland Chemical in
Bartow, Fla., where she is actually fitting pipe on her own. That
entails following blueprints and placing pipe pieces together like
a jigsaw puzzle and passing them along to a welder who attaches the
pieces together with a gizmo called a stinger.
</P>
<P>
   When she utters the word ``stinger,'' her eyes light up with the
memory of her father's use of the instrument in her hometown of
Ferron, Utah. As a child, she said, she spent hours hanging out
with him as he welded farming equipment and trailer parts for
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   But in high school, her teachers discouraged her from pursuing a
welding career.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I asked to take the welding or shop classes, they said it
wasn't for girls,'' she said. So, she took courses like shorthand
and typing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated it, but I figured you just have to follow the rules,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she is breaking the rules. That has become a lot easier in
the current tight labor market, of course, in which job hopping has
become common and many people are challenging established
assumptions in traditional industries and switching careers in
their late 30s, 40s and even 50s.
</P>
<P>
   Few are making such a drastic shift as Cooper. But women are
invading former male strongholds. Though they still account for
only 2.5 percent of construction workers, for example, their
numbers in that industry soared last year by nearly 30 percent, to
145,000 from 112,000 the previous year, according to the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is movement among women to join the trades, no question
about it, but it's very, very slow,'' said Ray Hilgert, professor
of management and industrial relations at Washington University in
St. Louis. ``In the construction industry, there is still a lot of
hostility toward women. There's a lot of tokenism that goes on. You
see highway projects and the women are usually out there holding
directional stop and go signs.''
</P>
<P>
   So how does Hilgert see Cooper's future? ``If she can make it,''
he quipped, ``she can be the Jackie Robinson of the pipe-fitting
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The analogy might be extreme, but Cooper has come a long way. In
the small Mormon community where she grew up, women were supposed
to be ``family oriented'' and were encouraged, if they chose a
career at all, to become bank tellers or teachers. She did not
disappoint. She married at age 18 and within four years had two
children. Her husband, Rodney, was a construction worker
specializing in electrical work, and the family traveled from
construction site to construction site. The temporary jobs she took
_ as waitress, administrative assistant and gymnastics coach _ were
all indoors. In Tampa, she spent 10 years in hotel management,
first running Shoney's Inn and then a Quality Suites.
</P>
<P>
   But the 80-hour weeks left her no time for her family, and in
1997 she realized it was time to get out when she learned, only by
reading the local newspaper, that her son had been chosen his
soccer team's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly, she applied for the apprenticeship program at the
plumbers' and pipe fitters' local of the AFL-CIO in Tampa. At first
she thought she had botched the interview; she showed up in a suit
and heels, while the 30 other applicants, all men, were in jeans
and T-shirts. Then, the interviewer tried to discourage her. ``You
know this is heavy work,'' he told her. ``You're going to get
sweaty.'' She said she didn't care. A week later, she was accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Her first job was lugging tools and water kegs. After her first
day, she remembers going home, taking off her boots and thinking:
``I love it.'' Since then, she has been working for a local
contractor, doing a variety of jobs. She also takes plumbing and
pipe-fitting classes every Tuesday and Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, she relishes the extra time she can spend with her
children, now 19 and 17, and her husband, who encouraged her to
change careers. And though money is tight _ she makes roughly half
her hotel manager's salary _ she takes comfort in her expectation
of future pay in the range of $60,000 to $100,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Cooper calls herself a feminist, but she warns women that
construction work is not for the faint of heart. Aside from the
heavy lifting, she is required to read blueprints and calculate how
to align pipes that will be connected to 55,000-gallon chemical
tanks and the like. Even a mistake by one-sixteenth inch can botch
the job, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the work environment, which includes not only
spitting and public urinating but lots of whistling at passing
women and the occasional dirty joke. ``It's a whole different
culture,'' Cooper said. ``You just have to get used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she said, her fellow workers and foremen have gone out
of their way to teach her the ropes, and one of them usually walks
her to her car after work.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's dream is to reach the top of her profession and work at
a nuclear plant, where the art of pipe fitting plays a critical
role in containing radiation. Her ultimate goal is to work side by
side with her son Rodney Jr., 19, who is in his first year as a
pipe-fitting apprentice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing glamorous at all about the job,'' Cooper said.
But, she added: ``When you finish a job, you can forever drive by
and feel good you helped complete it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
