<HEADLINE>
VIOLENCE ON THE RISE IN TEXAS PRISONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVAN MOORE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) An inmate brawl at a West Texas prison on Tuesday that
left one prisoner dead and 31 injured was the sixth violent
incident at a state prison this year, underscoring an escalating
spiral of unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Figures from the Texas Department of Criminal Justice reveal
that incidents of violence in Texas prisons have increased more
than 10-fold within the past decade, from 1,434 in 1990 to 14,669
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   That increase has outstripped the increase in inmate population
during that same period. The number of inmates has gone from 49,209
in 1990 to 148,734, in 1999, a three-fold increase.
</P>
<P>
   Both prison officials and guards, while differing on other
issues, agree that today's inmates are younger and more prone to
violence than prisoners of past years. Beyond that, however, they
differ over how badly the institutions are understaffed.
</P>
<P>
   The fight at the medium- to minimum-security unit near Lamesa
Tuesday came as prison officials were auditing their corrections
staffing and guards were demanding pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   The fight involved about 300 black and Hispanic prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The dead inmate was identified as Fernando Trejo, 24. Trejo was
serving a five-year sentence for burglary from Cameron County.
</P>
<P>
   Prison spokesman Larry Todd said the brawl was sparked by racial
tensions that erupted over an incident in the dining room at lunch,
when a black inmate began fondling himself in front of a female
corrections officer. Todd said a Hispanic prisoner attacked the
black prisoner with a water pitcher and the two were removed.
</P>
<P>
   Other prisoners began taking sides, however, and the
disagreement spilled over into the work area where the fight began.
Inmates broke into a storage shed and armed themselves with garden
tools. The disturbance was quelled after about five hours and the
unit was placed on lockdown.
</P>
<P>
   While the slayer has not been identified, ``We are making good
progress on finding the inmate who killed Trejo,'' Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   One guard received minor injuries when a pepper gas grenade
exploded in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred as prison guards were demanding that the
state Legislature hold a special session and raise their wages. The
guards, who want an average salary of $34,000 per year, contend
that prisons are dangerously understaffed, in part, because of the
low pay. Guards currently earn their peak pay of $26,724 a year
after 21 months on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Todd said the Lamesa unit, which has a capacity of 1,342 inmates
and currently houses 1,322, is budgeted for 422 guards and has 392
employed there at present.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not understaffed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The inmates there are not considered security risks, though many
of them may have committed violent crimes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problem is the same as it's been for some time now,'' Todd
said. ``Throughout the whole system we have younger, tougher
inmates. They're serving longer sentences and have less to lose and
they're more prone to violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Olsen, deputy director of the American Federation of
State, County and Municipal Employees, the union that represents
corrections officers, differed only on one point with Todd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it does have to do with younger, more violent
criminals,'' Olsen said. ``But some of it has to do with
understaffing as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the prisons remain short-staffed, we're looking at
some serious danger to corrections officers and to the prisoners
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Olsen said there are between 25,000 and 30,000 guards monitoring
about 150,000 inmates on a 24-hour basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean all those guards are out on the floor,'' he
said. ``A number of them are in offices and, by the time you spread
the others out over three shifts it boils down to one guard to
almost 100 prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't see a pay raise soon, there's going to be a mass
exodus from those jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The fight at Lamesa came on the heels of an incident at the
Connally Unit in Kenedy Sunday in which two prisoners stabbed
another prisoner. The motive for the assault was not known and the
injured prisoner was in stable condition at a San Antonio hospital.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, a nurse at the infirmary of the Hughes Unit near
Gatesville was attacked, beaten and threatened with scissors by an
inmate.
</P>
<P>
   On April 13, an inmate held a guard hostage for seven hours at
the William P. Clements Unit in Amarillo before releasing him,
unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar incident on Feb. 21 two inmates held a guard
hostage for 13 hours at the Terrell Unit in Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 15, a guard in Huntsville was stabbed with a pencil.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
