<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MEMYSELFI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ULTIMATE TRADING PLACES PLOT: ME FOR MYSELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest favor this movie does for us is resurrecting the
wonderfully solipsistic Joan Armatrading song from which the movie
borrows its title. Great tune, but unfortunately, a better song of
choice might have been ``Deja Vu,'' because the movie suffers from
a familiarity that's inescapable.
</P>
<P>
   Not that that will stop some people from connecting with this
Australian romantic comedy, in which single, thirtysomething
journalist Pamela Drury (Rachel Griffiths) ruminates over what
might have happened had she married the high-school sweetheart she
turned down. She gets a chance to find out when, through a bizarre
turn of events, she meets her alter-ego _ who did marry the guy.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela One and Pamela Two swap places, much to the befuddled
delight of husband Robert (David Roberts), who is pleasantly
surprised to find that the mother of his three children has a
renewed vigor and sex drive. That wanes, however, when Pamela
discovers that being a mom involves messes such as young children
with poor bathroom habits and that dreamboat Robert isn't the man
she thought he would be.
</P>
<P>
   Director Pip Karmel, who filmed in Sydney but steered clear of
the self-conscious eccentricity of many recent Australian films, is
primarily interested in illustrating the futility of regret. She's
right to use Griffiths, who brings a sort of perplexed and bemused
gravity to the role of Pamela, to help make her point. But the
movie quickly melds with any number of recent romantic-comedy
meditations on fate; it's easy to see Meg Ryan or a lighthearted
Gwyneth Paltrow doing something similar. In fact, they have;
Griffiths' edge helps separate ``Me Myself I'' from their work, but
it's only the merest shred of individuality in a movie that is, at
least partly, about individualism.
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Me Myself I'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
