<SLUG> BC-TOMASSON-DANCE-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAVORITE SON RETURNS TO NEW YORK CITY BALLET 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent as NYT15 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 30)  
 Susan Reiter's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about the
Jose Limon Dance Company.  
 By SUSAN REITER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, Helgi Tomasson, the celebrated dancer from
Iceland, stood onstage at the New York State Theater for the last
time as a member of the New York City Ballet, accepting flowers and
a resounding ovation for his final performance.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, if he goes against his innately modest and
reticent nature, he should be back on that stage, this time taking
a bow as the choreographer of a world premiere for the company's
spring gala program.
</P>
<P>
   Tomasson's ``Prism,'' set to Beethoven's Piano Concerto No. 1,
will be the closing work on a program that includes the premieres
of two Peter Martins ballets, ``Slonimsky's Earbox,'' to John
Adams's score of the same name, and ``Todo Buenos Aires,'' to
Adams's orchestrations of two Astor Piazzolla compositions. Along
with Christopher Wheeldon's ``Mercurial Manoeuvres,'' which opens
the gala evening, these ballets are all part of City Ballet's
fourth Diamond Project, a showcase for new choreography.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prism'' represents a homecoming, one that might have taken
place sooner had Tomasson's responsibilities as artistic director
of the San Francisco Ballet not been so all-consuming. In addition
to leading his troupe to a new level of achievement and
international recognition, he has choreographed 25 one-act ballets
and his own productions of 4 classics there since taking over in
June 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter Martins has been asking me for many years to come and do
a ballet here, and finally this season it worked out that I was
able to do it,'' Tomasson said during a mid-March interview at New
York City Ballet's Lincoln Center rehearsal studios. ``For the
first time, I was not making a new ballet in San Francisco. I put
together a Discovery Program there with six premieres by young
aspiring choreographers, so that meant that I stepped aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomasson was in town to finish ``Prism,'' which he began
choreographing last November, and to audition potential new members
for his San Francisco troupe.
</P>
<P>
   During a three-hour rehearsal a few days earlier, Tomasson took
a long pause to sort out a series of large circling patterns in his
ballet's third movement as the full cast of 29, plus understudies,
waited to start dancing again. This final movement features
bounding, bravura passages for Sebastien Marcovici and brings
together dancers from the first movement, which focuses on a lead
trio backed up by three additional trios, and the second, which
includes a lead couple (Maria Kowroski and Charles Askegard) with
seven supporting couples.
</P>
<P>
   While the others took a break, Tomasson, in a black T-shirt and
jeans, guided Marcovici through a tricky series of leaps and
clarified some details. When they reassembled and ran through the
full finale, its elegant details and sophisticated, pristine
patterns emerged, the dancers riding the energy of the robust
Beethoven score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been thinking for years that this music would make a
wonderful ballet,'' Tomasson said. ``It's early Beethoven; I found
it very danceable when I listened to it _ and in some ways a little
intimidating. But when the opportunity came to work with City
Ballet, I thought of that music, and felt it was right for this
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent so many years here, and coming back, in a whole new
way, to the company where I spent the better part of my career _ I
wanted to do a pure dance in a classical sense, using the classical
technique. I had a very clear concept of what I wanted to do, based
on how I heard the structure of the music. This is a big-sounding
work; I really wanted a lot of people onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Tomasson embarks on a new ballet as an experienced
choreographer, but he readily recalls creating ``Menuetto,'' his
first work for City Ballet, in 1984. He had already begun his
choreographic career with two well-received ballets for the annual
workshop of the School of American Ballet, which is affiliated with
City Ballet, but now he was in the big time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exciting, but it was not easy, because I was still part
of the company, just starting out as a choreographer,'' he said.
``Maybe it was just my perception, but there were times I felt
awkward. I was almost too much a part of them as a family of
dancers.''
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing ``Menuetto,'' Anna Kisselgoff wrote in The New York
Times that Tomasson ``has met his own test with flying colors _
using the most formal of methods to create the most natural of
ballets.'' The choreography bug had bitten him for good, and from
his first season in San Francisco, he made regular contributions to
the repertory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was very necessary, and also it's something I wanted
to do,'' Tomasson said. ``I felt it would really give the dancers
an idea of what I was looking for, how I want them to dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomasson, 57, who remains trim though his hair has gone from
black to white and thinned somewhat, has now been running San
Francisco Ballet for the same number of years he danced with City
Ballet. ``It was not a terribly smooth transition,'' he says, in
his understated way, of his arrival there; his restrained approach
and attention to the refinements of classical technique represented
a big change from the flashy showmanship of the previous director,
Michael Smuin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was trial by fire,'' Tomasson says. Making the company his
own and maintaining its high standards, he says, has been ``very
challenging, rewarding, frustrating _ it's been hard work, a
24-hour job.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Rose Building, where Tomasson was rehearsing
``Prism,'' had not yet been built when he was with City Ballet and
thus harbors no nostalgic associations, he did experience a few
pangs on entering the New York State Theater. ``It's amazing; it
doesn't seem like 15 years,'' he said. ``When I go into the
theater, it feels almost like it was yesterday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
