<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8071 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-FITNESS-BALL-LADN &LR;      04-26 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FITNESS-BALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET FIT AND HAVE A BALL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use on or after May 1, 2000) 
By PHIL DAVIS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judi Clark found her workouts were lacking. Then she found ``The
Ball.''
</P>
<P>
   She was skeptical when her personal trainer first rolled the
giant blue rubber ball into the high-tech gym at the Spectrum Club
in Valencia. It looked like a circus prop. What, she wondered,
could this goofy, air-filled thing do for her body?
</P>
<P>
   The question should have been, What (BEGIN ITAL)can't(END ITAL)
it do?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sweating on the third stretch,'' Clark said. ``It's
unbelievable. I worked out with different trainers for nine months
without real results. With the ball, I got results quickly. I'm
standing up straighter. My muscles feel stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Working out on the fitness ball _ also known as the stability
ball, flexi-ball, therapy ball, Swiss ball, Resist-a-ball or physio
ball _ is the latest exercise trend popping up at fitness clubs.
While new to the clubs, the method has been used by years by San
Fernando Valley certified personal trainers and physical
therapists. It was invented in Switzerland in the 1950s as a method
for restoring patients' motor skills after serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The ball capitalizes on the body's own weight by creating
instabilities that force typically unused ``stabilizer'' muscles in
the back, abdomen and buttocks to work. Ordinary exercise machines
give support that allows those muscles to relax. Perched on the
ball, the body improves its posture by straightening the spine.
</P>
<P>
   After mastering the initial balancing tricks _ lifting one foot,
then switching to the other without falling over _ trainer Larry
Painter has clients like Clark work through stretches, push ups or
even barbell workouts that put the whole body through the paces.
For example, a bench press on the ball turns the body into the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   Painter likes the ball because it builds strength physically and
mentally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It increases our awareness of where our bodies are in space,''
said Painter, who first used it a year ago when he was recovering
from a back injury. ``One of the most exciting things about doing
ball work is that people really feel good about their ability to
move and be in control.''
</P>
<P>
   Chain health clubs currently introducing class instruction for
the ball include Bally's Total Fitness and Bodies in Motion. Bodies
in Motion launched a pilot program in Century City in March, while
Bally's plans to roll out classes at its Northridge and Chatsworth
locations as soon as storage equipment arrives, said area aerobic
director Cricket Haskell.
</P>
<P>
   Bally's trainer Carl Harberger _ who has used the ball with
clients in Chatsworth for two years _ speculates all the recent
attention is part of an overall whole-body fitness movement that
also includes such programs as Pilates and yoga.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike extreme workouts such as spinning, he says, the ball
appeals to people of all fitness levels, including senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new cutting-edge sort of thing,'' agrees Phil Jun, a
manager for Bodies in Motion.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the response in Century City, Jun says Bodies in
Motion might introduce similar classes at San Fernando Valley
franchises, such as one in Encino. Club members have already
convinced him to add two evening classes at Century City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things that people are trying once, then
telling all their friends,'' said Jun. ``People like it because you
don't immediately get tired. But believe me, you feel it later.''
</P>
<P>
   Jun sees more weightlifters using stability balls to overcome
workout plateaus, points where marked improvement ceases. After
exercising underworked back and abdomenal muscles, they often begin
lifting heavier weights or increasing repetitions.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It's funny, because usually there's one or two of
these balls in the corner of every gym just collecting dust.''
</P>
<P>
   Sporting-good merchants also have noticed increased sales of the
ball. But Ronen Pollak, owner of Fitness Depot in Woodland Hills,
says most demand for the $25-$55 item has come from personal
trainers.
</P>
<P>
   Del Barrett, owner of Action Personal Training in Encino, said
all 22 trainers there use them for various purposes.
</P>
<P>
   And, Barrett said, many clients are referred from physical
therapists.
</P>
<P>
   Having worked ``Swiss balls'' into rehabilitative programs for
18 years, Dr. Ruth Gomez, clinical director of Progressive Physical
Therapy in Tarzana, is not surprised the ball is catching on in
exercise circles, given its range of possibilities and results.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez has administered ``Swiss ball'' therapy for conditions
ranging from weak bladders _ the exercises strengthen pelvic
muscles _ to muscle injuries. She even uses them in brain injury
cases, such as strokes, to help restore a patient's physical
balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens is that you attempt to right yourself,'' Gomez
explained of the latter exercise. ``When you start to go off
balance, the response to align yourself against gravity is an
automatic response.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``When you feel yourself begin to fall, the body
wants to catch itself. It's a survival instinct almost.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jolly, who works out at Spectrum Club in Valencia,
turned to the ball to help alleviate a back problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very effective,'' Jolly said. ``It looks simple, but it's
not so easy. Besides, sometimes the simplest things are the most
effective. I'm getting results, and that's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   As with any new exercise, experts recommend consulting a trained
exercise or medical professional for instruction before using the
stability ball.
</P>
<P>
   _ Staff Writer Angela Lemire contributed to this story. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
