<HEADER>
A8073 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-STNMT-REBELFLAG27-COX     04-26 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STNMT-REBELFLAG27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flagpole removal ignites Confederate emblem fight in Georgia
town
 &HT;    By Ben Smith III and Maurice Tamman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STONE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ The 21st-century battle over the banner of
the Confederacy shifted Wednesday from South Carolina to Stone
Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that its property rights had been violated, the Sons of
Confederate Veterans filed a federal lawsuit against the city for
removing a cemetery flagpole on which the group had intended to
hoist the battle flag Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   City officials, accusing the group of coming to town to pick a
fight on Confederate Memorial Day, said the flagpole was removed
because the group installed it without a permit.
</P>
<P>
   The verbal fracas marked the latest in a series of skirmishes
around the Southeast over the emblem. A measure to remove the flag
from atop the South Carolina Capitol is halfway through its
Legislature. That effort was prompted by a boycott of the state,
launched by the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People.
</P>
<P>
   This month the Jackson City Council in Mississippi voted to
remove the state flag, which incorporates the Confederate Cross of
St. Andrew design. And activists on both sides of the issue say the
moribund campaign to change Georgia's own Confederate-style state
flag is almost certain to be resurrected.
</P>
<P>
   ``What monument can be sacred? If we can't erect a memorial
where our dead are buried, where can we have one?'' said Gene Wade
of Snellville, Ga., one of more than a dozen Confederate veterans
who staged an impromptu march in Stone Mountain on Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The group includes H.K. Edgerton, a black member of the Sons of
Confederate Veterans who traveled from Asheville, N.C., to
participate in the memorial service Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That flag belongs to those dead heroes,'' said Edgerton, who
is among a small group of descendants of black Confederate
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Edgerton, Wade and others said the decision by Stone Mountain
Mayor Chuck Burris to have the flagpole removed Tuesday, the day
before Confederate Memorial Day, is clear evidence that opponents
of the Georgia flag want to rid the state of Confederate symbols.
</P>
<P>
   When former Gov. Zell Miller launched his unsuccessful bid to
change the state flag, he and other supporters argued, among other
things, that the Confederate flag belonged to museums and memorials
such as Stone Mountain Park.
</P>
<P>
   For Stone Mountain, which has long straddled an uneasy divide
between its past as a mecca for the Ku Klux Klan and its present as
a growing enclave of middle- and upper-class African-Americans,
this is an unwanted fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have really fought this image because of this one sad man
who owned property here,'' said Ginger Lipscomb, who owns Stone's
Jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Lipscomb, who said she didn't mind the Confederate emblem flying
in the cemetery but agreed that a permit was necessary, was
referring to James Venable, the former Ku Klux Klan leader who once
lived in Stone Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the city of Stone Mountain made worldwide news when it
elected its first black mayor, Chuck Burris. Many viewed his
election as symbolic of a new era, and business leaders backed his
pragmatic approach. Rather than seeking to remove ``mammy dolls''
from gift shops or strip the state flag from City Hall, Burris said
he was more interested in promoting tourism.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, before leaving for Dallas to attend the National
Conference of Black Mayors, Burriss said, ``I've never made this an
issue. They've always gotten a permit approved every year for the
Confederate Memorial (service). The real issue is the illegal
erection of a flagpole.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a city ordinance, anyone seeking to erect a structure
other than a stone monument must receive permission from the city
cemetery's sexton. That official, Tug Tuggle, said he never
received such a request this year from the Sons of Confederate
Veterans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the Sons had asked the city council for such permission
but were refused.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the group bought four cemetery plots and erected the
flagpole there 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   City council members said Wednesday that they invited the group
to a special meeting April 18 to work out a compromise, but the
group did not show up. Coleman said the group was not aware of such
an invitation.
</P>
<P>
   One proposal was to allow the group to keep the flagpole and to
fly the original Confederate national flag, the so-called ``Stars
and Bars,'' rather than the battle flag, which is far more
offensive to blacks, said City Council member Nan Odum Nash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not unsympathetic to (the SCV),'' said Nash, owner of a
local military antiques store that sells Confederate flags. ``I
wanted to work out a compromise but they didn't come to our
meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said Wednesday that flying the ``Stars and Bars'' was
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Bradley, a lawyer for the American Civil Liberties Union,
said he found the city's removal of the flagpole ``troubling ... I
think the people putting it up were clearly making a free speech
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley added that the city's position is probably
defensible because it has allowed small, temporary Confederate
flags in the city cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We often have flags in cemeteries. That is very traditional
and bears on what can be regulated ... That helps them (the city
council) because they don't seemed to be concerned with content,''
said Bradley. It gives them a leg up.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lipscomb and other area business owners seemed
annoyed by the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you will mention what a small crowd this is,'' Lipscomb
said. ``There is not some terrible turmoil going on in our town.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, hundreds of people, many dressed in period
costumes of hoop skirts and the somber gray uniform of the
Confederate soldiers, celebrated Confederate Memorial Day at the
cemetery. Many waved small Confederate flags as the sun settled
into the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
