<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Silicon Labs' net income triples
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In its first earnings report since its March 24
initial public stock offering, Austin-based chip maker Silicon
Laboratories Inc. said Wednesday that net income for the first
quarter was $3 million, or 7 cents per share, nearly triple the
$1.068 million or 2 cents a share for the comparable period a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Sales climbed 212 percent to a record $19.7 million from $6.3
million for the first quarter in 1999. In addition to higher sales,
gross margin increased to 66 percent from 62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Spending on research and development grew 177 percent to $3.6
million.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Lab shares closed down $1.31 at $79.44, $10 higher than
its closing price March 24. The results were announced after the
market closed.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Labs, which was profitable in the year leading up to its
IPO, designs and sells mixed-signal chips for
communications-related products.
</P>
<P>
   Net income before non-cash charges for amortization of deferred
stock compensation was $3.8 million in the first quarter of 2000,
up 245 percent from $1.1 million in the first quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
