<SLUG> BC-FUGITIVE-DIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUGITIVE DIES BY OWN HAND DURING RAID, POLICE SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR AND RAPHAEL LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Despite televised pleas from ministers, a phone call to
a youth worker, and pressure from police on anyone who ever knew
him, Sean Taylor, Boston's most elusive fugitive, died of a
self-inflicted gunshot as police burst into the house where he was
hiding.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Taylor fired about a dozen shots before turning the
gun on himself just after 5 p.m. The shooting followed 90 minutes
of tense negotiations that brought his mother, father, stepmother
and ministers to the scene outside an apartment building, pleading
for a safe surrender.
</P>
<P>
   After eluding police for close to eight months, Taylor was
brazenly living on the edge, cornered in a house two blocks from
the Boston police station where gang unit officers had been
plotting how to hunt Taylor down.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor had been on the run since a Sept. 2 car chase and
shootout in neighboring Brookline that ended in the capture of
accused killer Jason Pierce, who police say fatally shot two former
high school friends and nearly killed his ex-girlfriend in suburban
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But while the endgame Taylor promised delivered gunfire, it was
not the deadly volley with police he had envisioned: As tactical
teams entered the building and climbed the stairs, Taylor turned
one of the two automatic pistols he held on himself. He was taken
to Boston Medical Center in critical condition, where he died
minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a young man who thought he was in a rap video, but he
found out that life wasn't a game,,'' said the Rev. Eugene Rivers,
one of a dozen pastors who had pleaded in a televised conference in
September for him to turn himself in. ``Unfortunately Mr. Taylor
apparently did not recongize that in life, if you play, sooner or
later you have to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Rivers and the Rev. Hermon Hamilton, who was at the scene
of Wednesday's standoff and offered to go inside and bring Taylor
out unharmed, said police had used uncommon restraint both in
negotiations and in entering the building where he was hiding.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took himself out,'' said Hamilton, pastor of the Roxbury
Presbyterian Church, which is next to the scene of Wednesday's
drama. Hamilton said he believed all the gunfire came from Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brought his mother, they brought his father; I told them
I would be willing to negotiate,'' he said. ``Mr. Taylor had no
interest in that whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said the stand-off was triggered by an informant who
alerted police that Taylor was inside the building. Within minutes,
the house was surrounded, and police evacuated other residents
before starting lengthy negotiations. A white van with special
tactical teams was parked outside the house for more than 15
minutes before officers in SWAT gear emerged and burst into the
building.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's mother, who did not give her first name, said she
offerred to speak to her son before officers went into the house,
hoping she could persuade him to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made us leave,'' she said. ``We was there, they made us
leave, the SWAT team went up there. We heard shooting _ pop pop
pop! _ and he came out on a stretcher. It seems they weren't
interested in having me help.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the wild shootout outside the Mall at Chestnut Hill
last September, Taylor had been wanted by Boston Police since March
1999, when he allegedly shot a female victim in the ankle at the
Academy Homes Housing Development in the city's Roxbury section.
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor added three more counts of assault with a deadly
weapon, as well as attempted murder, after he shot at police
officers in the September incident.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation was part of a routine police patrol, but it
set in motion a chain reaction, sparking one manhunt as it ended
another. Pierce, 21, a longtime friend of Taylor also from Roxbury,
was himself the target of a massive multi-agency manhunt following
the Aug. 26 shooting that police say was motivated by jealousy in a
tumultuous relationship with his former girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the women, Patrice Lassiter and Monique Brown, died in
the shootings. Shunae Allen, who was Pierce's girlfriend, was
injured. The three women, all friends who graduated from English
High School in Boston last year, went to Atlanta to attend college.
</P>
<P>
   Arrested after he was shot in the leg during the shootout with
Brookline police, Pierce could face capital murder charges in
Georgia in the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Globe staff reporter Marcella Bombardieri contributed to this
story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2046EDT &QL; 
