<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8097 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CRUISE-FILMS-2TAKES-$     04-26 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOM CRUISE, TEAM PLAYER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   Molly Haskell's most recent book is ``Holding My Own in No Man's
Land: Men and Women, Films and Feminists.''  
 By MOLLY HASKELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The anticipated through-the-roof success of the sequel to
``Mission Impossible,'' ``M: I-2,'' should soothe any hurt feelings
in the Tom Cruise camp over the actor's Oscar loss for
``Magnolia.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally the academy swoons over beautiful stars who go into
ugly mode to show they can act, but Cruise's strutting,
pelvis-jutting television sex guru, out to seduce and destroy the
female half of the species, was perhaps too far off the empathy
curve when compared with Michael Caine's kindly doctor, patron of
wayward women, in ``The Cider House Rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The incongruity of the dimpled megastar in vinyl vest and
ponytail running a boot camp for misogynists might have delighted
the critics, but Caine was the sentimental favorite. That is
something Cruise has never been and is not likely ever to be, as he
tackles one steep career cliff after another, alternating between
conventional action movies and decidedly riskier enterprises with
such talented eccentrics as Stanley Kubrick and Martin Scorsese and
Paul Thomas Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the irony is that while playing cocky upstarts too full of
themselves to join the team, in his best work as an actor Cruise
has done just that: allowed co-stars and supporting players to
shine while his own subtler contributions have gone relatively
unheralded.
</P>
<P>
   Oscars have accrued, but not to him: Paul Newman won best actor
for ``The Color of Money'' (1986), ditto Dustin Hoffman in ``Rain
Man'' (1988). For ``Jerry Maguire'' (1996), he was nominated as
best actor, but it was Cuba Gooding Jr. who took home the prize,
winning for best supporting actor. As the flashy sports agent
suddenly seized with moral fervor, Cruise's Jerry played straight
man not only to Renee Zellweger, a fresh-faced enchantress emerging
into stardom, and the bad-attitude brother played by Gooding, but
also to a scene-stealing dad-seeking kid (Jonathan Lipnicki) with
sprouting hair and rimless spectacles.
</P>
<P>
   He partnered Rebecca De Mornay to delicious effect in ``Risky
Business'' (1983) and made a superb supporting cast in ``Top Gun''
(1986) look even better. And that's not to mention other major
awards for which he bears some credit, like best director Oscars to
Barry Levinson for ``Rain Man'' and Oliver Stone for ``Born on the
Fourth of July'' (1989), the other film that won him a best-actor
nomination but not an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   After 1986, flush with the stratospheric success of the
star-making ``Top Gun,'' he might have spent a decade performing
solo turns in bigger and noisier action pictures _ ``Days of
Thunder,'' ``Nights of Lightning.'' Instead, while doing the
occasional blockbuster, he chose to pit himself against seasoned
veterans in artier and more modestly financed projects.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just that he was eager to leap into the arena with
heavyweights like Newman and Hoffman but that he was willing to
play the jerk, to assume the odious qualities so that the
none-too-stellar characters played by his partners might appear
ingratiating and wise. In ``Rain Man'' he plays bad cop to Dustin
Hoffman's cuddly autistic savant. In their odd-couple odyssey _
slick car salesman and the institutionalized brother he kidnaps,
hoping to wrest his inheritance from him _ it is Cruise's Charlie
Babbitt who seems more likely to go over the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Insolent, greedy, rude and impatient, Charlie rants like an
out-of-control child; in the process he makes Hoffman's mentally
disabled mutterer seem more human than such a character, imprisoned
in his armor of compulsive tics, has any right to be.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's Oscar-winning performance is essentially a series of
mechanical gestures, relieved by a sentimental and improbable
``awakening'' to the pleasures of the flesh, while Cruise has to
carry the emotional trajectory of the film.
</P>
<P>
   In his anguished, push-pull relationship with the brother,
Cruise in a sense ``acts out'' the trauma of the family, the anger,
the resentment, the inability to love; and, as he probes, he
provides the film's sense of illumination, making us feel as if we
are grasping the essential mystery of Raymond and their childhood
together.
</P>
<P>
   In the heartbreaking parting, when Raymond, his limited capacity
confirmed, takes the train back to the institution, it is Charlie
who bears the weight of the loss. Having finally made emotional
contact, with his own feelings as much as with Raymond's, he turns
and walks away, shoulders slumped, shrunken in his clothes, as if
he had suddenly lost 20 pounds. Yet the loose-jointedness of his
previously coiled body suggests a sadness offset by growth, the
angry kid having become a man who accepts loss as an inevitable
consequence of feeling.
</P>
<P>
   It's a magnificent, generous performance in a movie that was
voted best picture and won Oscars for almost everyone except
Cruise.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Paul Newman's victory as the over-the-hill pool shark
Eddie Felson in Scorsese's ``Color of Money'' is as much a tribute
to Cruise's refusal to stop and ask for love in the role of
Newman's hustler protege as it is to Newman's own undeniable
charisma. In the darkened dens of cheesy two-bit pool halls leading
up to the climactic playoffs in a cathedral-like Atlantic City
casino, Cruise's Vince is a whirling dervish, determined to show
his stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Twirling his cue stick, dancing around the tables, alternating
between a smug, who-needs-you self-sufficiency and heartfelt
apology (``I was showing off, I'm sorry''), he resists Newman's
strategic blandishments to play possum as the two go toe-to-toe in
an Oedipal battle that only one can win.
</P>
<P>
   As with most stars, Cruise's talent is not without limits. He's
best in roles that cut close to the core of his own temperament and
personality: ones that may even draw on unconscious
autobiographical reverberations, such as _ one might speculate _
the actor's anger at the real-life father who divorced Cruise's
mother when he was a boy and from whom he was estranged for many
years.
</P>
<P>
   Stars become stars on the basis of a mysterious and seamless
meshing of personality and role, and for the adventurous among them
it's a delicate operation to chart a course between type and
stereotype, to play with and enrich the established and successful
persona, to vary its permutations, without going too far afield and
crash-landing in the alien and implausible.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise has done both, embracing stereotype in the superboy
heroes of ``Mission Impossible,'' ``A Few Good Men'' (1992), ``The
Firm'' (1993) and ``Top Gun,'' but in ``Eyes Wide Shut'' (1998)
straying too far from the extroverted charm of that very image.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   You have to admire the actor for taking virtually three years
out of his career at his bankable prime to offer himself up to the
erratic genius of Stanley Kubrick. If the movie proved to be a
disaster of overreaching, it was not Cruise's but Kubrick's fault,
inasmuch as the director wanted to have it both ways: a moody art
film with a Hollywood marquee star to boost the budget and bring in
the crowds. The sexual insecurity and introspective bent of the
protagonist in the Arthur Schnitzler novel Kubrick chose to adapt
is something Cruise simply can't project. The reflective spirit of
an intellectual, self-doubting man, anxious about middle age, is
not in his repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Even in ``Born on the Fourth of July,'' as good as he was as the
wounded Vietnam veteran turned activist, he couldn't quite convey
the spiritual evolution in Ron Kovic's self-portrait, and Stone's
sledgehammer direction doesn't brake for an interior life.
</P>
<P>
   There are very few male stars who would admit the possibility of
sexual inadequacy the way Cruise does in ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' as the
protagonist cuckolded by the desire of his wife (played by his
real-life spouse, Nicole Kidman) for other men. Star cinema, being
inherently macho, means never having to say you're sorry, never
having to apologize (``It'll be better next time''), never having
to own up to a shortage of masculine mojo.
</P>
<P>
   As if to compensate the Cruise character for his rejection at
home, he's a veritable magnet of desire in the world at large,
lasciviously eyed and hit on by both men and women. Women come out
of the woodwork to press his flesh or even, in the strenuously
unerotic orgy sequence, to sacrifice their lives for him.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise is not an interior actor in the brooding Method
tradition. He is an interesting blend of modern and traditional
star characteristics, a mixture of impulse and calculation, of
physical beauty and the resentment it breeds, in both the possessor
and the beholder. The high-testosterone movies are designed for the
action fans (kids) and the butts-and-biceps crowd (more male than
female), but even in the quieter pictures Cruise's directors have
generally understood his physical allure and provided appropriate
glimpses of flesh and curves, removing an undershirt for an upper
body eyeful, supplying form-fitting clothes for that shapely
derriere.
</P>
<P>
   Still youthful at 37, he's more the boy wonder than the
authority figure, a perennial ingenue who can't do the
furrowed-brow thing like Harrison Ford, or capture that actor's
rueful sense of regret; he has the cockiness but not the melancholy
of Bruce Willis, the intrepidity of Mel Gibson but not the irony.
</P>
<P>
   Also unlike the aforementioned, he's generally too fast-track
slick to draw women into the slow erotic dance of great movie
duets. He's not one of those screen stars like Ford, who attracts
by seeming not to know how attractive he is. In a recent A&AMP;E
biography of Ford, friends and commentators constantly reminded us
that he was a carpenter (read: ``real man'') before he was an
actor, and kept insisting, absurdly, that he wasn't
``good-looking'' in the movie star sense _ a defense he has clearly
cultivated to steer clear of the curse of male beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Even expert stage actors like Robert Redford and Paul Newman
have been taken less seriously on the screen because their
extraordinary faces brought suggestions of narcissism, and of
having it too easy.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Cruise's love interests have acted as mom or older
sister to his boyish heroes. Kelly McGillis in ``Top Gun'' struck
one critic as more ``big sister than lover,'' and Mary Elizabeth
Mastrantonio in ``The Color of Money'' becomes his brains and
manager as well as his lover. His inability to grow up, to ``work
through'' that sibling and Oedipal rivalry, seems to have placed
him in a kind of protracted adolescence, yet with the right woman
and in the right situation he can radiate sex appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The sweet and unworldly character played by Renee Zellweger in
``Jerry Maguire,'' and her winningly vulnerable son, bring out the
protective side of him; he becomes a surrogate father himself,
``falling in love'' with the boy, which in turn enables him to take
the first fearful steps toward intimacy with the mother.
</P>
<P>
   The coolness of Nicole Kidman in the films they've made
together, the harsh take-no-prisoners stance of Kelly Preston (his
fiancee in ``Jerry Maguire''), bring out the insecure and
competitive side of him, while softer, sweeter women allow him
breathing room, a space to both expand as a person and recede as a
star.
</P>
<P>
   When Zellweger's headed-for-disaster single mom confesses to her
loving and wiser older sister (Bonnie Hunt) that she's ``met a
guy,'' Hunt reacts warily. As ringleader of a support group/coven
of bitter divorcees, she knows whereof she speaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope he's not good looking,'' she says, and we smile.
We smile because we've seen the guy and how handsome he is, and we
smile because we know what she means. A gorgeous guy can't also be
a decent, trustworthy, marriageable male, at least not in any
real-life story we've ever lived. But just as the writer-director
Cameron Crowe pulls off this deft hybrid of satire and romance,
Cruise manages to make us believe in what might on paper seem
blatantly inconsistent: a slick, go-for-broke agent who suddenly
has an attack of conscience but who, after all, can't quite give up
the game.
</P>
<P>
   And a handsome hunk with dimples to die for who can also commit
to a forlorn little woman who believes in him, thus somehow both
confirming and defying the stereotype of the impossible dreamboat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
