<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8101 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-WHERETHEHEARTIS-     04-26 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WHERETHEHEARTIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN CHARM AND DESPAIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Servie clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Financially challenged small-town Southern folk have been the
butt of Hollywood jokes for so long that it's hard to muster
righteous indignation anymore. Trailer parks and discount stores
have a stereotypical cast of characters all their own, cemented
into our pop-culture consciousness through everything from
late-night talk show barbs aimed at our own president's roots in
Arkansas to the ubiquitous ``Jerry Springer Show.''
</P>
<P>
   But the dollops of truth in these unflattering stereotypes are
turned to the characters' advantage for once in Matt Williams' new
comedy/drama ``Where the Heart Is.''
</P>
<P>
   These are simple people with complex problems trying to come to
grips with them as best they can. They aren't necessarily proud of
their shortcomings, but they're not ashamed of them either. At the
heart of ``Heart'' is Novalee Nation (Natalie Portman), a waifish
mother-to-be abandoned at a small-town Wal-Mart by the baby's
brutish lout of a father, a handsome wannabe musician named Willy
Jack (Dylan Bruno). Broke and homeless, she wanders the aisles,
aimlessly ``shopping,'' only to wind up locked in the store while
she's in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   So she makes the mega-mart her new home, sitting in the park and
exploring the town by day, reading baby books and camping out in
the store by night _ all the while dutifully recording what she
owes her unknowing hosts. Her inevitable delivery attracts unwanted
celebrity as the mother of ``the Wal-Mart baby,'' drawing the
attention of her no-good mother (Sally Field, in a brief
appearance) who then proves her worthlessness once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   For Novalee, life is an endless series of hard lessons.
Fortunately, she surrounds herself with a surrogate family to help
along the way. She's given a place to live by Sister Husband,
(Stockard Channing) who then takes on the mother role. She's a
frisky, spiritual soul prone to apologizing for daily sexual
transgressions in her dinnertime prayers. Hospital nurse Lexie Coop
(Ashley Judd) acts as big sis, although she's not much of a role
model. With four kids and another on the way, the only thing she's
better at than breeding is picking lousy men.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a potential love interest in the local librarian,
Forney (James Frain), a timid brainiac who enters Novalee's life
after helping deliver her baby, given a mouthful of a name in
``Americus.''
</P>
<P>
   In a film crammed with drama _ there seems to be a life-altering
crisis, be it tornado or kidnapping, every few minutes _ ``Where
the Heart Is'' manages to skirt the pitfalls of soap opera
mushiness largely on the strength of its strong ensemble of female
players.
</P>
<P>
   Portman (Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace; Anywhere but
Here), it appears, can do no wrong these days. Though her
uneducated, hopelessly naive Novalee sometimes comes across as a
glamour queen whose shine has been dulled just a bit by greasy hair
and makeup shadows under her eyes, Portman exudes so much charm
it's hard not to root for her. Judd, who's on a similar box-office
winning streak these days, is equally charming, despite her
character's unwillingness to learn from her own mistakes. It's a
quibble many critics will have with the performance, but it's her
gullible optimism that makes the role so believable; real people do
make the same mistakes again and again, especially when it comes to
love.
</P>
<P>
   Channing's feisty mother hen is the strongest performance here;
it's still surprising she shows up only in supporting roles, having
proved herself capable of carrying a picture as well as any of
Hollywood's female elite.
</P>
<P>
   That Williams was able to find humor and heart while never
poking fun probably comes from his experience as executive producer
and creator of TV's ``Roseanne,'' a show that introduced
working-class values and problems into American homes far better
than Williams' ratings bonanza ``Home Improvement'' ever did. And
having family dramedy screenwriting pros Lowell Ganz and Babaloo
Mandel ``(City Slickers, Parenthood, EdTV)'' adapting Billie Letts'
bestselling novel didn't hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   The film's inevitable ``chick flick'' label is well-deserved.
This is a movie about women (Frain's bashful suitor not
withstanding), but that doesn't make it any less enjoyable for male
audiences. Its bigger hurdle is class-related. Anyone who's never
had to hold their car's hatchback open with a broom will have a
hard time relating to what it's like to walk in Novalee's flowered
house slippers. At least ``Heart'' will give them a delightful
taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the Heart Is'' is rated PG-13 for adult subject matter
and strong language. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM: ``Where the Heart Is'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RATING: 4 on a 1-5 scale &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Director: Matt Williams &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Natalie Portman, Ashley Judd, Stockard Channing &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Length: 120 min. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
