<HEADER>
A8102 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-ROSIE-JONES27-COX     04-26 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ROSIE-JONES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golf lesson: Perseverance pays off
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ She's relentless. She's opinionated. She fights for
every stroke. She's the type of player who attaches herself to an
opponent like a thistle to a sock.
</P>
<P>
   She's, well, Rosie.
</P>
<P>
   That's Atlanta's Rosie Jones, the ultimate grinder _ and quite a
successful one. Jones is 12th on the LPGA career money list, with
more than $4.3 million earned and 10 victories during an 18-year
career.
</P>
<P>
   Her swing is too flat. She isn't long enough. But she's an
excellent putter who can pull a string of birdies right from the
depressing depths of a double-bogey. And you be the one to tell
Rosie Jones on the back nine that she's out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is the ultimate grinder, and she's someone who gets the
most out of her game,'' Karrie Webb said Wednesday. Webb, the
LPGA's dominant player, was practicing for the Chick-fil-A
tournament that begins in Stockbridge on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She might not be the longest hitter or the best ball-striker,
but she just finds a way to get the job done, and I have a lot of
respect for that,'' Webb said. ``I don't think she gives herself
enough credit. I don't think she realizes how much respect she has
from a lot of players. She probably has one of the biggest hearts
there is.''
</P>
<P>
   The financial rewards certainly have eased some of the pain for
the 40-year-old Jones. The dream has been worth every extra hour it
takes to limber up joints stiffened by arthritis. Growing up as one
of eight kids in Albuquerque, N.M., Jones dreamed about being rich
and famous, perhaps an actress. Or maybe even a big-time jewel
thief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I don't want to be famous,'' she said, laughing. ``I just
want the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Would Jones' home be more suitably appointed with the trophy
from a major championship on the mantel? Of course. But would
winning this week's Chick-fil-A Charity Championship, her hometown
event now officially hosted by Nancy Lopez, be nearly as
satisfying? You bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never really felt that with my success out here, my
longevity and my consistency, that not having a major really
tarnishes that,'' Jones said this week at Eagle's Landing Country
Club. ``If I was to stop right now, I wouldn't regret anything or
not having a major. ... I look at my score at the end of the day
and I look at the money that I've made at the end of the year, and
I just have to think I'm doing something right.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the toughest time of the year for Jones, with cool
temperatures making it difficult to loosen her aching back. But her
game seems to warm with the weather. She tied for 11th in the
Standard Register Ping last month and tied for eighth in the
Nabisco Championship. She tied for sixth a year ago in the
Chick-fil-A and joined runner-up Lorie Kane in scoring in the 60s
all three days.
</P>
<P>
   If Jones is not watching the Golf Channel this week _ she was
filmed recently for an upcoming ``Profiles of a Pro'' segment _ it
will be the Weather Channel. Surely, a week of the old-time, rotten
``Chick-Delay'' weather might sink Jones as a likely contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weather is a big deterrent for me,'' she said. ``If it's
chilly, I'm fighting some arthritis in my back, and I really don't
have the flexibility. But when the weather turns and it's in the
70s and 80s, I have as good of a chance as anybody. If you had to
break down my money, I make the most in June, July and August.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chick-fil-A has become a better fit for Jones each year.
Good, fast greens and thick rough are what she loves. She's not
going to separate herself from enough players on a bomber's course
with no penalty for inaccuracy. It's tough enough for an older
player used to being outdriven on the teebox. Jones has to make up
the difference with course management and playing within her own
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always had to do that,'' Jones said. ``A grinder? I'm a
lifelong one. I'm used to it. That's what makes me so tough now. It
doesn't bother me to grind a bad round into a good round. I've done
that more times than anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Webb, Jones is playing her first event since the Nabisco.
She was in Albuquerque recently, helping her mother through cancer
surgery. Jones' golf has been mostly social, at either of her two
home clubs, Ansley Golf Club or Settindown Creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I just had spring break, and I'm just picking up
the books again,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of it, Jones doesn't need to study. She thinks that she is
a better player at 40 than 10 years ago because so many mental
mistakes are being eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't let my ego run my game,'' Jones said. ``Certain shots
dictate what you want to do and want you can do. I know what I want
to do is hit an 8-iron 160 yards over that bunker. Now, what I can
do, well, that's another story.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
