<HEADER>
A8107 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-SCOUTS-HNS &LR;      04-26 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-SCOUTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES HEAR ARGUMENTS ON ISSUE OF BOY SCOUTS, GAYS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A lawyer for the Boy Scouts told a skeptical
Supreme Court on Wednesday that the group has a constitutional
right to fire gay troop leaders because homosexuality violates the
message of morality it seeks to impart to youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   But the court appeared equally dubious of the attorney for a
fired leader, who said the Scouts are akin to a public company and
must abide by a New Jersey law that bans job discrimination on the
basis of sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, during the hourlong court session, grilled the
lawyers on whether the Boy Scouts could simply fire anyone who
fails to live up to its strict moral code or, conversely, must hire
female scoutmasters to comply with the state law, which also bans
sex discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the case is whether the Irving, Texas-based Boy
Scouts of America has a First Amendment right to choose for itself
the people it hires to advance its message of morality or if the
group is simply a business that must comply with state laws, like
other companies.
</P>
<P>
   The high court is expected to render its decision in Boy Scouts
of America vs. Dale by early July. The Girl Scouts organization is
not a party to this case.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney George Davidson, pressing the Boy Scouts' case before
the court, said the group bars avowed homosexuals from leading
youngsters because their presence would undermine its
constitutionally protected goal of teaching ``traditional moral
values.'' Calling homosexual conduct ``immoral,'' the New York
lawyer said the organization is a respected teacher of morality as
evidenced by the well-known compliment, ``He's a real Boy Scout.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson said the group does not inquire into a troop leader's
sexuality but believes it can take action if the issue becomes
publicly known, as it did in the case of the fired New Jersey troop
leader, James Dale.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg likened the Scouts' position to the
``don't ask, don't tell'' policy of the U.S. military, which also
drums known homosexuals from its ranks. Ginsburg and other justices
wondered aloud what other people the Scouts could bar from being
troop leaders in its effort to teach values.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living together before marriage is not uncommon these days''
but violates traditional moral values, she said in asking whether a
man in such a living arrangement could be fired.
</P>
<P>
   Justice David H. Souter asked Davidson if the Scouts, in light
of the group's concern with conduct, could fire a gay troop leader
who neither publicized his sexual orientation nor engaged in
homosexual activities. Justice Sandra Day O'Connor asked if a
heterosexual troop leader could be fired for telling his young
charges that homosexuality is not immoral.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson responded that the Scouts organization, as part of its
constitutional right to associate and teach its moral beliefs,
could terminate any troop leader who did not conduct himself in a
``morally straight'' manner or expressed views at odds with the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   But Evan Wolfson, representing the fired leader, countered that
the Boy Scouts of America is a business that must comply with the
state law.
</P>
<P>
   Souter and O'Connor, however, said compliance with the state law
could lead to the unusual result of the Boy Scouts being forced to
accept women into their ranks because the statute bans not only
discrimination against homosexuals but bias based on gender.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Wolfson said the New Jersey law specifically
excludes from its prohibition on gender bias those organizations,
such as the Boy Scouts, that have a sex-specific membership.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Stephen G. Breyer, picking up on his colleagues'
line of questioning, asked if religious organizations would be
required to hire people of different faiths to comply with a state
law that bans bias based on religion.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson responded that religious groups can discriminate based
on faith if religion is their reason for being and their sectarian
message would be impaired if they had to hire outside their faith.
But with the Boy Scouts, sexual orientation is not the group's
unifying theme, added Wolfson, an attorney with the gay-rights
group Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia disagreed, saying that the Scouts' moral
message is a uniting force and might be constitutionally protected.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think that homosexuality is immoral,'' Scalia said.
Having gay troop leaders would be ``a contradiction of its moral
message.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson reiterated that the Boy Scouts, like any other business,
must comply with state labor laws. To allow a company to use the
First Amendment to evade its legal obligations ``would swallow
civil rights laws,'' as the business could then fire employees
simply because their race undermines a message the firm says it is
trying to make, he added.
</P>
<P>
   James Dale, who earned the top rank of Eagle Scout during 12
years of scouting, was fired from his post of assistant scoutmaster
in 1990 after telling a local newspaper he is gay. At the time, he
was a Rutgers University student and served as co-president of the
school's Lesbian/Gay Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Dale sued the Boy Scouts, alleging illegal discrimination. The
trial court, however, threw out his case, ruling that the
organization had a First Amendment right to express its views about
homosexuality by dismissing him.
</P>
<P>
   But the state Supreme Court resurrected Dale's lawsuit, saying
the New Jersey law barring the Scouts from firing gays did not
interfere with the group's right to speak out against
homosexuality. The Scouts then appealed to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Dale, in Washington to hear arguments in his case, said he has
``always loved'' the Scouts and hopes the court will rule in his
favor so he can return to scouting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always been true to myself and I think that's most
important,'' Dale said. ``That's what being morally straight is all
about: standing up for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
