<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8108 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-SOC-INTLNOTES27-COX     04-26 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTLNOTES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Violence ratchets up worldwide
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The boorish, occasionally deadly behavior of fans in
and around soccer stadiums is no big surprise. But there was an
especially grim rash of incidents over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Three persons were crushed to death in Monrovia, Liberia, on
Sunday. A crowd more than twice the size of the national stadium's
33,000-seat capacity rushed in for a World Cup qualifier with Chad.
</P>
<P>
   In reaction Wednesday, the Kenyan federation disbanded the
entire team and fired coach Christian Chukwu, the English newspaper
The Telegraph reported.
</P>
<P>
   Across the African continent in Nairobi, Kenya, fans threw
bottles and other debris on the pitch, and Kenya's qualifier with
Malawi was abandoned in injury time with the score 0-0 and the
visitors about to advance on aggregate 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Two fans died in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, on Sunday before a
match between Vasco da Gama and Flamengo when fans of the bitter
rivals clashed outside the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Ten players on an Argentinian second-division team were
assaulted by fans, and their opponents had to rush them to safety
in the middle of a match.
</P>
<P>
   A star in the Colombian league briefly was held hostage by
guerrillas opposing the government.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, three Turks have turned themselves in to police after
being charged with the fatal stabbing of Leeds fans Christopher
Loftus and Kevin Speight before a recent UEFA Cup match in
Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are passionate (for soccer), but for others it's
more than that, it's even more than a religion,'' Atlanta
Silverbacks striker Ignace Moleka said. Moleka hails from the
Democratic Republic of the Congo, formerly Zaire, and was a student
in Belgium during a terrible spate of fan violence in Europe in the
mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad thing is that people are dying,'' Moleka said. ``For
those of us who grew up outside of the U.S., it doesn't amaze us,
because the passion sometimes goes to an extent where it's out of
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadder still is the reaction of authorities to the tragedies.
Wednesday, the Liberian authorities denied that deaths occurred at
the match. President Charles Taylor of Liberia had threatened his
cabinet ministers with their jobs if they didn't attend. Some civil
servants might have understood that order to apply to them,
possibly contributing to the overcrowding. People scaled fences and
pushed past overwhelmed security personnel to watch the match,
which ended in a 0-0 tie.
</P>
<P>
   But there are hopeful signs. The Argentine players association
threatens to strike unless they get stronger security at matches.
</P>
<P>
   And on Monday, a Spanish court imposed a 17-year prison sentence
on Ricardo Guerra, a member of a group of neo-fascist supporters
connected to Primera Liga club Atletico Madrid, for fatally
stabbing Real Sociedad fan Aitor Zabaleta before the clubs played
in December 1998. Guerra also was ordered to pay $175,000
restitution to Zabaleta's family.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE, GERMANY RALLY
</P>
<P>
   David Trezeguet had two goals, including the winner in the final
minute of regulation, as defending World Cup champion France
defeated Slovenia 3-2 Wednesday in one of several friendly contests
featuring 12 Euro 2000 qualifiers. Slovenia led 2-0 until
Trezeguet, a substitute, scored in the 63rd minute, and Laurent
Blanc equalized with 11 minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, the 1996 European champion, needed an 85th-minute goal
from Ulf Kirsten to even up Switzerland 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, Yegor Titov and Valeri Karpin scored in the second
half as Russia defeated the United States 2-0 in the first senior
international match between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED GETS RUUD AWAKENING
</P>
<P>
   Stung by the failed medical exam of new signee Ruud van
Nistelrooy, Manchester United has called in the striker's doctors
at his current club, new Dutch champion PSV Eindhoven, to conduct
further tests on an injured knee that has kept him out of action
for a month. The club had to postpone a Tuesday news conference to
announce the addition of Van Nistelrooy, 23, signed last week for a
English transfer record $28.5 million. United, which won its sixth
Premier League title in eight seasons on Saturday in a 3-1 win over
Southampton, expects the transfer to be made official in a few
days.
</P>
<P>
   BOYCOTTING BARCA FAVORED
</P>
<P>
   Barcelona's lame gesture in trying to cop out of the Copa del
Rey ostensibly means the Spanish champions will be ready for
Tuesday's European Cup semifinal first leg with Primera Liga rival
Valencia. Barca, which walked off the pitch before Monday's Copa
del Rey semifinal with Atletico Madrid and later forfeited it,
protested that the Spanish federation should have rescheduled the
match. The club has a number of star players away on international
duty or out with injuries, but it didn't express its concerns in
advance. On Wednesday, Real Madrid meets Bayern Munich (2:30 p.m.,
ESPN2) in the other half of the Champions League draw.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
