<HEADLINE>
FIGHTIN' WORDS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``How much can you know about yourself if you've never been in a
fight?'' asks Tyler Durden (Brad Pitt) in ``Fight Club.''
</P>
<P>
   David Fincher's provocative film works on the premise that in
world where we have been anesthetized by consumerism (``The things
you own end up owning you''), you need the .... beat out of you in
order to feel anything. And while his protagonists spend a good
part of the movie brutally pounding each other with bare fists, the
audience is likely to feel it's taken a few shots as well.
</P>
<P>
   The story open with a nameless narrator (Edward Norton) tied to
chair with Tyler holding a gun in his mouth. The narrator then goes
on to recount how he ended up in this predicament, including
setting up the Fight Club. The members of which are men who feel
emasculated by today's society.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a generation of men raised by women. I'm beginning to
wonder if another woman is what we really need,'' Tyler intones.
(Think journalist Susan Faludi's recent book about men ``Stiffed''
_ these guys have no interest in getting in touch with their
feminine side, only expressing their rage, not only with their
fists but in terrorist acts, including a some gross ones involving
food and bodily functions.)
</P>
<P>
   The first rule of Fight Club, according to Tyler, is that you
don't talk about Fight Club.
</P>
<P>
   The first rule of ``Fight Club'' is don't watch it with a date.
OK, maybe if you have as weird a relationship as Marla (Helena
Bonham Carter) and the narrator. (``Marla was like that cut on the
roof of your mouth that would go away if you'd stop tonguing it,
but you can't.'')
</P>
<P>
   The two meet because they are fellow support-group tourists,
meaning they crash meetings of people who have come together
because they are dying of something awful. It's only there that the
narrator, who lives by his Ikea catalog, can express any emotions,
crying into the chest of Bob (Meat Loaf), a former bodybuilder who
has developed breasts (we'll skip the more graphic description)
because of his testicular cancer. (Marla shows up there, too,
gender aside).
</P>
<P>
   Like the tiny scenes of pornographic material that Tyler splices
into children's movies, ``Fight Club'' ends up subliminally
imprinted on your brain. The film is a montage of consumer goods
(Krispy Kremes, Gucci, Ikea, etc.), violence, grotesque images,
including a raid on a dumpster that contains fat removed by
liposuction, which is then used to make expensive soap that is sold
in ritzy department stores (``We were selling rich women their own
fat asses back to them'').
</P>
<P>
   Now, does this make a good film? Yes, but with qualifications.
Fincher (``Seven'') is an immensely talented director but the film
could have been as effective with less. It's a bit strange that a
meditation about excess seems excessive, but that point can be
argued. Nevertheless, along with ``American Beauty,'' ``Being Jon
Malkovich'' and ``Magnolia,'' ``Fight Club'' was one of the more
interesting (even while being irritating) films of last year.
</P>
<P>
   You should be careful who you see it with, however; you could
end up in a fight. &QL; 
(BEGIN ITAL)``Fight Club'' is priced for rental on VHS ($106.99).
The DVD is $34.98 and includes commentary by Fincher, Pitt and
Carter, five deleted scenes and a making-of documentary.(END ITAL)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
