<HEADER>
A8120 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BEOWULF-HEANEY-REVIEW     04-26 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEOWULF-HEANEY-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREATHING NEW FIRE INTO `BEOWULF'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Beowulf'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Translated by Seamus Heaney &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Epic poetry &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Farrar, Straus and Giroux, $25 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite being the bane of English Lit students seemingly since
the invention of the printing press, ``Beowulf'' is a fantastic,
crackling good yarn.
</P>
<P>
   It always was, of course, but it has taken the Nobel
Prize-winning poet Seamus Heaney's astoundingly warm, briskly
paced, blazingly readable reworking/demothballing to bring this
out. He has done what all the stuffy academics with their dozens of
translations couldn't: remind the world that ``Beowulf'' is, first
and foremost, a tale, a good-vs.-ultimate-evil saga that was told
around campfires and hearths centuries before it was ever committed
to paper.
</P>
<P>
   More than a millennium separates us from the unknown writer who
penned this epic poem about a hero, his journeys to the land of the
Danes, and his battles with the monster Grendel, Grendel's mother
and, finally, 50 years later, a dragon. And over the centuries, the
images _ a valiant young hero; an epic journey; flashing swords; a
battle against an inhuman, overwhelmingly powerful, fire-breathing
foe; great castles; armies; minstrels spinning their tales _ have
been codified into our basic imagery of ancient times. ``Beowulf''
is the starting point, the literary Rosetta Stone, the place before
all the other places, the repository and starting line for so many
subsequent, sweeping sagas of dragons and men in chain mail and
heroic deeds done long, long ago.
</P>
<P>
   And now it's actually fun to read.
</P>
<P>
   Heaney's genius lies in how he moves the story along right from
the beginning:
</P>
<P>
   ``''So. The Spear-Danes in days gone by/and the kings who ruled
them had courage and greatness. We have heard of those princes'
heroic campaigns.''''
</P>
<P>
   Compare this to the popular 1973 translation by Michael
Alexander:
</P>
<P>
   ``''Attend!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard of the thriving of the throne of Denmark,/how
the folk-kings flourished in former days/how those royal athelings
earned that glory.''''
</P>
<P>
   Heaney certainly cuts to the chase. He gathers us around him,
tells us in language both simple and profound of Beowulf's epic
life and heartbreaking death, and moves the narrative along with
the grace and energy of a born storyteller.
</P>
<P>
   He writes action scenes with a clarity and sense of drama that
great film directors would envy. His reinterpretation of the epic
battle between an aged Beowulf and the gold-hoarding dragon _ in
which Beowulf is assisted by the brave soldier Wiglaf _ has the
fire and immediacy of an action movie, the dying-light poignancy of
Shakespeare:
</P>
<P>
   ``''Once again the king
</P>
<P>
   gathered his strength and drew a stabbing knife
</P>
<P>
   he carried on his belt, sharpened for battle.
</P>
<P>
   He stuck it deep into the dragon's flank.
</P>
<P>
   Beowulf dealt it a deadly wound.
</P>
<P>
   They had killed the enemy, courage quelled his life;
</P>
<P>
   that pair of kinsmen, partners in nobility,
</P>
<P>
   had destroyed the foe. So every man should act,
</P>
<P>
   be at hand when needed; but now, for the king,
</P>
<P>
   this would be the last of his many labours
</P>
<P>
   and triumphs in the world.''''
</P>
<P>
   Notice how much ground Heaney covers in such a small space:
Combat, triumph, the tragedy of Beowulf dying after his finest
fight. But more than that, Heaney's ``Beowulf'' reads like a story,
an entertainment for a winter's night. All of academia and lectures
and long-winded papers aside, that's the starting point, just as
``Beowulf'' is the starting point for so much literature that has
come after. We are separated by more than 1,000 years from the
original poet, whoever he was, who got this all down on paper, but
thanks to Seamus Heaney, his tale feels fresh today. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman, ``Star-Telegram'' pop music critic, is also a
dedicated student of Irish writers and literature. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8122 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-RDP-2TAKES-     04-26 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-RDP-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIAN'S FATHER SEEKS TO INTERVENE IN ASYLUM CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER and LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Juan Miguel Gonzalez on Wednesday asked a federal
appeals court to let him intervene in the asylum case involving his
son, Elian, and to oust the boy's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez,
from the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   If the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in Atlanta, granted
both requests, the case could become moot and the father and son
could return to Cuba. Attorneys retained by Lazaro Gonzalez said on
Monday that the boy was seized last weekend as part of a plot to
end the case.
</P>
<P>
   The father's brief, submitted by his lawyer, Gregory B. Craig,
condemned Lazaro Gonzalez as ``an uninvited meddler in Elian's
life'' who maintained ``a circus atmosphere'' in which the boy was
``paraded every day in front of mobs gathered in the streets of
Miami.'' The brief was filed in response to a motion filed earlier
this week in which lawyers for the great-uncle asked that a
independent guardian be appointed for Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Craig also argued against a court order sought by those lawyers
that demanded that the boy be kept away from Cuban diplomatic
property where he might be out of the jurisdiction of the appeals
court. ``To Juan Miguel,'' Craig wrote, ``the possibility of taking
Elian to an embassy or hiding behind diplomatic immunity is
non-existent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department also filed a brief on Wednesday quoting a
government-appointed psychiatrist, Dr. Paulina M. Kernberg of
Cornell University's Weill Medical College, as saying after a two
and a half hour visit that ``Elian and his father appear to enjoy a
rich, varied relationship.'' Kernberg wrote that ``a visit by the
Miami relatives would not be advisable in their current angry
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Other visitors are being allowed. One of Elian's cousins flew
here from Cuba on Wednesday night to see him.
</P>
<P>
   Visas were issued in Havana for four friends of the boy, and for
a parent to accompany each child. They are expected to arrive on
Thursday and remain in the United States for about two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Elian spent his second day on Wednesday with his father,
stepmother and baby half-brother at a secluded estate, the
Carmichael farm at the 1,100-acre Wye River Institute, on
Maryland's eastern shore. The family is living rent-free in a house
owned by Nina Houghton, a philanthropist who is the widow of an
heir to the Corning Glass fortune. The Cuban diplomatic mission is
providing their food.
</P>
<P>
   In another forum, the Senate Judiciary Committee scheduled a
hearing for next Wednesday on the raid in which armed immigration
agents took Elian out of his great-uncle's home in Miami on
Saturday. John Czwartacki, a spokesman for the Senate majority
leader, Trent Lott, R-Miss., said on Wednesday that more hearings
may be scheduled later in the week, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign that Senate Republicans do not want to conduct
drawn-out hearings on a raid that most Americans supported, Sen.
Orrin Hatch of Utah, the committee chairman, said he would not call
the Miami relatives to testify. He said he may call their lawyers
and said he would invite Juan Miguel Gonzalez to appear. If not,
Craig, his lawyer, would be called.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on Capitol Hill, the Miami relatives continued to push
for a reunion with the boy. They brought with them several
Cuban-American doctors and psychologists who said Elian should be
permitted to see Marisleysis Gonzalez, the 21-year-old cousin who
helped care for Elian during the past five months, to help him cope
with whatever stress he may be experiencing.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lydia Usategui, a child psychiatrist who was in the house at
the time of the raid, said during a news conference on Capitol Hill
with the Miami relatives that ``he needs to see this family as
quickly as possible'' because the last time he saw them was when
they were being restrained at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   But the affidavit of Kernberg, the government's child
psychiatrist, said that the boy was clearly happy with his father
and that his removal from Lazaro Gonzalez's home ``although clearly
startling and frightening, was in all likelihood not a traumatic
experience producing lasting effects.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Elian had told his stepmother ``that he has a secret
love, `Mary.''' Kernberg continued, ``In my observations of Elian,
there were indications that `Mary' (his cousin Marisleysis
Gonzalez) may be an idealized love, rather than a maternal figure.
His feelings for Marisleysis are similar to the romantic feelings
of a school boy for his teacher or a wished-for girlfriend.''
</P>
<P>
   Kernberg said that a visit by angry relatives ``would likely be
disruptive for the child, who demands a quiet period of emotional
healing from the last few weeks of stress.'' She suggested that the
relatives ``may benefit from counseling'' and that instead of
visits now, they should send letters, photographs and cassette
tapes with messages.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's court filings by Craig and the Justice Department
came in response to a motion filed on Tuesday by the lawyers
retained by Lazaro Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They asked the appellate court to make the Justice Department
allow them, the Miami relatives and a Miami psychologist to see the
boy, and asked the court to appoint a guardian to look after the
boy's rights. Both Craig and the Justice Department scoffed at
those requests as unnecessary, since the boy was now in the custody
of his surviving parent.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez's request to intervene, and his request to
remove his uncle from the asylum case, went far beyond simply
answering the demands of the Miami lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In their filings this week, the lawyers for the Miami family
alleged there was a plot to shut down the case entirely, thwarting
their effort to gain asylum for the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost assuredly, the INS, Juan Gonzalez and Cuban government
functionaries are working on a devastated, displaced and isolated
child to secure a repudiation of his asylum claim and thus mootness
of the appeal,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Miami attorneys, Jose Garcia-Pedrosa, said on
Wednesday that the legal moves by Juan Gonzalez and the government
had been foreshadowed by a Justice Department negotiator. ``The
last thing I asked him was if you get the boy and give him to the
father, doesn't it moot our appeal?'' Garcia-Pedrosa said. ``And he
said, `Yes, it does.'''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress have accused the administration of
colluding with Craig to organize the raid last Saturday and bring
the asylum case to an end. The administration has insisted its only
motive in seizing Elian last Saturday was protecting his safety.
</P>
<P>
   Craig would not say on Wednesday what he would do if the motion
to intervene and to remove Lazaro Gonzalez are both granted. The
court could deny them both, or allow both Juan Miguel Gonzalez and
Lazaro Gonzalez to participate in the case through written briefs
and motions and in oral arguments scheduled for May 11.
</P>
<P>
   Craig's brief said his client should be allowed to intervene
``to speak for himself and to assert his rights as a father'' and
``to speak on behalf of Elian, who has no other suitable
representative in these proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   He wrote that ``lawyers for Lazaro Gonzalez _ and they are
Lazaro's lawyers, noyt Elian's _ seek to use machination and legal
sleight of hand to turn this court into the arbiter of an
intra-family dispute in which the primary antagonist is too distant
a relative to be considered even `extended family' under Florida
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig wrote that while it may once have been proper for Lazaro
Gonzalez to speak for Elian in the period immediately after his
rescue, it was no longer acceptable given the arrival of the boy's
father in the United States. He said the fact that Lazaro Gonzalez
was so ``brazenly defiant'' that the Immigration and Naturalization
Service ``was compelled to execute a rescue by force of arms''
showed that the uncle was not dedicated to Elian's interests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
