<HEADLINE>
LAUNCH OF SPACE SHUTTLE POSTPONED A THIRD TIME 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Stormy weather at emergency runways in
Spain and Morocco on Wednesday thwarted a third try to launch the
shuttle Atlantis on a space station repair mission.
</P>
<P>
   NASA was unsure when it would schedule its next attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest the space agency could reserve use of the Air Force
radar-tracking equipment required for every commercial, military or
NASA launching from the East Coast is May 18. However, NASA is
holding May 3 and 4 for the launching of an unmanned rocket here
with a new National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration weather
satellite.
</P>
<P>
   A swap between the shuttle and the weather satellite is
possible, said Dave King, NASA's shuttle launch director. He said
it would be later this week before a decision is reached.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle itself will require at least three days for
reservicing of its electrical power generation system.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis commander Jim Halsell and crew mates Scott ``Doc''
Horowitz, Jeff Williams, Mary Ellen Weber, Susan Helms, Jim Voss
and Yuri Usachev, a Russian cosmonaut, planned to fly to Houston
early Thursday and resume their training at the Johnson Space
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The astronauts will likely remain in the medical quarantine they
entered before Easter until a new launch date has been selected,
said NASA spokesman James Hartsfield.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of this week's three launch delays was $1.85 million in
unused fuel and labor.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Atlantis and its crew were nine minutes from
liftoff when launch and mission control teams gave up on finding an
overseas runway with weather acceptable for an emergency shuttle
landing.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttle rules require clear weather at one of three runways in
Moron or Zaragoza in Spain or Ben Guerir in Morocco. Such a distant
runway would serve as a refuge of last resort in case the Atlantis
crew experienced a rocket-engine problem late in the 8{-minute
climb to orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Rain ruled out both sites in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   In Morocco high crosswinds at the runway and a cloud deck at
5,000 feet ruled out Ben Guerir. Hopeful that conditions in Morocco
would improve, flight control teams waited until the last moment
before calling a postponement.
</P>
<P>
   High winds at the shuttle's emergency runway at Kennedy also
caused postponements on Monday and Tuesday. The Kennedy runway must
be available to the shuttle crew in case the astronauts experience
an engine problem early in their ascent.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's postponement was only the fifth time in 98 shuttle
missions since 1981 that bad weather at an emergency overseas
runway has caused or contributed to a delay.
</P>
<P>
   NASA is eager to begin the 10-day mission, which is to
jump-start the stalled construction of the yet-to-be-inhabited
station.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantis crew is to prepare the first two modules of the
station, joined in orbit in late 1998, for the arrival of the
Russian crew module in July and the first resident crew in late
October.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
