<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8127 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-U.S.-RUSSIA-ARMS-570&AMP;     04-26 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-RUSSIA-ARMS-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA WANTS TO RESOLVE DISPUTE OVER MISSILES, SAY U.S. OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a second round of intensive meetings with the
Russian foreign minister about the missile defense system that the
United States wants to develop over Russian objections, senior
Clinton administration officials said Wednesday they had detected a
readiness by Moscow to explore all avenues of a possible resolution
to the looming standoff.
</P>
<P>
   But they acknowledged that Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and the
chief Russian arms-control negotiator, Georgy Memedev, had revealed
no significant shift in their opposition to the missile defense
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   In effort to show the United States was standing firm on its
position, the State Department said there was a three-prong
approach described as the ``three D's.''
</P>
<P>
   There would be no ``deferral'' of the missile defense issue,
there would be no ``destruction'' of the Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty and there would be no ``decoupling'' of the treaty that
regulates how both countries reduce their nuclear arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours before Ivanov spoke, the chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., appeared to
be urging that negotiations with the Russians be suspended during
the final days of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   He said his committee would be willing to consider amendments to
the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty but only after President Clinton
leaves office. Helms derided the president for wanting a ``final
photo-op'' with Russians before leaving the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The mission of Ivanov, who was on the second day of a three-day
visit, appeared to be to gauge the political situation in the
United States before Clinton meets with Russia's president-elect
Vladimir Putin in Moscow in early June. Ivanov also met Wednesday
with Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the Republican Party's
presumptive presidential nominee, and had a 90-minute encounter
with 20 Republican and Democratic senators on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they believed the Russians were
judging whether they have to make a decision now and deal with
Clinton or whether they can gamble and wait for the next
administration. Because Clinton would like an arms control treaty,
the administration is trying to convince the Russians that they are
better off to take a deal that they know rather than one they
don't.
</P>
<P>
   As one administration official said, ``The big sell is: `Take a
sure bet now, don't take a risk in the future.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the differences between the Clinton
administration and Moscow is the development of a limited missile
defense that the administration says is necessary to defend the
United States against ``rogue'' states like North Korea and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   National missile defense systems are prohibited in the 1972 ABM
treaty that is based on the principle that the only way to
encourage reductions in strategic arms is restrict ways to counter
them. But the administration argues it is seeking only a modest
change to the treaty, which would essentially remain intact.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, conservative Republicans believe that the ABM
treaty is an antiquated relic of the Cold War and should be
scrapped so as to allow a more robust missile defense than the
administration is proposing.
</P>
<P>
   As they counter the administration on national missile defense,
the Russians are urging Washington to agree to deep cuts in long
range nuclear arms as part of a Start III accord.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the meetings Wednesday between Ivanov and the administration,
the Russians offered two counter proposals, administration
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The first, dealing with curbing the proliferation of nuclear
weapons, involved expanding the current Missile Technology Control
Regime, an international accord that limits the range of missiles a
country can deploy.
</P>
<P>
   The second proposal involved working with the United States to
cooperate on theater missile defense systems that are allowed under
the ABM Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the State Department said the administration was
``interested in and intrigued by'' the fact that the proposals
showed that Russia understood new threats posed by nations like
North Korea and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration also publicly went out of its way to
state that there was, according to James Rubin, the State
Department spokesman, ``no chance of deferral'' of national missile
defense and amending the treaty
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the Russians would like to avoid this issue,'' Rubin
said at the State Department on Wednesday. But Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, who met with Ivanov on Tuesday and Wednesday,
was ``making clear that deferral is not an option,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov said in a speech to the National Press Club that the
administration would be making a ``fatal mistake'' if it went ahead
with the missile defense system. He urged the White House not to
``hurry'' on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Using a quotation from an F. Scott Fitzgerald short story, ``The
Swimmers,'' he said that America had been described as ``the
willingness of heart.'' ``There is every ground to apply his words
to Russia,'' he countered.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's new government requested Wednesday's meeting Bush, who
has made clear he would oppose any Clinton deal with the Russians
that limited the ability of a new president to make his own
agreement with them.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said it was unlikely that an agreement
involving a complicated package of support _ from the Russians,
from NATO allies, and from Congress _ would be ready by the Moscow
summit. ``That's not on,'' said one senior official.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin outlined this deal at the State Department on Wednesday,
saying: ``Our view of what's' best for the United States of
America, and that is to have a treaty that allows us to reduce our
strategic forces with the Russians, get deeper cuts than we have
now, reduce the nuclear danger that way.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, Rubin said, the United States wanted to
``allow a limited national missile defense that would allow us to
defend against a small number of North Korean or Iranian missile
warheads.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the theater missile defense proposal of the Russians,
countries that were under immediate threat _ for example, South
Korea from North Korea _ would have a missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   But such a system would protect not give universal coverage to
the United States, a factor that made it impossible for the
administration to accept, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov fielded questions from senators Wednesday afternoon. Much
of the focus was on the war in Chechnya and the brutal way that
Moscow was fighting. In response, Ivanov asked for help in fighting
terrorism, congressional aides said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, Ivanov, accompanied by Albright, was taken to
the secure conference room, known as the ``tank.'' He met with the
deputy secretary of defense, Walter B. Slocombe, and other
officials.
</P>
<P>
   As an opening gambit for the visit, Albright took Ivanov to
dinner Tuesday night at Les Pinasse, a French restaurant at the St.
Regis Hotel. In doing so, she abandoned earlier plans to take him
to The Palm, which is frequented by Washington lobbyists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
