<SLUG> BC-PASSOVER-RESORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOTEL PASSOVER MEALS LIBERATE JEWISH MOTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT16 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ On the sixth day of Passover, while the
kitchen staff rushed to prepare a lunch buffet featuring ``matzo
pizza,'' Ruth Goldschmidt slipped into a sparkling blue pool with
22 other women for a water aerobics class.
</P>
<P>
   The women had few concerns but keeping count as they flexed
their arms to the piped-in refrains of the song ``We Want the
Funk.'' The children and grandchildren were in the care of baby
sitters, or off ice skating or being entertained by a
ventriloquist; the husbands were playing golf or tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Until three years ago, Goldschmidt would have been home in
Brooklyn, N.Y., making yet another Passover meal from the
restricted set of kosher ingredients permitted for Passover use.
Now she and her husband, Fred, and their children and grandchildren
have joined a growing number of observant Jews who leave their
homes to make the Passover exodus to resort hotels for the holiday,
which ends at sundown on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   These resorts are a far cry and a long way from the Catskills,
where a previous generation gathered to celebrate Passover at
hotels that remained kosher year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish families are now going off to an increasing number of
luxury destinations in Arizona, Las Vegas, Palm Springs, Calif.,
the Caribbean, Switzerland and Italy that cater to the Passover
crowd. Most of these resorts are not kosher year-round, but are
buffed into Passover condition under the watchful eyes of rabbis
and trained kosher chefs. Travel agents who specialize in a Jewish
clientele estimate that Passover travel has increased 40 to 50
percent in the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing like having Passover in your own home. But
the family grows, thank God, and you get older and you just don't
have the strength to make Passover anymore,'' said Goldschmidt, as
a waiter trotted back and forth from the kitchen bearing rib
steaks, grilled tuna and vegetable souffles to a table long enough
to seat all 16 members of the extended Goldschmidt clan.
</P>
<P>
   Three ballrooms in this city's Wyndham Resort and Spa, formerly
the Bonaventure, were filled with tables, some for two, some for as
many as 36, seating more than 1,400 people in all. Babies ate in
laps and high chairs, great-grandfathers watched in wheelchairs,
and boys tired of sitting raced up and down the aisles.
</P>
<P>
   Surveying the scene, cell phone in hand, Sam Lasko, who runs the
family business that organizes Passover holidays in this hotel,
said, ``Instead of having to prepare and prepare, the mother comes
down and sits like a queen.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasko Family Kosher Tours started in this hotel 12 years ago,
with 320 guests. This year he has more than 5,000 guests in four
hotels. The cost? About $6,000 per couple at the Wyndham _ and more
at some of Lasko's other locations.
</P>
<P>
   To the uninitiated, Passover appears to be a one-night ritual _
a Seder dinner during which Jews retell the story of the exodus
from slavery in Egypt. But to more observant Jews, Passover is an
eight-day marathon. The first two days and the last two days are
considered full holidays, when no work is done and the use of
electricity or cars is banned, like on the Sabbath. The whole
holiday is preceded by weeks of preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Like many women, Goldschmidt used to start cleaning her house of
chometz _ or leavened bread _ as soon as Purim, another significant
Jewish holiday, ended, about a month before, said her daughter,
Linda Nordlichter. ``She would vacuum and wash the closets, the
drawers, the drapes, polish all the silver until it shined,''
Nordlichter said. ``When we finally had the Seder, my mother used
to fall asleep. That's how tired she was.''
</P>
<P>
   The hotel Passover is becoming a regular tradition for more and
more families as Orthodox Jewish women work outside the home and
have little time to bake honey cakes or grate horseradish as their
mothers once did. Some see this new tradition as a step of
liberation for women. But at some of the tables here, it sets off a
debate about whether a ready-made Passover dilutes tradition,
cheats the children, or neglects the whole notion of commemorating
the holiday with a personal sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were reluctant because we're a family that really values
the traditions and were afraid they would be lost here,'' said Leah
Polin, from Skokie, Ill., as she held her granddaughter on her lap.
``There's something to seeing and smelling and feeling the hours of
Passover preparation, something that people remember for a
lifetime. We feel it's important for the kids to experience that.''
</P>
<P>
   At home, the night before Passover, children brush bread crumbs
from the windowsills with feathers by candlelight. In a hotel, the
traditions are far less quaint. The process starts a month before,
said Rabbi Mordechai Smolarcik and Rabbi Kenneth Brander, who
together supervised the kosher transformation at this hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen appliances are cleaned with steam guns and pressure
hoses. The ovens and braziers are blasted with blow torches. Behind
the hotel, a tank is filled with 300 gallons of water and heated
with propane. The kitchen trays, utensils and plate covers are
placed in a cage, lifted with a fork lift and dunked into the hot
water, to ensure that any remnants of non-kosher food are removed.
</P>
<P>
   Two freezer trucks full of food supplies are parked behind the
hotel. Keith Stuart, the executive chef, said that he used 1,500
pounds of gefilte fish, 3,150 boxes of matzo, 75,000 eggs and 140
cases of potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   But the menus that Stuart and his minions produce range far from
standard Passover fare. At Tuesday's lunch buffet, guests heaped
portobello mushrooms, brook trout, three-cheese souffle and matzo
pizza on their plates. There was even a macaroni-and-cheese dish.
Pasta is usually considered chometz, but this brand was made with
matzo flour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen it come a long way in terms of what can be produced
with flour and water,'' said Rabbi Smolarcik. ``For many years,
there was no kosher for Passover ketchup.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Passover macaroni comes another new phenomenon:
Orthodox matriarchs who have never been host to a Passover in their
own homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to bronze me some day as the woman who never
made Pesach,'' said Judy Fishman, a grandmother of 14, using the
Hebrew word for Passover. She has been taking her family to hotels
for Passover for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can just play with my grandchildren, and not be in the
kitchen working,'' Fishman said. ``Passover is supposed to
celebrate the exodus from slavery,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they never released the women,'' said her mother, Molly
Bolnick, who is 80.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is the final exodus, it's just fine with me,'' Fishman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want,'' Bolnick said, turning to Alan Katler, a friend
whose family shares a table with the Fishmans, ``you do the
Passover. Next year in Alan's house.''
</P>
<P>
   Katler asked: ``How about Arizona? I say, next year in
Arizona.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
