<HEADLINE>
OPENING OF TROUT SEASON IN EASTERN SIERRA WILL BE BIG ONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL A. ANASTASI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAMMOTH LAKES _ No more waiting. Finally, it is next year.
</P>
<P>
   It is the year you dreamed of when the wind was so cold it
sliced through your heaviest jacket. It is the year you dreamed of
as you sat miserably in the rain and wondered why you drove five
hours and left work early. It is the year you dreamed of when
checking your bait became the highlight of every hour.
</P>
<P>
   This is the year.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's Eastern Sierra trout opener is widely expected to be
the best in a decade or two. Only the sorriest, dorkiest or most
unlucky anglers will fail to catch their five-fish limits _ you
know, the same kind of guy who's the only one in the office not to
get in on that winning $20 million Lotto ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opener,'' said Gary Hooper of Rick's Sporting Goods, an
angling landmark here off the main drag in Mammoth Village, ``is
going to be killer.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick's will be open all night Friday (and offering a $1 spooling
special) and early Saturday for good reason: Last year, an
estimated 50,000 anglers from the San Fernando Valley and
surrounding area fished the opener.
</P>
<P>
   Most make the 300-mile drive after work on Friday (a fact that
has not slipped past the CHP), sleep for an hour or two and wake
before dawn for a shot at catching a fish that costs a buck-fifty
at your local supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, misses the point. The trout opener is a
tradition for many L.A. families. For some, it's their only
significant outdoors experience of the year.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday afternoon, the waters of June Lake were
mirror-like, reflecting the snow-capped mountains that surround it.
</P>
<P>
   And even those who receive speeding tickets should be smiling on
Saturday as a rare combination of weather conditions has created an
ideal trout-fishing weekend.
</P>
<P>
   There is mild, spring weather in the Eastern Sierra _ daytime
temperatures have routinely reached into the 80s in Bishop _ yet a
tremendous amount of water is available for the region's lakes and
streams.
</P>
<P>
   The winter started late and ended early but was unusually
intense. As a result, the snowpack is 120 to 175 percent of normal.
There is plenty of water, little ice and, as a bonus, early
wildflower blooms.
</P>
<P>
   Most important to anglers, the Department of Fish and Game has
had far more time to plant waterways with trout, and they took
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you,'' said John Frederickson of June
Lake,``it's going to be a very easy opener.''
</P>
<P>
   The DFG has planted 1.1 million catchable trout in Mono County
waters and nearly 500,000 in Inyo County. In Crowley Lake alone,
the DFG has planted 450,000 trout, including 50,000 browns.
</P>
<P>
   And those figures don't include fish planted by various area
chambers of commerce to spice things up. They plant mostly bigger,
trophy-sized fish, including many of the famed Alpers trout.
</P>
<P>
   Because the region's lakes have been ice-free for so long, the
fish have been feeding longer. The DFG is expecting fish to be 20
percent bigger than normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Significantly bigger,'' is how DFG biologist Curtis Milliron
put it.
</P>
<P>
   The forecast calls for clear skies with strong winds today and
Friday. As usual, there will be a brief fireworks show over Crowley
Lake to mark the season's official opening, one hour before
sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   Anglers need to be especially careful if they run into ice at
the higher elevations. Many of the lakes that are normally frozen
over at this time of the year are not. Do not be deceived by a
lake's thin ice sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing licenses cost $28.10 this year, an increase of $1.05. A
second-rod stamp, valid in lakes, costs $9.20.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grass is green,'' said Mickey Frederickson, John's wife,
``and the fish are jumping.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
