<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AT&AMP;T-MARKETPLACE-(TRI     04-26 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-MARKETPLACE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T WIRELESS INITIAL OFFERING GETS LUKEWARM RESPONSE 

</HEADLINE>
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Individual investors who have been frustrated in
recent years as they have tried to buy into hot initial offerings
of high-technology stocks may be in for a pleasant surprise on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While AT&AMP;T's sale of shares meant to track the company's
far-flung wireless communications unit will be the nation's richest
initial offering, the sheer size of the deal, 360 million shares,
appears to have conspired with the recent market turmoil to ensure
that the offering will be warm at best.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, AT&AMP;T agreed to sell the shares for $29.50 each,
near the middle of the offering's expected range. That means AT&AMP;T
raised about $10.6 billion. But few analysts expect an explosive
first-day jump.
</P>
<P>
   For individual investors, that may mean that they will be able
to buy the new shares, to trade under the ticket symbol AWE, at
prices close to those paid by mutual funds and pension funds. But
as Groucho Marx might have put it, they may want to be wary of any
initial offering that would let them buy in.
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons the big institutions are not snapping up the
shares, despite the fact that AT&AMP;T's wireless unit is growing by
more than 40 percent a year and has annual revenue of more than $8
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The institutions obviously can be wrong, but they tend to be
wrong when they get into a herd mentality on the upside,'' said
Michael Mahoney, director for telecommunications investing at
Dresdner RCM Global Investors. ``This deal is not getting the
institutions particularly excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney manages about $400 million in communications investments
and said he declined to buy into the offering. He added:
``Individuals usually want to get into IPOs because they read about
these eye-popping first-day trades. That's probably not going to be
the case with this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Scarcity is often a big reason that technology offerings blast
off. Sycamore Networks, for instance, really has developed
innovative optical networking technologies. But it certainly did
not hurt that company's initial offering last fall that the public
had access to only 7.5 million shares, less than 10 percent of the
78 million shares then outstanding. That deal raised $284 million.
</P>
<P>
   Proportionally, AT&AMP;T's offering is not overwhelming; only about
15.6 percent of the wireless shares are to be sold in Thursday's
offering. But the overall size of the deal _ almost double the
previous record of $5.5 billion raised by United Parcel Service in
November _ has sharply reduced the scarcity factor.
</P>
<P>
   But there seem to be at least three other factors that have been
important in putting a small damper on AT&AMP;T's offering:
perhaps-unfounded concerns about the wireless unit's management,
the proliferation of other investment opportunities that has
emerged from the market downturn and the fact that AT&AMP;T intends to
distribute almost two billion additional shares as soon as this
autumn.
</P>
<P>
   When AT&AMP;T announced in December that it would offer the shares
to track the wireless unit, John D. Zeglis, the company's
president, was tapped to run the newly independent operation. That
was a slap to Daniel Hesse, who had been chief executive of the
wireless division since 1997, and he departed for a start-up,
Terabeam Networks, in March.
</P>
<P>
   Zeglis has just about made a career at AT&AMP;T in exceeding
expectations. A lawyer who worked on AT&AMP;T's divestiture of the
regional Bell phone companies in the early 1980's, Zeglis has
encountered skeptics each time his operational responsibilities
have increased. And each time, he has given the lie to the
predictions of failure, succeeding at every level.
</P>
<P>
   But apparently the skeptics have not yet been completely
defused.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal seems to be moderately undervalued, but we have some
concerns about the management turnover and the appointment of
Zeglis and the loss of Hesse,'' said Steven Lehman, manager of the
Federated Utility Fund, which has about $650 million invested in
telecommunications companies. Lehman said he declined to buy any of
the new wireless shares.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The business has been growing quite rapidly,'' Lehman added,
``but the long-standing head of the division was passed over for
what appears to be political reasons. It appears that they just
found a place for Zeglis in one of their most critically important
divisions. In this case the timing is unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney said of Zeglis: ``I never feel that I understand a
vision of what he wants to do the with the business. Even though I
think he's a very talented man, I'm concerned that the role of CEO
is not just to set the vision but to explain the vision internally
and externally. He has some difficulty doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For their part, some investors appeared to have difficulty
deciding to invest in the new AT&AMP;T stock rather than in some of the
many other communications companies whose shares have been beaten
down recently.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, shares of Nextel, a national wireless provider,
have lost more than a third of their value while shares of
Voicestream Wireless, another big carrier, have been slashed almost
in half. Global Crossing, which is building undersea communications
networks, has seen its shares lose more than half their value
recently.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, those losses made the AT&AMP;T deal appear more expensive
(especially because AT&AMP;T refused to reduce the projected price
range for its offering as the market shuddered).
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of the emerging communications companies have fallen
dramatically in a short time,'' Lehman said. ``I'd be inclined at
this point to look for some of those opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But for all of the various concerns, perhaps the most subtle is
uncertainty over how AT&AMP;T intends to distribute its remaining stake
in the wireless unit.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the offering's underwriters exercised their
over-allotment options, which would allow them to sell an
additional 54 million shares, AT&AMP;T would still retain 82.5 percent
of the wireless shares.
</P>
<P>
   In the six weeks or so immediately after AT&AMP;T's announcement of
the offering, many on Wall Street were privately led to believe
that AT&AMP;T intended to distribute its entire remaining wireless
stake to existing holders of AT&AMP;T's common shares, said analysts,
investors and people close to the offeringk.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent months, AT&AMP;T's management has all but decided not
to fully distribute the remaining shares, the people said. Instead,
AT&AMP;T will probably first give holders of its common stock the
option to exchange those shares for wireless shares outright.
</P>
<P>
   Such an exchange offer would obviously allow investors to decide
which shares to own, but could also have a significant positive
effect on AT&AMP;T's cash flow and per-share earnings. Because AT&AMP;T's
common shares earn a dividend while the wireless shares do not,
each share that is exchanged would allow AT&AMP;T to reduce its overall
dividend payments, which totaled $2.7 billion last year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition, as the common shares that are exchanged are
subsequently retired, the company's per-share earnings would
increase (though analysts would be sure to discount the value of at
least some of that rise).
</P>
<P>
   At least two people close to the offering pointed out that John
C. Malone, who sits on AT&AMP;T's board, has had considerable success
with such exchange offers at Liberty Media, his television
programming operation.
</P>
<P>
   According to people close to the offering, the current thinking
in AT&AMP;T's executive suite is to conduct an exchange offer first,
perhaps within six months, and then distribute the remaining
unclaimed wireless shares.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has said it will consider selling additional wireless
shares to the public, but that appears highly unlikely, at least
this year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
