<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASBESTOS-EPA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRACE WILL NOT SIGN AGREEMENT TO CLEAN ASBESTOS-CONTAMINATED
SITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIBBY, Mont. _ Last December, W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. promised to ``do
everything in our power to help the people of Libby.'' Now, the
company has notified the Environmental Protection Agency that it
will not sign an agreement with the EPA to clean two
asbestos-contaminated sites here.
</P>
<P>
   Grace made the promise after the Seattle Post-Intelligencer
reported that hundreds of people had died or contracted fatal
diseases from the asbestos-tainted ore at a vermiculite mine owned
by Grace.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the first P-I articles, an EPA emergency response
team and public health specialists began taking air and soil
samples around Libby.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the EPA said its preliminary testing found high
levels of asbestos in two areas. One was near the center of town,
where Grace packaged the expanded vermiculite, called Zonolite, and
the second was near the mine, where the raw ore was loaded on rail
cars. More testing is being done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The levels are high enough where we want the contaminated
material removed as quickly as possible,'' said Paul Peronard,
EPA's on-scene coordinator, when he announced the test results.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave Grace the option of cleaning up the asbestos or having
us do it and bill them.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, Alan Stringer, Grace's representative in Libby,
said his company would do ``whatever is required'' by the EPA to
remove the hazard.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, EPA announced that Grace told the agency it was
``not interested in signing a consensual cleanup agreement'' to
decontaminate the two sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``EPA's goal remains to complete the cleanup at both sites this
summer and take any other necessary actions to protect public
health and the environment in and around Libby,'' Peronard said.
</P>
<P>
   William Corcoran, Grace's vice president of corporate affairs,
confirmed the company declined to sign the cleanup agreement
``because of the rights we would have to give up if we signed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Corcoran offered no information on what ``rights'' Grace would
lose but said the company is still prepared to do the work.
</P>
<P>
   Grace's displeasure with EPA's proposed cleanup agreement
apparently centers on the methods the agency used to collect and
analyze samples of contamination.
</P>
<P>
   A lengthy letter from Grace's lawyer, Kenneth Lund, to EPA on
April 18 argued about the appropriateness of EPA's techniques and
expressed surprise at the agency's actions.
</P>
<P>
   EPA's reply to Grace a day later said the company had been told
about the testing methods and the cleanup plans on Feb. 3, March 6
and April 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposed removal actions at the site are based upon
current methodologies which clearly indicate a threshold for
removal,'' wrote Matthew Cohn, an enforcement lawyer from EPA's
Denver office.
</P>
<P>
   Grace is challenging EPA's testing protocol on numerous fronts.
Company officials met with high-ranking EPA officials at the
agency's Washington headquarters to question how testing was being
done, not only in Libby, but at hundreds of sites throughout the
country where tons of the contaminated vermiculite was processed
into insulation, lawn products and packaging material.
</P>
<P>
   In EPA's regional office in Seattle, letters and telephone calls
have been exchanged between the company and agency personnel over
the methods used to test vermiculite in various products,
particularly Zonolite chemical packaging material, which the EPA's
tests found to be heavily contaminated with asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   Grace said it hasn't produced Zonolite Chemical Packaging
Vermiculite since 1994. But as recently as last month, the EPA and
the P-I found the material was still being sold in several hardware
and garden stores in the Seattle area.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA is not the only government agency concerned about the
adequacy of testing techniques and the long-established safety
standards for asbestos. In Denver this week, investigators,
scientists and health experts from a variety of federal agencies
met to discuss a variety of asbestos-related issues, including
whether existing exposure ``threshhold levels'' were sufficient to
ensure the safety of workers and consumers. Among the agencies at
the meeting were the Occupational Safety and Health Administration,
the National Institute of Occupational Safety and Health, the Mine
Safety and Health Administration, the Centers for Disease Control,
and the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Libby, health officials and members of victims
groups have raised strong doubts over Grace's offer to provide
medical care for people exposed to asbestos from the vermiculite in
Libby.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have some real concerns about Grace's plans,'' says
Kerry Beasley, board chair of St. John's Lutheran Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grace's medical criteria appear to be so restrictive that many
people who need the care may not qualify for it,'' Beasley said.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital is also worried that there is no money or program
backing the plan, beyond Grace's promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Grace closes their doors, goes belly up or decides to stop
paying, there is nothing these people can do. There is no
protection for anyone,'' Beasley says.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital and the Asbestos Community Advisory Group is
discussing the formation of a Community Medical Trust, says Rick
Palagi, the hospital's chief exeuctive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trust would take money from the government, private
organizations and Grace, if it wanted to help, and make it
available to pay medical and other necessary expenses for people
with asbestos-related disease,'' said Jeanie Gentry, a hospital
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This way Grace will not be in a position to decide who gets
help,'' she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
