r e BC-JANEROBERTSWOOD-INTER     04-26 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JANEROBERTSWOOD-INTERVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANE ROBERTS WOOD'S `TRAIN' KEEPS PICKING UP STEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jeff Guinn c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jane Roberts Wood can't please everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when I meet readers and they tell me, `Write
faster, honey,' '' she says, laughing. ``Well, I'm trying.'']
</P>
<P>
   The 69-year-old Texas native, who took up writing after her
first husband died in 1974, never expected to become the
bestselling _ and beloved _ author that she is today. In fact, she
decided to attempt a first novel 15 years ago pretty much on a
whim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a few short stories that had been published, and I got
such a kick out of that,'' the Dallas-based writer said. ``I'd
remarried, and it was a good time in my life. I just started with
an idea about a young woman going out to be a teacher in West Texas
in 1911.''
</P>
<P>
   That idea became ``The Train to Estelline,'' published in 1987,
which surprised readers and the publishing industry alike.
Everybody, it seemed, fell instantly in love with Wood's creation,
schoolteacher Lucy Richards, who at 17 is old enough to travel to
the tiny West Texas town of Estelline but still young enough to
have plenty of life lessons to learn. ``Estelline'' stayed on
various bestseller lists for eight months. It is now considered a
Texas literary classic, on equal footing with John Graves'
``Goodbye to a River'' and Larry McMurtry's ``Lonesome Dove.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood continued Lucy's story through two sequels, ``A Place
Called Sweet Shrub'' and ``Dance a Little Longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Although her books were much-discussed and analyzed, Wood
remained a mystery. Even now, in the last stages of completing a
new novel and just as the University of North Texas reissues the
so-called ``Lucy Richards trilogy'' in paperback, the author isn't
comfortable talking about herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very strange sensation,'' she says, looking
embarrassed. ``I'd much rather talk about other interesting people
I've met.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed, Wood offers the following:
</P>
<P>
   She and her twin sister, Betty, were born and raised in the
small West Texas town of Memphis. Their father ran a school in a
nearby town, where he insisted that the ``West Texas farm boys'' in
his school learn Latin.
</P>
<P>
   Like many girls of that era, Wood says, she ``went to college
(at Texas Tech in Lubbock) to get married.'' Winston Roberts was a
dashing Navy pilot who wore his flight jacket and white silk scarf
around campus. They married and moved to Fort Worth. Roberts stayed
home to raise their two daughters, but in 1957 she enrolled at
Texas Christian University to pursue a master's degree in
literature.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Roberts family settled in Arlington. Wood
continued her education with a fellowship at Yale, and she taught
at Dallas' Mountain View Community College.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then my husband died,'' Wood says. ``Afterwards, I kept a
journal and wrote poetry as catharsis. I would never let anyone see
that work now; it was too self-pitying. But it taught me the
importance of each individual word. Then I took a writing course at
UT-Arlington. As part of the class I wrote a short story, and I
guess that sort of started things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Olive,'' a short story about a widower bringing a young woman
back to his hometown, earned Wood an A _ and more. Her twin sister,
Betty, had met Jean Stapleton (''All in the Family'') and sent the
famous actress a copy. Stapleton immediately optioned ``Olive,''
with the intent of playing one of the characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jean is one of the very nicest, and one of the most
businesslike, women I have ever met,'' Wood says. ``She told me
right away, `Jane, for every `yes' I've gotten in my professional
life, I've gotten 1,000 `nos.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Estelline,'' however, Wood hasn't gotten many nos. But
instead of concentrating on putting out more and more books, she
has tempered her writing success with a happy second marriage to
engineer Judson Wood, who brought two children to the union. The
blended family lives in Dallas, and Wood has followed the Lucy
trilogy with several short stories, which have appeared in various
magazines. Wood says Stapleton has optioned them all.
</P>
<P>
   Now Wood is almost finished with novel No. 4, still untitled,
which concerns a World War II veteran returning to West Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan to use as the title a line from some World War II song
or another,'' Wood says. ``The music of that era was so good, and I
was the greatest at dancing the jitterbug. I wanted to create a
sense of that time, and how, in those days, people did not put
their business in the street. Private lives meant private.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing we know about Wood's private life is that it will
always include writing _ if only to keep the reporters at bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'll keep writing always,'' she says. ``That is so much
more fun than talking about myself.'' .MDBR/.MDNM/ (Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
