<HEADLINE>
EX-BLACK PANTHER WINS LONG LEGAL BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The City of Los Angeles and the federal government
have agreed to settle a lawsuit filed by Elmer Pratt, bringing an
end to the three-decade legal odyssey of the former Black Panther
whose murder conviction was overturned in 1997 after he had spent
27 years in prison, his lawyers said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't prove that justice works,'' said Stuart D. Hanlon,
who as a young law student in 1974 took on the case of Pratt, known
as Geronimo, and has been with it ever since. ``To me, if it takes
27 years and this kind of legal struggle to get someone out, it
doesn't prove anything about justice. But on the other hand, it's a
resolution that makes sense and lets everybody move on with their
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers would not confirm the financial details of the
settlement, but people close to the case said the total was $4.5
million, with $1.75 million to come from the federal government and
$2.75 million from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   They said the city attorney here, James K. Hahn, had agreed to
that figure on Monday, and it was subject to the approval of the
City Council. The false imprisonment and civil rights lawsuit was
filed by Pratt's lawyers, including the Southern California chapter
of the American Civil Liberties Union and Johnnie L. Cochran Jr.,
who was the original trial lawyer and later gained fame defending
O.J. Simpson, shortly after a state court overturned Pratt's
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   They had threatened a trial that would focus not only on the
prosecution of Pratt, but also on what they called a broader
pattern of harassment of Black Panthers in the 1960s and 1970s and
subsequent cover-ups that they said would implicate officials still
serving in law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't just a story of the past,'' said Mark Rosenbaum,
legal director of the ACLU. ``It was a story of three decades of
cover-up, and we made it clear that we were going to litigate that
and that it would implicate current officials. Nobody wanted that
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Pratt's case has been one of the most prominent lingering
remnants of a turbulent time. He was arrested in 1970 and convicted
in 1972 of the murder of Caroline Olsen, a 27-year-old
schoolteacher, on a tennis court in Santa Monica in 1968. Pratt was
sentenced to 25 years to life in prison and spent nearly a third of
his sentence in solitary confinement. But he steadfastly maintained
his innocence, insisting that he was in Oakland for Black Panther
meetings when Olsen was killed, and that the police and agents of
the Federal Bureau of Investigation hid and possibly destroyed
wiretap evidence that would prove that.
</P>
<P>
   After years of stymied appeals, Pratt was released from prison
in June 1997 when an Orange County Superior Court judge reversed
his murder conviction, finding that prosecutors, during the 1972
trial, deliberately withheld the fact that a key prosecution
witness, Julius Butler, was a felon and an FBI informant.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors initially contended that disclosure of Butler's
status as an informant would not have changed the outcome of the
trial and sought to have Pratt returned to prison. But last year
the Los Angeles County district attorney, Gil Garcetti, citing the
long duration of the case, agreed to drop it.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, who now uses the name Geronimo ji Jaga, returned to his
hometown, Morgan City, La., where he works with a community group
to convert the abandoned, once-segregated school he attended into a
youth center. His lawyers said some of the settlement money, which
is expected to be paid in increments over several years, would go
to that effort. Some would also go toward lawyers fees and expenses
for the long legal fight.
</P>
<P>
   Hanlon said Pratt would have preferred to take the civil suit to
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 52 now,'' Hanlon said. ``I think we felt it was better
for him to have the money and get his life in order and move
forward. He's not a rich man, but now he's going to have money
every month.''
</P>
<P>
   Pratt did not answer a telephone message left for him in Morgan
City. But he told The Los Angeles Times, which first reported the
settlement Wednesday, that while he had wanted to use the suit as a
platform to expose what he called the FBI's ``evil scheme'' of
opposition to the Panthers and other radical groups, ``The wisdom
of my lawyers prevailed.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Miller, a Justice Department spokesman in Washington,
said the department would have no comment on the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
