<HEADLINE>
STARR STILL SAVORING BREAKTHROUGH NASCAR WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Giddy over his first NASCAR Winston West
Series victory Saturday at Las Vegas Motor Speedway, David Starr
never made it home to Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Starr headed directly for Southern California, where he
hopes to make it two in a row this weekend. Starr is at the Santa
Ana, Calif., shop of Embee Technologies, which has signed as his
primary sponsor for Saturday's Pontiac Wide Track Grand Prix 200 at
the California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's victory on the 1.5-mile trioval in Vegas came in only
his fifth Winston West start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm living out a dream,'' said Starr, driver of the No. 35
Team Texas Chevrolet Monte Carlo owned by his uncle, Mike Starr.
``If I never go further _ if it stops today or tomorrow _ I've
lived out one heck of a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I had won in everything up until I got into the NASCAR
Craftsman Truck Series. My uncle, he built the Winston West team
and we've been running two or three races a year. We've been close,
but circumstances always knocked us out. So this is a great victory
for us. It was neat, because as the race went on, we made the car
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr went from 25th-quickest in practice to a seventh-place
starting spot after a couple of late-practice chassis adjustments
suggested by his uncle/crew chief. But when the race started, a car
that had been tight and difficult to turn into the corners suddenly
developed a loose condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toward the end of the race, with like 15 laps to go, they had
a caution,'' said Starr, an instructor at his uncle's Team Texas
Driving School at Texas Motor Speedway. ``We were fifth or sixth
and I dove into the pits. When Mike found out there was only nine
cars on the lead lap, we threw on some left-side tires and
tightened up the car some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last six laps, the car was on rails. I was able to dive
deep into the corner and take it on the bottom and hold it
underneath them in the center of the corner. It was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr also said his pit crew _ all employees of his uncle's
driving school in Fort Worth _ exceeded expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time we had done a pit stop together,'' Starr
said.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was made more memorable by those who were there to
celebrate with him in Victory Lane: Ophelia and Jimmy Starr,
David's mother and father; grandmother Mary Ellen Starr; younger
brother Johnny; and aunt Margie Stinson.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also received the congratulations of a NASCAR Winston Cup
regular after the formal ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny Schrader came up to me and said, `David, this is big. A
lot of people have been talking about you,''' said Starr, 32. ``I
must have talked to him for 20 minutes. He even gave me his mobile
phone number and said to call him if I had any questions. Before
the race started I had asked Schrader a couple of things and he
answered me. But when I won the race, I had a 20-minute
conversation with him. So I'll say it helped my stock.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
