<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUP `SILLY SEASON' FORECAST FOR TMS IS BLEAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Months before the traditional start of Silly
Season, the shape of the 2001 NASCAR Winston Cup schedule has begun
making headlines.
</P>
<P>
   And no, a second Cup date at Texas Motor Speedway is not
included in the latest speculative 36-race schedule. As reported by
``The Charlotte Observer'' and on the ``That's Racin' '' Web site
earlier this week, NASCAR plans to add Cup events in Kansas City,
Kan., and Chicago while maintaining the schedule's status quo
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   That would increase the schedule to 36 points-paying events, and
38 weekends of racing when the Bud Shootout for pole-winners and
The Winston all-star event are included.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the additions of Kansas City and Chicago _ both
1.5-mile triovals each seating approximately 75,000 _ have been
anticipated since the season opener in February. But the notion
that NASCAR now is planning to plug the new racetracks into two of
five idle weekends currently on the calendar is an unexpected twist
for the management of Speedway Motorsports Inc.
</P>
<P>
   SMI chairman Bruton Smith and Eddie Gossage, TMS' executive vice
president and general manager, have been lobbying NASCAR for a
second Cup date since the track opened in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told directly by NASCAR that they have no weekends
on which to add dates,'' said Gossage, responding to the
``Observer'' report. ``I've got to assume from what I've been told
point-blank ... that's not possible. When we've talked about NASCAR
giving Texas its first date _ because we bought this one \Rfrom
North Wilkesboro Speedway\S _ they said there's not any more
weekends left in the year. Too many weekends on the road, and all
that stuff. I would assume that would mean not just for Texas, but
for anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Befitting its image as a family-oriented sport, NASCAR does not
run on either Easter Sunday or Mother's Day. Using this year's
schedule as a guide, that also left the sanctioning body with open
dates on July 16, July 30 and Oct. 29 to allow the troops a chance
to wash their socks. Pencil Kansas City and Chicago into two of
those slots, and only one ``future'' race date remains vacant.
</P>
<P>
   Most series observers had tabbed the Darlington (S.C.) Raceway
and the North Carolina Speedway in Rockingham, N.C., as likely
candidates to lose their spring races in 2001 to accommodate Kansas
City and Chicago. Those swaps largely would have been intramural,
as International Speedway Corp. owns Darlington, Rockingham and the
Kansas City tracks and is a partner in the Chicago facility.
</P>
<P>
   ISC, of course, is run by the family of NASCAR founder Bill
France Sr. His son, Bill France Jr., is NASCAR's president and
retains the final say-so on the schedule being massaged by Mike
Helton, NASCAR's senior vice president and chief operating officer,
and Brian France, Bill Jr.'s son and a NASCAR senior vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage, who is friends with all of the above, respectfully
declined to get into a debate about the long-standing NASCAR/ISC
conflict-of-interest issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they've not been shy about saying they're going to Kansas
City and Chicago, and even \Rmetro\S New York _ which are all
ISC-owned facilities,'' Gossage said. ``I haven't heard anything
else definitively.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do I expect them to do? I'm sure they're telling us the
truth \Rabout two races at TMS\S. I mean they tell you, you listen
and you believe. And they consistently have told me there is no
date to give to Texas or anybody. I guess we'll see. But I think
the fans have made a stronger case for TMS than we could ever
make.''
</P>
<P>
   The DirecTV 500 drew a NASCAR season-high crowd of 223,000 to
Fort Worth on April 2, a total that figures to be topped only by
the Brickyard 400 at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway on Aug. 5.
Also mindful of the 6 million-plus fans who watched the live
network TV telecast, Gossage said he hardly is prepared to accept
that NASCAR again has circular-filed TMS' second date request.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally believe that Brian France and Mike Helton are men
of their words and they'll keep their promises of giving us their
first Winston Cup race,'' Gossage said. ``I'm hoping and assuming
it will come next year. If not next year, the year after. But I
honesty don't know.''  &QL; 
Martin tops vote
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR Winston Cup points leader Mark Martin has edged Formula
One pacesetter Michael Schumacher in first-round balloting for
Driver of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Both Martin and Schumacher received seven first-place votes from
a national panel of 16 motorsports journalists, including this
reporter, who voted Ferrari ace Schumacher No. 1. Martin, who also
has won four of nine Busch Grand National races this season, fared
better in second-place balloting to emerge with a 101-90 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Points are awarded on a 9-6-4-3-2-1 basis for the top six
drivers of each quarter. A final secret ballot will be taken at the
end of the racing season to determine the successor to reigning
Driver of the Year Dale Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   Native Texan and Cup regular Bobby Labonte was a distant third
with 36 points, followed by CART's Paul Tracy, 31; NHRA Pro Stock
leader Jeg Coughlin, 30, and Pennzoil World of Outlaws star Danny
Lasoski, 28. \Nsubheds:Gossage hits the road Harley-Davidson
loyalist Eddie Gossage will break out his 2000 ``Dresser'' and
leather riding gear this weekend to participate in the sixth annual
Kyle Petty Charity Ride Across America.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage, the executive vice president and general manager of
Texas Motor Speedway, has ridden in five of the cross-country
treks, which raise money for children's hospitals. Gossage sat out
the 1996 event, to oversee construction of TMS.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great way to extend relationships with some of the
competitors and some of NASCAR's officials and meet and attract new
sponsors,'' Gossage said. ``I go back to where did Adam Petty make
his Winston Cup debut \RTMS last month\S and the reasons given. One
was the friendship between the Petty family and me. Kyle is like a
brother and Adam like a nephew. There's a professional benefit, but
it's also pretty personal.''
</P>
<P>
   The ride begins with a parade lap Sunday morning around the
California Speedway, site of the Winston Cup NAPA Auto Parts 500.
The 12-state journey will end in North Carolina on May 7.  &QL; 
Speed Club booked solid
</P>
<P>
   Launched in 1994, the National Hot Rod Association's Speed-Pro
200 mph Pro Stock Club finally is complete. Ron Krisher, of Warren
Ohio, became the 16th and final member with a career-best clocking
of 200.17 mph in the Eagle One Pontiac Firebird at Houston Raceway
Park in Baytown last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Five-time NHRA Pro Stock champion Warren Johnson (200.13 mph)
was the first to crack the magic 200 barrier in April 1997.
Arlington's Bruce Allen became the club's 12th member with a pass
at 200.17 mph in the Reher-Morrison Firebird on Sept. 18, 1999, in
Mohnton, Pa.  &QL; 
SCCA Sunburn run set
</P>
<P>
   Texas Region SCCA will contest the 10th annual Abilene Sunburn
Grand Prix on Saturday and Sunday on a 1.7-mile temporary road
course at the Abilene Municipal Airport. Races will be run in seven
groups, with practice and qualifying scheduled for 8:30 a.m. each
day. For more information, check the group's Web site
(www.texasscca.org).
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
