<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' OFFENSE A WORK IN PROGRESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Since Jack Reilly was hired as the Cowboys
offensive coordinator, speculation has abounded as to what the
Cowboys will do on offense next season.
</P>
<P>
   Considering it's the same offense that the Cowboys used during
Super Bowl title years in 1992, 1993 and 1995, one thought has them
looking like the Cowboys of old, dominating with the lead draw,
deep outs and slant passes.
</P>
<P>
   But because it's also the same offense the St. Louis Rams used
last season on the way to winning the Super Bowl, the Cowboys might
look like the Rams, whose running game was made up of swing passes
to their running back and threw a lot of deep passes.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that not even Reilly knows what the Cowboys will
do.
</P>
<P>
   He said a team's offense will depend on what the players can do
best.
</P>
<P>
   Except for veteran stars _ quarterback Troy Aikman and running
back Emmitt Smith _ Reilly is familiarizing himself with the
players.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' minicamp, which begins tomorrow and runs through
Sunday at Valley Ranch, is the first step in that process.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, who was the Cowboys quarterbacks coach in 1997, spent
the past two years in New England. He has never worked with Raghib
Ismail, who joined the team as a free agent in 1999 and led the
Cowboys in receiving last year. Receiver Joey Galloway and tight
end Jackie Harris, both expected to have an impact in 2000, were
acquired in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys offense ``was the way it was in 1990s because of who
they had,'' Reilly said. ``With Emmitt and Troy still around it
will look similar but we don't want to be pigeonholed. We picked up
a few guys in free agency, so we have to see how it all works
together. We really won't know until we do all the minicamps and
training camp and then play some games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have been doing individual drills twice a week for
the past month. But the minicamp will be the first chance that
Aikman, Ismail, Galloway and the offensive line will work against a
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said that's what makes this minicamp so exciting, as
``you get to do stuff and see what works.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys already know what works, considering the presence of
Smith and dominant offensive linemen like tackles Flozell Adams and
Erik Williams, guard Larry Allen and center Mark Stepnoski.
</P>
<P>
   For comparison sake, Ernie Zampese, the Cowboys' offensive
coordinator from 1994-1997 who now serves a team consultant,
believes the offense in 2000 will look more like the Redskins of
today and what the Cowboys did in the past than the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Redskins coach Norv Turner was the Cowboys' offensive
coordinator in 1992 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all the same offense, but they look different when
you see them because of personnel,'' Zampese said. ``The Redskins,
like the Cowboys, have a big, strong downhill runner in Stephen
Davis. The Rams made sure they threw the ball more to \Rrunning
back\S Marshall Faulk. We have a power running game here. I would
certainly think we would look more like Washington than St.
Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   Running the ball with Smith, however, is where the similarities
will likely end. The addition of Harris has the Cowboys planning to
use more two tight-end sets than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the presence of the league's fastest wide receiver
tandem in Galloway and Ismail and the desire to be aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly reiterates that it would be wrong to pigeonhole the
Cowboys offense as one way or another. His overall goal is to do it
all well, throw deep and have an effective running game.
</P>
<P>
   To Reilly, it's a blank screen. But the picture should start
coming together tomorrow.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
