<HEADLINE>
IGNORNING DUNCAN HELPED SPURS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ As harsh as it may sound, the San Antonio Spurs
had to approach Game 2 of their first-round playoff series against
the Phoenix Suns as if Tim Duncan didn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy worked, as the Spurs forgot about Duncan and scored
an 85-70 victory over the Suns that evened the best-of-five series
at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Game 3 is at 2 p.m. Saturday in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan has missed the past six games with a slight ligament tear
in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   David Robinson more than made up for Duncan's absence on Tuesday
as he had 25 points, 15 rebounds and blocked three shots.
Afterward, Robinson said that the constant talk about whether
Duncan will or won't play haunted the Spurs during their 72-70
series-opening loss to the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been kind of a little bit of a distraction for us,
because nobody really knows his status,'' Robinson said. ``We know
he's got a problem with his knee, and it gets swollen when he uses
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us want him on the floor if he's going to tear up his
knee. We don't really know what the doctors are saying, and for us,
at this point we can't worry about it. We just have to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurs coach Gregg Popovich said all his team can do is hope
Duncan improves, because winning back-to-back NBA titles without
him will be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's medically able to go, he's going to want to go,''
Popovich said. ``He's dying right now, he wants to be out there so
bad. But it's just not smart. There's nothing he can do on that
knee right now.''  &QL; 
Walker shines again
</P>
<P>
   Samaki Walker proved again that he can shine in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Walker grabbed nine rebounds and blocked a career-high eight
shots Tuesday night when the Spurs squared their best-of-five
first-round Western Conference playoff series against the Suns at
1-1. Walker had 13 points, 16 rebounds and blocked three shots in
Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Walker is starting in place of the injured Tim Duncan, and the
former Mavericks first-round draft pick is making the most of his
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a series we can possibly win without Tim,''
Walker said. ``Not taking anything away from Phoenix, but in that
first game we felt like we gave that game away.''  &QL; 
Road warriors
</P>
<P>
   After winning six of their last seven regular-season games to
receive homecourt advantage, the Spurs are saying the best thing
for them is to get out of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   After squandering homecourt advantage by losing Game 1, 72-70,
to the Suns last Saturday at the Alamodome, the Spurs must win at
least one of the next two games at America West Arena in order to
bring the series back to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Spurs guard Mario Elie said they can ``definitely'' win one game
in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a lot of distractions at home, including your boys
calling you for tickets,'' Elie said. ``But when you're on the road
you check into the hotel under an alias, and all you get to
concentrate on is your teammates and basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot of fans who call you and try to hassle you,
especially in Utah. They call and leave nasty messages like, `Karl
Malone is going to eat you up.' But when you're under an alias, you
don't have to worry about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs split their two regular-season games played in
Phoenix. They opened the season with three consecutive victories,
then lost at Phoenix, 77-74. They also snapped a two-game losing
streak with a 102-83 victory at America West Arena on Jan. 7. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
