<HEADLINE>
BUSH DEBATES FOREIGN POLICY WITH RUSSIAN FOREIGN MINISTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas met with the Russian
foreign minister Wednesday, airing differences over a missile
defense system and Chechnya but still expressing hope that the two
nuclear powers ``can work together to keep peace in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, who has faced sustained questions about his
inexperience in foreign affairs, the hourlong session with the
Russian, Igor Ivanov, was his second venture into the field this
week. On Monday he dedicated a bridge over the Rio Grande and
shared a stage with President Ernesto Zedillo of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides said the Russian minister had long sought the
meeting with Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee,
who was in Washington for a Republican fund-raising gala. Bush was
joined by his chief foreign-policy adviser, Condoleeza Rice, and by
Paul Wolfowitz, who was an undersecretary of defense in the
administration of Bush's father. Ivanov also brought along aides.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor and his aides said the talk ranged from a
discussion of President-elect Vladimir Putin's goals for his
country, to U.S. investment in Russia, to one of the most serious
disagreements between the two nations: U.S. interest in developing
an anti-missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, like many other Republicans, has said that if the Russians
are unwilling to suitably amend a 1972 treaty on anti-ballistic
missiles, he would back out of the treaty to free the United States
to pursue its own course. Other Republican leaders _ including Sen.
Jesse Helms, R-N.C., the chairman of the Foreign Relations
Committee _ are firmly opposed to changes that might be negotiated
by President Clinton before he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told reporters after the session: ``I explained to him my
position as to why we need to develop a system to protect ourselves
and our allies against a rogue missile launch, against any missile
launch. It's part of redefining a post-Cold War era.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said: ``I made it very clear that I was going to think
in the best interests of the United States. First and foremost, and
the best interest of our country is to figure out how to keep the
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men also disagreed over the Russian military campaign in
Chechnya. Aides to Bush said that Ivanov vigorously defended his
nation's conduct while Bush told him, ``It is troubling for me as a
potential president to see use of force on innocent civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice said afterward that Bush discussed how American executives
would make decisions on whether to invest in Russia. He told Ivanov
that with the struggle in Chechnya continuing it would be very hard
to do business in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting had its light moments too _ when Bush and Ivanov
started conversing in Spanish, for instance, confounding the
Russian translator. Putin, 47, and Bush, 53, are of the same
generation, a fact that seemed to intrigue Bush. ``I think that was
very encouraging,'' he said. ``It's time to redefine relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov later said the meeting with Bush presented ``an
opportunity to deliver our position.''
</P>
<P>
   When his presidential campaign began, Bush made several missteps
on foreign policy, mispronouncing the names of various
nationalities and failing a quiz on lesser known world leaders that
was sprung on him by a reporter.
</P>
</TEXT>
