<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL DEBATE ENERGIZES MEXICAN OPPOSITION CANDIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In the first televised debate of an unusually
competitive presidential election, Mexico's leading opposition
candidate made great strides in his effort to pull even with the
governing party's front-runner, polling experts and political
commentators said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   They said that during the debate on Tuesday night, Vicente Fox,
of the opposition center-right National Action Party, struck a
chord with millions when he called on them to rewrite Mexico's
authoritarian history with a vote for democratic change.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the front-runner, Francisco Labastida, who is
President Ernesto Zedillo's candidate, staged a series of
whoop-and-holler street celebrations in cities around Mexico to
declare victory in the encounter, which was televised nationwide by
the country's two major networks. But a string of newspapers,
opinion pollsters and other commentators said on Wednesday that Fox
had won the debate by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate, Fox, an often rough-spoken former Coca-Cola
executive, reached out with conciliatory language to four rival
opposition candidates who also participated in the debate,
promising to form a pluralistic government that would seek a
peaceful democratic transition without jeopardizing the country's
recent economic gains.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, a three-time Cabinet minister from Zedillo's
Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI, sought to
seize the initiative early in the encounter by presenting himself
as the candidate most likely to bring prosperity to working-class
Mexicans after years of economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the character to make big changes so we can leave
behind this period of belt-tightening,'' Labastida said. ``I
represent the real change.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox scoffed at those claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Labastida is talking to us about change, and he's been
inside the PRI for 37 years,'' Fox said. ``He was secretary of
interior, secretary of agriculture, he was a state governor, and we
didn't see change. It was all just more of the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida has held a comfortable lead in public opinion polls
over Fox since the campaign got under way in earnest in January,
with some surveys showing him with a double-digit advantage. But
several recent polls have shown that lead diminishing dramatically.
A poll published on Monday by the newspaper Reforma, for instance,
showed Labastida backed by 45 percent of respondents, with Fox
backed by 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The other four candidates have only minimal support, the surveys
indicate, yet all six had equal time before the cameras on Tuesday
night. Labastida, as the representative of a party that has ruled
since 1929, was heavily criticized by the four rivals.
</P>
<P>
   One newspaper counted 20 instances of opposition candidates
aiming criticisms at Labastida, who defended himself mainly by
criticizing Fox's recent rhetorical zigzags and his record as
governor of Guanajuato.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labastida looked as if he were surrounded,'' Juan Sanchez
Navarro, the influential patriarch of a wealthy brewing family,
told a television interviewer after the debate. ``His frontal
attacks against Fox suggested to me that he's started to fear that
he may lose the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida had his defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won! We won!'' Leonardo Rodriguez Alcaine, the leader of
the largest labor federation controlled by the PRI, told reporters
as he left the towering office building from which the debate was
broadcast. ``Labastida did very well.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After the televised confrontation, hundreds of union members,
neighborhood leaders and other PRI sympathizers were bused to a
downtown plaza to cheer for Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minutes after the debate, the PRI recycled its eternal
triumphalism,'' the newspaper La Jornada said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Fox's performance invigorated his supporters, its
importance in the broader campaign remains unclear. Ernesto Zedillo
was given an embarrassing trouncing in a 1994 debate with two
opposition candidates and went on to win a convincing victory on
election day.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the debate on Tuesday allowed Fox to
communicate with millions of voters without the mediation of
Mexico's mainstream news shows, whose coverage of his campaign has
been overwhelmingly unfavorable, according to a survey by the
Federal Electoral Institute, the autonomous agency that organizes
Mexican elections.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign coverage by the two largest Mexican networks this year
has been significantly more favorable to Labastida than to Fox, the
institute's survey said. Fox received four times as much negative
coverage as Labastida, the survey said. The networks are licensed
and closely regulated by the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
