<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIREE WITH HIGH DRUG BILLS LENDS A HAND TO GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST HARTFORD, Conn. _ Shirley Kindle, a 65-year-old retired
clerical worker, played a bit part in Al Gore's presidential
campaign Wednesday, but it was enough to win her over to the vice
president's side.
</P>
<P>
   She needs a dozen different prescription drugs each month. All
told, they cost more than $500 a month, which is more than her
Social Security check. To keep up her regimen, she has borrowed
money from her family, although, like many elderly people on fixed
incomes, she sometimes skips certain drugs altogether because she
cannot afford them.
</P>
<P>
   She likes Vice President Gore's proposal that Medicare cover the
cost of prescription drugs. And so Wednesday, after a magazine, to
which she had written a letter about the high cost of prescription
drugs, arranged with the campaign for a ``photo op,'' she posed
with Gore at Pelton's Drug Store here to illustrate her problem.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, she shops around at different pharmacies in her
hometown of Ansonia, and she had already bought her drugs for the
month. But in order to accommodate the vice president's campaign,
she and her son drove 40 miles from her home in Ansonia to East
Hartford, and she re-enacted her purchases at Pelton's, a quaint
family pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the drug store filled a dozen orange prescription bottles
with pills, rang them up at the cash register and declared to the
assembled cameras that her total came to $506.34, more than her
monthly Social Security check of $496.
</P>
<P>
   The event was part of a coordinated effort by Democrats across
the country to demonstrate their concern that drug prices are
soaring out of control and that they are more attentive than the
Republicans to the real-life needs of the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said only that Kindle was helping him to illustrate a
larger problem and that ``as a courtesy'' she had ``aggregated''
her purchase at Pelton's.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Kindle said that she did not mind being a prop in
the campaign, even after several calls from Gore aides who were
fretting that she might be overcome with ``stage fright.''
</P>
<P>
   She is registered as an independent. But as she and her son sat
in a hallway outside the vice president's holding room at a center
for the elderly, she said she decided then and there that she would
vote for him. ``The Democrats usually handle the issues that I
believe better pertain to the average citizen,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her son, Joe, 31, who had taken time off from his job as an
apprentice optician to accompany his mother, said that he is a
registered Republican but that Gore had won him over too. ``It's
amazing how he's taken an interest,'' he said. ``This is something
that's important to me because it's important to my family. He
definitely has my vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore used the event to promote his proposal for offering the
elderly a prescription drug benefit through Medicare, costing $200
billion over 10 years. He also took a jab at the drug industry,
calling it ``out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to the point where the margins are way out of
line with what most other industries and most other lines of
business believe is normal and adequate,'' he said, ``and they're
using the market power to dictate prices that are way above what
the competition would set them at.''
</P>
<P>
   This month's Fortune magazine reports that the pharmaceutical
industry has yielded the highest profits of the nation's top 40
industries. But it also notes that the industry's stock prices are
off considerably, and that this has been the source of considerable
concern at the drug companies _ that any Medicare plan to offer a
prescription drug benefit would ultimately constrain drug prices
and cut into profits. The drug industry worries that whatever it
might gain in new consumers who buy drugs because they are covered
under a government plan, it would lose in profits because the
government would pay less than the prices the companies charge now.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House Wednesday, President Clinton issued a study
saying that prices of the drugs most widely used by older Americans
had increased more than consumer prices in general. The study, by
Families USA, a consumer group, said that prices of the 50
top-selling drugs used by the elderly rose at nearly twice the
overall rate of inflation from January 1999 to January 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seniors living on fixed incomes simply can't cope with these
kinds of price increases forever,'' Clinton said. ``That's why we
should take action to help them, and do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said a proposal outlined recently by House Republicans
did not go far enough. Clinton said it would ``do nothing'' for
those with annual incomes below $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Kindle and her husband, Joseph, 70, a retired painter with a
union pension, earn less than half of that amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``We created Medicare in the first place because we knew it was
wrong for our parents' basic health to be decided by their
wealth,'' Gore said. His plan would allow those age 55 to 65 who
have no health insurance to buy into Medicare, providing free
coverage for low-income recipients and some benefits for those who
would pay $44 per month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
