u s BC-BOX-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     04-26 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE TURNER WAY IS KNOWN AS THE HARD WAY FOR GRANT 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For a boxer, Michael Grant has a bad habit. He drops
his hands, leaving his chin hanging out there like a punching bag,
begging to be hit. But whenever the 6-foot-7-inch, 250-pound
heavyweight is sparring and drops his hands, his trainer, Don
Turner, yells, ``Start the whole round over.''
</P>
<P>
   In assembling a 31-0 record with 22 knockouts, Michael Grant has
learned to keep his hands up. Learned the hard way, the Don Turner
way. The start-the-whole-round-over way.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the fighter who will try to detach Lennox Lewis from
two-thirds of the heavyweight title Saturday night at Madison
Square Garden had to learn just about everything about boxing since
he started studying under Turner in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael was a strong kid, but he didn't have any rhythm about
boxing,'' Turner recalled. ``But it took only two days to give him
balance and get him throwing combinations. He adapted right away,
and I called my wife, Minnie, and told her, `We got something
special here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not long after that, Turner realized how special.
</P>
<P>
   When Grant's early manager, Bill Cayton, wanted Grant to desert
Turner for Kevin Rooney, who once trained Mike Tyson, Grant
refused. Almost any other young heavyweight would have jumped at
the chance to develop under Tyson's former trainer, but Grant stood
up to Cayton and stood up for Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Turner has often said, ``is when Michael showed me how
much character he had.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner liked that. In all his years as a welterweight and a
middleweight who never got close to a title bout and as a trainer
who mostly toiled with lesser-known fighters in New York and
Philadelphia before he was hired by Evander Holyfield, he had seen
too many boxers who lacked character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most guys sneer and talk trash,'' Turner said. ``Some of them
have talent, but no character. Michael's got good morals.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Jim Thomas, the lawyer for both Grant and Evander
Holyfield, Turner is a ``father figure'' for the challenger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don matched up perfectly with both Evander and Michael,''
Thomas said. ``Evander doesn't need to be motivated, he just needs
to be reminded of things. Don would tell him, `You're turning the
wrong way,' that's all Evander wanted to hear. He doesn't need to
be bawled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael's different. He needs that motivation. He didn't know
anything about boxing until six years ago, and Don will tell him
how it really is. When Don told Evander, `You can take Tyson
apart,' Evander really believed it because he knew Don wasn't
trying to con him.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner also told the world that Holyfield would win, although
not many of his listeners believed the trainer who will be 61 on
May 7.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield did take Tyson apart in their first fight in 1996,
stopping him in the 11th round. In their 1997 rematch, Tyson was
disqualified when he bit Holyfield's right ear. Turner had finally
established himself on the top tier of trainers while he was also
developing Grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael lived with me and my wife in our house in Norristown,
Pa., in those years,'' Turner said. ``Now he's got his own home
there.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of Turner's confidence before Holyfield's two bouts with
Lewis, they ended in a debatable draw and a unanimous 12-round
decision for the 34-year-old Englishman. Turner was also in Henry
Akinwande's corner in 1997, when Lewis won by a fifth-round
disqualification.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don Turner's been up against me three times,'' Lewis said,
``and he still has no success.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner laughed that off as irrelevant, remembering that the late
Ray Arcel was in the corner of various challengers during Joe
Louis' reign. During the instructions at midring, Louis once looked
over at Arcel and said, ``You here again?''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Arcel was in the other corner when Ezzard Charles
defeated Louis.
</P>
<P>
   And now Turner has Grant, who emerged as the No. 1 contender
after he stopped Andrew Golota in the 10th round last Nov. 20 after
having been knocked down twice in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never knocked down before,'' Grant said, ``so for me to
come back like that, it stacks some chips in my corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner hasn't had to psyche Grant, not with Lewis already
talking vaguely about Tyson as an eventual opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking past Michael and he don't like that,'' Turner
said. ``He knows Lennox Lewis is a good fighter and a good puncher,
but Michael thinks he can win.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as he doesn't drop his hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
