<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-SPLIT-ASSES     04-26 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SPLIT-ASSESS-950WORDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: MICROSOFT BREAKUP IS A LEGAL STRETCH BUT A LIVE OPTION 
 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The government faces a formidable legal challenge in trying to
persuade a federal judge to split up the Microsoft Corp., but not
an insurmountable one by any means, according to antitrust experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be somewhat of a stretch,'' said William Kovacic, a
professor at George Washington University Law School, ``but I think
the breakup that has been suggested is consistent with the broad
and flexible historical legal standard in antitrust.''
</P>
<P>
   That malleable legal framework in which federal courts have
handled remedies in federal antitrust cases dates from a Supreme
Court ruling in 1959, International Boxing Club of New York Inc.
vs. United States. In that ruling, the Supreme Court declared that
federal district courts have ``large discretion to model their
judgments to fit the exigencies of a particular case.''
</P>
<P>
   The district courts, the justices added, can and occasionally
should adopt forward-looking sanctions _ beyond measures that deal
specifically with the products and practices in the trial evidence.
``Sometimes,'' the court declared, ``relief to be effective must go
beyond the narrow limits of the proven violation.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the courts over the years have been reluctant to break up
companies unless their monopoly position was obtained illegally or
through mergers. Neither of those apply in the Microsoft case. In
his ruling earlier this month, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson found
that Microsoft was a predatory monopolist whose illegal conduct
stifled competition. Yet he specifically noted that the company had
not obtained its monopoly in the market for personal computer
operating systems illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's unfair conduct, he said, was taken to defend its
monopoly position from the challenge of Internet software. That is
quite different, for example, from Standard Oil, which was broken
up in 1911 after the courts found that it had illegally obtained
its monopoly position. Stripped of any niceties, Standard Oil's
acquisition overtures often amounted to: Merge with us or we'll put
you out of business. (Another major corporate breakup _ of AT&AMP;T in
1984 _ resulted from an out-of-court settlement rather than a
court-ordered remedy to antitrust complaints.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition, courts have generally split up companies in federal
antitrust cases when the monopolist was created through mergers,
from Standard Oil and American Tobacco in the early part of the
century to Hollywood studios in the 1940s and '50s, who were forced
to divest themselves of the theater chains they had purchased.
Again, the merger precedent is not one that applies to Microsoft,
which has mostly grown on its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courts have very little experience with splitting up a
monopoly that is not the result of mergers,'' said Andrew I. Gavil,
a professor at Howard University law school. ``It is far easier to
envision where the line should be drawn for the breakup when the
defendant was created through a series of mergers than a company
like Microsoft. I think that would tend to make Judge Jackson more
hesitant to break up Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   The software maker argues that any proposal to break up the
company would be an extreme and radical step. In an e-mail message
to employees on Tuesday, Steven Ballmer, Microsoft's president and
chief executive, said that ``absolutely nothing in the current case
justifies breaking us up.'' Microsoft plans to appeal Judge
Jackson's ruling and is confident that it will win the case on
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In criminal cases, the courts apply the common sense notion that
the punishment should fit the crime. And in federal antitrust
cases, the courts, a legal expert noted, try to ensure that the
remedies are ``a good fit'' with what the monopolist did.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the role of the remedy in a case like this is not to
punish Microsoft but to restore competition,'' said Herbert
Hovenkamp, a professor at the University of Iowa law school and a
leading antitrust authority, who has occasionally been consulted by
the government on legal matters.
</P>
<P>
   According to people close to the proposal, which the Justice
Department and states plan to submit to the court on Friday, the
government has concluded that splitting Microsoft in two is the
cleanest, most effective way to restore competition. The
government's plan calls for one company to have Microsoft's
industry-standard Windows operating system and a second company to
have its Office productivity software business and most other
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the two companies will effectively have its own monopoly
franchise: Windows has nearly 85 percent of the personal computer
operating system market, while the Office software _ like its
word-processing, spreadsheet and presentation programs _ hold more
than 90 percent of their respective markets.
</P>
<P>
   Yet by separating them into individual companies, according to
government officials, the incentives for each will change, thus
fostering increased competition. The Office business, for example,
may well have a powerful incentive to make sure that it runs on
Linux, an increasingly popular version of the Unix operating
system, a competitor to Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his ruling, Jackson referred to the market power
Microsoft derives from the close linkage of Windows with its Office
applications software as the ``applications barrier to entry'' for
prospective rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that is the underlying legal logic for this breakup,''
Hovenkamp said, ``that it removes the applications barrier to
entry.''
</P>
<P>
   The other government arguments for the breakup approach are that
they would require less continuing regulation of Microsoft than a
series of restrictions on the company's conduct, and that such
restrictions were likely to be ineffective in any case.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Judge Jackson will only take the leap to a breakup if he
convinced that conduct remedies will not work,'' Hovenkamp said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
