<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8152 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-GALA-HNS &LR;      04-26 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-GALA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH DECRIES PARTISANSHIP AS HE RAISES MILLIONS FOR REPUBLICANS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
and BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush lamented partisan
divisiveness in the nation's capital Wednesday even as he headlined
a black-tie gala that raised a record $21.3 million for the
Republican National Committee to use against Democrats in the fall
election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,500 Republican politicians, operatives and donors
attended the RNC fund-raiser at the National Guard Armory, hosted
by lobbyists for Republican-friendly tobacco and gun interests.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the gathering that he will end the partisan bickering
and ``restore civility and respect to our national politics'' if he
is elected president. He blamed President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore, the likely Democratic presidential nominee, for
the partisan atmosphere in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton-Gore administration has been the most relentlessly
partisan administration in our nation's history, but sometimes some
in our own party have responded in kind,'' Bush said. ``Americans
have seen a cycle of bitterness, an arms race of anger. ... The
legacy is cynicism, a generic disgust.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were quick to question Bush's sincerity about
civility, noting that a co-host of the gala was Wayne LaPierre,
executive director of the National Rifle Association. Last month,
LaPierre accused Clinton of using high-profile shooting incidents
as justification for more gun control, and charged that Clinton was
``willing to accept a certain level of killing to further his
political agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane attacked Bush for advocating less
partisanship while accepting money from groups such as the NRA that
have slammed Clinton and Democrats. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``For George Bush to be talking about non-partisanship at a
fund-raiser headlined by some of the country's most partisan
interest groups is like his talking about tolerance and then going
to Bob Jones University,`` said Lehane _ an allusion to Bush's
primary-season appearance at the fundamentalist Christian South
Carolina college that until recently banned interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told The Associated Press he has no problem with LaPierre
hosting the gala with a pledge to raise more than $250,000 for the
GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I believe. I support reasonable laws to keep guns
out of the hands of people who shouldn't have them,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris, the tobacco conglomerate and a co-host of the GOP
event, gave $300,000 to the party in the first quarter of this
year. Tobacco lobbyists are opposing efforts by some in Congress to
tighten regulations on the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The gala's hosts also included Charles Wyly of Dallas, who,
along with his brother Sam, funded $2.5 million in commercials in
this year's primaries attacking Bush's opponent, Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the RNC gala he wants to show he can work with
Democrats and Republicans to do ``what is best for America.''
</P>
<P>
   He ticked off a litany of things Gore has said that Bush
characterized as the ``old Washington blame game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week was Earth Day. Unfortunately, for Al Gore's
campaign, every day is scorched-earth day, and it's time to clean
up the toxic environment in Washington, D.C.,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's fund-raiser broke the $14 million record for money
raised at a single event that was set last spring when Bush's
father, former President George Bush, headlined a national
Republican dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush already has set one record this year, raising $80
million for his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also are having a record year. The Democratic National
Committee has raised $26 million so far, and hopes to break the
newly set single-event record at a Washington fund-raiser scheduled
for May 24.
</P>
<P>
   DNC spokeswoman Jenny Baucus said the ``Tribute to Bill
Clinton'' is expected to draw 14,000 people to the MCI Arena for a
concert and barbecue. While the party is expecting some large
donations, Baucus said many of those likely to attend will pay
between $50 and $100, ticket prices designed to attract younger
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our event is blue jeans and barbecue. Their event is
limousines and cavier,'' said Baucus.
</P>
<P>
   On another evening, however, the Democrats are hosting a small
dinner with the president for higher-dollar donors. The DNC also
has hosted a number of exclusive fund-raising events, including a
recent Hollywood dinner that drew celebrities shelling out a
minimum of $25,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday's GOP event, the various Democratic committees
were slightly outpacing the Republicans in fund-raising for the
first quarter, raising about $26.7 million compared to $26.5
million for the GOP, according to a Common Cause analysis of
Federal Election Commission records.
</P>
<P>
   RNC Co-Chair Patricia Harrison said Wednesday's event raised a
combination of hard money and soft money for the party.
</P>
<P>
   Federal election law sets limits on individual donations of hard
money, which is used in candidates' election campaigns; soft money,
ostensibly intended for party-building or publicizing positions on
issues but not candidates, can be given to the political parties in
unlimited amounts.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail Wednesday, Gore took a shot at the
financial ties between Bush and the NRA evidenced by LaPierre's
prominence at the Wednesday gala. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Why does he always do what the NRA says he should do? '' Gore
asked as he campaigned in Connecticut &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Gore has attacked Bush for signing Texas' concealed handgun law
and a law prohibiting local governments from suing gun makers.
</P>
<P>
   The gun issue came to the forefront in Washington this week
after a teen-ager wounded seven children at the National Zoo in
what police believe was a gang-related shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the fund-raiser, Bush's day in Washington included a
private meeting with Sens. Judd Gregg, R-New Hampshire, and Bob
Kerrey, D-Neb., to discuss a bipartisan approach to solving
problems with Social Security. Kerrey at one time supported former
U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, who unsuccessfully challenged
Gore for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also met Wednesday with Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov. Bush said he stressed in the private meeting that the
United States and Russia can work together to ensure world peace.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush also said he and Ivanov held major differences of
opinion on Russia's invasion of Chechnya and amending the
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
