<HEADLINE>
REASON FOR SLUMP STUMPS RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The schedule suggested that it was a good
time for the Rangers to make a move. They returned to The Ballpark
in Arlington on April 17 after taking two of three games in
Cleveland, a series win that gave them both a .500 record and some
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   With a nine-game homestand looming, it seemed like a good time
to assert themselves. Not this time, not this team.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers went 2-7 on the homestand, after a 14-4 loss to the
Boston Red Sox yesterday, dropping to 8-13, their worst record
after their first 21 games since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing because it's like we're getting worse
instead of better,'' shortstop Royce Clayton said.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every phase of the game was lacking in the nine home
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not playing well right now,'' left fielder Chad
Curtis said. ``Even the games we win we're not real crisp.''
</P>
<P>
   The pitching staff had a 5.49 earned-run average, and opponents
averaged 11.3 hits per game.
</P>
<P>
   The defense committed 12 errors, including four in the past two
games that led to six unearned runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go out there and basically embarrass yourself,'' Clayton
said. ``The last couple of games have been pretty lousy.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense hit a respectable .276, but had few hits in key
situations. The Rangers hit .171 with runners in scoring position
the past four games. They averaged 4.4 runs per game in the
homestand and scored more than five runs just once in the nine
games.
</P>
<P>
   Young players such as Gabe Kapler, Ruben Mateo, Tom Evans and
Mike Lamb struggled, but veterans such as Rafael Palmeiro, Ivan
Rodriguez and Clayton also failed to deliver key hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's everybody,'' Palmeiro said. ``It's not just the young
guys learning how to play. We've got to figure out a way to get
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The homestand began with a sweep by the Yankees. That could be
dismissed as not that big a deal, considering the Rangers never
seem to beat New York. With the lowly Minnesota Twins coming to
town, surely things would change.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't. The Rangers lost two of three to the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox followed the Twins, and again the Rangers had reason
to hope. Boston hadn't won a series in Arlington since August 1997.
But the Red Sox also won two of three.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disappointing thing is we don't see any signs of
improvement,'' Clayton said. ``We haven't executed and made the
plays. We've gone backward instead of forward.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
