<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARK'S SHORT START CAPS 2-7 HOMESTAND FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers pitcher Mark Clark got rocked by the
Boston Red Sox yesterday, clear proof it's difficult to pitch with
your head in the guillotine.
</P>
<P>
   The worst-kept secret around the Rangers is that Clark's time in
the rotation is up the minute Justin Thompson is ready to pitch in
the big leagues. The problem is nobody knows when that will be.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Clark to hold down Thompson's spot, all the while
wondering if he's going to get traded, released or sent to the
bullpen. It's a difficult spot to be in and a 14-4 loss to the Red
Sox didn't help matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the back of my mind, this might happen, that might
happen,'' Clark said. ``But, hey, I'm making no excuses. This is
the big leagues. It's my job to go out there every five days and
pitch. I can't worry about what might happen in one week or two
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark failed to make it through the second inning, the first
time in 18 games the Rangers starting pitcher didn't pitch at least
five innings. His performance put the finishing touches on the
Rangers' 2-7 homestand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough homestand,'' designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro
said. ``We had some good teams come in, but we didn't play up to
par. Each player needs to focus on what we need to do to get out of
this and start playing good baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Said manager Johnny Oates: ``When you're going like this,
probably the worst possible thing that can happen, other than
getting one of your key players hurt, is to get four or five runs
behind in the first inning. Physically, the effort is there, but
mentally it's tough to keep it going.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark retired the first two hitters before everything fell
apart. Two-out doubles by Brian Daubach and Nomar Garciaparra
started the rally, then Troy O'Leary walked and Carl Everett
smashed a three-run home run into the right-field seats. A single
by Jeff Frye, a walk to Jason Varitek and Wilton Veres' single made
it 5-0 before Clark could get out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up, up and up,'' Oates said. ``Everything was up. He tried
everything, changing speeds, but they didn't miss. He had a couple
outings where everything was at the knees. Today everything was at
the letters.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach's one-out single in the second followed by Ranger third
baseman Tom Evans' error on Garciaparra's grounder and O'Leary's
single to center brought Clark's outing to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel I hardly got any work in,'' Clark said. ``But
when you give up six runs in an inning and a third, it's hard for
Johnny to stay with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark started the season with two victories, including a 6-4
decision over the Indians in Cleveland in which he gave up four
earned runs in 51/3 innings. But he's lost his past two starts, to
the Minnesota Twins and Red Sox, giving up 11 runs in 61/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get into a difficult spot, I'm trying to make great
pitches rather than be my natural self, go after hitters, say
here's the pitch, hit a ground ball,'' Clark said. ``I've just got
to put it behind me and get back to pitching the way I did the last
five or six years. That's what got me here.''
</P>
<P>
   He's here now, and the Rangers have him scheduled to pitch
Wednesday against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays. But that could be his
last start. The Rangers are hoping Thompson can join the rotation
May 7 against the Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, the Rangers have a lame-duck pitcher in their
rotation.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
