<HEADER>
A8157 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     04-26 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBE BRYANT IS NOT YOUR ORDINARY MAMA'S BOY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With 38 seconds to play Sunday and the Lakers
leading Sacramento by 14 points, Kobe Bryant fought Vlade Divac to
the floor for a loose ball, giving up six inches and 50 pounds to
the Kings center but absolutely nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   This snippet from the Lakers' 10-point Game 1 playoff victory
was like a bulging vein, exposing Kobe Bryant's bloodlines.
Wrestling Divac to a draw, Bryant never looked more like his
mother's son.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you read that right.
</P>
<P>
   We realize you constantly hear the Lakers swingman referred to
as the son of former NBA player Joe ``Jellybean'' Bryant, the
implication being he is a Xerox copy of his father, albeit one that
came out slightly reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the truth is, Bryant wasn't spit out of a copy machine, he
slipped out of his mother's womb. And Pam ``Jawbreaker'' Bryant's
involvement didn't end there.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's keen competitive nature, the wiring that makes winning
as much a reflex action as a sneeze? He gets it from his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most definitely,'' Bryant said. ``My mom is very competitive.
My dad is more the quiet type. He is more laid-back. I'm more like
my mom. When that side of me comes out, it can get pretty ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   True, that. Just ask the Knicks' Chris Childs, who earlier this
month got caught in Bryant's snarly web in the third quarter of a
game at the Staples Center, site of tonight's contest. The two
players exchanged blows before they were separated and sent to
their respective corners, er, locker rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The well-placed elbow to the mouth by Bryant that precipitated
the punches was a little trick he picked up in backyard games
growing up. Joe Bryant never coddled his kid in their one-on-one
contests and neither did Pam.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, hell hath no fury like a mother scored on.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom was tough,'' Bryant said the other day after a practice
pointed toward tonight's Game 2 of the best-of-five opening-round
series against Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   He smiled and shook his head as he spoke. This is how tough his
mother was, Bryant said: When he was 14 years old (and already
6-foot-3), he tried to dunk on her during one of their ``friendly''
games and Pam Bryant knocked him nearly into the neighbor's yard.
</P>
<P>
   If it surprises you that a good portion of what Bryant knows
about basketball, he learned from his mom, well, it shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Bryant might have been the one who introduced Kobe to the
game, but Pam Bryant was the one who fostered the connection when
basketball, a high-maintenance mistress, took Joe Bryant away from
his family for weeks at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was the one who drove me to practices and bought me
(basketball) videotapes,'' Kobe said.
</P>
<P>
   She also was the one who played Moses Malone to his Earl Monroe
when Joe Bryant wasn't around, a task Pam Bryant came to honestly.
Her brother, Chubby Cox, played basketball at San Francisco State
University.
</P>
<P>
   Had she been born a generation later, Pam Bryant might very well
have been the girl-next-door upon whom Sanaa Lathan's lead
character Monica Wright in the movie ``Love and Basketball'' was
modeled.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she was the mold from which sprang the competitiveness
that keeps Kobe climbing toward a summit nobody else can see, so
far in the clouds is it.
</P>
<P>
   Since his starting turn in the 1998 All-Star game, ``everybody
(has been) setting goals for me,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA suits led the way, trying to make him over in Michael
Jordan's image. ``But I have my own goals,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   He won't reveal them, except to say, ``They're higher than yours
(for him).''
</P>
<P>
   His mega-watt intensity? Bryant said he got that from his
mother, too. It didn't come from Joe Bryant, whose focus when it
came to basketball was diffused, like light filtered through a
lampshade.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother raised me to be an individual, to be independent,''
Kobe said. ``She encouraged me to set my own goals, to follow my
own path. I really appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   From his father, Bryant said, he took ``the Afro and the
ballhandling skills.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed. ``That's pretty much it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly. The father, like the son, always firmly
believed he could soar higher, if only his coaches would consent to
having the ceiling raised.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bryant saw himself as a guard trapped in a 6-10 body
pigeonholed in a league that hadn't yet come under the spell of a
Magic man. Joe Bryant dribbled behind his back, launched long-range
shots and, his first few years in the league, in Philadelphia, did
a lot of deferring to Julius Erving and George McGinnis.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Bryant was about to enter his fourth and final season with
the 76ers when his youngest child and only son was born in August
of 1978. Beginning in 1979, Joe spent three years playing for the
San Diego Clippers. It was there that the seeds for Kobe's NBA
career were planted.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 3, Bryant announced that he wanted to grow up to
be a professional basketball player, just like his dad.
</P>
<P>
   Say this about life: It employs a full-circle stratagem that can
be even more seamless than Tex Winter's triangle offense. People
familiar with Joe Bryant's game in his heyday say the son has grown
up to be the player the father always pictured himself to be.
</P>
<P>
   Only larger. And, yes, smaller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I was about 6-10,'' said Bryant, who comes up three
inches short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed my dad stole my height,'' he said,
flashing a smile that turned his face into a reflector for both his
parents. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Karen Crouse's column appears in the Daily News four days a week.
She can be reached at (818) 713-3619. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
