<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8161 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-CAROLINAMOON-TEX     04-26 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CAROLINAMOON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE'VE ALL SEEN THIS PLANTATION BEFORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Carolina Moon'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by Nora Roberts &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fiction &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Putnam, $24.95 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Success can be debilitating, and that appears to be the case
with writer Nora Roberts and ``Carolina Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Moon'' is one of several instant bestsellers following
Roberts' breakout from the romance genre into the literary
mainstream, whatever that latter term means.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Perhaps she has fantasies of being recognized by
critics as an authentic literary talent.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps part of the trouble is that Roberts' 100-plus titles
have collectively sold more than 85 million copies. She's not a
writer. She's her own industry, and she has legions of loyal fans
demanding more.
</P>
<P>
   So, how does one accommodate the readers who have made her rich,
justify an initial press run of 400,000 and produce a book that
will finally satisfy carping critics?
</P>
<P>
   ``Carolina Moon'' ain't the way.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a bad book, but it's not a good one, either. There's
certainly nothing unique about it. ``Carolina Moon'' is 438 pages
of well-traveled fictional territory.
</P>
<P>
   A young woman who once fled to escape her past returns to her
hometown of Progress (nothing subtle there), S.C., where she sets
up a small business and is wooed by a dashingly handsome scion of
the Lavelle family, masters of the oldest, richest cotton
plantation in the county.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, both of them come from dysfunctional families, and
both also have names suited to the sort of TV soap operas where the
women are all named Marissa or Nikki, and men are named Thorn or
Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Carolina Moon,'' our lovers are Tory and Cade _ short for
Victoria and Kincade. Cute, huh?
</P>
<P>
   For melodrama, Roberts tosses in the murder of Cade's sister,
Hope, 18 years earlier. An 8-year-old schoolgirl, Hope was
bicycling to see her best friend, Tory, when she was attacked _ so,
of course, many of the townsfolk somehow blame Tory for Hope's
death.
</P>
<P>
   The first chapter shows some promise as Hope's death and Tory's
mistreatment by her father, Hannibal (another soap opera name), are
related reasonably well. But, even then, Roberts resorts to
laughable cliches: ``Her hair was the color of cornsilk;'' ``When
she rode (her bicycle), she rode like the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the eventual sex scenes are yawners. It doesn't get much
better than: ``He rushed wild kisses over her face, foolish and
sweet as a puppy.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a tiresome, plodding, vastly overlong soap opera set
down South on the plantation; the magnolias and honeysuckles aren't
the only thing dripping here, y'all.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
