<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8163 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX     04-26 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUNOZ PUT ON DISABLED LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Left-handed reliever Mike Munoz was placed on
the disabled list with tendinitis in his left elbow and left-hander
Doug Davis was recalled from Triple-A Oklahoma. Munoz is scheduled
to undergo a magnetic resonance imaging exam today to see if
there's more serious damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what an MRI might show, but the doctors don't
seem to think it's serious,'' Munoz said. ``That's kind of baffling
because the pain doesn't allow me to pull down on my pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Munoz faced four batters yesterday and three reached, on two
singles and a walk. After seven appearances he has a 13.50
earned-run average, and opponents have 11 hits in 18 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully it's minor,'' Munoz said. ``But at the same time, I
do need these two weeks because it's progressively worse.''  &QL; 
Davis over hitter
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers recalled Doug Davis from Oklahoma for two reasons.
First and foremost, they want to give him a shot at being their
left-handed setup reliever. With Mike Venafro struggling and Mike
Munoz on the disabled list, the Rangers are looking for somebody to
get left-handed hitters out late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows,'' Johnny Oates said. ``After a couple of outings,
he might be the one in there in the seventh inning getting
left-handers out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers could still use a left-handed bat off the bench, but
they didn't see any attractive possibilities in Oklahoma. General
manager Doug Melvin has been looking around the big leagues but
said, ``I'm having a heckuva time trying to find anybody
worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Major-league officials said Quinton McCracken, Karim Garcia and
Luis Polonia are available, but the Rangers aren't interested in
overpaying for somebody who might be needed for no more than two
weeks. The Rangers asked the St. Louis Cardinals about Thomas
Howard but were told he was unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said outfielder Rusty Greer is making excellent progress
in his recovery from ankle surgery and both he and Frank
Catalanotto could be back in 2-3 weeks. That would eliminate the
need for a left-handed hitter, which is why the Rangers don't want
to make a big trade or take on a big salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus,'' Melvin said, ``We need to find out what Davis can
do.''  &QL; 
Cordero moving up
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Francisco Cordero is pushing for a more prominent role
in the Rangers bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Cordero, who's being used mainly in the fifth and sixth innings,
turned in his eighth consecutive scoreless outing yesterday,
pitching 12/3 innings. Cordero's ERA is 2.38, and opponents are
hitting .190 off him. Both numbers are the lowest on the pitching
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cordero threw well,'' Oates said.  &QL; 
Thompson target date
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have scheduled Justin Thompson to pitch for the
Double-A Tulsa Drillers on Monday, putting him in line to return to
the Rangers' rotation May 7 against the Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Much still depends on how he pitches, and the Rangers have not
ruled out keeping Thompson in the minors until May 15 when his
30-day medical rehabilitation assignment runs out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll make one more start, and then we'll re-evaluate,''
Johnny Oates said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
