<HEADER>
A8169 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AETNA-HEALTHCARE-ART-     04-26 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AETNA-HEALTHCARE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONALDSON TRIES TO RESHAPE AETNA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT20 and graphic have been sent to NYT
photo/graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ William H. Donaldson is driving hard to
transform Aetna, the nation's biggest health insurer, into a warm,
consumer-friendly company that makes more profits and fewer
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   In his first 60 days as chief executive, he has sidestepped
fights with belligerent trial lawyers, embarked on what he calls
first steps toward healing strained relations with doctors, and
hired a search firm to find a leader for Aetna's health care
business.
</P>
<P>
   But he is under pressure from disaffected shareholders who
played a role in ousting his predecessor, Richard A. Huber, on Feb.
25. These investors want even quicker action to bolster Aetna's
stock, which is languishing in the mid-$50 range after sliding 40
percent over the past year. Barring a takeover offer, which Wall
Street views as unlikely, the shareholders want Aetna to rapidly
sell more assets and use the proceeds to buy back shares.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna reports its first-quarter earnings on Thursday, a day
ahead of its annual meeting in Hartford, and a spokesman for
several institutional investors plans to press their case.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson said on Thursday that Aetna was talking with 30
business partners in 17 countries about selling some foreign units.
He said these assets could sell for $500 million to $1.5 billion.
But discontented investors say the company should sell even more,
perhaps its entire foreign operation.
</P>
<P>
   They are still dismayed that Aetna rejected a tentative offer to
discuss a takeover for $70 a share from ING, the Dutch-based
international finance group, and Wellpoint Health Networks, a
California managed care company, in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have a lot of time,'' said Nell Minow, a
shareholder activist in Washington who is editor of the Corporate
Library, which provides information on shareholder relations and
corporate governance. ``I think we're talking about months.''
</P>
<P>
   Herbert A. Denton, president of Providence Capital Inc., which
he described as a brokerage firm for institutional investors and
who was the host of a meeting of holders of some 25 percent of
Aetna shares in early April, said most investors hoped that
Donaldson, a co-founder of the Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette
securities firm, would please them by delivering more than he has
promised so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect any precipitous developments at the meeting,
Denton said. But he added that among the shareholders he had met
with, ``There was a consensus that they should strengthen the
split-up plan so more value is delivered with more certainty more
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street traders and investors are also watching the results
of Aetna's $1 billion purchase of the troubled health care business
of Prudential Insurance Co. last year. Prudential's health
maintenance organizations lost $327 million nationwide last year,
according to filings by the Texas insurance department.
</P>
<P>
   Since he succeeded Huber, Donaldson, 68, a Wall Street
investment banker and former president of the New York Stock
Exchange, has been trying to shake up the company. He says he will
stay at the helm ``for the duration,'' until the company's problems
are straightened out.
</P>
<P>
   Pursuing a plan to split Aetna into separate publicly traded
health care and financial services companies _ what the company
calls health and wealth _ Donaldson hired Russell Reynolds
Associates, the Chicago executive search firm, to seek a chief for
the health company, which generates half of operating income and
more than its share of problems.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna's U.S. Healthcare unit is under attack in lawsuits across
the country. And important hospitals like the Baptist Health
Systems in southern Florida are resisting sharp discounts and
refusing to renew managed care contracts.
</P>
<P>
   As for its Prudential subsidiary, Aetna will report improvements
for the first quarter. But because of a lag in receiving and paying
medical bills, actual results will not come in until May, said
William McKeever, a health care analyst at PaineWebber Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential's losses at its health maintenance organizations last
year, including $115 million in Texas and $112 million in Florida,
reflected prices that were too low, Aetna said, along with one-time
costs like payments to departing Prudential executives. Aetna has
since raised prices charged by the units.
</P>
<P>
   Successful chief executives are scarce in managed care, which is
just beginning to climb out of a lengthy downturn, and executive
recruiters are hard pressed to name any strong candidates who are
likely to be interested in the Aetna health care post.
</P>
<P>
   So Aetna is also looking at executives in pharmaceuticals and
other health care fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody not immersed in the old way of doing things'' could
be best, Donaldson said. Aetna needs ``an executive who knows how
to deal with 21 million customers,'' he said, and contend with big
changes in the health care market: customers who insist on choices
rather than tight cost controls and a rapidly growing role for the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna needs ``somebody who is politically astute as well,'' said
Mike Kelly, a health care specialist at Korn/Ferry International,
an executive search firm, referring to attacks on managed care in
Congress and a number of states.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to searching for a health care chief, Aetna has
asked Deloitte &AMP; Touche, the consulting firm, to examine its health
care strategies. The board and the new health care executive will
get the Deloitte report, which is expected shortly. Meanwhile,
Donaldson said he was ``well along'' with a previously announced
plan to squeeze payroll costs by $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna has tried to improve relations with doctors, settling a
lawsuit brought by the attorney general of Texas that challenged
managed care practices. But the Texas and American Medical
Associations have attacked the agreement. Donaldson said the Texas
deal was just a start, and implied that Aetna would go further to
smooth relations with care providers.
</P>
<P>
   It may have little choice. Two states, Kentucky and Maryland,
have already banned Aetna's so-called ``all products'' rule that
requires doctors who treat any patients insured by the company to
also accept the lowest-paying members of Aetna's health maintenance
organizations. Other states are considering similar bills. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
