<HEADER>
A8172 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-SHO-JACOBSEN-HNS &LR;      04-26 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SHO-JACOBSEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAYNE CUSTRED  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
It's still all about golf for Peter Jacobsen.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's all I know,'' Jacobsen said with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   He plays less tournament golf than he has in the past, choosing
instead to devote more time to family and his golf-related
businesses, like his course design company. But his love of the
game hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still fun,'' Jacobsen said. ``It's still golf.''
</P>
<P>
   It's why Jacobsen truly enjoyed himself during the Shell Houston
Open pro-am Wednesday, yukking it up with his amateur partners,
signing autographs and cracking jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Some pros merely suffer through the long pro-am rounds with
high-handicappers. Not Jake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, they're out there having fun and they're all good guys,''
Jacobsen said.
</P>
<P>
   But while the magic is still very much there for Jacobsen, the
music is now gone. The biggest thing missing from Jacobsen's many
golf-related ventures this year is his role as the lead singer of
the musical group Jake Trout and the Flounders.
</P>
<P>
   That ended when Payne Stewart's plane went down in a South
Dakota field just days before the Tour Championship in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Payne gone, it's really over,'' Jacobsen said. ``It's so
sad. The recording company is thinking about re-releasing our last
album as a tribute to Payne. But I'm not sure what's going to
happen. I just know we had so much fun doing it. Payne loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Jacobsen finds it hard to believe that just last year,
he and his fellow Flounders _ Stewart and Mark Lye _ were in the
recording studio, working on their second album and giggling like
small schoolboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd look at each other and laugh and say, `Can you believe
we're in here recording with people like Graham Nash, Alice Cooper
and REO Speedwagon?''' Jacobsen said. ``When we were recording, it
was such an emotional high for all of us. Music was such a passion
of ours.''
</P>
<P>
   As fans at the SHO came to know. At last year's tournament,
Stewart and Jacobsen spent several nights singing at a local
watering hole with the popular Austin-based band Duck Soup. In
fact, their impromptu appearances on stage were one of the things
Stewart and Jacobsen looked forward to every year in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a blast,'' Jacobsen said. ``I even used to bring
my guitar on the road. But since Payne died, I just don't have the
feel. Payne was always larger than life.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Jacobsen, the other areas of his golfing life
keep him busy, leaving little time to dwell on what's gone. He and
design partner Jim Hardy are putting the finishing touches on their
latest effort, a 36-hole public tract located on U.S. 290 off
Spring Cypress Road in Northwest Houston known as Black Horse.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen said 15 holes on the north course are now ready to go,
and he hopes to have the entire course ready for play by late
summer. The south tract should be open in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's one of the most unique courses in the United
States,'' Jacobsen said. ``You feel like you're in South Carolina
low country and the Pacific Northwest at the same time. It's really
cool. There are such beautiful trees on that property, and it's
just a very unique, interesting project.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the competitive fires might not be burning as
brightly as they once did, but Jacobsen would still like to make a
run at one more victory.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps take one more stab at finding the music again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duck Soup's playing again this week,'' Jacobsen said. ``I
think I might go over tonight and sing a little. I think it might
be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
