<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-PRIVATE-JAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE COMPANY TO PULL OUT OF OPERATING TROUBLED PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
   By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wackenhut Corrections Corp., the world's largest private
for-profit prison company, announced Wednesday that it was
abandoning a contract to run a juvenile prison in Louisiana after a
New Orleans judge and the Justice Department found that the inmates
were being physically abused and deprived of adequate food and
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Wackenhut said it had informed the Louisiana Department of
Public Safety and Corrections that it intended to seek bids from
other states and the federal government to convert the juvenile
prison into one for adults.
</P>
<P>
   What will happen to the 226 boys at the prison, at Jena in
central Louisiana, is unclear. In a press release, Wackenhut said
it would ``cooperate fully'' with the authorities ``to ensure an
orderly transition of the juvenile residents currently housed at
the facility to other suitable facilities over a period of several
months.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Louisiana Department of Public Safety and
Corrections did not return phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Mark Doherty of the New Orleans Juvenile Court, who has
released 11 boys he sentenced because of the conditions at Jena,
said, ``This isn't a victory for me, but for the kids and for
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Doherty has been holding hearings on the prison and has
denounced Wackenhut for depriving the boys of adequate food and
warm clothing and allowing physical abuse by the guards.
</P>
<P>
   On April 5, the Louisiana Department of Public Safety and
Corrections took over the prison after a state investigation
discovered that part of a videotape that reportedly showed abuse by
a guard was missing.
</P>
<P>
   Wackenhut said that it had made ``extensive improvements'' at
Jena as a result of the criticism but that a series of lawsuits
over conditions at Jena and other juvenile prisons in Louisiana had
made operating Jena very difficult.
</P>
<P>
   David Utter, the director of the Juvenile Justice Project of
Louisiana, which has sued Wackenhut and Louisiana, said,
``Privatization has been a failure in Louisiana and the sooner we
end that experiment the better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
