<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8180 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TAUBMAN-AUCTION-1STLD     04-26 1354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAUBMAN-AUCTION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNIGHT ERRANT OR ERRING? SOTHEBY'S TALE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Calif.)  (CORRECTS to ``Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania''
in 13th graf) 
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes fairy tales do not have happy endings, even for
knights in shining armor. That lesson should come as no surprise to
A. Alfred Taubman, the shopping mall magnate who has made a second
career out of rescuing companies in distress from the arms of
unwelcome suitors.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, however, could have dreamed up a tale like that of
Sotheby's, the venerable auction house that Taubman saved in 1983.
As if by magic, Sotheby's recovered, then prospered, under
Taubman's reign as chairman. It hit another rough patch in the
early 1990s, along with the rest of his empire. Then, Sotheby's
rebounded once more _ until federal investigators intervened.
</P>
<P>
   Taubman, 75, resigned in February as chairman and is now
stepping down as a director of Sotheby's, with his armor tarnished.
And the Sotheby's story threatens to overshadow a life that might
well qualify as a Horatio Alger story come true.
</P>
<P>
   Government prosecutors are investigating whether, in 1995, and
perhaps as early as 1992, Sotheby's conspired with its chief rival,
Christie's, to split business and fix commissions. Christie's has
as much as acknowledged antitrust violations by entering a
government program that promises leniency to the first conspirator
in antitrust cases to confess. Scores of customers who contend that
they were grossly overcharged have sued both auction houses.
</P>
<P>
   And fingers are being pointed at Taubman. Prosecutors have been
told that he and the former chairman of Christie's dreamed up the
commission-fixing scheme and ordered their executives to carry it
out, according to people involved in the case. No one, however, has
been charged, and much about the investigation remains murky.
</P>
<P>
   Taubman, while declining to be interviewed, has adamantly denied
any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   His son Robert was to replace him as a director at a shareholder
meeting that was set for Wednesday in London. But the meeting was
suddenly postponed on Tuesday because the company's largest outside
shareholder, Ronald Baron, objected to the continuing Taubman
influence. Baron's firm, Baron Capital Management, owns about 38
percent Sotheby's; the senior Taubman still owns about 22 percent
of Sotheby's and has so-called supervoting rights that give him
control of the board.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time that Taubman's knight errantry has
landed him in trouble. His rescue of the Washington
department-store chain Woodward &AMP; Lothrop cost him hundreds of
millions of dollars and ended in bankruptcy in 1994. Macy's, the
department store in which he had a major stake, also went bankrupt,
in 1992. And he went into New York City real estate in the late
1980s, just before the local economy swooned.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the early '90s recession hurt his department stores
and shopping malls and slammed Sotheby's, where auction sales, and
profits, plunged. In 1992 Taubman began trying to raise cash,
selling off some of his depressed Sotheby's stock, some art works
and, eventually, a major stake in his malls. All this occurred
during the period now under investigation by prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the financial pressures he faced, Taubman's friends
and business associates say they cannot believe that he would have
done anything illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't recall a single instance in which anyone has said that
he cut a corner or did anything inappropriate,'' said one friend,
Richard A. Manoogian, chairman of Masco Corp. in Detroit. ``I just
can't believe that Sotheby's was that important in the overall
scheme of things that it would be the one area in which he would do
something improper.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of immigrants from Germany (the initial A. stands for
Adolph), Taubman studied architecture at the University of Michigan
but never graduated. In 1950, he borrowed $5,000 and began building
on a small scale, a bridal shop here, a shopping strip there.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two decades, the shopping centers grew bigger and
grander until they turned into the glossy regional malls. Peter
Linneman, a professor at the Wharton School of the University of
Pennsylvania, said that it was Taubman who ``took the shopping
center from a sort of schlocky product in the 1950s and 1960s into
very creative and exciting places of business and of suburban
activity.''
</P>
<P>
   He became famous in the business world for his good eye, his
attention to detail _ and his bluntness. Leslie H. Wexner, founder
of Limited Inc., likes to tell the story of the first time they met
when Taubman summoned him to Detroit in the early 1970s. They
climbed aboard a helicopter and visited one mall after another.
</P>
<P>
   Over lunch, Taubman ordered Wexner to fix up his stores, which
he called ``a blight on my shopping centers.'' Wexner says now that
he was ``really mad,'' but eventually realized that Taubman was
right.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until Taubman reached his 50s, though, that he
developed a reputation as an investment whiz after putting together
what turned out to be one of the real estate deals of the century:
the purchase of the Irvine Ranch, then being developed in Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   Taubman was invited by some members of the Irvine family to come
in as a white knight and rescue the 77,000-acre property from Mobil
Corp., which had won a bidding war for it. He assembled a band of
his rich friends, who bought it for $337 million in 1977. When they
sold out six years later, Taubman and his friends had scored a
profit of more than $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   That was where the cash came from to buy Sotheby's, the English
auction house, which was founded in 1744. Having expanded too
rapidly in the late 1970s, it was forced after an art market slump
to fire half its staff and started losing money. A pair of U.S.
corporate raiders began to buy up shares, sending shudders though
the ranks of the titled gentlemen and Old Etonians who had always
run the place.
</P>
<P>
   Taubman, once again, looked like a white knight. He may have
been another rich U.S. businessman, complete with a perpetual tan,
constant cigar and a beautiful young second wife, but at least he
wasn't a breakup specialist. And he had artistic connections. A
collector himself, he had been a Sotheby's customer, a force at the
Detroit Institute of Arts and a patron of the Whitney Museum of
American Art.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to bid by Sotheby's directors, Taubman once again put
together a group of friends, including Wexner, to buy the auction
house and take it private.
</P>
<P>
   The business executives were surprised to find out exactly how
antique Sotheby's practices were, Wexner said. Records were kept on
file cards and legal pads, the London offices were a rabbit warren,
and nobody could explain exactly how the business operated. ``It
was incredibly goofy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Taubman did not simply drag Sotheby's into the computer age. He
also used his retailing talent to change the very nature of the
business. Sotheby's clients were no longer art and antiques
dealers, they were the collectors _ the shoppers _ themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a chance for people to get involved with the auction
social swim,'' recalled John H. Gutfreund, the former chairman of
Salomon Brothers. ``The old money dominated the sellers, and the
new money dominated the buyers.''
</P>
<P>
   To get buyers and sellers in the door, the company added more
cocktail parties, glossy catalogs and blockbuster auctions of
celebrity collections like those of Andy Warhol and Claus von
Bulow. Selling art, Taubman famously said, was not too different
from selling root beer. (And he knew; until 1994 he owned the A&AMP;W
restaurant chain.)
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was pleased with the changes. Dealers, in
particular, complained about the commercialization of the art world
and about how the auction houses were now competing with them.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And there were missteps, some involving a rapidly expanding
lending program. Sotheby's was embarrassed when it became known
that in 1987 it had put up about half of the record-setting $54
million an Australian financier paid for a Van Gogh painting. The
buyer promptly defaulted; Sotheby's eventually sold the painting
again. And it stopped lending to buyers without other collateral.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Taubman's methods seemed to work, and his timing was
good. The art market rebounded, and sales began to soar. Profits
rocketed, too; Sotheby's, which had lost more than $6 million in
1984, earned almost $113 million in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Things were so good that Sotheby's sold shares to the public
again, in May, 1988. Taubman made millions of dollars on the sale
and still owned about half the company's increasingly valuable
stock.
</P>
<P>
   His takeover of Sotheby's turned Taubman into a mover and shaker
in New York's social scene, a paradoxical position for a gregarious
man who nevertheless had always claimed to cherish his privacy. His
wife, Judith, was on the cover of Town &AMP; Country magazine; his
perfectly appointed homes in New York; London; Palm Beach, Fla.;
Southhampton, N.Y.; and Bloomfield Hills, Mich., attracted lots of
attention. Meanwhile, he endowed government-studies programs at
Harvard and Brown, donated millions to the University of Michigan
and the Detroit Art Institute and was active in Jewish
philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   As the 1990s began, real estate tanked. And mall sales slumped.
The art market went into a recession, too, as the rich suffered
from a global economy slump. Sotheby's shares lost two-thirds of
their value in 1990. Auction sales dropped, and so did profits,
falling to less than $4 million in 1992. It was that year,
prosecutors have been told, that Sotheby's and Christie's may have
began to collude; it is certainly the year that they raised the
commissions they charge buyers, by exactly the same amount.
</P>
<P>
   Taubman's friends repeatedly say that it would be out of
character for him to have done anything improper, no matter what
his financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   There appear to have been some. In 1992, Taubman was trying hard
to raise money. He sold a third of his stake in Sotheby's, even
though the share price was low, and he had borrowed against much of
his remaining stake.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to sell stock in his malls, a deal that was completed
the following year and brought in a lot less money than originally
hoped. The transaction was complicated because Taubman and his
family had earlier borrowed hundreds of millions of dollars from
the giant corporate pension funds of AT&AMP;T and General Motors,
secured by a stake in the shopping centers. The GM pension plan
ended up owning so much of Taubman's company that in 1998 it
swapped its shares for 10 of his malls.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all these financial pressures, Taubman remained the
model of a modern mogul, with all the lavish living that entails.
Indeed, he served as an inspiration for a major character in a
modern sort of fairy tale, Dominick Dunne's novel ``People Like
Us.'' In the book, about the clash of old and new society in New
York, the Taubman-like character is a rich trader who ends up in
jail. (Some details were so apt that Taubman demanded changes by
Dunne.)
</P>
<P>
   But not entirely apt, Dunne says now. When he wrote the book, he
said, he had watched Taubman only from afar; they have since met
and he has grown to like Taubman. ``I have never heard of a stain
on his reputation,'' Dunne said. ``Sure he's a tough guy; if you're
going to be a billionaire, you've got to be a tough guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8182 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-VIETNAM-MCCAIN-1STLD-     04-26 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-MCCAIN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN, IN VIETNAM, FINDS THE PAST ISN'T REALLY PAST  
(subs 5th graf to correct number of times McCain has been to
Vietnam since 1973; subs 10th graf to clarify reference to pilot in
photograph; subs 18th graf to give title of McCain's memoir) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOI, Vietnam _ As he strode through the shadowy hallways and
incongruously sunny courtyards, gesturing here, pointing to a
detail there, Sen. John McCain might have been a father showing a
son his alma mater. Except the landmarks on this tour were dank
cells like the one where McCain spent two years in solitary
confinement, and leg irons, which he once wore as a punishment for
insulting the guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always interesting for me to be back here and show my son
the place where I lived for a long time,'' the Arizona Republican
said as he paused next to a faded photograph of himself as a
grim-faced, unmistakably defiant inmate. ``But I put Vietnam behind
me when I left.''
</P>
<P>
   But as he guided his wife and 13-year-old son through the
remnants of the grim jail known as the ``Hanoi Hilton,'' McCain,
long a proponent of better relations with Vietnam, betrayed
feelings still raw a quarter of a century later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still bear them ill will,'' he said of the prison guards,
``not because of what they did to me, but because of what they did
to some of my friends _ including killing some of them.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and his wife, Cindy, had visited the prison, known as Hoa
Lo, on one of his seven earlier trips to Vietnam since his release
in 1973. But McCain, whose visit comes just before the the 25th
anniversary on Sunday of the end of the Vietnam War, said he wanted
to show his son Jack the place.
</P>
<P>
   A sprawling French colonial-era fortress, the jail housed 300
U.S. pilots at various periods during the war. The Vietnamese
authorities tore down much of it 1993 to make way for a luxury
hotel and office complex called Hanoi Towers. But they preserved
one corner as a museum.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, McCain seemed aware that the site of his suffering
had become just another stop on the tourist trail for people
visiting Vietnam's now-popular capital. At several points during
the self-guided tour, he stopped to say hello or to have his
picture taken with American tourists _ most of whom said they
supported him during his unsuccessful campaign for the Republican
presidential nomination this year.
</P>
<P>
   He also offered an acidic commentary on how the Vietnamese
portrayed life inside the prison. Alongside the pictures of McCain
and his fellow prisoners, a plaque declared: ``Though having
committed untold crimes on our people, the American pilots suffered
no revenge once they were captured and detained. Instead, they were
treated with adequate food, clothing and shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaking his head, McCain muttered, ``That's entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, another set of photos showed the Americans receiving
letters from their families, meeting with North Vietnamese
journalists and attending Mass. McCain pointed out that one of the
pilots photographed at Mass had placed his hand on his chin, with
only his middle finger extended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that sums up how he felt about being here,'' McCain
said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has described his five-and-a-half-year imprisonment as a
nightmarish time, in which he was beaten and kept in solitary
confinement. Twice he tried to hang himself, only to be cut down
and assaulted by the guards.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was captured on Oct. 26, 1967, after his Navy plane was
shot down while on a bombing run over Hanoi. He crashed into a
lake, breaking both arms and a leg.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, McCain paid a visit to the lake, known as Truc Bac,
where he described to reporters being dragged ashore and beaten by
an angry mob. On this visit, several curious locals stepped forward
to greet McCain _ some posing for photographs with his family.
</P>
<P>
   In prison, McCain said the American inmates communicated by
tapping on the walls of their cells. The prisoners nicknamed their
cell-block Thunderbird, and McCain described how it was lighted
with a single bulb. During the day, loudspeakers that hung from the
ceiling would drone with music by North Vietnamese propaganda
figures like the singer known as Hanoi Hannah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard her every day,'' McCain said. ``She's a marvelous
entertainer. I'm surprised she didn't get to Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnamese government has expressed anger at McCain's
description of his treatment as a prisoner of war, especially in
his recent memoir, ``Faith of My Fathers'' (Random House, 1999).
Wednesday, despite his sarcasm and fleeting bitterness, the senator
seemed reluctant to add to his earlier accounts of that period.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, McCain has long advocated reconciling the two countries
and was instrumental in the establishment of diplomatic relations
with Hanoi five years ago. At his arrival here Tuesday, he said he
had come to ``commemorate the beginning and continuation of a new
relationship between the United States and Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   In meetings with senior Vietnamese officials, the senator said
he discussed negotiations on a trade agreement between the two
countries. A deal was agreed to in principle last July, but has
bogged down since then as the Vietnamese have balked at several
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for this most celebrated of POWs, the war is the shadow
the lurks behind every meeting and every ritual. On Tuesday, soon
after he landed in Hanoi, McCain attended a ceremony on a
sweltering airport tarmac, in which the remains of six people,
believed to be U.S. soldiers missing since the war, were loaded on
a U.S. Air Force plane and flown to Hawaii for forensic analysis.
</P>
<P>
   For Jack McCain, Wednesday's visit seem to confirm the stories
his father had told him. As he left the prison, Jack said he had
expected the cells to be cramped and dark. Indeed, his knowledge of
the prison seemed so thorough that he expressed surprise at only
one small detail: the iron doors at the main entrance were wide
enough that his father was delivered through them in a truck.
</P>
</TEXT>
