<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-EARNINGS-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON.COM REPORTS $308 MILLION LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Amazon.com, the biggest retailer on the Internet,
said on Wednesday that it lost $308 million in the first quarter,
five times its loss a year earlier, but that its sales rose 95
percent, beating forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly loss translated into 90 cents a share, compared
with a loss of $61.7 million, or 20 cents a share, in the quarter a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But Amazon said investors should focus on its pro-forma loss,
which excludes the cost of stock options, merger costs and Amazon's
share of the losses of the companies in which it has invested. On
that basis, Amazon lost $122 million, or 35 cents a share, compared
with a loss of $36 million, or 12 cents a share a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected the company to lose 36 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon posted sales of $574 million, beating the $521 million
that analysts had expected. The sales were up 95 percent from
$293.6 million in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Before the results were announced, shares of Amazon closed up
$1.0625, to $53.50, but slipped as low as $52 in after-hours
trading. Amazon's stock has been on a steep slide since hitting
$113 in early December, although it has rebounded some over the
last week as two other online merchants _ eBay and Priceline.com _
posted higher sales and lower losses than Wall Street expected for
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts praised the company for what appeared to be an
increased focus on efficiency and financial prudence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are bringing costs under control and their targets seem
more achievable than they did at the end of the fourth quarter,''
said Henry Blodget, an analyst at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with investors, Warren Jenson, Amazon's
chief financial officer, stressed that the company was moving
toward profitability.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Amazon said that its pro-forma operating loss represented 17
percent of sales but that it hoped to reduce that to less than 10
percent of sales by the fourth quarter of this year. That
improvement will come largely from increased efficiency in the
company's network of seven warehouses. Jenson said the company
expected to have fewer employees to handle the Christmas season
this year than last year despite a vigorous growth in sales.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it spent $41 million in marketing in the
quarter. That represents $13 for each of its three million new
customers, a far lower cost than any other major online retailer.
Amazon now has 20 million customer accounts. Of those customers,
those that were active in the last year bought an average of $121
in the quarter, up from $107 for the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Levitan, an analyst with Robertson Stephens, said she was
surprised that Amazon has been able to add so many customers at
such a low cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 20 million customers they have distanced themselves from
everybody else and shown themselves to be the first place people go
when they think of shopping online,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The company had $1 billion in cash at the end of the quarter,
down slightly from $1.01 billion at the end of the fourth quarter.
Investors have increasingly been looking at the cash positions of
Amazon and other money-losing Internet companies wondering whether
they will be able to survive until they reach profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Jenson said Amazon was not at risk of running out of cash.
Indeed, he said that for the next nine months Amazon would generate
enough cash from its operations to cover its planned capital
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Of its sales, the company said its book, music and video
business in the United States represented $401 million, up 50
percent from figures in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in its British and German subsidiaries increased by 300
percent, to $75 million. And sales of its other units _ including
toys, tools and auctions _ were $97 million in the quarter and
virtually nil a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it lost $2.4 million in books, music and video,
$27 million from its international business and $69 million from
its other businesses.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
