<HEADER>
A8185 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-HABEAS-CORPUS-     04-26 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-HABEAS-CORPUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT GIVES STATE INMATES BROADER RIGHTS TO APPEALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Nev.)   By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the third time in a week, a Supreme Court
ruling Wednesday kept the federal courthouse doors open to appeals
by state inmates, with the justices overturning a lower court's
decision that, in the majority's view, had closed those doors
prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   Interpreting the newly amended law governing habeas corpus
petitions, the court ruled 7-2 that an inmate could not be barred
from raising a constitutional challenge to his conviction simply
because a lower federal court had previously dismissed an earlier
habeas corpus petition on procedural grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The writ of habeas corpus plays a vital role in protecting
constitutional rights,'' Justice Anthony M. Kennedy wrote for the
majority Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In setting new preconditions for appealing a federal district
court's denial of a habeas corpus petition, Kennedy said,
``Congress expressed no intention to allow trial court procedural
error to bar vindication of substantial constitutional rights on
appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   The dissenters were Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The inmate in this case, Antonio T. Slack, convicted of
murdering a 12-year-old girl when he was 19, is serving a life
sentence in Nevada. Under the ruling Wednesday, Slack will have a
renewed chance to persuade the 9th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals to
hear his petition, raising various constitutional challenges to
events that occurred at his 1990 trial and to the quality of his
legal representation.
</P>
<P>
   The decision Wednesday, involving several technical aspects of
habeas corpus law, gave added force to a pair of habeas corpus
decisions last week by which the court set aside the death
sentences of two Virginia murderers. The court's broader message
now, as then, was that despite Congress' efforts in 1996 to place
severe new limits on habeas corpus, federal courts retain the
ability, and the obligation, to take these cases seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Among the several issues in this case, Slack vs. McDaniel, No.
98-6322, the central question was under what circumstances an
inmate who had failed with one habeas corpus petition could get a
chance to amend the petition and get back into federal court. A
series of Supreme Court decisions in the 1980s and early 1990s
instructed lower courts to dismiss many second or successive
petitions under a doctrine known as ``abuse of the writ.'' In the
Anti-terrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act of 1996, which
restricted many aspects of habeas corpus, Congress made the ``abuse
of the writ'' obstacle even higher.
</P>
<P>
   Slack had filed an initial habeas corpus petition in 1991, which
the federal district court in Nevada dismissed under a separate
``exhaustion'' doctrine under which claims must first be presented
to the state courts. After bringing an unsuccessful case in state
court, he refiled his federal court petition in 1995, adding more
claims two years later when a lawyer was appointed to assist him.
The district court then dismissed this second petition as an
``abuse of the writ.''
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion Wednesday, Kennedy said that a petition filed
after an initial petition was dismissed on procedural grounds, with
its constitutional claims unadjudicated, should not be considered a
``second or successive'' petition within the meaning of the abuse
of the writ doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that some new issues were raised in the new petition
should not bar its consideration, Kennedy said, because that result
``would limit a prisoner to claims made in a pleading that is often
uncounseled, hand-written'' and dismissed by the district court
without a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   In their dissenting opinion, Scalia and Thomas said the decision
would require a state ``repeatedly to appear and expend its
resources, with no help in sight from supposed limitations on
`second or successive' petitions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
