<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0430 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8187 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-JONESES27-COX     04-26 1516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-JONESES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones run ends
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, Ga. _ Opponents of Albany State won't have to keep up
with the Joneses anymore.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 39 years, no Jones from the small town of
McGehee, Ark., is directly involved with the basketball program at
the NCAA Division II school on the banks of the Flint River.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, Oliver Jones was cast aside as the Rams'
coach after his second losing season in 28 years. The move capped
the pipeline that had provided Albany State with six tall and
talented brothers from a 100-acre farm in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could say that it's the end of an era,'' Oliver
Jones said recently, ``and it's a little tough to take, the way it
ended.''
</P>
<P>
   During a stretch of 18 years, the Rams basketball team had at
least one Jones brother. Four of them _ Wilbert, Caldwell, Major
and Charles _ spent a collective total of 54 years in the ABA and
NBA.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the past three decades, Oliver and Melvin, who also
had stints on pro basketball rosters, have worked together as head
coach and assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this business, you've got to have someone you can depend on
and trust, and someone who is not trying to take your job,'' said
Melvin, who had been a head coach at Union High in Leslie before
joining his brother's staff in 1979. ``I never wanted Oliver's job.
All I wanted to do was help him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Joneses' relationship with Albany State began in 1961 with
Oliver. Six years earlier, he had met Rams second-year coach Robert
Rainey, a McGehee resident who had built his reputation by winning
big and consistently at several high schools in southern Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the influence of Rainey, who frequently visited the
Joneses, Caldwell Jones Sr., father of seven towering sons and
6-foot-3 daughter Clovis, abandoned hopes of developing at least
one pro baseball player and turned his focus to basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cleared an area around the house and made it a court, then
put a backboard on a tree that he had cut down,'' Oliver said about
his father, who died in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   His junior year in high school, Oliver, who at 6-2 was three
inches shorter than older brother Clint, hit a sudden growth spurt
that affected his vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``In three months, I grew 5 1/2 inches and started to have
problems with my eyesight,'' he said. ``I had to squint to see or
read anything. When my dad took me to a doctor, I was told to read
the writing on a building across the street. I could hardly see the
building.''
</P>
<P>
   A team of three doctors eventually decided that Oliver's sight
had been affected by the rapid growth spurt, and that glasses were
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started wearing glasses, it was like a new world had
opened for me,'' Oliver said. ``At 6-2, I had played the point
guard position. Now I was about 6-7 1/2 and able to play every
position _ and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Rainey, who became Albany State's head coach in 1960, started to
benefit from his relationship with the Joneses his second season
with the Rams, when Oliver committed to the program.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin followed several years later, and Wilbert several years
after that.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the high volume of interest shown him by numerous
college recruiters his senior year in high school, Caldwell, the
tallest of the brothers at 7 feet, was determined to follow
Oliver's lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started concentrating on basketball seriously after Oliver
went to college,'' said Caldwell, who played 17 NBA seasons. He was
with the Chicago Bulls when Michael Jordan was a rookie (1984-85),
and with the San Antonio Spurs during David Robinson's first season
(1989-90).
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I had about 150 college offers. Integration was just
becoming acceptable,'' said Caldwell, now the proprietor of an
amusement park in Stockbridge. ``But Coach Rainey had the inside
track.''
</P>
<P>
   To the amazement of many, the Joneses kept on coming, each of
them at least 6 feet 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not surprised by their heights, because my father was
tall, and his father was tall, about 6-foot-6,'' said Cecelia
Jones, the 80-year-old mother of the celebrated brothers. ``I'm
5-11, and my (late) husband was about 6-4. The children got plenty
of exercise, so it was no chance of any of them being short.''
</P>
<P>
   NEXT GENERATION NOT BASKETBALL-MINDED
</P>
<P>
   A Jones from the subsequent generation is unlikely to surface in
the Albany State or any other college basketball program. The six
brothers with Albany State ties have five male children among them.
None has shown much interest in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the pressure, probably,'' Oliver said. ``As I look back,
I think it started with Charles. He was faced with a lot of
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, a four-year starter at Albany State before being drafted
by Cincinnati and sent off to the once-thriving Eastern League,
returned to his alma mater as Rainey's assistant in 1970, only
months after being discharged from the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Rainey died of a massive heart attack. He was
replaced by his most pivotal recruit, who led the team to the
school's first SIAC tournament title in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big blow to me personally, because coach wasn't
feeling well and had tried to call me to come over and sit with
him,'' Oliver said. ``I was sitting outside my apartment and didn't
hear the phone. He was so excited about that upcoming season,
especially since Major was coming to play with Caldwell, who was a
senior that year.''
</P>
<P>
   COACH INSPIRED QUIET RESPECT
</P>
<P>
   In compiling a 395-348 record, Jones, 56, guided the Rams to six
SIAC regular-season titles, six tournament championships and seven
appearances in the NCAA Division II playoffs. And he accomplished
it without raising his voice or using profanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a religious commitment that a lot of people don't know
about,'' said Robert Skinner, the Albany State women's coach.
``I've been here nine years, and I've never heard him cuss. Heck,
I've seen something happen out there on the court that made me want
to cuss for him. But that was never his approach to coaching. He's
always had a calmness about him that players respected and
responded to.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Jones' coaching career was not without its trials and
pain. After the 1990-91 season, he underwent brain surgery for the
removal of a life-threatening tumor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors told me that if I had been hit in the nose by a
tennis ball or bouncing basketball, I could've bled to death and
nobody would've known why,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly six years later, triple-bypass heart surgery forced
Oliver Jones away from courtside during the stretch run to the 1997
SIAC tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were headed to Memphis to play LeMoyne-Owen, and everybody
was watching Coach, because we knew something was wrong,'' former
Rams star Erwin Josey said. ``He kept trying to play it off because
he didn't want to disrupt the team. That was his way. He was like a
father to all the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after heart surgery, Oliver was back in the lead
chair at the Columbus Coliseum, where his Rams captured the SIAC
tournament title.
</P>
<P>
   ATHLETICS MAINSTAY GONE WITH DISMISSAL
</P>
<P>
   But none of the basketball program's achievements mattered about
five weeks ago when school athletics director Dan Land delivered a
memo to the athletics program's most stable entity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It said, `As of the 17th of March, I'm relieving you of all
responsibilities in athletics, specifically basketball,''' Oliver
said. ``In other words, `You're fired.' He said something about a
new direction. I never got an understanding of the direction he was
talking about. ''
</P>
<P>
   Land, a former Rams football star in his second year as
athletics director, refused to comment on the dismissal of Oliver
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a personnel issue, and I'm not going to elaborate on
it,'' Land said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great man, and a lot of people around here are upset
about what happened to him,'' said James White, an Albany State
alumnus and the first-year football coach.
</P>
<P>
   Before this season's dismal 3-24 finish, the worst record posted
by the Rams under Jones was 13-15.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the NCAA penalized the school's athletics
program for a number of rules infractions, but Jones' basketball
team was not involved.
</P>
<P>
   But at the root of any problems he encountered the past few
seasons was the school's lack of commitment to the basketball
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for maybe three years since I've been here, my
recruiting budget consisted mostly of what I pulled out my own
pocket,'' he said. ``Not too long ago, I had a chance to go to a
Division I program with a five-year contract, but I chose to stay
here. I've thought about that decision a lot lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who teaches two classes a day, insists that his
interaction with students is just as special as it has been with
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like this is my school and my home, and the students
and my players are part of my family,'' he said. ``At least I can
go out feeling good about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
