<HEADLINE>
SITE PRESENTS WEB-ONLY DOCUMENTARY ON BOXER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Sportcut.com took a risk when it decided to
feature a six-minute video documentary on heavyweight boxer Michael
Grant in training for his fight Saturday against Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   With 56K modems the standard in most home computers, Grant could
have looked like one of the Rock'em Sock'em Robots. The slower the
modem speed, the choppier the image, and the screen is so small
that it can make it difficult to follow rapid motion.
</P>
<P>
   But filmmaker Brian Harty and Sportcut.com content manager
Nicholas Twemlow understood the flaws of working with streaming
video and adjusted accordingly. Twemlow, who produced the film,
said they framed shots tightly and used cutaways to imply a lot of
movement. As they were shooting, they tracked their shots on the
camera's tiny viewfinder, which is about the size of an browser
audio-player window.
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Unifying Michael Grant'', a nicely done film
that rivals the work of a mainstream short-subject documentary.
</P>
<P>
   While film is nothing new to the Internet, ``It's unique that we
had professional filmmakers'' shooting the documentary, said
Sportcut.com spokesman Dan Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed in digital video on location in rural Oriental, N.C.,
``Unifying Michael Grant'' includes interviews with Grant, trainer
Don Turner and other members of Grant's camp. Helping
Sportcut.com's effort was cooperation from Grant and his trainers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Grant caught the vibe and really opened up,'' Twemlow
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sportcut.com is better known as the site that had the most
successful one-day Internet launch in history on Nov. 30. According
to Nielson Net Ratings, Sportcut.com logged 12 million hits in
response to Pete Rose's petition for reinstatement to baseball. The
New York-based startup company's mission is dedicated to covering
celebrities in sports.
</P>
<P>
   The film was conceived as a partnership project between
Sportcut.com and Harty with the intention of making the film
available for distribution through the site. Harty, a University of
Kansas graduate like Twemlow, is a graduate of the New York
University film program.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting Web-exclusive film is better than using
television-first footage made by the big-media or official league
sites, Twemlow said. He compares the Grant documentary to work
featured on Atom.com, a popular video site.
</P>
<P>
   ``There you can see films made only for the Web which probably
won't see the light of day in another form,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper said more multimedia projects might be pursued depending
on the success of the Grant documentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an excellent way to tell a story,'' Jasper said.  &QL; 
Speaking of video
</P>
<P>
   Sal LaRocca, vice president of NBA Entertainment's e-commerce
division, said no alerts are in place but NBA.com is ready for
increased traffic for tonight's Celebrity Fashion Show from the NBA
Store in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Will the show rival the Victoria's Secret show that caused major
shutdowns and disruptions on Broadcast.com a year ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we're equipped to handle the anticipated traffic
increase,'' LaRocca said.
</P>
<P>
   They better.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity models such as Carmen Electra will walk the runway
wearing basketball-inspired, NBA-licensed apparel and original
designs, including pebble-grain bikinis, his/her pebble-grain
leather pants and a dress made from basketball trading cards.
</P>
<P>
   The show is scheduled to be Webcast live on NBA.com and
broadcast on NBA.com TV, the league's 24-hour digital television
network. The show celebrates NBA.com's relaunch of its e-commerce
site. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
