</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Images show universe's infancy
 &HT;    By Mike Toner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Space scientists Wednesday unveiled the first detailed
images of the universe in its infancy _ baby pictures from a time
not long after the big bang when, cosmologists say, everything was
smaller, smoother and a whole lot hotter.
</P>
<P>
   The images, taken from a balloon 120,000 feet above the surface
of Antarctica, capture the faint glow of microwave radiation from
the edge of the visible universe _ traces of structures that were
formed 12 billion to 15 billion years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``These images represent the ultimate limit of our vision,''
said Andrew Lange, a physicist at the California Institute of
Technology who headed an international team of scientists involved
in the research. ``They predate the first star or galaxy in the
universe.''
</P>
<P>
   To laymen, the pictures _ color-enhanced clumps of blue, orange
and red that represent minute variations in the cosmic microwave
background that fills the sky _ may not look like much.
</P>
<P>
   But to the team of international scientists of Project Boomerang
_ short for Balloon Observations of Millimetric Extragalactic
Radiation and Geophysics _ the fuzzy hints of structure, from so
early in the universe's development, shore up several key theories
associated with the origins of the universe in a single violent
event called the big bang.
</P>
<P>
   Lange says the images, which measure heat left over from the big
bang, are ``little snapshots of a time'' when the universe was only
a few hundred thousand years old _ and 1,000 times smaller and
hotter than it is today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because our instruments are so sensitive, we can measure the
intricate pattern of minute temperature variation that fills the
sky,'' he said. ``Because it comes from so far away _ 12 billion to
15 billion light-years _ we are literally seeing the seeds of
galaxies and star clusters that formed very early in the history of
the universe.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Kamionkowski, a theoretical astrophysicist at Cal Tech,
says the measurements represent a ``watershed event in cosmology.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The results suggest that we are on the right track with our
theories for the origin of the universe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They also open up a path toward scientifically addressing what
happened in the first micro-micro-second after the big bang.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest images support predictions _ consistent with big bang
theory _ that two-thirds of the universe consists of
still-undetected ``dark energy,'' that today's universe is still
expanding at an accelerating rate, and that the geometry of the
universe is flat. The big bang, which forms the underpinning of
most modern cosmology, holds that the entire universe grew from a
tiny subatomic region during a period of violent expansion that
occurred within microseconds _ an expansion so swift that it
stretched the geometry of space until it was flat.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling universe started out hot and dense and then cooled
as it expanded. Within a few hundred thousand years of the big
bang, it cooled sufficiently to allow the formation of atomic
hydrogen and the release of photons, particles of light, that moved
freely through the universe until they were intercepted by the
team's balloon-borne instruments over Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
   The project _ funded by NASA, the National Science Foundation
and scientific institutions in Italy, Britain and Canada _ is the
first step in a decade-long effort to study the residual microwave
radiation left by the big bang that permeates the universe.
Instruments aboard the balloon were able to study only a small
portion of the sky. With the launch of a NASA space probe later
this year, and another in 2007, scientists hope eventually to
construct an atlas of the entire sky.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
