<HEADER>
A8196 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SNOWMOBILE-PARKS-BAN-     04-26 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNOWMOBILE-PARKS-BAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION BAN SNOWMOBILES FROM MOST NATIONAL PARKS 
</HEADLINE>
  By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a new effort to protect public lands, the
National Park Service will impose a broad and immediate ban on the
recreational use of snowmobiles at nearly all of the country's
national parks, monuments and recreational areas, Interior
Department officials said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, to be announced in Washington on Thursday, will
directly affect more than two dozen parks where snowmobiling now
takes place, including Yellowstone National Park in Wyoming, which
has been the focus of a major battle over whether the noisy,
high-powered vehicles should be permitted within the park system.
</P>
<P>
   The policy, which Interior Department officials said could
affect thousands of snowmobiles a year, is the latest step by the
Clinton administration to put larger swaths of public land
off-limits to recreational vehicles. It follows a decision this
month that banned the use of the personal watercraft sold under
several brand names, including Jet Skis, from most areas of the
park system.
</P>
<P>
   A ban on the use of snowmobiles had been vigorously opposed by
off-road vehicle advocates and by several Western senators, who had
warned that the move could unfairly disrupt a long-established
practice. But more than 60 environmental groups had petitioned the
Interior Department in favor of the move, and though the policy
will include some notable exceptions, a news release prepared in
advance of Thursday's announcement essentially echoes the
environmentalists' claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come for the National Park System to pull in its
welcome mat for recreational snowmobiling,'' Donald J. Barry, the
assistant secretary of Interior for Fish and Wildlife and Parks, is
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snowmobiles are noisy, antiquated machines that are no longer
welcome in our national parks. The snowmobile industry has had many
years to clean up their act, and they haven't.''
</P>
<P>
   A copy of the announcement and details about the decision were
provided to The New York Times by Interior Department officials. In
an angry response, an official of the snowmobile industry accused
the administration of bad faith, noting that manufacturers had been
cooperating in the case-by-case reviews of snowmobiling that have
been under way in Yellowstone and neighboring Grand Teton National
Parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden now the Department of Interior comes out and
says regardless of what you've done, we're just going to come out
and ban snowmobiling outright,'' said the official, Edward Klim,
president of the International Snowmobile Manufacturers'
Association. ``This may be happening to snowmobiles today, but I
tell you, tomorrow it will be campers, and the next day it will be
sport utility vehicles. It's part of a planned campaign by this
administration to limit public access to public lands.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 180,000 snowmobiles are used in the National Park
System each winter, said the National Parks Conservation
Association, a nonprofit advocacy organization.
</P>
<P>
   The most important exception to the ban will apply at Denali
National Park and 11 other parks in Alaska, where snowmobiling is
explicitly permitted by law. At those sites, and at Voyageurs
National Park in Minnesota, which was also established under a law
that permitted snowmobiling, recreational use of the vehicles will
still be allowed, although under stricter guidelines, park service
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But at the other 29 park sites where snowmobiling now takes
place, the park service officials said, the only exceptions will
apply in limited cases in which snowmobiles would be permitted to
cross a small section of park land so that they could gain access
to adjacent private or public land where snowmobiling was
permitted.
</P>
<P>
   The new ban would not prohibit the use of snowmobiles for
essential transportation, as long as it did not involve
recreational activity, the park service officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the environmental groups pushing for a ban had been the
Wilderness Society, which had joined the Bluewater Network and the
dozens of other organizations in urging the park service to revise
its rules. Bob Ekey, who directs Wilderness Society operations in
the northern Rocky Mountain states, said the group would welcome
any new restrictions on snowmobiling in the parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's clear that the national parks should be places
where the public can go and escape traffic,'' Ekey said. ``And
clearly these snow machines are loud, they're polluting and they
cause conflict with other visitors.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of snowmobiles for recreational purposes has long been
prohibited at some areas administered by the park service, Glacier
National Park in Montana and Yosemite National Park in California.
But it has thrived at more than 40 sites that range from Acadia
National Park in Maine to California's Sequoia National Park and
numerous parks in the Northwest, in addition to those in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Under existing regulations, as set out in executive orders that
date back to the Nixon administration and in Congressional
legislation, public lands are to be closed to off-road vehicles
including snowmobiles only when explicitly authorized. Under those
orders, park service officials said, off-road vehicle use should be
halted if it is determined that the activity was causing harm to
the environment.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not until last year, when the controversy over
snowmobiling in Yellowstone focused attention on the adverse
environmental effects, that the park service decided to take a
closer look at the activity in other public lands.
</P>
<P>
   Denis Galvin, deputy director of the park service, said an
internal survey had revealed ``years of inattention to our own
regulatory standards on snowmobiles.''
</P>
<P>
   (mg)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
