u f BC-CIRRUS27-COX     04-26 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIRRUS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cirrus Logic soon to be based in Texas
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Cirrus Logic Inc., a Silicon Valley
computer-chip maker that has switched its focus to audio-processing
chips and magnetic and optical storage, said Wednesday it is moving
its corporate headquarters to Austin from Fremont, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive David French, who has lived in Austin since
becoming head of the company in February 1999, said the move makes
sense because most corporate functions and 900 of Cirrus' 1,300
employees are in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   With the move, Cirrus will become the largest semiconductor
maker based in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola Inc., Advanced Micro Devices Inc. and equipment maker
Applied Materials Inc. have more employees, but they are based
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Separately Wednesday, Cirrus said net income for the fourth
quarter was $62.1 million, or 82 cents per diluted share, compared
with a loss of $214 million, or $3.55 a share, for the fourth
quarter last year. The current quarter includes proceeds from sales
of securities in Phone.com Inc. and the sale of Ambient
Technologies to Intel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding extraordinary events, net income for the quarter was
$6.2 million, or 5 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, Cirrus lost $47 million, or 77 cents per share, on
revenue of $564 million. In the 1999 fiscal year, losses totaled
$427 million, or $6.77 a share, on revenue of $628 million. The
1999 losses were tied to discontinued business operations.
</P>
<P>
   The results for the quarter ended March 25 were released after
the close of the stock market. Cirrus shares ended Wednesday
unchanged at $16.
</P>
<P>
   Cirrus in the early 1990s was among the fastest growing
companies in the semiconductor industry and a major supplier of
computer graphics processing chips.
</P>
<P>
   But the company fell out of its leadership position in computer
graphics in 1996 and in 1997 dropped out of the graphics chip
business. At its 1996 peak, Cirrus employed more than 3,000
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few local jobs will be added in Austin because of the
corporate move. In addition, Austin executive Robert Fay will take
over as the company's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   The company's divisions for computer-storage-related chips and
for optical-disk storage chips, which employ 400 people, will
remain in California.
</P>
<P>
   Cirrus Logic remains a strong player in developing audio
processing chips for computers, consumer electronics products and
Internet audio players. It also is a leading maker of chips for
rewritable computer CD-ROM drives. It is adding workers in Austin
and in California.
</P>
<P>
   Cirrus Logic arrived in Austin in 1991, when the California
company bought Crystal Semiconductor, a local chip startup.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
