<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8203 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-U.S.-RUSSIA-ARMS-1STL     04-26 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-RUSSIA-ARMS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA WANTS TO RESOLVE DISPUTE OVER MISSILES, SAY U.S. OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Rewrites for additional details, quotes and perspective, mostly in
grafs 2 through 7)  
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a second round of intensive meetings with the
Russian foreign minister about the missile defense system that the
United States wants to develop over Russian objections, senior
administration officials said today that they had detected a
readiness by Moscow to explore all avenues of a possible resolution
to the looming standoff.
</P>
<P>
   But they acknowledged that Foreign Minister Igor S. Ivanov and
the chief Russian arms control negotiator, Georgi Memedev, had
revealed no significant shift in their opposition to the missile
defense plan. ``The Russians have shown a willingness to intensify
the process,'' a senior administration official said. ``But we're
not seeing a huge shift.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to show that the United States was standing firm on its
position, the State Department said there was a three-prong
approach it described as the ``three D's.''
</P>
<P>
   There would be no ``deferral'' of the missile defense issue,
there would be no ``destruction'' of the Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty of 1972, which limited both Washington's and Moscow's
ability to deploy defenses against missiles. And it said there
would be no ``decoupling'' from Start III, which would cut the cut
the number of nuclear warheads in each country's arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms and other leading conservative Republicans
believe that the ABM treaty is an antiquated relic of the Cold War
and should be scrapped, thus allowing a more robust missile defense
than the one the administration is proposing.
</P>
<P>
   And Gov. George W. Bush, the Republicans' presumptive
presidential nominee, who met with Ivanov on Wednesday, has said
that he would oppose any Clinton deal with the Russians that
limited the ability of a new president ot make his own agreement
with Moscow. And he has also said that if Russia does not make
suitable changes in the treaty, it should be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Helms, Republican of North Carolina and
chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, had appeared to
urge that negotiations with the Russians be suspended during the
final months of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   He said his committee would be willing to consider amendments to
the ABM Treaty but only after the departure of Clinton. The senator
derided the president for wanting a ``final photo-op'' with
Russians before leaving the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The mission of Ivanov, who was on the second day of a three-day
visit, appeared to be to gauge the political situation in the
United States before President Clinton meets with President-elect
Vladimir Putin in Moscow in early June. Ivanov also met Wednesday
for 90 minutes with 20 Republican and Democratic senators on
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the differences between the Clinton
administration and Moscow is the development of a limited missile
defense that the administration says is necessary to defend the
United States against ``rogue'' states like North Korea and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   National missile defense systems are prohibited in the 1972 ABM
treaty, which is based on the principle that the only way to
encourage reductions in strategic arms is to restrict ways to
counter them. But the administration says it is seeking only a
modest change to the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   As they counter the administration on national missile defense,
the Russians are urging Washington to agree to deep cuts in
long-range nuclear arms as part of a Start III accord.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they believed the Russians were
judging whether they have to make a decision now and deal with
Clinton or whether they could gamble and wait for the next
administration. Because Clinton would like an arms control treaty,
the administration is trying to convince the Russians that they are
better off to take a deal that they know than one they do not.
</P>
<P>
   As one administration official said, ``The big sell is: `Take a
sure bet now. Don't take a risk in the future.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Wednesday's meetings between Ivanov and the administration,
the Russians offered two counterproposals, administration officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The first, dealing with curbing the proliferation of nuclear
weapons, involved expanding the current Missile Technology Control
Regime, an international accord that limits the range of missiles a
country can deploy. The second proposal involved working with the
United States to cooperate on theater missile defense systems that
are allowed under the ABM Treaty. These theater systems can spot
incoming missiles early in their trajectory and target them high in
the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the State Department said the administration was
``interested in and intrigued by'' the fact that the proposals
showed that Russia understood new threats posed by nations like
North Korea and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration also publicly went out of its way to
state that there was, according to James P. Rubin, the State
Department spokesman, ``no chance of deferral'' of national missile
defense and amending the treaty
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the Russians would like to avoid this issue,'' Rubin
said at the State Department on Wednesday. But Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright, who met with Ivanov on Tuesday and
Wednesday, was ``making clear that deferral is not an option,''
Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov said in a speech to the National Press Club that the
administration would be making a ``fatal mistake'' if it went ahead
with the missile defense system. He urged the White House not to
hurry on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Using a quotation from an F. Scott Fitzgerald short story, ``The
Swimmers,'' he said that America had been described as ``the
willingness of heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is every ground to apply his words to Russia,'' he
countered.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said it was unlikely that an agreement
involving a complicated package of support _ from the Russians,
from NATO allies and from Congress _ would be ready by the summit
meeting in Moscow. ``That's not on,'' said one senior official.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said the administration's view of what is best for the
United States ``is to have a treaty that allows us to reduce our
strategic forces with the Russians, get deeper cuts than we have
now, reduce the nuclear danger that way.'' But at the same time,
Rubin said, the United States wants to ``allow a limited national
missile defense that would allow us to defend against a small
number of North Korean or Iranian missile warheads.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the theater missile defense proposal of the Russians,
countries that were under immediate threat _ for example, South
Korea from North Korea _ would have a missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   But such a system would not give universal coverage to the
United States, a factor that made it impossible for the
administration to accept, one official said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov fielded questions from senators Wednesday afternoon. Much
of the focus was on the war in Chechnya and the brutal way that
Moscow was fighting. In response, Ivanov asked for help in fighting
terrorism, Congressional aides said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, Ivanov, accompanied by Albright, was taken to a
secure conference room known as the ``tank.'' He met with Deputy
Secretary of Defense Walter B. Slocombe and other officials.
</P>
<P>
   As an opening gambit for the visit, Albright took Ivanov to
dinner Tuesday night at Les Pinasse, a French restaurant at the St.
Regis Hotel. In doing so, she abandoned earlier plans to take him
to The Palm, which is frequented by Washington lobbyists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
