<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
RANGERS STUNG BY KILLER B's 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON _ Figuring out what's wrong with the Rangers these
days is like watching reruns of ``Sesame Street.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all right there near the top of the alphabet.
</P>
<P>
   Today, kids, we're talking about the letter `B.'
</P>
<P>
   B, as in bullpen _ surprisingly shaky.
</P>
<P>
   B, as in balance in the lineup _ there is none.
</P>
<P>
   B, as in bench _ thin as Jason McDonald's resume.
</P>
<P>
   B, as in bottom half of the batting order _ dead weight.
</P>
<P>
   B, as in bad _ really, really baaaad.
</P>
<P>
   Can you say that?
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, let's add one more `B,' as in, boy, does Mark Clark
stink.
</P>
<P>
   Clark says he's too good to pitch in the bullpen but he wasn't
too good to cough up five first-inning runs to Boston _ yep,
another `B' _ and last just four outs into yesterday's 14-4
bloodbath against the Boston Red Sox, closing out a disastrous 2-7
homestand at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   My original intention was to tell you that it's way too early to
be overly concerned about the Rangers' early struggles.
</P>
<P>
   Then I saw Clark pitch.
</P>
<P>
   And Matt Perisho relieve.
</P>
<P>
   Hurry, Justin Thompson. Please hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Clark's abominable performance yesterday was an
aberration for the team's starting rotation, which has been the
most promising aspect of he season's first three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's four-out stint broke a string of 17 consecutive games in
which Rangers starters had gone at least five innings.
</P>
<P>
   There, I've said something positive about the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's talk reality.
</P>
<P>
   If there was one thing the Rangers were confident in when they
left spring training, it was their bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Guess again. If the 'pen had done its job adequately, the
Rangers' dismal 8-13 record could easily be a comfortable 13-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get left-handed hitters out,'' general manager Doug
Melvin said. ``The numbers for our right-handers are actually
pretty good. Our bad games have been one pitch here or there. The
concern is that we have given up the runs at crucial times.''
</P>
<P>
   Balance in the lineup _ the Rangers are heavily weighted to the
right side _ disappeared when Rusty Greer and Frank Catalanotto
took their left-handed bats to the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   That has also negatively impacted the bench, exposing the
Rangers' weak underbelly at Oklahoma. The switch-hitting McDonald
(0-for-9), called up from the RedHawks, has failed miserably as a
pinch-hitter and extra outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Catalanotto and Rusty are hurt, our bench is obviously
thinned out,'' Melvin said. ``Somebody who was a fifth outfielder
becomes a fourth outfielder. Somebody you might see as an extra
player on the bench has to become an everyday player. Once
Catalanotto and Rusty come back, our bench will become a strength
again. It's a matter of getting through these few injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might could have signed someone else at Oklahoma City, but
the problem is, when they see you have Chad Curtis, Rusty Greer,
Gabe Kapler and Ruben Mateo, why would they sign here? They ask,
`When am I going to get playing time? You've got those young guys
and Rusty Greer never gets hurt, plus you've got Curtis. When am I
going to get called up?' ''
</P>
<P>
   With Greer out and Juan Gonzalez long gone, opposing managers
look at the Rangers' lineup and tell their starting pitchers,
``Don't let Rodriguez or Palmeiro beat you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After the fifth spot in the batting order, the Rangers' lineup
turns into a black hole. Gabe Kapler and Ruben Mateo are scaring no
one, except maybe Melvin, who nevertheless continues to put up a
brave front.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking at the stats today,'' Melvin pointed out. ``Gabe
Kapler has 12 hits. Tim Salmon \RAngels\S has 12 hits. Tony Clark
\RTigers\S has seven hits in 52 at-bats. Damion Easley \RTigers\S,
two hits. Brady Anderson \ROrioles\S, 14 hits. And here's the one:
Ken Griffey Jr. \RReds\S, has 14 hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the part that leaves you baffled. Everybody's talking
about all the good hitting, but there are a lot of good hitters
that aren't hitting yet. I would like to see us hit a little better
with men on base and runners in scoring position.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all Melvin would like to see the Rangers catch the ball
better. Two errors yesterday bumped the Rangers to 23 errors in 21
games. That's just unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're third in the league in starting pitching,'' Melvin said
before Clark almost single-handedly wrecked those numbers.
``Seattle, Boston, Cleveland, they're all pitching well, but
they've all made just made 10 errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between 12-8 or 8-12, a four-game swing \Rit's
five now\S, is the difference between \R23\S and 10 errors. And
that's not even talking about the mental errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's still early in the season. Plenty of time to turn
things around. But even Melvin has a sense of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to dig yourself too big a hole,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Do that and you're facing the worst `B' of all.
</P>
<P>
   Can you say ``buried?''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
