<HEADER>
A8213 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-KISSES-FILMS-2TAKES-$     04-26 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KISSES-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN A KISS ISN'T JUST A KISS: A LIP-SMACKING TOP 10  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   Lisa Zeidner's fourth novel, ``Layover,'' has just been released in
paperback. She is director of the Graduate Program in English at
Rutgers University in Camden, N.J.  
 By LISA ZEIDNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He hesitates. He dips his head. (The head bend is mandatory, for
the physics of the thing.) While their lips smoosh, up comes her
hand, tentative or grabbing, to his neck, as the score swells and
the camera swoops. Let's face it, most movie kisses are dull and
predictable, about as titillating as a dental hygiene appointment.
But that makes the good ones even more memorable.
</P>
<P>
   I apologize to everyone whose favorite kiss is absent here. I
apologize for the exclusion of certain legendary kisses, like the
360-degree one in the original ``Thomas Crown Affair,'' or firelit
Rhett and Scarlett in ``Gone With the Wind.'' Nor have I included
anything mostly comical, like Dustin Hoffman catching Anne Bancroft
on the inhale in ``The Graduate'' or, fond as I am of Brad Dourif
smooching his creation through bulletproof glass in ``Alien
Resurrection,'' any variety of interspecies foreplay. Only scenes
that produce a quantifiable rise in blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Herewith, from incontestable to perhaps slightly more
idiosyncratic (one choice below caused a respondent to my informal
poll to make a bad-fish pucker and say eee-yoo): &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Jimmy Stewart and Donna Reed, jointly holding the phone
to their ears in ``It's a Wonderful Life'' (1946)(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll go out and find a girl and do a little passionate
necking,'' George Bailey declares. He doesn't fool us. Judy Garland
and Mickey Rooney may get the prize for the most first kisses ever
filmed. But Jimmy Stewart, with his patented slide from restraint
to passion, is the best First Kisser. He kisses as if he's never
done it with anyone before, and will never do it with anyone else
again. Skip the 9{ weeks _ Capra cuts from the first kiss directly
to the wedding. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Baby and Bogey in ``To Have and Have Not'' (1945)(end
italics)
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Bacall initiates it. ``Whadja do that for?'' Humphrey
Bogart asks, startled. ``Been wondering whether I'd like it,'' she
says. Does she? ``I don't know yet,'' she retorts, but allows,
after she kisses him again, ``It's even better when you help.''
</P>
<P>
   Good as the script is _ and we should all be so lucky as to have
dialogue like this provided for our dates _ the power of the scene
resides in the weight of what we now know about Bacall and Bogart
off-screen. He's an uptown boy playing lowdown; she's a girl from
the Bronx playing posh. She seems his equal, but she's also not.
She's 19. For all the subversions and inversions, their complex
chemistry feels as easy as whistling.
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Cary Grant and Ingrid Bergman, the notorious
three-minute balcony scene in ``Notorious'' (1946, a very good year
for kissing).(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock circumvented the censors, who had strict time limits
on kissing, by having Grant and Bergman peck at each other while
they whisper wetly about whether or not to have chicken for dinner.
They are delayed kisses, full of both longing and the promise of
longing fulfilled, delightfully slow-building _ as close to tantric
sex as '40s movies get.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, have two better-looking pairs of lips ever met? No matter
where she moves, light glints off Bergman's hair, eyes and teeth,
as if invisible fireflies were hovering to provide a perpetual
personal lighting source, except it somehow doesn't look staged or
corny. And Grant has that profile: the cleft of chin, the
sculptural arc of hair around his ear, the ear itself perfectly
shaped, a kind of uber-ear; Bergman can't resist reaching out and
just tracing its curve, speculatively. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Jack Nicholson and Faye Dunaway in ``Chinatown''
(1974)(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a nasty cut,'' she notes, by way of understatement, as
she removes the grotesque white bandage that he has worn over the
wound on his nose for most of the film and swats at it with
peroxide. And while she may look china-doll perfect, her hair
marcelled into immobile waves, he is quick to observe, as he gazes
into her eyes, that she has a flaw in her iris. Watching Nicholson
and Dunaway today, they seem almost painfully young and
fresh-faced, but with an edge, as if their performances carry hints
of all the kitschy, self-parodying roles they will play in the
future, from Heeeere's Johnny to Mommie Dearest.
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Al Pacino's Kiss of Death to John Cazale in ``Godfather
II'' (1974)(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   Michael Corleone grabs his brother Fredo through falling
confetti, on the dance floor, on New Year's Eve in Cuba. ``I know
it was you, Fredo. You broke my heart. You broke my heart.'' In
case a reminder is needed that not only in sex is there passion,
intrigue, betrayal. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Julie Christie and Donald Sutherland in ``Don't Look
Now'' (1973)(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   For the obvious plot payoff reasons, most movie kisses are first
kisses. This long scene is unusual in that the participants are
married. They've kissed before and will kiss again; mixed with
their passion is tenderness, affection, even some humor (``You have
toothpaste all over your mouth''). The scene doesn't come at the
end of the movie, either, but toward the beginning, and rather than
the standard disrobing we get a montage of robing, post-coitally.
Kissing exists, here, in a context _ the context of the couple's
layered history. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Harvey Keitel and Jodie Foster slow-dancing in ``Taxi
Driver'' (1976)(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Does this even count? Is there some percentage of measurable
joint lip involvement that must be achieved before an interaction
can be fairly labeled kissing? Does the partner even have to kiss
back? I could posit that almost-kisses on screen are often more
seductive, less clinical, than the full-throttle variety, but then
couldn't I find a sweeter, more Jane Austen-y moment? Still, the
scene sticks.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's Jodie Foster's passivity, as Keitel murmurs and
slithers his bejeweled hands with their cocaine-scooping
pinkie-nails around her back and hair, that makes the scene so
queasy. Forget ``Looking for Mr. Goodbar'' or ``Fatal Attraction,''
indeed forget sexually transmitted disease: Harvey Keitel as
adoring pimp may have single-handedly made the world safe for
monogamy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Klaus Kinski and Isabelle Adjani in ``Nosferatu the
Vampyre'' (1979)(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   Most vampire kisses are played for camp, with the lucky lady
donating blood in a tango-style backward swoon. In Werner Herzog's
version, Kinski is bald, with pointy ears, a major need for
undereye concealer and really, really bad teeth. ``You must excuse
my rude entrance,'' Count Dracula actually tells Lucy, on his first
attempt to win her favor. But soon Lucy awaits him, perfectly still
and dressed in coffin-white, pale and placid as a daguerrotype.
Bats fly in slo-mo to Bulgarian chants, and Dracula slurps so loud
you'd think he was a frat boy with a Big Gulp.
</P>
<P>
   It should, in short, be a downright howler. It's not. Kinski
lifting her chiffon skirt with his repulsively long fingernails
(even longer than Keitel's) is the ultimate in dangerous sexuality
_ sex as ``a very severe brain fever.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Ralph Fiennes and Juliette Binoche in ``Wuthering
Heights'' (1992), or Ralph Fiennes and Kristin Scott Thomas in
``The English Patient'' (1996) _ Fiennes with anyone, since the
actress, no matter how gorgeous, will not register.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   Fiennes has my nomination to take home the Jimmy Stewart
Memorial Unrequited Love Statuette. With his soulful eyes and slow,
haunted hands, he manages to keep plaintive longing from seeming
silly as he wails for his beloved over the moors, or the desert.
The actual object of his affections becomes baldly, boldly
irrelevant. Which is, of course, as we learned as far back as
``Casablanca,'' the very point of unrequited love: it's always a
solo act. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Greta Scacchi and Peter Coyote in ``A Man in Love''
(1987)(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   They don't get very far into the hotel room. He leans her up
against the back of the door. He unbuttons her blouse before he
kisses her; their first kiss slides, rather quickly, into their
first everything else. Her welcoming blush, his hand to her neck _
it's all fairly standard issue, so it's hard to pinpoint what
they're doing to make the scene so compelling. It may not be
irrelevant that the director was a woman. Diane Kurys focuses on
Scacchi's face, but her gaze is more empathetic than lascivious.
And Scacchi actually smiles. Love isn't always painful, at least in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Another plus for Kurys: she has the good sense to leave the sex
act unscored. The lusty duo does not pause to tune the hotel radio
to ``My Heart Will Go On (Love Theme From `Titanic').'' As someone
who has just fast-forwarded through slews of films to get to the
sex scenes (perhaps, I grant, not the ideal way to savor the
mounting relationships), I can attest that nothing ruins the mood
of the moment faster than a few hundred hyperactive violinists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
