<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8215 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OHIO-GODMOTTO27-COX     04-26 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-GODMOTTO27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio motto was too sacred
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner, Michael C. Bender
 &HT;    and Khalid Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ God may be causing trouble in Ohio, but not in
several other states across the nation that use references to the
Almighty in their mottoes.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona they use ``God Enriches.''
</P>
<P>
   In South Dakota they say ``Under God The People Will Rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida's motto, ``In God We Trust,'' mirrors the nation's.
</P>
<P>
   None of those mottoes are in danger of being challenged, but
Ohio's motto of ``With God All Things Are Possible'' was ruled
unconstitutional Tuesday by the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   The court agreed with the American Civil Liberties Union and the
plaintiff, the Rev. Matthew Peterson, a Presbyterian minister, who
claimed the words were a government endorsement of Christian
religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safe prediction is that other state mottoes won't suffer
the same fate,'' said Louis Jacobs, an Ohio State University law
professor.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy surrounding Ohio's motto, as opposed to the
other states, is that it comes from Matthew 19:26, which quotes
Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ACLU officials argued that the motto is a clear violation of
keeping church and state separate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those other states have much more casual or bland references
to God in their mottoes,'' said Raymond Vasvari, legal director for
the ACLU of Ohio based in Cleveland. ``Officials like (Ohio Gov.)
Bob Taft and (Attorney General) Betty Montgomery are downplaying
the fact that the state appropriated sacred text.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ruling, Taft and Montgomery are backing the state
motto and will appeal the court's decision to the full 13-judge
appellate court.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruling puzzled Dayton-area lawmakers, both Republicans
and Democrats, who said they see nothing wrong with the state
motto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty strongly about the separation between church and
state but I think this decision is off base,'' said state Rep. J.
Donald Mottley (R-West Carrollton). ``In God We Trust, One Nation
Under God, why are those constitutional and this isn't?''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Tom Roberts (D-Dayton) said the motto does not
promote religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a statement of fact, that's all,'' Roberts said.
``I guess we can dispute the religious implications of that all
day.''
</P>
<P>
   The court ruling against the motto was also criticized heavily
by Dayton-area ministers, who believe society has established a
crusade to eliminate references to God as part of daily life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a step backward,'' said Pastor Allen T. Ross of the
Kettering Assembly of God Church. ``It symbolizes an erosion of
values that are beneficial to our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Walker, youth pastor at Beavercreek Church, said the
decision is ``disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We go to great lengths to exclude mention of God in all
sectors of our life and where has it got us? We dismissed God from
schools and look at the state they are in,'' he said. ``I believe
that if I'm going to have a relationship with God, it reigns over
everything in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The state motto was adopted in 1959 when a 10-year-old school
boy, Jimmie Mastronardo, now 52 and living in Kentucky, learned
that Ohio didn't have a motto. That's when he suggested the phrase
``With God All Things Are Possible'' to his teacher because his
mother and grandmother used to say it all the time.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU's Vasvari compared the motto issue to the controversy
over whether public school districts should be allowed to display
the Ten Commandments on school grounds.
</P>
<P>
   As for state mottoes, most states have chosen patriotic sayings
or slogans that symbolize local history. But some seem a little
unusual, including:
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas _ ``The People Rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Maryland _ ``Manly deeds, womanly words.''
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico _ ``It Grows As It Goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas _ ``Friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington _ ``Bye &AMP; Bye.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin _ ``Forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Until this week's court ruling, some residents were unaware that
Ohio even had a motto and believe the controversy is a waste of
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a firm believer in the separation of church and state, but
I don't think it's hurting anybody to have the motto,'' said
Nannette Anderholdt, general manager at Kinko's in downtown Dayton.
``Just because it's the motto, that doesn't mean you have to abide
by it,'' she said. ``I think it's just a big brouhaha over
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
