<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8216 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-R-BUSH-ART-690&AMP;ADD-NY     04-26 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BUSH-ART-690&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH STRESSES BIPARTIANSHIP IN VISIT TO WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note; no other changes.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For once, George W. Bush was not acting like the
Washington outsider.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his rare visits to the nation's capital, and his first
since clinching the Republican presidential nomination, the Texas
governor Wednesday huddled privately with a Republican and a
Democratic senator on Social Security. He burnished his foreign
policy credentials by meeting with the Russian foreign minister,
Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   And he proved once again that he is a master fund-raiser,
bringing in $21.3 million for his party at a black tie dinner that
was a who's who of lobbyists and businesses with interests before
the government. Those represented included AT&AMP;T, the National Rifle
Association, Philip Morris Cos., the Blue Cross and Blue Shield
Association and the Chevron Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as he was toasted by the Washington establishment, Bush
tried to create some distance from it, criticizing ``eight years of
excessive partisanship and fingerpointing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton-Gore administration has been the most relentlessly
partisan administration in our nation's history,'' Bush told the
crowd of about 1,500 Republican officials and lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   ``But sometimes some in our own party have responded in kind,''
he said. ``Americans have seen a cycle of bitterness: an arms race
of anger. And both parties bear some of the blame. The legacy:
cynicism, a generic disgust. A feeling by too many Americans that
it doesn't matter who wins the election, you see they're all the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, cited the fund-raising event in
criticizing his Republican rival. Speaking to reporters in
Connecticut, Gore suggested that Bush's positions on issues had
been influenced by his donors, including the Philip Morris Cos. and
Wayne LaPierre, the executive vice president of the National Rifle
Association, who was a dinner co-chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fighting for common sense restrictions on the availability
of guns, but Governor Bush is receiving all this financial help
from the NRA and he is opposed to these common sense
restrictions,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush every trip to the nation's capital in this campaign
represents a delicate balancing act. Though Bush was an informal
adviser to his father when he was president, he is positioning
himself as an outsider from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He has cultivated relations with Republicans on Capitol Hill yet
at the same time stands as what he terms a new kind of Republican _
implicitly criticizing the Republican Congress that was led by Newt
Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when Bush came to Washington for a fund-raiser, he
included a somewhat triumphal tour through the Capitol, where he
was surrounded by Republican lawmakers. This time, he stayed blocks
away from the Capitol and any similar images, instead meeting with
lawmakers from his room at the J.W. Marriott hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, his communications director, said he had meetings
and receptions planned from 7:30 a.m. to 9:30 p.m. ``It was easier
for him to be able to have the kind of meetings he wanted to have
here without going over to the Hill,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with his wife, Laura, Bush did make one midday appearance
at a Republican women's forum that seemed the pinnacle of
Oprah-style politics, with the Bushes, two Republican lawmakers and
a series of guests _ young students and teachers _ all sitting on
chairs and couches arranged like a TV talk show set.
</P>
<P>
   Behind them, a large poster of girls and women acted as a
backdrop emblazoned with the words ``For Our Daughters.''
Introducing her husband, Laura Bush said, ``Since this is about our
daughters, I think I'll talk about our own daughters and the way
he's been as a dad.'' She said, ``He actually got up in the middle
of the night and fed the babies with me and changed the diapers.''
</P>
<P>
   When he came on stage to cheers and applause, Bush thanked his
wife, saying, ``you read it just like I wrote it.'' He quickly
added that he was happy to be with ``three really brilliant
women,'' referring to his wife and the two moderators, Rep.
Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., and Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Such education events have left Bush running well among women
who in past elections have favored Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the day Bush held closed-door meetings at his hotel,
and senior members of his campaign team planned to stay in
Washington for the rest of the week to meet with senior
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the meeting with Ivanov, Bush held a one-hour
session on Social Security with Sens. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., and Bob
Kerrey, D-Neb..
</P>
<P>
   The two have sponsored a wide-ranging measure to overhaul the
Social Security system that includes as one element individual
accounts that would be opened at citizens' birth.
</P>
<P>
   Bush pointed to that meeting later at the Republican fund-raiser
to show that he was willing to work with Democrats. Kerrey, who is
the chairman of Gore's campaign in Nebraska, but differs with the
vice president on Social Security said he was not bothered by the
mention.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it produces some bipartisan middle ground on this issue
I'll think this meeting has been worthwhile,'' Kerrey said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been showcasing Democrats all this week. But for all
his protests about partisanship, he and the other Republican
speakers were unsparing of Gore at the party's gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, the Republican National Committee chairman, said,
``Welcome to the RNC's Al Gore retirement party.'' And Bush lashed
into his opponent calling him ``an integral part of an
administration that has waged the same old Washington blame game.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``Last week was Earth Day. Unfortunately for Al Gore's
campaign every day is scorched earth day. And it's time to clean up
the toxic environment in Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush vowed, ``Make no mistake about this. When I am attacked in
this campaign I will respond.''
</P>
<P>
   As the keynote speaker, Bush helped his party raise an expected
$21.3 million Wednesday night, a one-night record, including the
unregulated unlimited donations that his primary opponent, Sen.
John McCain had campaigned against.
</P>
</TEXT>
