<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Wednesday, 04/26/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) WASHINGTON -- April 26, 2000 -- BUSH -- Gov. George W.
Bush talked with Elena Douglass on Wednesday at a meeting of the
Republican Women's Forum. Yet even as he was toasted by the
Washington establishment, Bush tried to create some distance from
it, criticizing ``eight years of excessive partisanship and
fingerpointing.'' (Carol T. Powers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) CHICAGO -- April 26, 2000 -- MATH-SCHOOLS -- In Chicago,
the Daniel Boone School has been a laboratory for the development
of a constructivist math program. Here, some of Mila Kell's fifth
graders learned about sampling by using painted and unpainted
beans. (Todd Buchanan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- April 26, 2000 -- OBIT-MERRICK-B&AMP;W -- David
Merrick, the producer whose gift for creating Broadway hits was
matched only by his genius for attracting publicity and making
enemies, died Tuesday in his sleep at St. George's Rest Home in
London. He was 88. Merrick is shown outside the Imperial Theater in
1959, where ``Suzie Wong'' had been playing. (Sam Falk/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- April 26, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-RAPTORS-2 --
Marcus Camby of the New York Knicks getting run over by Vince
Carter (No. 15) of the Toronto Raptors during Game Two of their
opening round series at Madison Square Garden on Wednesday night.
The Knicks lead the series, 1-0. (Barton Silverman/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- April 26, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-RAPTORS-1 --
Latrell Sprewell of the New York Knicks in action during Game Two
of the opening round series against the Toronto Raptors at Madison
Square Garden on Wednesday night. The Knicks lead the series, 1-0.
(Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) HUE, Vietnam -- April 26, 2000 -- VIETNAM-MILITARY --
Members of the Air Force's 353rd Special Operations Group helped
Vietnamese volunteers load relief supplies into a truck last
November. Americans in uniform had not undertaken a mission in
Vietnam since 1975. (U.S. Air Force/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- April 26, 2000 -- OBIT-TOBIA -- Sister Mary
Geraldine Tobia, a longtime co-director of the Center for Family
Life in Sunset Park, a social service agency serving people in that
section of Brooklyn, died Tuesday at Mount Sinai Hospital in
Manhattan. She was 59. (Center for Family Life/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- April 26, 2000 -- NY-BLACK-CIRCUS-2 -- The
Universoul Circus, which has pitched its big top in the southeast
corner of Prospect Park in Brooklyn through May 7, bills itself as
the nation's only black-owned circus. ``There aren't many black
circus families,'' said Vicki Amedume, 24, who performs on the
trapeze. ``Physical black people think about going into dance or
sports. But this circus opens people up to the idea they can do
anything.'' (Michelle V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- April 26, 2000 -- NY-BLACK-CIRCUS -- Like an
actor in community theater who dreams of Broadway, Robert Dunn -
Onionhead to his fans - lusted after a shot under the lights of the
big top. So Dunn, 58, worked his way up at the Universoul Circus -
which bills itself as the nation's only black-owned circus - from
assistant cook to crowd-pleasing clown. On Wednesday, Dunn took a
little too much cotton candy from a little fan after a performance
in Brooklyn's Prospect Park. (Michelle V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) SAN FRANCISCO -- April 26, 2000 -- BIOTECH-VENTURE-BOS
-- For the last three years, it seems that venture capitalists have
been willing to invest in anything - anything, that is, but
biotechnology. But tapping European money sources, MPM Capital's
president, Dr. Ansbert Gadicke, quickly raised $230 million for his
Cambridge-based firm, which has invested in 25 companies in less
than three years. Gadicke video conferenced with Luke Evnin in San
Francisco. (Janet Knott/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- April 26, 2000 -- JESUS-TRIAL-BOS --
From left, Allen Callahan, Harvey Cox and Alan Dershowitz, a law
professor and trial attorney, during ``The Trial of Jesus of
Nazareth,'' held Tuesday during a meeting of ``Contemporary
Interpretations of Jesus,'' the course Cox and Callahan are
teaching at Harvard Divinity School. The roles of prosecutor
(Callahan) and defense attorney (Dershowitz) were invented to
personify the forces for and against Jesus. (Bill Greene/The Boston
Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- April 26, 2000 -- TAUBMAN-AUCTION-2 -- Amidst
allegations that Sotheby's, the venerable auction house, conspired
with its chief rival, Christie's, to split business and fix
commissions, A. Alfred Taubman, 75, resigned in February as
chairman and is now stepping down as a director of Sotheby's.
Taubman graced the cover of Business Week on Sept. 4, 1971. (The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- April 26, 2000 -- TAUBMAN-AUCTION-1-B&AMP;W --
Amidst allegations that Sotheby's, the venerable auction house,
conspired with its chief rival, Christie's, to split business and
fix commissions, A. Alfred Taubman, 75, the shopping mall magnate
who has made a second career out of rescuing companies-in-distress
from the arms of unwelcome suitors, resigned in February as
chairman and is now stepping down as a director of Sotheby's.
Taubman went out on the town with his wife, Judy, in New York in
1992. (The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) HARTFORD, Conn. -- April 26, 2000 -- AETNA-HEALTHCARE --
William H. Donaldson is driving hard to transform Aetna, the
nation's biggest health insurer, into a warm, consumer-friendly
company that makes more profits and fewer enemies. In his first 60
days as chief executive, he has sidestepped fights with belligerent
trial lawyers, began healing strained relations with doctors and
hired an executive search firm to find a leader for Aetna's health
care business. (George Ruhe/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- April 26, 2000 -- GERMANY-RUSSIA-LOOT --
Konstantin Akinsha, an art scholar and specialist on Soviet trophy
art who now works at the United States Advisory Commission on
Holocaust Assets, helped retrieve 101 drawings for Germany. This
weekend, the drawings will surface together for the first time at
an exchange ceremony to be attended by President Vladimir V. Putin
of Russia and Culture Minister Michael Naumann of Germany. (Carol
T. Powers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- April 26, 2000 -- U.S.-HOLOCAUST-ART --
Picasso's ``Still Life: Job'' (1915), donated to the Museum of
Modern Art in 1979 by Nelson A. Rockefeller. Its wartime trail is
murky, which has fueled suspicions of a Nazi link. (Museum of
Modern Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- April 26, 2000 -- CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN --
Clockwise, from upper left: The Stowaway Portable Keyboard is a
full-size, folding keyboard that can turn handheld computers into a
laptop alternative. From Think Outside, $99; the Streetfinder GPS
is an attachment for Palm computers that gives a detailed location
and displays it on the screen. Rand McNally, $179; The Jornada 545
is more than just a personal information manager, it takes
advantage of the new Microsoft operating system for handhelds,
Pocket PC. Hewlett Packard, $499; The eyemodule Camera is a simple
digital camera that attaches to a Handspring Visor. Snapshots are
displayed on the screen and can be transferred to a desktop when
data is synchronized. From Design by IDEO, $149. (Tony Cenicola/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. -- April 26, 2000 --
PASSOVER-RESORTS -- Spending Passover at a hotel is becoming a
regular tradition for more and more families as Orthodox Jewish
women take jobs outside the home. Rabbi Mordechai Smolarcik, of
North Miami Beach, Fla., left, supervises meal preparation at the
Wyndham Resort &AMP; Spa. (Cindy Karp/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- April 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 30 --
TOMASSON-DANCE -- Helgi Tomasson, left, and Charles Askegard and
Maria Kowroski, right, rehearsing Tomasson's new work, ``Prism,''
for the New York City Ballet. In addition to leading his troupe to
a new level of achievement and international recognition, Tomasson
has choreographed 25 one-act ballets and his own productions of 4
classics there since taking over in June 1985. (Ozier Muhammad/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- April 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 30 --
DAWN-UPSHAW-MUSIC -- Dawn Upshaw and Dwayne Croft in the
Metropolitan Opera's production of Debussy's ``Pelleas et
Melisande.'' No sooner has Upshaw come up for air (after the
premiere of John Harbison's ``Great Gatsby'' and a run of ``Pelleas
et Melisande'') than she takes up ``Images of Dawn,'' an ambitious
series of three programs produced by Lincoln Center which starts
Sunday afternoon at Alice Tully Hall. (Sara Krulwich/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- April 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 30 --
MODERN-ART-MUSEUM -- The main event at the Museum of Modern Art
these days is the Museum of Modern Art itself. Such has been the
case since last fall, when a project called MOMA 2000 kicked off
with the first of what will be three successive top-to-bottom
reinstallations of the museum's permanent collection galleries.
``Agrarian Leader Zapata,'' a 1931 fresco by Diego Rivera, left,
and ``Help Spain'' (''Aidez l'Espagne''), a design for a postage
stamp by Joan Miro, 1937, are at the Modern. (Museum of Modern
Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ATLANTA -- April 26, 2000 -- ROOFTOP-COX -- Jerry Pair
on the deck of his midtown penthouse with a view of the Four
Seasons Hotel. Pair covered a barren concrete roof with wooden
decking and built a wisteria-draped pergola as a romantic outdoor
dining room. (Jean Shifrin/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- April 26, 2000 -- YARD-THEATER-REVIEW --
Sharon Duncan-Brewster, left, and Amelia Lowdell in ``Yard Gal.''
An import from the Royal Court Theater, this intense, lopsided
production, which opened Wednesday night, sets its pace by the
pharmaceutically exaggerated rhythms of its characters, who number
two but who give the impression of being about 10 times that many.
(Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- April 26, 2000 -- MOMA-SCULPTURE -- Shigeru
Ban's latticework, made of self-supporting cardboard tubes, curves
over the Abby Aldrich Rockefeller sculpture garden at the Museum of
Modern Art. Weighing six tons and spanning 87 feet, it has a
lightness of being, a kinetic energy. And even though it is solidly
bolted in place, it looks like a giant box kite about to snap its
string and take off into the sky. Below, the designer took time to
enjoy his work. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- April 26, 2000 -- SUB-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W --
Many beginning woodworkers think that gluing is simple and
straightforward. Actually, the task is a lot more complicated.
First it is important to use the right glue. While it might seem
that all glues are pretty much alike, they differ in a number of
important properties: cost, convenience, assembly and setting time,
and application. (Edward R. Lipinski/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MONTECITO, Calif. -- April 26, 2000 -- MONTECITO-LADN --
For nearly a century, Montecito has been favored by captains of
industry, power players of the silver screen and vacationers
desperate for solitude. The patio of Pierre LaFond is a nice place
to sit and eat in the town in the foothills of the Santa Ynez
Mountains, overlooking the Pacific Ocean and the Channel Islands.
(Michael Owen Baker/Los Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LAKE PARK, Fla. -- April 26, 2000 -- ELIAN-SOPHONIE-COX
-- Sophonie Telcy, motherless, adrift, in the eyes of the law an
illegal alien, is not Elian Gonzalez, and many Haitians know it. It
is hard to find a speck of resentment about Elian in the Haitian
neighborhoods that dot South Florida. But what, they ask, about
Sophonie? Sophonie Telcy colors in her kindergarten class at Lake
Park elementary. (Sherman Zent/Cox News Service) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- April 26, 2000 -- SCI-COSMOLOGY -- Astronomers
are both elated and puzzled over the first clear pictures ever
taken of the infant universe. This image, approximately 1000 square
degrees of the southern sky, shows the distant universe as it makes
its transition from a glowing 4892 degrees Fahrenheit plamsa to a
cooler transparent gas, approximately 14 billion years ago, a mere
300,000 years after the Big Bang. (NASA/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- April 26, 2000 -- CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI --
Marisleysis Gonzalez, second cousin of six-year-old Elian Gonzalez,
and her father Lazaro Gonzalez, the child's great-uncle, listen as
a child psychiatrist speaks to reporters during a news conference
in a Senate hearing room, Wednesday. Several doctors spoke to
reporters expressing their views on the impact of Elian Gonzalez's
forced removal his great-uncle's house in Miami for a reunion with
his father last Saturday. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- April 26, 2000 -- DECORATOR-SHOWCASE-2 -- 16
designers were represented at the 28th annual Kips Bay Boys and
Girls Club Decorator Show House this year; at least 7 of the 16
rooms would cost a client more than $1 million, retail. The most
formal space in the house was a lounge: John Barman and John Levy's
plastic-mirror-paneled, 1970s-inspired disco stair-landing.
(Antoine Bootz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- April 26, 2000 -- DECORATOR-SHOWCASE-1 -- 16
designers were represented at the 28th annual Kips Bay Boys and
Girls Club Decorator Show House this year; at least 7 of the 16
rooms would cost a client more than $1 million, retail. Anderson,
Papachristidis Raeymaekers Interiors created this pricey room:
Chintz to doughnuts, a reporter's dawn was enacted underneath a
Warhol silk-screen of Elizabeth Taylor. (Antoine Bootz/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- April 26, 2000 -- KOSOVO-PROTEST
-- Kosovar Albanians block a NATO armored vehicle during a protest
calling for the release of ethnic Albanian prisoners held in Serb
jails, Wednesday. Ethnic Albanian prisoners were transferred from
Kosovo to jails in the rest of Serbia during the retreat of Serbian
forces from the disputed province ahead of the arrival of KFOR
troops in June 1999. The vehicle was eventually allowed to pass.
(Alan Chin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- April 26, 2000 -- CIR-SIMS-VIRUS -- A guinea
pig that can be obtained from the official Sims Web site is not
just a household pet. It also carries a virus and can infect human
characters in the game Sims, causing them to fall ill and,
sometimes, die. The sequence of infection to death is seen starting
at upper left progressing clockwise to bottom right. (Sims/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
