<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORTER OF BATTLE FLAG SWITCHES; SIERRA CLUB WEIGHS IN; BUSH TOPS
$78 MILLION; RACE FOR NEBRASKA SEAT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Neb.)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, it was Sen. John McCain who changed his mind and said
the Confederate battle flag should no longer fly atop the South
Carolina Capitol. This week, McCain's best-known supporter in the
state, Rep. Lindsey Graham of the 3rd Congressional District,
ventured the same opinion, saying he now supports the state
Senate's proposal to remove the flag and put a smaller version on a
Confederate monument in front of the Capitol. But Graham, a flag
supporter who had urged McCain to stay away from the issue in the
South Carolina primary, lest it cost him votes, added a qualifier
to his change of mind. The flag, he told The Associated Press on
Monday, should stay where it is if the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People continues its economic boycott of the
state. Still, said Graham, who has his eye on a Senate seat, the
flag is eventually going to come down.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA CLUB WEIGHS IN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club has begun an $8 million television and radio
campaign aimed at 17 House and Senate races. The commercials,
mostly praising Democrats, are focused on tight races in which the
club believes it has the best chance to make a difference. The
commercials will be combined with other campaign efforts, the club
officials say, including mass distribution of voter guides and
fliers. The officials say they also plan to run presidential
campaign commercials that criticize the environmental record of
Gov. George W. Bush in Texas and may throw in advertising that
praises Vice President Al Gore. The club has not made public where
it got the money to pay for the advertising campaign and under
federal tax and election regulations is not required to do so.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH TOPS $78 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   Continuing his record fund-raising pace, Gov. George W. Bush
pulled in an additional $6.4 million in campaign donations in
March, bringing his total for the race to $78.6 million. But at the
same time, new campaign finance figures show, he spent $10.2
million and ended the month with $6.8 million in the bank. Vice
President Al Gore pulled in $4.4 million in March, bringing his
total fund-raising for the campaign to $40.4 million. He spent $4.7
million and ended the month with $3.8 million on hand. Gore has
aggressively used the Internet as a campaign financing tool,
raising slightly over $1.1 million online through Feb. 15. By
comparison, Bush has raised $350,000 online. Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., remains the most successful online presidential
fund-raiser, pulling in $4.3 million electronically, followed by
former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey with $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   RACE FOR NEBRASKA SEAT
</P>
<P>
   As the May 9 primaries approach for Nebraska's open U.S. Senate
seat, fund-raising figures for the two leading Republican
contenders show that in the first half of April, Secretary of State
Scott Moore raised more than twice as much as Attorney General Don
Stenberg _ $51,000 to $24,000. For the year, Moore now leads
Stenberg $224,000 to $144,000 in fund-raising. But polls have
Stenberg running ahead in the race itself, and overall in the
campaign he has raised more than Moore _ $399,000 to $224,000 _ in
part because he started a year earlier. Still, Moore now says he
has the momentum in the contest on the basis of his latest
fund-raising effort. On the Democratic side, former Gov. Ben Nelson
faces no serious opposition in his nomination quest and, despite a
late entry in the race, is well ahead of both Republicans in money
raising, having taken in $129,000 in the first half of April, for a
total of $763,000 for the campaign. More to the point, he also
leads both Republicans in the polls. The incumbent senator, Bob
Kerrey, a Democrat, is retiring. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Greensboro, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Pittsburgh, Philadelphia
</P>
</TEXT>
