<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TRADE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS ACQUIRE FORMER SMU LINEBACKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys yesterday acquired former SMU
linebacker Chris Bordano from the New Orleans Saints in a trade for
oft-injured cornerback Kevin Mathis, and the Cowboys probably won't
stop there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trade shouldn't be looked at as a reflection on Kevin
Mathis ... \Rbecause\S it wasn't,'' Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said.
``We liked the way \RMathis\S competed for us, and we like the
depth that Chris Bordano now provides at linebacker as well as
special teams. Mainly it came down to what we believe makes our
football team look better numbers-wise.''
</P>
<P>
   Translated: The Cowboys had too many cornerbacks and not enough
linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXXIV starting middle linebacker Barron Wortham, an
Everman native who has expressed a strong desire to play for the
Cowboys, was released by the Tennessee Titans on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Bordano does not preclude the Cowboys signing
a veteran free-agent linebacker with NFL experience, such as
Wortham, Joe Bowden (Tennessee unrestricted free agent), William
Thomas (released by Philadelphia) or Darrin Smith (released by
Seattle).
</P>
<P>
   We will continue to look at \Rimproving\S our depth at
linebacker,'' Jones said. ``We will evaluate Wortham along with
some others out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans released Wortham midway through a four-year, $8.4
million contract in large part due to the free-agent signing of
Randall Godfrey, who left the Cowboys for a five-year, $25 million
deal in February.
</P>
<P>
   This led to the promotion of Dat Nguyen to Cowboys' starting
middle linebacker followed by yesterday's trade for Bordano. It has
been made clear that Nguyen is still the starter, but Bordano is
excited about being back in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity, and we're going to take advantage of
it,'' said Bordano, who tutored elementary school children in
Dallas while attending SMU. ``We're going home. Hopefully, I can
compete this year for a starting job. And if not, I'll do whatever
I can do to help the team, including special teams.''
</P>
<P>
   All 18 of Bordano's NFL starts in two seasons in New Orleans
came at middle linebacker, although he can play outside as well.
</P>
<P>
   Bordano ``brings some depth at a position where we need it,''
Cowboys linebackers coach George Edwards said. ``Everybody is
coming in to compete for a job. Nothing is etched in stone. That's
what you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis, who missed eight games with injuries last season after
winning a starting job from Kevin Smith at the end of 1998, was
signed to the Cowboys' tendered offer of $472,000 just before the
trade forBordano was made.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Williams, who has all but signed a one-year contract for
the veteran's minimum of $440,000 with the Cowboys, stays because
he has shown more durability than Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Deion Sanders is expected to be released by the
Cowboys after June 1. Still, the Cowboys have seven cornerbacks who
figure to make the 53-man roster: Ryan McNeil, Smith, Williams,
Duane Hawthorne, and rookie draft picks Dwayne Goodrich of
Tennessee, Kareem Larrimore of West Texas A&AMP;M and Mario Edwards of
Florida State. Staff writer Clarence E. Hill Jr., contributed to
this report
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
