<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8224 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FATHER-DAUGHTER-TEX     04-26 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FATHER-DAUGHTER-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Asking a teen-ager to spend time with their
parents is usually like asking a puppy to cuddle with a badger.
</P>
<P>
   They're not doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Paschal senior student-trainer Wende Pippin if she minds
spending time with her father, she doesn't mind so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would just put up with it to meet some hot
football players,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As parents take their daughters to work on ``National Take Your
Daughters to Work Day'' Jim Pippin is in the unique position of
taking his daughter to work not only today, but every day.
</P>
<P>
   He is the head athletic trainer at Paschal High School and his
only daughter is a member of his student staff.
</P>
<P>
   Sound awkward? It can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand it would be a little awkward,'' she said.
``Any problems we have here get carried over a little to home. But,
this gives me time with my dad I wouldn't have had otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 53-year old trainer who has suffered two heart attacks,
it provides him with the opportunity to work with one of his
children, something he hasn't done since sons Cade and Derek worked
alongside him as lifeguards in Fort Worth more than 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For the 18-year old teen-ager who has been more interested in
theater, it provides her with the chance to be around dad, meet
students she probably would never have met, and learn about
something she previously had little interest in: sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned some things about my daughter I didn't know,''
said Pippin, who has been in the business since 1970 and worked at
Paschal for the past two years and with his daughter since January
1999. ``It helps to see her learn some values in athletics and gain
some interest in it. I've seen that come through in her and it
makes me proud.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been one of the best years I have had in training.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that one of the best years in his professional career
doesn't come without some headaches. After all, she's a well spoken
_ and sometimes outspoken _ teen-ager whose father is laid back and
relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times she gets so mad at him; she thinks he didn't
do something or should have handled something differently,'' her
mother, Marcia, said. ``If she's mad she might come home and only
says, `I'm taking a walk.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the only thing Wende Pippin got mad about her
father's job was the amount of time it requires. Now that she's a
part of it, things are different.
</P>
<P>
   ``She used to only be into theater and didn't really care about
sports,'' said Marcia, who is a self-described football mom. ``She
used to never want to go to games. Now, she understands football.''
</P>
<P>
   She understands it so well she is known to give coaches advice
on plays.
</P>
<P>
   She understands it so well that her grand intention of meeting
the aforementioned ``hot football players'' has a fatal flaw: dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are scared of him,'' Marcia said. ``She might have a
crush on one of them but he will call him stupid or something so
they won't ask her out.''
</P>
<P>
   He understands her so well that if he can't communicate
something to a staff member or student-athlete, she can.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we can hear him and understand him, we knows he's
serious,'' said Wende Pippin, who is affectionately referred to as
``mom'' by some of the student-athletes.
</P>
<P>
   None of this means that she is on a path to follow in her
father's footsteps. To the contrary _ she plans on earning her
massage therapy license to help pay for college. If she can work in
athletic training in college to curb some of the costs, great.
</P>
<P>
   And what happens if or when Wende changes her mind and asks her
father to help her become a professional athletic trainer?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd ask him to slap me,'' she said. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
