<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8228 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-DODGERS27-     04-26 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-DODGERS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves dig the long ball
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the midst of their longest April winning streak
since 1982, when the Braves set a major-league record by winning
their first 13 games, no Brave wants to flinch first.
</P>
<P>
   So to follow Tom Glavine's 1-0 shutout against Kevin Brown,
Kevin Millwood put himself to the task of keeping a good thing
going. Millwood stretched the Braves' win streak to nine with a 5-1
victory Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Like their Opening Day of 2000, the Braves got back-to-back home
runs _ this time from Andruw Jones and Chipper Jones _ to give
Millwood a 2-0 headstart. That's all he would need, as he allowed
one run in seven innings for his second consecutive victory.
</P>
<P>
   That kept alive the chances for a perfect nine-game homestand.
The Braves have one game remaining at Turner Field before they head
to the West Coast to play the Padres and the Dodgers. One more
victory today and the Braves will have matched their longest
winning streak since Aug. 19-29.
</P>
<P>
   Andres Galarraga chipped in with his eighth home run of the
season in the sixth inning. It moved him into a tie with Steve
Finley and Barry Bonds for the National League lead. Quilvio Veras
added two hits and one RBI, and Chipper Jones drove in two runs for
the first time in more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones had given it a wide smile when hitting coach Merv
Rettenmund dished some grief his way during batting practice
Wednesday. ``I sure wish you'd get an offensive highlight,''
Rettenmund said in reference to Jones' ninth-inning diving catch to
help save Glavine's 1-0 shutout Tuesday night. And then he did
something about it.
</P>
<P>
   He jump-started the Braves offensively with a home run off
rookie Eric Gagne in the third inning, which was followed two
pitches later by Chipper Jones' fourth homer of the year. This one
ended a 41 at-bat homerless stretch for Chipper Jones, who hit his
first three homers at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers broke their string of 24 consecutive scoreless
innings with an unearned run off Millwood in the fourth to draw
within 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   The run came on a checked-swing bouncer up the middle by Gagne
with two outs and the bases loaded. Walt Weiss charged in on it but
couldn't secure it for his fifth error of the season as Eric Karros
scored from third.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Millwood allowed only one runner past first in seven
innings. He allowed five hits and struck out seven.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
