<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BOURQUE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE'S FIRST CHANGE OF ADDRESS MEANS ODD SURROUNDINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Do the jerseys fit the same? Is it hard
getting around in a new city? What's it like?
</P>
<P>
   There were so many questions, he couldn't think of them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was nervous,'' winger Dave Andreychuk said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Bourque doesn't get nervous. Then again, Ray Bourque doesn't
get traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a long talk about it on the plane going to Calgary. He
asked a lot of questions on what to expect,'' Andreychuk said of
his conversation with Bourque after they were traded from Boston to
Colorado in March.
</P>
<P>
   It was move No. 4 for Andreychuk. No. 1 for Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was worried about his family and making sure they are OK
back in Boston,'' Andreychuk said. ``It could be only until June,
but it was a chance he had to take. I told them the organizations
would be different. You are going to see different things.
Hockey-wise, he was going to fit right in.''
</P>
<P>
   How could Bourque know? This is a player who had played 21
seasons in the same city. This is a player who is the Bruins'
all-time leader in scoring and games played.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what shirt he's wearing,'' said Phoenix
Coyotes forward Jeremy Roenick, who grew up in the Boston area,
``there's still a Boston Bruins shirt underneath it.''
</P>
<P>
   This was trading Bobby Orr to the Montreal Canadiens. This was
trading Larry Bird to the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   This is what Ray Bourque wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the one who asked for it,'' Bourque said. ``But, when it
happens you deal with a lot of different emotions. I've never been
through it before. It's just a change in terms of a new town, new
teammates, a new jersey, a new room and a whole new situation you
have never been through.''
</P>
<P>
   This was exactly what Bourque _ and Colorado _ needed.
</P>
<P>
   In an age of the nomad athlete, Bourque was the exception. But,
being 39 and his playing days fading, the desire for one last shot
at the Stanley Cup was greater than the need to finish his career
as a Bruins player.
</P>
<P>
   Round 2 of Bourque's shot begins at 9 tonight in Denver when the
Avalanche plays Detroit in Game 1 of a Western Conference semifinal
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a double-sided coin,'' Roenick said. ``You don't
want him to get traded because he's a Boston guy forever. But the
flip side is, with the career he's had, not to have a Stanley Cup
would be a sin.''
</P>
<P>
   The sin is that Bourque, who leads all NHL players in games
played without a Stanley Cup, hasn't had a chance at one since
1990, when Edmonton defeated the Bruins, 4-1, in the Stanley Cup
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado went looking for its own Stanley Cup revival on March 6
when it traded forward Brian Rolston, defenseman Martin Grenier,
center Sami Pahlsson and Boston's choice of a first-round pick in
either 2000 or 2001 for Andreychuk and the five-time Norris Trophy
winner and 18-time All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone believes they have a chance again,'' ESPN hockey
analyst Barry Melrose said. ``I'm not sure Colorado thought they
had a chance \Reight\S weeks ago, but now they feel they can
compete with the Big Three \RDetroit, St. Louis and the Stars\S.''
</P>
<P>
   With Bourque, one of the NHL's best on the power play, the
Avalanche has been playing at its highest level since late last
season, when they pushed the Stars to seven games in the Western
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be like if \RWayne\S Gretzky was with \RJoe\S Sakic
or a guy like \RMario\S Lemieux,'' Stars center Guy Carbonneau
said.
</P>
<P>
   With Bourque in tow, Colorado finished the regular-season 14-2-1
as he scored 14 points in 14 games. The Avalanche rolled past
first-round opponent Phoenix, 4-1. Bourque had four assists and is
the key reason why Colorado's power play is firing at 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tremendous player, future Hall of Famer and everything,
so he would make any team much better,'' Detroit defenseman Niklas
Lidstrom said. ``And with the depth that they have already there,
he has kind of helped their team even more.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockey-wise, the move has been easy. But for a man with a wife,
three children and a legacy as long as any Boston sports icon, it's
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a role model for a lot of people throughout the
years,'' Roenick said. ``Myself, Keith Tkachuk, are just two of
them. Going to Boston Garden every Saturday night and watching him,
All-Star game after All-Star game.''
</P>
<P>
   But the hard part is about leaving an organization that is as
much of him as the Detroit Red Wings were to Gordie Howe. It's
about being away from his family longer than an average road trip
or extended preseason workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are with me 100 percent,'' said Bourque, whose children
are 16, 14 and 9. ``I talk to them every day. They knew something
would happen, and we talked about it, and they know I am in a good
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche has flown his family to Denver to be with him a
few times already, easing the transition. It also helps that a
familiar face _ Andreychuk _ lives nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more to coming somewhere else than just playing
hockey,'' said Andreychuk, who is with his fifth team in his
18-year career. ``For me, the more you move, the easier it gets.
The good thing is the two of us were there together, and now we're
staying close to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   For Colorado, the move couldn't have come at a better time. The
Avalanche labored through a regular season in which it was supposed
to compete with Detroit and the Stars for the top spot in the
Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, injuries and mediocre play led to the Avalanche's
fighting Edmonton for first place in the Northwest Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure, we had a disappointing regular season,'' Colorado's
Adam Deadmarsh said. ``When Ray and Dave came, it seemed to light a
candle in the room and raise our confidence level. I think it's
what we needed to go in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Is playing another season part of Bourque's direction for the
future? He's not sure. His body has a lot of ice time and frequent
flier miles and it may be telling him ``enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an adjustment, and there are a lot of little things to
adjust to, but it's been great,'' Bourque said. ``It's a great
team, and I am with a team I think I can help. It's a situation I
wanted to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a situation he needed to be in. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
