<HEADER>
A8232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-REPORT-NYT &LR;      04-26 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAFT REPORT BY RIGHTS PANEL SCOLDS NEW YORK POLICE ON RACE
RELATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A draft report from the U.S. Commission on Civil
Rights says that the New York Police Department's own records
indicate that its officers engage in racial profiling and suggests
that the city consider creating a law enforcement ``mechanism,''
independent of local prosecutors, to pursue serious accusations of
police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   In the 250-page draft, the panel applauds the department for
several efforts to improve its relationship with minorities, but
characterizes its overall approach to race relations as flawed in
everything from training to promotions.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-member panel, which consists of four Democrats, three
independents and one Republican, is appointed by the president and
Congress and makes advisory reports on civil rights issues. It
cannot compel changes in policy.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's report has been greatly anticipated, in part because
the Police Department's frayed relationship with blacks and
Hispanics is under scrutiny and in part because Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani has called the panel a ``political operation of the
Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   He has dismissed the report as an attempt to aid his rival in
the race for the U.S. Senate, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The draft report, a copy of which was obtained by The New York
Times, was prepared by the commission's staff. It may be amended by
the panel after further deliberations. The mayor and the Police
Department received copies Wednesday and have 20 days to offer
rebuttals.
</P>
<P>
   Even though its findings are largely critical, the draft report
is restrained in its language, and there are several discussions of
disputed issues in which the commission acknowledges that
statistics support the Police Department's version of events. For
instance, although critics have suggested that psychological
screenings were being used to block minority candidates from the
Police Department, the commission found that the statistics did not
support that contention.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most far-reaching recommendations in the report is the
suggestion that the city create an undefined mechanism to prosecute
serious accusations of police brutality instead of using local
district attorneys ``who must work with the police on a routine
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   The report also says that the city should create an independent
monitor to review how citizen complaints of police misconduct are
handled and that the department should reshape its diversity
training, which it found defective.
</P>
<P>
   The report's most biting criticism is the conclusion that ``the
NYPD's data strongly suggests that racial profiling plays some role
in the stop-and-frisk practices of the overall department.'' For
example, the report says that data from 1998 indicated that 51
percent of the people stopped and searched by the police on Staten
Island were black, even though the island's population is only 9
percent black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere African-Americans were stopped far out of their
proportion in any of the communities policed,'' the report says.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, the Giuliani administration has sought to portray the
report as a political instrument written by Democrats to tarnish
Giuliani's record and promote the candidacy of Clinton, to whom the
panel's chairwoman, Mary Frances Berry, has made a political
donation of $250.
</P>
<P>
   ``The civil rights commission is a partisan political joke,'' a
spokeswoman for Giuliani, Sunny Mindel, said Wednesday. ``Their
report is predicated on events of over a year ago and does not take
into adequate account the NYPD's record of restraint.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Giuliani's biggest complaints has been his contention
that the commission did little research beyond holding a daylong
hearing last year. Giuliani has also faulted the commission for the
decision to examine New York when other cities like Washington,
where the panel is based, had higher incidences of excessive-force
cases by the police.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission has said it could hardly ignore New York
after the police torture of Abner Louima and the police shooting of
Amadou Diallo led to large demonstrations in which critics charged
that the department had trampled civil rights, especially of blacks
and Hispanics, in its zeal to cut crime.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Police officials would not comment on the draft report, saying
that the commission's rules state that the report should not be
discussed before a final version is approved. But in recent days,
officials have released a series of statistics to demonstrate that
the department is restrained in its use of force.
</P>
<P>
   One tabulation showed that the number of citizen complaints of
excessive force has been dropping rapidly since 1995, when officers
were nearly twice as likely to be accused of that form of
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the commission, Kimberly Alton, said she could
not discuss or elaborate on the draft report until it had been
approved for release by the panel.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which was created by the Civil Rights Act of
1957, is the second outside agency to criticize how the police stop
and search citizens. Last year, Attorney General Eliot L. Spitzer
found a similar disproportion in the number of blacks and Hispanics
who were stopped, although he did not accuse the department of
racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have defended the street searches as a pivotal tactic
and have said more blacks and Hispanics are stopped because more
officers are deployed in high-crime neighborhoods with high
minority populations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
