<SLUG> BC-NY-CASINO-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT SEEKS TO OVERTURN MOHAWK CASINO DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A dissident group of St. Regis Mohawk Indians at the Akwesasne
Reservation on the Canadian border filed suit in tribal court
Wednesday seeking to overturn a secret agreement between six Mohawk
chiefs and the largest gaming company in the world, Park Place
Entertainment, to build and manage casinos in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks to restore the Mohawk tribe's longstanding
partnership with Catskill Development, a group in the Catskills
that had won federal approval earlier this month to build a $500
million casino at the Monticello Raceway in Sullivan County, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed on behalf of 29 members of the Mohawk tribe,
contends that the chiefs were deceived into signing an April 14
agreement that grants Park Place exclusive rights over Mohawk
casinos throughout New York in return for a $3 million loan and a
portion of future profits. They said that Park Place was more
interested in derailing the Monticello project and protecting its
three casinos in Atlantic City, N.J., from competition than in
helping the tribe, a claim vehemently denied by the gaming company.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Place deal and the lawsuit place a cloud over prospects
for gambling in the Catskills just as the tribe and its original
partners appeared to be on the verge of achieving their goal after
more than four years of negotiations and regulatory reviews.
Whatever the intentions of Park Place, the casino project now faces
almost certain delays and other legal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chiefs were duped,'' said Michael Rhodes-Devey, a lawyer
who filed the suit on behalf of a group that includes former
members of the tribal government. ``Park Place is attempting to
deprive the people of St. Regis of countless jobs and hundreds of
millions of dollars through their illegal and unethical conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Clive Cummis, general counsel for Park Place, disputed the
claims. ``The tribal leaders were not fraudulently induced,'' he
said. ``We don't do business that way. They made a good deal with a
good company.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the tribal leaders did not consult the lawyers they
hired to work on casino gambling, Cummis insisted that the chiefs
had legal counsel when they signed the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The chiefs, who were meeting Wednesday in Hogansburg, N.Y., to
discuss the Park Place deal, did not return telephone calls
requesting comment. According to one Mohawk executive, the chiefs
were hoping that Park Place could solve the problems at its small,
money-losing casino in Hogansburg and assure lucrative operations
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Their agreement specifies that Park Place must begin building a
casino within three years and that the tribe would get 70 percent
of the profits. Some Mohawks and gaming analysts say that Arthur M.
Goldberg, Park Place's chief executive, said he could get approval
for the project within four months, a claim they found improbable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
