<SLUG> BC-SCOUTS-SPEECH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONNIE ST. JOHN DEANE DELIVERS STORY OF INSPIRATION TO GIRL
SCOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT STEARNS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Her family didn't have much money. Her leg
was amputated when she was 5 because of a birth defect.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie St. John Deane could have admitted defeat at an early
age.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of giving up, Deane never stopped pushing, never let an
obstacle get in the way of her goals.
</P>
<P>
   That perseverance led her to Harvard, to a Rhodes scholarship,
to jobs in the White House and on Wall Street, and to a career as
an author and motivational speaker. Not to mention silver and
bronze medals as a skier at the Paralympics.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to more than 900 Girl Scouts on Wednesday at the
Crown Center Exhibit Hall, Deane, wearing her silver medal on a
ribbon around her neck, shared the story of her rise to show the
young women that they, too, could overcome obstacles on their way
to fulfilling their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you know how to overcome obstacles, you can go anywhere
you want,'' Deane told the Scouts and their troop leaders. ``If an
African-American girl with one leg, from San Diego, where there's
no snow, can get to the olympics, what is possible for you?
Anything must be possible, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Deane's speech was part of Sweet Ambitions 2000, sponsored by
the Girl Scouts of Mid-Continent Council. The event was a kick-off
for today's Take Our Daughters to Work Day, occurring at businesses
in the Kansas City area and around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all part of trying to motivate girls,'' said Martha
Singleton, Girl Scouts spokeswoman. ``It's a celebration of girl
power. We want to prepare them for tomorrow and for their
careers.''
</P>
<P>
   The message is especially important for girls on the cusp of
adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Research shows that's when girls' confidence really
diminishes,'' Singleton said. ``We want to build their options and
their confidence in their futures.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany Spencer, a 10-year-old from Kansas City sitting right by
the stage for Deane's speech, was confident in her options. She
plans on becoming a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   And, said her mother, Suzy Spencer, Tiffany knew about
overcoming obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always tell her,'' Spencer said, ``winners never quit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' chimed in Tiffany, ``quitters never win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
