<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-DEBATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON AND GIULIANI AGREE TO TV DEBATE THIS FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Hillary Rodham Clinton
agreed Wednesday to what aides said was the first in what would be
a series of senatorial debates, accepting an invitation for a
statewide forum with Tim Russert, the host of ``Meet the Press,''
to be broadcast this fall on NBC affiliates across New York.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Giuliani and Clinton said details of this and other
debates remained to be worked out. But the agreement with Russert
appears to have moved the discussion about debates beyond the realm
of political jockeying and into the stage of actual negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Russert sent a personal letter to Clinton and Giuliani,
proposing two debates, one of which would be held Sept. 11 in
Buffalo, where Russert grew up. Giuliani and Clinton's campaign
manager, Bill de Blasio, agreed to the request in separate
conversations with Russert.
</P>
<P>
   Russert said some details, mainly having to do with format,
remained to be worked out, but he had no doubt that the event was
on track. ``From the very first day, both sides seemed very
optimistic and enthusiastic about debating,'' Russert said in an
interview. ``In my mind, both campaigns have accepted, and we're
very pleased. We look forward to very substantive, civil and
informative debates.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's campaign manager, Bruce J. Teitelbaum, said the mayor
had agreed to appear on both debates proposed by NBC, one on Sept.
11 in Buffalo and the other on Oct. 30. They would be shown on
MSNBC, as well as on NBC's New York affiliates. Clinton has so far
agreed to one of those debates but has not specified which one. De
Blasio, in a letter to Teitelbaum, said he had also accepted an
invitation for a debate sponsored by the League of Women Voters,
which would be broadcast over ABC affiliates. The Giuliani campaign
had no immediate response to that offer.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's advisers said Wednesday night that they were looking
forward to the debate, asserting that the mayor's experience in
politics and government would make him a formidable opponent to
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be refreshing to have Mrs. Clinton in a setting in
which she is finally required to answer real questions without
ducking, bobbing and weaving,'' Teitelbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's press secretary, Howard Wolfson, responded by alluding
to Giuliani's relative absence from the campaign trail. ``It'll be
refreshing if Mr. Giuliani is in a setting in which he begins to
talk about what he would do in the Senate and begins to offer a
positive view of what he would do in New York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
