<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAY EQUITY SHOULD BE A PRIORITY FOR ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a disconnect between what we say a job is worth and what
we're willing to pay someone to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Service companies tell their front-line workers they're the most
important customer relations agents they have _ and pay them the
least of any employees on the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Our society claims to value its children and creates
organizations to keep child-oriented issues in the forefront of
public consciousness _ yet pays child-care workers barely a living
wage.
</P>
<P>
   We've spent decades talking about gender equality and wage
parity between the sexes _ but women's average earnings are just 73
cents on the dollar compared with men's.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of economic theories to explain why people are
paid what they are. Supply and demand is one. We've heard since
elementary school that the price goes up when the commodity is
scarce.
</P>
<P>
   That's supposedly why the highest of high-tech workers have been
able to write their own tickets in recent years as companies fought
over them. But, despite severe shortages, the theory hasn't boosted
teachers' pay similarly.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the theory about paying what the market will bear.
We hear that from corporate compensation boards who explain the
``sun, moon and stars'' pay packages for their CEOs.
</P>
<P>
   In tough, competitive markets, company directors say they need
to pay top dollar for talent with a proven business track record.
Sales and stock prices are up, so the CEO is getting paid nothing
more than he (rarely she) is worth in terms of improved results.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side of ``worth,'' a story last month in The New
York Times highlighted a Vassar graduate who chose to be a
$37,000-a-year librarian. She lamented that fellow graduates ``are
investment bankers and lawyers and are making a quarter-million,
and I can't even afford to go out t dinner with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Is a librarian really worth that much less to society than
someone who decides where to put other people's money?
</P>
<P>
   That's oversimplification, of course, but it's worth serious
thought. We don't spend enough time battering down the pink-collar
ghetto that confines mostly female workers to lower-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the more familiar blue-collar sector _ largely and
historically male _ pink-collar jobs (such as child care) haven't
benefited from collective bargaining and market forces that pushed
blue-collar pay up to and, in some cases, beyond those of
white-collar professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when the National Committee on Pay Equity sent out
press materials for its annual Pay Equity Day, the packet contained
a button that asked, ``Where's My 26 Cents?'' in reference to the
earnings gap between women and men.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the press packet sent in advance of the May 11
observation also held a button. This one asks, ``Where's Her 27
Cents?''
</P>
<P>
   Note that the earnings disparity rose by a penny on the dollar.
That's the wrong direction to bring pink-collar relief.
</P>
<P>
   Note, too, that the question is framed differently. At least
this year, someone other than the aggrieved is doing the asking.
It's a question everyone has the responsibility to ask.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
