u a BC-MEAT-AD-COLUMN-NYT     04-26 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAT-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW EFFORTS TO PROMOTE BEEF AND PORK
</HEADLINE>
 By COURTNEY KANE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pork is still the other white meat and beef is still
for dinner, but the associations that created those long-running
campaigns are planning multimedia efforts to help freshen them up.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge that the National Pork Producers Council and the
National Cattlemen's Beef Association face is to get consumers
interested not only in their meats, but also in their ads, which
they have been seeing for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns seek to challenge consumers' perceptions, with
the pork ads hoping to position the meat as the ultimate solution
to meal-time monotony and the beef ads trying to bolster women's
awareness of beef's nutritional value.
</P>
<P>
   The new television and print campaign for pork is the most
significant since the introduction of the ``Pork. The other white
meat.'' campaign in 1987. The new effort continues to use that
slogan but plays off the ``other'' by featuring scenes in which a
consumer making a choice for dinner has to choose from the same old
thing or exciting pork.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have chicken fatigue, burger boredom and are tired of
pasta and pizza as alternatives,'' said Al Tank, chief executive of
the National Pork Producers Council, Des Moines, Iowa. ``We think
this campaign will make pork a real attractive and acceptable
alternative to consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, created by the pork association's longtime agency,
the Chicago office of Bozell Worldwide, a unit of True North
Communications, is part of a multiyear effort, with spending
estimated at $25 million for the first year.
</P>
<P>
   The initial 30-second television commercial features a man
pondering menu options at a meat case in a supermarket. As he scans
the meat, the choices he is contemplating pop up on the screen: (A)
ground chuck, (B) chicken (again), (C) crablike meat product? and
(D) other. As he smiles, discovering pork, an announcer says,
``There is an alternative to the ordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From our perspective, the opportunity really exists to
underscore that in fact pork's greatest virtue is that it is not
beef or chicken,'' said Mark Williams, senior partner for account
management and development at Bozell Chicago. ``The challenge is to
bring that to life creatively in a way that connects for
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The print portion of the campaign follows a similar creative
format. One ad features a woman in her car. As she is stuck in a
traffic jam, she thinks about what to have for dinner. Her four
options are (A) pasta salad, (B) cheeseburger, (C) bowl of cereal
and (D) other. Other is circled and a headline reads: ``Road rage
may have a direct correlation to one's limited dinner options.
There is a cure.''
</P>
<P>
   A second ad features a man peering into the refrigerator trying
to find something to eat. The four options: (A) chicken pot pie,
(B) Tuesday's Chinese take-out, (C) the previous Tuesday's Chinese
take-out and D) other. The headline reads: ``Meal monotony. The
leading cause of facial freezer burn. Visit your local supermarket
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The spots began on Wednesday on cable stations including the
History Channel and the Weather Channel, while four initial ads
will appear in the May issues of national magazines like Cooking
Light and Good Housekeeping. Besides television and print, the new
marketing plan includes a revamped Web site at
www.otherwhitemeat.com, as well as other initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   The long-running pork campaign helped turn around declining
demand for the product 13 years ago and has kept it level since,
the association said. Williams added that the new effort was the
result of pork producers ``capitalizing on the progress that we've
made.''
</P>
<P>
   The council said the retail value of pork has steadily grown,
outpacing the rate of inflation. Production has increased 37
percent, while per capita consumption has climbed to 53.4 pounds
from 51.5 pounds and the United States has changed from being an
importer of pork to being a net exporter.
</P>
<P>
   For the beef campaign, the new cycle of ads represents the
return of a nutrition campaign after a 10-year absence. This time,
though, the ads are aimed at influencing women ages 25 to 54,
considered by the industry to be the ``gatekeepers'' of dinner
tables.
</P>
<P>
   ``After research revealed women's widespread misunderstanding of
beef's nutritional value,'' said Mark Thomas, vice president for
consumer marketing at the beef association in Denver, ``we wanted
to let women know that they can enjoy beef as a great-tasting
option that also fits a balanced diet.'' In describing the
marketing objective, he said, ``We want to make beef easy to choose
and easy to use for the target audience.''
</P>
<P>
   A new television effort, with billings estimated at $10 million,
was created by the association's longtime agency, the Leo Burnett
Co. in Chicago, a unit of the B Com3 Group. Two 30-second
commercials, which began running on Monday, continue to carry the
industry's long-running theme, ``Beef. It's what's for dinner.'' In
addition, the commercials feature familiar trademarks from previous
beef industry spots including the signature voice of the actor Sam
Elliott and music by the composer Aaron Copeland.
</P>
<P>
   The setting for one commercial is a classic steak house, which
are traditionally frequented by men. As two men finish looking at
menus and scan the room, they realize that they are completely
surrounded by female diners. One man says to the other, ``You want
to go? I feel a little ...'' and the other man finishes his
sentence, ``... out of place.'' The announcer states, ``Make room
at the table boys,'' then continues to advocate beef's nutritional
benefits like being a good source of iron, zinc and B vitamins. A
second commercial features a bride and her mother doing a
last-minute count of the meal responses for a wedding reception.
After the bride rattles off the count, totaling 99 to 1 for beef
against chicken, the spot cuts to the wedding reception, where a
disappointed bridesmaid is being served a chicken meal. She quickly
remedies her unfortunate situation by slyly switching her dinner
with another bridesmaid's beef meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we wanted to tell women is, `Jump on the bandwagon, beef
is back,''' said Amy Haddad, vice president and creative director
at Burnett. She added that through focus groups the association
found that women ``love the taste'' of beef, but ``they just have
been not eating it because it's maybe out of vogue a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But once you tell them about these nutrients,'' she added,
``it's like giving them permission to eat it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said the association had realized that ``changing
attitudes is not an overnight position.'' Nonetheless, over the
last year, he said, the price that people are willing to pay for
beef has risen, reversing a 20-year trend.
</P>
<P>
   The television spots will run on national cable stations
including A&AMP;E, Lifetime and the Food Channel, in addition to local
networks. A radio campaign promoting beef's nutrients will also be
introduced in local markets. The broadcast portion of the campaign
comes after print ads by Burnett, which have been in national
magazines since January. A separate print campaign focusing on
health professionals is also running; those ads were created by the
Sudler &AMP; Hennessey unit of Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. in New York. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
