u a BC-NY-CABBIES-NYT     04-26 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CABBIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK LEADERS ASK HELP ON LIVERY KILLINGS
</HEADLINE>
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A group of religious and civic leaders who have long
ranked among the loudest critics of the New York Police Department
urged residents on Wednesday to help track down the killers of
livery cab drivers.
</P>
<P>
   At a forum organized by the New York State Federation of Taxi
Drivers, the speakers set aside their criticisms of the police.
They said that the overwhelming number of crimes against livery
drivers were being committed by young blacks and Hispanics who prey
on the providers of a vital transportation service and who must be
brought to justice.
</P>
<P>
   Among the speakers were the Rev. Al Sharpton, U.S. Rep. Charles
B. Rangel, and the Rev. Herbert Daughtry of the House of the Lord
Pentecostal Church in Brooklyn. In the most passionate speech,
Daughtry asked residents of poor neighborhoods to stop harboring
killers, and to put out a message that criminals would be turned
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give them up, bro, give them up,'' he said. ``Tell them you
are going to give them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight livery cab drivers have been killed this year, and 19 have
been slain in the last 16 months. Almost all of the killings remain
unsolved. Fernando A. Mateo, president of the taxi drivers'
federation, said the crimes were a case of minorities killing other
minorities, and that almost all had been committed by residents of
the communities the drivers served.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a state of emergency in the inner-city community,''
Mateo said. ``We have a major problem, and it's time to assume
responsibility for our problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officials were not invited to the forum. In attendance
were civic leaders who have demonstrated against the police over
the fatal shootings of unarmed men, and who have sought an
independent federal monitor over the 40,000-officer force. Marilyn
Mode, a police spokeswoman, said the police appreciated the gesture
of support.
</P>
<P>
   During the forum, word circulated that more livery cab drivers
were attacked in the darkness Tuesday night and Wednesday morning.
The police said none of the drivers were hurt, and one, Hemogenes
Cabrera, 27, was saved by a bulletproof barrier behind his seat,
which kept at bay an attacker who pounded on it with a knife during
a ride through the South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The Taxi and Limousine Commission passed a rule last week that
requires livery car owners to outfit their cabs with either a
partition or a digital security camera by next month, and the city
has allocated $5 million to help the owners pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said that livery cabs were a means to move about in
areas where yellow cabs did not venture. He described the drivers
as heroes who ``tread where others will not go'' and who are being
killed by ``traitors to our community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
