<SLUG> BC-NUKE-WASTE-PRICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL FOR RADIOACTIVE WASTE CLEAN-UP HITS SNAG ON COST 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Energy Department's plan to hire a British
company to solidify liquid radioactive waste that has been leaking
from storage tanks in Washington State stumbled Wednesday night
when the Energy Secretary said an increase in the company's price
estimate was unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Secretary, Bill Richardson, said the company's
statement a few days ago that the cost of the project was likely to
be more than twice what it estimated 18 months ago amounted to
``unacceptable and unexplained budget escalation.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement is a blow to the company, BNFL PLC, which was
anticipating a multibillion-dollar contract. It also casts doubt on
how the Energy Department will deal with the site, the Hanford
nuclear reservation in Washington State, its most serious long-term
environmental problem.
</P>
<P>
   The leaky tanks contain 54 million gallons of liquids, sludges
and salts, holding about 60 percent of the radioactivity left over
since bomb-making began in World War II. Of the 177 tanks, 149 are
made of single steel shells, all of which have leaked or are
expected to leak. The remainder have two steel shells, and none of
them have leaked yet, but no one is sure of the effects of decades
of high radiation.
</P>
<P>
   The department had planned to privatize the project by having
BNFL build a factory at its own expense to mix the wastes with
extra-strong molten glass to stabilize it and seal it in stainless
steel canisters. The company would have been paid only for the
canisters it produced. But BNFL said a few days ago that the price,
which it estimated 18 months ago at at $6.9 billion, was now likely
to be $15.2 billion, including design, construction, financing and
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the latest estimate, Richardson said, ``These
circumstances raise serious questions about the capacity of BNFL to
carry out the vitally important job of cleaning up nuclear waste at
the Hanford site _ something which is a top priority for the
Department of Energy, the State of Washington and the people who
live in the vicinity of the site.'' The department has an agreement
with Washington State and the Environmental Protection Agency to
solidify the waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still very committed to working with the Department of
Energy,'' said Jeff Harvey, a spokesman for BNFL Inc., the American
subsidiary of the British company. ``We believe we have a proposal
and the technology and the team that can work.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson had previously begun a re-examination of BNFL's work
for the department because of problems that surfaced recently at
the company's main operation, the Sellafield nuclear complex in
England, where workers falsified documents on plutonium fuel
production.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's statement also complained that the company had
shuffled its senior management in Britain ``without consultation or
advance warning,'' and that regarding the Hanford project, the
company had ``chosen to conduct its negotiations in the press.''
</P>
<P>
   The department might look for other contractors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the leakage from the tanks has dumped radioactivity into
underground water, and from there, into the Columbia River.
</P>
<P>
   The tanks range in size from 55,000 gallons to one million
gallons. While Richardson's announcement Wednesday makes it less
likely his department will proceed with its plan, that plan itself
was not complete; engineers have not figured out how to handle the
wastes without producing benzene gas, which can burn or explode at
some concentrations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
