<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRAHS-GAMBLING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMOTIONAL FEES BRING FINES FOR HARRAH'S AND SUSPENSION FOR
EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY _ Missouri gambling regulators alleged Wednesday
that Harrah's executives in North Kansas City solicited, accepted
and might have tried to cover up illegal promotional fees from beer
distributors for boxing matches and other special events.
</P>
<P>
   State liquor laws prohibit such fees, aimed at promoting any
brand of alcoholic beverage. Meeting in Jefferson City, the
Missouri Gaming Commission voted unanimously to fine Harrah's North
Kansas City Casino &AMP; Hotel $150,000 and to suspend for five days
the gaming license of its vice president and general manager,
Michael St. Pierre.
</P>
<P>
   The state said $50,000 of the fine was for the alleged
promotional payments and $100,000 for Harrah's lack of cooperation
in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's officials did not speak in their defense at the
meeting. But St. Pierre, who was traveling Wednesday, later said
Harrah's officials ``would not have knowingly or intentionally
violated any regulation or failed to cooperate with the commission
or its staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's has 30 days to appeal the penalty and request a Gaming
Commission hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look forward to obtaining a better understanding of the
basis for the allegations and having our opportunity to provide an
appropriate response,'' St. Pierre said. Harrah's officials ``look
forward to having the opportunity to be heard on the matters raised
in these pleadings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Gaming Commission action against Harrah's and
St. Pierre, company officials ``knew it was a violation to enter
into such agreements.'' The commission said there were incidents
between 1997 and 1999 involving Harrah's and boxing promoter Tony
D. Holden, doing business as Holden Productions; North Kansas City
Beverage Co., a distributor of Anheuser-Busch products; and the
Coors Co. in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's top regional executives were apparently aware of the
arrangements, according to at least one internal Harrah's memo that
advised Anthony Sanfilippo, president of Harrah's Entertainment
Inc.'s central division, last fall that interests representing
Budweiser beer were paying $7500 per event for ``advertising
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   A regional Coors executive confirmed Wednesday that the contract
between Coors and Harrah's boxing promoter was signed by a company
official at Coors headquarters in Colorado. A Coors spokeswoman in
Colorado said the company was unaware of the charges and had no
comment at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Poole, a manager with North Kansas City Beverage, said
that company executives were not available Wednesday and that the
company would have no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Mullally, deputy director of the Gaming Commission, told
commissioners that Harrah's accepted an estimated $30,000 to
$40,000 in unlawful advertising fees to promote various beer brand
names during special events.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a substantial violation of law,'' Mullally said. The
prohibition against advertising fees ``is a well-known rule of
liquor control in Missouri.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullally also said Harrah's had refused to cooperate in the
investigation and still had not turned over some records the
commission had sought. Mullally said Harrah's was fined $20,000
last fall for failing to cooperate and provide records in an
unrelated investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Mullally also said state wholesale liquor regulators had been
alerted to the findings and could take action against the beer
distribution companies. The Missouri Gaming Commission regulates
and issues liquor licenses to casinos.
</P>
<P>
   J.T. Taylor, chief enforcement officer for the Missouri Division
of Liquor Control, confirmed that his agency had opened an
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In other news:
</P>
<P>
   - Commissioners approved Isle of Capri Casinos Inc. as the
preferred developer for the Boonville market. The unanimous
decision eliminated Five Trails Casino Co., operated by William
Grace, from consideration. The two companies had sought commission
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Isle of Capri officials said they hoped to have their Boonville
casino open by Labor Day 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Biloxi, Miss., Isle of Capri has taken over Davis
Gaming's long-delayed Boonville riverboat project on the south bank
of the Missouri River. The company recently bought out
California-based Davis' interest and will spend about $75 million
on the project.
</P>
<P>
   Isle of Capri operates 11 casinos in Iowa, Mississippi,
Louisiana and Colorado; a racetrack in Florida; and a gambling
cruise ship that sails from New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The company also is in the process of buying the Flamingo Hilton
Casino in Kansas City from the Hilton Hotels Corp., and is seeking
commission approval for a project in the St. Louis market.
</P>
<P>
   Grace, who lost out in the Boonville market, is majority owner
of St. Jo Frontier Casino and lead developer of the $15 million
Mark Twain casino project in LaGrange, Mo., north of Hannibal.
</P>
<P>
   - Wednesday's meeting was the first for new commissioner Muriel
Battle, a retired educator from Columbia who was nominated by Gov.
Mel Carnahan and approved last Thursday by the Missouri Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Battle, 70, is a former teacher, principal and assistant
superintendent in the Columbia public school system. She is a
former chairwoman of the Lincoln University board of curators,
serves on the Stephens College board of trustees, and is active in
many civic and professional organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Battle replaces Jenice Stewart, the last of five original
commission members, for a term that expires in April 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
