<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8242 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-RURAL-BUSINESS-KAN &LR;      04-26 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RURAL-BUSINESS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ As the U.S. economic boom has spread like
kudzu, rural America's residents have seen more jobs and more
money.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they have lost ground compared with families in cities.
</P>
<P>
   The per capita income of rural residents stood at $19,090 in
1997, according to the U.S. Department of Agriculture, compared
with $26,861 per capita for urban residents. Moreover, that income
gap widened by $935 over the five years studied from 1993 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The question, say some policy-makers, is whether rural America
will participate in the emerging digital economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``By any measure you choose, rural areas have a less-skilled
work force and a brain drain. How will those areas attract the best
and the brightest?'' asks Mark Drabenstott, vice president of the
Federal Reserve Bank of Kansas City and director of its Center for
the Study of Rural America.
</P>
<P>
   The center, which was created last year, will turn that ground
in a two-day conference, ``Beyond Agriculture; New Policies for
Rural America,'' which begins today at the Westin Crown Center
hotel. About 250 people are expected at the invitation-only
meeting, which will include a live video broadcast by Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan on ``The Outlook for Rural America
in the 21st Century.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is enamored with the center. A grass-roots
collection of ranchers and farmers from around the country think
the center is biased toward industrialized agricultural and against
small, family farms. They will respond with their own meeting this
weekend to formulate their vision for the future of rural America.
Their meeting at the Heartland Presbyterian Camp &AMP; Conference
Center near Parkville is expected to draw 30 to 40 persons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand all is for naught, if we can't convince the
voting public they have been lied to and globalization is not a
panacea. We have to make them understand that after they have
squeezed all of the blood out of the farmer, the consumer is
next,'' said Fred Stokes, a Mississippi rancher and president of
the Organization for Competitive Markets, a group that thinks food
conglomerates have a stranglehold on small farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The rural center's vision, Stokes said, is one in which ``some
farmers may own the farms, but big agribusiness owns the farmers.''
</P>
<P>
   Drabenstott shrugs off the group's charges, saying the bank has
reported on the changes in agriculture without advocating for or
against policies. ``We have addressed some of the steps the country
might take to keep farmers in the game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the fate of rural America has been entwined with
American agriculture, Drabenstott said. It is time to forge a rural
policy that acknowledges the needs of small-town America to
sometimes diverge from the fortunes of agriculture, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make sure agriculture is not a victim in this
process,'' Drabenstott said. ``It will still be a part of the
puzzle but there is a realization growing that it is not the only
piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives of groups such as the Nebraska Bankers Association in
Lincoln and the Iowa Rural Development Council in Des Moines say
the center gives an authoritative voice to their concern of
isolation from America's prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dealing with areas without access to the Internet or
where they do have it, residents and entrepreneurs who don't know
how to take advantage of it,'' said Beth Danowsky, executive
director of the Iowa Rural Development Council. ``One of the really
good things coming out of the center is that we now have a highly
credible organization bringing these issues to the forefront.''
</P>
<P>
   The center's research shows that rural areas of the Rocky
Mountains, where outdoor amenities can attract young entrepreneurs,
have outpaced the rest of America in job growth, Drabenstott said.
Areas like rural Nebraska have failed to keep up. That lag is
decimating pastoral life in areas lacking in allure.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more agricultural communities are staring disaster in
the face,'' Drabenstott said. ``Their rural water, sewers, street
repairs are all piling up.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, rural areas are closer to inner cities than to suburbs,
says Richard Foster, vice president of the W.D. Kellogg Foundation,
which dedicates its funding to issues of rural life. Rural and
inner-city America have similar poverty rates, high school drop out
rates, drug use rates and rates of outward migration.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have are all of these retirement communities that
don't even know they are retirement communities,'' said Foster,
during a trip to Kansas City. ``It is not that old people went
there. Young people just left.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation welcomes the spotlight that the bank conference
shines on rural problems. It also is providing public relations
assistance to the Organization for Competitive Markets.
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues Drabenstott sees facing most of rural America
is whether it will produce or can nurture entrepreneurs who
traditionally create businesses and jobs. Beyond friends and
families, where can the money be found to finance fertile ideas?
</P>
<P>
   Many believe technology, if extended to rural areas, could be
the great equalizer. That may require public underwriting like
rural electrification received.
</P>
<P>
   ``Telecommunications is the wild card,'' Drabenstott said.
``Will rural America get wired to the same extent as urban areas?
``How will e-commerce affect rural America? Will it filter out to
places like rural Kansas or will it serve only urban America?''
</P>
<P>
   Foster agrees wiring rural America will be essential to keep it
vibrant and connected to the rest of the world. But the foundation
also believes small farmers are the stewards of the land, and
``sustainable'' agriculture has as important a role to play in
feeding America as corporate farming, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rural America represents 80 percent of our geographic area and
23 percent of the population, but yet it is where all of the food
is grown,'' Foster said. ``We believe rural America has lost its
advocacy, but it is a national treasure and demands to be nurtured
and preserved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
