<HEADLINE>
HITCHCOCK NOT BUYING THE SHARKS AS UNDERDOGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD AND MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The San Jose Sharks say they are the underdogs
against the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, said Stars coach Ken Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can blow the underdog status wherever you want to blow it,
but it's not going to sell,'' Hitchcock said. ``They just knocked
off the first seed and played one of the best games ever I've seen
a team play in a Game 7.''
</P>
<P>
   With the likes of Bryan Marchment, Mike Ricci, Owen Nolan and
Mike Rathje littering the roster, it's easy to see how, too. The
Sharks play one of the most physical games in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made life hard for St. Louis. They were more than willing
to pay that price,'' Hitchcock said. ``There is a physical price to
play San Jose and we have to be willing to pay it.''  &QL; 
This is the reason
</P>
<P>
   If you were wondering why the Stars acquired Dave Manson and
Scott Thornton and called up Brenden Morrow, this series should
answer all of those questions.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks are a gritty team that doesn't mind getting physical.
Along with Derian Hatcher, Richard Matvichuk and now the
aforementioned trio, the Stars can match the Sharks pound for
pound.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the pickups knowing the price you have to pay,''
Hitchcock said. ``We made it for now and now's the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem for the Stars now is not to be goaded into bad
penalties by the likes of Marchment and Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the problems St. Louis ran into is they
retaliated a lot, they let some people get under their skin, and
you can't do that,'' Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk said. ``We've
played these guys enough to know what they're all about. We know
what they are going to do and, it's up to us to react in a proper
way.''  &QL; 
To play or not to play
</P>
<P>
   While the Stars are happy with the extended rest they received
for disposing of Edmonton in five games, they realize that the
Sharks have done something they haven't: played recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are probably going to be pretty crisp,'' Stars center
Mike Modano said. ``You play a seven-game series beating the number
one team in the league, you are going to have the current going
with you. The first game is going to be crucial to stop that. The
first 10 minutes will be crucial.''  &QL; 
Sloan is now available
</P>
<P>
   As members of the media surrounded Joe Nieuwendyk yesterday,
Stars winger Mike Keane casually sneaked in behind the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blake Sloan is now available for comment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters spun around to see the hubbub at Sloan's locker, but
he wasn't there. In his place stood a life-size cardboard cutout of
``Mini Me'' _ the little man from the movie /Austin Powers 2'',
wearing a Stars cap.
</P>
<P>
   Who says the Stars aren't loose?  &QL; 
Backseat for NHL
</P>
<P>
   There are two days off between Games 3 and 4 in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   San Jose Arena already had an event scheduled for that night, a
Latin music concert.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars and Sharks shouldn't feel too bad, though. The
Washington Capitals had to schedule their first-round series
against Pittsburgh around a World Wrestling Federation event.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
