<DOCNO> NYT20000426.0479 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8245 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT     04-26 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL STEPS BY PETTITTE AND YANKS IN VICTORY OVER TWINS
</HEADLINE>
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sean Bergman is a journeyman pitcher who contributes
generously to major league batting averages, but as the Minnesota
Twins thrashed the new York Yankees on Tuesday night, Bergman
challenged Derek Jeter with a fastball, right down the middle.
Jeter swung and missed, striking out, and he turned and gaped at
Bergman, shocked he didn't drive the ball.
</P>
<P>
   His desolate expression might as well have been the face of the
Yankees. They have been losing and don't know why. Joe Torre, their
manager, reminded them in a meeting before Wednesday's game against
the Twins that they are a team that builds victories in small
increments and with ample intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Those increments Wednesday included a strong five-inning
performance from Andy Pettitte, who was making his first start
since April 7, a remarkable throw from catcher Jorge Posada, and
home runs from Derek Jeter and Tino Martinez in a 2-0 shutout of
Minnesota, before 27,919 at a frigid Yankee Stadium. ``This was a
big win for us,'' Jeter said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees still haven't emerged from their collective
offensive slump, and they need improvement from the likes of David
Cone and Roger Clemens. Outfielder Paul O'Neill may be out of the
lineup in days to come, after departing in the third inning to have
tests on blurred vision in his right eye. But the victory prevented
the Twins from recording their first three-game sweep in Yankee
Stadium since 1968, and will enable the Yankees to think better of
themselves as they rest Thursday before beginning a three-game
series against Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees lost two of three games to the Blue Jays last
weekend, and games to the Twins Monday and Tuesday _ four losses in
five games _ and Torre saw frustration in their play, an
uncharacteristic anxiousness. The starting pitchers were getting
hammered, and in the face of early deficits, the hitters seemed to
be trying to do too much with their at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still have to do this in small bits,'' Torre said, adding
that to do otherwise would be taking away from the Yankees'
expertise.
</P>
<P>
   A sign was posted on the Yankees' clubhouse door Wednesday
morning _ MEETING 12:00 _ and for about five minutes, Torre spoke
positively, calmly, cajoling gently, reminding the players that the
best teams emerge from slumps rather than drive themselves deeper
into them.
</P>
<P>
   For five innings, it was impossible to see whether Torre's words
made a difference. As Bergman had done Tuesday night, Joe Mays
stifled the Yankees, holding them hitless for the first three and
two-thirds innings. There had been a couple of two-out singles in
the fourth inning, from Martinez and Posada, before Shane Spencer
took a called third strike. The Yankees looked just as lifeless as
they did Tuesday night, as they have for the better part of a week.
</P>
<P>
   But Pettitte, having recovered from a strained back muscle, held
the Twins scoreless through the first five innings, pitching at an
accelerated pace, catching and throwing and catching and throwing
before coming into range of his 80-pitch limit in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nelson relieved him for the top of the sixth, and Cristian
Guzman laced a single to center _ a crisis, when the other team's
leadoff man reaches base late in the game and your men aren't
scoring any runs.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman took a lead against Nelson, who is not adept at holding
runners. Nelson threw a fastball far inside to Denny Hocking and
Guzman broke for second, but Posada did not know it; he hadn't
heard any infielders yelling to alert him.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's fastball forced Posada to lunge to his right, to
backhand the ball, and out of the corner of his eye, Posada saw
motion _ Guzman running. Without setting his feet, unbalanced,
Posada turned his shoulders and whipped the ball toward second
base, unsure whether anyone would cover the bag. Nelson couldn't
believe he had thrown the ball; the whole play seemed to be
happening in slow motion, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Wilson Delgado, the second baseman, was in position and
deftly caught the ball on a short hop. Guzman slid headfirst into
the tag, and Bob Didier, the Yankees' catching instructor, turned
to scouts sitting around him and said, ``That's all arm strength
right there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a crucial out, at a crucial juncture. ``Anything in a
game like that can open it up,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter led off the bottom of the sixth, feeling comfortable at
the plate. Even in striking out against Bergman, he had felt fine,
wondering only how he had missed the ball. Jeter fell behind in the
count, one ball and two strikes, fouled off a pitch, took another
outside. Mays threw a changeup down and away, a great pitch, after
five consecutive fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   And Jeter smashed it, reaching down, the ball carrying into the
right-field stands, his first home run at the Stadium this season.
Mays said later that it was most impressive piece of hitting he had
ever seen, how Jeter managed to drive a pitch out of the strike
zone so far.
</P>
<P>
   Three batters later, Mays challenged Martinez with a fastball,
right down the middle. Martinez slammed it over the wall, for a
second run that turned out to be more than enough for the Yankees'
bullpen. He rounded the bases with a serious expression cracked
only by the slightest smile: the old face of the Yankees, and on
this day, a new face for the Yankees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
