u k BC-EDIT-ZIMBABWE-NYT &LR;      04-26 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ZIMBABWE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: JUSTICE AND STABILITY IN ZIMBABWE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, April 27:
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years after he triumphantly led Zimbabwe to independence
from white rule in what had been Rhodesia, President Robert Mugabe
seems bent on driving his once hopeful nation into violent conflict
and economic ruin. Threatened as never before by a surging
multiracial opposition, he is seeking to preserve his corrupt
regime by unleashing the forces of lawlessness and racism. The
challenge for Zimbabweans now is to avoid being goaded into a cycle
of retaliatory bloodshed that can only end in disaster.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks, mobs allied with Mugabe's ruling ZANU-PF
party have murdered at least nine opposition supporters and two
white farmers. Mugabe is flouting court orders to remove squatters
who have illegally occupied hundreds of white-owned farms. Instead
he has condoned the seizures and denounced the farmers as ``enemies
of Zimbabwe'' who are coercing workers to back the fledgling
Movement for Democratic Change.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes that land reform is essential. Fewer than 5,000
white farmers, descendants of British settlers who stole the land,
still own more than half the country's best land while millions of
blacks scratch out a meager existence on barren communal farms. But
much of the land already purchased from whites has gone not to
landless peasants but to cronies of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Land is not the real issue for Mugabe. It is a political weapon
with which to divide and discredit an opposition movement that is
threatening to undermine his party's near-monopoly on power in
parliamentary elections later this year. Lawful land redistribution
would be a legitimate means of winning votes from rural peasants,
but violent coercion and racial scapegoating are a reckless
distraction from a disintegrating economy that now features 70
percent inflation, 50 percent unemployment and chronic fuel
shortages _ all compounded by a costly and unpopular war in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe seeks to portray the opposition as a conspiracy in which
blacks are being manipulated by unreconstructed white Rhodesians
bent on reviving the racist rule of Ian Smith. Smith has in fact
sought to exploit the current crisis to make a comeback. He has
been rejected by most whites, who instead are providing cash and
organizational support for Morgan Tsvangirai, an articulate trade
unionist who leads the overwhelmingly black opposition movement.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, after five more oppositionists were beaten to death
this week by pro-government activists, Tsvangirai warned that his
followers would defend themselves against lawlessness, declaring
that ``We shall take this violence to their doorstep.'' That kind
of incendiary language will only invite further bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe's fledgling opposition must not allow itself to be
lured into retaliating. But it will need support from neighboring
states and friends in the West if it is to stick to its course of
peaceful change. Last weekend the leaders of South Africa,
Mozambique and Namibia met with Mugabe at Victoria Falls and voiced
their support for his land reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Given their common inheritance of the legacies of racial
domination throughout southern Africa, their reluctance to isolate
Mugabe is understandable. But their countries also depend for their
own continued economic growth on stability in Zimbabwe. They should
be using all their influence, with Western support, to ensure that
Zimbabwe's opposition is allowed to compete without fear of further
bloodshed. Free and fair elections and respect for law represent
the best hope for both justice and stability. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
