<HEADER>
A8386 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     04-26 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA PLAYOFFS HAVE STARTED, OFFICIALLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a sacred rite of spring, as much a part of it as blooming
flowers, blustery winds, chirping birds and disillusioned Clipper
players seeking asylum in some faraway venue where Donald T.
Sterling doesn't own an apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, has there ever been an NBA playoff series in which one
of the coaches, usually the one whose team is behind, doesn't
publicly denounce the officials?
</P>
<P>
   I knew before the current Los Angeles Laker-Sacramento King
debate that Rick Adelman, esteemed headmaster of the Kings, would
engage in such gamesmanship because I knew his center, Vlade Divac,
would be woefully overmatched against Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   And, sure enough, as soon as O'Neal dispensed his 46-point,
17-rebound, 5-block masterpiece Sunday in the Lakers 117-107
triumph over the Kings, Adelman loudly made it known that the
7-foot-1, 325-pound O'Neal was taking terrible physical liberties
on his cowering players and that the NBA officials were amiss in
letting him get away with such plunder.
</P>
<P>
   Adelman might have been reflecting on the work of the men who
officiated Game 1, but his comments were calculated to influence
the work of the men who will work Game 2 of the series that resumes
this evening at Staples Series.
</P>
<P>
   A man who has heard such rhetorical posturing before, Jerry West
actually finds Rick Adelman's eruption amusing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Shaquille O'Neal the one who gets fouled every time down
court,'' says the Lakers' top administrator. ``I think it was the
Kings who shot 35 free throws in the first game compared to only 14
for the Lakers. What he (Adelman) has to say doesn't disturb me.''
</P>
<P>
   What does disturb Jerry West is the widespread perception that
it's a preordained certainty the Lakers will dethrone the San
Antonio Spurs as NBA champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already heard the coronation of the Lakers as world
champions, and that's ridiculous,'' says West. ``All these games
are going to be difficult for us. The competition in the Western
Conference is fierce. For a team to even think that it has it made
can result in a loss of focus. Everything that you've accomplished
during the regular season can quickly be undone. Just look what
happened to the St. Louis Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers don't figure to lose their focus this spring, not
after being swept out of the playoffs the past two seasons, not at
a time when Shaquille O'Neal has clearly emerged as the most
dominant player in the league, not with a supreme motivator, Phil
Jackson, as their coach.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the St. Louis Blues, who had the NHL's best regular
season record, found out against the mediocre San Jose Sharks,
terrible things can happen in the playoffs to favored teams who
don't show up in prime form.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers might show up listless this evening against the
Kings, the refs might unconsciously react to Adelman's accusations,
O'Neal might get into early foul trouble, and Sacramento might
steal a game at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   You must understand there is a compelling reason for Rick
Adelman to diminish Shaquille O'Neal's monstrous opening-game
performance and shift the attention to the officials.
</P>
<P>
   Such tactics sometime do work.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1988 NBA finals between the Lakers and Detroit
Pistons, I was on the airplane carrying the Lakers back to Los
Angeles after they fell behind 3-2 in the series when Pat Riley
went into a lengthy dissertation on the injustices being
perpetuated by you guessed it the officials.
</P>
<P>
   Well, in the final two games of that epic series at the Forum,
the Lakers were the beneficiaries of almost every big call,
including the biggest in the closing stages of Game 6 when referee
John Vanak whistled the Pistons' center, Bill Laimbeer, for a
phantom foul against Kareem Abdul-Jabbar that allowed Abdul-Jabbar
to make the game-deciding free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Riley proudly confided to me, ``You saw what happened
after I complained. Officials are human. Like all of us, they react
to criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting tonight to see if the officials react to
Rick Adelman's tirade, and stifle O'Neal's aggressiveness by
calling fouls against him when he's jostling for offensive
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a player in the league who gets hammered as much
as Shaquille,'' says West. ``Like I said, he gets fouled almost
every time he touches the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Kings do upset the Lakers tonight and O'Neal is plagued
by foul trouble, then it will be Phil Jackson's turn to harangue
those cursed souls in the striped shirts.
</P>
<P>
   But it's doubtful that will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Adelman can complain all he wants about Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   But the ghastly reality for the Kings and Adelman is trying to
defend Shaquille O'Neal with Vlade Divac is scandalously
inequitable, a monopolistic practice I'm sure the
anti-trust-obsessed Justice Department soon will investigate. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
