<HEADER>
A8393 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BLACK-CIRCUS-NYT     04-26 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BLACK-CIRCUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIRCUS ACTS FOR THE STREETWISE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT25 and NYT26 have been sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert Dunn likes to say he came in through the back
door.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the Universoul Circus went to Miami and Dunn
seized the chance to realize a lifelong dream.
</P>
<P>
   Most circus clowns come from the Ringling Brothers and Barnum &AMP;
Bailey Clown College, not from the local children's birthday party
circuit that Dunn had been working for 17 years. But like an actor
in community theater who dreams of Broadway, Dunn _ Onionhead to
those who like him, and those who do not _ lusted after a shot
under the big top.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, 58, took the only job available, assistant cook. As the
tour traveled he got a promotion, albeit to the tent crew. After a
year, he finally got to do some clowning, so long as he continued
to help with the tent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the show was over I would grab a broom and start
sweeping,'' Dunn said. Today, the circus management does not let
him clean up. They want him outside, signing autographs and gently
teasing his fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Universoul Circus, which has pitched its big top in Brooklyn
through May 7, bills itself as the nation's only black-owned
circus. Cedric Walker, the chief executive and a founder of
Universoul, said he tries to showcase black performers and to
inspire a black, urban audience.
</P>
<P>
   Not unlike many families, the Universoul Circus has become an
eclectic group of people. Although there was a black-owned circus
that toured the country in the early 1900s, a strong
circus-performing tradition never developed in black communities,
forcing Walker to search for his performers among Las Vegas variety
shows, eager amateur acts and overseas circuses after Universal
began in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In South Africa, Walker found Lucky Malatsi, 9, and Lunga
Buthelezi, 10, the contortionist and acrobatic team. In London, he
found Vicki Amedume, a 24-year-old trapeze artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many black circus families,'' Amedume said.
``Physical black people think about going into dance or sports. But
this circus opens people up to the idea they can do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Count among the inspired Saiydah Weems, 19. When the circus came
last year to her hometown, Cleveland, Weems took a job handing out
goody bags. By the end of the Cleveland run she was convinced she
wanted to become a performer. She drove to Detroit, the next stop
on the tour, and begged the owners to let her run away and join the
circus.
</P>
<P>
   Weems said she wanted to become the first African-American hair
hanger. The only problem was that Weems had never hung by her hair
before. So circus officials hired Elizabeth Rodriguez, whose family
has been dangling by its follicles for five generations, to teach
her.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Rodriguez had shown anyone outside her
family the trade secrets. Each day, she helped Weems hang a little
longer, building her neck muscles and her tolerance for pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get used to the pain, you have to learn how to be
graceful,'' Weems said. ``When I first saw it I thought, it's so
cool. I have long hair so I thought, what else can you do with it?
Why not hang from it?''
</P>
<P>
   Now, during the finale of the show, Weems' waist-length hair is
hooked to a rope and she is pulled 50 feet into the air, with
Rodriguez dangling beside her.
</P>
<P>
   Other performers have also benefited from professional training.
But some performers, including the Dragonmasters, a break-dancing
and gymnastics group from New Orleans, learned their tricks on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we do comes from inside,'' said Anthony Coleman, a
member of the Dragonmasters who goes by the name Lil' Country. ``We
are street-taught, self-taught.''
</P>
<P>
   The message directed to black families at the circus is often
blunt: the ringmaster, Cal Dupree, urges young audience members to
sacrifice, have discipline and be obedient. And the finale is a
religious appeal, culminating with the appearance of a Jesus
character.
</P>
<P>
   Other acts are less overt. Dunn's performances as Onionhead are
a respectful lampoon of urban culture and stereotypes. He makes an
appearance as a self-important security guard, a sendup of the
inflated sense of power a badge can bring. He also appears as ``a
player'' in a pair of giant wingtips and an exaggerated zoot suit.
Other times, he plays an overconfident basketball player who is cut
down to size when someone steals his shorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are all people you see in the black belt, in the
ghetto,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For many of the acrobats and clowns in Universoul, the circus
has been very rewarding, because black audiences can be more
effusive and enthusiastic, but also more demanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Urban audiences are used to watching kids flip down the
sidewalk, so you have to go a step above in the ring,'' said Ameera
Matheny, 28, who has worked for Ringling Brothers and now works
with the animal acts at Universoul.
</P>
<P>
   Each afternoon, after the morning show crowd is ushered out and
before preparations for the night show must begin, a lull descends
on the circus.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Gabonese teeterboard troupe practiced refinements
to its act. The young contortionists were turned over to their
tutor so they could learn geography, as well as how to bend their
foot over their head and touch their nose with it. And the three
elephants _ Jan, Bunny and Marie _ rocked themselves back and forth
and then lay down for a nap.
</P>
<P>
   But Dunn, always in character and his face still in paint,
seemed unable to stop. As he walked by a line of people waiting to
buy tickets, he was spotted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, a clown!'' shouted one boy.
</P>
<P>
   About a half-dozen children rushed toward Dunn, all the
inspiration Onionhead needed. ``Oh my god!'' Dunn shouted back.
``Look, look, a kid, a kid!''
</P>
<P>
   (mg)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
