u a BC-NY-ONEIDA-LAND-NYT &LR;      04-26 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ONEIDA-LAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN TRIBE PROPOSES A DEAL ON LAND IT SEEKS TO RECLAIM
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saying they wanted to extend an olive branch in their
long-simmering land-claim dispute with New York state, the Oneida
Indians said Wednesday that they would not, given the right
conditions, seek to evict or demand rent from 20,000 landowners in
central New York.
</P>
<P>
   The offer _ which will have to be accepted by the state and two
upstate counties to become effective _ is the latest twist in a
case that has dragged on since 1970, when the Oneidas filed a claim
to more than 270,000 acres near Rome and Utica. The claim was based
on the tribe's contention that state and local governments
illegally seized Indian lands 200 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That claim was upheld by the Supreme Court in 1985. But not much
happened until 1998, when the federal government sided with the
Oneidas and filed an amended complaint naming 20,000 owners of land
the Oneidas claimed as defendants _ setting the stage for a charged
atmosphere of distrust and fear.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the Oneidas have said that they have no
intention of physically seizing anyone's land. And while most
residents have said they do not believe that their land will be
taken, they have long been bothered by the notion that the Oneidas
could do just that at any time. So now, with the case expected to
move to trial soon, the Oneidas have made their strongest statement
yet to try to allay those fears, saying they will do their utmost
to shield owners of private land.
</P>
<P>
   ``The landowners in this region have endured nearly a year and a
half of uncertainty over their future,'' said Ray Halbritter, the
chief executive of the Oneida Indian Nation, in a statement. ``We
hope that the steps we have taken today will end that
uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the offer is merely lip service or a serious gesture,
though, is something that all parties said late Wednesday they
still needed to determine.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the Oneidas filed two documents with Judge Neal P.
McCurn of U.S. District Court in Syracuse: the first was a
stipulation in which the Oneidas pledged to give up their rights to
seek any damages from private owners of land they claim is theirs.
The second was a request to separate the state from the landowner
defendants, and have the case seeking hundreds of millions of
dollars in damages and other relief from the state proceed first.
</P>
<P>
   The offer was made contingent on New York state and Madison and
Oneida Counties agreeing to certain conditions, including not
arguing that the stipulation is tantamount to the Oneidas dropping
the entire land claim.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, the counties were not impressed. Among other
problems, they said, was their concern that separating the
defendants would deprive the counties of involvement in the legal
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first reaction is that we are very disappointed,'' said
Ralph J. Eannace Jr., the Oneida County Executive, and Rocco J.
DiVeronica, chairman of the Madison County Board of Supervisors, in
a statement. ``To provide true relief, the claims against
individual landowners have to be removed permanently.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials, meanwhile, had a mixed reaction. Michael
McKeon, a spokesman for Gov. George Pataki, repeated Pataki's calls
that the federal government withdraw from the lawsuit altogether.
At the same time, though, McKeon said that ``if the rhetoric of the
press release is matched by reality, then we will give it serious
consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon Koziol, a Utica lawyer who has become a de facto legal
representative for many of the affected landowners, said that
although he was wary of the Oneidas and the state, the offer did
contain a sliver of hope. ``It is a step in the right direction,''
he said, ``but ultimately the landowners want to see that the
clouds be removed altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government continues to oppose the eviction of the
landowners while maintaining the hope that a fair settlement can
still be reached, said James F. Simon, a deputy assistant attorney
general.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
