A8400 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-TIGER-LADY-NYT     04-26 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-TIGER-LADY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RECOMMENDS CLOSING OF TIGER PRESERVE
</HEADLINE>
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Jersey's Tiger Lady lost another round on Wednesday in her
effort to keep and exhibit the big cats on her property.
</P>
<P>
   An administrative law judge upheld a decision by the New Jersey
Division of Fish, Game and Wildlife not to renew the license of the
woman, Joan Byron-Marasek, to operate the Tigers Only Preservation
Society, in Jackson Township.
</P>
<P>
   Finding that the compound in which 26 tigers live is
``unsanitary and rat-infested'' and that Byron-Marasek failed to
keep adequate records or cooperate with state inspectors, the
judge, John R. Tassini, recommended it close.
</P>
<P>
   He gave Byron-Marasek ``a reasonable period of time'' to move
the tigers to properly licensed compounds.
</P>
<P>
   Under New Jersey law, the commissioner of the State Department
of Environmental Conservation has 45 days to accept, modify or
reject the administrative judge's decision. If he accepts it,
Byron-Marasek could appeal the ruling to the state appellate court.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Byron-Marasek nor her lawyer, Valter Must, could be
reached for comment on the ruling or on any plans to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-page ruling, which included details of the zoology and
morphology of tigers, is another chapter in a yearlong effort by
state officials to close the preserve. In the 24 years that
Byron-Marasek has owned the compound in the south-central part of
the state, the once rural area has become more heavily populated,
and the preserve is now hemmed in by subdivisions and commercial
development.
</P>
<P>
   The compound came under scrutiny in January 1999, when a
4-year-old, 431-pound tiger wandering in the area had to be killed
after the police were unable to sedate it.
</P>
<P>
   The tiger was found close to Byron-Marasek's compound and to
Great Adventure, a theme park that also keeps tigers. A check of
the park and its records found all of their tigers accounted for,
but similar efforts to check Byron-Marasek's property and records
were met with denials that the tiger was hers. Neither Wednesday's
ruling nor other efforts by state inspectors have conclusively
determined where the tiger came from.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Tassini found that although the licenses approved
over the years for the preserve had specified that the tigers were
for theatrical and educational use, there were no indications that
they had ever served any such use.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the legal battle over the renewal, Byron-Marasek has
conceded that her motivation is a passion for the animals and their
survival, not a wish to exhibit them educationally or theatrically.
Her property, she once said in an interview, was to be a sanctuary
for the tigers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-00 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
