<HEADER>
A8403 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DAUGTHERS-PROFILE-NYT     04-26 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAUGTHERS-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE NEW FACES AT WORK TODAY  
</HEADLINE>
   By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Attention, young women of Take Our Daughters to Work
Day: time to meet your maker, Nell Merlino.
</P>
<P>
   Is she committed to the equality of women? Absolutely. Have a
few stories of girl discrimination? Hey, wait till you hear her on
the Dukakis campaign and the Archdiocese of New York. Looking to
the future? Why do you think her press agent called us to do a
story? (No, we cannot explain press agents. It would be too cruel.
Let us put it this way: Merlino is doing something important and a
person to whom she paid money called it to the attention of every
paper and television network in America. This is one of the brutal
realities of journalism, kids. We don't just stumble on these
stories.)
</P>
<P>
   Another brutal reality, regarding Take Our Daughters to Work
Day:
</P>
<P>
   It was a gig. An assignment for pay, the pay being $45,000. Not
that Merlino, 47, doesn't care, because she does, but coming up
with programs that will create social change happens to be her
business. Strategy Communications Action Ltd., it's called. Merlino
has created programs to combat domestic violence; she worked with
the U.N. World Conference on Women in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the way it worked with Daughters was that eight years
ago the Ms. Foundation, concerned about the findings that girls in
early adolescence suffer a loss of self-esteem, asked Merlino if
she could create some sort of public education campaign. She
developed and promoted the program for several months. Last year,
19 million girls participated in the program.
</P>
<P>
   So we can really say one woman started it all?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' says Merlino, an exuberant woman who talks not just in
streams, but in geysers, gushers, and who lives and works in a
spectacular Chelsea loft that is itself a life lesson. ``But I
would also say I don't think any of these things are one person.
One person may write the script, but then it takes hundreds of
thousands to make it come alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The professional options Merlino was told would be hers growing
up in Trenton?
</P>
<P>
   None of those wonderful opportunities you girls take for
granted!
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Joseph P. Merlino, was a New Jersey state senator,
her mother, Molly McGoogan Merlino, an artist and housewife. In
elementary school, at the Blessed Sacrament, girls were given three
career choices: mother, teacher or nun. Merlino knew only that she
wanted to be ``kind of in charge, to be the boss.''
</P>
<P>
   Merlino graduated from Antioch College, worked as a union
organizer, in state government in New York, as an advance person in
the presidential campaigns of Walter Mondale and Michael Dukakis.
Typical assignment: being sent to a city to pull together a rally
of 40,000 in five days.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, she quit political work. ``Working on a
presidential campaign is exciting, but long term, it's not very
satisfying,'' she says. ``Someone would ask me what to do, then
they would turn around and ask some 20-year-old boy. It's still
very much a boy's game.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after the end of the Dukakis campaign, she went into
business for herself, a move, she says happily, that enabled her to
own a wonderful apartment. Her new project is count-me-in, a
nonprofit Internet organization (www.count-me-in.org) that will
provide business loans of $500 to $10,000. Women across the country
will be asked to donate $5. Merlino is not consulting on this one,
she is the co-founder and president and will get a salary.
</P>
<P>
   Having made her name with Take Our Daughters to Work, Merlino
could handle all sorts of accounts. Why pursue women's issues?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do I care that little girls end up feeling crummy about
themselves and make less money than the boys?'' Merlino says,
annoyed.
</P>
<P>
   No, not why it's an important issue, why does Merlino care?
</P>
<P>
   She goes back to her political work, on the Dukakis campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to have Secret Service look at me and ask when the guy
in charge was going to be there. I had the man who was in charge of
public relations for the Archdiocese of New York tell me he'd
negotiate with me when I could be ordained a priest; telling me, in
effect, you're not a man. We were having a discussion about where
the photographers would be for an Al Smith dinner. He said, `I'll
negotiate with you, young lady, when you can become a priest.'''
</P>
<P>
   Steamed. ``This was in a room full of Secret Service agents and
priests and he calls me, young lady.''
</P>
<P>
   Calls to a spokesman for the archdiocese were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   A happier subject: How does Merlino, who is married but has no
children, spend the day she created?
</P>
<P>
   A smile in her voice, now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to Grand Central Station and watch everybody coming in
with their girls. It's mind-boggling, it knocks me out. You see
thousands of them, all different ages, all different jobs. In the
morning they look spectacular, at the end of the day their hairdos
are askew, they're tired. They look just like the grown-ups. It
makes me cry. It makes me cry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
