<SLUG> BC-OLY-CYCLING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYCLIST'S RECYCLED CAREER GIVEN BOOST WITH WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRISCO, Texas _ There will be no compromise, vows Erin Hartwell,
the only American male cyclist to medal at consecutive Olympiads.
</P>
<P>
   Hartwell, who secured his silver and bronze medals in track
cycling's sprint events, will become a force as an endurance rider
or leave the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't flounder in this,'' Hartwell said. ``I'll either get
to the top of the game or I'll quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartwell's triumph last night in the men's individual
4,000-meter pursuit final during the U.S. Olympic Track Cycling
Trials suggests prospects for a successful transition.
</P>
<P>
   Hartwell, known better as ``Erv,'' covered the 4,000 meters with
a winning time of 4 minutes, 38.002 seconds to beat Michael Tillman
(4:47.390) at the Superdrome in Frisco and resurrect a career
derailed by injury and sustained by will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a strong person,'' Hartwell said. ``I didn't get to the
top in my event by being weak-minded, so I'm using the same
approach toward the endurance side. Hopefully, I'll make it ... or
I'll die trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Torn meniscus cartilage in Hartwell's left knee prevented him
from training for five months during 1999, and surgery and
rehabilitation did not restore the knee's explosiveness that
sprinters require. That prompted Hartwell's transition from sprints
to endurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to give myself probably two years and see if I can
get to a good European level and then take that next step,''
Hartwell said. ``If within two years I cannot get to there, then
I'm going to have to make some decisions on coaching and schooling
and some other things I'm interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Hartwell labeled this performance ``a start.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I win the Olympic Games in an endurance event or a World
Championships or become a Division I professional rider, I won't
consider myself a success in the transition because I was at the
top level in sprint cycling in Olympic and World competition,''
Hartwell said. ``So, until I'm at that level in endurance, it's
definitely not a success.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartwell, 30, captured an Olympic silver medal in the
1-kilometer time trial at the 1996 Atlanta Games and the bronze in
the event at the '92 Barcelona Games. His performances at the World
Track Cycling Championships produced five silver medals and two
bronze in the 1-kilometer time trial.
</P>
<P>
   Hartwell won't settle for less as an endurance rider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in this to fail,'' he said. ``I have aspirations in
this sport. I have every expectation to become one of the best in
the world in endurance events and show that sprint cyclists can
make the transition.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennie Reed earned the No. 1 seed for today's women's 200-meter
sprint finals with a time of 11.609 seconds during last night's
qualifying time trial. The top 12 U.S. riders advanced to today's
round of 12 and included Nos. 2-6 seeds Tanya Lindenmuth (11.805),
Christine Witty (11.869), Tammy Thomas (12.103), Nicole Reinhart
(12.141) and Suzanne Marshall (12.524).
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
