<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S SIMPLE: LAKERS WANT A SWEEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ As difficult as it was to get through three
off-days between playoff games, the Lakers' next goal is to earn a
six-day break. If they sweep the Sacramento Kings in this
first-round series, that's what awaits them.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what else happens, the NBA (read: NBC) won't let the
second round begin until next weekend, May 6-7. With a victory
tonight at Staples Center, the Lakers would be in position to sweep
the Kings on Sunday at Arco Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely want to try and put this team away,'' Glen Rice
said. ``If it comes down to being a sweep, then we'll settle with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Lakers won Game 1 by 10 points, they know better than
to expect an easy series, however. Sacramento, an unexpected
playoff team in 1999, pushed the Utah Jazz to five games last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year they got blown out by Utah in the first game, came
back the second game and were ready to play,'' Kobe Bryant said.
``So we expect it to be another war. You have to know your
opponent. And they play with that type of attitude, that they have
nothing to lose, very emotional, just come out and play hard. ...
You don't want to stretch a series out to be longer than what it
should be. It's imperative for us to defend our homecourt and take
it from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson wasn't shy about his goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to sweep the series,'' he said. ``I'd like to sweep
the championship. I'd like to go 15-0. The less you have to play,
the better off you are in the playoffs. The more you have to play,
the more chance of injury, the more excruciating it becomes.''
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT TIME: Maybe a six-day break next week isn't a great thing
either. The Lakers didn't enjoy the three-day layoff this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think guys are just a little bit antsy, a little bit
agitated,'' Bryant said. ``We're tired of beating up on one
another, so our tempers are naturally a little bit shorter than
what they normally are, because we're so ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson blasted his team for a lousy day of practice Tuesday but
seemed pleased with their focus Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good practice today, short and right to the point of
what we wanted to do,'' he said. ``I think we're OK.''
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE: The Kings' scoring output (107 points) and shooting
percentage (.435) in Game 1 both exceeded the average for Lakers
opponents this season (92.3 and .416). The Lakers would prefer a
defensive stand to a scoring contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to kind of pack our defense up and play like
we've been playing all year long, because Sacramento is so up and
down, you don't have a chance to set up,'' Bryant said. ``So it's
important for us to just kind of slow them up and not let them get
easy baskets all night. The score can be deceiving. I mean, they
can score 107 points, but yet still taking them out of what they do
on a consistent basis, and that's run up and down and get layups
all day long.''
</P>
<P>
   OUCH REPORT: Reserve center Travis Knight (flu) returned to
practice after a two-day absence and Jackson expects him to be
available tonight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
