<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDS WIN AS MET WIN STREAK ENDS 
 
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was obvious from the first couple of Cincinnati
Reds batters on Wednesday night that the Mets' nine-game winning
streak would end, and probably emphatically.
</P>
<P>
   The knuckleballer Dennis Springer started the game with a
fastball to Pokey Reese that went for strike one, but Reese
singled. Then Springer started Dmitri Young with a fastball, but he
left it over the middle of the plate, and Young clubbed it deep
into the left-field bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   With that, the Reds had a 2-0 lead for their best starting
pitcher, Denny Neagle, and the Mets never came to life. In
persistent rain and wind and with a game-time temperature of 43
degrees, the Reds prevailed, 12-1, at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those games that kind of started out on the
wrong note, and then got worse,'' Mets Manager Bobby Valentine
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets sold 33,371 tickets, but the conditions kept most fans
away. Those who came had little to cheer. Their most robust roar
was for the pitching coach Dave Wallace, who emerged from the
dugout in the top of the seventh inning with the Mets trailing,
7-0. It was a signal that Springer had sacrificed enough and would
be removed.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets needed innings from Springer last night; their best
relievers had been used often during the winning streak, and the
long reliever Pat Mahomes was unavailable because he started on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Springer undertook the task gamely, pitching six innings and
facing three batters in the seventh. He allowed 13 hits and 8 runs,
walking 4 and throwing 2 wild pitches. The hits and runs were
season highs for a Mets starter; Springer and reliever Rich
Rodriguez had to ``take one for the team,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to try to eat it up and help the team out as far
as giving some of the guys a night off,'' Springer said. ``If it
were a 2-1 game, I'm not out there still. You realize you've got to
take it to help some guys out.''
</P>
<P>
   After their two-run first, the Reds scored one run apiece in the
second, third and fifth innings to take a 5-0 lead. It could have
been worse: they left six runners in scoring position in six
innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, with one out and Rey Ordonez on first, Valentine
let Springer bat. Valentine said he felt Springer had to go more
than five innings. Springer struck out against Neagle, who fanned
nine battes in seven innings and allowed two hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't ideal conditions, by no means, but he did it,''
Springer said of Neagle. ``It wasn't pretty, but we weren't going
to win tonight. He threw a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace went out to get Springer after the game unraveled in the
seventh. A Sean Casey double bounced in front of left fielder
Rickey Henderson, then caromed off his shin. The next hitter, Ed
Taubensee, buried Springer's next pitch over the right-field fence
for a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez relieved Springer after a walk, and with two outs,
Young bashed a ball over the head of center fielder Jay Payton.
Young doubled and singled after his homer, and he ended up a few
feet short of hitting for the cycle when Payton and Ordonez
combined to throw him out trying for a triple.
</P>
<P>
   The only drama remaining was whether Ken Griffey Jr. would join
the Reds' hit parade. Griffey struck out three times in his Shea
debut on Tuesday and was hitless in three at-bats against Springer
last night.
</P>
<P>
   But Griffey dropped a single into right field in the eighth, and
the Mets' fans, who have had so much to cheer lately, officially
had nothing to smile about.
</P>
</TEXT>
